<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-PREDATORS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS DEFEAT PREDATORS, 7-4 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE _ Wayne Gretzky may not be finding the net lately, but
he's still a dazzling playmaker.
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky, who has not scored a goal since Feb. 4, handed out a
season-high five assists on Monday night as the New York Rangers
went on a rare scoring binge. They scored four times in the first
period, took a 6-0 lead in the second and cruised to a 7-4 victory
over the expansion Nashville Predators before a sellout crowd of
17,298 at the Nashville Arena.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers (21-26-7), who were averaging only 2.6 goals a game,
needed this victory. They had lost three consecutive games, and
their playoff hopes seemed to be fading with only one victory in
their last five games entering Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Adam Graves and John McLean scored 47 seconds apart in the first
period to ignite the Rangers' attack and drive Nashville's starting
goaltender Mike Dunham to the bench. Dunham had stopped only four
of the seven shots he faced.
</P>
<P>
   For Gretzky, it was the 14th time in his career that he had a
five-assist game, the last coming on Nov. 16, 1995, against the New
York Islanders. In his last nine games Gretzky, the Rangers'
leading scorer, has 12 points _ 1 goal and 11 assists.
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky remained tied with Gordie Howe for the major league
career lead in goals with 1,071.
</P>
<P>
   Nashville (19-31-5) remained without a victory at home in
February. In losses to Detroit, Pittsburgh and the Rangers, the
Predators have been outscored by 14-8. They have not had the lead
in any of those contests.
</P>
<P>
   McLean scored at 5 minutes 43 seconds of the opening period when
his shot from the right boards caromed in off Dunham's skate. It
was McLean's 20th of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Brent Fedyk's fourth goal of the season and second in as many
days caused Nashville Coach Barry Trotz to make the change in goal.
As he left the ice, Dunham heaved his stick in anger. He never
returned to the bench.
</P>
<P>
   Last Nov. 29, Dunham played only one period against the Rangers
before he left the game with a groin injury that sidelined him for
nearly two months. In that one _ a 5-1 New York victory _ he
allowed three goals on 13 shots. In 26:10, the Rangers have scored
6 goals on 19 shots against Dunham.
</P>
<P>
   Tomas Vokoun replaced Dunham and gave up three more goals on the
first seven shots he faced.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Harvey and Kevin Stevens both beat Vokoun for power-play
goals before Graves tipped home a blue-line blast by Todd Harvey.
</P>
<P>
   Goalie Dan Cloutier, starting in place of Mike Richter, made 29
saves for his first victory since Jan. 10.
</P>
<P>
   Nashville, which lost its sixth straight home game, finally came
to life trailing 6-0 midway through the second period.
</P>
<P>
   The Predators finally got on the board with goals by Greg
Johnson and Sebastien Bordeleau 17 seconds apart. Johnson stuffed
home a loose puck from the front of the net for his 15th of the
season. Bordeleau then took a pass in the right circle, whirled and
scored with a wrist shot.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Walker got Nashville within 6-3 when he scored his seventh
at 16:51 of the second. The Predators' three second-period goals
came on a total of seven shots.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Fitzgerald scored Nashville's final goal at 7:50 of the
third period.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers became the third Eastern Conference team to sweep a
two-game set from the first-year Predators. Ottawa and Boston did
so previously.
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky had a scoring chance late in the first period only to
see Harvey get his 11th goal of the season by scoring off Gretzky's
miss at 14:08. His final assist came on a power play at 16:47 in
the third from behind the net to Mathieu Schneider, who had a slap
shot from the high slot for a 7-4 lead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
