<SLUG> BC-HKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO ROSTERS, ONE GREAT TEAM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ We saw a heck of a hockey team Monday night
at the Forum. It is speedier than the Presidents Day commute. It is
stronger than ore. It is more skilled than Bobby Orr.
</P>
<P>
   This team has enough star power to sell those few remaining
luxury suites at the new Staples Center or Paul Kariya's middle
initial isn't T., as in Titanic. Call us crazy, but we don't think
it's California dreaming to picture this merry band of icemen
bumping the Phoenix Coyotes from one of those Western Conference
penthouse suites that they've turned into a cushy, comfy home.
</P>
<P>
   The ice below wasn't responsible for those goosebumps on our
arms when the two local NHL entries skirmished. Southern California
could be Puckville, if not for one minor problem. The players on
the team we're wild about weren't all wearing the same-colored
jerseys during the Anaheim Mighty Ducks' 3-1 win in front of a
crowd pretty evenly divided between Los Angeles Kings fans and
Ducks faithful.
</P>
<P>
   The team that could be the talk of every town between San Diego
and Santa Barbara is a melding of the Kings' and Ducks' rosters.
Hey, if our neighborhood grocery store can be gobbled up by another
and our corner bank similarly absorbed, what's to stop us from
consolidating the two area NHL teams into a single mellifluous one?
</P>
<P>
   Well, besides Disney's dollars, Roski's real-estate empire and
Anschutz' mined millions?
</P>
<P>
   Never mind them. It's our space and it can't be bought, not even
for $85 million, the going rate these days for NHL expansion
franchises. So here goes something substantial. Ladies and
gentlemen, introducing your SoCal SigAlerts (named in honor of all
those red goal lights).
</P>
<P>
   The team would commute between the Forum/Staples Center and the
Pond and be worth following to the ends of the San Andreas Fault,
if only to feel the earth move under one's seat every time the Fab
Five takes a shift.
</P>
<P>
   Forwards Teemu Selanne, Jozef Stumpel and Kariya and defensemen
Rob Blake and Mattias Norstrom would stultify the opposition the
way Detroit's Russian unit once did.
</P>
<P>
   To calculate how many of Stumpel's pretty passes Selanne and
Kariya would put away is to risk blowing your mind. Playing with
interchangeable centers this year (most of the time it has been
rugged Steve Rucchin; lately it has been Matt Cullen), Kariya and
Selanne have combined for 50 goals and have assisted each other
enough to stand fourth and fifth, respectively, in the league in
scoring.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings' Blake is no slouch offensively. He led all defensemen
in scoring in 1997-98 while his partner, Norstrom, is on the
cutting edge of jarring, scarring checks.
</P>
<P>
   Left wing Luc Robitaille is the Kings' top scoring threat with
29 goals. He'd be on the second line of the SigAlerts, alongside
center Rucchin and a healthy Glen Murray.
</P>
<P>
   They'd be a sight to behold in the opposition's end, with
Rucchin winning faceoffs, Murray wasting no time getting the puck
on net with that quick release of his and Robitaille waiting to
pounce on any rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   It says a lot about Murray _ and perhaps even more about the
Kings' firepower _ that he stands second on the team in goals
despite sitting out the past 18 games with a torn medial collateral
ligament in his right knee.
</P>
<P>
   Ducks defenseman Fredrik Olausson was bothered in the exhibition
season by an enlarged spleen. His spleen is fine now; it's his
stats that are swollen. He has almost as many points (38) as the
Kings' top two scoring defensemen (Blake and Steve Duchesne)
combined (39).
</P>
<P>
   Ten of Olausson's 14 goals have come with a man-advantage. He'd
be an integral part of the SigAlerts' power play in addition to
playing regular shifts alongside the Ducks' Ruslan Salei, a rising
stay-at-home defenseman with a rising slapshot that is truly
wicked.
</P>
<P>
   Salei is a one-time teammate of the Kings' Vladimir Tsyplakov.
They'd be reunited again, with Tsyplakov, a left winger, skating on
the third line alongside Cullen and the Kings' Donald Audette.
Audette would be the resident rodent, nibbling at the nerves of
opponents and forcing them into taking cheesy penalties. Once on
the power play, he has a pretty effective top-shelf shot.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings' Doug Bodger and Sean O'Donnell would round out the
defensemen. As he demonstrated Monday, Bodger has never seen a shot
he won't sacrifice his body to block. O'Donnell is every inch as
fearless and selfless.
</P>
<P>
   Blake, Norstrom and Ian Laperriere anchor a Kings' unit that
killed off 28 straight penalties before an ex-King, Tomas
Sandstrom, beat them with a man-advantage in the 16th minute of the
second period.
</P>
<P>
   There'd be a place on the checking line for Laperriere, who does
so many of the little things so well. He's good at faceoffs, he
chases down pucks, he finishes his checks and his shot isn't
half-bad, either; he nearly scored the go-ahead goal off Guy Hebert
from the left circle early in the third.
</P>
<P>
   Sandstrom would also grace the checking line, never mind that on
this night he looked a lot like the King who had 45 goals and 89
points in 1990-91. Sandstrom's heads-up hustle earned him a penalty
shot in the seventh minute of the third and he coolly converted it
to finish off the Kings (Kariya completed the scoring with an empty
netter in the final minute).
</P>
<P>
   Kings tough guy Matt Johnson would play alongside Sandstrom and
Laperriere and in front of Hebert, winner of six of his past seven
games. Jamie Storr, who's nine years younger than the 32-year-old
Hebert, would be the backup goaltender.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Robinson would coach the SigAlerts, because after four
years of driving a jalopy, he deserves to steer a custom-built set
of wheels.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
