<SLUG> BC-BKC-SCHOOP-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCALABRINE FINDS ENERGY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ USC forward Brian Scalabrine has been physically
worn down recently, but he thinks he might have found a way to stay
fresh for the Trojans' final five games.
</P>
<P>
   Scalabrine's legs felt stronger Saturday than they have in weeks
during USC's 86-82 victory over Stanford, when he had a game-high
22 points and five rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't break into a whole sweat before the game during
warmups,'' Scalabrine said. ``I didn't work out as hard. I felt
great in the game. I think a lot of my getting tired in the game
comes from the shootaround. We didn't have one against Stanford
because it was a day game.''
</P>
<P>
   Scalabrine, who's averaging 14.7 points and 6.7 rebounds this
season, continues to be a top contender for the Pacific-10
Conference's newcomer of the year award.
</P>
<P>
   __ Meeting the challenge: One of the unsung heroes of the
Trojans' upset was freshman forward Sam Clancy, who had 12 points
and 10 rebounds, his fourth double-double of the season. Clancy has
more double-doubles than any freshman in the Pac-10 except
Arizona's Michael Wright, who has nine.
</P>
<P>
   Clancy also held his own against Stanford's Mark Madsen,
probably the most physical player in the conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``I challenged Sam Clancy,'' USC coach Henry Bibby said. ``I
said, `Your father's watching you on TV. Are you going to let
Madsen push you around?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Added Scalabrine: ``Sam was like a Superman.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Clutch free throws: The Trojans defeated Stanford despite the
fact the Cardinal made 28 of 32 free throws while the Trojans were
18 of 24. But USC made 9 of its 10 free throws in overtime, when
Stanford was 4 for 6.
</P>
<P>
   The two biggest were by USC guard Elias Ayuso, who hit them with
three seconds left to seal the victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those were the two biggest free throws of my college career,''
Ayuso said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
