<HEADLINE>
WITH BLAKE, IT'S GREAT EXPECTATIONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; Wayne Gretzky of the New York Rangers was saying in an
interview this weekend that trying to live up to his remarkable
legacy is ``the hardest part of being me.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, we know Wayne Gretzky, and let us tell you, Rob Blake is
no Wayne Gretzky.
</P>
<P>
   But Blake, the Kings captain, did win the Norris Trophy last
season as the NHL's top defenseman, so he entered this season
bearing his own share of lofty expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Though Blake hasn't played poorly, the Kings ask a lot of their
best player, and when his performance this season is compared to
anything, it is to last season, when he led NHL defensemen with 23
goals.
</P>
<P>
   But injuries and a suspension robbed him of 18 games, and
following Monday's loss to the Mighty Ducks at the Forum, Blake had
just one goal and four points in his last 15 games, and just four
goals all season. Still, to quantify his importance to the team,
consider that the Kings have a winning record when he's in the
lineup and are an abysmal 3-15 without him.
</P>
<P>
   That said, he hasn't lately been dominating the way he does when
he's at his best, and Blake readily accepted a large share of the
blame for Saturday's 3-2 loss to Dallas because he was caught
flatfooted on Guy Carbonneau's game-winning goal.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings' team leader said, ``It's tough to lead when you're
the guy making the mistakes. It's tough to stand up in the dressing
room and say something.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Larry Robinson said, ``I think he's capable of making much
better plays. He's definitely not playing the way he's capable of
playing. . . . I spoke to him a week ago and I told him how much
this team needs him. We need him at the top of his game. We need
everyone at the top of their game.''
</P>
<P>
   But most of all, especially if they are to stage a last-ditch
run for a playoff berth, the Kings need Blake, and he knows it
better than anyone.
</P>
<P>
   __ Fleury of the week: If Calgary remains in the playoff hunt
when the trading deadline arrives on March 23, it would be sensible
for the Flames to trade unrestricted-free-agent-to-be Theoren
Fleury, but it wouldn't be popular with their fans.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Fleury is making it clear he prefers to remain in
the Western Conference, in large part for family reasons. His wife,
Veronica, is due April 8 with the couple's second child, and Fleury
would also like to remain close to a child (from a previous
relationship) who lives in Calgary.
</P>
<P>
   A definite hang-up in a Fleury trade is that he has said he
intends to test the free-agent market, which opens July 1, meaning
that a team could make a deal for him in March and have nothing to
show for it a few months later.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, a source familiar with the situation said, one option for
a team trading for Fleury would be to send the Flames one piece
now, with a second piece going to Calgary contingent on signing the
gritty 5-foot-6 right wing after the season.
</P>
<P>
   __ Steel City savior?: The bankrupt Pittsburgh Penguins owe
their creditors $127 million, $26.3 million of that to former
superstar center Mario Lemieux, who says he would be willing to
convert a ``large portion'' of what is owed him into equity in the
ailing franchise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm taking a big chance,'' Lemieux admitted. ``But I believe
hockey can work in Pittsburgh. I believe in the fans of
Pittsburgh.''
</P>
<P>
   Lemieux said he would make regular appearances in the Penguins'
offices, unlike absentee owners Roger Marino and Howard Baldwin.
But if anyone is thinking that Lemieux, who is 33, would consider
returning to the ice, forget it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm an owner, I can't be player,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If Lemieux's efforts fail, it is possible the Penguins will
move, which would be a pity for their supportive fans and for the
NHL.
</P>
<P>
   __ Looney tunes: It's hard to imagine what was going through th
mind of Art Williams when he took over as owner of the Tampa Bay
Lightning before the season. Apparently, in the aftermath of last
season's league-worst 17-55-10 record, he figured a Stanley Cup was
just around the corner.
</P>
<P>
   The Lightning will fall a tad short. Tampa Bay is a league-worst
11-39-5, and this has been upsetting to Williams, who is
considering selling a portion of his team.
</P>
<P>
   ``This thing has just devastated me,'' said Williams, whose team
is expected to lose $20 million this season. ``The losses have been
a really tough thing for me to take. . . . This has been a tragic
year for me.''
</P>
<P>
   The man with the skewed sense of tragedy was asked how the
Lightning can turn itself around and said, ``You do that with young
kids and draft picks and clearing out some of the dead-wood
veterans. And some of the pansies we have.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said, ``I don't know hockey.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Is bigger better?: In their second and final season in
Greensboro, the Carolina Hurricanes are averaging fewer than 8,000
fans at their home games. Obviously, what this franchise needs
above all else is a 19,000-seat arena.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the Hurricanes are scheduled to move into just such an
edifice next season in Raleigh, 80 miles from Greensboro.
Considering there are doubts North Carolina State can fill the
building's 20,000 seats for basketball in a region of
hoop-a-holics, the Hurricanes clearly have a big selling job to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've said all along that 19,000 is too big,'' Raleigh Mayor
Tom Fetzer said. ``We'll have to figure out ways to fill it up.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hurricanes have recruited racing legend and North Carolina
native Richard Petty to appear in print, radio and TV ads. In the
first TV spot, Petty drives a Zamboni around a rink at warp speed.
</P>
<P>
   Whether that's sufficient to motivate locals to spend up to $95
for tickets remains to be seen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
