<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AIRLINE TRAVELERS ENJOYED A DECLINE IN TICKET PRICES
</P>
<P>
   When several major airlines raised their fares at the end of
last month, they were bucking a longer-term trend of decreasing
prices.
</P>
<P>
   The new, higher fares, part of the same search for greater
profits that has made the airlines determined to keep a lid on
employee costs, will primarily affect the business travelers who
schedule flights too late to take advantage of most discounts. But
in general, all passengers have experienced a drop in what they
have paid for flights over the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   ACCUSERS LOOK TO MICROSOFT'S FUTURE
</P>
<P>
   As the Microsoft antitrust trial nears its end, the Justice
Department and the 19 states involved in lawsuits against the
company are scrambling to devise restraints on Microsoft that, if
they are victorious, they could ask a Federal court to impose.
</P>
<P>
   PROTESTERS SEEK WINDOWS REFUNDS
</P>
<P>
   Saying they had been forced to pay for something they did not
intend to use, 100 computer aficionados went to Microsoft offices
to request refunds for the Windows operating systems that came with
their computers.
</P>
<P>
   SAVINGS LIMITED IN FRENCH BANK DEAL
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition of Paribas by Societe Generale combines the
activities of two big French banks, but it may not provide the
economies that produce significant cost cuts and enthusiastic
investors.
</P>
<P>
   VOLVO SHOPS FOR A U.S. TRUCK MAKER
</P>
<P>
   Volvo, after agreeing last month to sell its car operation to
Ford for $6.45 billion, is reported to have had talks with Navistar
International of Chicago as it looks in the United States for a
truck manufacturer to buy.
</P>
<P>
   TERMS ANNOUNCED IN AEROSPACE DEAL
</P>
<P>
   Groupe Lagardere, the owner of Matra High Technology, will pay
the French Government as much as $345 million for a third of the
shares in the new combination of the state-owned Aerospatiale group
and the privately owned Matra High Technology, a deal that will
create the world's fifth-largest military and aerospace contractor.
</P>
<P>
   SOME RIG OPERATORS RESIST LAYOFFS
</P>
<P>
   Even as a glut of petroleum shuts down rigs and keeps prices
low, some oil service companies are keeping workers on their
payrolls to preserve their skills for another day.
</P>
<P>
   EURO GLITCHES FOR VENDING MACHINES
</P>
<P>
   Few businesses in Europe are as directly affected by the
transition of 11 nations to a common currency as operators of
vending machines, who face tricky logistics for converting their
machines to accepting euro-denominated coins.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN SET TO RESUME BUYING BONDS
</P>
<P>
   Japan plans to resume buying Government bonds this month and in
March, in a bid to stem a rise in long-term interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. MARKETS REOPEN
</P>
<P>
   All financial markets in the United States, as well as banks and
Government offices, are scheduled to reopen today. They were closed
Monday in observance of Presidents' Day. On Friday stocks gave up
most of the gains they had made on Thursday, when the Nasdaq index
leaped 96 points in its biggest one-day point gain ever. Technology
stocks were the culprits as earnings concerns about Dell Computer
sent its shares down 12, to 89~. The Nasdaq index declined 83.66
points, or 3.5 percent, to 2,321.89. The Dow Jones industrial
average fell 88.57 points, or 1 percent, to 9,274.89. The Standard
&AMP; Poor's index of 500 stocks dropped 23.91, or 1.9 percent, to
1,230.13.
</P>
</TEXT>
