<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUCKS DUNK KINGS AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ It was a game rife with symbolic moments,
moments when it became ever clearer which team was going nowhere
and which was on the rise.
</P>
<P>
   There were the Kings, getting what should have been an emotional
lift from a shorthanded goal by Olli Jokinen that broke up a
scoreless tie late in the second period. But here were the Mighty
Ducks, tying the score on a power play just 17 seconds later with a
goal by a Kings hero of yesteryear, Tomas Sandstrom.
</P>
<P>
   And here, again, was Sandstrom, scoring on a decisive
third-period penalty shot that lifted the Mighty Ducks a little
higher and sank the Kings just a little deeper.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still in the playoff race,'' Kings coach Larry Robinson
said grimly following Monday's 3-1 loss to the Ducks before a Forum
crowd of 14,664. ``But we're slowly putting ground over our own
graves.''
</P>
<P>
   Ducks coach Craig Hartsburg said, ``It took all our energy and
everybody had to contribute. We did a good job and stayed solid. We
did a lot of little things right.''
</P>
<P>
   The loss, the second straight for the Kings (20-31-4), left them
six points behind Edmonton in the race for the final playoff berth
in the Western Conference. The Kings are 0-3 against the Ducks this
season and have been outscored, 9-2.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks (23-23-9), who recorded their fourth consecutive road
victory and second in as many nights, are fifth in the conference
and are well on their way to the second playoff appearance in their
six-year history.
</P>
<P>
   It was scoreless until late in the second period, when Jokinen
scored his first goal since Dec. 30 off a pass from Yanic Perreault
after Ducks goalie Guy Hebert misplayed a loose puck in the corner
with his team shorthanded.
</P>
<P>
   But the Kings' celebration lasted just long enough for Sandstrom
to get behind defenseman Sean O'Donnell, take a lead pass from
Pascal Trepanier and slip the puck between the pads of goalie
Stephane Fiset. The goal broke a string of successful penalty kills
by the Kings at 28.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a huge part of the game for us,'' Hartsburg said of
his team's quick response to Jokinen's goal.
</P>
<P>
   O'Donnell said, ``I saw Sandstrom cut behind me. I thought that
to go behind me, he'd have to go offside. It was a bad read. My
fault. Totally my fault.''
</P>
<P>
   On a similar play 6:40 into the third period, Sandstrom got
behind Duchesne, this time taking a pass from Steve Rucchin.
Duchesne pulled Sandstrom down and referee Richard Trottier awarded
Sandstrom a penalty shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a step on (Duchesne),'' Sandstrom said. ``I think he was
standing still at the blue line and it was a turnover, so I just
took off and Rucchin hit me with a perfect pass.''
</P>
<P>
   Duchesne said, ``I was trying to make the right play. I was
trying not to give up a breakaway. I take the blame for it. It's my
fault.''
</P>
<P>
   Sandstrom made no mistake, beating Fiset to the glove side with
a quick wrist shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``With his experience and background, he was the perfect guy to
take (the penalty shot),'' Hartsburg said. ``I didn't even watch. I
wanted to watch, but eight guys were standing in front of me.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks sealed the victory in the final minute with an
empty-net goal by Paul Kariya.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you could put in a capsule what's happened this season,''
Kings center Ray Ferraro said, ``instead of finding a way to win,
we found a way to lose.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
