<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGNOT-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS STARS FIZZLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Los Angeles Kings coach Larry Robinson tried
something new Monday, having players _ specifically defenseman Sean
O'Donnell and center Ray Ferraro _ discuss at the pregame meeting
what the team needed to do against the Mighty Ducks.
</P>
<P>
   Usually that's the coaches' job, but Robinson figured he might
as well try something new. However, as with everything else this
season, the ploy didn't work and the Kings lost 3-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``They pointed out all the things that needed to be done,''
Robinson said, ``and a 20-year-old kid (rookie Olli Jokinen) is the
only one who plays to his potential.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's disturbing. It's the biggest game of the year, or one of
them. . . . How come you can't mentally _ all your big stars _ come
up with your best game of the year? It's very disturbing.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson praised only Jokinen, Ian Laperriere, Sandy Moger,
Yanic Perreault and Sean Pronger, who made his Kings debut.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what he told his team after the game, Robinson said,
``They're undressed and out of there so quick, you have to be a
magician to get in there fast enough. They should be sitting there
concentrating on the game. A lot of heart checks need to be done.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Ailing Ducks: For the second consecutive game, the Mighty
Ducks lost a defenseman to an injury. This time, it was Pascal
Trepanier, who left in the second period with a bruise after he was
struck on the left leg by a puck. He is listed as day to day.
</P>
<P>
   In Sunday's victory at Phoenix, the Ducks lost Jamie Pushor, who
suffered a bruised left shoulder when checked into the glass by
Coyotes center Tavis Hansen.
</P>
<P>
   Before Monday's game, the Ducks recalled defenseman Dan Trebil
from their Cincinnati affiliate in the American Hockey League.
Trebil had 19 points in 45 games at Cincinnati and he also has
appeared in one game for the Mighty Ducks. He did not play against
the Kings.
</P>
<P>
   __ Penalty shots: Tomas Sandstrom's penalty shot was the fourth
in Mighty Ducks history and their first against the Kings. The
Ducks have scored on three of their four penalty shots. Sandstrom
has scored two penalty-shot goals in his career, the other nine
years ago as a King against Pittsburgh goalie Wendell Young.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings have faced 27 penalty shots in their history and
allowed nine goals. Washington's Peter Bondra scored on the only
other penalty shot against the Kings this season. The Kings have
had two penalty shots against the Ducks, getting a goal from Dan
Quinn in 1995. Glen Murray was stopped by Guy Hebert last season.
</P>
<P>
   __ Offensive defense: A key to the Mighty Ducks' success this
season has been the offensive production by their defensemen. A key
factor in the Kings' struggles has been lack of same.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings' defensemen have scored 12 goals, eight fewer than the
Ducks' defensemen have scored. With 14 goals, Ducks defenseman
Fredrik Olausson has two more than the Kings' defensemen combined.
</P>
<P>
   Olausson, 32, already has tied the Ducks' record for most goals
by a defenseman, set by Bill Houlder during the inaugural 1993-94
season. He is eight points from tying the franchise record for a
defenseman. Dimitri Mironov had 46 points for the Ducks in 1996-97.
</P>
<P>
   Olausson recently became only the 37th defensemen in NHL history
to reach 500 points, and the native of Sweden is only the second
defenseman born outside of North America to do so. The first was
Hall of Famer Borje Salming, another Swede who retired in 1990 with
787 points for Toronto and Detroit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
