<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPNOTE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO PLAYERS ON THE BUBBLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ At first blush, Los Angeles Clippers math might
seem easy: five games equals five losses.
</P>
<P>
   But this a different math problem.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, an NBA mandate kicks in, forcing each team to trim
its active roster to 12 players. In tonight's game vs. Vancouver at
the Arrowhead Pond of Anaheim, the Clippers will have 14 players in
uniform. So, subtract two and you're there, right?
</P>
<P>
   Well, we can't forget two Clippers on the injured list - veteran
free-agent guard Scott Brooks and rookie power forward Brian
Skinner.
</P>
<P>
   Skinner, whose injured knee soon will be ready to roll, may come
off the injured list within the week.
</P>
<P>
   That means the team must do even more subtracting (unless, of
course, someone sustains an unfortunate, but timely, injury).
</P>
<P>
   Who's a likely goner? Aside from Brooks, the only member of the
Super 16 without a guaranteed contract is undrafted rookie forward
Tyrone Nesby.
</P>
<P>
   But there's a problem; Nesby , who backs up Lamond Murray at
small forward, has hustled his way into Coach Chris Ford's heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been playin', hasn't he?'' Ford said of Nesby's immediate
future. ``He's been part of my rotation.''
</P>
<P>
   And that means it's unlikely Nesby will be cut.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think about,'' said Nesby, who scored 9 points in 19 minutes
during Sunday's loss to Minnesota. ``But if they cut me, they cut
me. I'll just thank Coach Ford for giving me the opportunity and
move on.''
</P>
<P>
   A more realistic scenario would involve the Clippers buying out
the remainder of another player's guaranteed contract.
</P>
<P>
   __ Double trouble: Like the composite sketch on a wanted poster,
the moves of Michael Olowokandi are receiving great scrutiny from
Clippers opponents.
</P>
<P>
   In his first three games, the rookie center averaged 14 points
and 10 shots per game. In his last two, both starts, Olowokandi has
managed 7.5 points and 7 shots per game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael has to work on holding his position,'' Ford said of
the league's top draft pick. ``He has to learn to handle the
double-team.''
</P>
<P>
   In last weekend's losses to Phoenix and Minnesota, Olowokandi
had trouble establishing position against veteran centers Luc
Longley and Dean Garrett, respectively. The Timberwolves also
assisted Garrett with fierce double-teaming tactics, usually
applied by 7-foot Kevin Garnett or 6-10 Joe Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he gets the ball in the paint,'' Ford said, ``he's got to
get into his move right away. After guys get used to being
double-teamed, they start to wait for the double-team.''
</P>
<P>
   Another problem, Ford said, is Olowokandi's busy low-post
repertoire, which may be forcing him to decide which move is best.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Michael's gotta rely more on his jump-hook,'' said
Ford, who also pointed out that Olowokandi's quick spin move is not
yet ready for the doubting eyes of NBA officials.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
