<DOCNO> NYT19990216.0021 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-16 03:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6590 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPEECH-ORIGINS-SFCHRO     02-16 1231
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPEECH-ORIGINS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 STUDY POKES HOLE IN TALKING NEANDERTHAL THEORY  &HT;     By DAVID PERLMAN 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A study by three University of California
graduate students has rekindled an old controversy about the
mysterious origins of human speech.
</P>
<P>
   The study by the UC Berkeley anthropology students compared the
obscure anatomical features of apes and monkeys with modern humans
and with their prehuman ancestors of 2 million years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Their findings challenge a widely accepted contention by senior
researchers at Duke University that the extinct Neanderthal people,
who vanished from Earth some 30,000 years ago, may have possessed
the capacity for speech at least 400,000 years earlier _ long
before modern human beings arrived on the evolutionary scene.
</P>
<P>
   The gift of speech and language _ more than almost any other
ability _ makes possible the expression of symbolic thought, of
organized societies, of art and culture. They distinguish us from
our long-ago prehuman forebears and from our primate cousins, the
apes and monkeys of today.
</P>
<P>
   Until about 30,000 years ago our direct ancestors, modern Homo
sapiens, shared the forests and plains of Europe with another more
primitive people, known today as Neanderthals, who also hunted,
made stone tools and buried their dead in the same territory as
Homo sapiens.
</P>
<P>
   The Neanderthals had evolved from earlier prehumans and had
thrived for hundreds of thousands of years before Homo sapiens
arrived, but ultimately they were doomed to become only a dead-end
branch on the tree of evolution.
</P>
<P>
   They died away even as modern humans had advanced to create
societies, to fill caves with symbolic art and to become the
dominant species in a lineage that traces directly back for
millions of years to the first humanlike creatures, now known as
hominids. Only the scattered fossil bones of Homo Neanderthalensis
remain today to recall their extinction.
</P>
<P>
   But for anthropologists _ and for all of us profoundly curious
about our beginnings _ the great mystery persists: Did Neanderthals
have language? Could they speak? Or are we moderns the only ones
graced by evolution with that capacity?
</P>
<P>
   The sparse but intriguing evidence about the origin of speech,
like so much in science, is bound to evoke puzzlement and may never
be finally resolved.
</P>
<P>
   But last year a team of Duke University researchers concluded
that the shape of tiny tube-like bone structures they analyzed in
fossil skulls from two Neanderthals gave evidence that those squat,
heavy-bodied people with their beetling brows could well have
developed speech as far back as 400,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The tubular bones at the base of the brain _ no thicker than
pencils _ are called hypoglossal canals. They carry specialized
nerve fibers from the brain to the tongue and control the flexible
tongue's movements in shaping the elements of spoken language. The
same canals also carry blood vessels that nourish the flexible
tongue.
</P>
<P>
   The Duke anthropologists compared the size of the tube-shaped
bone structures in their 70,000-year-old Neanderthal fossils with
those of early and modern Homo sapiens. Because the average
dimensions of the bone structures were nearly equal, the Duke
scientists concluded that the canals of the extinct Neanderthals
were easily large enough to hold the elaborate nerve fibers and
blood vessels essential to make their tongues capable of forming
articulate speech.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; First to Speak
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the Neanderthals at least 400 millennia ago
could well have been the first people to speak, according to
Richard F. Kay, Matt Cartmill and Michelle Ballow, the Duke
researchers. They published their widely heralded findings last
April in the Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences.
</P>
<P>
   And the much smaller hypoglossal canals in earlier fossil
hominids, known as Australopithecus africanus, were almost
identical in size to those of modern monkeys, chimpanzees and
gorillas, the Duke scientists found. So clearly, like the
Australopithicenes, nonhuman primates who lived some 2.5 million
years ago, they could not have possessed even the rudimentary
structures essential for human speech, the anthropologists said.
</P>
<P>
   Australopithecus, like today's apes and monkeys, may well have
screamed and grunted, but it was not true language.
</P>
<P>
   But in Tuesday's issue of the same publication, the three
Berkeley graduate students have boldly challenged their seniors
with a compelling counterargument.
</P>
<P>
   David DeGusta, W. Henry Gilbert and Scott P. Turner contend in
their research report that they have ``falsified'' the Duke theory
that the size of the hypoglossal canal and its nerves is an
indicator of speech and language capacity. And their argument found
support at once from one of the foremost experts on human
evolution, UC Berkeley physical anthropologist F. Clark Howell.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Howell said enthusiastically that the Duke report
``adds a new arrow in the quiver of evidence'' that is slowly
attacking the language origin problem. At that time he called the
Duke conclusions based on size comparisons of the hypoglossal canal
``a very promising approach.''
</P>
<P>
   But this year Howell has sponsored the publication by DeGusta
and his colleagues, and in an interview over the weekend he backed
the UC Berkeley students more strongly.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; `It Just Doesn't Work'
</P>
<P>
   The Duke approach of comparing the size of the hypoglossal
canals in the skulls of Neanderthals with modern humans, with
monkeys and apes, and with far more ancient hominids ``just doesn't
provide good evidence for the origin of speech,'' Howell said. ``It
just doesn't work.''
</P>
<P>
   DeGusta and his colleagues, in fact, did make a detailed
comparative study, and they did it meticulously. But they found no
correlation at all between canal size and language ability.
</P>
<P>
   They measured the dimensions of the canals in museum-held skulls
of 104 modern humans; 75 monkeys, chimps and gorillas; and two
fossil species of early hominids dating as far back as 2.5 million
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Among all those samples, the Berkeley scientists found, the
average size of the hypoglossal canals overlapped so strongly that
many were larger than human canals while others were smaller. Even
the canals of the Australopithicenes were equal in size to the
canals of modern humans, DeGusta said in an interview, and he added
that in one gibbon skull the canal was actually twice as large as
the average human.
</P>
<P>
   The Berkeley researchers dutifully sent an advance copy of their
report to Kay and his colleagues, and in an interview Kay
acknowledged it this way:
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very interesting paper, indeed,'' he said, ``and it's
on our horizon right now, so we'll certainly have to deal with it.
But there's been a lot going on in human evolution over the past
million years, and based on their data our view isn't seriously
challenged.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing in it refutes us, and while they've raised a
cautionary flag, there are signal difficulties with their data and
there's still a lot we don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   To that, DeGusta and his colleagues have already replied in
their own paper:
</P>
<P>
   ``The size of the hypoglossal canal does not reflect vocal
capabilities or language usage. Thus, the date of origin for human
language and the speech capabilities of Neanderthals remain open
questions.''  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-99 0348EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990216.0022 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-16 03:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6591 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALBANIA-IMMIGRANTS-SF     02-16 2336
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALBANIA-IMMIGRANTS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 GLOBAL MOB CASHING IN ON HUMAN CARGO  &HT;     By FRANK VIVIANO 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  ON THE ADRIATIC SEA _ From the moment he sees the rust-streaked
freighter slide out of a fog bank on the Otranto Strait, 25 miles
west of the Albanian coast, and abruptly change course, Captain
Antonino Lo Presti is wary.
<P>
   ``She's an old gas tanker, the kind a smuggler can buy at a
scrap yard for next to nothing,'' he says, giving the order for
full throttle. ``When we picked her up on radar, she didn't even
respond to our signals.''
</P>
<P>
   This is where the war-torn Third World meets Western Europe
head-on, in a tense struggle between civil society and organized
crime that holds hundreds of lives hostage every night.
</P>
<P>
   Lo Presti's command, the high-speed pursuit vessel Cavaglia,
sailing under the flag of the Guardia di Finanza, Italy's
counterpart to the U.S. Coast Guard, patrols one of the most
dangerous seaways on Earth.
</P>
<P>
   An international conspiracy of unprecedented dimensions,
involving crime syndicates in half a dozen nations _ and
trafficking in enormous quantities of narcotics, arms and desperate
human beings _ operates in these waters.
</P>
<P>
   As the two vessels close on a moonless January night, the
220-foot freighter's radio finally crackles into response, agreeing
to heave-to. The vessel's name and Syrian home port are faint,
nearly illegible scrawls on her stern.
</P>
<P>
   ``Could be drugs,'' Lo Presti says to a reporter. ``Could be
guns. Could be people.''
</P>
<P>
   Led by chief engineering officer Girolamo Gambino, four of Lo
Presti's men strap on bulletproof vests and handguns and prepare to
board.
</P>
<P>
   They return after an hour, shaking their heads. The freighter
carries only a herd of goats bound for the port of Koper, Slovenia.
It makes no commercial sense as cargo, but there is nothing more
the Cavaglia can do.
</P>
<P>
   Two days later, police report that a large group of clandestine
emigrants has landed on the coast near Venice, from a small port
just south of Koper.
</P>
<P>
   The 42-mile-wide Otranto Strait, the narrowest waterway between
the rich European Union and a Third World engulfed in civil war, is
the last leg of a epic journey for vast numbers of undocumented
migrants.
</P>
<P>
   Their origins are a catalog of the planet's bloodiest crises in
1999. Crossing the strait in the holds of rusting freighters _ or
more often aboard ``gommones,'' 60-mph motor launches based in the
Albanian port of Vlore _ they include refugees from every conflict
now raging in Africa, the Balkans and south and central Asia.
</P>
<P>
   On the single January afternoon and night that a Chronicle team
spent aboard the Cavaglia, the Guardia di Finanza rounded up 365 of
the clandestine emigrants.
</P>
<P>
   They had set sail from Vlore after journeys to Albania of up to
10 weeks, from Sri Lanka, Afghanistan, the Kurdish borderland of
Turkey and Iraq, Kosovo, Algeria, Sierra Leone, Liberia and
Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
   Government spokesmen estimate that 800 to 1,000 such emigrants
leave Vlore daily, successfully eluding detection _ or drowning en
route.
</P>
<P>
   Once in Italy, the emigrants are able to travel north unimpeded
and disappear into the swelling Third World ghettoes of Paris,
Berlin, Brussels and Rotterdam. In an effort to further integrate
their economies, Italy and most other European Union nations have
dismantled border posts with their EU neighbors in the past two
years.
</P>
<P>
   It is what precedes the clandestine voyages on the Otranto
Strait that suggests an underworld conspiracy more extensive, and
more ominous, than anything preceding it in the annals of organized
crime.
</P>
<P>
   Put simply, ``mafia'' groups from the South China Sea to Sicily
have recognized a golden opportunity in Europe's open internal
borders.
</P>
<P>
   With extraordinary sophistication and minute planning, they have
combined forces to smuggle thousands of human beings over the EU's
Adriatic frontier.
</P>
<P>
   In dozens of interviews, emigrants said they had paid for their
transportation to Western Europe in their homelands, once and for
all. At each step on the subsequent journey _ whether it be the
remote frontier between Iraq and Turkey, or a port in Nigeria,
Albania or Pakistan _ buses, cars and maritime vessels were
waiting, and no further payment was asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I gave a man in Kabul $6,000 for myself and my sister,'' said
a traveler from Afghanistan. ``When we crossed into Pakistan, there
was a minibus ready for us, and others when we reached Iran and
Turkey.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither he nor his sister had passports or official
identification documents, yet they had crossed several of the
world's most heavily defended borders.
</P>
<P>
   ``After Turkey, it was a freighter to Albania,'' the Afghan
said. ``Nobody anywhere said a word about more money.''
</P>
<P>
   In short, each driver or helmsman's share of the fee had been
assigned in advance, and distributed by an international team of
paymasters who were trusted to meet specific billing schedules that
stretched across two continents.
</P>
<P>
   The size of the advance payment is based on a complicated
formula that takes into account the level of political risk, as
well as distance.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Afghans, several Sri Lankans had paid $3,000 apiece.
``We were the last sons alive in our families,'' one said.
``Everybody gave something, everybody hopes we'll be able to get
them out, too.''
</P>
<P>
   A group of 14 Kurds and six Christians from Iraq who made the
journey together had paid $1,500 per person, and a family of four
from Kosovo $1,000 per adult and $500 per child.
</P>
<P>
   Albanians are offered a special package if they make their own
way to Vlore: three voyages to Italy for a flat $1,200 _ ``in case
we're caught the first two times,'' one explained.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from the Albanians, most of those who are apprehended at
sea by the Guardia di Finanza, or on the beaches by the Italian
carabinieri, are refugees eligible to apply for political asylum,
although there is no certainty that they will eventually receive
it.
</P>
<P>
   The Italian government will not forcibly repatriate those who
arrive illegally from war-torn countries where they might be
imprisoned or executed as suspected terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   Large numbers of clandestine emigrants from Kosovo, Kurdish Iraq
and Turkey, and northern Sri Lanka _ especially young men between
21 and 35 _ are clearly militants who have been identified by law
enforcement authorities in their homelands and obliged to flee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course I am a Tiger,'' one refugee said, referring to the
ethnic-Tamil guerrilla army that has waged a bloody 15-year war
against the Sri Lankan government. ``Every Tamil my age in our
country is a Tiger.''
</P>
<P>
   The apprehended newcomers find themselves on a complicated,
demoralizing road once they reach Italy.
</P>
<P>
   The first stop is a cluster of metal sheds, aluminum truck
containers that have been refashioned into temporary housing and
installed on the wharves of Otranto, the Cavaglia's port.
</P>
<P>
   Once their origins are established, those who are not identified
as nationals of Albania, Morocco or Tunisia _ countries that have
signed ``instant deportation agreements'' with Italy _ are bused to
the Casa Regina Pacis, a refugee camp 15 miles north of Otranto in
the town of San Foca, where they are photographed and
fingerprinted.
</P>
<P>
   Within a week, most are freed to the custody of relatives in
Germany, northern Italy or France, in keeping with legislation
covering asylum applicants. Others are sent to larger holding camps
in Sicily _ or climb over the San Foca fences at night to make
their way north as best they can.
</P>
<P>
   The scene at San Foca in a late January week was Babel
revisited, with a dozen languages pouring into the hallway phones
from which internees called relatives.
</P>
<P>
   The facility was built to house 300 boy scouts on summer
vacations. It held nearly 600 emigrants on January 24. The walls of
the building's crowded sleeping halls were covered with graffiti,
also in a dozen languages, left behind by earlier arrivals:
``Kosovo I love You.'' ``I went to Germany.'' ``Allah protect us.''
</P>
<P>
   Down the hall from the phones, two Liberian prostitutes sat
quietly on bunk beds, awaiting a decision on their next
destination.
</P>
<P>
   The clandestine traffic has increasingly become a modern slave
trade, with young women _ chiefly from West Africa, Ukraine, Russia
and Albania _ forced into prostitution and sold to middlemen
overseeing sex rings in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The Liberian women declined to talk, but many others at San Foca
were eager to tell their stories.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a schoolteacher, from a country where there are no
classrooms or books anymore,'' a refugee from Afghanistan said. ``I
am also a Tajik,'' he added, drawing a finger across his neck to
suggest a throat-slitting.
</P>
<P>
   The Tajik minority in Afghanistan, which resisted the revolution
of the fundamentalist Taliban movement, has been subjected to
genocidal campaigns by the government in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   The Roman Catholic charity organization Caritas, which
administers the camp for the Italian authorities and oversees
reporters' visits, asks only that no names be used.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are political refugees,'' said a Caritas executive.
``Their families could well be in mortal danger if the wrong person
reads your article.''
</P>
<P>
   Her concern reflects a widespread mixture of alarm and sympathy
over the influx among Italians, for whom mass emigration is a
recent episode in their own history.
</P>
<P>
   ``They arrive with every imaginable problem _ bayonet wounds,
broken limbs, infections of the respiratory system, intestinal
disorders, acute mental trauma. It's heart-breaking,'' says Dr.
Marina Greco, who presides over a two-physician clinic at Regina
Pacis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at these people, and I can't help but think of how many
of my own family made the same kind of voyage to America,'' said
Cavaglia engineering officer Gambino, a Sicilian.
</P>
<P>
   But the sentimentality does not extend to Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the refugees who share their boats, Albanians in police
custody are returned home within 24 hours. One result is that the
ferries that travel daily between Italy and Albania are nearly
empty westbound _ the voyages in that direction are made in
gommones or freighters _ and crammed full on the eastbound run.
</P>
<P>
   The returnees are a living encyclopedia of the reasons why
Italian popular opinion has shifted from open-armed sympathy toward
Albania when it threw off half a century of oppressive Stalinist
rule in 1992, to fearful hostility.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent voyage from the Italian port of Brindisi to Vlore,
the Illyrian Lines ferry Tirana was packed to the gunwales with
young men who drank themselves into a brawling rage on the
night-long voyage, leaving ransacked cabins and decks full of
broken chairs and tables in their wake.
</P>
<P>
   Thieves quickly singled out the few foreigners on board _
including two Chronicle correspondents, who were threatened
repeatedly with beatings, and whose cabin vouchers and return
tickets were stolen before the ship even sailed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a distorted mentality after all those years of
isolation,'' says Antonio Probo, a Cavaglia officer, referring to
Albania's years under the late Enver Hoxha, a reclusive dictator
who shut his country to the Soviet Union and Mao's China as well
the capitalist West.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have no sense of a relationship between legitimate work
and money. The worst of them are evil bastards who will throw a
baby overboard without a second thought if it will slow us down in
a chase.''
</P>
<P>
   The charge is widely repeated by Italian law enforcement
authorities and aid workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every night, in the last few months, a baby or a young girl
has been pushed into the sea,'' according to Alessandro Russo, a
medical aide with the Catholic charity Misericordia who treats
injured emigrants on the Otranto wharf.
</P>
<P>
   At 11:30 p.m., as Probo and Gambino scour the horizon with
binoculars, the voice of the radar officer suddenly squawks over
the Cavaglia loudspeakers: ``Gommone, 41 degrees 22 minutes north
by 18 degrees 43 minutes east, bearing west southwest at 45
knots.''
</P>
<P>
   Captain Lo Presti adjusts course and speed to intercept.
</P>
<P>
   The chase is an exercise in the frustrations that make Europe's
spiraling immigration crisis seem beyond solution to many
observers.
</P>
<P>
   Equipped with sensitive computerized navigation instruments, the
Cavaglia is able to bring the gommone in sight one hour later. But
until the smugglers' work is done _ until the emigrants are safely
ashore _ ``we can't do anything but keep track of its location,''
Lo Presti says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Otherwise,'' he adds, ``just in getting too close, we might
accidentally kill a lot of people. These vessels are dangerously
overcrowded and unstable.''
</P>
<P>
   The concerns are justified. On December 6, two Italy-bound
vessels foundered in a winter storm. International maritime
officials believe they carried up to 700 Kurds, West Africans,
Algerians, Afghans, Iraqis and Pakistanis. It is feared that more
than 200 drowned.
</P>
<P>
   ``A confrontation at sea with gommones weighed down with mothers
and children is something that cannot be undertaken without the
gravest risks,'' said Italian Prime Minister Massimo D'Alema.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the frustration only grows when the gommone has landed its
passengers, and probably a cargo of narcotics, and put back to sea.
In a perilous midnight cat-and-mouse game at nearly 50 mph on the
high seas, the Cavaglia brings the motor launch alongside several
times, only to be outmaneuvered and eventually outrun by its more
agile quarry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd like to put a shot into their sides, that's for sure, and
we have the armaments to do it,'' says Domenico Di Gianvittorio, a
veteran Guardia di Finanza officer in his 50s.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we come out here with shackles on our wrists. The policy
is `No shooting unless they shoot first,' and the smugglers are
well aware of that. So the result is that we race back and forth,
night after night, to little purpose, and the flesh trade goes on
under our noses.''
</P>
</TEXT>
