<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-16 10:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6758 &Cx1f; tad-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONLINE-LAWS-$ADV21-CO     02-16 0503
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONLINE-LAWS-$ADV21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CONGRESS WEIGHS CURBING DISCLOSURE OF PRIVATE BANK DATA
 &HT;    With ONLINE-PRIVACY. For release Sunday, Feb. 21.
 &HT;    By ELLIOT JASPIN
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ At first glance, a pending House bill seems to be
on the side of the angels: it would make it a federal crime for
anyone to fraudulently obtain information about your account from a
bank.
</P>
<P>
   But Dana LeJune(cq), a Houston attorney, says the devil is in
the details.
</P>
<P>
   LeJune should know, because he spends a good part of his time
trying to collect money owed to his clients. And in order to find
where these debtors are hiding their money, he says it is sometimes
necessary to trick banks into revealing if a deadbeat has an
account.
</P>
<P>
   No trickery, no money.
</P>
<P>
   LeJune and other attorneys who specialize in collections say
debtors routinely try to hide their assets, leaving bill collectors
with two options.
</P>
<P>
   One is to file legal papers with every bank in the area looking
for an account that can be legally seized. While fees vary from
state to state, LeJune says Texas banks typically charge $500 per
search, making such a tactic prohibitively expensive.
</P>
<P>
   The second alternative is to hire private investigators who, for
a fee, hunt down a debtor's assets, often by misleading bank
employees.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it was ads placed by private investigators offering
their services to collections attorneys that caught the eye of Rep.
Jim Leach, R-Iowa, who chairs the House Banking Committee. Leach,
with the help of the American Bankers Association, crafted a bill
known as H.R. 30 that would curb the practice.
</P>
<P>
   The bill says that a person could get up to five years in jail
for ``knowingly making a false, ficticious or fraudulent
statement'' to a financial institution in order to get customer
information. If the fraud is commited in connection with another
crime or if there is a ``pattern of illegal activity,'' the maximum
penalty is doubled. Hearings will be held this spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Mr. Leach's view, `` explained committee spokesman David
Runkel, ``the privacy argument is more important than the
difficulty that comes about as a result of collecting on a
judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't believe that the only way people have been able
to collect on judgments over the past number of years has been to
use illegal means to obtain financial information,'' Runkel said.
``It defies logic. People do owe money and other people pay up. It
is just part of the way the world works.''
</P>
<P>
   LeJune finds people like Runkel hopelessly naive.
</P>
<P>
   ``That couldn't be further from the truth,'' LeJune said. ``They
obviously have not done collection work in Texas, because if they
had, they would know how ridiculous that sounds.''
</P>
<P>
   Runkel says the bill was blocked in the last Congress because of
objections from people like LeJune. He declined to speculate on how
it may fare this year.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
