<HEADER>
A6772 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN17-COX     02-16 0676
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Luxury dream apartment? Try a locker in Penn Station
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ Rumor has it that Hillary Rodham Clinton has
been apartment shopping in New York and is considering a co-op on
Manhattan's Upper West Side. She should have checked with me first.
I spent a year there one week looking for a place to live. I could
have told her that it's sometimes referred to as the ``city that
never sleeps'' because no one can afford a place to...
</P>
<P>
   It was 1960. My husband of five months had just been bumped out
of his junior co-pilot slot in Chicago and shipped to an even more
junior one in New York. The airline offered to pay for our move,
but we didn't own enough to bother. We had a little English car,
some clothes, a few pots and pans, and a set of dishes
</P>
<P>
   his grandmother had given us for a wedding present.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be an adventure,'' I remember saying to him as we hung
onto a strap in the aisle of the Port Authority bus that was
shuttling us from LaGuardia into the city. His reply was a wan
smile.
</P>
<P>
   The airline sprang for two weeks in a mediocre hotel (the
elevators were working and so were the girls in the lobby) while we
searched for a place to live. Sunday morning we split up the Times
classifieds and took turns reading to one another. I went first:
``19th St. West. Bright, sunny studio. $400.'' My husband rolled
his eyes and told me to keep looking. I read another: ``77th St.
and 3rd Ave. Studio, neat. Good location. $625.'' Same response.
</P>
<P>
   Ugly reality was beginning to break through our youthful
naivete. We may have been from out of town, but it didn't take a
skyscraper to fall on us. The only place we could afford to live in
this town was beginning to look less like our dream apartment and
more like a locker in Penn Station. Time for a different approach.
</P>
<P>
   Early the next morning we contacted a rental agent, told him
what we were looking for and how much we could afford. He didn't
laugh, but he did take a phone call during our chat. Big smile:
``Yes, Mrs. Gotrocks, I have a beauty on Fifth near the park. Four
bedrooms, four baths, library, two fireplaces, and maid's room.''
There was a pause as he listened intently to the caller and then
casually added, ``Somewhere in the neighborhood of $150.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's our kind of neighborhood,'' I enthused to my husband.
</P>
<P>
   The rental mogul hung up and turned back to us. Right away, I
told him I wanted one of those too. He tilted his head as though
bemused, sniffed once, and said he didn't think so. ``That's $150
per room.'' I ran up the numbers in my head and figured it out _ at
that rate, our housing budget would buy us three-quarters of a room
in a crummy neighborhood and we'd have to hope the missing
one-fourth wasn't the one with the plumbing.
</P>
<P>
   Anxious not to waste too much time on the pair from Podunk who
were taking up space on his Oriental, he half-heartedly handed my
husband a list. ``Try these and give me a call if you find
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   A couple of dejected kids hit the pavement and over the next two
days, we saw it all _ everything we could afford, anyway. There was
a studio on 53rd Street with a mattress on a shelf and the kitchen
cabinets painted shut. Another on 9th Avenue had the bathtub in the
kitchen, the toilet down the hall, and cockroaches everywhere. When
exhaustion set in, we settled on one room in the Village with a
purple toilet, and the stove in the living room. It wasn't pretty,
but we could pay the rent.
</P>
<P>
   If the rumor is true, the first lady is planning on moving into
a luxury, pre-war building where a two-bedroom apartment sells for
$700,000. A far cry from frying bacon next to the sofa bed, but who
knows where she's going to end up after she's dug into her savings
to bail out Bill.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail to: 320 East
Madison, Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or email: eschuett(at)nwonline.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
