<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Unlike home movies, video has reflections and, yikes,
inflections
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ The last time I saw these shards of my youth they
were in a World War II ammunition box in Dad's basement. I wasn't
in that box alone. Brothers, cousins, uncles, aunts, long-gone
loving pets, and a great grandpappy I never knew were there. We sat
together, wound tightly around 16-millimeter reels _ a
generation-and-a-half of silent home movies.
</P>
<P>
   On Christmas Day in my Waco living room I held the whole ammo
box's contents in one hand, a brute feat made possible by
technology.
</P>
<P>
   My brother had copied them all, chronologically, on one two-hour
video cassette, a most magnificent gift.
</P>
<P>
   From the first national Boy Scout Jamboree in 1936 when my dad
and his brothers did a trapeze act for Franklin Roosevelt, to my
taking of a bride nearly five decades later, it's all on one reel
now.
</P>
<P>
   So, is this the near-death experience: having your life
fast-forward before your eyes. Thank goodness for the pause button.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing everything again for the first time on video accented
what we didn't record then and what we record now: voices.
</P>
<P>
   All I can say is, thank heavens.
</P>
<P>
   Thinking about the indignities we've recorded from the mouths of
our babes in their formative years, I'm relieved to know there's no
way that I'll be similarly revealed.
</P>
<P>
   It's inglorious enough to be filmed at age 4 with a six-gun
holster around your bare belly, a cowboy hat sagging over your ears
as you fire at flood lights in the living room. Yes _ ahem. That's
me. We are left to imagine the sound effects I supply from my
crouched position, sort of a ``kew, kew.''
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, we have a 1987 home video of our oldest son, at 5.
He's also wearing a cowboy hat, but armed with a miniature guitar.
He is strumming, so to speak, a tune for his infant brother's
benefit.
</P>
<P>
   ``My name is Cowboy Buddy,'' he sings as he lyrically describes
how he fights bad guys, how he'll ``shoot and shoot and shoot'' if
need be.
</P>
<P>
   Talk about embarrassing. Let's invite all his high school
friends over.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, children aren't the only ones whose secrets are
better preserved in the silence of a home movie.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1952 home movie we have my dad showing off a newborn me in
his arms, strong and invincible.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1987 home video we have me holding up our youngest son as
he performs one of his first sounds: a slobbery motor-boat against
my upper arm. Then we get my startled yelp as the teething child
tries out a newborn incisor on unsuspecting Daddy's flesh.
</P>
<P>
   Home movies betrayed no yelps.
</P>
<P>
   Today's children are forever to be haunted by the high pitches
of their voices as they say childish things on tape. For all my
children know, I had my current mellifluous voice when I emerged
from the womb, and could sing ``Born Free'' with the ease I do
today.
</P>
<P>
   I shudder to think what will happen in years to come when
today's children start to run for public office, and when some
political hit man gets his hands on another's old home videos,
evidence sure to disgrace any statesman or stateswoman.
Undoubtedly, some day the pursuit of truth about candidates' past
lives will demand it.
</P>
<P>
   We'll see the unauthorized airing of grade-school tapes showing
a presidential candidate singing ``I'm a Little Teapot'' while
doing the gotta-go-to-the-bathroom dance that only a PTA program
can inspire.
</P>
<P>
   I'm telling you, this will destroy great people.
</P>
<P>
   As for me, I revel in the solemn silence as my long-lost
childhood purrs through the VCR. I never said anything embarrassing
as a child, to my recollection.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is editorial page editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald,
Waco, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
