<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-16 10:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6777 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEALTHBRIEFS17-COX     02-16 0926
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTHBRIEFS17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HEALTHBRIEFS: Drugs, light combat SAD symptoms
 &HT;    (EDS: This is a compilation of health stories which moved to the
wires this week.)
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Growing up in Pennsylvania, Tamara Alexander remembers
how bad she began to feel around September each year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd become lethargic and moody and tearful, and I'd have a lot
of temper tantrums, starting from the time I was 10,'' says
Alexander, now 28 and a secretary at Emory University. ``I spent
much of my adolescence thinking I'm just an unhappy person.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until she turned 23 that Alexander's boyfriend
suggested she might be suffering from seasonal affective disorder _
depression caused by a shortage of sunlight during the fall and
winter months.
</P>
<P>
   A psychiatrist confirmed the diagnosis, prescribing the
antidepressant Prozac. Alexander also tried light therapy, spending
several hours a day in front of a specially designed box that gives
off a powerful exposure of full spectrum light to mimic natural
sunlight.
</P>
<P>
   Both therapies helped Alexander significantly, and they are the
only methods routinely prescribed to treat the disorder, which
afflicts an estimated 10 million Americans. Winter blues _ milder
seasonal depression _ affects another 14 million people. For
reasons not entirely clear, four times as many women suffer from
SAD and winter blues as men.
</P>
<P>
   But many people who have SAD symptoms also try alternative
remedies, or use them to supplement light therapy and
antidepressants. Some of those treatments show promise _ St. John's
wort, for instance _ but doctors urge caution when trying
alternative methods.
</P>
<P>
   People who truly have SAD, and not other depressive disorders
that might mimic it, usually start treatment with antidepressants
such as Prozac or Paxil and light box therapy, says psychiatrist
Jeffrey Kelsey, assistant professor of psychiatry and behavioral
sciences at Emory University.
</P>
<P>
   Other treatments that might help: monitoring what you eat and
drink and taking brisk outdoor walks during sunlight hours. And if
you can swing a winter vacation, go to someplace sunny, Kelsey
advises.
</P>
<P>
   As for over-the-counter products or herbs, use caution, he says.
``Often medications that treat anxiety can worsen depression,''
Kelsey says.
</P>
<P>
   Taking sample of newborns' DNA useful tool, some parents find
</P>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ In the freezer next to the frozen orange
juice, in a little foil pouch, Micky Cradit's mom keeps a sample of
his DNA.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven months ago, Micky became one of the first babies
genetically fingerprinted under a program _ now being proposed as a
state law _ that allows hospitals to take a newborn's blood sample
for future DNA identification. Not a bad idea, thought Micky's mom,
who also happens to be a lab tech at the Florida Department of Law
Enforcement's DNA lab, where blood samples are typically used to
find criminals.
</P>
<P>
   ``DNA analysis is a powerful thing and a wonderful tool and
we're just starting to tap into all that can be done,'' said Rona
Kay Cradit.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, Micky's venture into the high tech world of DNA
analysis began long before his birth, when the problem of child
abductions made national headlines with the disappearance of Adam
Walsh. A year after the 1982 kidnapping and slaying, FDLE created
its Missing Children Information Clearinghouse, which is
shepherding the program. So far, 1,300 babies have taken part in
trial sampling.
</P>
<P>
   The number of abducted children has remained fairly constant _
about 4,600 nationally every year _ but public attention to the
problem has intensified. Florida had 2,089 children reported
missing or abducted in 1997. But those numbers include children
lost at the mall or missing only briefly before being found.
</P>
<P>
   High profile cases like JonBenet Ramsey's have only increased
concern and generated ideas to help find children. Among them are
several home-test kits that use a child's saliva for analysis.
</P>
<P>
   Mandating the sampling would ensure it is available to all
parents at a reasonable cost, said Rep. Bob Starks (R-Casselberry),
who drafted a Florida House bill. The kit costs only $1.40 and
hospitals can be reimbursed for the procedure through the state, he
said. Hospitals could choose to charge patients more than $1.40 for
the service.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, North Carolina started a similar program using a
federal grant with elementary school children. But when the grant
stopped, so did the program, Starks said.
</P>
<P>
   Medical conditions illustrated in 3-D
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ ADAM Internet Health has acquired a library of videos
that can be used to illustrate _ in three-dimensional animation _
various medical conditions as they appear inside the body. The
announcement of the purchase from an Austrailian development
company came from the Atlanta-based company.
</P>
<P>
   ADAM's use of the Net is aimed at exploiting the growing use of
``streaming'' technology that lets computer users download and
watch video, said Robert S. Cramer Jr., ADAM's chairman and chief
executive. The company also depends on increasing use of broadband
technologies like digital subscriber lines and cable modems.
</P>
<P>
   But ADAM also will work CNN Newsource Sales, a Time Warner
company, to distribute the new video content to television
stations, which can use it to illustrate health and medical news
coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ADAM recently announced a change of its name to reflect its new
Net-reliant strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
