<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-16 10:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6780 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OXBOW17-COX     02-16 0584
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OXBOW17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Oxbow building power plant in Costa Rica
 &HT;    By Susan Spencer-Wendel
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Oxbow Power Corp. broke new ground last
week in the Central American power industry, starting construction
of a $70 million power plant it will build, operate for 15 years
and then turn over to the Costa Rican government.
</P>
<P>
   Called a build-operate-transfer agreement, the West Palm
Beach-based company says it will finish the ``build'' part of a
geothermal plant in northwestern Costa Rica by April next year.
It's the first BOT plant agreement in Central America, and the
first BOT geothermal outfit in all Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   ``We intend to make this plant a showcase of what we can do
there,'' says Oxbow Power President Bud Cherry. Co-owners of the
plant with Oxbow are Marubeni Corp. of Japan, a Costa Rican company
and the project financiers which include the InterAmerican
Development Bank, Cherry says. Oxbow and Marubeni put up $20.5
million of the $70 million cost.
</P>
<P>
   Oxbow Power is the most profitable affiliate of Oxbow Group, an
energy and minerals conglomerate privately held by Palm Beach
resident William ``Bill'' Koch. Oxbow Group, with 1998 revenue of
$475 million, ranks No. 482 on Forbes magazine's list of the Top
500 private companies.
</P>
<P>
   Oxbow's primary businesses are generating and selling
electricity, and mining and marketing coal and other energy
commodities. Forbes estimated the company's 1998 net profit to be
$50 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Costa Rican project is the company's seventh power plant and
its fifth geothermal unit. Oxbow also has a geothermal plant under
construction in Mindanao, Philippines, and starts construction on a
coal-burning plant in eastern China in a few months, Cherry says.
</P>
<P>
   In 15 years, Oxbow and its partners expect to recoup all their
investment - plus a nice profit - before turning over the plant to
Costa Rica's national utility.
</P>
<P>
   Cherry says BOT's are good deals for developing countries and
are gaining popularity throughout the world. The host country gets
the plant, technology and expertise for free, he says.
</P>
<P>
   The Costa Rican national utility owns two geothermal plants in
the same region, but awarded the bid to build the third to Oxbow
and Marubeni in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Geothermal plants use naturally occurring steam found thousands
of feet in the earth to turn turbines to generate electricity.
Oxbow bills geothermal as one of the most environmentally friendly
methods of power generation.
</P>
<P>
   One drawback of geothermal plants, though, is they must be built
where the steam occurs. And that is near volcanoes or in earthquake
zones where the earth's crust is thin and easier to drill through.
</P>
<P>
   The Costa Rican project is near a dormant volcano and in a
seismically active area, Cherry says.
</P>
<P>
   Oxbow Group _ at a glance
</P>
<P>
   Headquarters: West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Lines of business: Generating and selling electricity; mining
and marketing coal and other energy commodities.
</P>
<P>
   Employees: 900 worldwide, including 100 in West Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Operations: Mines and plants in various states, and power plant
projects in the Philippines, China and Costa Rica.
</P>
<P>
   Estimated 1998 revenue: $475 million.
</P>
<P>
   Estimated 1998 net income: $50 million.
</P>
<P>
   As estimated by Forbes. Oxbow does not disclose.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Spencer-Wendel writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
