u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDITOR-MAKEOVER17-COX     02-16 0496
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITOR-MAKEOVER17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fashion editor kisses the tomboy look goodbye
 &HT;    By Cara Anna
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The ponytail is still on the dashboard
of my car, wrapped in a red rubber band.
</P>
<P>
   The eyebrows are just plain gone.
</P>
<P>
   What better way to kick off a monthly makeover series, I
figured, than to have one myself. We could headline it, ``Fashion
editor leaps, then looks.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, I like how it turned out. Chase Thomas (of Chase Salon in
West Palm Beach) was creative, funny and patient during what turned
out to be five hours in the chair, makeup and all.
</P>
<P>
   My fault. ``With you, we started from scratch,'' Thomas said
cheerfully, stepping back yet again and squinting.
</P>
<P>
   We certainly did.
</P>
<P>
   I grew up a tomboy. My thick hair had been long and straight for
the past decade, and my morning routine consisted of applying
lipstick and concealer, then grabbing a tissue and rubbing it off.
I was dull but happy.
</P>
<P>
   Then I got The Insult.
</P>
<P>
   A model who shall remain nameless came by the office one day to
show off a line of cosmetics. Miffed that I wasn't going to write a
story about it, she leaned in and sneered, ``How can you be a
beauty editor if you don't even wear makeup?''
</P>
<P>
   As silly as the question was, it sounded like a challenge.
</P>
<P>
   A makeover seemed like a simple enough experiment. Here was the
chance to be glamorous, at least until I slept on it. The only rule
was that I be open to anything.
</P>
<P>
   Chase already had a plan. He wanted to put highlights in the
hair, cut it short and tweeze the eyebrows into oblivion.
</P>
<P>
   Strange, it was just as everyone predicted in the days preceding
the makeover. ``If it's that obvious,'' I wondered, ``why didn't
someone throw me down and do this before?''
</P>
<P>
   Chase whacked off the ponytail and trimmed the rest into sort of
an egg shape, then put blonde highlights along the hairline from
ear to ear. In the rest, he massaged a golden-auburn glaze. ``It
goes with your coloring,'' he explained.
</P>
<P>
   Then he bleached the eyebrows, colored them the same shade and
spent a good hour plucking. It opens the eye area, he said.
</P>
<P>
   It also gave me time to worry. Will the eyebrows grow back?
(Yes.) And if they do, will they be two-tone? (Unless I keep
bleaching them, yes.)
</P>
<P>
   For makeup, Chase used light eye shadow colors near the nose to
widen my close-set eyes. He applied medium-brown eyeliner and
mascara on the upper lids, and drew the mauve, Sandra
Bernard-shaped lips himself.
</P>
<P>
   I can't say I could duplicate it the next morning. The same old
lipstick and concealer got the same old dab-and-wipe.
</P>
<P>
   But the hair was a nice surprise. Right away I stumbled on a
nice, tousled style _ wash it, sleep on it, rake fingers through it
in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad you can't do that with clothes.
</P>
<P>
   Cara Anna writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
