   So soon after the device went on the market, Chris became the
first person in the Miami Valley, Ohio area with a vagus nerve
stimulator (VNS). It was implanted last June by Dr. Theodore
Bernstein, a neurosurgeon who works with Simkins at the Wallace
Kettering Neuroscience Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Indications are the VNS will at least be as effective as brain
surgery, Simkins says, and certainly safer for many of the 25
percent of epileptics whose seizures can't be controlled by
medication. It works by stimulating areas in the brain that are
associated with starting, stopping and preventing the electrical
short circuits that cause seizures in the 2.5 million Americans
with epilepsy.
</P>
<P>
   Eight months after the surgery, Simkins says Chris' seizures
have decreased by more than 75 percent. It seems more like about 30
percent to Margaret, but she says the ones he has are shorter and
less apt to wake up her and her husband.
</P>
<P>
   Chris, 20, wouldn't know. His seizures strike only when he's
sleeping. ``I've never realized when my seizures took effect,'' he
says, ``and I've never remembered them.''
</P>
<P>
   He has seen the holes he kicked in walls, though. He remembers
the two times in the year before surgery that he needed stitches
for cuts near his eye. He knows his bedroom furniture is bolted to
the walls.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been pretty lucky he hasn't damaged himself more,''
Margaret says. ``He's had some violent ones where he gets out of
bed and kicks or rolls on the floor and hollers.''
</P>
<P>
   There's no obvious cause for 60 percent of epilepsy cases, but
head injuries are related to the rest and suspected in many others.
Babies with epilepsy, for example, might have been injured during
birth.
</P>
<P>
   Chris had his first seizure when he was 6 months old. When he
was about 5, his petit mal seizures would cause him to lapse into a
faraway stare, or maybe climb under his school desk and punch
himself. ``His teacher thought he was just making trouble,''
Margaret says.
</P>
<P>
   The diagnosis came at 7. The batteries of tests never really
seemed to stop.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just kind of stumbled into Dr. Simkins,'' Margaret says.
They were looking for a different, more communicative doctor just
as Simkins was opening his clinic.
</P>
<P>
   In Chris, Simkins found a patient whose various medications
helped no more than slightly and whose brain monitors didn't
identify the problem in a particular part of the brain that could
be surgically removed.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can always stick electrodes in people's brains and operate
on people,'' Simkins says, but the low success rate isn't worth the
risk. Vagus nerve stimulation, on the other hand, has regularly
reduced seizures by 40 percent to 50 percent in clinical trials,
with rates continuing to drop for as long as three years after the
surgery.
</P>
<P>
   When Simkins proposed the VNS implant, ``It was not a hard
decision,'' Chris said before the operation. It required just two
small incisions, under the collarbone to insert the device and in
the neck to attach its wiring to the nerve. If it didn't help, it
could be removed.
</P>
<P>
   His epilepsy wasn't debilitating. It didn't stop Chris from
setting up a seasonal lawn-mowing business or playing sports,
including softball and soccer after high school. But he couldn't
spend a night outside his bedroom, with his parents nearby, and his
medications left him too drowsy to try college even if they were
only minimally effective.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to get these seizures under control,'' he said
last spring. Sure, he was nervous about the operation. But this was
his best hope.
</P>
<P>
   The device is about the size of a small pocket watch, according
to manufacturer Cyberonics Inc. Chris and his parents can use a
magnet to start it any time, and Simkins has used a wand to adjust
the stimulator's strength and schedule several times. It's
currently at a low strength and a quick cycle, on for seven seconds
and off for 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ideas behind this device go back hundreds of years,''
Simkins says, to the observation that epilepsy patients who rubbed
their arms as seizures began seemed to stop their progression. The
vagus nerve is one of the body's largest; it sends impulses from
the brain to control heart rate, bowel function and limb movement,
among other things, and it carries impulses back to the parts of
the brain that are especially active during seizures.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only can vagus nerve stimulation abort a seizure, it can
also help prevent a seizure,'' Simkins says. How? ``We have no
idea. We know the areas it affects, but we're only scratching the
surface.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stones have noticed a mystery of their own since adding a
puppy to the household after Chris' surgery. ``This dog seems to
know when he's going to have a seizure,'' Margaret says, ``and runs
back there before we do.''
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the family often feels as though it is running in
place as it waits for continued improvement. Chris wants to go to
college. He wants a career in law enforcement. ``I'd like to get
into the Air Force if I ever got rid of the epilepsy,'' he says.
``I want to get on with my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Margaret hopes he'll soon have more freedom, to drive or simply
to be left alone. They all find their encouragement in the progress
he has made so far, of which they're reminded every morning. As
Margaret says, ``We're definitely getting more sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Lamb writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
