<SLUG> BC-EPILEPSY-SYMPTOMS17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Symptoms of Epilepsy
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Subtle signs of epilepsy are often missed at a time when a
physician's diagnosis could lead to early treatment. These symptoms
can indicate either epilepsy or an unrelated condition and are
cause for a medical checkup, according to the Epilepsy Foundation
of America.
</P>
<P>
   Periods of blackout or confused memory.
</P>
<P>
   Occasional fainting spells in which bladder or bowel control is
lost, followed by extreme fatigue.
</P>
<P>
   Episodes of blank staring or brief periods without responding to
questions or instructions, especially in children.
</P>
<P>
   Sudden falls by a child for no apparent reason.
</P>
<P>
   A convulsion, with or without fever.
</P>
<P>
   Clusters of swift jerking movements by babies.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
