<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-16 10:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6789 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOMELESS-NEIGHBOR17-C     02-16 1553
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMELESS-NEIGHBOR17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Homeless man's pride a strong survivor of ordeal
 &HT;    By Ron Wiggins
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, FLA. _ My appointment with 61-year-old Bill
DeRuiter was for 8 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   When at 8:10 a.m. I knocked on his dumpster and asked, ``Bill,
are you up?'' a gravelly voice rumbled from within.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, sir, I overslept. Can you come back?''
</P>
<P>
   Good acoustics, I thought. Of course I could come back. The fact
is, I felt funny about interviewing a man who lived in a trash bin
beside a convenience store.
</P>
<P>
   I had been referred to DeRuiter by his old Palm Beach High
School classmate, Chuck Otterson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew Bill in high school, Class of '56,'' Chuck told me.
``He was a fine athlete and very popular with boys and girls. I
think he went on to marry and put a couple of daughters through
Cardinal Newman.''
</P>
<P>
   Chuck said that other classmates in the area were aware of the
man's plight, and they had been known to drop by the store to say
hello. Usually, Otterson said, they would bring a six pack or a
carton of cigarettes. Outright offers of money embarrass DeRuiter,
but if you offer to buy him something to eat, he likes a Cuban
sandwich slightly warmed in the microwave, and if you insist on
buying him something to wash it down with, he will mention that
your best value is a quart of Milwaukee's Best at 99 cents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean is that all we can do?'' Chuck asked. ``It doesn't seem
right, somehow. I guess the thing that I keep thinking about is
that if Bill DeRuiter can end up on the street, it can happen to
anybody. Maybe he would talk to you.''
</P>
<P>
   When I first approached De-Ruiter at the West Palm Beach
convenience store he calls home, he had just finished pumping gas
for an elderly woman who tipped him a dollar. I introduced myself,
saying right up front that one of his old high school buddies was
worried about him, and would he mind being interviewed?
</P>
<P>
   DeRuiter's leathery, sun-ravaged face split into a dazzling
smile of recognition. ``Sure, I know you, Ron. I read your stuff in
the newspaper.''
</P>
<P>
   Injuries prevent working
</P>
<P>
   At first, he balked at the write-up. He said that he hit the
skids after his second marriage ended, leaving him depressed. A bad
back and two operations to have disks removed have left him unable
to work for sustained periods.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people know me, and I don't want them coming down
here trying to give me money. I've gotten myself into this mess and
I have nobody to blame but myself. Now if you're going to ask me a
bunch of stupid questions, we're going to stop right now.''
</P>
<P>
   So what if I stuck to smart questions?
</P>
<P>
   Fair enough, he nodded, and although our first appointment found
DeRuiter under the weather, some days later we did sit down beside
the waist-high metal dumpster that is his shelter from cold and
rain these past three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dumpster is clean,'' he said. ``Just cardboard in there,
no garbage. The garbage goes into that other one,'' he said,
indicating a companion container next to his sleeper.
</P>
<P>
   DeRuiter's life these past few years is days telescoped into
days, one with little to distinguish it from another. The store
closes at 11 p.m. and opens at 6 a.m. DeRuiter does not sleep well
even if he stays warm and tolerably dry in his metal box. Road
noise is magnified. Passersby awake and alarm him.
</P>
<P>
   He is a night watchman without portfolio, a flesh and blood
extension of the convenience store, keenly aware that without the
indulgence of the management, DeRuiter would have to sleep
elsewhere. He tidies the grounds and washes windows. On Mondays he
stocks shelves. When he sees anyone struggling with the gas pumps
or in a hurry, he pumps gas.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes DeRuiter is tipped; often patrons take the smiling
service for granted.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever the manager has a job that DeRuiter can handle, he taps
on the window and DeRuiter rises out of his lawn chair by the
dumpster. He trades such services for smokes and an occasional
sandwich.
</P>
<P>
   DeRuiter recalls a night two years ago when thieves smashed a
window with a concrete block and took off with cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I jumped up and called 911. A train hit the car on the
crossing, and killed everybody inside, three or four of them as I
recall. I went there and gathered all the cigarettes I could
salvage and gave them to the manager.''
</P>
<P>
   Wake-up rattle
</P>
<P>
   The manager, DeRuiter volunteers, ``rustles me out in the
morning if I oversleep.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He is one fine Haitian gentleman,'' he declares. ``They don't
come no better.''
</P>
<P>
   If this peculiar symbiotic relationship between a homeless man
and a store endures, it may have something to do with DeRuiter's
manner, almost courtly in a way reflexive to men who were reared to
respect elders and to address everyone as ``ma'm'' or ``sir.''
</P>
<P>
   But when you threaten the one possession DeRuiter has left _ his
dignity _ he will let you know it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will not beg,'' he said. ``I have never stood at an
intersection with a sign, no sir, I will not do it.''
</P>
<P>
   But if you do ask DeRuiter if he will accept money, he fixes you
directly with amazing blue eyes and says ``Yes sir, I will,'' and
when you give it to him, he says, ``thank you.''
</P>
<P>
   DeRuiter is blade thin and does not look like he gets enough to
eat. When he's asked if he eats enough, he answers matter of
factly: ``Not really.''
</P>
<P>
   But then he cracks a smile and laughs. ``Let's put it this way,
Ron, I'm happy to be alive.''
</P>
<P>
   He dates his depression to the breakup of his second marriage
and the collapse of the house cleaning business with his second
wife. Before that, he was a surveyor for Ranger Construction Co.,
and somewhere in his work history, according to a classmate, he
managed a gas station.
</P>
<P>
   Children?
</P>
<P>
   ``Four,'' he answered. ``Two by my first marriage and my second
wife had two.''
</P>
<P>
   And here, probing was not welcome. DeRuiter's children know
where to find him, and they do visit him on holidays and birthdays.
When I got nosy, he brought me up on stupid question charges.
</P>
<P>
   He could not pinpoint precisely when he became homeless. The
unraveling, he guesses, began about five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't work since those disks were taken out, and I've had a
cancer taken out of my nose.'' The skin on his face, hands and neck
are fearfully damaged from thousands of hours spent under the
relentless Florida sun, reading in his lawn chair by his dumpster.
</P>
<P>
   Out of `the system'
</P>
<P>
   When I suggested that DeRuiter's depression could be treated and
that his back problems would surely qualify him for disability
payments, it was clear that I had touched a nerve.
</P>
<P>
   ``Disability? No, sir, I tried that and got beat. And I'm not
taking no damned drugs!'' Then he backed off a turn, and smiled.
``Cigarettes is enough drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   I went into the store and bought a pack of Dorals. His friend,
the store manager, declined to be interviewed.
</P>
<P>
   When I returned, DeRuiter was shooting the breeze with Frank
Bowman, who works odd jobs and checks in on DeRuiter every day or
two. A police officer came out of the store with a cup of coffee
and waved amiably in DeRuiter's direction. ``Hi, Bill, how's it
going?''
</P>
<P>
   Bowman told me that De-Ruiter knows dozens of people.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of people who like Bill. They stop by and give
him books and magazines. I know he reads a lot. There should be
something better for him than a dumpster.''
</P>
<P>
   When DeRuiter and I picked up the thread of our conversation he
remembered that he had gotten a bit testy with some of my
aggravating questions and said quietly, ``You can't always treat
people the way you feel.''
</P>
<P>
   In one phrase, it seemed, he had captured the essence of
civility.
</P>
<P>
   So, Bill, why not go into a shelter? Again, the testiness.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't sleep with the loud music and the television going.
People have asked me to stay with them, but I feel obligated, and I
won't do it.''
</P>
<P>
   I had saved my last question because I wasn't sure I wanted the
answer.
</P>
<P>
   What does Bill DeRuiter have to look forward to?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be 62 July 14 and get Social Security. When I get my
first check, I'll get my own little place.''
</P>
<P>
   And until then?
</P>
<P>
   ``When I get up in the morning, the manager gives me a cup of
coffee and I feel better. People stop by and say, `Hi, Bill,' and
it kind of gives you a lift. It picks you up.''
</P>
<P>
   A day or two later, DeRuiter mentioned to customer LaJan Gartner
that I was writing him up for the newspaper. She called to pass on
something for my story.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel safer when I'm at the store because Bill is there,''
the West Palm Beach legal secretary said. ``If you'll notice, it's
one of the cleanest convenience stores around. Bill pumps my gas
and is very thankful for anything I give him.''
</P>
<P>
   On Super Bowl Sunday I stopped by the store, and DeRuiter was
fiddling with a 5-inch battery-powered TV set someone had loaned
him to watch the game. Channel 29 was coming in like gangbusters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Isn't this something?'' he exclaimed, marveling. ``When it
gets dark it will be even better!''
</P>
<P>
   That was quintessential Bill DeRuiter, living life in the
moment, looking forward to something better, just hanging in there
until his 62nd birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
