<HEADER>
A6791 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANIMAL-ADS17-COX     02-16 0482
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANIMAL-ADS17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Animals favored in advertising
 &HT;    Jeffry Scott
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Guy walks into a bar, and the barkeep says to him,
``What'll ya have?''
</P>
<P>
   And the guy says, ``I'll have what the frog's drinking.''
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe the guy goes into a fast food joint and orders the taco
that's favored by a Chihuahua.
</P>
<P>
   Things like this seldom happen in life.
</P>
<P>
   Why is it, then, that they happen so often in TV commercials,
where animals seem to be challenging humans as product endorsers?
</P>
<P>
   The Madison Avenue menagerie includes frogs and lizards for
Budweiser, a Chihuahua for Taco Bell, gophers for BellSouth
Mobility, dogs for RCA, cows for Chick-fil-A and a beaver for
Planters Peanuts.
</P>
<P>
   Advertising experts say animals are eye-catching, memorable and
lovable, as well as less expensive and _ in some cases _ safer than
human endorsers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Budweiser frogs can do goofy things and convey the relaxed
nature of having a few drinks,'' says Richard Morgan, who covers
the ad industry for the trade paper Variety.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's politically incorrect to have humans doing the same
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Animals have long been a favorite with advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most memorable commercials of the '70s, for instance,
featured a dog biting sour cream salesman Sam Breakstone. And, in
the 1980s, Alex the dog fetched Stroh's beer.
</P>
<P>
   What changes, says Mark Dolliver, an Adweek magazine editor, is
the animals.
</P>
<P>
   ``A few years ago the popular dog was Jack Russell terriers,''
he says. ``Now it's a Chihuahua.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, breakthroughs in technology _ the so-called ``Jurassic
effect'' _ have made it easier to make animals seem to talk, as
cats do in a current Freshstep litter commercial.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all those goodies, you can make animals more likable than
people,'' says Morgan.
</P>
<P>
   Animals don't guarantee a campaign's success, says Luke
Sullivan, creative director for WestWayne, the Atlanta ad agency
that put gophers in the BellSouth mobility ad. ``They have to fit
the problem you're trying to solve or the market you're trying to
reach.''
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan's own agency ran a commercial for Publix Super Markets
that featured monkeys interrupting a family's picnic _ for reasons
that were unclear. The spot was short-lived.
</P>
<P>
   More successfully, the agency put gophers in the BellSouth
mobility ad because they look like office workers poking their
heads above cubicles.
</P>
<P>
   The agency has another animal spot in the works, a humorous
commercial for NAPA Auto Parts featuring a bear that eats a man.
</P>
<P>
   What the connection between that and spark plugs, oil filters
and fan belts?
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of that market hunts and camps,'' says Sullivan, ``so
it's relevant to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeffry Scott writes for The Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
