<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-16 10:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6792 &Cx1f; tad-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMMENTARY-BJT17-COX     02-16 0456
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMMENTARY-BJT17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE COMMENTARY BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These columns for release Wednesday, February 17, 1999 are
moving today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ There's a delicious new thrill running through
conservatives, who sometimes seem to like nothing more than scaring
themselves with lurid frights. This one has President Clinton
veering to the far left after escaping the impeachment posse. (Tom
Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers.) MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ As I sat down to write this, I intentionally
placed my late father's timeworn, quarter-sized green union button
on the desk in front of me, not only as a reminder of where I came
from, but as a notation of my personal lifelong support of the
American labor movement. I put the pin of Local 133 of the Club and
Restaurant Employees Union _ dad once had been a bartender _ so
that I wouldn't go off the deep end in what I had to say about the
sick-out against American Airlines and the paying public by the
Allied Pilots Association _ so arrogant that it initially ignored a
federal judge's demand that the pilots return to work. (Howard
Kleinberg is a former editor of the Miami News.) MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   SCHUETT-COLUMN _ GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ After relocating to New York
with my husband of five months, ugly reality was beginning to break
through our youthful naivete. The only place we could afford to
live in this town was beginning to look less like our dream
apartment and more like a locker in Penn Station. (Elizabeth
Schuett, a teacher and writer in Gibsonburg, Ohio, writes twice a
week for Cox News Service) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG-COLUMN _ It's inglorious enough to be filmed at age 4 with
a six-gun holster around your bare belly, a cowboy hat sagging over
your ears as you fire at flood lights in the living room. Yes _
that's me. We are left to imagine the sound effects I supply from
my crouched position, sort of a ``kew, kew.'' By contrast, we have
a 1987 home video of our oldest son, at 5. He's also wearing a
cowboy hat, but armed with a miniature guitar. He is strumming, so
to speak, a tune for his infant brother's benefit. ``My name is
Cowboy Buddy,'' he sings as he lyrically describes how he fights
bad guys, how he'll ``shoot and shoot and shoot'' if need be. Talk
about embarrassing. Let's invite all his high school friends over.
(Young, Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
