available for purchase in paginated form:
www.nytsyn.com/pageexpress.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS
</P>
<P>
   TVSURFER-COLUMN _ ATLANTA _ Highlights of tomorrow's TV viewing.
(Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE/MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH-BRIEFS _ A compilation of health briefs from the past
week. Subjects are: Seasonal affective disorder (SAD), DNA testing
on newborns, new medical technology. (Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   FASHION-MAIN _ NEW YORK _ Fall fashion week '99 continues.
Designers showing: Oscar de la Renta, Vivienne Westwood, Hugo Boss,
Mark Eisen and Richard Tyler. (Walton, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   FASHION-NOTES _ NEW YORK _ Runway notes and scene sidebar.
(Walton, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   FASHION-POSTCARD _ NEW YORK _ Greetings from New York
postcard-like story. (Walton, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   ACUPUNCTURE-THERAPY _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Palm Beach area
doctors and hospitals are embracing acupuncture and other ancient
forms of once-alternative healing. Not far from the CAT scans and
high-tech medicine practiced at St. Marys hospital, patients
receive accupuncture to ease pain _ by prescription. The AMA
devoted a whole issue to alternative medicine last November, and
more medical doctors are being trained in its use. We talk to some
of the M.D.s and others who use it about the growing blend of
traditional and alternative therapies. (Susman, Palm Beach Post)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   FASHION-DIARY _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Lesley Friedman is a
self-made woman. She created a temporary-lawyer business in New
York, sold it and became a multimillionaire, then retired early and
moved to Palm Beach, Fla., four years ago. Then she took a look at
herself. She never had the time before, she says. She and other
women at the law firm had purposely dressed conservatively, even
matronly. She got manicures when she remembered to, and she let her
naturally curly hair be. Makeup and styling really didn't make a
difference, she thought. ``Sometimes on dates, I would wear my
business suit,'' she says. She was too busy to bother. ``I had the
attitude of, `This is me, successful and smart. People are going to
like me no matter how I look.' '' Find out what happens after she
gets a head-to-toe (literally!) makeover. (Anna, Palm Beach Post)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR-MAKEOVER _ In the spirit of previously-named Lesley
Friedman, fashion editor Cara Anna treats herself to the makeover
works. (Anna, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   HOMELESS-NEIGHBOR _ WEST PALM BEACH, FLA. _ My appointment with
61-year-old Bill DeRuiter was for 8 a.m. When at 8:10 a.m. I
knocked on his dumpster and asked, ``Bill, are you up?'' a gravelly
voice rumbled from within. ``No, sir, I overslept. Can you come
back?'' Good acoustics, I thought. Of course I could come back. The
fact is, I felt funny about interviewing a man who lived in a trash
bin beside a convenience store. (Wiggins, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   EPILEPSY-SEIZURES _ DAYTON, Ohio _ Chris Stone starts to stiffen
up while he's sleeping, a sure sign a seizure is beginning. But
before he starts flailing and kicking, they see him let out a deep
breath and go limp again. The young man's seizures had grown
progressively worse through adolescence, and medication hadn't
seemed to help much when he met Dr. Robert Simkins 16 months ago.
Since 1990, Simkins had been part of research in Texas into a
device for treating epilepsy that was comparable to a cardiac
pacemaker. Soon after the device went on the market, Chris became
the first person in the Miami Valley, Ohio area with a vagus nerve
stimulator (VNS). Indications are the VNS will at least be as
effective as brain surgery, Simkins says, and certainly safer for
many of the 25 percent of epileptics whose seizures can't be
controlled by medication. It works by stimulating areas in the
brain that are associated with starting, stopping and preventing
the electrical short circuits that cause seizures in the 2.5
million Americans with epilepsy. (Lamb, Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   with EPILEPSY-SYMPTOMS (Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   (ATTENTION: Ohio, Texas editors.)
</P>
<P>
   ADS-ANIMALS _ Animals are playing an increasing role in
advertising. (Scott, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   HOLBROOK-TWAIN _ ATLANTA _ Hal Holbrook's mad as hell about a
lot of things, per a phone interview, especially as pertains to
today's politics, and he's letting his old pal Mark Twain say it
for him in yet another engagement of his beloved solo show on Feb.
17, his 74th birthday. Also speaks humorously of wife and companion
(``She's a loon''), actress Dixie Carter. (Hulbert, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) W/BIO BOX. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TESTDRIVE-AUDI _ Review of Audi Avant A6 sport wagon (DeVault,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS. MOVED FRIDAY.
</P>
<P>
   SHARP-DRIVING _ (Sharp, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   THE-MECHANIC _ (Carter, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
