<DOCNO> NYT19990216.0045 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-16 10:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6796 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOLBROOK-TWAIN17-COX     02-16 1106
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLBROOK-TWAIN17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Holbrooks uses Twains' wit for political revenge on stage
 &HT;    (EDs: W/BIO BOX at end of story.)
 &HT;    By Dan Hulbert
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Hal Holbrook is mad as heck about a lot of things:
politicians, tabloid journalists, junk-filled cable channels,
Shakespeare productions in Nazi uniforms, to name but a few.
</P>
<P>
   But the actor doesn't have to stew in silence. He has a secret
weapon named Mark Twain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been agitated and fed up with the political scene lately
_ the country's come unhinged, for God's sake!'' declares Holbrook,
``So I'm grateful for Twain to get things off my chest.'' He's been
performing ``Mark Twain Tonight!'' since he was 29 and will perform
it Wednesday, his 74th birthday, at the Fox Theatre. (He'll also
step in briefly next month for Brian Dennehy in the acclaimed
Broadway revival of ``Death of a Salesman.'')
</P>
<P>
   ``Twain was in top form on the idiocies of politics,'' Holbrook
continues, ``so I've added new material on that subject. These days
I just say the word `Congress' and the crowd goes beserk! They know
something hilarious is coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having Twain's wit at my disposal is revenge on all the morons
of the current scene,'' Holbrook adds with hearty, wicked laugh. He
sounds a Twainlike curmudgeon with his twangy Ohio-Massachusetts
accent (he modulates it to a Missouri drawl for the role) by phone
from his Los Angeles home. ``It's like having a machine gun: I get
to stand up there and mow 'em all down!''
</P>
<P>
   Harold Rowe Holbrook Jr. has performed ``Twain'' at least one
night in each of the last 45 years, sometimes slipping a show into
the odd pause between TV and movie roles. ``Twain'' is the sire,
and still king, of today's many solo shows. It's a compendium of
sly satire, crackerbarrel philosophy, timeless truths on human
foibles and excerpts from such Twain classics as ``The Innocents
Abroad'' and ``Huckleberry Finn.'' The show is so long-lived and
indestructible that it's almost taken for granted _ carved into the
American landscape like Mount Rushmore _ though it's hard to
imagine that Holbrook's ever done it better than now.
</P>
<P>
   After all, it was only recently that he caught up with Twain in
age. ``I've always played Twain as 70, as he was in 1905, because
by then he'd written all the pieces I use in the show. Accuracy is
important to me.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Making Twain authentic: Holbrook purchased a series of
turn-of-the-century photographs of Twain at his Connecticut home,
enlarged and mounted them on the floor and walls of a room in his
home. ``I stood there for hours studying the pictures, looking this
way and that, absorbing the body langauge, the way Twain tilted his
head or held his cigar.'' The six-foot actor wears a too-long
jacket to appear closer to Twain's height of five-eight.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Finding his sea legs: ``I went aboard a Mississippi steamboat
similar to one that Twain used to pilot. The decks were so tilted,
to let water run off, that to keep my balance I found myself sort
of shuffling, sliding my right foot out in front. Twain's gait was
described in exactly that way. So I keep the deck in mind when I'm
rehearsing the show.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Keeping it straight: Holbrook has returned to regional stages
in Shakespearean roles in the '90s. He'll play Shylock in an
upcoming production of ``The Merchant of Venice'' at The
Shakespeare Theatre of Washington, D.C. ``I do these roles because
I genuinely enjoy them; what I don't enjoy is seeing Shakespeare
jerked around to different periods. When they bring on the Nazi
uniforms, I don't buy it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Bliss at home (and on TV): In commercials for the Yellow
Pages, Holbrook plays second banana to actress wife Dixie Carter as
she uses the phone book to make make lavish purchases. Holbrook
grumbles or smiles ruefully in the background, playing a sort of
George Burns to her Gracie Allen: ``Dixie and I are often that way
with each other, so we've enlarged it into a kind of routine. I
call her a loon. She's very Southern and improvisational. I with my
New England background tend to be more organized. I watched her
pack the other day. She folded one dress very carefully, then a
second one, then closed the suitcase, saying, `I don't want
anything to get crushed.' `Crushed?!' I said, `There's nothing but
empty space in there!' She took seven suitcases. But she's utterly
adorable.''  &QR;  The other side of Dixie: ``My wife is an astute
observer of acting. I run my `Salesman' lines at home, and the
other day she said, `Hal, don't use a character voice, keep it in
your own voice. Remember, your dad was gone when you were young.
You had troubles with your own son. You've spent 50 years on the
road. You think you're not close to Willy Loman?'''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Not slowing down: ``I once woke up in Spokane and found my
flight was fogged in. I had to make a connection in Seattle for a
(``Twain'') performance that night. I told my stage manager to rent
a town car and meet me at the hotel. I took the wheel and we roared
286 miles across Washington _ luckily the snow had just been plowed
in the Cascades _ in just over three hours. That's an average of 86
miles per hour. I was 69 at the time.''
</P>
<P>
   THEATER PREVIEW
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark Twain Tonight!''
</P>
<P>
   8 p.m. Wednesday (Feb. 17). $19.50-$29.50.
</P>
<P>
   Fox Theatre, 660 Peachtree St. 404-817-8700.Hal Holbrook: At a
glance
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Background: Born Feb. 17, 1925, in Cleveland (same year and
city as Paul Newman). Raised mainly by grandparents in
Massachusetts. Graduated from Dennison College, Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Home life: Married 15 years to actress Dixie Carter; two
stepchildren; home in Los Angeles. Three grown children from two
previous marriages.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The script: Though he's performed ``Mark Twain Tonight!''
nearly 2,000 times, no two shows are exactly alike, since Holbrook
draws at will from 12 hours of material he's unearthed in libraries
and private archives across the country.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Awards: Tony for ``Mark Twain Tonight!'' (1966). Emmys for
``The Senator'' (1971); ``The Pueblo'' (1974); ``Sandburg's
Lincoln'' (1976).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Other roles: Film: ``All the President's Men'' (role of ``Deep
Throat,'' 1976); ``Julia'' (1977). Stage: ``I Never Sang for My
Father'' (Broadway, 1968); ``King Lear'' (Old Globe, San Diego,
1994). TV: ``Designing Women'' with Carter (also directed);
``Evening Shade.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Recreation: At 55, Holbrook skippered his 40-foot sailboat
from San Francisco to Hawaii _ 2,400 miles _ alone.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Hulbert writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
