<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Tuesday, Feb. 16, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Wednesday. If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOLS-RACE (San Francisco) _ Patrick Wong, Brian Ho and Hilary
Chen were turned away from the San Francisco public schools of
their choice for one undisputed reason: They are Chinese Americans.
By policy, Chinese American kids must score higher on admissions
exams than students of other races. The families of the students
filed a class-action lawsuit seeking to overturn San Francisco's
desegregation plan. By JULIAN GUTHRIE.
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOLS-LOWELL (San Francisco) _ At the vortex of the most
high-stakes lawsuit in the history of San Francisco's public
schools is Lowell High School, a fiercely competitive campus that
is being shaped by race. It is Lowell that required Chinese
American students to score higher than kids of other races in an
attempt to bring diversity into its hallowed halls. By JULIAN
GUTHIRE.
</P>
<P>
   CHINESE-CALENDAR (San Francisco) _ John Kim doesn't like to
discuss it, but there's no getting around it: he was born in the
Year of the Rabbit. ``It's not a pleasure being a bunny,'' he said.
``At work, you want to be taken seriously.'' Starting Tuesday, this
is the year of the rabbit by the Chinese lunar calendar. By JULIE
CHAO.
</P>
<P>
   FAT-PROTEST (San Francisco) _ Despite protests from fat
activists, a health club is refusing to budge from its new ad that
suggests that overweight people will be the first to be devoured by
hungry space aliens when the invasion comes. By ULYSSES TORASSA.
</P>
<P>
   TET-OFFENSIVE (San Antonio) _ Thirty-one years after the Tet
Offensive in Vietnam, one-time Air Force Airman 1st Class Alonzo J.
Coggins was honored for his bravery. By SIG CHRISTENSON.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   DRUGS-FOOD (Albany, N.Y. ) _ It's no mystery that many
prescription drugs don't mix well with each other and that taking
drugs with alcohol is almost always a mistake. But it may surprise
you to learn that sometimes food and drugs interact in ways that
may be bothersome or even harmful. The culprits may include such
seemingly benign and healthy foods as milk, leafy green vegetables
and grapefruit juice. By SYLVIA WOOD.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACHMENT-CLASS (Albany, N.Y.) _ Here's an opinion on
impeachment you didn't hear in the U.S. Senate last Friday: ``If
the sex helps him do his job better, so be it,'' said Kelly Davis.
She was telling the more than 100 students attending the ``Sex,
Lies and Impeachment'' class at the University at Albany that the
president should be held to a lower standard than most Americans.
By ANDREW BROWNSTEIN.
</P>
<P>
   MENSWEAR (New York) _ The fall '99 menswear collections opened
with an edgy salvo from Kenneth Cole, who didn't even bother to
acknowledge that there were any other colors but black, gray and
navy. Cole's collection, however, set the pace for everyone else in
terms of cut (sleek and boxy at the same time) and attitude (young,
urban, futuristic). By CYNTHIA ROBINS.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   KNAPP-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ The ad in USA Today, titled ``In
tribute to Reggie White,'' included a short letter signed by more
than 100 NFL players. The letter's conclusion was bold-faced: ``So
get ready, America, because we're standing with Reggie to defend
the Gospel.'' The point, however carefully veiled, seemed clear.
White has been criticized for his brand of Christianity only once.
He took up the anti-gay cause last spring, using religion as a
cover for bigotry. By GWEN KNAPP.
</P>
<P>
   OUTDOORS-COLUMN (Yosemite National Park, Calif.) _ America's
greatest lookout, normally crowded beyond comprehension, can now be
visited with only a few souls within miles. It is Glacier Point, of
course, where the scope of view is unparalleled. By TOM STIENSTRA.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   LYNCH-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ My friend and colleague, Fred
LeBrun, and I disagree on President Clinton. My thoughtful view was
that the president had committed felonies, ``high crimes` by
definition. Therefore, even if the effort to oust him was partisan
(it was), even if he'd been trapped into a position where he would
be tempted to break the law (he was) and even if you find his
policies generally acceptable (I do), he still had to go. LeBrun's
laughable position, on the other hand, was that it was all a put-up
job over a private sexual encounter, and that Clinton should stay.
By DAN LYNCH.
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ President Clinton survived
impeachment, but, thanks to the Monica Lewinsky scandal, his public
life will never be the same. It's safe to assume his personal life
has been similarly altered? By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
</TEXT>
