<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990216.0054 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-16 11:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6857 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOURNAL-RUSSIA-0217-C     02-16 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOURNAL-RUSSIA-0217-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    JOURNAL: CHANNEL-SURFING ZOO MONKEYS AROUND WITH MOTHERHOOD
 &HT;    EDs: Optional add begins at 600 words.
 &HT;    With Photo mug of Holmes and orangutan Photo to be placed in the
International folder on the Cox Server.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (k) Commentary
categories.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Russia _ As a snowstorm rages outside, what to
do on a deep winter afternoon while hanging around in your small,
musty Russian digs?
</P>
<P>
   Catch a soap opera or maybe some music videos on the tube.
</P>
<P>
   At the St. Petersburg Zoo, orangutans Monika and Rabu(CQ both)
are literally hanging around -- from the steel bars of their cage
-- watching TV. Sequestered upstairs in a makeshift nursery, their
three-month-old son Ramon is wearing Pampers and being bottle-fed
baby formula by a human.
</P>
<P>
   Such parental neglect is not what the zookeepers had in mind.
The orangutans were exposed to television with the hope that it
would help Monika learn how to be a better mother.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the St. Petersburg Zoo learned a fundamental lesson of
our century: merely turning on a television set does not make it a
tool of education.
</P>
<P>
   Monika, who came to the zoo as a toddler in 1987, was raised in
captivity and thus never taught the lessons she would have learned
in the jungles of Sumatra. When her son Ramon was born on Nov. 20
she showed motherly concern, but did not bond where it counted. She
showed no interest in breastfeeding.
</P>
<P>
   Zoo officials recalled reading about zoos in America that used
instructional videos to help primates like Monika learn what would
have been instinctively imparted in the wild.
</P>
<P>
   In St. Petersburg, they did not have the educational videos, but
they had a color TV set. They rigged it outside the cage in the
primate house in hopes that wildlife programs on Russian broadcast
channels would give Monika the right idea.
</P>
<P>
   It did not work. After a few days young Ramon was taken from his
mother to be fed by bottle and sleep in a crib complete with sheets
befitting a strapping young boy -- they are emblazoned with
automobiles.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, downstairs in the cages of the decaying 19th-century
zoo the television experiment continued.
</P>
<P>
   Rabu, the male orangutan, initially became so captivated with TV
that he ignored his mate.
</P>
<P>
   Monika was upset over being neglected. She stood between her man
and the TV screen. She grabbed him in an effort to distract him
from the set (complete with rabbit ears and a remote control --
which are out of reach of the pair).
</P>
<P>
   And eventually, she gave up and joined him, seeming to enjoy
cartoons, soap operas and music videos (though Monika became highly
excited one day when a nature program showed a lion).
</P>
<P>
   ``Now they've calmed down. They watch it together. If something
comes on they don't like, they do something else,'' says Yelena
Goraschenkova, veteran zoologist in the primate department.
</P>
<P>
   Their TV viewing is limited to no more than an hour a day and
monitored by the staff, who have been in contact with officials at
Zoo Atlanta and the Brookfield Zoo in Chicago for more information
about videotaped programs to inspire orangutan motherhood.
</P>
<P>
   Monika was already something of a local celebrity before her
exposure to television. Scientists from the Pavlov Institute gave
her art supplies in a comparative study on the development of
primates and human children. Some of her unquestionably abstract
artwork, in watercolors, crayon and pencil, was auctioned off at a
local gallery to benefit the zoo.
</P>
<P>
   Rabu also tried his hand at drawing. ``But Monika was far, far
better -- no comparison,'' says Goraschenkova.
</P>
<P>
   Coverage of Monika's plight hasn't exactly rivalled the story of
another Monica, even in Russia. But it has made the Russian papers
in a splash of sexual sensationalism. It was reported, not so
correctly, that Rabu had become a television addict and no longer
found Monika desirable, ruining the pair for life.
</P>
<P>
   But their love endures, confirmed when a male newspaper reporter
stepped too close to the cage to take a look at Monika, provoking a
jealous Rabu to spit at him, several times, and then caress
Monika's hand.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows).
</P>
<P>
   In a more momentous tone, with the country's economy in the
dumps and its politics not much better, some observers suggested
that Monika's story in a way reflects the plight of Russia today.
</P>
<P>
   The zookeepers had a notion of the way things worked at some
American zoos and so turned on the TV, an ultimately superficial
and unsuccessful experiment in the same way post-communist Russia
has tried and failed to emulate the democratic and free-market
West.
</P>
<P>
   But that weighty analysis runs much too deep. After all, it's a
pair of TV-watching orangutans who favor music videos over
documentaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``They like pop,'' says Natalya Popova, curator of the zoo's
primate exhibit.
</P>
<P>
   Yet wary about creating an impression that the zoo is creating a
couple of orangutan delinquents, she quickly adds: ``They haven't
developed a dependence on TV -- yet.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
