<SLUG> BC-AUTOS-LEASE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO BUY OR LEASE IS THE QUESTION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   To buy or lease. That is the question.
</P>
<P>
   It's one that's been around for some time, and while the answer
may seem easy, getting into a new set of wheels is no quick
decision or easy matter.
</P>
<P>
   The world of wheels is changing. Not only is the way one shops
changing, but also changing are the makes available and their
options and body styles. The answer to buying or leasing is both
simple and complex.
</P>
<P>
   Simply put, to lease can be less costly on paper than buying.
Your monthly payments will be less if you lease a vehicle. You will
be able to ``afford'' a more luxurious vehicle on a lease. But, at
what cost in the long run?
</P>
<P>
   A lease is very simple. You never own the vehicle. You may not
need a down payment (but you may need a ``cap-cost reduction,'' _
jargon for a down payment). Basically, the dealership ``lends'' you
the car for a certain number of months or years.
</P>
<P>
   When the lease is over, the dealership will sell that vehicle
for its residual value. The residual value is the price the
dealership believes the vehicle will bring on the used car market
two or three years down the road. So you are paying the difference
between the resale price and the agreed-upon price. Sounds good,
but there are a lot of potholes along the way.
</P>
<P>
   The most important thing to first consider is how much you
intend to use the vehicle. Mileage is the key. All leases allow for
a certain amount of miles a year _ 10,000, 12,000, maybe more. Go
above that number of miles and you pay somewhere in the
neighborhood of 15 cents for every mile over the agreed-upon number
in the lease. If you average 20,000 miles a year _ and lots of
people do that many and more _ you could be in for a dollar shock
when you return the vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   If you think you might want to buy the vehicle at the end of the
lease, get an agreed-upon price in writing at the outset.
</P>
<P>
   You don't just walk away at the end of the lease. If your
mileage is over the limit, you pay. If you don't return the vehicle
in salable condition _ check the lease stipulations before signing
_ you pay. And, should you have signed an open-ended lease (one
where the value of the vehicle will be determined at the end of the
lease), you could be in money trouble if that vehicle is not worth
what everyone said it would be. That has happened and could happen
again, especially if you buy a vehicle with no track record.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, lease contracts are now required to be more
understandable. You should know before signing the cost of the
vehicle, the interest you'll be paying, and the ins-and-outs of
allowed mileage, responsibility for repairs, maintenance and
insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of insurance, you should know the vehicle's value in
the event of a total loss. The original price? Don't be so sure.
Your insurance may only cover the price as a used car.
</P>
<P>
   Also check whether there is a termination fee. And what happens
if you decide to get out of the lease before the contract expires?
</P>
<P>
   A lease may also not be written in stone. In many cases, you can
negotiate factors from allowed mileage to acquisition fees.
</P>
<P>
   Leases can be a very attractive way to go, but before you sign
on the line, do your homework. Check on the ``up front'' costs
(that down payment) and other inception costs. Add up all the costs
before you decide if it's really a good deal for you _ not the
dealer.
</P>
<P>
   Whether you buy or lease, it always pays to do your homework.
Know what's in the marketplace. There are more choices than ever _
not just in cars, but also trucks, minivans and sport utility
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Before you lease or buy anything, think about what you need _ or
want _ to drive, and how it will be used _ work, play, family
transportation or all three.
</P>
<P>
   While every dealership has a deal for you, only you can tell how
good a deal it is. To do that you should know what the vehicle
costs, whether there are rebates or other incentives to be factored
in, and what you can expect for your trade-in.
</P>
<P>
   How do you find prices? Not by looking at the sticker _ that's
only a suggested retail price. Sign up for a service such as
Consumer Reports or AAA. For $10 to $15, they'll supply you with
the retail cost of the vehicle, the dealer's cost, and any rebates
or incentives being offered. These services will also give you the
value of your present vehicle, so you'll have an idea of what it
could be worth in a trade in.
</P>
<P>
   If you have access to the Internet, you can obtain these figures
there as well.
</P>
<P>
   One such service is offered by autosite.com. What's nice about
this service is that not only does it contain prices and other
information on all the makes and models, but you can do some
instantaneous comparison shopping. Can't decide between two makes
as to features etc.? Autosite will provide you with a side-by-side
comparison of the two models, similarly equipped.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet is becoming a valuable tool in the search for a
vehicle. Many dealerships are now on the Web _ Daewoo, the newest
car company to hit American shores, is planning to sell cars on the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Other easy-to-access sources of information on the '99 models
magazine publications such as Automobile's 1999 Buying and Leasing
Guide, or Consumer Reports annual auto-buying guide.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, when factoring in the costs, consider, the vehicle's
warranty. Many makers have extended the length of the factory
guarantees.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-99 1231EST &QL; 
