 PageExpress budget for the week of FEB. 15, 1999
<TEXT>
<P>
   PageExpress, a new service from The New York Times Syndicate,
consists of paginated pages built with content from Cox Newspapers
and The New York Times News Service. The pages are easy to retrieve
from a web site. You can use them just as they are or customize any
or all of the elements _ text, fonts, photos and graphics _ to suit
your needs.
</P>
<P>
   For more information on these pages, or to view a sample, use
your web browser to visit http://nytsyn.com/pageexpress.
</P>
<P>
   For the password to download and use the pages, call John
Gardner, pagination consultant for The New York Times Syndicate, at
917-224-4381 or e-mail him at pages &LR; nytsyn.com.
</P>
<P>
   Unless otherwise noted, pages are available after 2 p.m. Tue.,
Feb. 16.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FOCUS: CAMBODIA ROYAL(Available by 2 p.m., Fri., Feb.19) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Only a few monarchs left in the world really matter. And not one
has mattered for longer than King Norodom Sihanouk, Cambodia's
master of dramatic intrigue for the last 58 years.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: CAMBODIA-GENOCIDE: Twenty years after the Khmer Rouge fell
from power, a United Nations team of three legal experts is
scheduled this month to recommend to Secretary General Kofi Annan
whether to start action against the remaining Khmer Rouge leaders
living openly in Cambodia. Some form of international tribunal
likely will be proposed to hear evidence against the men who
masterminded the madness that left as many as 2 million Cambodians
dead in less than four years.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT: SWEEP AWAY SWEEPS?(Available by 2 p.m., Thu., Feb.
18):
</P>
<P>
   The sweeps _ when Nielsen Media Research measures the
demographics of local TV affiliates, so the stations can set their
ad rates _ are part of an antiquated system that is responsible for
a lot of what's wrong with network television today. ``If we don't
get serious and change our game, we're gonna be left in the dust,''
warns Steven Bochco, executive producer of ``NYPD Blue.'' ``We
ought to be reinventing the medium, changing the rules of the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   WITH: VIDEO REVIEWS: ``Practical Magic,'' ``Snake Eyes'' and
``The Governess.''
</P>
<P>
   WITH: CD REVIEWS: Kyle Eastwood's (Clint's son) ``From Here to
There,'' Libby Whittemore's ``Almost a Legend'' and country/rock's
Kelly Willis' ``What I Deserve.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NASCAR (Available by 2 p.m., Thu., Feb. 18) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR Winston Cup drivers this week turn their focus from the
season opener at Daytona to the season's second race, the Dura
Lube/Big K 400 at North Carolina Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FOOD: TAMALES IN MISSISSIPPI &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Oscar Orsby has been selling tamales on the street corners of
Clarksdale, Miss., for 17 years. He's part of an unlikely tradition
that shows things aren't always as black and white as they seem,
even in the deepest recesses of the Deep South.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: RECIPES: Mississippi Tamales, with dough, filling recipes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHEELS: CHEVROLET TAHOE Z71 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If bigger really is better _ and there's a segment of the market
that agrees with that theory when the goal is going off-road _ then
the '99 Chevrolet Tahoe Z71 is a certified winner.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: AT A GLANCE: Facts about the '99 Chevrolet Tahoe Z71
</P>
<P>
   WITH: SHARP DRIVING: It wasn't long ago that the automotive
industry was preparing the obituary of the minivan. It seemed
sport-utility vehicles were all the rage and certain to displace
the popular mom-mobile as the vehicle of choice for carrying people
and cargo in the safety of a large vehicle. Well, not so fast.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PERSONAL TECHNOLOGY: BLACK HISTORY MONTH &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For some, the arrival of February _ Black History Month _ used
to mean countless hours in the library searching for information on
such figures as Paul Robeson, Madame C.J. Walker and Bessie Smith.
But today, students and parents have another reference point: the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TECH TOOLS: I upgraded the other day to Windows 98. Oh,
wow, as the hippies used to say.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TECH BRIEFS: There was a time when shooting your own video
was impressive enough. How can you beat pictures that move? 3D
Video Inc. is selling a camcorder attachment that lets you record
video in 3-D.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TECHNOBUDDY: The fears surrounding Y2K are likely
overblown, but buy a little food just in case.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRAVEL: NEW ORLEANS' WINDSOR COURT HOTEL &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The mantra of the Windsor Court Hotel in downtown New Orleans is
details, details. Details such as the 175 roses flown in from South
America every Friday and placed in a priceless antique urn in the
lobby. The $8 million collection of English art and antiques
adorning common rooms. The afternoon tea poured in Wedgewood china
cups and accompanied by homemade scones and tarts.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: GEORGE WASHINGTON BICENTENNTIAL: The man who was ``first
in war, first in peace and first in the hearts of his countrymen''
will be honored this year as the George Washington Bicentennial
1999 officially begins Feb. 15 at the newly furnished Mount Vernon,
the Virginia home of the first president.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL BRIEFS: International travelers passing through some of
Canada's major airports to the United States may soon have fewer
bureaucratic hurdles to jump.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BOOKS: BLACK HISTORY MONTH &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   We call each February Black History Month, but it needs to be a
whole lot more than a revisitation of black history. With the focus
on the black experience, the view can be forward as well as
backward, which is _ or should be _ the goal of any study of the
past. Books have always done well to record and remind us of the
events that brought us to this time, this place.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: REVIEW: Patricia Cornwell writes a good story when she's
being Patricia Cornwell. She has an eye for detail and a stomach
for the gruesome aspects of crime, embodied in her regular heroine,
coroner Kay Scarpetta. Unfortunately, in ``Southern Cross,''
Cornwell's apparently trying to be Virginia's answer to Carl
Hiaasen, the wickedly funny writer who mocks all things modern in
Florida. And Hiaasen she isn't.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: SKUBE ON BOOKS: Allen Barra's sympathies are with Wyatt
Earp, but he is no hagiographer. His understated humor and his
sense of the ironic make ``Inventing Wyatt Earp'' part revisionist
history and part disquisition on the malleable meaning of legend,
with impromptu forays into film criticism.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: N.Y. TIMES BEST SELLERS LIST
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &AMP; HEALTH: IS IT JUST A COLD? &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's very important, doctors say, that people be able to
differentiate among a cold, a routine case of the flu and a
complication that commands medical attention.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: FLU TEST: The first practical diagnostic test for flu is
on the market this year.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: HEALTHY TEA: Sometimes there's hardly a better tonic for
what ails you _ whether it's a stuffy head or achy joints _ than a
nice cup of hot tea. Emerging research is suggesting that while tea
may not cure, it might help prevent many serious diseases, such as
cancer and heart disease.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: FONDA: Actor-activist Jane Fonda says she wants parents to
talk openly to their children about sex because her own parents
rarely did.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: HEALTH BRIEFS: Drug-resistant forms of the AIDS virus are
showing up more and more often, worrying doctors and patients who
fear they'll run out of treatment options before new drugs become
available.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
