<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-JOURNAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THE NAME OF `RESPECT,' A SHAKEDOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILLIPOV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BAKU, Azerbaijan _ This was a novel approach to airport
security.
</P>
<P>
   It was the dark, run-down departures hall of Baku's airport,
inside the security zone, between customs and passport control. The
two men who identified themselves as ``police'' wanted a passenger
to ``take a small package.''
</P>
<P>
   The passenger balked. What was that line they tell you at
airports all over the world? Never carry a bag for a stranger . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't you want to show us some respect?'' one ``officer''
retorted.
</P>
<P>
   The respect thing. The passenger had heard this before.
</P>
<P>
   The airport security man, who had introduced himself as
``Airport KGB,'' said it when he had offered to bump up an economy
class ticket to business class for a small fee. The airline
representative said it when he wanted to make that small fee a big
one. The customs agent a year ago said it when he had confiscated
the passenger's money.
</P>
<P>
   Trying not to sound rude, the passenger declined the police
officer's request and prepared for the worst.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
---- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Airports are a sore spot in the former Soviet Union. The Baltic
states have world-class airports, as does Kiev. But most seem to
operate on two principles: ``The customer is always blight'' and
``You can check in any time you like, but you can never leave.''
</P>
<P>
   For attempted extortion from foreigners, Baku beats them all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got hit up for a little `respect' at the ticket gate by two
Azeri cops,'' said Tom Goltz, author of ``Azerbaijan Diary: A Rogue
Reporter's Adventures in an Oil-rich, War-torn Post-Soviet
Republic.'' ``It was so incredibly shameless and brazen that it
really took me aback.''
</P>
<P>
   What happens at the airport is indicative of the times in a
country waiting to get rich from the oil under the Caspian Sea.
</P>
<P>
   For now, most of Azerbaijan is in shambles. Many regions have no
electricity, and even Baku experiences water and power shortages.
At least 700,000 people _ one tenth of the country's population _
are refugees from the territory Azerbaijan lost during a six-year
war with Armenia.
</P>
<P>
   Some foreign money has come in, via oil companies and
Western-style shops and eateries that have opened to support them.
</P>
<P>
   But little wealth has trickled down from the inner circle of
President Geidar Aliyev, 75, the authoritarian former KGB general
and Communist Party chief. The Aliyev government keeps its oil
dealings secret and suppresses all dissent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest businesses have ties to the inner circle of
Aliyev,'' says opposition leader Etibar Mammadov. ``And corruption
and bribery are so highly developed, there are huge obstacles to
anyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   That perhaps explains why Baku's airport, or at least the part
that is not reserved for VIPs, has no shops or cafes, which are
never profitable in corrupt societies. Instead of the market
identifying and meeting people's needs, Baku airport works on the
old Soviet principle of letting officials do it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The police were still waiting.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, if you don't want to carry something for us, maybe you'll
just pay us a small fee instead?'' one said. ``Out of respect.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Gentlemen,'' the passenger said. ``I respect you. But I just
gave all my money to the Airport KGB.''
</P>
<P>
   They didn't know what to make of that. The passenger strode off
to passport control, where the border guard was waiting.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Filipov is the Globe's Moscow bureau chief.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
