u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-BIDDERS-ART-BOS &LR;      02-16 1483
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-BIDDERS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE OLYMPIC SCANDAL, US CITIES CARRY TORCH FOR 2012 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A graphic is being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.)  
 (a and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MITCHELL ZUCKOFF  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Each city has a fancy logo, a multimillion-dollar budget, and
more endorsements from Olympic medalists than a mountain of
Wheaties boxes. Most of all, each has a dream.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is, they all have the same dream.
</P>
<P>
   Despite cascading revelations of corruption within the Olympic
movement, a record eight US cities are vying to host the 2012
Summer Games _ the next potential chance to stage the Olympics on
US soil after the 2002 Winter Games in Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   The sheer number of US cities bidding for the 2012 Olympics is,
by itself, a tribute to the enduring lure of top-flight athletes,
five-ringed flags, two weeks of the world's undivided attention,
and billions and billions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of all eight bid efforts, contacted last week, said they
were thoroughly unruffled by the still-unfolding scandal involving
allegations that IOC members took payoffs and gifts from Olympic
host cities, including Salt Lake City and Sydney. All expressed
nothing but the upbeat optimism and blithe enthusiasm expected of
Olympic hosts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The scandal has actually helped us,'' said Nick Vehr,
president of Cincinnati 2012 and, fittingly, a public relations
executive. ``It has convinced everybody that the playing field is
going to be level in the future. That other game that occurred off
the field won't be going on. We view that as a silver lining in
what is a very dark cloud.''
</P>
<P>
   Susan Loder, bid coordinator of the San Francisco-based Bay Area
Sports Organizing Committee, said: ``The Olympics is a dream, an
ideal, and neither this scandal nor any other that I could imagine
is going to tarnish the beauty of the Olympics.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Cincinnati and San Francisco, the 2012 bidders
are Dallas, Houston, a combined Baltimore-Washington effort, New
York, Los Angeles, and a Florida proposal that includes Tampa and
Orlando. Each has paid $100,000 to $150,000 to secure its place as
a bidder, and each has won required support from local government
officials to pursue the Games.
</P>
<P>
   Three other cities, Boston, Chicago, and Seattle, had been
expected to bid, but all dropped out before a Dec. 31 deadline.
</P>
<P>
   The United States Olympic Committee will choose one of the
cities as the US candidate for 2012 based on comprehensive final
bids due in March 2000. The USOC winnowing process will occur in
late 2002, and the US choice will then go before the International
Olympic Committee. The IOC is scheduled to choose the 2012 host
city in the fall of 2005.
</P>
<P>
   For now, though, the US bidders are focused on the domestic
competition _ stressing to anyone who will listen their cities'
natural beauty, easy access, modern facilities, love of tourists,
and can-do spirit. At the same time, all are downplaying potential
problems such as 100-degree summer days, drenching humidity,
traffic gridlock, and acts of God large and small, from mosquitoes
to tornadoes to earthquakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're the ideal choice. Florida is differently positioned than
any other place on the planet,'' said Ed Turanchik, president of
the Florida 2012 bid effort. ``Atlanta was traumatized by the
crowds. We handle those crowds every year.''
</P>
<P>
   ``New York is the only international capital that has never
hosted the Olympics,'' countered Dan Doctoroff, head of NYC-2012.
``There were 197 nations at the Atlanta Games. Every single one of
them could have found a neighborhood in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Houston is a natural,'' offered Susan Bandy, executive
director of the Houston 2012 Foundation. ``We're a well-known
international city with great amenities, wonderful airports, plenty
of hotel rooms, and probably the best corps of volunteers in the
country.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, all eight bidders eagerly boast about the
luminaries who have loaned their names and reputations.
</P>
<P>
   The Bay Area group is heavy on skaters, including Peggy Fleming,
Kristi Yamaguchi, and Brian Boitano, with former secretary of state
George Shultz thrown in for good measure. Houston trumps Shultz
with former President George Bush, plus Olympic stars Carl Lewis
and Mary Lou Retton, whose father-in-law is an executive with the
bid team.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas weighs in with Ross Perot Jr., Cowboys owner Jerry Jones,
and sprinter Michael Johnson. DC-Baltimore has the longtime
television host of the Olympics, Jim McKay, as well as Oriole Cal
Ripken. Cincinnati has astronaut legend Neil Armstrong and
basketball great Oscar Robertson, a 1964 Olympian.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles has decathlon hero Rafer Johnson and swimming star
Janet Evans, as well as Olympic impresario Peter Ueberroth, who led
the city's organizing committee for the 1984 Summer Games. Florida
has Olympic softball star Dot Richardson and soccer phenom Michelle
Akers. New York, which had hoped to bid for the 2008 Olympics until
the USOC decided there would be no US bidder for those Games, is
still rebuilding its all-star list.
</P>
<P>
   Though each bid group says its venues, supporters, and plans are
far and away the best, all try not to violate the first rule of
Olympic diplomacy: Never trash the competition.
</P>
<P>
   But with promises of anonymity, several bid organizers and close
Olympic observers were willing to handicap the field. There is a
vague consensus that Washington-Baltimore will offer a hard-to-beat
bid on the strength of location and already advanced organization,
and that either Dallas or Houston will be in the running until the
very end. San Franciso gets credit for the best scenery, and
Cincinnati is considered a potential spoiler that benefits from a
wholesome image. Florida is viewed as a mixed bag, with excellent
resources but doubts in some minds that the IOC would share the
world stage with Mickey Mouse.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles and New York are wild cards, having waged low-key
stealth campaigns, thus far. New York is still getting its plans
together and Los Angeles is banking on its reputation as a
successful past host.
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of the current tumult, the USOC is positively
buoyant about the number of bidders and the prospect that by the
time one is chosen, the scandal will be a distant memory.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's going on now is a painful exercise for us. It is
excruciating,'' said USOC spokesman Mike Moran. ``It took 100 years
for us to build the brand, and in less than 100 days it has been
tarnished. We've got a job to build this back up. But the cities
still want it. The Games are the Games and the athletes are the
athletes. But the other stuff has to change.''
</P>
<P>
   Each city expects to spend millions of dollars in the domestic
phase of the competition, with Los Angeles working with the
smallest budget and most others budgeting between $3 million and
$10 million. None has a firm idea how much it will cost 13 years
from now to actually host the Games.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the process, all the cities will have to conform to
rules the USOC enacted in November 1997, more than a year before
the scandal broke, that strictly limit contacts with USOC and IOC
members, set a $50 cap on gifts (rising to $150 in the final phase
of competition), and spell out detailed ethics and disclosure
requirements.
</P>
<P>
   At an October 1998 conference of bid cities, ``We gave a fanny
pack, a pin, and a water bottle, with a combined value of $7.63.
And I think we might have been the big spenders in the pack,'' said
Turanchik, head of the Florida 2012 effort.
</P>
<P>
   One unresolved question for all the bidders is a requirement
that arrangements be made _ either through local governments or
some other ``third party'' _ to pick up the cost of any budget
shortfalls if the 2012 Games run in the red. That requirement
helped to knock Seattle from the bidding, and at least some others
are expected to follow.
</P>
<P>
   Once a winner emerges from the US field, it will face the rest
of the world. Among the international cities expected to be in the
competition are the losers in the chase to host the 2008 Summer
Games, the winner of which will be chosen in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Early handicapping gives Beijing front-runner status for 2008,
with bids also expected from Toronto; Paris; Osaka, Japan; Kuala
Lumpur, Malaysia; Buenos Aires; Istanbul; and Seville, Spain.
</P>
<P>
   The US bidders have to hope that Toronto doesn't pull away from
the crowd and win the 2008 Games; under Olympic protocol, the Games
are expected to rotate from continent to continent. If Toronto were
to win the 2008 Games, the US cities probably would have to keep
smiling and bidding at least until 2016.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's OK, I'm young enough to hang in there,'' said
Turanchik. ``Whenever it comes, it'd be worth the wait.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
