<HEADER>
A6927 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN18-CO     02-16 0535
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN18-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   DISPATCHES FROM DREAMSVILLE
</P>
<P>
   (''Dispatches from Dreamsville'' is an occasional series in
which readers share their memories of growing up in small-town
America. Back then, or at least the way we remember it, life was
like a dream.)
</P>
<P>
   By Michael M. Alvarez
</P>
<P>
   Special to Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   ``Tell me a story.''
</P>
<P>
   It was more of a command than a request.
</P>
<P>
   His name was Tony. And he was built like a lifesize Tonka truck.
</P>
<P>
   I had no place to hide, so I did the only thing I could to save
myself from getting hammered into a bloody pulp.
</P>
<P>
   I told Tony the most interesting story I knew, making it up as I
went . . . and so began my life as a writer.
</P>
<P>
   The long bus rides to and from school would have been completely
unbearable had it not been for my newfound talent as a storyteller.
I discovered, much to the delight of our beleaguered bus driver,
that I could entertain a majority of the students by telling them
stories.
</P>
<P>
   They weren't just any stories. They were stories with characters
that had the same names as those of my listeners; they seemed to
perk up and pay more attention when the hero was named Hector and
the hero's girlfriend was named Helen.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of stories and a couple of years later, I discovered that
I could save myself a lot of wear and tear by writing down my
stories and passing out copies instead of delivering them orally.
</P>
<P>
   My dear mother gave me one of the most invaluable gifts anyone
can receive _ she forced me to learn how to touch type the summer
before I entered high school.
</P>
<P>
   I figured my storytelling days on the bus were over. But there
was just one hitch: my large friend Tony didn't like to read.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tell me a story,'' demanded Tony.
</P>
<P>
   Towering a good two inches above me, Tony gave me his best
I'll-pulverize-you-if-you-don't look. But deep down I knew Tony
would never hurt me.
</P>
<P>
   I negotiated a compromise. I would read him the story I had
typed the night before instead of just spewing it out off the top
of my head. Tony said he liked my typewritten stories better
because they flowed more smoothly.
</P>
<P>
   Bless his heart. Aside from being my greatest fan, Tony was also
my first critic.
</P>
<P>
   I lost track of Tony through the years. The scuttlebutt in my
hometown was that he had been killed in Vietnam. Others said that
he had died from a drug overdose. There was also speculation that
Tony had married a wonderful woman and moved to parts unknown.
</P>
<P>
   That last story was the one I preferred to believe. I'd like to
think that things turned out well for Tony.
</P>
<P>
   Every time I sit down to write, I listen carefully . . . so
intently that I almost hear the voice of my special friend who
unknowingly helped me to become a writer by voicing every reader's
wish:
</P>
<P>
   ``Tell me a story.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael M. Alvarez is a freelance writer living in Tucson, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   (If you have a story to share, send it to ``Dispatches from
Dreamsville,'' c/o Joe Murray, Cox Newspapers, P.O. Box 151108,
Lufkin, Texas, 75915. A photo of the writer is optional. If your
article is used, you will receive $25.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
