<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-16 13:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6928 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTOS-SUVS-BOS &LR;      02-16 1826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTOS-SUVS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUVS: THEY COME IN ENDLESS VARIETIES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just when you think you've seen all the sport-utility vehicles
imaginable, along come more. And the end isn't in sight. Let's face
it: Sport-utes are hot. And, if that market should cool, some
manufacturers are hedging their bets by offering hot performance
wagons. (Yes, the old station wagon, the model declared dead on its
wheels a few years ago, is having a revival, not as a family
hauler, but as a sports wagon.)
</P>
<P>
   Also, if a passenger car is not for you, and you're not into a
sports-utility or a wagon, there's always a pickup truck. One
neighbor just bought a small pickup to go along with an older and
larger family-hauling Oldsmobile sedan. Another neighbor, a single
woman, just bought a full-sized Dodge pickup. In both cases the
choice ``made sense.'' The small pickup provides low-cost
transportation and serves as a utility hauler. It has rear,
swing-out doors so the kids can fit in otherwise tight quarters.
The other neighbor liked the full-size pickup's ride and the
handling plus the fact it is a great vehicle for camping trips.
</P>
<P>
   And we haven't even addressed the world of minivans yet.
</P>
<P>
   Minivans, like the SUVs, are considered a part of the truck
family in the motor vehicle world. They are another alternative to
both the old station wagons and to SUVs, especially since Chrysler
and Dodge offer all-wheel-drive options on the Town &AMP; Country and
Caravan.
</P>
<P>
   As car sales cool, manufacturers turn to SUVs to boost sales.
Lincoln did it last year with the Navigator, and now Cadillac has
seen the light with the Escalade. And while it may seem there's no
need for these huge models, both basically plusher versions of the
Ford Explorer and GMC Yukon, they are selling. Ford is even
thinking of building an even larger SUV to top Chevrolet's mammoth
Suburban.
</P>
<P>
   This fall, BMW will join the SUV market with its
``sport-activity vehicle.'' The X5, as BMW is calling it, really
isn't an SUV, says the carmaker. Instead, they portray it as a
luxury-car alternative.
</P>
<P>
   It will boast a number of seating configurations, a cargo load
platform that extends at the push of a button, a 5-series
touring-style split tailgate, and four-wheel drive. The X5 is said
to be longer, wider and lower than a Mercedes M-class SUV. The X5
is being built in Spartanburg, S.C. and will be available in a
number of engine choices, including a high-performance V8. It will
be priced a bit higher than a 5-series wagon, so guess around
$50,000.
</P>
<P>
   Taking aim at the sport utility crown is the new Jeep Grand
Cherokee. The new Jeep may look a lot like the old, but is far
different in ride, handling and room. There's a new engine, new
all-wheel-drive system, new seating, and new transmission. Jeep
even has taken the spare tire out of the cargo area and put it
underneath for added room. The Quadra-Drive system is designed to
keep the Jeep going even if three wheels lose traction. The new
4.7-liter, V8 offers better mileage and 30 percent lower emissions.
Add a long list of luxury and comfort amenities and you have quite
a package.
</P>
<P>
   Now that Jeep is part of the DaimlmerChrysler family, the
company has a strong one- and two-punch approach in SUVs. The
Mercedes M-class, priced right with top of the line Jeep and Ford
Explorer products, is my choice as the best all-around sport-ute,
especially with this year's introduction of the V8-powered M430.
</P>
<P>
   Lexus, which last year entered the market with the innovative
RX300, has an all-new, full-sized LX470. The Lexus is based on the
likewise all-new Toyota Land Cruiser. These new SUVs are aimed at
becoming the ``kings of the 4WD' vehicles, and boast new stability,
an Automatic Height Control system allowing the driver to raise the
body by up to 2 inches at the push of a button, and a spacious
interior.
</P>
<P>
   The luxury market for SUVs keeps growing. Unlike other makers,
GMC is not pushing ``car-like'' in its ads; instead it is stressing
the ``truck-like'' strength of its models built on truck frames.
GMC has two luxury models in its SUV line, the full-sized Denali
and compact Envoy.
</P>
<P>
   Worth checking out is the all new Suzuki Grand Vitara. Starting
at around $18,000, Suzuki says its Vitara is the only V6-powered
mini-sport-ute and calls it ``unbelievably quiet.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all SUV's have to be expensive: Honda, Kia, Toyota, and
Subaru have competent sports-utes that are easy on the pocket and
fun to drive. Ford is expected to join the mini-sports-ute field in
the near future.
</P>
<P>
   Ford, which is still king of the hill in sports-utes, has added
features for safety, comfort and the environment for '99. A Reverse
Sensing System (a whole-range rear warning system to alert drivers
of objects to avoid when backing up), side air bags, and engines
with low-emissions can be found on the Explorer, Mercury
Mountainer, Expedition and Lincoln Navigator. For shorter drivers,
Ford's huge Expedition has optional power-adjustable brake and
accelerator pedals that can be adjusted up to three inches.
</P>
<P>
   One of the complaints about SUVs, especially smaller ones, is
the uneasiness felt as the vehicle leans on turns. The new Land
Rover Discovery Series II has a computer-assisted system that
should allay this unsettling feeling. The Discovery's ACE (active
cornering enhancement) system _ which uses hydraulic levers that
counter the lateral tilt of the vehicle's body _ counters this
feeling. This second generation Discovery has added room, and also
adds an electronic hill descent control that supplements engine
braking on steep hills by automatically applying the brakes as
needed.
</P>
<P>
   SUVs are coming in many shapes and styles. One of the more
unusual is the new Isuzu VehiCROSS which could be mistaken for
something other than an SUV. But this small vehicle will go
anywhere, and from reports, handles quite nicely without any of the
roll of other SUVs. It's tight on space, but handles four
passengers. It is palette-challenged, however: This fully loaded
vehicle ($29,000) is available in only three colors.
</P>
<P>
   Just to play it safe, BMW brought back its 5-series wagon after
a three-year absence and is said to be bringing out a 3-series
wagon shortly after the turn of the century. Makers like BMW know
that not everyone is happy with the ride of a sports utility
vehicle _ no matter how ``carlike'' the manufacturers claim it to
be. If you want sports car handling and performance, along with
extra space, one of the new breed of wagons from Europe may be for
you. Some have cargo capacities equal to a sport utility; others
give preference to design and handling over utility.
</P>
<P>
   For the performance-oriented driver who needs the space of a
wagon, the Audi A6 Avant includes Tiptronic _ a transmission that
allows one to shift through the gears without a clutch, and that
also can be used as an automatic.
</P>
<P>
   This spring, Saab is bringing out a wagon version of its new
9-5. The wagon will be Saab's' first since the '70s. Audi, Volvo,
Mercedes, Volkswagen and BMW wagons are all available with
all-wheel-drive, making them great choices for an all-around
vehicle, especially for New England winters. The only holdback is
the price _ most range the mid-30s to mid-50s. For those who feel
the SUV still has the advantage because of height off the road,
check out the Volvo Cross-Country: It sits almost as high as most
SUVs. The VW Passat (around $23,000) deserves a good look, not only
for its price, but also as it shares many of its mechanics with
Audi.
</P>
<P>
   In the minivan field, Chrysler the leader (and originator) of
these vehicles has new competition. Honda offers an all new
Odyssey. The Odyssey has more of everything and it even tops
Chrysler with two powered doors in the EX model. The new Odyssey is
larger than the previous model (still available as the Isuzu
Oasis). Odyssey offers lots of seat configurations _ the rear seat
can even be folded flat on the floor and with the seats out, a 4 x
8-foot sheet of plywood can be placed inside). While it doesn't
offer all-wheel drive, it does have optional traction control.
</P>
<P>
   Ford is pushing safety in its redesigned Windstar. The new
minivan offers dual power-operated sliding doors, a reverse sensing
system to warn of objects at the rear of the vehicle, and head and
chest side-impact airbags. The Windstar gets a 5-star rating in
crash tests, and Ford says its V6 engine is the cleanest running of
any minivan.
</P>
<P>
   All new for '99 are the Mercury Villager/Nissan Quest. While
these vehicles are not as large as other minivans, for this model
year they have been enlarged by 5 inches to provide additional
cargo and passenger room. Both now have four (two which are
sliding) doors.
</P>
<P>
   Still the benchmark for all the minivans are the Chrysler Town &AMP;
Country, Dodge Caravan and Plymouth Voyager. Within the Chrysler
line are multiple choices in size (the Grand Caravan is 13.3 inches
longer than the standard Caravan). The truly plush and fully loaded
Chrysler Town &AMP; Country comes with dual climate control for driver
and passenger, heated seats and all-wheel drive.
</P>
<P>
   The news in trucks continues to be doors, the more the better.
The added doors make getting into the rear of an extended cab model
a breeze.
</P>
<P>
   Even though I don't see the need to own a truck, I recently
gained a new appreciation of their added comfort, along with the
added doors. In the process of moving, I used an F-150 Ford that
rode and handled almost as well as a car. Add to that comfortable
seating and great visibility and you have a vehicle that even my
wife conceded would be fine to own.
</P>
<P>
   Now I can see why my neighbors have turned to trucks as either
the household's first or second vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   About the only objection I found with the Ford was the tonneau
cover over the cargo area. While it adds a nice look, and is a
blessing in rain or snow, I found it almost impossible to snap back
into place during recent cold snaps.
</P>
<P>
   New for '99 in the truck field are the Chevrolet Silverado and
the GMC Sierra. An easy way to describe these new full-sized
pickups is to use Chevrolet's words: ``bigger, faster, stronger,
and smarter.'' In the compact truck field, Nissan offers a nice
performing Frontier.
</P>
<P>
   While foreign manufacturers have left the full-sized pickup
field alone up to now, that is about to change. This spring Toyota
will launch its Tundra, which is being built in Indiana and has a
V8 engine and the capacity ``to haul more and tow more.''
</P>
<P>
   Toyota says the vehicle will ``set a new standard in the segment
for handling, ride comfort, and interior noise isolation.'' The
Tundra will be available in two- or four-wheel drive, two-door
regular cab with an eight-foot bed or a four-door Access Cab with a
6 1/2-foot bed. The Access Cab will feature exterior handles on
each door for easier access.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
