<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-16 13:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6935 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-GOP-BOS &LR;      02-16 1050
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-GOP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR GOP, IT`S TIME TO LISTEN TO AMERICA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For weeks, Senate Republicans have sat silently in
their seats listening to the impeachment trial as they watched
their public approval ratings plummet. Now, leading Republicans
say, the best way to rebuild the tattered party is once again to
sit silently _ but this time listening to the American people.
</P>
<P>
   The future prospects of the Republican Party could be determined
by the way the GOP handles the transition from an unpopular
impeachment trial to the legislative calendar and Campaign 2000.
The first step in the rebuilding process will begin in the next few
weeks, as Republican governors join with congressional leaders at
town hall-style meetings.
</P>
<P>
   The forums, titled ``Listening to America,'' are intended to
focus public attention on the top four legislative priorities:
preserving state and local control over education dollars, saving
Social Security, improving national defense, and providing tax
cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Republican National Committee Chairman Jim Nicholson said the
biggest fight with Democrats could be over tax cuts _ a fight
Republicans like. Nicholson, who recently made headlines by joking
that ``every day at the RNC feels like an eternity,'' sounded
euphoric as he envisioned the public focusing on tax cuts instead
of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will be a distant memory,'' Nicholson said about the
impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   The continuing problem for Republicans, however, is they will be
hard-pressed to pass any of their major initiatives over a
presidential veto, possibly leaving the GOP with few
accomplishments to tout in the upcoming campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our 2000 plans depend a lot more on what happens after
impeachment than what is happening now,'' said Republican pollster
Glen Bolger. ``We have to get things done on key issues. On the
other hand, the Democrats have zero incentive to help by passing
any legislation. It is not going to be an easy road back.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republican Party's problem is well documented. A recent New
York Times/CBS poll, for example, said the party is viewed
unfavorably by 52 percent of Americans, with half of those who
identify themselves as conservative Republicans saying the party's
handling of impeachment will make it harder to elect GOP candidates
in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders, however, said the polls obscure a silver
lining: The GOP is stronger than ever at the state level, with
Republican governors in 31 states, representing nearly 70 percent
of Americans, including traditionally Democratic states such as
Massachusetts and Rhode Island.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to remain true to the principles of the party, and we
need to be listening carefully to the people we serve,'' said
Montana Governor Marc Racicot, who is helping coordinate the
Listening to America forums. ``We need to recognize that it is
their government, and we work for them. It is our best hope.''
</P>
<P>
   If Republicans are right, the party's strength at the local
level might be the political equivalent of finding the yellow brick
road after a tornado.
</P>
<P>
   ``If any Democrat thinks that they are entering the era of beer
and skittles, they are wrong,'' said Governor Frank Keating of
Oklahoma, chairman of the Republican Governors Association, quoting
what he called one definition of nirvana. ``To the average
American, Republicans have shown at the state level they can
provide the answers.''
</P>
<P>
   Keating acknowledged that the trial, in the short term, ``has
been calamitous for Republicans. But in the long term, if anything,
it will have a positive impact.''
</P>
<P>
   Keating said it could take months for Republicans to recover,
but the party eventually will be applauded for its impeachment
action, while Democrats might be mired in the legacy of a tarnished
president.
</P>
<P>
   To GOP leaders, it is ironic that their party is viewed as
needing national healing, when it is Clinton who committed the
offenses that resulted in impeachment. Republicans remember how
difficult it was for the party to recover from Watergate, when
Democrats scored large gains in the midterm elections in 1974 and
watched Jimmy Carter ascend to the presidency in 1976. When Gerald
Ford became president in 1974, he both healed and divided the party
by pardoning former President Nixon. But Ford was clearly the
party's leader.
</P>
<P>
   Yet today, at another critical juncture for the GOP, the party
does not have an obvious leader. For decades, the party has been
led by the World War II generation, exemplified most recently by
President Reagan, former President Bush, and former Senate majority
leader Bob Dole.
</P>
<P>
   But some Republicans see a silver lining in the lack of
leadership. Former House Speaker Newt Gingrich retired from office
and is no longer the lightning rod of the party. A little-known
Illinoisan, Representative Dennis Hastert, is now speaker, and
Senate majority leader Trent Lott, though bruised in the eyes of
some for his leadership of the Senate trial, is not viewed as a
divisive, acerbic figure in the way Gingrich was.
</P>
<P>
   Most likely, the GOP leadership will be determined not by the
impeachment drama, but by the fight for the Republican presidential
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   It is noteworthy, analysts said, that much of the Republican
presidential field comes from outside of Congress: Texas Governor
George W. Bush, former Red Cross President Elizabeth Dole, former
Tennessee Governor Lamar Alexander, publisher Steve Forbes, and
former Vice President Dan Quayle.
</P>
<P>
   Of the three members of Congress expected to get in the GOP
race, Senator John McCain of Arizona probably has the strongest
shot at the nomination because he plans to run as an outsider and
reformer who doesn't fit the Senate mold. McCain bucked the
Republican Party in his fights for campaign-finance legislation and
tobacco regulation.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Senator Bob Smith of New Hampshire has filed
candidacy papers, and Representative John Kasich of Ohio is poised
to enter the field.
</P>
<P>
   While many of these presidential prospects have criticized the
president and some have called for his resignation, those who are
not members of Congress have the luxury of separating themselves
from the impeachment trial.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-99 1305EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
