<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-16 13:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6937 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-SENATE-BOS &LR;      02-16 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-SENATE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE MAY EMERGE MORE UNIFIED THAN EVER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Senator Phil Gramm was railing against a Democratic
plan for censure, his Southern drawl echoing throughout an
underground hallway in the Capitol. Suddenly, he spied a target
coming down the hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, that's a sweet lady right there,'' shouted Gramm, a
Republican from Texas, blowing kisses in the direction of Senator
Dianne Feinstein, the California Democrat leading the push for
censure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hello, tough guy,'' Feinstein playfully shouted back, as she
kept walking.
</P>
<P>
   The encounter was brief but intriguing. A day earlier, the two
senators had sparred on a Sunday morning talk show, spitting snide
remarks back and forth on the topic of censure. By the next day,
they were laughing about it. And while Gramm and Feinstein may not
have moved closer together on the ideological spectrum, their
exchange seemed to indicate a flash of bipartisan fondness, despite
their month trapped together in the Senate chamber.
</P>
<P>
   And in the end, that may illustrate a kind of impeachment
victory. Despite a series of partisan votes, and, at times,
forceful disagreements, senators say the process has prompted as
many cross-party discussions as any political wrangle in the past.
Unlike the House, which dissolved in bitter acrimony over
impeachment last fall, many said the Senate has actually benefited
from the ordeal and may emerge more unified than divided,
particularly at a personal level.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there was a keen awareness that not only the president
but also the Senate was on trial,'' said Senator Edward M. Kennedy.
Senator Fred Thompson, a Republican from Tennessee, agreed: ``In a
strange way, we've had more interplay and back and forth. We've
been forced to work together, with each other, toward our mutual
goal of handling the thing responsibly. I think we've shown that
when the chips are down, we can at least talk to each other and
listen to each other. And I think, in some respects, it might
enhance our ability to work together in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether the Senate's relations with the House will be as smooth
remains a good question. Several senators said they feared members
of the House _ especially the 13 Republican prosecutors who had
bitterly complained that their case was hamstrung by Senate
strictures _ would be less interested in cooperating on
legislation, particularly after disparaging remarks by senators
about the chaotic nature of the impeachment process in the House.
</P>
<P>
   The House is expected to have far greater post-impeachment
internal struggles _ and has already felt destructive effects. Two
congressmen were ruined by it. House Speaker Newt Gingrich resigned
in the wake of embarrassing November election returns for
Republicans. Just over a month later, the man tapped to replace
him, Representative Robert Livingston of Louisiana, unexpectedly
stepped aside as well, following revelations that he had had
extramarital affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Another potential trouble spot is relations between both
branches of Congress and the White House. Although many senators
downplayed the notion that post-trial tensions would inhibit
legislative relations with the president, there already has been an
explosive rift between the White House and the House in recent
days. News reports that Clinton was planning to seek revenge for
impeachment by helping Democrats regain control of the House in
2000 stirred denunciation by some GOP leaders.
</P>
<P>
   But that bitterness, to whatever degree it exists, may
ultimately be trumped by a strong desire to move on _ not just by
Republicans, who are desperate to separate the party's identity
from impeachment, but also by Democrats. Vows to ``return to the
people's business'' have echoed from all corners of the Capitol for
weeks, beginning with Clinton's State of the Union address on Jan.
19, in which he wished later generations might look back and say,
``We put aside our divisions and found a new hour of healing and
hopefulness, that we joined together to serve and strengthen the
land we love.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, Senate majority leader Trent Lott has indicated he will
push ahead with legislation immediately after the Senate returns
from its weeklong President's Day recess. During the trial, he
repeatedly said it was ``time to get to a vote and move on'' _ and
routinely ticked off his priorities, including education, defense,
tax cuts, and Social Security. Committee hearings have continued
throughout the trial, albeit at a slower pace, and numerous bills
have been hammered out, all in anticipation of the trial's end.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Republicans are going to engage in a flurry of
effort to prove they haven't lost time and they have an agenda,''
said Senator John F. Kerry. ``The public will look for substance,
not form.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether the wish to move on is realized may depend in part on
the lasting value, if any, of personal connections made during the
Senate trial. But even at the end of the trial on Friday, there
were glimmers of the old strains. After the impeachment votes were
taken, and the House prosecutors were escorted from the Senate
well, a senator objected that the White House lawyers should be
escorted out as well.
</P>
<P>
   Lott, raising his hand, said with a wry smile: ``There's the
door.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
