<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-16 13:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6938 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-CHIMPS-RIGHTS-BOS     02-16 1261
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-CHIMPS-RIGHTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAW WOULD GIVE RIGHTS TO PRIMATES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. CHANDLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Does a chimpanzee have rights? Should our primate cousins be
entitled to some of the same protections of life and liberty _ or
at least a basic protection from needless suffering _ that humans
enjoy? These are no longer just abstract philosophical musings, but
have become part of an active legislative debate.
</P>
<P>
   A proposed amendment to an animal welfare law being considered
by a House subcommittee in New Zealand would for the first time
confer some basic legal rights on chimpanzees and other great apes.
The bill is expected to come to a vote within the next month. Some
see this as an important first step toward acknowledging humans'
kinship with our closest relatives, but others see it as a
potentially dangerous step toward limiting medical research that
might save lives.
</P>
<P>
   Regulations in many nations, including the United States,
already protect apes used for research from being subjected to
unnecessary suffering and set rules for their treatment that go
beyond the basic animal-welfare guidelines that apply to all
species _ for example, specifying minimum cage sizes. But the
proposed New Zealand law, being promoted by an international
organization called the Great Ape Project, goes much further. It is
the first to speak in terms of ``rights'' for these animals, and
the first to prohibit any scientific or medical research that is
not in the best interests of the animals themselves.
</P>
<P>
   That language is strongly supported by many animal-rights
advocates and researchers who specialize in great apes. But it
gives chills to those who contend that research using animals,
including those most closely related to us, is needed to develop
life-saving treatments for human diseases.
</P>
<P>
   The specific law being debated in the New Zealand parliament is
moot. Only about 36 great apes are currently held in New Zealand _
there are no native species there _ and none is used for medical
research or subjected to conditions that would be prohibited by the
new law.
</P>
<P>
   But David Penny, a biologist at New Zealand's Massey University
and author of a brief in support of the law signed by 38 academics,
said, ``We've found that chimps and humans have some very similar
abilities,'' including a capacity for complex communication. Thus,
he said, ``We have to change our laws to take this into account.''
</P>
<P>
   What worries some medical researchers _ and encourages some
animal-rights advocates _ is that this law is seen as just a first
step, a foot in the door. The Great Ape Project hopes to see
similar legislation adopted in other nations, including the United
States, where it would have direct effects on some research
(although very little research is currently done on great apes).
Ultimately, the group hopes to get similar language incorporated in
a United Nations resolution that would apply to all nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to break the species line'' for beings that are
considered deserving of basic rights, said Paul Waldau, who teaches
ethics at Tufts University and is vice president of the
international Great Ape Project. The all-volunteer organization, he
said, is ``pushing for recognition of these kinds of rights and
protections'' for all great apes, a category that includes five
species: chimpanzees, bonobos, gorillas, orangutans, and humans.
</P>
<P>
   The rights conferred by the proposed New Zealand law include the
right not to be killed, not to be tortured, and not to be used for
any research that doesn't benefit the individual being subjected to
the research.
</P>
<P>
   The Great Ape Project's view on all medical research using apes
_ even if it might have the potential to lead to life-saving
treatments for human disease _ is that ``we want it abolished,
unless it is for the direct benefit of the individual involved,''
Waldau said.
</P>
<P>
   But what about the potential medical benefits of such research?
</P>
<P>
   ``We will lose some benefits,'' Waldau acknowledged. But, he
added, ``suppose there was a disease that you could only cure by
experimenting on Tibetan orphan children. We would have to say
no.'' In the same way, he said, because the other great apes are
such ``rich, complex individuals,'' they should not be sacrificed
for research ``any more than a particular group of humans.''
</P>
<P>
   Those involved in medical research using primates worry about
the possible outcome of such efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very important issue; the implications are very
widespread,'' said Bertha Madras, acting director of the New
England Regional Primate Research Center in Southborough, which is
run by Harvard University.
</P>
<P>
   The implications of such laws for researchers' ability to
develop treatments ``for a broad range of human diseases are quite
serious,'' Madras said.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Southborough center does not use any of the great apes
in its present research, the specific implications are only in
terms of setting a precedent that might later be extended to other
species _ or in terms of limiting potential future research.
</P>
<P>
   For research on possible AIDS treatments, for example, the
center uses Rhesus monkeys. Chimpanzees, shown to have been the
source of the AIDS virus, are unsuitable for research on treatments
because they apparently have a natural immunity to the disease.
</P>
<P>
   But in principle, Madras sees no reason to exclude chimpanzees
from such research if it turns out that would be useful. ``I'm a
speciesist,'' she freely admitted. ``I prioritize life. Human life,
to me, is my priority.''
</P>
<P>
   Waldau and others who support a ban on research using apes say
efforts should be directed toward developing better alternatives
for such research, such as laboratory work using human cells or
genetic material, rather than whole animals. They emphasize that
animal models are always imperfect, and that some treatments that
work in a lab animal may be useless on humans _ and vice versa.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Fouts, director of the Chimpanzee and Human Communication
Institute at the University of Central Washington, agrees with the
push to ban research using great apes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to bring our laws into line with the biological
reality . . . with the historical and biological fact that we're
all connected,'' Fouts said.
</P>
<P>
   Present US laws protecting chimpanzees, he said, are minimal:
They must be kept in cages that are at least 5 feet by 5 feet by 7
feet, and must be provided at least one toy. ``To put them in a
5-by-5 cage for life imprisonment is an abomination,'' said Fouts,
who is the author of a book on chimpanzee research called ``Next of
Kin.''
</P>
<P>
   But Madras pointed out that ``some of the regulations are far
better for primates than for humans.'' For example, primates must
be kept within a strictly limited range of temperatures, must not
have any sharp, dangerous objects in their cages, and must have
toys to play with. ``That's not true for our children . . . I would
love to see'' such regulations extended to children as well, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Fouts suggested one of the arguments made for the importance of
using apes for medical research can just as easily be turned around
to make the opposite point.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say we need to use chimps because they're so close to
us,'' he said. ``But isn't that also an argument against using
them? We do biomedical research on humans, but with strict
regulation. Maybe we should use the same standards, or similar
standards'' for experimenting on our closest animal relatives.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
