<DOCNO> NYT19990216.0091 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-16 13:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6941 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WALLING-EMOTIONS-BOS &LR;      02-16 1579
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WALLING-EMOTIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WALLING OFF EMOTIONS A BUY-NOW, PAY-LATER STRATEGY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH P. KAHN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What do Bill Clinton, O. J. Simpson, and Tom Hanks in ``Saving
Private Ryan'' have in common?
</P>
<P>
   Each has shown a knack for walling off one part of his emotional
life so it doesn't interfere with other parts. For ignoring what is
momentarily troublesome or painful in order to concentrate on a
narrow, self-serving agenda. For ``compartmentalizing,'' to use the
pop-psychology buzzword of the moment.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's ability to partition aspects of his public and private
persona _ Monica mess over here, bridge to the 21st century over
here _ has become, for better or for worse, the distinguishing
characteristic of his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Simpson, whose capacity for denial borders on the delusional,
responded this way last year when asked how it felt to lose his
Brentwood, Calif., estate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a sentimental guy,'' he said. ``But there's things you've
got to compartmentalize. You take them and file them away. I've
tried to live my life forward and not backward.''
</P>
<P>
   Hanks's character bravely soldiered on in ``Private Ryan,''
forgoing the impulse to stop and grieve over fallen comrades.
</P>
<P>
   Having survived both Monicagate and impeachment, Clinton may now
go down in history as the Great Compartmentalizer, much as Simpson
is likely to forever reign as the prince of pathology. But are they
really that uncommon in a culture that celebrates ``toughing it
out'' in tough situations? Is compartmentalizing strictly a guy
thing? Is it ever a good thing? Do we all do the C-thing at times?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mental health experts may not agree on the answers, any more
than political pundits agree on what accounts for Clinton's lofty
poll numbers _ beyond the public's ability to compartmentalize its
feelings about politicians and public officials, that is.
</P>
<P>
   But experts do seem to agree that there are degrees of
difference to this sort of psychological defense mechanism _
compartments to compartmentalizing, if you will _ and that what
works in the short term can be dangerous to one's health if adopted
as a way of life, a permanent modus vivendi.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I support patients doing it, it's usually when they're
under siege or duress,'' says psychiatrist and author Dr. Joseph
Glenmullen, a staff clinician at the Harvard University Health
Services.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most extreme example would be combat,'' Glenmullen says,
``when you simply can't afford to sit down and deal with your
feelings. To a lesser extent, college students face similar
choices. If they have a personal crisis during exam week, sometimes
they have to put off dealing with it until they can focus on it
more.''
</P>
<P>
   Borrowing from his own practice, Glenmullen cites the case of a
patient who is undergoing a personal crisis in the midst of a
crucial career change.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can't really deal with the crisis until the job situation
stabilizes,'' says Glenmullen. ``But then we'll come back to those
issues. I still have mixed feelings about it, though _ wanting to
help right away, even though it's not appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   Another example ripped from the news pages is Jimmy Johnson, the
tough-guy coach of the Miami Dolphins, who flirted with retirement
recently because he did pause to look backward. Johnson's mother
had died in December, and his father has cancer. Having skipped his
mother's wake to prepare for a football game, Johnson was overcome
with grief when the season ended.
</P>
<P>
   Said Johnson, at a press conference to announce he will scale
back on his coaching duties this year, ``There's a time you pull
back and say, `Be with people you care about. Don't shortchange
them.' ''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To psychologist Irene Stiver, author of ``The Healing
Connection,'' it is important to differentiate between what she
calls ``mechanisms people use to help them do their work better and
ones that don't help them live their lives better.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Clinton analysts have theorized that the president learned
to compartmentalize early in life, in response to his having to
deal with alcohol abuse and domestic violence in the Clinton
household. Sheetrocking his psyche into neat compartments was young
Bill's way of building an impermeable ego, or so goes this theory
of Clintonian dysfunction.
</P>
<P>
   While hesitant to speculate about Clinton and his psychological
profile specifically, Stiver sees him as a ``strong person'' who,
10 years removed from office, could well suffer from depression or
some other breakdown of his internal defense systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate to pathologize someone like Clinton, because a lot of
people screw up their lives like that,'' says Stiver. ``But he's
one of those people who do their jobs well but who aren't connected
to their inner experience of pain.''
</P>
<P>
   Men do that more than women, Stiver says, primarily due to
cultural conditioning. Whereas women learn to pay attention to
their feelings more, men are encouraged not to. With high-profile
high achievers _ Senator Edward Kennedy and former defense
secretary Robert McNamara being two other examples _ boxing up
emotions or trafficking in half-truths may lead to problems down
the line, including alcohol abuse and depression.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many men have made such an investment in achievement and power
that they can exist on those for a long time,'' says Stiver. ``At
some point, though, they have to pay a price. You always pay a
price for not representing yourself fully, or at least relatively
fully.''
</P>
<P>
   Psychologist Janet Surrey, coauthor of the book ``We Have to
Talk: Healing Dialogues Between Men and Women,'' agrees that men
and women have different cognitive styles _ and thus differing
abilities to compartmentalize feelings from action. To illustrate,
she cites the husband and wife who quarrel in the morning, then
separate and go off to work.
</P>
<P>
   The woman ``may be processing the fight all day long,'' says
Surrey, ``talking about what happened with her friends. Then she
goes home and wants to talk about it some more. He, meanwhile, may
have completely put the disagreement out of his mind. For him, it's
over. So he's caught off guard when she brings it up again.''
</P>
<P>
   Says Surrey, reaching well back into history for another
example, ``It goes all the way back to Ulysses not being led off by
the Sirens. To not be as relationally aware of everything can
clearly be a strength, when you need to blot out feelings in order
to act. To focus on the goal. But there's also a moral question
here, which is a different issue. At some point there must be some
integration with a moral sense. The big question is, do you use
this defense selectively or does it define who you are?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Renana Brooks, a clinical psychologist in the Washington,
D.C., area, flips the political paradigm on its head. Brooks
contends that without Clinton's extraordinary ability to stay on
message _ tuning out whatever personal static interferes with his
public broadcasts _ the Great Compartmentalizer would be a great
washout politically.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the essence of Bill Clinton's resiliency,'' Brooks
maintains, adding that no, it's not just a guy thing. Hillary
Clinton is also a ``master compartmentalizer,'' Brooks says. So is
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, who was ``badly hurt by her
husband,'' says Brooks.
</P>
<P>
   Both Ronald and Nancy Reagan (remember the Kitty Kelley
biography?) exhibited similar traits during their years in the
White House, even though their marriage had a much sunnier public
image than the Clintons'.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Republicans are the great compartmentalizers, if you
want to know the truth,'' says Brooks. ``They're the ones talking
about family values when most of them are divorced or have had
extramarital affairs. Compartmentalizing seems to be a requirement
for political service across the board. If you're going to set
yourself up as some sort of moral example for the country, you
pretty much have to compartmentalize.''
</P>
<P>
   At least one prominent psychologist disputes the conventional
wisdom on Clinton. Frank Farley of Temple University, a past
president of the American Psychological Association, says Clinton
is less a compartmentalizer than a compulsive risk-taker who
thrives on uncertainty and discordance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saying he compartmentalizes is a neat box to put Clinton in,
you can visualize it, but I'm not sure it has much validity,'' says
Farley. ``He's more what I call a T-type personality. By which I
mean, someone who likes excitement and adventure and who is capable
of juggling many things at once.''
</P>
<P>
   Comparing Clinton to other T-type politicians _ John F. Kennedy,
Gary Hart, and Theodore Roosevelt are three names that come up _
and to Albert Einstein, a more purely intellectual T-type, Farley
notes that even in impeachment, Clinton exuded self-confidence.
That wasn't a byproduct of denial or delusion, Farley suggests, but
a shining example of the Clinton who gets most energized when he's
most beset by contradictory forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gave his State of the Union speech like he was the last
gunfighter standing at the OK Corral,'' observes Farley. ``He's a
jazz man. He lives for uncertainty. When you say he
compartmentalizes, I say the human mind doesn't really work that
way. We're the one species that doesn't live in boxes.''
</P>
<P>
   Except, of course, the ones fashioned by historians.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
