<DOCNO> NYT19990216.0094 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-16 13:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6949 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-FRANKIE-BOS &LR;      02-16 1486
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-FRANKIE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEEN ANGEL FOREVER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL BLOWEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; BOSTON _ Frankie Avalon, a teen idol on the cusp of 60, pops
out of a long black limousine and points toward the beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is Malibu?'' he asks, incredulously. ``This is the
beach?''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, he's at Dorchester's Malibu Beach, just across an
inlet from the Dorchester Yacht Club. There are no frolicking
bikini babes, and not a surfboard in sight. Two people are walking
their dogs and the tide's about as low as it gets. The wave in
Avalon's hair is bigger than the ones haplessly lapping at the
shore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Surf's down,'' smiles Avalon, who's about as happy as a guy
gets. He's trim and tan and smiling. Just like in all those beach
movies he made with Annette Funicello back in the '60s. And why
not?
</P>
<P>
   ``What's not to like?'' asks Avalon, rhetorically, as he
searches for something complimentary to say about the MDC's Malibu
Beach. ``OK, so there aren't many waves. Hey, it's not crowded,
either.''
</P>
<P>
   He laughs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made those beach movies in 15 days for $350,000,'' says
Avalon, in town promoting his upcoming appearance as Teen Angel in
``Grease'' opening Wednesday at the Wang Theatre. ``We didn't get
rich. But they were a lot of fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it's hard not to have fun when you're hanging with
Frankie. His smile is sincere and straightforward. His tan, in a
shade that would make George Hamilton envious, comes from Twilight
Tan, a self-tanning product he sells on the Home Shopping Network.
His kids are fine, his wife loves him, and he's still getting paid
to play the world's oldest teenager.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always thought the image was funny,'' says Avalon as he
steps back into the limo. ``I mean, I take my acting and singing
seriously. But not myself.''
</P>
<P>
   From 1958 to 1960, they didn't get much hotter than Frankie
Avalon. From ``Dede Dinah'' to ``Venus,'' he had prepubescent
screaming female fans hitting octaves that wouldn't be heard again
until John, Paul, George, and Ringo hit town. At $5,000 a night
performing for crowds of 10,000, Avalon racked in the dough. And he
was still just a kid.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought it would end,'' he says. ``I was wild. I had a
hangout house in Los Angeles. Johnny Rivers. Glen Campbell. Jack
Nicholson. They'd hang out and we'd play cards and there were
starlets all around. That's the way it was. One night, this girl
Lisa showed up and I fell in love. That was it. I told everyone
there that I was going to marry that girl. Three weeks later, I
did. And we've been married ever since.''
</P>
<P>
   For 36 years, to be precise _ long enough to have eight children
ranging in age from 25 to 35.
</P>
<P>
   Avalon's introduction to show business wasn't through his voice
but through a trumpet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved the trumpet,'' he says. ``I practiced for four or five
hours every day. I remember cooling off in a bathtub on those hot
Philly nights and playing the trumpet. I was 11 and I heard that Al
Martino, who came from our neighborhood, was having a party. So I
snuck in. I just went in and started playing. It was just like a
movie. Everyone stopped talking and Al Martino liked me. The next
thing I knew I was in the penthouse of the Sheraton Hotel in New
York playing for Jackie Gleason. He booked me on his show.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Into the stratosphere &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But it was singing that made Avalon a star. Some friends founded
Chancellor Records, and Avalon started hanging out in the studio.
One day, he recorded ``Dede Dinah,'' a song that achieved its
unique nasal quality when Avalon, as a joke, held his nose while he
was recording. That was the cut they released, and it sent Avalon
into the pop star stratosphere.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a while everything was great,'' says Avalon, as the
limousine noses along the Southeast Expressway toward town. ``When
I was in Hollywood making the beach movies with Annette we got to
meet everybody. I was lucky. I met Gary Cooper. I worked with John
Wayne (in ``The Alamo''). Elvis.''
</P>
<P>
   What about Elvis?
</P>
<P>
   Presley was often portrayed as Avalon's evil adversary in those
early fanzines. Avalon, the pretty boy next door vs. the
hip-swinging, sexually dangerous Presley.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was just made-up stuff. We liked each other, but Elvis
was strange. He left his house in the morning _ was driven to the
studio. Worked all day. Was driven home. And he stayed there. He
invited me up to his house a couple of times. It was strange. One
of his friends or bodyguards _ whatever they were; they all dressed
like him _ came into the living room and announced that Elvis would
be down in five minutes. It was as if he was doing a show. And he
had this great jukebox that held 100 records _ all but one of them
by Elvis. I remember the only one not his was `It's Only Make
Believe' by Conway Twitty _ and he sounded just like Elvis.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the things that make Avalon likable is his guilelessness.
He would rather talk about other people than about himself. He
realizes his limitations. He stills gets a kick out of his work and
he refuses to become a parody of himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Randall Kleiser, the director, asked me to play Teen
Angel in the movie `Grease,' I hesitated,'' says Avalon, who
descends from the heavens singing ``Beauty School Dropout'' in the
hit film. ``I'd seen the play and Teen Angel was played all in
black like a motorcycle gang leader. I didn't want that. So, I
redesigned him. I made him more my style.''
</P>
<P>
   What is Avalon's style?
</P>
<P>
   ``I was never a threat to anyone,'' he says. ``I wasn't 9 feet
tall. I was nice.'' Avalon pauses, staring out the window at the
flock of giant cranes working on the Big Dig. ``I can't believe it
lasted.''
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to think of Avalon without thinking of Annette, his
beach partner and love interest in the beach movies. Annette
Funicello suffers from multiple sclerosis, and according to Avalon,
``she's not doing well.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We had so much fun doing `Back to the Beach,' '' he says,
referring to the 1987 retro-beach movie that Variety called ``a
wonderfully campy trip down pop culture's trash-filled memory
lane'' and inspired critic Leslie Halliwell to write, ``Not so bad
as it sounds.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Annette was great,'' Avalon says. ``She never complained, but
she was having trouble with her eyes and she stumbled a little. I
just accepted an award for her at a special ceremony. Michael
Eisner was there. I saw her backstage and told her how beautiful
she looked. I told her to keep praying. She told me that she keeps
praying, but God didn't answer her prayers.''
</P>
<P>
   Avalon, a devout Roman Catholic, says he responded, ``God's
delay is not God's denial.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Congenial partnership &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We made seven films together and we never had an argument or a
disagreement,'' he says. ``One of the sad parts is that she never
made any money until `Back to the Beach.' ''
</P>
<P>
   For a while, during the late '60s through the mid-'70s, money
was a problem for Avalon, who at one time had thought he had ``more
money that I ever dreamed of.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was broke,'' he says as the limousine pulls up across from
the Wang Center for the Performing Arts. ``And I thought I was
broke before I got in trouble with the IRS. I thought, at least, my
managers were taking care of the taxes. They didn't. I thought I'd
never recover. There were nights where I'd ask the manager of a
club where I was playing how many people we had. `Forty,' he'd say.
I was used to playing for thousands. I'd ask him if I had to go on.
He said yes. And I'd go on. But it was difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, Avalon's eyes brighten. ``But I'll tell you something.
I had success at such a young age that I never learned anything.
When you're doing so well everyone assumes you know everything. And
I was so swept up in everything I never stopped. I only learned
when I started over. At the bottom. Now, I have one of my daughters
working in the office and I take care of my own business. I don't
leave it to someone else. That's why I'm enjoying myself so much
more now. This is just a whole lot of fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, at Quincy Market, Frankie Avalon sits behind a long table
surrounded by colorful balloons and dozens of fans. He signs
autographs and exchanges small talk while Paul Perry, a radio
personality on WODS-FM (103.3), plays ``Venus'' and offers tickets
to ``Grease'' as prizes in a trivia contest. Just before the
hula-hoop contest gets underway, Avalon glances up at the ceiling
in the rotunda where a cadre of additional fans had assembled. He
smiles and waves.
</P>
<P>
   Just before Avalon's mother died, four years ago in May, she
told her son she didn't want him to shed a tear when she was gone.
``Why?'' he asked her. ``Because you gave me all the joy and
happiness a mother could want,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   So, while Avalon is no longer a teen, his mother believed he was
an angel. And for him, there is no greater testament.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
