<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENNOCHI-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUTHARDT'S STAYING POWER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOAN VENNOCHI  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Why is Linda Ruthardt still the state insurance commissioner?
</P>
<P>
   Just after Paul Cellucci was elected governor last November, it
was reported that Ruthardt wanted to step down _ code for saying
the newly elected governor wanted her to step down.She was
supposedly asked to take a job as risk manager for the Big Dig, as
good a place as any to bury a burdensome bureaucrat.
</P>
<P>
   Yet when Cellucci was asked recently about Ruthardt's status as
commissioner, he said he hoped she would remain in her current job
_ code for saying she isn't going anywhere soon. Why not?
</P>
<P>
   Ruthardt is almost always described as ``quirky,'' but that is
hardly a fireable offense _ particularly since it is used so often
to describe women.
</P>
<P>
   In Ruthardt's case, the quirky label comes partly from her
background and partly from her personal style. She is a former
president of the Camp Fire Boys and Girls Inc. and a former
director of risk and insurance for the Girls Scouts of the USA. She
refers to her staff as ``worker bees'' and ``busy bunnies.'' She
once told a reporter ``I'm not the dumbest bunny in the hutch,''
reinforcing an image of cheery flakiness.
</P>
<P>
   She gets credit for overseeing decreases in auto and workers
compensation rate, but is criticized for being an ineffective
department leader. Staff discontent is said to be high, and morale
low. The division is generally considered overworked, understaffed,
and underbudgeted.
</P>
<P>
   Now, this scenario of benign bureaucratic neglect is fairly
typical of government during the Weld-Cellucci years. It exacts its
not-so-benign penalty on whatever area the specific agency is
supposed to be regulating _ children or insurance companies, for
example. Normally, it's no reason to remove anyone, but in
Ruthardt's case, the complaints were loud and they came from
insurance industry sources, as well as from consumer advocates.
</P>
<P>
   However, she's still on the job, an occurrence partly explained
by her willingness to take hits for the administration and the fact
that her husband is ill.
</P>
<P>
   Another theory about her longevity involves the Emlico
imbroglio.
</P>
<P>
   This complicated case, reported extensively by the Globe's Steve
Bailey and Steve Syre, involved Ruthard's quick approval of a move
by Electric Mutual Insurance Co., a Massachusetts insurer, to
Bermuda. The company, Emlico, filed for bankruptcy a few months
later.
</P>
<P>
   Emlico was founded by General Electric Co. its sole customer.
Robert Cordy, chairman of Cellucci's judicial screening panel and a
former legal counsel to Governor William F. Weld, has been a
lawyer/lobbyist for GE. Other graduates of the Weld-Cellucci
administrations, including former Economic Affairs Secretary Gloria
Larson, have also worked for GE.
</P>
<P>
   When Emlico moved to Bermuda and declared bankruptcy, it left
its reinsurers holding the bill for around $500 million needed for
reserves to cover GE's asbestos and environmental liabilities.
</P>
<P>
   Angry reinsurers sued in Massachusetts courts, charging that
Emlico knew it was bankrupt and that it relocated to avoid lawsuits
stateside. The case cast a cloud over Ruthardt's decision to allow
Emlico to relocate. The Massachusetts Supreme Court eventually
ruled that Ruthardt had erred.
</P>
<P>
   In sworn testimony before a legislative committee investigating
the matter, Ruthardt said she was getting signals from someone in
the Weld administration to ``just sort of forget the whole thing''
and let Emlico escape to Bermuda. She later attributed those
signals to a ``misunderstanding.''
</P>
<P>
   After the November election, word seeped out that Ruthardt
``wanted'' to leave her job. Suzanne Bump, a former state
Democratic state representative, was said to be ``emerging'' as a
leading candidate to replace her.
</P>
<P>
   As a legislator, Bump helped reform the state workers'
compensation law. Now, she is an insurance industry lobbyist.
</P>
<P>
   Cordy and Larson, the administration's former economic affairs
secretary, were said to be pushing Bump. Larson declined comment
when asked about her support for Bump. Cordy said the report of his
support for Bump ``stuns me,'' then declined comment.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Bump was bumped and Ruthardt remains.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'd still like her to leave. But they are not going to rush
her out the door,'' says an administration insider.
</P>
<P>
   Could Cellucci be treating Ruthardt gently because he worries
what she will say if he doesn't?
</P>
<P>
   Should we care? It's all inside baseball, isn't it, over a
somewhat obscure political post?
</P>
<P>
   Only the quirky Linda Ruthardt knows for sure.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Joan Vennochi is a columnist for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
