<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-QUESTIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHICH PLANET IS THE SMALLEST? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ROPEIK  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. What is the smallest planet in the solar system?
</P>
<P>
   F.R., Quincy, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Pluto, with a diameter at the equator of just 1,429 miles, is
the smallest of the nine planets. Discovered in 1930, it's made of
the same ice and dust that other objects that far from the sun are
made of, and some say that because of its small size, composition,
and elliptical-instead-of-circular orbit, Pluto shouldn't even be
called a planet.
</P>
<P>
   But other astronomers say it's not fair to pick on the little
guy. They point out that one suggested astronomical definition of a
planet is anything wider than 621 miles (1,000 kilometers) that
orbits the sun. Pluto qualifies.
</P>
<P>
   But it is small. Earth's moon is nearly 50 percent bigger,
measuring 2,159 miles across. Charon, Pluto's moon, is almost as
big as Pluto itself. Together they are the closest thing to a
double planet in our solar system.
</P>
<P>
   The next smallest planet is Mercury, which is only 3,032 miles
in diameter and the closest planet to the Sun. Earth's diameter is
7,927 miles. Jupiter is the solar system king, more than eleven
times bigger than Earth at a median diameter of 88,875 miles.
Jupiter, made up mostly of gasses, is spinning so fast it's a
little bit oval, so they don't just measure it equatorially.
</P>
<P>
   Compare all that to the sun. At 870,105 miles across, it's
nearly ten times larger than Jupiter.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Is the red spot on Jupiter part of the planet or part of its
atmosphere?
</P>
<P>
   M.P.M., Concord, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   They don't call Jupiter's Great Red Spot ``great'' for nothing.
It's bigger than the Earth, 8,700 miles from north to south, 17,400
miles across the middle!
</P>
<P>
   The Great Red Spot is part of Jupiter's atmosphere. Like a giant
hurricane, it has a center and clouds swirling around it. They take
an average of six earth days to make one complete rotation around
the spot, traveling at about 180 miles per hour.
</P>
<P>
   Jupiter has lots of ``spots,'' rotating weather systems that are
tougher to see from Earth because they're smaller and mostly white.
Nobody knows why the Red Spot is red. Astronomers think it may be
because it has enough power to draw trace chemicals up from the
planet's lower levels (Jupiter, like all the giant outer planets,
is believed to have little or no solid surface.) But even the
Voyager 1 and 2 spacecraft that flew by for a close look back in
1979 and the observations by Galileo, which has been orbiting
Jupiter since Dec. 1995, weren't able to figure that one out.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Readers are invited to send science questions to How&AMP;Why. Write
to How&AMP;Why, Health/Science, Box 2378, The Boston Globe, Boston, MA
02107; or send via Internet to: howwhy(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-99 1319EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990216.0098 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-16 13:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6960 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-OLDER-COLUMN-2TAK     02-16 1042
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-OLDER-COLUMN-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS YEARS ADVANCE, PEOPLE SLEEP LESS, WAKE EARLIER 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like most people with his condition, Frank Tosti, who is 67, had
no idea why he constantly felt so logey that he was in danger of
dozing off in the middle of a business conversation.
</P>
<P>
   But when he drifted onto the highway median strip at 65 miles
per hour one day, Tosti's wife insisted he get help. Two nights in
a sleep laboratory revealed the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``They found out I was waking up 53 times an hour, although I
didn't know it,'' he recalls. ``That didn't leave me much time for
sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   Tosti's problem is sleep apnea _ momentary cessation of
breathing while asleep. It's among the most common reasons why many
people of a certain age discover they can no longer take a good
night's sleep for granted.
</P>
<P>
   Sleep disorders are rampant among the elderly. ``All sleep
disorders increase in prevalence with age,'' says Dr. John
Winkelman, the Brigham and Women's Hospital sleep specialist in
Boston who diagnosed Tosti's problem. More than half of people over
65 have persistent trouble sleeping, a proportion that rises to two
of every three in nursing homes, according to a National Institutes
of Health report on the problem.
</P>
<P>
   A report to Congress last year by the National Center on Sleep
Disorders Research decried an ``epidemic of more than 40 million
undiagnosed and untreated, or misdiagnosed and mistreated,
chronically ill sleep-disorders victims.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's not just ``disorders'' that are to blame. Researchers
have found that normal, healthy elders with no identifiable
disorders sleep less, wake earlier, have more nocturnal
wakefulness, and spend less time in deep sleep than younger adults.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've found some fascinating changes in older people,'' says
Dr. Charles A. Czeisler, director of the Circadian, Neuroendocrine
and Sleep Disorders Section at Brigham and Women's. ``As we get
older, the range of times in which we can sleep soundly is much
narrower. That's probably why older shift workers have so much more
difficulty sleeping during the daytime.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Sanford H. Auerbach, director of the sleep disorders center
at Boston Medical Center, notes that these changes often arise in
middle age. ``As we age, we become more intolerant of sleep
deprivation. The whole sleep system is a little more delicate,''
Auerbach says.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, starting in middle age, ``people can't sleep late
any more. Their clock just won't allow it,'' he says. ``So if they
want to catch up on their sleep, they have to go to bed earlier.''
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that some of the most common sleep disorders
can be successfully treated _ but only if they are recognized and
properly diagnosed. Unfortunately, specialists say, many physicians
don't know much about sleep problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``The diagnosis and treatment of sleep disorders in primary-care
medicine today is essentially zero,'' the National Center on Sleep
Disorders Research said in its report. Winkelman notes that medical
schools devote an average of only one hour in their four-year
curricula to the subject.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, many people think nothing can be done about their
their difficulty getting to sleep, their poor-quality sleep, or
their too-early awakening. ``People think it's just part of growing
old,'' Auerbach says. ``Patients don't even complain to their
primary care physicians sometimes, thinking there's nothing that
can help them.'' Or they make matters worse by practicing poor
sleep habits or resorting to over-the-counter nostrums that give
rise to other problems.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors' successes in treating sleep apnea and another leading
cause of sleeplessness, called ``restless legs syndrome,'' are
antidotes to despair.
</P>
<P>
   Sleep apnea, which afflicts more men than women, can interrupt
sleep hundreds of times a night because breathing is blocked by
narrowing or collapse of the air passages at the back of the
throat. A rapid buildup of carbon dioxide in the blood sets off
alarms in the brain so conscious breathing can take over. Like
Tosti, most apnea victims don't remember waking, because it takes
three to five minutes of wakefulness to establish a lasting memory.
</P>
<P>
   The problem ceased when Tosti began a nightly treatment called
CPAP, for ``continuous positive air pressure.'' At bedtime, the
Taunton man puts on a plastic mask attached to a device that gently
forces air into his nose, keeping his airways open. It has made all
the difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sleep a solid six hours a night and wake up bright-eyed and
bushy-tailed,'' the real estate broker says.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin Clifford, a 61-year-old retired school guidance
counselor, is another CPAP success story. ``I feel invigorated in
the morning now,'' Clifford says, ``whereas before I'd drag myself
through the day.''
</P>
<P>
   Not every sleep apnea sufferer needs CPAP. Some can be helped by
weight loss, avoidance of alcohol within six hours of bedtime, or
even such expedients as sewing a tennis ball into the back of their
pajama tops to prevent them from sleeping on their backs.
</P>
<P>
   Another man, 65-year-old Edmund Teixeira, a retired school
principal and coach, had a double dose of sleeping trouble. In
addition to sleep apnea, Teixeira had a severe case of restless
legs syndrome, or RLS _ an irresistable urge to move the legs
during the night that makes sleep impossible. In addition to the
restless movement, patients often describe the syndrome with words
like achy, crampy, creepy-crawly, worms crawling under my skin, and
heebie-jeebies.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of RLS is probably in the nervous system, but beyond
that no one knows if it originates in the lower brain, the spinal
cord, or the peripheral nerves in the legs. Whatever the cause,
Teixeira and other victims testify that it's a maddening malady
that can ruin everyday life.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a period of 18 months, it was a nightmare,'' he says. ``My
legs would start bouncing like mad. I could not go to sleep. People
said, 'You're retired, you can sleep late.' But I'm a diabetic, I
need physical activity. I need to get up and play golf with
friends. It gets to the point where you'd do anything to get to
sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-99 1320EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990216.0099 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-16 13:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6961 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-OLDER-COLUMN-2ND &LR;      02-16 1006
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-OLDER-COLUMN-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... to sleep.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Teixeira's problem was tamed, as many patients' are, with low
doses of l-dopa (Sinemet) and pramipexole (Mirapex), drugs designed
for people with Parkinson's disease, another movement disorder that
is thought to have nothing to do with RLS. For individuals in whom
those drugs don't work, doctors sometimes prescribe benzodiazepine
sedatives, opioids such as codeine, or anticonvulsants such as
gabapentin (Neurontin).
</P>
<P>
   With faithful use of his CPAP face mask for apnea and medication
for his restless legs, Teixeira says, ``I feel that I've turned the
corner. Lately I've been sleeping right through the night.''
</P>
<P>
   Patients like Teixeira, Clifford, and Tosti are relatively easy
cases, the kind about which Winkelman says, ``You get to feel good
about yourself as a doctor because usually you can produce
tremendous relief for people.''
</P>
<P>
   Other victims of sleeplessness pose more challenges, but that
doesn't mean they can't be helped.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, about one-third of chronic insomnia is rooted in
depressive mood disorders that can range in severity from mild to
severe, and affect women more often than men. Antidepressants can
often improve their sleep, specialists say.
</P>
<P>
   Menopause often gives rise to sleep problems in women. Winkelman
recently saw a 60-year-old woman who has not slept normally since
she underwent menopause a decade ago. ``No one knows why this
occurs,'' he says. ``Somehow estrogen is related to a number of
functions _ mood, memory, sleep, and so on. We're investigating
menopause-related sleep disturbance and how much hormone
replacement helps or does not help sleep problems.''
</P>
<P>
   A broad array of age-related medical problems can also wreck
sleep: arthritis and other painful conditions; prostate enlargment;
heart and lung disease that can cause shortness of breath; the
``heartburn'' caused when stomach acid leaks into the esophagus or
food tube; Alzheimer's disease and other dementias.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the medications to treat these and other problems
can themselves interfere with sleep _ a factor to which doctors and
patients should be alert whenever sleep is an issue.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, some sleep problems are more amenable to treatment
than others, depending on the underlying cause. But almost always,
careful dissection of the problem can lead to helpful treatment,
specialists say.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to make a diagnosis of sleep disorders,'' Winkelman
says. ``Unfortunately, many physicians will just tell people, `Oh,
drink a glass of wine,' or `Take a hot bath,' or `Here's a sleeping
pill'.''
</P>
<P>
   And often, of course, the sleep deprived will go to the
drugstore and buy one or more over-the-counter sleep aids. Bad
idea, sleep specialists say. They usually contain antihistamines
such as benadryl, which can cause or aggravate constipation,
urinary retention, tachycardia (a racing heart beat) and confusion.
</P>
<P>
   As for alcohol, another favorite sleep aid, its short sedative
effect wears off in a few hours, leaving users stranded on the
shores of sleeplessness _ and it's a diuretic to boot, requiring
noctural trips to the bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   Prescription sleeping pills, or ``hypnotics'' as they're called,
can be useful for short periods when unusual stress or bereavement
is an issue. But better for the long run, doctors say, are
antidepressants in carefully modulated doses. Doctors prescribe
well-tested drugs such as trazodone (Desyrel), amitriptyline
(Elavil), and doxepin (Sinequan) for their mildly sedating, rather
than their antidepressant, effects. And unlike other sedatives,
they don't pose the risk of addiction.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
HELP IS OUT THERE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Anyone battling a sleep problem _ but especially elders _ should
begin by practicing good ``sleep hygiene.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This has nothing to do with flossing your teeth, but with
habits and behaviors that prepare you for sleep and facilitate
optimal sleep quality,'' says Dr. John Winkelman of Brigham and
Women's Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   These habits may sound obvious, but sufferers dismiss them at
their peril. They include:
</P>
<P>
   Regular bedtime. Recent science backs up your mother. Elders are
less flexible about shifting schedules, and their inner clocks are
set about an hour earlier than young adults', predisposing them to
awaken earlier than they may want to.
</P>
<P>
   Many make matters worse, says sleep researcher Charles A.
Czeisler, by exposing themselves to light in the early morning,
which resets their circadian clocks to an earlier hour. Those who
want to sleep later, he says, should ``avoid early-morning light
exposure and increase exposure to light in the evening.''
</P>
<P>
   Be careful with caffeine and alcohol. Caffeine after noon and
alcohol within six hours of bedtime are ``two major culprits'' in
sleeplessness, says Dr. Sanford Auerbach of Boston Medical Center.
``Caffeine can be a much bigger issue in the elderly.'' Limiting
liquid intake in the evening will also reduce the chance that a
full bladder will disrupt sleep.
</P>
<P>
   Follow the Goldilocks rule. Be sure everything is just right:
Not too hot, not too cold; not too firm, not too soft; not too
bright, or noisy either. And reserve the bedroom for sleeping or
sex.
</P>
<P>
   If you can't sleep, don't fret in bed. ``If you're not sleepy,
you shouldn't be in bed,'' Winkelman advises. ``If you're not
asleep after 20 or 30 minutes, you should get up and do something
distracting. After that, anxiety and clock-watching is only going
to increase.''
</P>
<P>
   Where to learn more:
</P>
<P>
   American Sleep Disorders Association, 1610 14th Street NW, Suite
300, Rochester, Minn. 55901. Website: http://www.asda.org
</P>
<P>
   American Sleep Apnea Association, 2025 Pennsylvania Ave. NW,
Suite 905, Washington, D.C. 20006. Telephone: 202-293-3650.
Website: http://www.sleepapnea.org
</P>
<P>
   Restless Legs Syndrome Foundation, P.O. Box 7050, Department CP,
Rochester, Minn. 55903-7050. Website: http://www.rls.org
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Richard A. Knox is a member of the Globe staff. His e-mail address
is: knox(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
