<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-16 13:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6963 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-NEWS-REALITY-BOS &LR;      02-16 1056
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-NEWS-REALITY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV NEWS FEELS A HARSH NEW ECONOMIC REALITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ As suddenly as it flared up, a highly publicized
contract dispute involving Susan Wornick, one of Boston's most
popular TV news anchors, could be nearing a resolution.
</P>
<P>
   Just last Friday, WCVB-Ch. 5 general manager Paul La Camera
announced that Wornick was finished at Channel 5, sending shock
waves through a station where she had worked for two decades, and
through a community where she had become a gregarious fixture. But
La Camera and Wornick are now talking again, amid signs that the
offer she previously rejected may be put back on the table, and
that this time she will say yes.
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not it is settled, the Wornick-Channel 5 imbroglio
has thrown a revealing light on the changed landscape of TV news.
In the cable era, shrinking audiences have imposed a new economic
reality on local broadcast stations, especially those that are _
like Channel 5 _ owned by out-of-town conglomerates. ``It's a
message that all bets are off, that it really is a new age,'' said
one Channel 5 staffer Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reporters and anchors no longer stand on the firm ground they
once stood on. There was a time when, if you were doing well, and
your ratings were up, you could name your deal. That's no longer
the case.''
</P>
<P>
   Wornick's ratings could scarcely be better: Since she began
coanchoring the Channel 5 noon newscast 10 years ago with Jim Boyd,
the newscast has won every ratings ``sweeps'' period. But Jim
Thistle, who hired Wornick 20 years ago when he was news director
at Channel 5 and who is now the dean of broadcast journalism at
Boston University, said the old cause-effect assumptions no longer
apply.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's under pressure. The business has changed,'' said
Thistle. ``In the 1970s and '80s, the axiom was that you would
always make more money the next year than you did the previous
year; owning a network affiliate was like a license to print money.
</P>
<P>
   ``But those days are long gone because of competition from cable
and home satellites and the Internet. So local on-air people don't
command automatically the kinds of salaries they did 10 or 15 years
ago.''
</P>
<P>
   If an agreement between La Camera and Wornick is reached, it
would still be subject to approval from executives at Hearst-Argyle
Television, Inc., Channel 5's corporate parent. La Camera declined
to discuss details of the negotiations, saying only that ``there's
continued discussions occurring'' with Wornick.
</P>
<P>
   Wornick herself did not return calls.
</P>
<P>
   While the contract offer was not initially satisfactory to
Wornick, there are no indications it contained a pay cut in her
salary of nearly $300,000 per year. Neither are there indications,
however, that it contained a pay raise as hefty as some others at
Channel 5 have reportedly received.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has nothing to do with cost-cutting,'' insisted La
Camera. ``Susan Wornick decided not to renew her contract with
WCVB-TV and decided to leave on Friday.'' Channel 5 news director
Candy Altman said it is ``patently false'' to suggest the station's
negotiating stance was motivated by cost-cutting concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, some observers speculated that Channel 5's
apparent initial willingness to let Wornick walk may have stemmed
from the temptation to unload a big salary and replace it with that
of a lesser-paid journalist. The echoes had barely faded from
Wornick's final negotiating session with La Camera when the station
put out a press release announcing her departure.
</P>
<P>
   A reporter at a rival station who requested anonymity said that
Hearst-Argyle, owner of Channel 5, has developed a reputation of
being ``very much bottom-line people, much more `show me the money,
let's run this like a normal business.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Few of those interviewed by the Globe believed the difficulties
encountered by Wornick, 49, were related to the plight faced by
many aging TV newswomen in a business that wants fresh, young faces
before the camera. Several, however, noted that she was passed over
five years ago for an anchor post on one of Channel 5's
early-evening newscasts in favor of Heather Kahn, nearly two
decades her junior.
</P>
<P>
   Wornick acknowledged last year in an interview with The Boston
Globe Magazine that ``it was upsetting to me, and everybody knew
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Some say the dispute will put a dent in the image of a
professional ``family'' that Channel 5 tries to project. Others,
however, predict it will quickly blow over. They say the truth of
the matter is that negotiations simply got out of hand between two
people who like and respect each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was just one of these last minute, very emotional,
spur-of-the-moment issues that popped up,'' said Emily Rooney,
former news director and a close friend of Wornick's. ``It was an
unfortunate confluence of events. It didn't have as much thought
behind it as it should have on Susan's part.''
</P>
<P>
   Rooney added that Wornick is ``really pleased that they're
talking again and really wants to go back to Channel 5,'' and that
Wornick ``really hopes they forgive her.''
</P>
<P>
   The ebullient Wornick is also a consumer reporter for Channel 5
and she is known as a figure who throws herself zealously into
community events. She was conspicous by her absence on Channel 5's
noon news Monday; colleague Liz Brunner substituted for her.
</P>
<P>
   For Channel 5, long the dominant force in Boston TV news, the
dispute _ with its damaging headlines and calls from irate viewers
_ occurred at what even La Camera conceded is ``not the most
opportune time.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the middle of the vital February ``sweeps'' period,
during which newscast ratings are closely measured to set future
advertising rates, the chief revenue source for local stations.
</P>
<P>
   While still firmly on top at noon, Channel 5 seems vulnerable
elsewhere. Long dominant in Boston, the station has been losing
ground lately to WHDH-Ch. 7.
</P>
<P>
   ``Channel 5 would make a mistake in allowing a person who's that
well-known and that well-liked in the community to leave,''
remarked WBZ-Ch. 4 reporter Dan Rea.
</P>
<P>
   It is no longer clear that Wornick will in fact leave. What is
clear, however, is that Boston's broadcast community is buzzing
about once-staid Channel 5.
</P>
</TEXT>
