<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-LAW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH IMPEACHMENTS, LITTLE SET IN STONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ADAM PERTMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On the one hand, many constitutional scholars and historians are
deeply upset by the precedents growing out of President Clinton's
legal and political travails. Then again, most aren't very worried
about what those precedents portend.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for the seemingly contradictory analysis is this: No
matter how important the short-term impact may be of any actions
taken by the courts or by the Congress since the president's affair
with Monica S. Lewinsky was revealed, the experts believe future
judges and lawmakers probably won't model their behavior strictly
on this case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course not,'' said William Van Alstyne, a constitutional
historian at Duke University who maintains Clinton committed
impeachable offenses. ``Everything could be reassessed if and when
there is another episode like this, and much of it probably will
be. . . . Absolutely, we could make too much of all this.''
</P>
<P>
   This is not to say that legal specialists take this case
lightly. Indeed, some argue it already may have shifted the balance
of power among the branches of government, and set other important
precedents, but they disagree about what the changes are and how
lasting they may be.
</P>
<P>
   Most critics of the charges against Clinton, for instance,
assert that Republican prosecutors _ by focusing on behavior that
was mainly private _ have so diminished the intent of ``high crimes
and misdemeanors'' that future House majorities will be tempted to
impeach presidents whenever it suits their partisan purposes. In
this view, the effect of the prosecution was to shift the balance
of power away from the executive and toward the legislative.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, some conservative scholars contend that Democratic
pressure put such constraints on the prosecution's case,
particularly by limiting the number of witnesses and blocking live
testimony, that it undermined the prospect of success for future
prosecutions. This analysis holds that the legislative branch has
diluted its ability, through impeachment, to keep presidents in
check, thereby shifting power to the executive branch.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, experts with diverse views about other issues said a
major shift toward the judicial branch, at the expense of the other
two, could take place if there is an appeal to the Supreme Court
about any aspect of the trial _ from the closing of Senate
deliberations to the final verdict _ and the court agrees to hear
it. That now seems extremely unlikely, but legal scholars don't
preclude it given the harshly adversarial nature of the
proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Theoretically, there are supposed to be neutral, historical
standards . . . and changing them can have a real impact on the
balance of power,'' said Judith Olans-Brown, a constitutional law
professor at Northeastern University. ``But the truth is that
precedent in many ways is a myth. When the Supreme Court doesn't
want to follow one of its rulings anymore, it changes it. So do the
courts . . . and so do the House and the Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   Precedents, both on legal and procedural matters, are
particularly susceptible to change in presidential impeachments
because they occur so rarely. Moreover, the Constitution gives
Congress such broad latitude in deciding issues relating to them
that precedent matters less than it does in other legal
proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   So the Senate's decision to close its doors for deliberations in
the Clinton case was based on Andrew Johnson's trial more than a
century earlier, when television and open-meeting laws didn't
exist. But that doesn't mean future senators, faced with different
social pressures and advanced technologies, will make the same
judgment.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, just because the Supreme Court held unanimously that
Paula Jones could proceed with her civil suit against Clinton while
he was in office _ a decision that ultimately led to his
impeachment trial _ doesn't mean that subsequent courts will allow
similar litigation against other presidents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't go so far as to say they can or would totally
reinvent their decisions each time they're made, but they have such
wide discretion that, certainly, they can do it,'' said Todd
Gaziano, a senior fellow in legal studies at the Heritage
Foundation. He was referring to both the courts and Congress.
</P>
<P>
   This is not to say that the circumstances and management of the
Clinton trial won't have substantial legal and historical
reverberations.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, both the Supreme Court decision about civil suits
and the expansive authority given to the special prosecutor in this
case, Kenneth W. Starr, have led many potential congressional and
presidential candidates to reassess whether high offices in the
United States are worth seeking or holding.
</P>
<P>
   But, largely as a result of Starr's actions, members of both
parties predict the special prosecutor law will be radically
revised or even eliminated this year. And many legal analysts agree
tat if civil suits against presidents proliferate as a result of
the Clinton v. Jones ruling, the high court probably will reverse
this judgment.
</P>
<P>
   It is the Congress that provoked the most scholarly concern
about the fluidity of impeachment precedent. Just because the
Constitution gives lawmakers so much discretion and power, those
interviewed said, doesn't mean they should necessarily use it.
</P>
<P>
   Experts of every political stripe, for instance, decried the
Senate's serious consideration of splitting its final vote: one on
whether Clinton committed the acts he was charged with, the other
on whether he should be removed from office. Conservatives like
Gaziano and former federal judge Robert Bork joined liberal
scholars in pronouncing that idea as patently unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a big difference between having the power to do
something and having the right to do it,'' said Dan Coquilette, a
constitutional historian at Boston College who thinks the charges
against Clinton should not have led to his impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how that difference manifests itself, since a
congressional action probably could not be appealed to a higher
authority, Coquilette replied: ``It's not just a question of the
immediate consequences. The big difference comes in terms of
people's respect for what they do, and the legitimacy of what they
do. . . . History will be the final judge.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
