u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-VICTIMS-BOS &LR;      02-16 1174
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-VICTIMS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNCELEBRATED PAID BIG PRICES FOR THEIR BIT PARTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The FBI agents showed up at 6 a.m. at Ben Hiatt's
door in Alexandria, Va., with a subpoena and a surprise:
Independent counsel Kenneth W. Starr was seeking his grand jury
testimony in the case against President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Hiatt, a hospitality consultant, didn't welcome the intrusion.
``I felt invaded,'' Hiatt said. And he definitely felt intimidated.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, he recalled something his sister, Julie Hiatt Steele,
had said to a Newsweek magazine reporter who was examining her
friend Kathleen Willey's relationship with the president _ a
relationship that had drawn Starr's scrutiny. And on that slender
thread he found himself ensnared in Starr's ever wider net.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody has paid much attention to Ben Hiatt or the dozens upon
dozens of little voices who played bit parts in Washington's
dramatic Year of Sex, Scandal, Starr, Monica, Linda, Clinton, and
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   But it doesn't mean that in ways large and small, lives haven't
been altered, relationships bruised, and nest eggs shattered in
what, for many, amounted to one very scary moment in the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   ``The havoc this has caused to families and children, in dollars
and cents, and in the disruption of lives, has been huge,'' said
Ann Kendall, a well-known Washington child psychologist. ``So many
of them were public servants put under such stress.''
</P>
<P>
   Kendall understands the personal toll because the scandal has
all but devoured her husband, David, one of the lawyers who
defended Clinton in the impeachment trial that ended Friday with
acquittal. Like many others who have been touched by the year of
troubles, Ann Kendall is under an attorney's orders not to talk to
reporters about the case.
</P>
<P>
   Julie Hiatt Steele isn't allowed to give interviews, either. She
faces trial March 30 on Starr's charges she lied to two grand
juries about whether the president groped Willey, a White House
volunteer, outside the Oval Office. But Ben Hiatt, who has set up a
legal defense fund for his sister, an unemployed single mother of
an eight-year-old son, is vocal about how the scandal is putting
her through the wringer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Julie is a classic victim. Every day she asks, `Why me?' ''
Hiatt said, noting that his sister faces a maximum 35-year jail
term and is the only person indicted so far by Starr in the
Lewinsky phase of his long investigation. ``She's got a strong
will, but it takes a lot of energy to withstand this kind of
pressure, emotional and financial. It pains her that her son gets
teased at school.''
</P>
<P>
   While under investigation, Steele lost her sales job at a
telecommunications company in Richmond, Va., and her neighbors
began avoiding her, Hiatt said. Worst of all, he said, prosecutors
began questioning him and other relatives about the circumstances
and legality of Steele's adoption of her Romanian-born son in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Steele, Jennifer Palmieri was only a witness in the Starr
probe. A former aide in the office of then-White House chief of
staff Leon Panetta, Palmieri had the bad luck to have been
supervising Lewinsky the night she delivered pizza to, and began an
affair with, the president. For her, testifying before the grand
jury was a ``Kafkaesque'' experience, said Richard Sauber,
Palmieri's lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jennifer felt terribly guilty, and she still does,'' Sauber
said. ``Who wants to drop a dime on a co-worker or get a friend in
trouble? Nobody understands how dramatically a thing like this
alters a workplace and how absolutely deleterious it is to personal
and professional relationships when people are afraid to talk to
one another.''
</P>
<P>
   Sauber donated his legal services to Palmieri, which is one
reason she has stayed at the White House, now as a deputy assistant
to the president for press operations. ``Spending $20,000 or
$30,000 for a defense in a criminal case is nothing,'' Sauber said.
``But to somebody making $80,000, that is a huge bill.''
</P>
<P>
   And that, of course, is small change compared to what Betty
Currie, the president's secretary, has incurred in her six-figure
legal bills. While some of the big names in the administration
bailed out early, most of the small fish hauled into Starr's probe
remain at the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Stewards Bayani Nelvis and Glen Maes, for example, are still on
the job after being grilled by Starr's prosecutors about what they
saw in the pantry outside the Oval Office. Nancy Hernreich and
Marsha Scott, two aides who didn't trust Lewinsky around the
president, and who testified to that, remain as Clinton deputies in
the West Wing.
</P>
<P>
   The Secret Service made a fuss, and an unsuccessful legal
challenge, when more than a dozen of its agents were called to
testify about the president and Lewinsky before Starr's grand jury
last year. Arguing for the privilege of ``protective function,''
lawyers for the service said they feared for a future when the
president would not allow agents to be near enough to carry out
their guard assignments.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Larry Cockell, Clinton's agent in charge, is back and
heading the presidential detail _ Cockell was reassigned around the
time of his testimony _ and there is speculation he is soon going
to be named by the president as director of the Secret Service.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very awkward position for all of us, but I can't say
we have suffered any adverse effect professionally,'' said John
Muskett, a Secret Service officer who told the grand jury he had
often seen Lewinsky around and about the president's office.
</P>
<P>
   Rahm Emanuel, one of the president's closest advisers through
the scandal, called working in the White House ``one of the
greatest experiences of my life,'' but also one of the most trying.
Emanuel recently left to become an investment banker in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some, this period has been a tiring and draining death
march,'' Emanuel said. ``For others, it has been a noble battle
waged against the endless effort of a prosecutor to distract,
attack, and derail the administration.''
</P>
<P>
   For a few, the scandal took them on a strange journey into
celebrity status and media madness. Irene Kassorla, a Los Angeles
psychologist who counseled Lewinsky from 1992 to 1997 and was
required to give Starr a deposition about her patient, said she got
very weary of finding a throng of television cameras at her gate
and reading press interviews she had never given.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm used to security, privacy, and confidentiality,'' said
Kassorla, noting she would have to ``crouch down in the back seat''
of her car to avoid the press. She also hired three lawyers _ two
in California, one in Washington _ to guide her though the legal
thicket.
</P>
<P>
   All the attention and aggravation had some good effect, however.
Kassorla said her practice now receives more calls from would-be
patients, and attendance has improved at her lectures.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like that,'' Kassorla said. ``I really like to help
people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
