<HEADER>
A6978 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-ANALYSIS-BOS &LR;      02-16 1731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN ALTERED POLITICAL LANDSCAPE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID M. SHRIBMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A quarter century ago, Watergate ended with the
resignation of President Nixon and with booming proclamations of
triumph: (itals)Justice was done, the system worked.(unitals) On
the day Nixon left office, The Boston Globe stretched the words of
the preamble to the Constitution (``We the people . . .'') across
the top of the front page.
</P>
<P>
   Hardly anyone feels that way in America today. There's no sense
of triumph, only trepidation.
</P>
<P>
   Our long national nightmare may be over, but that doesn't mean
Americans can now sleep easily.
</P>
<P>
   Because now that we are awakening to the dawn of the post-Monica
era, we are discovering that the landscape of American political
life and culture has been altered substantially _ and in disturbing
ways.
</P>
<P>
   The respect of the public for national authority has diminished.
The connection between the electors and the elected has broken. The
gap between the selfless and the cynical has grown. The wall
between the public and the private has tumbled. The restraints on
the press have loosened. The powers and prerogatives of the
president have eroded. The majesty and mystery of high office have
vanished.
</P>
<P>
   Watergate ended with hope. The Clinton sex-and-deception scandal
ends in dejection. Watergate brought a new beginning. The Clinton
episode foreshadows a frightful new era of more intrusion into
public lives, more comprehensive investigations of government
officials and more public alienation.
</P>
<P>
   Watergate left a blot on American political life, but Republican
Senator Howard H. Baker Jr. was able to rise above party and
Democratic Senator Sam J. Ervin Jr. of North Carolina was able to
rise above parochialism. Watergate put administration officials in
impossible positions, but Attorney General Elliot L. Richardson
resigned over a matter of principle. Watergate left the law
trammelled, but the integrity of Archibald Cox and Leon Jaworski
above reproach.
</P>
<P>
   The long struggle to determine if President Clinton had an
affair with a onetime intern and then conspired to lie about it
produced no such shining figures _ and no sense or where or how to
make a new start.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Americans _ weary of politics _ are girding for a
congressional session full of suspicions and for a presidential
contest in which the candidates' personal affairs will be as
important as their positions on national affairs. Now Americans
must grow accustomed to a presidency that is grounded in celebrity,
to national debates that are more than ever distilled down to
personality conflicts, and to a bigger gap than ever between
Washington leaders and the people who chose them as their
representatives.
</P>
<P>
   In the past year, as the president has repeatedly deceived the
American public, and as the nation's politicians have bent the
constitution to partisan advantage, the fragile sense of decency
that pervaded the nation's politics has evaporated.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a new political world _ one where the sturdy
signposts of the past have been toppled and where the assumptions
that guided Americans in times of turmoil and testing no longer
hold firm. Here are some of the unknowns in that new world:
</P>
<P>
   --The future of the presidency. Clinton set his cap for the
presidency because, in his youth in the heady Kennedy years, the
presidency was the commanding heights of American life and culture.
The strong stewardship of Franklin Delano Roosevelt and the
reassuring presidential presence of Dwight D. Eisenhower made the
White House an irresistible focus of national attention. Throughout
the Cold War, when American survival in the face of the communist
threat was not assured, the White House, along with the
``football'' with the secret nuclear-weapons code, was the symbolic
center of American security.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was the first modern president whose tenure fell
completely outside of the Cold War tensions. But Clinton helped
diminish the presidency further when he adopted a political style
that was better suited to afternoon television than to prime-time
presidential addresses; when he chose to be approachable rather
than formidable; and when, after his health-care plan died in 1994,
he changed his approach from grand policy proposals to small
suggestions.
</P>
<P>
   All presidents change the office they hold, but few will have
changed it as dramatically as Clinton did. He will leave to his
successor in 2001 a presidency that is shrunken and trivialized _
posing an enormous challenge for an office that until now has shown
remarkable resiliency. In the past, most recently for Gerald Ford
and Ronald Reagan, a diminished presidency has presented an
opportunity for a strong leader to restore the office's prestige _
and with it the nation's.
</P>
<P>
   --The future of the legislative branch. For two centuries,
American congresses have been organized by parties, but seldom _ in
the Reconstruction era, perhaps in the New Deal period _ has the
sense of partisanship on Capitol Hill been as strong as it is
today. Historians likely will apportion the blame evenly _ to the
Democrats for enforcing a near tyranny in the House for 40
consecutive years, to the Republicans by responding with a searing
partisanship of their own once Newt Gingrich led them to power in
1994 and presided as speaker for four years thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   The House impeachment and Senate trial only exacerbated those
tensions. Every important question was settled by votes basically
along party lines. When the House finally voted to impeach the
president, only five Democrats and five Republicans broke from
their parties to embrace the views of the other side. When the
Senate voted on whether to call witnesses or dismiss the trial late
last month, only Senator Russell D. Feingold, the Wisconsin
Democrat, strayed from party lines.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Daniel Patrick Moynihan, the scholarly New York
Democrat, used to say that the glory of the American legislature
was that no important measure ever passed by a party-line or narrow
vote; America jumped into new waters or deep water with both feet,
and both parties. The Clinton impeachment saga jeopardized that
tradition.
</P>
<P>
   --The future of the two-party system. The framers of the
Constitution didn't envision a two-party system, but the enduring
power of the two major parties has been one of the hallmarks of
American political stability. Even so, third-party candidates have
made major challenges to the Democrats and Republicans four times
in the last third of the century (George C. Wallace in 1968, John
B. Anderson in 1980, Ross Perot in 1992 and 1996).
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's second term opened with an inquiry into the Democrats'
questionable fundraising practices, but there remained serious
questions about the Republicans' campaign-finance techniques as
well. In behaving more like corporate fund-raisers than like party
organizers, the Republicans and Democrats seemed to undermine their
stability rather than solidify it. The public attention to the
campaign-finance system hurt public confidence in the parties. The
deeply partisan behavior of both parties in the Clinton impeachment
and trial only deepened public suspicions.
</P>
<P>
   --The convergence of politics and technology. President
Clinton's liaison with Monica S. Lewinsky and the furor that
followed it made for a thoroughly modern scandal, recorded by tape,
proven by DNA evidence, prosecuted on television, chewed over on
cable. The technology that transformed into a consuming national
scandal the sort of sexual adventure that Presidents John F.
Kennedy and Lyndon B. Johnson were accused of having were
unimaginable in the Kennedy and Johnson years. One of the elements
of proof in the Clinton scandal, e-mail from Lewinsky, was unknown
to most Americans at the beginning of the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton scandal is a harbinger of a new politics for the new
world. As technology expands and the capability of individuals to
record the failings of humans grows, politicians can expect new
levels of scrutiny and Americans can expect scandals to develop
with new levels of volume and velocity.
</P>
<P>
   --The worth of the president's word. Americans have disbelieved
their leaders before; even the earliest observers of the new nation
noted that a hearty crop of skepticism is bred in the fertile
American soil. The popularity of the term ``credibility gap'' in
the Johnson years is proof of Americans' well-justified skepticism
of the president. Harry Truman once said of President Nixon: ``I
don't think the son of a bitch knows the difference between telling
the truth and lying.''
</P>
<P>
   Now President Clinton has added his own half-truths and
deceptions to the nation's repertoire of presidential whoppers. His
finger-wagging denial of any sexual relationship with ``that woman,
Miss Lewinsky'' and his hair-splitting legalisms on subjects such
as the definition of the word ``is'' have further eroded public
trust in the person who occupies the Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   --The role of the public. One of the chestnuts of politics is
the story about the lady who said she didn't vote because ``it only
encourages them.'' That lady now speaks for the country, and the
story no longer is a joke.
</P>
<P>
   From the start, at every twist, on issues small and large, the
public recoiled from this case, and at every turn the political
establishment, which until recently was reviled for listening too
carefully to polls, defied the public. Americans didn't want
Clinton impeached. The House impeached him anyway. A day before the
Senate voted to depose witnesses, a Pew Research Center poll showed
that 53 percent of people opposed witnesses. The Senate did it
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   The result was a growing gap between those who govern and those
who are governed _ but, perhaps more significant, a growing view
that the governing class and the governed class have little in
common, little to do with each other, and little to say to each
other.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge for the political system is as great at the close
of the 20th century as it was at the close of the 18th: To nurture
a connection between public officials and the public, to establish
a sense of legitimacy for the political system, and to infuse the
public with a sense of ownership of the institutions of government.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
