<SLUG> BC-AUTOS-COUPES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUPES ARE BACK _ THOUGH THEY NEVER WENT AWAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The coupe is back in favor in the automobile world. It isn't
that these two-door models ever left the car scene, but this year
they are `in' as never before. And more new models are on the way.
</P>
<P>
   Is this a sign that buyers are nostalgic for the cars of their
youth or do these cars have an aura of performance combined with
sex appeal?
</P>
<P>
   For the manufacturers, it seems an easy way to gain a more
``youthful'' market and jazz up what might be considered a dull car
line.
</P>
<P>
   The coupe is not the most practical of vehicles _ it's hard to
get into the back seat and cargo space is usually smaller than in a
sedan. And limiting a vehicle to two doors doesn't seem to make
sense at a time when manufcaturers are adding doors to minivans and
trucks.
</P>
<P>
   This new marketing of coupes may be the signal of a new era in
the auto world. Manufacturers view the baby-boomers _ now in their
50s and freed of college payments and the need to haul things
around _ as leaving sport utilities and looking for something more
dashing.
</P>
<P>
   Is this fanciful thinking on the part of carmakers or, even a
momentary craze among car buyers? Certainly the numbers don't
justify the new interest in coupes. In 1985, sales of coupes
reached almost 2.1 million or 13.6 percent of the auto market. In
1987, sales were down 1 million with coupes capturing just 6.8
percent of the market. According to Automotive News, the past
year's sales of such coupes as the Honda Accord, Cadillac Eldorado
and Lexus SC have been way off projections. And yet, along comes
Audi, Mercedes, Mercury, Toyota, Volvo and BMW with coupes that
range from the fanciful and sleek to BMW's M Coupe that can best be
described as a drive into nostalgia.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the more eye-catching coupes are designed to do just
that _ catch buyers' eyes in the showroom. How else can you explain
the Volvo C70, the Toyota Solara or the Mercury Cougar?
</P>
<P>
   Volvo, better known for its boxy designs, has built its
reputation on safety, not style. Volvo knows, as other makers add
to their safety credentials, that it needs to draw in new customers
looking for sleeker style. Toyota's Camry has everything going for
it _ including a reputation for reliability and quality _ but to
many people, it's also short of pizzaz. Enter the Solara, a
Camry-based coupe that is anything but dull in looks. The Cougar is
the first shot from Mercury in its new goal to be more than a Ford
lookalike. The Cougar is a Mercury exclusive. When the new Ford
Thunderbird comes out, it will not share anything of the Cougar
design or platform as it has in the past.
</P>
<P>
   While these coupes have appeal, it's harder to explain the
appeal of the BMW M Coupe. Its design is unusual. A long hood,
short body. Room for just two and enough cargo space to carry two
suitcases of moderate size. But it does perform on the road.
</P>
<P>
   The BMW M Coupe is a bit of nostalgia and its design comes out
of the past. When BMW introduced this South Carolina-built coupe,
it predicted Europeans would use it to dash off to the seashore or
the mountains for a weekend. Little luggage was needed, but the car
had to be quick and handle those mountain roads or twists and turns
down to the sea as nimbly as possible. At $42,000, the car is
loaded with safety, performance and comfort features. BMW says it
will do 0-60 miles per hour in 5 seconds and has a top speed of 137
m.p.h. Not bad for a funny-looking little car.
</P>
<P>
   More in trend with the times, the all new BMW 3-series coupe
will be going on sale this summer. Like the new 3-series sedan for
'99, the coupe will be larger and more quality driven and will
debut as a 2000 model.
</P>
<P>
   Mercedes-Benz offers two coupes in its CLK line. The V6-powered
CLK320 ($40,600), which was launched last year, is now joined by
the V8-powered CLK430 ($47,200). Mercedes designed the CLK
structure specifically for coupe and Cabriolet models. However, the
Cabriolet convertible is not a coupe with the top cut off. In fact,
except for modified doors on the Cabriolet, the two models share
very little structure and no body panels beyond the A pillars.
</P>
<P>
   For New England drivers, these coupes have added features to
ensure safe driving in wet and winter driving. An Electronic
Stability Program is standard on the 430 and optional on the V6.
ESP prevents slides and spins by automatically detecting the road
problem and applying selective braking to keep the car going where
the driver is pointing it. And there is ASR traction control that
detects when one rear wheel is spinning faster than the other and
selectively applies the brake to that wheel to restore traction. If
it were not for a warning light on the dash to indicate ESP action,
you'd never know something was happening.
</P>
<P>
   These hot performers provide Mercedes safety innovations along
with room for four passengers. There is ample room in the rear for
two passengers, and entry is easy. When a latch is moved on the
driver's or passenger's seat, that seat automatically moves
forward, then returns to its original position.
</P>
<P>
   Like its sedans and wagons, Volvo's C70 coupe is loaded with
safety features. Volvo finally has broken out of its rectangular
looks, and the C70 is proof positive of that change. Volvo isn't
skimping on performance, either. The C70 also is available as a
high-pressure turbo model.
</P>
<P>
   The Cougar already is proving to be a winner for Mercury. It is
drawing people into Mercury showrooms who have never bought or
thought of buying a Mercury before. That's success. The Cougar is
available with either a 2.0-liter four-cylinder or a 2.5-liter V6
power plant.
</P>
<P>
   Toyota says its Solara is aimed at ``consumers entering their
peak earning years, who are nostalgic for the sports cars of their
youth, but need more room and comfort that a sports car can
provide.'' It comes with either a four-cylinder or V6 engine and a
choice of five-speed manual or four-speed automatic transmission.
The Solara is the first Toyota to have a new JBL premium sound
system with 200 watts and eight speakers ``that will achieve a
level of performance and sound reproduction previously unavailable
in a Toyota.''
</P>
<P>
   The coupe craze extends throughout the auto world. Reading
Automobile magazine's 1999 Buying and Leasing guide, I counted 59
coupes ranging in price from $9,000 to $319,900. Both in looks and
convenience, one of the best buys is the Saturn SC with a third
door. Yes, hidden near the driver's side door is a hinged third
door, just like those on extended cab trucks. You'd never know it's
there until you need it. Then you'll love it.
</P>
<P>
   For $9,000, you can get the Chevrolet Metro and have the EPA's
overall winner in the fuel economy listings. If you wish to spend
$319,900, you could buy the Bentley Continenta. It isn't much on
mileage, but if you've got this much money to spend, who cares?
</P>
<P>
   The Honda Accord is another distinct coupe. Like the Volvo and
Camry coupes, the Accord has its own sheet metal package, setting
it apart from the four-door sedan.
</P>
<P>
   Among other new '99 models to check out are the Oldsmobile
Alero, Pontiac Grand Am, the Plymouth/Dodge Neon, Ford Mustang,
Daewoo Lanos, and from Volkswagen, the new Golf or the very catchy
Beetle.
</P>
<P>
   Joining in the coupe craze is Audi, which this spring will bring
out a striking-looking TT coupe with a 180-horsepower turbocharged
1.8-liter, four-cylinder engine. You'd never know it shares a
platform with the VW Beetle.
</P>
<P>
   So are two doors enough? Unquestionably, especially in two-car
families where the second vehicle is a people-mover.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
