<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-16 13:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6983 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIETNAM-JOURNAL-BOS &LR;      02-16 1559
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIETNAM-JOURNAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIECING TOGETHER A WAR STORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW V. STORIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (itals)I arrive at Pochentong Airport in Phnom Penh amid a
fusillade of two dozen 107mm rockets, a welcome delivered by the
Khmer Rouge. In a few weeks they will control all of Cambodia. For
now, they are just making their presence felt. I join other war
correspondents on the scene. It is March 4, 1975.(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PHNOM PENH _ I'm back at Pochentong, a middle-aged man
revisiting a part of the world that figured prominently in my life
and my country's. I am trying to make sense of it all through the
lens of the quarter-century that has passed since my last visit. It
is Jan. 19, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The day I arrived all those years ago, I got up off the cool
tiled floor of the airport when the rockets ceased, hastily signed
up a driver/interpreter. We turn right out of the airport, headed
for town.
</P>
<P>
   Today, I am accompanied by Indira Lakshmanan, who holds the post
I once held as the Globe's Asia bureau chief. We are met by Bernie
Krisher, a retired American journalist-turned-philanthropist who
offered to show us around. This time we turn left out of
Pochentong, headed for a surprise.
</P>
<P>
   In five minutes we are at the Future Light Orphanage, which
Krisher supports with both his own money and money he raises from
Japan, the states, and elsewhere. It's a few simple but clean
buildings in the middle of pretty country. The sun is just setting
as we are ushered into the orphanage's rare treasure: an
air-conditioned computer lab.
</P>
<P>
   Powered by generators (there are no power lines this far from
town), the unit was built with help from several private sources,
including the MIT Media Lab in Cambridge. The Lab's founder and
director, Nicholas Negroponte, visited a few days ago for the
dedication. On 33 computers of varied vintage, the children learn
the future. Most know how to get onto the Internet. (E-mails will
be waiting when I return to Boston.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (itals)March 1975: In a small orphanage operated by Canadians, I
write about a premature baby girl found in a gutter of Phnom Penh
shortly before dawn a few weeks earlier. In an incredible
coincidence, she is adopted by a Cambridge couple, Rikk and Pam
Larsen. By the time I learn this in the early '80s, Siri Larsen is
already a talented gymnast. She goes on to star at Michigan State
University. Siri was a very fortunate child, rescued weeks before
the Khmer Rouge took Phnom Penh.(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Today, children at Future Light are similarly blessed. There is
still much poverty and political uncertainty in Cambodia, but
clearly there are signs of a better world.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (itals)March 12, 1975: St. Joseph's Hospital has been in
business less than two weeks. I file a story reporting that seven
children have already died there from malnutrition. A Filipino
doctor tells me, ``What we really have to do is to change their
standard of living. To do that, of course, we have to end the
war.''(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jan. 20, 1999: Today we visit the Sihanouk Hospital Center of
HOPE, where two doctors from the Boston area, Graham Gumley
(Carlisle) and Cameron Gifford (Wellesley), are training Cambodian
doctors and nurses and giving the locals the best medical care they
perhaps have ever had. But the rising incidence of the HIV virus is
alarming, and cholera is another problem.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (itals)In the Boston Sunday Globe, I report that this ``city is
considered virtually indefensible against two North Vietnamese
divisions, plus reinforcements, poised to attack, reliable
intelligence sources said last night.'' The dateline is Saigon, the
date April 6, 1975.(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jan. 22, 1999
</P>
<P>
   HO CHI MINH CITY _ I wrote a few things back then that were
wrong about Vietnam, but that Page One story was dead on. One of my
sources (it's probably OK now to say he was a US intelligence
officer) had told me, ``The NVA (North Vietnamese Army) right now
are maneuvering for a major assault on Saigon and if they don't
come straight to the Continental Palace (a downtown hotel where the
interview was taking place), it's only because they don't want
to.''
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks later, the North Vietnamese marched right into
Saigon. I had been out of the country for seven days, under orders
from Globe publisher Davis Taylor, who was worried about my health.
Neither of us realized that premature departure would haunt me
professionally for years. A reporter wants to stick with a story to
the end, and I sometimes regret I did not _ especially since the
end came, as it turned out, just seven days after I departed, and
all those correspondents still on the scene managed to get out
safely.
</P>
<P>
   Today I walk through the lobby of the refurbished Continental
Palace, lamenting only the disappearance of the open-air veranda
where reporters, soldiers, spies, and bar girls shortened their
hours back then.
</P>
<P>
   Indira and I go the next day to visit the Museum of the Ho Chi
Minh Campaign. Inside the gate, in the blazing sun, sits what
appears to be an American jet fighter, an F-5E. There's a legend in
Vietnamese and English.
</P>
<P>
   The words leap out at me. I tell Indira, ``I saw this plane
fly!'' On the morning of April 8, 1975, Lieutenant Nguyen Thanh
Trung, a defector from the South Vietnamese Air Force, disregarded
his flight plan and set off for Saigon. He flew low over the city
on two runs, dropping a total of four bombs and slightly damaging
his target, the presidential palace. He then flew to the safety of
North Vietnamese territory. I was among the reporters who saw it
all from a nearby restaurant. I can still see the plane, flying
slowly, it seemed, against an unusually clear sky for Vietnam, and
dropping its final two bombs. Rarely is one confronted with a
museum piece one saw in its functioning phase. It does not make one
feel young.
</P>
<P>
   At last report, Nguyen Thanh Trung is working as a pilot for
Vietnam Airlines. For all I know he could have piloted my flight
from Phnom Penh.
</P>
<P>
   In the early '70s, my colleagues and I used to speculate about
how Saigon might change under what seemed to us the inevitable
victors from the north. Nearly 28 years later, I am seeing it.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Phnom Penh _ which except for the addition of two or
three first-class hotels and restaurants looks virtually the same _
Saigon is transformed. It's brightly lit skyline includes perhaps a
dozen mini-skyscrapers.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout this city (not often called by its new name) beggars
still crowd the sidewalks, and haphazard hordes of Honda motorbikes
dominate the streets. (Note to aging warhands: The bikes are
infinitely quieter than they were back then.)
</P>
<P>
   A Vietnamese journalist tells us the Hanoi government still puts
too many restrictions on the economy but is learning slowly to open
up some areas. Collective farms are giving way to private
ownership, mirroring the American ``Land to the Tiller'' program
that legendary American adviser John Paul Vann pitched to me in my
first reporting trip as one of the best roads to possible victory
over the communists.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (itals)We have been out on night patrol in Thang Binh, just
below the demilitarized zone that separates North and South
Vietnam. Colonel Nguyen Minh Dang, 38, is now holding court over
tea. ``We are happy to receive the help of the Americans,'' he
tells me and Peter Jay of The Washington Post. ``But I like my
people to be proud. The Americans came six years ago. Now you must
move out.'' It is April 1971.(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The last Americans of the war era left four years later, their
departure captured in a famous photograph of an evacuation
helicopter rising from the roof of the US Embassy. That building no
longer exists. In its place, a modern new consulate, representing
``The United State of America'' is being built.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Brinks'' _ the high-rise Bachelor Officers' Quarters from
which I watched the early morning attack by Lieutenant Trung _ is
being renovated. According to a sign on the construction perimeter,
this concrete remnant of the American war machine will soon be a
Park Hyatt Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   An item in the Vietnam News notes that the United States is the
leading importer of the much-admired Vietnamese coffee bean. A
letter to the same newspaper from a businessman, perhaps a
foreigner, asks, ``Why do people all over the world buy Adidas, La
Coste, and Nike products? Because it is a status symbol. Why should
Vietnam be different?''
</P>
<P>
   For Americans, of course, Vietnam is different: 58,151 of our
fellow citizens died here. After nearly a quarter-century, it would
perhaps seem that something about that period would either make
more sense, or yield to greater understanding.
</P>
<P>
   Defenders then of American foreign policy might argue now that
forcing yet another stand against communism was a part, albeit a
sad part, of a long march toward 1989, the crumbling of the Berlin
Wall, andthe dissolution of the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   I can tell you that today's Vietnam, so peaceful and prosperous
compared with 1975, seems nothing so much as isolated from those
major currents of a larger world. So far from Berlin, Moscow, and
from that dark, glossed wall in Washington with its thousands of
names.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-99 1333EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
