<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-16 13:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6987 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRESIDENT-RACE-BOS &LR;      02-16 1073
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRESIDENT-RACE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENTS' LEGACIES ON RACE GET A FRESH LOOK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TATSHA ROBERTSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Abraham Lincoln said he didn't believe that blacks should vote,
marry whites, sit on a jury, or hold office. Still, with the stroke
of a pen, he freed millions of slaves when he signed the
Emancipation Proclamation.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Clinton has spoken eloquently on matters of race. He has
frequently talked of ``One America.'' But critics complain that he
has done little to create the policies to translate his words into
action.
</P>
<P>
   From George Washington, who struggled with the issue of slavery,
to the varied race-relations records of recent leaders, presidents
always have had to perform a balancing act between political
reality and their personal views on the role of African-Americans
in society.
</P>
<P>
   Historians say it's appropriate that Presidents' Day should fall
in the middle of Black History Month, since issues of race _ from
slavery to affirmative action _ have dogged the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   But as a new generation of high school and college students
explores the contradictions between the public statements and
private acts of their leaders, teachers and historians are seeking
ways to tell the full story of the relationship between
African-Americans and US leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, the presidents did everything right. . . . It was
a red, white, and blue kind of history,'' said Walter Lambert,
chairman of the history department at Boston Latin School. ``Now we
need to tell the truth, but also put it in context.''
</P>
<P>
   How important is it that Lyndon B. Johnson, who signed the Civil
Rights Bill of 1964 into law, used racial epithets when cozying up
with Southern politicians? Does it matter, according to some
historians, that Richard Nixon expanded affirmative action not to
help minorities but to stir white resentment and a backlash?
</P>
<P>
   Of all the presidents, historians say, only Johnson and Lincoln
stand out for what they did to improve the lives of
African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have their baggage, but even with their baggage, it's
hard to criticize them,'' said Kenneth O'Reilly, author of
``Nixon's Piano,'' which examines presidents' views and actions on
race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beyond those two, it's a stretch (to rank others),'' O'Reilly
said. ``Maybe Truman. . . . He did desegregate the military.''
</P>
<P>
   Others say that if contemporary standards were applied to past
presidents, most would fail to measure up. It is more important to
look at what they ultimately accomplished rather than focus on
their personal views, in the opinion of Wendall Bourne, a content
specialist for the Massachusetts Department of Education and a
seventh-grade teacher.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Lincoln's views, Bourne said, the 16th president
nonetheless changed the course of history and the direction of race
relations. ``I tell the students that you probably wouldn't be
looking at me (a black man) if history had been different.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Gibbons, of Harvard University's Graduate School of
Education, says a close study reveals that most presidents are
reluctant to push civil rights issues at election time for fear of
losing white votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frederick Douglass was very angry with Lincoln for not ending
slavery fast or quick enough, but when Lincoln signed the
Emancipation Proclamation, he became a hero in his eyes,'' Gibbons
said. That is significant, scholars say, because of Douglass's
clout among African-Americans and other abolitionists of the time.
</P>
<P>
   John F. Kennedy was criticized for taking too long to act on
civil rights. ``He was more concerned with keeping the white
vote,'' Lambert said. ``You won't see Kennedy at the rally in
Washington in 1963 or the (other) Kennedy brothers.''
</P>
<P>
   But some historians give Kennedy credit for initiating the
sweeping civil rights bill that Johnson later signed into law. It
was Kennedy who sent the National Guard to the University of
Alabama in June 1963 when the all-white school had to be forced to
admit two black students.
</P>
<P>
   Gibbons, who travels around the country talking to students
about the tarnishing of heroes, said youngsters often bring up
Thomas Jefferson's record on race. ``It's a tough one,'' he
admitted.
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson, author of the Declaration of Independence, maintained
that the worst thing a slave owner could do is exploit a female
slave, Gibbons said. Yet advances in science, such as DNA testing,
and dogged detective work have shown that Jefferson apparently did
just that.
</P>
<P>
   Most students today have a hard time dealing with the fact that
Jefferson owned slaves and fathered a child by his slave mistress
Sally Hemings, Gibbons explained.
</P>
<P>
   Even Washington, a slave owner who did not free his slaves until
his death, ranks higher than Jefferson in the eyes of most young
people.
</P>
<P>
   In the past 10 to 15 years, according to Lambert, textbooks
largely have been rewritten to include a more diverse portrait of
the past. And teachers are beginning to ask questions to make
students think more critically about the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because Jefferson was a hypocrite, does that mean we
should discount him?'' he asked. ``Kids come out with mixed views,
and in some cases, that leads to cynicism.''
</P>
<P>
   Of all the 20th century presidents, only Johnson's record on
race passes the test, in Lambert's view.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, we have had a lot of conversations (on race),'' he said
in reference to Clinton's national race initiative, ``but I can't
think of any real acts or decisions by a recent American
president.''
</P>
<P>
   Historians like O'Reilly say Clinton and his dialogues on race
place him on the same level with Kennedy _ among the better
preidents, but not at the top.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Clinton distanced himself from the Rev. Jesse
Jackson, criticized rapper Sistah Souljah, and was accused of
abandoning law professor Lani Guinier after her nomination to head
the Justice Department's civil rights division was challenged _
acts seen as traitorous by many blacks.
</P>
<P>
   Still, O'Reilly said, Clinton's dialogue on race is admirable
and proves that he believes race relations still is a problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton is a smart fellow,'' he said. ``He looked at how race
(relations) deteriorated during the Reagan and Bush
administrations.'' And Clinton, mindful of his legacy _ however
tarnished it may now be _ was determined that the same would not be
said of him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
