<DOCNO> NYT19990216.0110 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-16 13:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6988 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLACKHISTORY-POSTWAR-     02-16 0349
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACKHISTORY-POSTWAR-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Postwar surge shifts racial tide
 &HT;    By John Keilman
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The postwar years brought an unprecedented rush
of prosperity to America. Returning veterans flooded colleges,
corporations and factories, their brainpower and labor transforming
the nation into the world's premier economic superpower.
</P>
<P>
   Yet most of the country's blacks were denied a fair piece of
this bountiful pie. Many were no longer willing to accept that.
</P>
<P>
   In 1954, the U.S. Supreme Court ruled that segregated public
schools violated the Constitution. A year later, housekeeper Rosa
Parks refused to give up her seat on a bus, sparking a boycott that
kick-started the modern civil rights movement and vaulted Martin
Luther King Jr. to prominence.
</P>
<P>
   There was much to overcome. In Dayton, nearly all blacks lived
south of Wolf Creek, their efforts to settle in other areas
thwarted by nervous bankers and real estate agents. But people like
Ned Wood gradually did move, only to watch whites stream to the
suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   Racial brutality accelerated in the South as many whites sensed
power shifting. Yvonne Walker-Taylor, whose life in Wilberforce was
largely discrimination-free, experienced this cruelty when she
spent two summers teaching in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Still, progress was made. The Civil Rights Act of 1964, the
Voting Rights Act of 1965. These inspired thousands of blacks to
cast ballots for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Many attitudes seemed to change as well. Ellen Lee Jackson moved
from Dayton to Tennessee and found her new white neighbors
congenial. George Cooper became Dayton's first black city
government department head.
</P>
<P>
   The advances didn't mean the end of violence. A series of urban
riots erupted across the country, including one in Dayton in 1966
that doomed much of a West Dayton commercial district to
abandonment.
</P>
<P>
   But the convulsions had done their work. As the 1960s ended,
equality was the law, and America was a new nation.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-99 1336EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990216.0111 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-16 13:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6990 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-SCANDAL-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE     02-16 1361
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SCANDAL-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 SALT LAKE CITY: ... reports found.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Welch and Johnson soon found there was a growing queue of
outstanding individuals with hungry hearts and open hands. IOC vice
president Kim Un Yong of South Korea had a son who had been laid
off in New York and needed a job to keep his green card. The
bidders hooked him up with a Salt Lake telecommunications company
and subsidized nearly $100,000 in wages.
</P>
<P>
   Kim had a daughter who was an aspiring pianist. The bidders
landed her a solo with the Utah Symphony and a $5,000 fee. Kim knew
a Russian woman who needed a scholarship to Utah. The bidders set
it up and paid $15,000.
</P>
<P>
   There was nothing, it seemed, that Salt Lake wouldn't do to make
its Olympic friends part of the family. Sonia Essomba, daughter of
now-deceased IOC member Rene Essomba of Cameroon, got more than
$100,000 for tuition at American University, as well as living
expenses. When she changed apartments, finance director Rod Hamson
and Welch's secretary flew to Washington to help her move.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Rignault Arroyo, daughter of IOC member Agustin Arroyo of
Ecuador, was divorced and distressed in Texas. Welch got her a job
painting murals at the Utah Fair Grounds, put her up in the Santa
Fe Apartments, and paid the $23,000 tab.
</P>
<P>
   Bjarne Haeggman, husband of IOC member Pirjo Haeggman of
Finland, wanted a forestry job. Welch and Johnson got him a phantom
$34,000 consultancy with an Ogden engineering firm.
</P>
<P>
   But the bid committee's favorite family, by far, was the Gangas
from the Republic of Congo, who visited Salt Lake more than half a
dozen times. They flew first class from Brazzaville and stayed in
the best hotels. They got free medical care: IOC member Jean-Claude
Ganga was treated for hepatitis, his wife had cosmetic surgery, and
his mother-in-law had a knee replaced.
</P>
<P>
   And they shopped until their hosts' credit cards were maxed out.
Ganga's wife was a Wal-Mart whirlwind, stocking up on carpets and
draperies; a committee employee helped her plan the decor for a new
kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   The bidders had decided that the biggest reason Salt Lake had
lost to Nagano (other than the saltwater taffy/Honda differential),
was that too few IOC members had sampled the legendary Utah
hospitality, had seen the gorgeous Mormon temple, or skied down the
white-capped Wasatch mountains.
</P>
<P>
   So the bidders brought members from around the planet to their
capital and treated them like royalty. Their guests sat in
front-row seats at Utah Jazz basketball games and were introduced
at halftime. They ate gourmet dinners at local restaurants, went to
the symphony, skied at Snowbasin, went white-water rafting. Arroyo
and his family spent two weeks in a Park City ski condo at a cost
of $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   If local attractions proved insufficient, the IOC members were
jetted off to Las Vegas, to Disneyland, to New York City, to
Yellowstone Park, to Niagara Falls, or to Florida for the Super
Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The Lords and their families got tokens and keepsakes by the
armful _ coffee-table books, ski parkas, watches, spurs, crystal
globes, porcelain bells, neckties, and scarves. Samaranch received
a limited-edition Browning pistol worth $9,000. IOC member Jan
Staubo from Norway got a replica of the Spitfire he flew in World
War II.
</P>
<P>
   Computers, HealthRider exercise machines, perfumes, purebred
dogs, golf clubs, English lessons, skiing gear, kitchen appliances,
violins, bathroom fixtures, video games, decorative doorknobs _
there was always a smiling bidder with a credit card or an in-kind
account to charge it to 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal was to extol the virtues of Salt Lake City,'' the
ethics report concluded, ``and use the power of persuasion with
these newly made friends.''
</P>
<P>
   When 1995 and the IOC vote grew nearer, and ``giftage'' and
scholarships weren't enough, persuasion evolved into straight cash
by check or wire transfer. In some cases, the IOC members openly
asked for money.
</P>
<P>
   Just before the 1994 Games in Lillehammer, Charles Mukora of
Kenya, who had already received $5,200 from Welch, sent him a
plaintive letter begging for more assistance. ``I am considering
leaving Kenya, at least, for a period of time as I am so depressed
that I may develop ulcers or more serious ailments as I personally
feel I cannot cope,'' Mukora wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life is a great testing field where even the strongest must
walk through their own Garden of Gethsemene (sic),'' Welch replied.
``. . . I am greatly disappointed that others have not responded to
your need, and look forward to being with you in Lillehammer when
we can discuss this matter first hand.'' Welch ended up paying
Mukora another $29,000.
</P>
<P>
   IOC member Zein El Abdin Mohamed Ahmed Abdel Gadir of Sudan had
already received $17,000 in ``tuition payments'' for his son. Now,
he wanted $1,000 a month for his fictitious daughter Zema. Johnson
eventually wired Gadir $7,000. Essomba, whose daughter was still
living in Washington on Salt Lake cash, got $60,000 for himself.
IOC member Sergio Santander-Fantini of Chile got $20,000 for his
political campaign. Ganga got $70,000.
</P>
<P>
   The bidders had also hired lobbyists and middlemen who claimed
they could influence voters. Mahmoud El Farnawani, a Toronto
businessman with connections in northern Africa, received nearly
$150,000. Muttaleb Ahmad, who directed the Olympic Council of Asia,
got $62,000. Alfredo LaMont, the US Olympic Committee's director of
international relations, received $18,000, much of which was passed
on to IOC member Austin Sealy of Barbados, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
   Though Welch said every trustee up to Governor Mike Leavitt of
Utah was aware of the payoffs, they all denied it. They had gone to
the meetings or sent permanent alternates, glanced at the line
items on a bare-bones summary budget, and saw nothing amiss, even
though the budget nearly doubled between 1994 and 1995 with the
``slush fund'' soaring sevenfold.
</P>
<P>
   ``Board members, especially executive committee members, have a
duty to oversee the activities of management,'' the ethics panel
scolded. ``This is especially true where, as here, the trustees
believed that the CEO was undisciplined in his expenditure of
funds.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet every year through 1995, the accountants from Ernst &AMP; Young
gave them a clean audit, overlooking mysterious five-figure
payouts. Welch had told them that the executive committee had
approved undocumented payouts to IOC members, and the accountants
took him at his word.
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of the 1995 vote, the Utahans took $30,000 in cash
and traveler's checks to Budapest, where the final decision was
being made, for expenses and last-minute influencing. Salt Lake
breezed on the first ballot, 54-14, one of the most lopsided votes
in Olympic history. The outcome was never in doubt, IOC officials
said then and now. ``Salt Lake won on the merits,'' insisted vice
president Richard Pound of Canada.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until last December that the price of winning hearts
and votes was revealed. Somebody from the organizing committee
leaked a copy of a 1996 letter from Welch to Sonia Essomba, telling
her that the committee could no longer pay her tuition. Marc
Hodler, the Swiss lawyer who has been an IOC member for 36 years,
shrugged and said that Salt Lake hadn't done anything other cities
hadn't been doing for years. If anything, he said, the Utahans were
victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know what happened here wasn't right,'' Leavitt said last
week. The payoffs had been ``disgusting and disguised,'' said
Garff, the board chairman. What the bidders had done was clearly
unethical, the ethics panel declared, but it wasn't criminal.
</P>
<P>
   There was no evidence of bribery. In the 50,000 pages of
documents that the panel thumbed through, Jordan said, nobody
offered or asked for anything in exchange for a vote. ``The flavor
of the interactions was much more along the lines of currying
favor,'' said Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   What Salt Lake did, the ethics panel concluded, was about
treating foreigners like family. For bribery, you needed a quid and
a quo. As much as the bidders spent, they never knew what they got
in return. The IOC's balloting, as always, was secret.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
