<DOCNO> NYT19990216.0113 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-16 13:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7002 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-SCANDAL-2TAKES-BO     02-16 1141
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SCANDAL-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIPS, TUITIONS: A `RELENTLESS' OLYMPICS BID 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS  
 (a and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ The Utahans doused their fact-crammed ``bid
books'' with pine scent and slipped them into leather saddlebags
for a distinctive Western touch.
</P>
<P>
   They packed up jars of local honey, white Stetson cowboy hats,
logo-emblazoned duds, souvenir pins, disposable cameras, and boxes
of home-style mementos and brought them to England in the spring of
1991, where the Lords of the Rings were awarding the 1998 Winter
Olympics. But when they arrived in Birmingham, the Salt Lake
bidders realized that they were putting a rummage table up against
Sotheby's.
</P>
<P>
   Their Japanese rivals were feeding sushi and champagne to the
International Olympic Committee members and giving them jewelry,
luggage, laptop computers, and video recorders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were giving out saltwater taffy,'' a Utah bid official
mused after underdog Nagano had edged Salt Lake by four votes out
of 88 cast. ``And they were giving out Hondas.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't matter that Salt Lake had the best technical bid _
superb venues, a modern airport, huge hotels, superhighways,
state-of-the-art telecommunications, and the ``greatest snow on
earth.'' The Utahans had been playing the wrong game.
</P>
<P>
   Landing the Olympics wasn't about luge runs and cloverleafs, bid
chief Tom Welch and his team told the trustees and local
businessmen when they returned home. It was about ``winning
hearts,'' about getting to know the Lords and their wives and
children and making them feel part of your family _ and ultimately,
about winning their votes.
</P>
<P>
   So Welch drew up a mission statement for 2002 with one goal: to
``establish and maintain long-term, vote-influencing relationships
with IOC members.'' What resulted was a bid that went haywire and
created the worst scandal in modern Olympic history. Salt Lake's
corrupt quest for the Winter Games was a seven-year cornucopia of
cash handouts, tuition payments, free medical care, jobs, lavish
trips, shopping sprees, and gifts ranging from shotguns to golden
retrievers.
</P>
<P>
   A 300-page report issued last week by the organizing committee's
ethics panel and interviews with Olympic insiders paint a sordid
portrait of two ``relentless'' men (Welch and Dave Johnson) who
spent hundreds of thousands of dollars in secret, of trustees who
asked few questions, of independent accountants who gave clean
audits without demanding details, and of greedy IOC members who
broke their oaths and succumbed to temptation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is plenty of blame to go around,'' said ethics panelist
David Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   A quarter of the IOC voters have since been implicated. Nine
have either resigned or been forced out, and more than a dozen
others still risk expulsion. The US Department of Justice, US
Olympic Committee, and Utah attorney general are all probing the
Salt Lake Organizing Committee. The committee's top two officials,
Frank Joklik and Johnson, have resigned, and Welch, who stepped
down in 1997 amid charges of spousal abuse, lost his pension and
$10,000-a-month consultancy. The board of trustees and executive
committee have been reshuffled.
</P>
<P>
   And Salt Lake City, which prides itself on hospitality and
rectitude, has been profoundly embarrassed before the world. All
was to guarantee an Olympics that IOC insiders say was never in
doubt.
</P>
<P>
   Salt Lake easily won on the first ballot, collecting nearly
twice as many votes as the three other bidders (Sion, Switzerland;
Ostersund, Sweden; and Quebec City) combined. It didn't need any of
the IOC members that it paid to influence. ``We won the vote fair
and square,'' board chairman Robert Garff said last week.
</P>
<P>
   Why, then, did Salt Lake try to rig a game it had already won?
Because after five failed bids, it was determined to win the Games
at any cost. Because after losing to Nagano despite having the best
package, it concluded that merit meant little. And because it
believed that the IOC's unwritten rule was that you won hearts by
filling hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were told that was the way business was done,'' said
Jordan, referring to explanations by the Salt Lake bidders. ``And
they were not in a position to fix it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning, the Utahans just didn't get it, said IOC
marketing director Michael Payne. They should never have bid for
1998, not when Atlanta had already won the 1996 Summer Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We told Salt Lake, `There's not a chance in the world you'll
get them,' '' recalled Payne. ``We can't go back to America two
years later. That's the simple geopolitical reality.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States had already hosted the 1980 Winter and 1984
Summer Games, and the IOC was sensitive to criticism that Uncle Sam
was turning the Olympics into its own backyard block party.
</P>
<P>
   Asia hadn't had the Winter Games since 1972; it clearly was
Japan's turn. If the IOC members hadn't sensed that, one of IOC
president Juan Antonio Samaranch's top aides told them the night
before the vote that Samaranch favored Nagano.
</P>
<P>
   Salt Lake City would have its turn in 2002, the IOC hinted, but
the Utahans set out to win hearts anyway, targeting voters in
developing nations just as Atlanta had. The Africans and Latin
Americans had no stake in where the Winter Games were held, and
conversations with middlemen offering blocs of votes in Birmingham
had convinced Welch that they were eager _ even asking _ to be
influenced.
</P>
<P>
   In November 1991, with the 2002 vote still nearly four years
away, the wife of IOC member Paul Wallwork of Western Samoa wired
Welch asking for a $30,000 loan to help a friend in a ``serious
situation.'' Welch raided his daughter's trust funds, meant for
tuition at Wellesley College and the University of Utah, and sent
the cash.
</P>
<P>
   IOC member David Sibandze of Swaziland wanted his son Sibo to
attend Utah. The bidders helped get him admitted, wangled him a
visa, and spent more than $100,000 in committee funds to pay for
his education.
</P>
<P>
   Thus began a ``scholarship program'' purportedly allowing
Olympic committees from developing countries to send ``outstanding
individuals'' to Utah colleges at bid committee expense. It turned
into a slush fund that the ethics report said Welch and Johnson
tapped liberally for payoffs to IOC members and their children _
with no questions asked.
</P>
<P>
   Though the executive committee knew about the program and was
supposed to approve the recipients, it never asked where the money
was going, the report concluded. That became the Salt Lake pattern.
The board's job was to raise cash. Welch's and Johnson's jobs were
to spend it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The executive committee paid less attention to specific
expenditures so long as the overall budget balanced,'' the ethics
report found.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
