<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-16 13:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7003 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      02-16 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CONSTITUTION STILL STANDS TALL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and k coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Now that the impeachment process is finally over,
it doesn't hurt to recall that there have been four genuine
impeachment imbroglios in the history of the American presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Three of them have been real dogs.
</P>
<P>
   The latest is merely the ugliest and least reputable. Off the
stats alone, the temptation would be to declare the constitutional
provision for impeachment flawed.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it stands tall, still an awesome power, but on the
shelf for only the gravest of contingencies. In this revival season
for the English language's greatest Bard, the fault is not in the
provision but in ourselves, a truth the framers acknowledged by
inserting the Everest-sized requirement that a two-thirds vote in
the Senate is required for conviction.
</P>
<P>
   Our experience with it, at a minimum, teaches that we have yet
to make the same mistake twice.
</P>
<P>
   In the beginning, just the majority vote required to proceed in
the House of Representatives was enough to stop impeachment
proceedings against John Tyler in 1843. The two-thirds provision
was, of course, central to Andrew Johnson's survival 25 years
later, and it played at least an ancillary role in the case against
President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   When it worked, magnificently, during Watergate, the two-thirds
mandate was correctly interpreted even in the House Judiciary
Committee to require the meticulous assembly of hard and direct
evidence of felonies that were also ``high crimes'' that could
command support beyond the Democratic Party. Richard Nixon was
toast even before the ``smoking gun'' tape recording produced his
unique resignation.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton case was clearly a regression in an age of lowered
standards, but the decisive character of its rejection blunts its
force as precedent.
</P>
<P>
   So do its origins. It is enough to note that the actions of
independent counsel Kenneth Starr in getting jurisdiction over the
Monica Lewinsky mess are themselves the subject of official
inquiry. But it is more important to note that this is the first _
and, one trusts, the last _ impeachment case based solely on work
done outside Congress. In every other one, Congress did its own
work to make its own case.
</P>
<P>
   In the Clinton case, however, the House first played politics
with Starr's referral by dumping it unexamined into the public
domain, and then carelessly re-writing it into an impeachment case.
Even Representative Henry Hyde now acknowledges that the failure to
check the facts and fill the holes in an admitted rush to judgment
was a fatal flaw that a longer trial in the Senate would only have
demonstrated more conclusively.
</P>
<P>
   Now that nearly all the statements made during the closed-door
speeches last week in the Senate have been made public, it is clear
that more than 33 Democrats and at least one Republican (Rhode
Island's John Chafee) voted to acquit solely on the facts of the
case. What took the number to 50 senators were additional opinions
that the offenses alleged were not worthy of the capital punishment
of removal from office.
</P>
<P>
   This rejection was unique. In no other impeachment trial has a
case failed to attract even a bare majority of the Senate to any of
its elements.
</P>
<P>
   In the Clinton case, the lesson is as old as the Constitution's
specific design to guard against impeachments pushed by one
political faction. And it may be as modern as an implicit rejection
of personal misbehavior (in this situation, arising out of alleged
misbehavior in another case that preceded his presidency) as proper
grounds for impeachment. The problem was not with the Democrats who
saw it one way and the Republicans who saw it another, for
partisanship is a natural crutch in relatively close decisions; the
problem was with the case itself.
</P>
<P>
   The House's decision not to proceed against Tyler showed that a
failed presidency and massive unpopularity would not become grounds
to alter election, or in Tyler's case, succession results after
William Henry Harrison's death made him president. Johnson's
survival meant that impeachment would not be used to change
national policy, in this case post-Civil War Reconstruction.
</P>
<P>
   But the Nixon precedent stands, leaving impeachment precisely
where it was intended to be, as protection against presidents who
directly threaten constitutional government by corruptly using
their official powers.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton case was a dog recognized correctly by the public
from the beginning. That the Senate rescued the country from Ken
Starr's overzealousness and the House's irresponsibility may be
small consolation; but it is real consolation.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
