<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-16 13:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7006 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-MEDIA-BOS &LR;      02-16 1319
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-MEDIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCANDAL'S EFFECT ON JOURNALISM IN DOUBT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ AND DON AUCOIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Big stories always change media,'' says media critic Jon Katz.
``The death of Elvis created the tabloid culture. The Gulf War
legitimized cable as a medium.''
</P>
<P>
   So how has a mind-boggling year of sex, lies, and impeachment
altered the media landscape? Will it change the way journalists
pursue the confounding ``character issue?'' Has it permanently
damaged press credibility in the eyes of the public? Does it mark
the coronation of the instantaneous ``new media'' embodied by the
Internet and cable news networks?
</P>
<P>
   The Bill Clinton/Monica Lewinsky affair may have triggered the
quickest orgy of media introspection in history. One week after the
story broke, journalists were guiltily assailing their pursuit of
the tawdry details on a CNN program tellingly called ``Media
Madness.'' Yet more than a year later, the story's impact on
journalism is as murky and as ambiguous as the lessons of the
scandal itself.
</P>
<P>
   The most obvious conclusion is CNN analyst Jeff Greenfield's
assertion that ``even though (``Monica-gate'') led to an
extraordinary event, I don't think it blew anybody's mind in the
way that Watergate did.'' And not just because the president
survived. Watergate spawned a movie starring Robert Redford and
Dustin Hoffman as hero journalists and steered a generation of
starry-eyed students to journalism school.
</P>
<P>
   When University of Virginia government professor Larry Sabato
recently asked his class of 500 students how many of them planned
on entering journalism, not a single hand shot skyward. &QL; 
 &QL; 
The new media &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the first big story since journalism had changed,''
says ABC's Cokie Roberts. ``We never had a story like this, with
three 24-hour channels and all the `dot coms.' None of us knew how
to operate in that world.''
</P>
<P>
   This was a scandal introduced on the Internet when cyber snoop
Matt Drudge pirated Newsweek's reporting and broke the Lewinsky
tale several days before the mainstream media. It was maintained at
a screeching decibel level by the unceasing
``all-Monica-all-the-time'' punditry on cable news stations like
MSNBC, Fox News Channel, CNBC, and CNN.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a sad moment for America, a fine moment for Fox
news'' acknowledges John Moody, Fox News Channel vice president for
news.
</P>
<P>
   The cable channels have come in for serious criticism for
trivializing the story and for grinding it to a pulp. But no one
expects them to fold their tents.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it ends, you've still got all of these networks with 168
hours a week to fill,'' says television and cultural critic Steven
Stark. ``They're on to the next tabloid crisis if they can find or
invent one.''
</P>
<P>
   Echoes Wall Street Journal executive editor Al Hunt: ``I can't
wait to hear (CNBC talkhost) Chris Matthews do a whole show on
Social Security reform.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at the National Press Club last June, Drudge lauded the
virtues of cybernews as ``an era vibrating with the din of small
voices . . . a future where there'll be 300 million reporters,
where anyone from anywhere can report for any reason.''
</P>
<P>
   In truth, the Internet's peformance left plenty to be desired.
Drudge hyped a bogus story about a supposed Clinton ``love child''
and The Wall Street Journal and Dallas Morning &UR;  &LR; News had to retract
erroneous stories hastily posted on their web sites. Still,
analysts think the ``disconnect'' between the public and mainstream
journalism over this scandal plays into Drudge's scenario,
hastening the fragmentation of news and the further decline of the
traditional gatekeeper press. Whether it be a talk radio host, a
web site, or cable TV pundit of choice, citizens will be more
likely to customize their news in an era of expanding outlets.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public is much less dependent on journalism,'' says Katz.
``They're reaching their own conclusions. We have this spectacle of
a very, very well informed citizenry that is reaching different
conclusions than Washington journalists.'' Adds Sabato:
``Everyone's going to have a different set of sites. Everyone's
going to believe in a different reality.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
The character issue &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There is widespread agreement that the salacious
Clinton-Lewinsky affair marks a high _ or low _ point in the public
scrutiny of the ``character'' issue that has been on the front
burner since Gary Hart's adultery-plagued 1988 presidential
campaign. In the wake of the scandal, there's some feeling that
journalists may be less eager to sniff around the bedsheets for a
while.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do feel that we've come to the end of the road with this
stuff,'' says Newsweek's chief political correspondent, Howard
Fineman. ``Every reductio ad absurdum has been reached. We've
almost gone real time in the private lives of public people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In many ways, (journalists) are the idealists here. We believe
there are good and bad public servants,'' says U.S. News &AMP; World
report columnist and CBS analyst Gloria Borger. She believes there
may be more emphasis on the positive aspects of government as part
of a mini-backlash to the past year.
</P>
<P>
   Sabato worries, however, that to compensate for the Monica
scandal ``the next wave could easily be a truly lowered standard, a
feel-good journalism where we basically go back to the '50s.''
</P>
<P>
   And there are dissenting votes. Hunt thinks the post-Monica
media will still be eager to ``define character in terms of sex and
I think it's going to be a travesty. We're going to cover
pseudo-character.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
A press in disrepute: &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even David Broder, the painfully well-mannered dean of
Washington political columnists, doesn't mince words when gauging
his profession's current standing. In all likelihood, ``we're in
the crapper,'' he says. The public is ``very angry at us for our
yearlong proccupation with this.'' Echoes Greenfield: ``It
certainly didn't make heroes out of journalists. As a general
statement, Washington does cover politics with its head up its own
intestinal tract.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet despite the widespread belief that this story exposed a
yawning gulf between the media and the citizenry, there are some
hopeful signs. For one thing, polls indicate that as the scandal
dragged on, people were inclined to think more favorably of the
media's performance _ even as they fervently hoped for an end to
the story. In January 1998, only 36 percent of the respondents to a
Media Studies Center poll considered coverage of the Lewinsky story
``excellent'' or ``good.'' A year later, the number of satisfied
customers was nearing 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The rumors that ``seemed to be so outrageous and out there at
the beginning, basically were confirmed,'' says Media Studies
Center research director Larry McGill. ``I think the media, in a
funny way, have escaped relatively unscathed.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, that may depend on whether journalism has absorbed
some of the lessons of the last 12 months. One lingering fear is
that the media have become so addicted to covering the likes of the
O.J. Simpson trial, the death of Princess Diana and the White House
scandal, that they will transform the frantic hunt for the next
mega-story into a full-preoccupation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is whether this story is a kind of crack cocaine
. . . and whether we find a way of telling other stories,'' says
Fineman. ``I don't think things will ever slow down again. . . . A
huge apparatus has been built to keep the pace up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The great thing about this business is there's always another
story,'' says Moody, who seems to be confirming Fineman's theory.
``We're not too far from a presidential cycle; we have an unsolved
murder in Colorado; we have an institution we thought was
incorruptible, the Olympic Committee. When does it end? It never
ends. That's why it's called news.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
