<SLUG> BC-LANGUAGE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHANGING THE WORD, BUT NOT THE POINT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAN FREEMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Those unhappy Macbeths are hardly the ideal Valentine's Day
couple, but here they come, thanks to a recent query from Bob
Michel. He's bugged, he says, by the media's use of sticking point
to mean a point of contention: ``My recollection is that the phrase
comes from `Screw your courage to the sticking point,' '' he
writes.
</P>
<P>
   Almost right. When Shakespeare's Macbeth begins to waffle on
whether to murder Duncan, his tough-talking spouse tells him to
``screw your courage to the sticking-place'' _ not point _ ``and
we'll not fail.''
</P>
<P>
   But today, sticking point (no hyphen) is the one in the
dictionary and in everyday use. Like many a familiar quotation _
from gilding the lily to blood, sweat, and tears to play it again,
Sam _ it's been edited, as time goes by, to roll more trippingly
off the collective tongue. Sometimes, as in these examples, the
essential meaning stays the same.
</P>
<P>
   In other cases, it's misconstrued: When Juliet asks ``Wherefore
art thou Romeo?'' she doesn't mean ``Where are you, Romeo?'' but
``Why do you have to be from that family?'' (English teachers seem
to be making no progress on this front: In newspaper citations,
misuses dominate by better than 3 to 1. Dave Barry punctuates it
correctly, putting William F. Buckley Jr., among others, to shame.
Whether Monica would have gotten it right we can't say; for her
1997 valentine message to the president, she chose a verse from a
bit later in the balcony scene.)
</P>
<P>
   In the case of sticking point, the appeal of the change from
sticking-place is easy to see. After all, the Macbeths are planning
to kill the king with daggers _ and sticking was a common synonym
for stabbing at the time. Sticking-place also meant the part of the
neck you sliced to slaughter an animal. It sure sounds as if Lady
Macbeth means to say, ``Pull up your socks, gird your loins, and
stick in the shiv, Mac.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Oxford English Dictionary has a different take on
Shakespeare's sticking-place: ``The allusion seems to be to the
screwing-up of a peg of a musical instrument until it becomes
tightly fixed in its place,'' it says. (Not that this meaning
couldn't coexist happily with the more bloody connotations, of
course.)
</P>
<P>
   If that's the primary meaning, then today's sticking point is
not so different from Lady Macbeth's: Both mean the place at which
a process stops, fixed and immobilized. Her sticking-place meant
steely resolve, while our sticking points tend to be roadblocks in
negotiations, but the modern variation is no further from the
original image than Shakespeare's was. If we want to castigate
ourselves for sticking point, the grounds should be overuse, not
misquotation.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Words for the wary
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Our recent discussion of the flap over niggardly _ an innocent
word tainted by its taboo sound _ prompted some stories from
readers about other endangered words.
</P>
<P>
   Jon Quay said the whole thing reminded him of his attempt to get
his wife to read the Sherlock Holmes mysteries. ``She was quite
taken aback because Watson kept ejaculating every time Holmes
astounded him with some example of his ability, as in `My dear
Holmes!' Watson ejaculated.'' This ejaculation is, of course, a
sudden and forceful exclamation (the word comes from the Latin for
javelin); once upon a time, that's the only meaning we would have
encountered in everyday, nonscientific parlance.
</P>
<P>
   Kristine McGuire of Sudbury offered a similar story: She was in
charge of a plaque honoring a dean, and its wording referred to his
seminal textbook in his field. ``People actually asked me to remove
the plaque and change the word seminal, she recalled, ``even though
I explained that it meant `first' or `beginning.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Alpert of Newton spoke up in defense of niggardly,
arguing that ``a well-educated population would not have this
problem'' of confusing an inoffensive word with a racial slur.
That's true, of course, if a well-educated population means a
nation of people who know every word in the language. But in the
absence of that utopian state, less familiar words often change
their meanings in response to popular associations or
misunderstandings (see internecine, livid, and shambles, for
starters). When meanings are in flux, caution is advised; the goal,
after all, is not to have a fight but to make your point.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
What's the word? Write or e-mail yours to Jan Freeman at The Boston
Globe, PO Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378; freeman(at)globe.com.
Please include a hometown and phone number.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-99 1345EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
