<HEADER>
A7008 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-NEW-AZR &LR;      02-16 0918
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-NEW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW AND NOTABLE BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A survey of recently published books:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; WHILE I WAS GONE &QL; 
 &UR; Sue Miller (Knopf, $24)
</P>
<P>
   After a very slow start, Miller's fifth novel blossoms not only
into the story of a marriage and a family, but of an unsolved
murder that haunts the past of her main character and resurfaces in
a most unexpected way. Jo Becker is a veterinarian who lives with
her husband, a minister, in a small town in Massachusetts. They are
quietly happy _ their three daughters are grown and making their
own ways in the world, leaving Jo and Daniel to lavish time on
their jobs and on their enviable relationship with each other.
Then, one day, a new patient comes to Jo's practice, a dog whose
owner is a figure from Jo's shadowy past. Eli Mayhew was one of her
six housemates in Cambridge during the summer of 1968, when she was
on the run from her stifling first marriage and living under an
assumed name. For Jo, the house had been a place of liberation and
camaraderie until the terrible night when one of its residents _
Dana, Jo's closest friend _ was stabbed to death by an intruder who
was never caught. Now Eli, a prominent research scientist, has
moved to town with his wife, and Jo begins to feel the seductive
pull of the past. The suspense is potent as Miller hints that we
will discover, over the course of the novel, just what happened to
Dana and why, and yet the final third of the book is oddly
unsatisfying. This is partly because Jo inexplicably takes three
weeks to make a moral decision that should have taken three minutes
(and then weathers its consequences with baffling ease), and
because her husband and youngest daughter respond to her dilemma
with a self-interest that strains credulity. Indeed, the best
passages here are the quiet ones in which Miller displays her
remarkable ear and eye for the understated interplay among members
of a family _ among mother and daughters, among sisters, between
husband and wife. If the mystery brings us into the story, it is
these moments, deeply rendered, that keep us there. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; TRAVELING MERCIES &QL; 
 &UR; Anne Lamott (Pantheon, $23)
</P>
<P>
   Here we have an odd book, a sort of ``Bird by Bird'' of faith
and redemption. Those of you who have read ``Bird,'' Lamott's
treatise on the process of writing, and Operating Instructions,''
her memoir of her son's birth and first year, will recognize much
of the territory here, and many of the people. There's Sam, the
little boy who is the center of Lamott's life, and Pammy, her dear
friend who died of breast cancer, and a host of other friends,
relatives and acquaintances. If you've read her previous books you
also know that Lamott has had demons in her life, and she has come
to some sense of equilibrium with the arrival of Sam and with the
continuing, if somewhat incongruous, help of her faith. Here is how
she puts it, in the very first sentence of this book: ``My coming
to faith did not start with a leap but rather a series of staggers
from what seemed like one safe place to another.'' In that spirit,
this is more of a memoir, a collection of anecdotes, than a book on
religion (although faith is at its core, and in its subtitle). It
has the same disarming humor and meandering but dumbfoundingly
readable voice of her previous books of non-fiction. If you're a
fan, you'll probably like this one, too. If you're new to Lamott,
this isn't a bad place to start. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; GETTING OVER JOHN DOE &QL; 
 &UR; Suzanne Yalof (Morrow, $19.95)
</P>
<P>
   Morrow sent no less than six copies of this book, so we took a
look, and now we're here to save you from the same fate. Yalof is a
fashion editor at ``Glamour'' magazine. John Doe was a Wall Street
trader who wooed her, then inexplicably dumped her. This is her
story, of the wooing, dumping, post-breakup distress and eventual
emergence from an abyss of confusion and despair (this last step
involved eating beef jerky and not shaving her legs). Our attention
died on the first page. Here's a paragraph from the early stages of
the relationship, just so you know what we're dealing with: ``We
would sit up all night and talk about our families. His parents
insisted on good grades _ mine settled for a clean room. He won
Most Likely to Succeed in his high school yearbook _ I was Class
Clown. What did we have in common? Would you believe sushi?'' If
you insist on more, you go alone. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; BE COOL &QL; 
 &UR; Elmore Leonard (Delacorte, $24.95)
</P>
<P>
   Chili Palmer is back, and he's talking movies, which is good
because Leonard is the crown prince of dialogue and he (begin
itals) knows (end itals) movies. He used to be a lowly screenwriter
before his novels hit it big, and now he's impossibly rich because
his novels become movies, one right after the other. This sequel to
``Get Shorty'' opens with Chili meeting at a sidewalk cafe with a
record producer who tries to talk Chili into making a movie about
him. When Chili takes a trip to the men's room, the record producer
is gunned down by a wiry little man wearing a toupee. And even as
Chili stands there, the star witness, he's rewriting the scene in
his head, because ``you couldn't have the star get popped 10
minutes into the picture.'' What follows is a typical Leonardian
farce full of record producers and the threat of Russian gangsters.
We'll probably see it in theaters soon. &QL; 
(You can reach correspondent Anne Stephenson at
amstephenson(at)worldnet.att.net via e-mail.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-99 1345EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990216.0119 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-16 13:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7010 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JORDAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      02-16 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARR, TRIPP DESERVE GRILLING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT A. JORDAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The people have spoken.
</P>
<P>
   While it's time now for President Clinton to move forward, it is
also time for the judicial process to look back and consider the
potentially illegal conduct of Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr
and former White House aide Linda Tripp. After all, their
potentially illegal, not to mention unethical, conduct is largely
responsible for dragging this nation through one of the most
disgraceful episodes in its history.
</P>
<P>
   But first, the people. They spoke Friday through the votes of
the 55 US senators _ 45 Democrats and 10 Republicans _ who
acquitted President Clinton on the charge of perjury; and the 50 US
senators _ 45 Democrats ands five Republicans _ who voted against
the charge of obstruction of justice.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did the outcome fall far short of the required
two-thirds support of the Senate for removal of the president,
neither measure received even a majority vote, denying the House
Republicans even a symbolic, though meaningless victory.
</P>
<P>
   While not a vindication of Clinton's personal conduct, the vote
to acquit is a complete repudiation of the Republican effort to
oust a popular president against the wishes of 70 percent of the
people, based on the polls.
</P>
<P>
   But even this repudiation does not bring the entire sordid
process to an end. There are still ongoing investigations related
to this impeachment that must be brought to a conclusion, if not to
justice. Starr, who is still using his office to both persecute and
prosecute Clinton's friends, still has to answer to potential
allegations that he misled Attorney General Janet Reno on getting
her approval to pursue the Monica Lewinsky case.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of alleged illegal leaks from the grand jury to the
news media must also be resolved. And his alleged tactics of
keeping Lewinsky a near-prisoner and trying to force her to wear a
wiretap to trap Clinton must also be investigated. His links and
connections to Tripp, who has her own legal problems, must also be
pursued.
</P>
<P>
   As for Tripp, who is trying to rehabilitate her negative image
by making the media rounds, she ought to be fully investigated for
her alleged illegal wiretapping of her conversations with Lewinsky.
No amount of spin can change the reality that she wiretapped
Lewinsky to get at the president.
</P>
<P>
   The eventual links between Tripp, Starr, the religious right,
lawyers for Clinton accuser Paula Joness, and the right-leaning
elements in the House and Senate suggest a widespread, partisan
effort that might have brought down most other presidents, but not
the resilient Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt, Tripp, Starr and other Republicans argue that it was
Clinton's reckless behavior, not the subsequent wiretaps and the
investigation that bled this nation through the impeachment
process. But Starr, knowing that Clinton would not exactly proclaim
in a grand jury proceeding that he had sex with Lewinsky, set him
up for a fall.
</P>
<P>
   Although many legal experts became divided over the issue of
whether Clinton committed either perjury or obstruction of justice,
it became clear to the national audience that this was a political,
not a legal, proceeding against Clinton. It also became clear to a
majority that even if he committed perjury and obstruction of
justice, it was over a private sexual affair that, however wrong,
posed no threat to this nation. Such a case was not what the
Founding Fathers wanted the impeachment process to be about.
</P>
<P>
   Because of Starr's partisan political zeal to use and abuse that
office to get Clinton and his friends, there can be no doubt that
an office with such unlimited power and resources can be a
dangerous weapon in unsteady hands. The vast powers of this office
that made the impeachment fiasco possible ought to be eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   If Reno can show that she was misled by Starr regarding the
Lewinsky investigation, he should be fired. If he was the source of
illegal leaks from the grand jury, he should be prosecuted. If it's
discovered that Starr have performed other illegal acts in his
pursuit of Clinton, those allegations should be pursued.
</P>
<P>
   As for Clinton, he can now focus on getting much of his agenda
approved over the next two years. And he can simply deny, if not
ignore, media reports that he will seek revenge against the House
Republican managers who brought the impeachment case to the Senate.
Of course, that should not dissuade Clinton from taking his
popularity on the campaign trail and working hard to return the
House, and possibly the Senate, to a Democratic majority.
</P>
<P>
   If the voters agree in the 2000 election to return Congress to
the Democrats, the Republicans will have no one to blame but
themselves. After all, if they had listened to the people earlier,
they could be spending more time working to retain control and less
time trying to wipe off the egg on their faces.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Robert A. Jordan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
