<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-16 13:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7011 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-LOSTBIRD-AZR &LR;      02-16 0917
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-LOSTBIRD-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOST BIRD: REUNION WITH TRIBE WAS BITTERSWEET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
LOOKING FOR LOST BIRD 
by Yvette Melanson with Claire Safran (Avon Books, $22) 
 
 By CAROL SOWERS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   On a cloudless May morning in 1996, Yazzie Monroe, a Navajo
medicine man, guided his long-lost daughter through the throng of
reporters and well-wishers who wanted to witness her miraculous
homecoming.
</P>
<P>
   Monroe's daughter, Yvette Melanson, had been missing for 43
years, stolen with her infant twin brother from a hospital and
whisked into a black market that placed Indian babies with White
couples.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of these ``Lost Birds,'' adopted illegally from the
1950s to 1970s, have never been found.
</P>
<P>
   But on that day, Yvette Melanson _ the woman who was raised
White and Jewish _ would walk with her birth father into the
chapter house of the tiny reservation community of Tolani Lake, 55
miles from Winslow, where she would be wrapped in a sacred blanket
and welcomed by her Navajo cousins with old songs and booming war
dances.
</P>
<P>
   Melanson's return to the high-desert plains of Tolani Lake had
begun just a month earlier, when her 20-year search for her roots
led her to a posting on the Internet that linked her to her Navajo
family.
</P>
<P>
   Within weeks, the story of the reunion of the Jewish woman and
her Navajo kin was making national headlines, and Melanson and her
family were making their way to the reservation for the rousing
reunion.
</P>
<P>
   However, that is only the beginning of the complex, but clearly
told story that unfolds in Melanson's just-released 240-page
memoir, ``Looking for Lost Bird.''
</P>
<P>
   Co-written by journalist/novelist Claire Safran, the book steers
clear of the deep, dull waters of self-revelation. Instead, the
writing is breezy, touching, a conversation with your best friend,
not your shrink. And as Melanson struggles to understand her
new-found family, she gives readers a tantalizing taste of the
soulful ceremonies that continue to define ancient Navajo culture
in modern times.
</P>
<P>
   The book opens a year after the homecoming. Yvette; her husband,
Dickie; and their two teenage daughters, Heather and Lori, are
loaded into an aged black van. Pulling a horse trailer stuffed with
their furniture, they are headed across country from their farm in
Palmyra, Maine, to Tolani Lake.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a woman in a hurry, as usual, driving across the country
toward an unpredictable future,'' Melanson writes. ``With every
mile, I was leaving an old identity behind and coming closer and
closer to a new one.''
</P>
<P>
   As the Melansons coaxed their van cross-country, they clearly
were not prepared for what lay at the end of the journey:
joblessness, poverty, doubt, and, at times, brutal rejection _
familiar themes in Yvette's life.
</P>
<P>
   Newspaper stories drew a broad sketch of Yvette Melanson. The
book completes the portrait of a woman troubled by painful memories
of the underground adoption, devastated by the rejection of her
once-loving adoptive father, and tormented by the disappearance of
her own son, Brad.
</P>
<P>
   Young Yvette languished for what she believes was three years in
the adoption underground. Then, suddenly, she was pulled away from
her foster mother and whisked to another unfamiliar family.
</P>
<P>
   Larry and Bea Silverman, a well-to-do Jewish couple in New York
City, dressed her in frills, gave her music and ballet lessons, and
tucked her into a pink canopy bed at night. They told her she was
adopted and had a twin brother, but if they knew, the Silvermans
never told her she was Indian.
</P>
<P>
   After Bea died, Yvette's world imploded. Her adoptive father
remarried, and her stepmother wanted the teenage Yvette out of the
house. Homeless, she moved from the home of one friend to another.
At age 17, her stepmother shipped her to Israel, where she became a
soldier and was wounded in a skirmish in the days before the 1973
Yom Kippur War.
</P>
<P>
   After returning home, she served in the Navy, married for a
short time and gave birth to a son. In a stunning parallel to her
birth mother's life, Melanson's emotionally troubled son was ripped
out of her arms at age 15 and sent by state officials to live with
strangers. Brad became Yvette's own Lost Bird, a runaway who melted
into the streets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what my mother must have been feeling because I, too,
have lived with that emptiness,'' she writes.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, she married Dickie Melanson, a retired
scallop-fisherman who, like his new wife, had a big heart and small
bank account.
</P>
<P>
   He encouraged the family's 1997 move to Tolani Lake. But in
time, he became embittered by the lack of jobs. He felt isolated
and unaccepted, once the target of an ominous warning, ``Kill
whitey,'' scribbled on a water tower in front of their home.
</P>
<P>
   As difficult as life was on the reservation, Melanson wanted to
stay.
</P>
<P>
   She was learning to weave, savoring Navajo stories about
Changing Woman, the corn people and mischievous coyote. While
Melanson burrowed deeper and deeper into the Navajo culture, she
was unaware that her daughters were being taunted at school.
Heather was beaten up on the school bus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was deep in denial and finding it hard to dig my way out,''
Melanson writes.
</P>
<P>
   But the gritty Melansons persevere, find a way to pay their
bills and stay in Navajo Country. There is more to this story,
another beginning that begs to be written. &QL; 
 &QL; 
(Carol Sowers can be reached at carol.sowers(at)pni.com via
e-mail.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
