<DOCNO> NYT19990216.0121 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-16 13:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7012 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDIA-WILLES-2TAKES-B     02-16 1081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-WILLES-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEIGHING WILLES'S RECORD AT THE LA TIMES 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the 16 months since he took over the reins as publisher of
the Los Angeles Times, Mark Willes, 57, has become the most
debated, dissected, and discussed newspaper executive in the
country. The topic at hand: Is he leading the Times to the promised
land or on a suicide mission?
</P>
<P>
   When he became publisher, the former General Mills executive
generated reams of bad press with heretical pronouncements about
breaking down the sacred ``wall'' between the paper's editorial and
business departments. No story was complete without references to
the ``Cereal Killer'' and ``Captain Crunch'' nicknames that mocked
his proclivity for cost cutting and for passing out pink slips. The
fear was that a major paper had been hijacked by a man who'd
specialized in packaging cereal boxes, a bottom-line buccaneer.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Willes _ along with new editor Michael Parks _ is
amassing a record as he tones down the rhetoric. That record is
controversial, lauded and assailed within media circles. But it has
reinforced his reputation as the industry's flashiest riverboat
gambler, a marketer in search of a magic formula.
</P>
<P>
   That Holy Grail is Willes's audacious goal of bolstering the
Times's circulation of 1,067,540 by 500,000 new subscribers. Beyond
that is his heartfelt belief that newspapers, including his own,
are in dire need of major surgery.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech at a media conference last October, Willes, who is
also the Times-Mirror CEO, warned that ``newspapers have been, for
almost two decades now, a declining industry. You can either say,
`That is inevitable.' Or you can say, `We can do something about
it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   In the past year, the Times has feverishly tried to ``do
something about it.'' It created an 11-person ``Latino desk'' to
win hearts and minds in the growing Hispanic community; produced a
new Southern California Living lifestyle section targeted at women;
cranked out ultra-localized Our Times supplements to address
complaints about community coverage; and embarked on an ambitious
Reading by 9 project that makes the paper a partner in a sweeping
child literacy campaign. It has also launched a new national
edition and a major redesign is slated to be completed within the
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I admire the fact that he's really trying to do something
different. He's willing to take risks,'' says Tonnie Katz, editor
of the rival Orange Country Register. ``On the other hand, I'm not
sure how much he has tried to learn the industry. I wonder about a
person who can blithely say, `I'm going to pick up 500,000
circulation.' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a tremendous skepticism about where he's going to get
those 500,000 readers,'' says Jill Stewart, an ex-Times employee
who writes for the weekly Los Angeles New Times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm totally unrepentant on that subject,'' says an undaunted
Willes. ``The same people who thought I was crazy when I started
talking about that still think I'm crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Financially, 1998 was what LA Times CEO Kathryn Downing has
called ``a tough and disappointing year.'' There was a modest
17,000 circulation gain, but operating profits were expected to
drop by about 11 percent from 1997. Even as the paper expands into
new initiatives, it eliminates hundreds of jobs and seeks a 25
percent decrease in entertainment and travel budgets. In December,
Downing told a PaineWebber Media Conference that ``we have scrubbed
significant expenses out of the Times.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Willes sees nothing contradictory about growing and
shrinking simultaneously, nothing dangerous about juggling so many
balls at once.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just too slow,'' he laments, confounded by the newspaper
culture's cautious approach to change. ``You have to try a lot of
things to find out what works.''
</P>
<P>
   The evolution of the Times's new Latino desk tells you
everything you need to know about Willes's modus operandi.
</P>
<P>
   The catalyst was a circulation dilemma: In a market that is
roughly 40 percent Hispanic, less than 20 percent of Latinos buy
the Times. Willes initially suggested creating a separate Latino
section of the paper to entice those readers. That generated a
furor as Times staffers complained about ghetto-izing Latino news.
Then Willes relented and this past fall, the Times created a Latino
desk consisting of 10 Spanish-speaking reporters and a photographer
assigned to different editors and beats scattered throughout the
paper. The idea is to cover the growing Latino population in a more
concerted and sophisticated fashion.
</P>
<P>
   The idea for a separate Latino section was ``one of the
rhetorical flourishes that got Mark in trouble,'' says Frank del
Olmo, who heads the Latino desk. ``That went over just awful. It
was clear he was throwing out ideas and looking for feedback.''
</P>
<P>
   The ill-fated plan for stand-alone Latino coverage reflects
Willes's tendency to raise eyebrows in his search for readers. Last
year, he talked about creating quotas for quotes by minorities and
women in the paper and told The Wall Street Journal that to attract
women, stories need to be ``more emotional, more personal, less
analytical.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't come out of the newspaper tradition,'' says media
analyst John Morton, who calls Willes ``a beneficial influence. He
does things in untraditional ways. . . . Clearly, he's gonna put
his foot in (his mouth).''
</P>
<P>
   Whether the Latino desk succeeds in bringing in new readers, it
may improve upon the Times's traditional coverage of Hispanics as
what del Olmo calls a ``problem people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We can see things that we're covering that we've never covered
before,'' says Parks. ``I'm looking for the paper to recognize in
its journalism the huge demographic changes that have occurred.
This is reality and we need to wake up to it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Like the Latino experiment, Southern California Living _ which
debuted on Nov. 1 _ is an editorial answer to a demographic
problem. There are 500,000 women who read the Times on Sunday, but
do not buy it the rest of the week.
</P>
<P>
   For a while, rumor had it that the lead story in the first
Southern California Living section would explain how to fold
sheets. That didn't materialize. But the new section is widely seen
as too fluffy, with its page of ``news, trends, gossip, and stuff
to do'' and a Section Gee! featuring a diet of astrology and
advice.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
