<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-16 13:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7014 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      02-16 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON'S BIG MISSILE THREAT 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Has it occurred to anybody else that the United
States might be this-close to a national security crisis because
our indisputably hyper-libidinous commander-in-chief may no longer
be getting, um, any?
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton survived impeachment, but, thanks to the
Monica Lewinsky scandal, his public life will never be the same.
It's safe to assume his personal life has been similarly altered?
</P>
<P>
   For the rest of his days in the White House _ and there are
nearly two years of days remaining _ what chance has Bill Clinton
got of getting, um, any from anybody? How close do you suppose a
female White House intern gets to the Oval Office these days? (Are
there any female interns left?) How many private, one-on-one
meetings are scheduled between the leader of the free world and
women under the age of 85? How often do you figure the president
gets away with, ``Oh, I'm just going to take Buddy out for a little
walk''? And how loose is the agenda on trips to the Middle East or
The Hague?
</P>
<P>
   Given the astounding humiliation that he has visited upon his
wife of 22 years, it doesn't seem too large a leap to assume that
Bill Clinton is not getting, um, any at home. (As many of my gal
pals have pointed out, the president is darned lucky not to have
joined John Wayne Bobbitt in the surgical capon hall of fame.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Ha! Only what he deserves!'' shout all the moral absolutists.
</P>
<P>
   Fine, but before they bruise one another from so much triumphal
back patting, they ought to think long and hard about the
ramifications.
</P>
<P>
   A 52-year-old, physically healthy man _ who may or may not be a
sex ``addict'' but who certainly is an above-average horny toad _
has been forced to go cold turkey. After three decades-plus of
relatively unbridled freedom, at least 30 years of riding the
endorphin roller coaster of seduction-and-conquest, this man now
has no outlet.
</P>
<P>
   How many times can Clinton run around the outdoor track at the
White House? How many rounds of golf can he play and raise, not
lower, his endorphin level? In the short run (like until January
2001), how much stress can he relieve in weekly counseling sessions
with three mainstream Protestant ministers? Absent his customary
quota of getting, um, any, President Clinton is bound to turn, more
and more, to some sublimated activity. Drinking, doping and binge
eating probably can be ruled out.
</P>
<P>
   Based on a long-held tradition of male leaders and on
not-so-little hints that the president has ordered the military to
literally drop over the past year, I suggest we all ... Think
Missiles.
</P>
<P>
   While most folks yelled ``Wag the Dog!'' each time Clinton OKed
the bombing of Iraq or Afghanistan or Sudan, I suspected folks were
barking up the wrong Douglas fir. Instead of Clinton wasting $200
million in cruise missiles to distract the nation from his
political troubles, my guess is that it was just the next-best
substitute he could find for his own prodigious rocket launchings.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, my guess looked like prophecy when I read about the
Clinton administration's escalated activities in Iraq and its
expanded get-tough policy on harboring terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   Since ``Desert Fox,'' the Iraqis need not fire on U.S. or
British aircraft to court a missile drop. All they must do is fix
an aircraft on their radar, and it's bombs away.
</P>
<P>
   As for terrorists, according to Richard Clarke, Clinton's
coordinator for counterterrorism: ``We may not just go in and
strike against a terrorist facility; we may choose to retaliate
against the facilities of the host country, if that host country is
a knowing, cooperative sanctuary.''
</P>
<P>
   Such facilities could include host countries' government
buildings or other such ``assets.'' Heaven help us. That could mean
a lot of cruise missiles, which could mean a lot of mistakes and
civilian casualties, which could mean a lot of re-retaliatory
attacks by Saddam Hussein and less-than-stable leaders of host
countries.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's time for a bipartisan funding bill to prevent such an
outcome. Let's call it the, um, Heidi Fleiss Act.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-99 1349EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990216.0123 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-16 13:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7016 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDIA-WILLES-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAK     02-16 0898
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-WILLES-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... and advice.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a piece she wrote for the New York Press, Times watcher
Catherine Seipp derided the section and the Reading by 9 campaign
as ``back-of-the-cereal-box journalism.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The paper strikes a lot of readers as furlongs and furlongs of
froth,'' adds Bryce Nelson, a journalism professor at the
University of Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Parks thinks the new lifestyle section is ``more
focused and structured than it was a year ago. Features are always
derided as soft and fluffy.''
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, that's the way the Times's local coverage has
been characterized as well. In the October speech, Willes admitted
that readers ``think we do generally a lousy job on local news.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The longstanding belief internally at the LA Times is that we
are a national paper and cannot get all caught up in the parochial
stuff,'' says Stewart. ``Under Willes, nothing has changed.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That's not quite true. Starting in early 1998, the Times began
publishing very localized, zoned supplements called Our Times.
Billed as ``the 100 percent all-local newspaper for your
community,'' these inserts carry everything from sports schedules
to police logs and have that cozy garden-club tone. There are seven
current Our Times editions with about 10 more on the drawing board,
says Parks.
</P>
<P>
   Some critics dismiss the Our Times supplements as amateurish
community rags. But Parks contends that ``community journalism is
different from covering Washington. People are interested in what's
going on in their neighborhood. . . . I think we have a sense of
what a zone needs to be now. It needs to be a social community as
opposed to a ZIP code.''
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to community outreach, the Times's most ambitious
effort may be Reading by 9. Unveiled last October, the project _
backed by a five-year, $5 million Times commitment _ is designed to
combat poor third-grade reading performances.
</P>
<P>
   In playing Good Samaritan, the Times is publishing stories on
childhood literacy and a Southern California Living feature called
``The Kids' Reading Room.'' It is soliciting corporate volunteers
to purchase books and pay for tutor training and enlisting Times
employees to read to children.
</P>
<P>
   With Reading by 9, Willes has injected the Times into a major
media debate. Detractors complain that such journalistic activism
is the first step on the slippery slope to advocacy. But it fits
Willes's style.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's kind of a phony debate. Newspapers have always
had a point of view,'' he insists. Student illiteracy ``is the
biggest single tragedy in southern California and (we should) see
if we can't become part of the solution.''
</P>
<P>
   The debate raging here is whether Willes is an outsider bringing
fresh ideas to a stagnant industry or a market-driven agent of
journalistic erosion. And can he be both?
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things people like about him is he does seem
committed to saving the newspaper,'' says USC's Nelson. He adds,
however, that Willes's most ``visible impact'' is that ``he's cut
the number of employees.''
</P>
<P>
   One Willes asset is Parks, the Pulitzer Prize-winning longtime
foreign reporter. There were concerns that Parks was not ready for
prime time when he succeeded Shelby Coffey III, the high-profile
Times editor whose sudden resignation coincided with Willes's move
to publisher. But analysts say Parks has earned his staff's respect
as a smart newsman who balances Willes's more impulsive nature.
</P>
<P>
   Parks admits that becoming editor when Willes was generating
nasty headlines and scaring his own staff with remarks about
melding journalists and bean counters was ``a rather strange entry
in that I was dealing with a whole set of issues that weren't mine,
that were good concerns that were based on misunderstanding and
frankly, some miscommunication on the part of the Times.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If Parks harbors doubts about Willes's lofty goals, he keeps
them to himself. ``At many newspapers in the United States, a good
year is 1 1/2 percent growth in circulation,'' he says. ``That's
crazy. I think newspapers continue to have far more potential as a
business.''
</P>
<P>
   But critics say that Willes is fixated on the bottom line and
that he only respects what he can measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think making the numbers better is his plan,'' says Sara
Fisher, a reporter at The Los Angeles Business Journal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is there a way to measure the quality of international
coverage? I don't have a clue,'' he responds. ``On the other hand,
can you measure readership? Of course you can.''
</P>
<P>
   The Times publisher says he recognizes the intrinsic qualities
of good journalism and the incalculable value of the Times's
reputation. ``What's unique about journalism is the editorial
side,'' he says, sounding all the right notes. ``We haven't cut out
coverage of foreign news. We haven't cut out coverage of national
news.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though he isn't one of us, he talks the talk, he speaks
like a journalist,'' says an admiring Jan Schaffer, executive
director of the Pew Center for Civic Journalism.
</P>
<P>
   But in his high-powered crusade to save his newspaper _ and
perhaps the entire industry _ the man who began his career as an
assistant professor of finance at the University of Pennsylvania
has sealed his fate. He is someone who will ultimately live or die
by the numbers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
