<DOCNO> NYT19990216.0124 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-16 13:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7019 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      02-16 0669
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN'S MAGAZINES RELY ON SEXUAL INSECURITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A &UR;  &LR; University of Chicago sex study published last week revealed
that nearly half of all women and one-third of men have serious
sexual problems. The findings shed light on a range of hitherto
dimly lit corners, among them the question of why women's magazines
feature so many stories about sex. Sex sells, of course, but why
does it sell? The answer may not be as obvious as it seems.
</P>
<P>
   This month's crop of women's magazines has even more sex than
usual. Blame it on St. Valentine's Day, when editors' minds turn
not-so-lightly to thoughts of love. Or blame it on February, the
shortest, nastiest month of the year, when readers need a reason to
go on living. Or blame it on Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Sex shouts at us from the newsstand, in headlines.
</P>
<P>
   Allure: ``Rated X. Sex Lessons of a Paris Madam.''
</P>
<P>
   Glamour: ``Is He Your Secret Sexual Soulmate? How to Meet or
Make Your Man the Lover of Your Steamiest Dreams.''
</P>
<P>
   Last Sunday, Max Frankel wrote a column in the New York Times
Magazine about the surfeit of sex in women's magazines, suggesting
that it accounts for the nation's surprisingly blase attitude
toward the steamy details of the presidential sex scandal. Prurient
stories in mainstream women's magazines have shaped our attitudes
about sex, Frankel said, so that we are now a nation of cynical
sexual sophisticates.
</P>
<P>
   But which came first? Monica or the magazines? It used to be
that only Cosmopolitan could be relied upon to put sex on its
cover. Now even traditional women's magazines like Redbook hook
readers every month with headlines about sex.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent interview in the New York Post, Redbook's editor
Lesley Jane Seymour said the events in Washington have shaped the
content of women's magazines. ``The reality is we are all talking
about sex and this makes (the subject) more accessible,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few days after Frankel's column appeared came the results
of the University of Chicago sex survey, published in the Journal
of the American Medical Association. Are we a nation of sexual
sophisticates? We're anything but, if the study can be believed.
</P>
<P>
   The results of this survey may have come as a surprise to many,
although probably not to the editors of women's magazines who know
their readers are as insecure about sexual matters as they are
about weight, aging, hair, makeup, and a host of other issues.
Readers crave information about sex, and they turn to women's
magazines in search of it. Lately they've been getting more advice
than ever, some of it good, some of it nonsense. Sexy headlines are
major weapons in fierce circulation skirmishes, so perhaps it's not
surprising that the headlines are often racier than the stories.
For example, a piece in Mirabella provocatively titled ``Hot and
Heavy. Does More Body Fat Mean Better Sex?'' turns out to be an
interesting but non-titillating report on the relationship between
weight and estrogen levels. (The answer? Maybe. It depends on how
much fat you own and where you carry it _ just in case you're
wondering.)
</P>
<P>
   The women's magazine industry has always played upon readers
feelings of inadequacy. When it comes to sex, editors don't even
have to try to make readers feel as though something's missing in
their lives. Once you might have felt inadequate because your
sponge cake didn't measure up. Now you have to worry that your
orgasm potential doesn't meet the standard.
</P>
<P>
   What ordinary woman really feels equal to this Cosmo challenge:
``Be the Best Sex of His Life _ How to Tease Him Mercilessly,
Seduce Him Slowly, Then Rock His World in Ways He's only Dreamed
About!'' The University of Chicago sex survey revealed, among other
things, that women suffer almost as much as men from performance
anxiety. Readers of women's magazines probably suffer more than
most.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Diane White is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
