<HEADLINE>
THERE'S COLOR AMID THE DARKNESS OF MEN'S FASHION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CYNTHIA ROBINS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The fall '99 menswear collections opened with an edgy
salvo from Kenneth Cole, who didn't even bother to acknowledge that
there were any other colors but black, gray and navy.
</P>
<P>
   Cole's collection, however, set the pace for everyone else in
terms of cut (sleek and boxy at the same time) and attitude (young,
urban, futuristic).
</P>
<P>
   Cole showed his Darth Vader blacks and silvered modernisms (such
as padded microfiber and leather outwear paired with slick, black
microfiber snowboarder zippered pants and overalls) and his totally
New York approach to jeans and suitings alike, in Grand Central
Terminal's Vanderbilt Hall, with its soaring 40-foot ceiling and
marble floors. It was a salvo buyers will not forget and set the
bar fairly high for every other designer who followed.
</P>
<P>
   The minute the show ended with actors Kevin Bacon, Billy Baldwin
and Jeremy Piven strolling the runway, those hard-bitten and jaded
buyers and other spectators stood up and gave Cole a warm ovation.
</P>
<P>
   Trends broke down into two separate and highly divergent areas.
The first was Millennial Modern, with utilitarian clothes like
cargo pants, jeanswear, blue-collar uniforms worked up in high-tech
fabrics such as oiled cottons and boiled wools, microfibers,
rubberized chino, and light-reflective and plastic-coated man-made
fibers. Then there was the Young Urban Dandy, who is not afraid of
color, dramatic pieces or luxurious fabrics.
</P>
<P>
   If there was any message to men for fall it was: Women stole our
styles from us and we're stealing them back. Where the women's
collections for spring featured body packs, drawstring pants (a
take-off on men's pj bottoms), hooded sweaters, ponchos and
anoraks, men's fall collections have reclaimed them with a stylish
vengeance. The one proviso: Don't be afraid to affect these pieces
in vivid, arresting color.
</P>
<P>
   Here is some of the other talent:
</P>
<P>
   _ Sandy Dalal. When Wilkes Bashford mentions that he's ``looking
at Sandy Dalal,'' then you know this designer, 23, is definitely
one to watch. Dalal uses his Indian heritage to good effect with
this collection, which is a romance with color and texture more
than adventuresome cut.
</P>
<P>
   Dalal has taken conservative clothing like the three-button suit
and juiced it up with sensuous color. His jewel-toned velvet
tuxedos are just the ticket for men who are leaving their penguin
suits behind. He uses color as accent on thick, luxurious cashmere
sweaters (slashes of contrasting color holding down shoulder or
side body seams); in playful floral jackets and trousers; and as
shirtings atop waxed and oiled fabric trousers that look like
flexible leathers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Everett Hall. He's in love with color. Showing only
well-tailored suits and sports jackets, Hall went for the dramatic
_ like a gorgeous twilight blue, three-button draped suit worn with
a black silk charmeuse shirt and matching tie or a black six-button
double-breasted suit with a retro-gangster feel.
</P>
<P>
   Hall's clothes are well-in-keeping with the accent on youthful
experimentation, but it takes a really secure, adventuresome guy to
carry them off. Fabrics are lightweight and creaseproof; cuts are
the sleek/boxy look, which might seem like an oxymoron, but these
are stand-away from the body cuts that require well-tailored
shoulders to hang right and no beer gut to look good.
</P>
<P>
   _ Gene Meyer. It is expected that he will play with color and
push the envelope. But with this collection, someone should have
put a tether on him. Meyer's outwear, particularly the shearlings
and hooded duffel coats were swell; and his jersey and flannel
draw-string pants were sexy and body-hugging, but to gussy them up
with massive cargo pockets in front and a built-in fanny pack in
back screamed ``unclear on the concept.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there were the pink, acid green, and graphic red, white and
black shirts decorated with beads and sequins. Very festive,
circuit party stuff.
</P>
<P>
   _ Perry Ellis. He is forever reminding me of a big, playful dog
who makes you laugh. The line has always been youth-oriented and
super preppie and still is, but with certain gentrified country
twists. Color reigned here with a fall palette of browns
(everything from walnut and bark to tobacco and earth tones),
greens, burgundies and cranberry (a deep red/cranberry leather
jacket was a major shock). The best pieces: dramatic shin-swept
ponchos and short-sleeved cashmere T-shirts. The tuxedo look is
winter white, nothing the young urban pioneer would even attempt
unless he had a good dry cleaner.
</P>
<P>
   _ R. Scott French. This first-time menswear designer sent real
men in real clothes down the runway, but since a lot of them were
famous baseball players and Alan Cumming, the Tony-winning star of
``Cabaret,'' it was the guys who were noted, not the clothes. Which
was too bad. Some of French's designs were right on, like the
stretch drawstring trousers. Putting a pair of them on Boston Red
Sox pitcher Bret Saberhagen may have been a mistake though, what
with his tree-trunk thighs and double ax-handle butt. However,
French's sportswear was colorful and body-friendly.
</P>
<P>
   _ David Chu for Nautica. Using eerie, Prada-esque blue neon
lighting on the runway and an ear-splitting electronic score, Chu
may have alarmed and turned off more people than he charmed. Chu's
inspiration was the American worker. There were jeans, overalls,
carpenter pants and vests _ done up in cyber gray, black and navy
tones in rubberized and space-age fabrications. His clothes go
beyond edgy. They're threatening. Chu's outerwear is heavy and
winterized, equipped with face-obscuring hoods and created out of
high-tech, waterproof (and probably bullet-proof) fabrics.
Personally, I like his bright yellow sailing parkas better.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
