<HEADLINE>
STUDENTS SYMPATHIZE WITH PRESIDENTIAL AFFAIR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANDREW BROWNSTEIN  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Here's an argument not heard in the impeachment
trial of President Clinton: If the sex helps him do his job better,
so be it.
</P>
<P>
   No, those words were not uttered by presidential defenders as
the Senate voted to clear Clinton of perjury and obstruction of
justice charges stemming from his affair with Monica Lewinsky.
Rather, they were uttered by Kelly Davis, who was telling the more
than 100 students attending the ``Sex, Lies and Impeachment'' class
at the State University of New York at Albany that the president
should be held to a lower standard than most Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president has responsibilities we can't possibly fathom,''
said Davis, an archaeology major from Yonkers, N.Y. ``I don't think
he should have to explain why he had sex with an intern.''
</P>
<P>
   Just hours before the Senate voted to acquit Clinton on Friday,
Professor Martin Edelman asked his class how they would vote.
</P>
<P>
   The students turned out to be more pro-Clinton than the Senate,
with roughly two-thirds raising their hands for acquittal. But
freed from the restraints of political convention, they gave
reasons seldom heard in Washington _ at least not publicly.
</P>
<P>
   Consider Sean Carroll, a political science major from Brooklyn.
He's a Republican, but don't expect to hear arguments from him in
favor of punishing Clinton. Rather, he advocated acquittal for
political reasons: If Vice President Al Gore became president, he
argued, it might increase his chances for election in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd vote to acquit, just so the 2000 election is more
competitive,'' Carroll said.
</P>
<P>
   The course, which for the past month has been probing the
historical and cultural forces behind Clinton's impeachment, took
on the air of a Capitol hearing room Friday. Far from sounding
jaded and tired of the scandal, students were impassioned, railing
against factions in society they blame for the scandal: Republicans
(obsessed with sex), Democrats (morally bankrupt), the news media
(narrow-minded) and the American people (complacent).
</P>
<P>
   A poll taken by Edelman revealed that all but a handful of
students believed that Clinton would have been convicted during an
economic downturn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a Democrat, so its hard for me to say, but I think he
should just walk away with whatever dignity he has left and
resign,'' said Susan Idiculla, a political science major from
Poughkeepsie, N.Y. ``I was hoping it would not come to impeachment
and it did. I was hoping it would not come to removal and it did. I
can't believe all this has happened and his approval ratings are
still sky high.''
</P>
<P>
   Others, while admitting Clinton's wrongdoing, said they feared
his opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's something worse about people who can't forgive
Clinton for human failings,'' said Matthew Reif, a political
science major from Syracuse, N.Y.
</P>
</TEXT>
