<HEADLINE>
NEW BOOKS RECENTLY REVIEWED BY THE GLOBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Empress of the Splendid Season'' by Oscar Hijuelos
(HarperFlamingo, $25). An upper-class Cuban woman, reduced to
cleaning posh New York apartments, encounters wealth from
underneath. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Hitler: 1889-1936: Hubris'' by Ian Kershaw (Norton, $35). A
massive and highly readable account of the rise of the tyrant. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Law of Similars'' by Chris Bojalian (Harmony Books, $23).
A prosecutor falls for a sexy homeopathist, with dangerous results
when she is suspected of malpractice. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Careless Love: The Unmaking of Elvis Presley'' by Peter
Guralnick (Little, Brown, $27.95). The decline and fall of a king. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Elegy for Iris'' by John Bayley (St. Martin's, $22.95). Scenes
from a 42-year love affair and marriage _ before and after the
onset of Alzheimer's disease. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Endurance: Shackleton's Legendary Antarctic Expedition''
by Caroline Alexander (Knopf, $29.95). To hell and back with Sir
Ernest Shackleton's attempt to cross the Antarctic in 1914.
</P>
</TEXT>
