GLOBE CRITICS RATE FILMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
 ! poor, !! fair, !!! good, !!!! excellent  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; !! &LR;  ``Blast from the Past'' Lame comedy about a family that
dives into its backyard bomb shelter in 1962 LA and doesn't emerge
until 35 years later. The problem is that they aren't given much to
come out to. Wasted performances by Brendan Fraser, who goes the
``Encino Man'' and ``George of the Jungle'' route as the cocooned
Adam, and Alicia Silverstone as his Eve. (PG-13) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; !! &LR;  ``Message in a Bottle'' Waterlogged romance about a
boat-builder whose letter to his dying wife, placed in a bottle, is
found by a Chicago newspaperwoman. Kevin Costner is appealingly
minimalist as the forlorn guy. Robin Wright Penn is fine as the
lovelorn woman. Paul Newman spices the mix as his outspoken father.
But Luis Mandoki's lethgargic, overblown direction sinks this one.
(PG-13) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; !! &LR;  ``My Favorite Martian'' Lame remake of the '60s TV series about
a reporter trying to cover up the arrival of a Martian until he can
repair his spaceship and get back home. Christopher Lloyd eyeballs
energetically as the alien, and the special-effects guys stay busy,
but this one is no morphing glory. (PG) &QL; 
 &QL; 
(FL)  &UR; !!! &LR;  1/2 ``My Name Is Joe'' One of the best of Ken Loach's
impassioned films on behalf of the working class trying to survive
patterns of deadly corrosion when they can't find jobs. In the
title role of a recovering alcoholic trying to keep his life
together, Peter Mullan delivers one of the year's best
performances. So does Louise Goodall, as a nurse who's both drawn
to and wary of him. (R)
</P>
