<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-16 13:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7027 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-ARCHANGEL-BOS &LR;      02-16 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-ARCHANGEL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARRIS THRIVES IN THE GRAY AREAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CLEA SIMON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
ARCHANGEL 
By Robert Harris 
Random House, $24.95, 373 pp. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Robert Harris deals in futures. In his sure-footed treks through
the worlds of political thriller-mysteries, he takes historical
situations and asks ``What if?'' His first fictional outing, the
best-selling ``Fatherland,'' imagined a world in which Hitler had
won World War II, and where one lonely cop bent on investigating a
mysterious death becomes tangled in Reich bureaucracy. For
``Archangel,'' his third mystery, the setup is more subtle.
History, at least the big facts, isn't changed. Instead, the gray
areas, the possibilities, and the rumors come to life. The
present-day Russia that our hero, an alcoholic academic named
``Fluke'' Kelso, finds himself wandering through is recognizable
from today's news reports. The future, however, couldn't be
scarier.
</P>
<P>
   Harris knows his history. The British writer was a BBC
journalist and the author of the nonfiction ``Selling Hitler''
(about the fake Hitler diaries) before turning his hand to
breathless pop fiction. And though his specialty seems to have been
Germany, he's up on the former Soviet Union as well. In its 1955
Pulitzer Prize-winning coverage, The New York Times reported the
possibility that Josef Stalin's death two years earlier had been
murder. Harris takes that idea and runs with it, flicking back and
forth through time to witness a conspiracy that may have hastened
the mad tyrant's death but that couldn't stop one of his schemes
for controlling the future. Uncovering that plan in the present day
_ Kelso is desperate for a research coup _ brings 40-year-old
factions into play, evoking terrible echoes of Germany immediately
before Hitler took control. As Russia teeters on the edge of a
political collapse that too closely recalls Weimar Germany's, the
flailing academic must fight for both his life and world peace.
</P>
<P>
   That's quite a load to dump on poor Kelso, an antihero with
flaws big enough for Harrison Ford to fly a jet through. He's not a
well man. His drinking has caused the end of several marriages, and
ego-driven career choices have left him jobless and unable to
write. And while these factors help force him into action, they do
detract a bit from his appeal. Unlike the innocent Nazi cop of
``Fatherland'' or the unstable codebreaker hero of ``Enigma,''
Harris's second thriller, Kelso is a difficult protagonist with
whom to identify. Unlike those earlier characters, the sloppy sot
has few attractive vulnerabilities and lots of nasty habits, not
the least of which is his tendency to be bullied by an even slimier
fellow, an American TV reporter named R. J. O'Brian.
</P>
<P>
   To further hamper Kelso, he and his colleagues are forced to
clamber through prose that has grown simpler with each successive
book. O'Brian's flat characterization _ he's a stereotypically
self-important American _ serves the plot but little else. Hands
grow ``slippery with blood'' and silence must be ``utter.''
</P>
<P>
   But mystery-thrillers have their own laws, and sometimes their
limited range just sounds right. The sometime prostitute Zinaida,
for example, is a tough babe; we pick that up from her walk, her
tight apparel, and her relative nonchalance about her profession.
But her character is tamped down when she digs out her father's
gun: ``She had discovered that she could still strip and load it
without looking at it _ like riding a bicycle, it seemed: one of
those childish accomplishments you never forgot.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris has the pitch just right in other minor characters as
well. Rapava, the old-timer who tells Kelso about Stalin's last
days, is a grand storyteller in Harris's hands, bringing to life
his youth as a naive young recruit and his innocent observations on
the half-mad Stalin. The way Rapava's murder reverberates through
Kelso's mind, along with images of wolves, is equally chilling. And
Harris knows how to play up the action: A harrowing, extended hunt
through the Russian subarctic works every element for tension,
setting Kelso against not only a crazed enemy and government
killers, but also the crushing cold that puts a time limit on
survival. These are the factors, ultimately, that hook readers, and
in these Harris excels. ``Archangel'' may not live up to its
predecessors, but it will keep readers awake till the small hours
in fear of endless night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
