<DOCNO> NYT19990216.0132 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-16 13:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7028 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ART-MORELL-2TAKES-BOS     02-16 1447
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-MORELL-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE I OF THE CAMERA 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRISTINE TEMIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ After fleeing Castro's Cuba in 1962, Abelardo
Morell, his parents, and his sister eventually landed in New York
City, where Morell's father took a job as a building
superintendent. With the job came a basement apartment with only
one window, high up on the wall, which gave the 14-year-old Morell
an odd perspective on the outside world.
</P>
<P>
   He's kept that. In the camera obscura photographs that have
occupied him for the last few years, he's created upside-down
images of cities, mountains, and the Empire State Building, the
exterior world projected onto the walls of various interiors,
giving new meaning to ``A Room With a View.'' As his home east of
Havana had been during the revolution, as the family digs in
Manhattan became, the rooms in Morell's photographs are a refuge.
</P>
<P>
   Some of his camera obscura works are in ``Abelardo Morell and
the Camera Eye,'' a show organized by the Museum of Photographic
Arts in San Diego and opening Wednesday at the Boston Museum of
Fine Arts. Although the exhibition comes from California, Morell is
a local. Since 1983 he's taught at the Massachusetts College of
Art, whose director of exhibitions, Jeffrey Keough, first showed
his work 14 years ago. ``Abe's art is the quintessential
immigrant's search for identity in a new country,'' Keough says.
Morell's MFA appearance, meanwhile, is a rare example of the museum
paying serious attention to a living Boston artist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Artist'' is a label Morell has only recently come to accept.
Sitting in the dining room of the modest triple-decker here where
he lives with his wife and two children, he says, ``In college I
wasn't an art major because I couldn't think of myself as an
artist. When I have to draw, I do stick figures. I'm lousy at it.''
</P>
<P>
   The art world, on the other hand, has gone mad for Morell these
past few years. He's constantly asked to lecture or serve as artist
in residence, internationally, although he says that ``as an exile,
I hate to travel. I like being at home.''
</P>
<P>
   He's the recipient of awards including a Guggenheim Fellowship
and an honorary degree from his alma mater, Bowdoin College in
Brunswick, Maine. He's been the subject of numerous shows and of
one of the Smithsonian Institution Press monographs ``Photographers
at Work.'' His art is in important public collections: the Museum
of Modern Art in New York, the Israel Museum in Jerusalem, the Art
Institute of Chicago. His New York dealer, Bonni Benrubi, sells his
work for $1,500 _ $7,500 a print, one to the Whitney Museum of
American Art just last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Abe's popularity is endless,'' Benrubi says, ``which is why
he's so backed up.''
</P>
<P>
   Language and music have played pivotal parts in Morell's
development. The role of language is clear to anyone who's seen his
images of stacks of children's alphabet blocks, his poignant
close-ups of Braille texts illuminated by shafts of light, his
photographs that make books as monumental as the pyramids. His
earliest exploration of books _ in his uncle's Havana library _ was
physical. He appreciated them more for their shapes, sizes, and
even their smells than for their content.
</P>
<P>
   Music is no less key, but far less obvious. ``I'm a CD addict,''
he confesses, ``everything from Bartok to Lauryn Hill. I listen
constantly when I'm in the darkroom. And I'm starting to take piano
lessons now. I had a sophisticated knowledge of music without even
knowing where middle C was.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a child, music and dancing were a way to belong,'' he says.
``I was 8 or 9 when my parents taught me how to dance. It was
important to them, a passport into culture in Cuba. They're in
their mid-70s now and they still go dancing twice a week, in New
Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cuban music is probably the world's most exciting and
rhythmically complex. But the dancing is very formal, a contrast to
the brassiness of the music. That combination of form and something
sexy and hot shaped me.''
</P>
<P>
   Morell's family left Cuba after his father, who had been a
sergeant in Batista's navy and was twice arrested during the Castro
regime, was tipped off that he'd been marked for a firing squad.
``He managed to negotiate `tourist' visas,'' Morell says, which
involved giving everything you owned to the government before you
left on your `vacation.'
</P>
<P>
   ``We were walking to a KLM prop plane and two secret service
agents stopped my father and interrogated him for an hour,'' Morell
recalls. ``Finally they let him go. When the plane took off, all
the adults started to cry. They knew that was it. They had no
illusions about going back. I'm still angry about having to leave.
I was just beginning to become a person in a society. That was
taken away from me. I had to be an instant grown-up. I learned
English more quickly than my parents, so I had to be their
negotiator.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that travel from the United States to Cuba is possible in
certain situations, Morell says, he has a ``complicated reaction to
the idea of going back.''
</P>
<P>
   What he calls ``the Spanish-English thing'' made his early years
in this country tough and made language and literature all the more
crucial. The part-time jobs he held in high school and college left
little time for socializing, and his imperfect English didn't help.
To improve his command of his new language he read Hemingway. ``I
liked its concreteness,'' says the artist who would later give his
photographs no-nonsense titles Hemingway would have approved of.
</P>
<P>
   At 14, he bought himself a Brownie camera, with money earned
from being Drugstore Delivery Boy to the Stars, working for a
pharmacy that counted Steve Lawrence and Eydie Gorme among its
customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Images became a way to deal with things,'' Morell says, ``to
tell my own story.'' He holds up one of his earliest photographs, a
shot of his parents, his father bare-chested and shoveling coal
into a boiler in a dank basement, his mother standing nearby.
``They're smiling,'' notes Morell, who himself smiles almost
constantly during a two-hour interview. ``The place was Dickensian,
subterranean, a complete contrast to Cuban light. But they were
happy. In America, no one could come and take them away.''
</P>
<P>
   An admissions officer from Bowdoin College arrived at Morell's
New York high school when he was a senior. ``They were trying to
recruit people not like them,'' he says. He was offered a
scholarship. His parents looked up Maine on a map. He took the bus
to Brunswick for his freshman year, and the more rural the terrain
became during the ride, ``the more frightened I got,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   A sophomore-year photography course with Bowdoin professor John
McKee sparked Morell's passion. ``From the first roll of film,'' he
says, ``it was clear I was going to do this forever.'' Music also
figured in his college career. He had his own program on the
college radio station, where he played everything from Cage to
Coltrane. ``I admire John Cage's use of form to explore the
unknown,'' he says. ``This was the Woodstock era. Rampant
formlessness.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
``An absurd place'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He went on to earn an MFA from Yale, working in the
street-photography tradition of Henri Cartier-Bresson and Robert
Frank. His images were urban, gritty, full of angst. ``The world
was an absurd place, where I was a Camus-like observer,'' he says.
That's as close as he comes to art philosophy. Otherwise, he's
allergic, wincing as he speaks the dreaded word ``deconstruct'' and
proclaiming that ``I can pronounce Foucault and that's it.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Diane Arbus, he initially found truth edited by his own eye
to be stranger than fiction. An early photograph taken in a bike
shop, for instances, stars a little blond girl who looks eerily
irradiated, even possessed, as if she's auditioning for ``The Turn
of the Screw.''
</P>
<P>
   Morell and his wife, filmmaker Lisa McElaney, had their first
child, Brady, in 1986, and Morell turned his time _ and lens _ to
things domestic. ``The child is father of the man,'' Wordsworth
wrote, and so it was with Morell. Brady's birth prompted the first
body of work that earned him a place as one of America's foremost
contemporary photographers. Getting down on the floor with his son,
he made a whole series of photographs from a rugrat's perspective.
A tower of blocks became a skyscraper; a view from the top of a
metal playground slide seemed a virtual Everest, terrifyingly
steep; a floor-level view of bathroom tiles with a trail of muddy
footprints suggested both a baby about to crawl into them and the
sheer gooey mess of early childhood.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-99 1357EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990216.0133 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-16 13:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7030 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ART-MORRELL-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE     02-16 1048
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-MORRELL-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 BROOKINE, Mass.: ... early childhood.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The long exposures his works require turn humble objects into
testaments to the passage of time. ``It's part of being a lapsed
Catholic,'' he jokes. ``Exposures of five to six minutes are my
hair shirt. I'm impatient; the waiting settles me down.'' In the
San Diego show catalog, curator Diana Gaston writes of the effect
of time in Morell's ``Water Pouring Out of a Pot'': ``An otherwise
ordinary stream of water becomes a weighty column, achieving its
shape over the course of a five-minute exposure.''
</P>
<P>
   Five minutes is nothing, though, compared with the eight hours
Morell's camera obscura works take. The principle of the camera
obscura is that if all light is blocked from a box except for a
tiny hole in one side, the image of the exterior world will pass
through that hole and appear on the opposite side of the box _
upside down. The device dates back to Leonardo, possibly even to
Aristotle. Morell uses it to create an eight-hour record of
shifting clouds and perambulating people, like Warhol's famous
six-hour film of someone sleeping, but condensed into a single
image.
</P>
<P>
   It's photography at its most basic, which pleases Morell. ``Most
of what I do, anyone can,'' he says. ``I'm 50. If I were 20, I'd
feel forced to master all this digital stuff.'' He regularly
delights a lot of 20-year-olds with the camera obscura technique,
though, which he demonstrates each semester to his Mass. Art
students, turning a classroom into a giant example. ``They're
astonished,'' he says. ``They don't expect it, as much as I prepare
them. They say things like, `Oh, my God, it's in color! People are
moving! It's like doing card tricks for your kids.' '' When the
results are shown in galleries, people tend to list while looking
at them, Morell says, as if they wanted to stand on their head.
</P>
<P>
   The purest and most transparent of the camera obscura pieces is
the 1991 ``Light Bulb,'' an ode to photography's origins, an
entirely visual explanation of how the camera obscura works. A
light bulb shines outside the hole cut in a cardboard box. A dim
bulb appears inside, inverted. When viewers look at it, a light
bulb goes on in their heads, with an ``aah!'' of recognition. On
one occasion, Morell turned a room in his house into a camera
obscura and his family settled in to watch this homemade theater,
like a '50s family in a car at a drive-in. The neighborhood
appeared on the living room wall, upside down. ``It was slightly
perverse,'' says Morell, ``like being peeping Toms.''
</P>
<P>
   The whole Morell family occasionally collaborate on a piece.
``Sometimes I even pay the kids,'' he says. In the 1994 ``Laura and
Brady in the Shadow of Our House,'' shot from a third-floor window,
the two children lie sleeping on the ground, in the shadow of a
house defined by its roof line. Using sticks, Morell and his wife
drew windows and doors. The children look like they're floating,
weightless. ``It's like Chagall,'' says their father. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Compared with Hopper &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Often, though, his photographs are unpopulated. Their lonely
stillness has been compared with that in the paintings of Edward
Hopper. ``I think I'm as good as Hopper,'' Morell says, quickly
adding, ``That's a joke.'' On the hierarchy that still ranks
painting above photography, he adds, ``It's not a concern to me,
politically. But if I'd been segregated and only shown in the
context of photography, I'd resent it. That's happened to some
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Morell also photographs other art, transforming its context. In
residencies at the Boston Athenaeum and the Isabella Stewart
Gardner Museum, he's photographed artbooks and paintings, using odd
vantage points to create sly commentaries. He shows the shifty-eyed
subject of Raphael's ``Portrait of Ingharami'' reproduced in a book
open at a 45-degree angle, then photographs the real painting with
Ingharami's face confined to a corner, as if it's going to drop out
of the picture. Odd perspectives have been a specialty all along:
In ``Looking Down _ Miami 1974,'' a precipitous balcony view
resulted in a shot with a head popping up from the bottom and legs
coming down from the top.
</P>
<P>
   ``Looking Down'' was made after Morell dropped out of Bowdoin.
(He eventually returned to graduate.) He migrated to Miami, took a
job as a janitor, and started photographing the Cuban exile
experience. But, he says, ``I've tried not to be labeled `The Cuban
Photographer.' I came to the US to be free. Some contemporary Latin
American artists make pictures of peasants holding skulls,
specifically targeted to the Yankee market. That's not me.''
</P>
<P>
   Play with scale is part of his fun. So it's no wonder that
Morell would turn his talents to that masterpiece of surreal scale,
Lewis Carroll's ``Alice's Adventures in Wonderland.'' His new
version, just published by Dutton, is an homage to the original
illustrator, Sir John Tenniel, and a continuation of Morell's
art-about-art and art-about-books. He photographed Tenniel's
figures, then, as if they were paper dolls, put them in new
settings. ``I used books as the architecture of the story,'' he
explains. ``I had a dream where the hole Alice goes down was a hole
in a book.'' So he drilled a hole in a picturesque leatherbound
tome and photographed it. He acknowledges that harming a book is,
to some, ``a violation, something naughty.'' But in a world
routinely scandalized by the Mapplethorpes of the field, Morell's
``naughtiness'' seems downright quaint.
</P>
<P>
   Morell is a big Wallace Stevens fan, and his show's catalog
opens with a quote from the poet's ``The Planet on the Table'':
``His self and the sun were one / And his poems, although makings
of his self / Were no less makings of the sun.'' To Morell, the
lines summarize his search for a place in a world he wasn't born
into, a search accomplished through art. ``It's through looking at
the outside world,'' he says, ``that you reckon with the things
inside you.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(``ABELARDO MORELL AND THE CAMERA EYE'' is at the Museum of Fine
Arts, from Wednesday through April 1. On March 24 at 7:30 p.m., in
Remis Auditorium, Morell gives a slide talk, ``A Picture Account,''
about his work. Admission is $9 for museum members; $12 for
non-members. Call 369-3306 for tickets.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-99 1358EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
