 Tuesday, Feb. 16, 1999    
 Editors      The Hearst News Service will file these stories for
Wednesday. If you have questions, please call Susie McBee or Tim
Spence at 202-298-6920.       (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all
sluglines.)   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   AFFIRMATIVE-ACTION-LEE (Washington) _ Former Attorney General
Edwin Meese and two conservative legal watchdog groups attack
President Clinton's top civil rights enforcer, Acting Assistant
Attorney General Bill Lann Lee. They charge that he has pursued
``racial and ethnic preferences.'' Lee's nomination to the
assistant AG post itself was blocked by Senate Republicans in 1997,
and it's expected to come up again this year. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ In launching a campaign for a 10
percent across-the-board income tax cut, Senate Majority Leader
Trent Lott is getting too far ahead of his Republican troops.
Traditionally tax cuts are popular in the GOP, but this time
important party leaders prefer targeted cuts, which would have a
better chance of congressional passage. By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
</TEXT>
