<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-16 14:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7039 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-ESPINAGE-BOS &LR;      02-16 0977
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-ESPINAGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPY VS. SPY VS. SPY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
THE HAUNTED WOOD 
Soviet Espionage in America _ The Stalin Era 
By Allen Weinstein and Alexander Vassiliev. Random House. 402 pp.
Illustrated. $30. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many of the dozens of Americans who passed secrets to the Soviet
Union before World War II apparently did so for ideological and
philosophical reasons, not monetary ones. Often drawn from the
ranks of privileged intellectuals, American informants in the 1930s
and '40s trafficked in heady infatuation with Moscow's communist
experiment.
</P>
<P>
   Samuel Dickstein was an exception. A New York Democrat in
Congress who worked early on to root out Nazi sympathizers,
Dickstein ran a lucrative trade in illegal visas for Soviet
operatives before brashly offering to spy for the NKVD, the KGB's
precursor, in return for cash. To wheeler-dealer Dickstein, to whom
the Soviets assigned the code name ``Crook,'' green, not red, was
the motivating factor.
</P>
<P>
   Dickstein's tale, new in the literature on Americans who spied
for the Soviet Union, is among the shortest and most startling in
``The Haunted Wood,'' a new investigation by American historian
Allen Weinstein and Russian spy-turned-journalist Alexander
Vassiliev. Over 1993-'95, the authors had unparalleled access to
selected, never-before-seen KGB files. Based on that research, they
have compiled a selective account of what they term ``the golden
age'' of Soviet espionage in the United States, casting new light
upon Moscow's intelligence machine from 1933 to 1945.
</P>
<P>
   Fresh elements of cloak-and-dagger make cameo appearances
throughout this highly detailed, dense narrative. Martha Dodd
Stern, the comely and capricious daughter of President Roosevelt's
ambassador to Hitler's Germany, launches a love affair with a
Soviet diplomat in Berlin right under her father's eyes, becoming
``courtesan, agent, and student of communism.'' Years later she and
her husband, the financier Alfred Stern, flee suspicious US
officials for permanent exile in Prague.
</P>
<P>
   There are others. Hollywood con artist Boris Morros, a
fast-talking film producer-director who strings the Soviets along
by name-dropping Washington connections while two-timing as an FBI
double agent, played a melodramatic, flamboyant role that exceeded
his bit part in the film industry. His achievements _ installing a
Russian spy in Paramount's Berlin office, for example _ seem small.
One wonders why this windbag so interested his handlers, until one
recalls the central role played by film in the Soviet propaganda
machine, a cultural feature that may have led Moscow to keep up
ties with Morros.
</P>
<P>
   Better-known American spies _ Alger Hiss, Whittaker Chambers,
and Laurence Duggan among them _ are detailed, with fresh light
cast on their evident guilt. At the same time, the authors saw NKVD
documents suggesting that Robert Oppenheimer, the American
physicist, was a ``secret member of the compatriot organization
(the American Communist Party)'' _ and nothing more. Weinstein and
Vassiliev note that despite vigorous efforts by Moscow to
infiltrate America's bomb-making program, there is no evidence to
suggest that the father of the Manhattan Project spied for the
Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   Though not the first to do so, the two authors describe how the
NKVD, which carried out Stalin's purges, managed to contribute to
its own demise. Many of the organization's US-based Russian
operatives were recalled to Moscow and then exiled or shot, the
victims of a highly paranoid organization that saw traitors
everywhere. The suspicion extended to American operatives, too _
and sometimes justifiably so. By 1945, Elizabeth Bentley, a Vassar
graduate, had shifted her allegiance from the NKVD to the FBI, so
scaring the Soviets that they immediately shut down virtually all
of their underground US operations.
</P>
<P>
   The irony is obvious: In Weinstein's and Vassiliev's hands, much
of what has been alleged or suspected about Americans working for
the Soviets becomes highly probable. Yet by the time of the
McCarthy-era trials in the early 1950s, the Soviet spying machine
was in shambles.
</P>
<P>
   Readers should not expect elegantly written, well-paced
narrative in ``The Haunted Wood.'' While the book is essential,
pathbreaking reading for anyone interested in Soviet espionage, it
is a trove of data and direct quotation from KGB files, and not a
fluid, readerly text.
</P>
<P>
   Although the authors gained access to certain Venona cables _ US
intelligence decryptions of coded Soviet diplomatic telegrams _
that in some cases corroborate the KGB files, lacunae abound. How
complete and unvarnished a tale do the files selected by the
cash-strapped SVR for Weinstein and Vassiliev's perusal actually
tell? The men write that ``Russian intelligence agencies received
substantial and sometimes critical information (including many
classified documents) concerning US government policies, its
confidential negotiating strategies and secret weapons
developments.'' Yet for all the detail in ``The Haunted Wood,'' it
is often unclear how much damage some of its characters actually
did. One exception is Harold Glasser, a US Treasury Department
official (code-named Ruble) who passed scores of key State
Department and Treasury policy documents to Soviet intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   Vassiliev and Weinstein (who probed some of these issues in his
``Perjury: The Hiss-Chambers Case'') do not claim to have closed
the book on the nature and extent of Soviet spy operations. Until
more US and Russian intelligence files are opened and examined,
``The Haunted Wood'' will stand as a new and important chapter in
the literature of Soviet espionage, and not a final account.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Lynnley Browning, a former correspondent in Russia, writes for the
Globe Business pages.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-99 1404EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990216.0140 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-16 14:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7040 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      02-16 1597
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLOWER SEASON JUST AROUND THE CORNER, SHOWS REMIND US 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sure signs of spring are the many flower shows blossoming around
the country. And two of the best shows, the largest and the oldest,
are in Boston and Philadelphia, respectively. It's time to sow your
travel plans to greet spring.
</P>
<P>
   The New England Spring Flower Show in Boston is the third
largest in the world and will have a theme of Artistry in the
Garden with 40 landscaped gardens on display. The show at the
Bayside Expo Center, March 13 to 21, also will feature a number of
special events and presentations. For information on the 128th
gardening showcase, call 617-536-9280.
</P>
<P>
   Among displays will be one with favorite scenes from the classic
children's stories by Beatrix Potter of ``Peter Rabbit and
Friends''; another, a ``living'' room of furnishings made from
living plant material, will have some technological surprises; and
a third display will be an ``inspirational garden'' that might have
inspired composers of 19th-century music.
</P>
<P>
   Call the Boston Convention and Visitors Bureau (888-SEE BOSTON)
for information on hotel packages to the show. Adult tickets are
$16 weekends, $14 weekdays, with discounted weekday tickets
available at Stop &AMP; Shop.
</P>
<P>
   The Philadelphia Flower Show, March 7-14, is the largest single
destination event in the city. The Philadelphia show, the largest
in the world, is almost twice the size of the Boston show, its
theme will be ``Design on Nature . . . The Art of Gardening,''
recognizing the idealized natural visions of 19th-century American
Romantics.
</P>
<P>
   It will be held at the Pennsylvania Convention Center and also
will feature special presentations, Tea Time, and even a gardener's
playstation.
</P>
<P>
   Among displays will be 12 ``micro'' gardens, and four settings
inspired by the formal gardens of the National Trust for Historic
Preservation _ one of the gardens captures the elaborate
magnificence of the Kykuit gardens at the Rockefeller Mansion along
the Hudson River.
</P>
<P>
   Since Philadelphia's show is downtown, visitors can receive free
same day reentry, allowing them to explore the city, then return to
the show. The show is $18 weekends, $16 weekdays. The city goes all
out for Flower Show Week and offers a free Bouquet Book filled with
discounts and special events (available at the show or by calling
215-988-8899). For information on hotel packages that include show
tickets, call 800-380-4683.
</P>
<P>
   Both shows feature extensive displays of products and plants to
purchase. For out-of-town visitors to these shows, when calling for
hotel packages ask about any discounted transportation deals.
American Airlines has a $99 companion fare from anywhere in the
continental United States.
</P>
<P>
   Among other garden shows upcoming is the Rhode Island Flower
Show, Feb. 18-21, at the Rhode Island Convention Center in
Providence.
</P>
<P>
   More than 30 of southern New England's top garden designers,
horticulturists, and landscape architects will have exhibits
ranging from a spectacular Victorian greenhouse to an urban pet
garden, which suggests ways humans and canines can share outdoor
spaces.
</P>
<P>
   For show information, call 800-766-1670. For information on
discounted hotel packages, call the Providence/Warwick Convention &AMP;
Visitors Bureau at 800-233-1636. Amtrak offers a 10 percent fare
discount (for information, call 800-872-7245 and ask for fare code
X-65H-938).
</P>
<P>
   Authentic English garden design will be one of the features of
the annual Maymont Flower &AMP; Garden Show at the Richmond Centre in
Richmond, Va., Feb. 18-21. The show benefits Maymont, a 100-acre
Victorian country estate with Japanese and Italian gardens,
wildlife habitats, and a children's farm that is open to the public
free of charge. For information on the show or about Maymont, call
804-358-7166.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Garden week
</P>
<P>
   America's largest open house, Historic Garden Week in Virginia,
will be April 17-24. The 66th annual garden week is the oldest and
largest statewide house and garden tour event in the nation. Three
dozen separate tours are scheduled on various days during the week
from the commonwealth's Atlantic shoreline to its highlands.
</P>
<P>
   Properties open include town houses with walled gardens,
expansive country and suburban estates, and dwellings dating to the
American Revolution, the Civil War, and the Victorian era. Owners
of properties include popular musician Bruce Hornsby. For a
brochure with tour dates, call 804-644-7776 or, on the Web, visit
www.VAGardenweek.org
</P>
<P>
   For a 200-page guidebook with descriptions of houses and
gardens, along with directions and ticket prices, send a $5
donation payable to Historic Garden Week, 12 East Franklin St.,
Richmond, VA 23219. Tour tickets range from $10 to $20 per event.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Flowering ideas
</P>
<P>
   Visitors will have the rare opportunity to view the interiors
and gardens of some of America's most beautiful private residences
during the 52d annual Festival of Houses and Gardens, March
18-April 17, in Charleston, S.C. More than 150 homes and gardens
are included, and there will be 11 neighborhood tours (each offered
twice). Since tickets are limited and many tours sell out before
the day of the event, advance reservations are encouraged. Tickets
are $35 per event and can be obtained by calling 843-722-3405.
</P>
<P>
   New Bern, N.C., will have its annual Historic Homes and Gardens
Tour on April 9-10. The Hats Off to Spring tour includes 14 homes,
two gardens, and 11 churches.
</P>
<P>
   A Friday evening walking tour with architectural specialists
will point out landmarks such as the 1895 City Hall and the
birthplace of Pepsi-Cola. Tickets for the homes tour are $13.50 in
advance, $15 on the days of the tours. For tickets, write to
Historic Homes Tour, PO Box 207, New Bern, NC 28563. For
information, call 252-638-8558.
</P>
<P>
   Knoxville, Tenn., will hold its annual Dogwood Arts Festival,
April 9-25. The festival, which draws some 350,000 people to East
Tennessee each spring, features more than 100 public and private
gardens open for viewing and 60 miles of blooming Dogwood Trails.
For information on the festival, call 800-DOGWOOD or 423-637-4561.
For package tours, call 888-400-8955.
</P>
<P>
   Another dazzling display of flowers can be seen during the
annual Daffodil Festival on Nantucket. This year's festival is
April 23-25 and features more than 3 million yellow, orange, white,
and pale pink daffodils along the roadsides, in gardens, and in
window boxes.
</P>
<P>
   An annual feature is the antique- and classic-car parade that
features blossom-bedecked vehicles. Since rooms are limited on the
island, advance reservations are recommended.
</P>
<P>
   Call the Visitors Service for information at 508-228-0925. For
an official guide to Nantucket, call 508-228-1700. Nantucket is now
served by two high-speed ferries, cutting the trip down from 2 1/2
hours to about an hour (call the Hy-Line at 508-778-2600 or the
Steamship Authority at 508-771-4000).
</P>
<P>
   Also in Massachusetts, the town of Brewster on Cape Cod will
hold its annual Brewster in Bloom festival on April 29-May 2,
featuring a crafts fair and daffodil parade.
</P>
<P>
   Old Sturbridge Village, the 1830s New England village, will hold
a Garden Planning Symposium on March 6, focusing on heirloom
varieties and 19th-century garden styles. Garden Planning Workshops
are set for March 7. For information, call 508-347-3362.
</P>
<P>
   Another place to head for garden planning workshops is the
Disney Institute at Walt Disney World in Florida. ``We're going a
step further to appeal to not only the garden hobbyist but the
serious gardener as well,'' said Kristin Ptegas, program manager
for the institute's gardening classes. For information, call
800-496-6337.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Garden tours
</P>
<P>
   The Secret and Spectacular Gardens of Holland is a May 3-11 tour
from the Horticultural Society of New York. All participants in the
tour, which includes an insider's look at the world's largest
flower auction, receive membership in the Dutch Garden Society. For
information, call 800-595-CITY.
</P>
<P>
   The gardens of England, including a visit to the famed Chelsea
Flower Show, are featured in a 10-day tour leaving May 18 from
Lucas &AMP; Randall. For information, call 800-505-2505
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts Horticultural Society is offering tours to
Historic Garden Week in Virginia, April 17-22, and the Hampton
Court Flower Show and Royal Gardens in London, July 4-14. For
information, call the society at 617-536-9280, ext. 223.
</P>
<P>
   The Connecticut State Museum of Natural History is sponsoring a
guided Wildflower Hiking tour in the Alps July 11-19, the Historic
Gardens of Virginia April 29-May 6, and a tour to catch the solar
eclipse in Turkey, Aug. 6-18. For information on these tours, call
860-486-4460.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Garden art
</P>
<P>
   Orient-Express Hotels is holding Botanical Master Class series
for students wishing to learn botanical art from master painters in
a relaxed surrounding. The classes are held at Orient-Express
properties in South Carolina, Portugal, South Africa, and Italy.
For information, call Diane Zweiman at Orient-Express Hotels at
212-302-5055.
</P>
<P>
   From Botany to Bouquets: Flowers in Northern Art offers 61 works
by some of the greatest still-life artists of the 16th and 17th
centuries. These Dutch and Flemish flower paintings, watercolors,
manuscripts, and books are on view at the National Gallery of Art's
West Building Dutch Cabinet Galleries in Washington through May 31.
For information, call 202-737-4215.
</P>
</TEXT>
