<HEADLINE>
WHO'S THAT? WHY IT'S YOUR WIFE! 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With Valentine's Day still in mind, it's nice to know that love
and humor can help you weather the most difficult times _ even when
those times are part of your honeymoon. Just ask these people, who
entered the fifth annual Thrifty Car Rental Honeymoon Disasters
Contest:
</P>
<P>
   --Paul and Leah Lusk of Sugar City, Idaho. Their trip to Nevada
was cut short when their car spun out of control, flipped, and
became submerged in flood waters. After hitting his head, Paul
couldn't remember the accident, recognize his bride, or recall that
they were newly married.
</P>
<P>
   --Kim and John Cross of Pittsburgh. John's new mother-in-law
joined them on their car trip to the beach. After an hour in the
car, Mom made them turn back when she realized she'd forgotten to
feed the cat. (Turned out she had fed him after all). At a
restaurant 40 miles out of their way, they stopped so Mom could
stick to her strict dietary regimen. And that's when the car got
stolen.
</P>
<P>
   --Joe and Veronica Frattaioli of Akron, Ohio. Their cruise
featured a tropical storm that made all of the passengers seasick.
And then there was the theft of Joe's wallet and ``green card'' to
let him back into the United States.
</P>
<P>
   --Allan and Skylar Stone of Chickasha, Okla. When Allan ran out
of money in Cozumel, Mexico, he didn't tell his wife he'd hocked
his wedding ring for $25 to pay a cab driver. Several days later,
he paid twice as much to get the ring back. Now that's devotion!
</P>
<P>
   Was your honeymoon disastrous? Send your terror tale to Thrifty
and you could win the grand prize of a second honeymoon with all
the amenities. (This year's top prize was won by an Ohio couple,
whose sad story we related last week.) Check out the Thrifty Web
site at www.thrifty.com and e-mail your entry by visiting the
``Promotions'' section, or write to Honeymoon Disasters 1999, c/o
Thrifty Rent-A-Car System Inc., Corporate Communications Dept.,
CIMS (NU)1020, PO Box 35250, Tulsa, OK 74153-0250. Include a
self-addressed, stamped envelope. Entries must be postmarked by
Aug. 31, 1999, and winners will be announced around Valentine's Day
2000. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Travel Trivia: Once it was Transcontinental and Western Air. What
is it today? (Answer at end of column.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Quotable: ``Please gather all your belongings, including smaller
carbon-based life forms.'' _ A robot spokesmachine at Walt Disney
World's ``Extra-TERROR-estial Encounter.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Today's fractured English lesson: In a Norwegian Lounge: ``Ladies
are requested not to have children in the bar.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Party hearty: It's Mardis Gras time again at Universal Studios
Florida in Orlando. Nightly through March 27, Universal's backlot
streets will be colorfully converted into a street party featuring
a parade with 14 floats and props direct from New Orleans, as well
as 400 participants who will throw doubloons and beads to
spectators. Entertainment ranges from the Pointer Sisters to
Journey to Chaka Kahn. What's more, ``N'awlins'' food such as
crawfish, jambalaya, and gumbo will be readily avallable. When it's
all over, more than a million doubloons and beads and 500 pounds of
confetti will have been flung. The festivities are included in the
regular admission price, and for a limited time guests get a free
second day at Universal. For more information, call 407-224-5500. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Claim to fame: Puerto Rico has the world's largest J.C. Penney
store. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Glassy and classy: The instrument is called a glass armonica
(without an ``h'') and it is played with the fingertips to produce
a sweet, almost angelic sound. Carolinn Skyler will play the
instrument, which was invented by Benjamin Franklin, at Historic
Deerfield Feb. 21 at 1:30 p.m. and 3:30 p.m. as part of the
village's big Washington's Birthday celebration. For more
information on the 330-year-old Massachusetts village, call
413-774-5581 or visit www.historic-deerfield.org. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Sign of the times: Len Sampson of Melrose reports seeing an ad for
a New Hampshire beauty shop that read ``Ears Pierced While You
Wait.'' He adds, ``I didn't call to see what to do if I couldn't
wait.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Did you guess it? Of course you did: Trans World Airlines, or TWA.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Send comments and questions to Travel Tidbits, Boston Globe,
Boston, MA 02107. Send e-mail to carpen(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
