its lowest close since Jan. 29, from 2.135 percent on Monday, after
the Finance Ministry says it will resume buying the bonds. By
Sheryl WuDunn.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST (Washington) _ John T. Rose, who was a
senior vice president at Compaq and responsible for all its desktop
computers, will take the stand on Wednesday. In pretrial testimony
made public Tuesday, Rose credits Microsoft with making computers
easier to use, more reliable and less expensive, and he disputes
the Government's characterization of several disagreements with
Microsoft. By Joel Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   ALTAVISTA-ZIP (Boston) _ Compaq Computer's Alta Vista unit buys
Zip2, a private company, for an undisclosed amount. (It says it is
paying more than the $220 million it recently spent for
Shopping.Com.) Zip2, in conjunction with big media companies like
The New York Times, provides localized content on the Internet.
Lisa Napoli.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At midday, the industrial average was up 70
points, or eight-tenths of 1 percent, and the Nasdaq index was up
34 points, or 1.5 percent. Elsewhere, prices rose 1.3 percent in
Tokyo, while the Hong Kong market was closed for a holiday. Shares
were up two-tenths of 1 percent in Frankfurt and 1.7 percent in
London. Prices fell four-tenths of 1 percent in Brazil and rose
nine-tenths of 1 percent in Mexico. On the American debt market,
the long bond was up 26/32 point, with the yield at 5.37 percent.
By Robert D. Hershey Jr.
</P>
