<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESSS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE STREET OVERTAKES BANKBOSTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ They're number two!
</P>
<P>
   With barely a notice, State Street Corp. has eclipsed BankBoston
Corp. to become Boston's second most-valuable public financial
services company, trailing only Fleet Financial Group.
</P>
<P>
   It happened for the first time months ago and has not been the
case every day since. But the value of State Street's stock has
exceeded that of BankBoston during the vast majority of that time.
As of Monday, Wall Street valued State Street at $11.5 billion,
about $900 million more than BankBoston.
</P>
<P>
   That says something about BankBoston, which only a decade ago
was still New England's undisputed banking leader. It says even
more about State Street, which has been known for most of its 200
years as a tony but second-tier bank.
</P>
<P>
   Call it the triumph of the fee model. State Street has been
transformed for years now, by decisions made even earlier, to wade
into the back-shop world of securities processing and caretaking
for giant institutional investors. Only about a tenth of its money
is made today from the conventional banking business of earning an
interest rate spread between borrowing and lending.
</P>
<P>
   State Street still trails BankBoston in many ways. The most
important: BankBoston remains a lot more profitable. BankBoston
earned $792 million even after some special expenses last year,
while State Street made $436 million.
</P>
<P>
   But State Street has convinced Wall Street its kind of business
is more valuable. Its shares are priced at about 24 times earnings
expected for 1999, within a whisker of the earnings multiple
awarded Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 stocks and much more than the 13 to
15 multiple of a typical commercial bank.
</P>
<P>
   BankBoston's stock trades at just over 11 times earnings, dead
last among the 24 big stocks in the Keefe Breyette &AMP; Woods Bank
Index. The weakness in comparison to other commercial banks is
mostly a reflection of investor fears over the Latin American
economies where BankBoston does business.
</P>
<P>
   BankBoston stock could bounce back with a South American revival
(it was worth 60 percent more just seven months ago) and possibly
become more valuable than State Street again, at least for a while.
But a gap in earnings multiples that drastically favors State
Street stock is unlikely to disappear and makes the outcome of any
long-term value comparison almost certain.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't that State Street's fee business is more predictable,
though that helps. It isn't even because the fee business is a lot
less risky way to make a buck than lending money, though that helps
a lot.
</P>
<P>
   State Street's real blessing is that it decided to serve a
business with a truly explosive growth rate. As mutual funds and
other institutions built up trillions of dollars under management,
State Street prospered with them.
</P>
<P>
   State Street's earnings per share have grown at 16 percent,
compounded annually, for the last 15 years. Chief financial officer
Ronald O'Kelley says State Street researched every stock with a
beginning market value of at least $200 million that had earnings
in each of those same 15 years and found only two companies that
did better: Wal-Mart Stores Inc. and Coca-Cola Co.
</P>
<P>
   State Street executives insist they barely noticed that their
company's shares became more valuable than those at BankBoston, an
unlikely claim meant to emphasize a point. State Street doesn't
think of itself as a bank at all and would dearly like to break
away from any such comparison.
</P>
<P>
   As much of a premium as State Street stock wins compared to
other banks, it's not doing nearly so well in other leagues. State
Street wants to be thought of as an information technology company
and, in that field, it would be cheap.
</P>
<P>
   State Street executives would much rather compare themselves to
Automatic Data Processing Inc. than BankBoston, or to Electronic
Data Systems Inc. rather than Fleet. ADP shares sell for 36 times
earnings. EDS, which has been under pressure lately, sells for
nearly 26 times profits.
</P>
<P>
   O'Kelley said State Street is attracting a following among stock
analysts besides the usual bank-research crowd, like information
technology analyst Patrick Burton of Lehman Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   State Street's fee-based business neatly avoids the lending
risks that go with economic cycles, but it is saddled with another
kind of uncertainty: technology investment cycles.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing when to plow money into new equipment, how much to
spend, and what to choose are big-ticket decisions for companies
like State Street. Bad timing or bad choices can be a disaster.
Even the good decisions are expensive.
</P>
<P>
   State Street estimates it will have spent $200 million on Year
2000 expenses before it is done, an investment it has yet to recoup
in its normal course of business.
</P>
<P>
   The company faced a less expensive problem when the Euro was
born on New Year's Day, but State Street still had to pull 4,000
Boston-area employees into the office over that weekend to convert
all its clients.
</P>
<P>
   Considering the rewards, it's not such a bad risk to take.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre can be reached by e-mail at boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
