<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON   (Editors note: This week, The Chronicle's panel of professional
tasters tries whole milk.) 
  
 
 
 TASTER'S CHOICE:  
 Got Milk?  
 Lucerne Rises to the Top 
 &HT;       
   
   
 By Robin Davis  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
 &LR; When it comes to milk, not many of us search out brands. It's such
a staple ingredient that we tend to buy whatever's available at our
neighborhood market _ which is frequently a house brand _ or we may
just buy what's on sale.
</P>
<P>
   But according to today's tasting panel, different brands of milk
taste distinctively different. The panel tasted nine brands of
whole milk (the results of a nonfat-milk tasting will be published
in an upcoming issue), and scores varied a great deal.
</P>
<P>
   Panelists agreed that their taste in milk comes from personal
preference. Some like mild flavors; others like stronger, grassier
notes.
</P>
<P>
   Top honors went to &UR; Lucerne  &LR; (1/2 gallon, $2.20 at Safeway),
which scored high enough to make the Hall of Fame for products
earning 80 points or more. One panelist gave it a perfect score of
20 and called it ``picture perfect for taste.'' Three others
particularly liked the rich, creamy flavor, but another panelist
thought it tasted too sweet. Four would buy it; one might.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Clover Stornetta &LR;  (1/2 gallon, $1.89 at Whole Foods) took
second place. One panelist labeled it thin and plain-tasting, and
another detected a slight bitter aftertaste. But three liked the
flavor and richness. Four would buy it; one would not.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Castle Creamery  &LR; (1/2 gallon, $2.29 at Andronico's) scored just
three points lower. Panelists picked up both buttery and nutty
flavors. Two would buy it, and three might buy it.
</P>
<P>
   Fourth place went to  &UR; Berkeley Farms &LR;  (1/2 gallon, $2.09-$2.29
at many supermarkets). Three panelists complained that it wasn't as
rich as other brands, but they liked the flavor. One panelist
described the taste as ``bland and thin without much character.''
Three would buy it, one might buy it, and one would not.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Dairy Glen  &LR; (1 gallon, $3.67 at Safeway) came in a close fifth.
Three panelists noted a slight grassy taste, but another thought it
was rich, with good flavors. One would buy it, three might and one
would not.
</P>
<P>
   Panelists were divided on  &UR; Straus &LR;  (1/2 gallon, $3.29 at many
supermarkets), which was also the most expensive brand tasted. Two
panelists thought it had an off flavor, and another described the
taste as ``mineral.'' But one panelist liked its character, and
another thought it was less sweet and easier to drink than the
other brands. Two would buy it; three would not.
</P>
<P>
   Three brands scored too low to rate: Horizon, Sunnyside and
Michael's Organic.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; Robin Davis is a Chronicle staff writer.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; Panelists were Dan Bowe, associate culinary director, Center for
Culinary Development; Patricia Hart, dietitian and consultant;
Donna Katzl, chef-owner, Cafe For All Seasons, San Francisco;
Roland Passot, chef-owner, La Folie in San Francisco and Left Bank
in Larkspur and Menlo Park; and Kirk Webber, chef-owner, Cafe Kati,
San Francisco. All products are tasted blind.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
