A7051 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WARSH-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      02-16 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIRTY HANDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Now that the impeachment trial is over, is it possible to
pardon everyone involved in it? To pretend that it never happened
and go back to discussing tax cuts and Social Security?
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately not. The principal actors all have dirty hands. To
put this mess behind us will require an election cycle or, more
likely, two.
</P>
<P>
   What should be the priority of Congress in the next two years?
The answer is campaign finance reform. Uncertainty over the next
election may block action on big issues like Social Security and
health care. Nothing else on the legislative agenda can compete.
Citizens are disgusted with the power of back-door money in
politics; even corporate America is alarmed.
</P>
<P>
   Rivers of newspaper ink have been spilled to describe the
various new specimens of political corruption in the 1996
presidential election, the first time the Democrats and Republicans
alike exploited the soft-money loophole in a big way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Soft money'' is that which is raised by the national political
parties on their own behalf _ as opposed to the ``hard money'' that
candidates raise themselves. The size of the latter is strictly
regulated by legislation enacted in the wake of the Watergate
scandal in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   On ``soft money,'' however, there are no limits. There haven't
been since the loophole was first seriously exploited in the
presidential election in 1988. The national parties then turn
around and spend the cash on ``issue ads'' on behalf of the
candidates, more or less the way the candidates would have spent it
on themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Soft money spending tripled in 1996. Illegal foreign donors
showed up in significant numbers for the first time, especially
Asians _ in addition to the usual corporations, rich people, and
labor unions.
</P>
<P>
   Impeachment-minded Republicans _ and a few misguided reformers _
have been clamoring for Attorney General Janet Reno to appoint yet
another special prosecutor to examine the Democrats' fund-raising
practices, especially those of Vice President Al Gore. Wisely, Reno
refused. Another freelance moralist roaming over the Washington
landscape is not what America needs.
</P>
<P>
   What we need instead is the Shays-Meehan bill. This measure
would ban all soft money and apply to political parties and
independent groups the same stringent federal guidelines that now
regulate candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Co-sponsored by Representatives Christopher Shays, a Connecticut
Republican, and Marty Meehan, a Massachusetts Democrat, the bill
passed the House last summer by a strong majority of 252 to 179.
Sixty-one Republicans crossed over to vote with the majority,
petitioning House Speaker Newt Gingrich to compel a vote.
</P>
<P>
   It was then immediately sidetracked in the Senate by majority
leader Trent Lott, who bottled it up with the threat of filibuster.
The Republicans' drive toward an impeachment trial provided cover.
</P>
<P>
   But Senators John McCain, an Arizona Republican, and Russell
Feingold, a Wisconsin Democrat, backers of a similar bill, have
promised to bring their measure up again. It's just possible
they'll have the 60 votes necessary to circumvent a filibuster. The
majority may remain in the House.
</P>
<P>
   And that's where House Speaker Dennis Hastert, an Illinois
Republican, comes in. The amiable former wrestling coach, who was
catapulted to prominence when Newt Gingrich and Bob Livingston
resigned the post in quick succession, told reporters earlier this
month that he wanted to keep campaign finance reform on the back
burner _ until health care, tax cuts, and Social Security issues
have been attended to. That's a polite way of saying ``Not if I can
help it.''
</P>
<P>
   Will Hastert and his allies succeed in blocking the nationwide
interest in campaign finance reform? That's the single most
interesting question in Washington after the impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Warsh is a Globe columnist; his e-mail address is
warsh(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
