<DOCNO> NYT19990216.0150 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-16 14:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7083 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AGING-ARABS-TIMEBOMB-     02-16 1029
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AGING-ARABS-TIMEBOMB-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT HAPPENS WHEN ARAFAT, ASSAD, FAHD AND MUBARAK DIE?  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This excellent 850-word ``separate buy'' article is from the
current (week beginning 13 Feb. 1999) Economist magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate in New York at 1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333, or
fax us at 212-499-3382.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Intimations of mortality, hard to avoid at any funeral, were
inescapable at King Hussein's.
</P>
<P>
   The large and diverse collection of world leaders who came to
Amman this week to pay their respects to an extraordinary man
included the elderly, the frail and the one-man rulers of several
volatile places that have no constitutional line of succession.
</P>
<P>
   Some of them, such as Syria's Hafez Assad and the Palestinians'
Yasser Arafat, combine in quite a perilous way all three
attributes.
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks ago King Hussein himself was in this bracket. He
caused consternation with his last despotic act, emerging from
hospital to sack Hassan, his brother and longtime heir, and replace
him with his soldier son, Abdullah.
</P>
<P>
   Commentators, The Economist included, brooded on the safety-nets
that would have been afforded by a genuine constitutional monarchy,
the folly of making oneself indispensable _ and the added folly of
inadequate provision for succession.
</P>
<P>
   That said, the early signals from Amman are promising.
</P>
<P>
   At the funeral, heads were bowed in honor of a king whose warmth
of heart and spirit even enemies respected. The new successor
conducted himself impeccably and so, most honorably, did his uncle,
Prince Hassan.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan has few natural advantages _ a sandpit of a place lying
like a bunker between states that hate each other _ but it gives no
impression of being about to fall apart.
</P>
<P>
   What, however, of the others? What chance that the handover of
power in Syria, Saudi Arabia, Egypt or Palestine will be as smooth?
</P>
<P>
   Take no bets on it. The rulers of these countries share a
certain myopia: all of them are despotic to one degree or another;
all are hitting 70, yet behave as though they were immortal,
without need of clear-cut succession plans.
</P>
<P>
   Confusion in any of these places would profoundly affect the
region. Saudi Arabia is the odd one out in that its king, Fahd, is
already disabled and the kingdom is competently run by Crown Prince
Abdullah.
</P>
<P>
   But the Saudi Abdullah is himself in his mid-70s, and it is far
from clear which of his extended family of brothers and
half-brothers will eventually take over from him _ or whether the
others will accept the choice.
</P>
<P>
   Egypt's Hosni Mubarak is confidently expected to be ``elected''
to a fourth six-year presidency this October, when he will be 71.
</P>
<P>
   Although his own role as vice-president helped Egypt to a smooth
transition when Anwar Sadat was assassinated in 1981, Mubarak has
chosen not to appoint a deputy. He prefers, it seems, to have the
driving seat to himself, without a potential rival fighting for the
wheel.
</P>
<P>
   He looks robust, but what happens if he does not survive his
next term? Some Egyptians wonder, not entirely in jest, whether he
might not, in a monarchical way, be grooming a son.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, this is what Syria's President Assad has long been
doing. After his favored son, Basil, died in a car crash, he turned
to Bashar, a former ophthalmologist, who is thought to be much less
of a chip off the harsh old block.
</P>
<P>
   The president may not be as frail as his gaunt looks suggest
but, when he does go, will Syrians quietly accept an Assad dynasty?
</P>
<P>
   And what of Arafat in this macabre actuarial exercise? At 69, he
looks poorly, and his trembling lip suggests the onset of
Parkinson's disease.
</P>
<P>
   True, he takes good care of his health and his capacity for hard
work seems unimpaired. Moreover, he has shown survival powers that
match or surpass King Hussein's. But how reassuring is that, in the
circumstances?
</P>
<P>
   To complicate matters he holds two posts: president of the
Palestinian Authority (PA) and chairman of the Palestine Liberation
Organization (PLO).
</P>
<P>
   The man most likely to succeed him at the PA is still the
Palestinians' chief negotiator, Mahmoud Abbas (also known as Abu
Mazen). But West Bankers and Gazans, having nudged noses with
Israeli democracy, may not be content to have an old PLO hand
imposed on them.
</P>
<P>
   The dream of democracy was one of the reasons why they did not,
after Israel occupied their land in 1967, want King Hussein's
Hashemite rule back again. Instead, they got Arafat's erratic
authoritarianism.
</P>
<P>
   Worse off by far are the Palestinian diaspora, whose members
have nobody to represent them but the PLO, a body that once made
history but has long since passed its best-before date.
</P>
<P>
   Will anything be left of the PLO when Arafat, whose name is
synonymous with it, joins his maker? The outlook for the hundreds
of thousands of Palestinian refugees who live stateless and ignored
in countries such as Lebanon is grim.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings matters back to Jordan, and its kings. Hashemite
rule was not the Palestinians' first choice, but refugees who
crossed the Jordan River were automatically given Jordanian
citizenship and the rights that go with it.
</P>
<P>
   Constitutional rule should be King Abdullah's goal, but
continuing his father's civilized, intelligent conduct would be a
splendid start. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this excellent 850-word article, it must be purchased
from the New York Times Syndicate in New York at 1-800-972-3550 or
212-499-3333, or fax us at 212-499-3382.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: Please note that this article is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
