<HEADER>
A7119 &Cx1f; tad-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLACKHISTORY-BJT-ADVI     02-16 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACKHISTORY-BJT-ADVISORY-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   The following stories are part of a five-day series for Black
History Month. Stories that already have moved are marked as such;
the rest of the stories will move later in the week. The stories
will move in the (n) National category.
</P>
<P>
   The contact person at the Dayton Daily News is Ann Pettee,
937-225-2134. At Cox News Service, copy editor Chante LaGon can be
reached at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   DAY ONE
</P>
<P>
   BLACKHISTORY-VOICES-1900 _ DAYTON, Ohio _ America in the early
1900s was a nation in metamorphosis. Yet some things appeared stuck
in the 19th century. The nation's blacks, with more than 50 years
of emancipation behind them, were still brutally segregated and
subject to racial violence. More than 70 were lynched in 1920.
Abject conditions in the South prompted many to come north,
launching what would come to be known as The Great Migration.
George Cooper: ``The realization of racism came on me in a gradual
way. I think it came on most kids in a gradual way, both white and
black.'' Ellen Lee Jackson: ``Dayton was a prejudiced place. As far
as the jobs were, you didn't get to have the good jobs like they
have now.'' Yvonne Walker-Taylor: ``I liked school because I was an
only child and going to school was just my piece of cake.'' Ned
Wood: ``In the Depression, life sure changed. We lost our farm in
1931. One year, we had boll weevils.'' (Keilman, Dayton Daily News)
103. (Keilman, Dayton Daily News) WITH PHOTOS. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   BLACKHISTORY-BIO _ DAYTON, Ohio _ Biographies of the four
octogenarians in this series. This element should be carried each
day of the series. (Dayton Daily News) 7. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   BLACKHISTORY-TIMELINE1900 _ Timeline of events significant to
African-Americans in 1890-1939. (Jones, Dayton Daily News) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   DAY TWO
</P>
<P>
   BLACKHISTORY-WAR _ DAYTON, Ohio _ President Franklin D.
Roosevelt issued an executive order banning discrimination in
defense industries and government jobs. And though he maintained
segregation in the armed forces, he allowed some blacks to become
officers for the first time. One of them was George Cooper. Black
forces fought well. On the homefront, Ellen Lee Jackson continued
working in Dayton while two of her brothers served. Yvonne
Walker-Taylor, who had married a Tuskeegee Airman, moved to a
military base in Alabama. George Cooper never made it to combat.
(Keilman, Dayton Daily News) 30. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   w/BLACKHISTORY-VOICES-WAR _ DAYTON, Ohio _ Dialogues culled from
extensive sit-down interviews with each individual. (Keilman,
Dayton Daily News) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   BLACKHISTORY-BIO _ DAYTON, Ohio _ Biographies of the four
octogenarians in this series. This element should be carried each
day of the series. (Dayton Daily News) 7. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   DAY THREE
</P>
<P>
   BLACKHISTORY-POSTWAR _ DAYTON, Ohio _ The post-war years brought
an unprecedented rush of prosperity to America. Returning veterans
flooded into colleges, corporations and factories, their brainpower
and labor transforming the nation into the world's premiere
economic superpower. Yet most of the country's black citizens were
denied a fair piece of this bountiful pie. Many were no longer
willing to accept that. (Keilman, Dayton Daily News) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   w/BLACKHISTORY-VOICES-POSTWAR _ DAYTON, Ohio _ Dialogues culled
from extensive sit-down interviews with each individual. (Keilman,
Dayton Daily News) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   BLACKHISTORY-TIMELINE-POSTWAR _ Timeline of events significant
to African-Americans in 1960-1969. (Jones, Dayton Daily News) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   BLACKHISTORY-BIO _ DAYTON, Ohio _ Biographies of the four
octogenarians in this series. This element should be carried each
day of the series. (Dayton Daily News) 7. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   DAY FOUR
</P>
<P>
   BLACKHISTORY-VOICES-RIGHTS _ DAYTON, Ohio _ The end of the 1960s
marked the completion of the civil rights movement's most urgent
battles. The once radical crusade had become mainstream, and many
blacks reaped the benefits. African-Americans began claiming more
seats of power, from Congress to corporate boards. New generations
found opportunities their parents could scarcely imagine. One of
Ned Wood's sons became a surgeon. George Cooper's daughter became a
law professor.
</P>
<P>
   w/BLACKHISTORY-DIALOGUES-RIGHTS _ DAYTON, Ohio _ Dialogues
culled from extensive sit-down interviews with each individual.
(Keilman, Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   BLACKHISTORY-TIMELINE-RIGHTS _ A timeline of significant events
for African-Americans from 1970 to the present. (Jones, Dayton
Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   BLACKHISTORY-WEBSITES _ A long list of Internet sites that tie
into this series. (Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   DAY FIVE
</P>
<P>
   BLACKHISTORY-VOICES-PIQUA _ DAYTON, Ohio _ Acceptance into Piqua
society came slow and hard for black families at the height of the
integration movement during the early 1960s. But some black
families, including the Elmer V. Harris family, didn't back down to
segregationist pressures and smoothed the road to integration for
future generations. (Keilman, Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   w/BLACKHISTORY-ORAL _ DAYTON, Ohio _ Collecting an oral history
can be as easy as sitting down with a tape recorder or notebook.
But those who have done it say it is far more effective if you
follow a few tips.
</P>
<P>
   BLACKHISTORY-BOOKS _ Books that can help with family history.
(Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
