<HEADER>
A7134 &Cx1f; tad-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPOT-BJT17-COX     02-16 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPOT-BJT17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Wednesday, Feb. 17,
1999.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   JOURNAL-RUSSIA _ ST. PETERSBURG, Russia _ Not tonight honey,
they're showing ``Planet of the Apes.'' Zookeepers in St.
Petersburg have learned the hard way about the power of television.
Hoping TV would show orangutans Monika and Rabuhow to be good
parents, zoo officials rigged up a set outside their cage to show
them videos on proper childrearing. But Rabu, the male orangutan,
became so captivated with TV that he has been ignoring his mate,
who was upset over being neglected. The TV must go, but zookeepers
now fret that the pair is so addicted, their incapacity for passion
may only deepen with video withdrawal. (Holmes, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in both the International and Commentary categories.
</P>
<P>
   HONDURAS _ To bring relief to some of the most remote and
hurricane-ravaged areas of Honduras, Westley Wiles of Missionair
has been flying his 1966 Cessna on a wing and a prayer, often
landing in cow pastures full of ruts and on dangerous gravel
runways. As a result, his plane, and especially his propeller, has
taken a beating. Having heard of his plight in a recent DDN story
about local relief efforts in Honduras, the McCauley airplane parts
company in Vandalia has custom-built a new propeller for Wiley and
is donating it to the cause. They will be boxing it up for delivery
today. (DeBrosse, Dayton Daily News). 8-10.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   JASPERDEATH-TRIAL _ JASPER, Texas _ Testimony begins Tuesday
with lawyers' openings statements in the dragging death trial of
Bill King, the first of three East Texas men to go on trial for a
murder that captured the nation because of its brutality. (Gamino,
Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   DEAD-DOGS _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ What killed the racing
greyhounds around the country? Latest tests indicate it was an
unusual form of a viral respiratory disease, not kennel cough.
Necropsies of three dead dogs, including Chances Are from West Palm
Beach, showed the dogs had severe internal bleeding. One of the
dead dogs had bacterial pneumonia associated with `e. coli' as a
complication of the suspected viral disease. Researchers are still
trying to isolate the exact virus. So what are kennel clubs doing?
(Donald, Palm Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   BAXTER-COLUMN _ The notion that public disgust with the
impeachment year might generate a big turnover in the next
congressional elections is being discounted both by Republican
strategists, who have reason to hope it won't be so, and Democrats,
who want to hedge their bets. All these predictions have the
classic earmarks of capital self-denial. Within the Beltway it is
hard to see this or admit it, but the most obvious impact of the
impeachment year is the profound toll it has taken on the prestige
of Washington itself. (Baxter, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
MONDAY.
</P>
