NYT-02-16-99 1451EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990216.0176 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-16 14:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7145 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAMBODIA-BOX-$ADV21-C     02-16 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMBODIA-BOX-$ADV21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A KING'S UP-AND-DOWN CAREER: PLAYBOY PRINCE TO PRISONER TO
PEACEMAKER
 &HT;    With CAMBODIA-ROYAL-$ADV21.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (k) Commentary
categories.
 &HT;    By JOSEPH ALBRIGHT and MARCIA KUNSTEL 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHNOM PENH, Cambodia _ These are among the twists and turns in
King Norodom Sihanouk's life:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  April 1941 _ The French-educated prince is placed on the
throne at the age of 18 by Vichy French colonial administrators who
considered him pliable.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  1940s _ Sihanouk takes his cousin Norodom(CQ) as his first
official wife and forms liaisons with scores of palace concubines.
``As king, we were not allowed to have more than one queen, but we
were allowed hundreds of mistresses,'' Sihanouk would later tell an
interviewer.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  1952 _ Sihanouk divorces Norodom and takes up with Monique
Izzi, the daughter of a French-Italian father and a Cambodian
mother, whom he spotted in a beauty contest. Monique would become
his lifelong companion and is now his Queen.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  1953 _ Sihanouk travels to France and convinces a weakened
French government to grant Cambodia independence. He remains bitter
at the United States because the U.S. State Department gave him a
brush-off.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  March 1955 _ The king dumbfounds Cambodia by abdicating in
favor of his father. Retaining his princely prerogatives as
``Citizen Sihanouk,'' he would rule Cambodia as an autocratic prime
minister denying Cambodians democratic rights, but giving them
nearly 15 years of peace, prosperity and international prestige.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  April 1955 _ Resisting American pressure to join the Southeast
Asia Treaty Organization (SEATO), Sihanouk becomes a Cold War
neutralist. He reaches world prominence at the Afro-Asian
nonaligned conference in Bandung and befriends Yugoslavia's Tito,
India's Nehru, Indonesia's Sukarno and China's Zhou Enlai.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  1963 _ Angry at American intervention in South Vietnam,
Sihanouk calls on Cambodians to wear red arm bands in celebration
of the assassination of U.S. President John F. Kennedy and the
deaths of two right-wing Southeast Asian dictators. The three will
``all meet in hell,'' Sihanouk exclaims.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  1965 _ Bored with statecraft, Sihanouk throws himself into
cinematography, horseback riding and playing jazz saxophone. In the
next four years, he writes, directs, and produces nine feature
films, sometimes acting the romantic lead opposite his wife
Monique.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  By 1966 _ Sihanouk makes a secret military alliance with North
Vietnam, under which the North Vietnamese win permission to station
troops inside Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  October 1967 _ Sihanouk signals a warming with the United
States by receiving the widowed Mrs. Jacqueline Kennedy in
Cambodia's famed temples at Angkor Wat.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  January 1968 _ Sihanouk tells U.S. diplomat Chester Bowles
that he wouldn't protest if American troops crossed into Cambodia
in ``hot pursuit'' of enemy Vietnamese forces.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  March 1969 _ With Sihanouk silent, President Nixon orders a
secret operation in which B-52s drop 100,000 tons of explosives on
Cambodian villages and Viet Cong strongholds in eastern Cambodia
over four years.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  March 1970 _ Sihanouk is overthrown in a military coup led by
Cambodian Gen. Lon Nol. Though the right-wing general had tacit
approval from mid-level U.S. intelligence contacts, no clear
evidence has emerged to support Sihanouk's insistence that the CIA
overthrew him.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  1970 _ Sihanouk goes into exile as guest of the Chinese and
North Korean rulers. He serves as figurehead leader of an alliance
of pro-Sihanouk and pro-Chinese guerrillas fighting against the Lon
Nol government. Sihanouk nicknames the latter group the ``Khmer
Rouge'' (Red Cambodians).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  April 1975 _ Ultra-Maoist Khmer Rouge guerrillas seize the
Cambodian capitol Phnom Penh, ordering a mass evacuation for forced
labor in the countryside. A murderous reign of terror begins under
the leadership of Pol Pot in which up to 2 million people perish.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  September 1975 _ Pressured by the Chinese, the Pol Pot regime
allows Sihanouk to return to Cambodia as its nominal head of state.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  March 1976 _ Upset by sights of destruction, Sihanouk tries to
resign and return to Beijing, but the Pol Pot regime refuses.
Instead, he and Monique begin three years of house arrest inside
the royal palace in Phnom Penh. Sihanouk later says that the Khmer
Rouge occupation led to the deaths of his five children, 14
grandchildren and four cousins.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  1979 _ Vietnamese invaders defeat Pol Pot, capture Phnom Penh
and free Sihanouk, who flies out to resume his exile in Beijing.
Sihanouk becomes head of a guerrilla coalition that includes
remnants of the defeated Khmer Rouge. The coalition, now backed
both by the United States and China, aims to end Vietnam's military
occupation of Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  1991 _ With the collapse of the Soviet Union, Vietnamese
forces pull out of Cambodia. Cambodian factions agree to a United
Nations call for a cease-fire. The following month, Sihanouk
brokers a crucial agreement among the factions that leads to a
peace settlement, along with the decision to place him back on the
throne.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
