<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990216.0179 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-16 14:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7150 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAMBODIA-GENOCIDE-021     02-16 1075
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMBODIA-GENOCIDE-0216-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ATTN Cox EDs: Resending for those who did not use it.
 &HT;    CAMBODIANS DEMAND _ AND FEAR _ JUSTICE FOR KHMER ROUGE KILLERS
 &HT;    Optional add begins at 600 words.
 &HT;    A PHOTO for use with this story is available in the
International folder on the Cox server and also through DTI on the
Washington Bureau graphics desk at the Atlanta location.
 &HT;    EDs NOTE TIME ELEMENT: Story best used week of Feb. 14-21,
before the UN panel announces recommendation.
 &HT;    By MARCIA KUNSTEL and JOSEPH ALBRIGHT 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHNOM PENH, Cambodia _ Sitting on a bamboo-slatted bench, widow
But Lin crumbled dried lumps of cooked rice in a basket and talked
about what she wants to happen to the Khmer Rouge leaders who
brutalized her country.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we arrest them, we should cut off their heads,'' said the
52-year-old. ``In fact, if they asked me to do this, I am willing
to do it myself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lost six children from starvation and my husband and parents
were killed,'' she went on. ``I am still alone today. We cannot
forget that regime. No Cambodian people can forget.''
</P>
<P>
   Such an outburst seemed incongruous from this fragile-boned
woman in simple clothes and rubber sandals, a poor woman who saves
burned rice.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years after the Khmer Rouge fell from power, a day of
judging them approaches. But Lin hopes it will put her anger to
rest.
</P>
<P>
   A United Nations team of three legal experts is scheduled this
month to recommend to Secretary General Kofi Annan whether to start
action against the remaining Khmer Rouge leaders living openly in
Cambodia. Some form of international tribunal likely will be
proposed to hear evidence against the men who masterminded the
madness that left as many as two million Cambodians dead in less
than four years, from 1975 to 1979.
</P>
<P>
   However, not all Cambodians, including the leaders of this wary
country, view the prospect of trials with the same longing as the
widow But Lin.
</P>
<P>
   Even those who believe that only justice can release the ghosts
shackling their country often fear justice well might bring new
dangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must be cautious and consider how to avoid a civil war
before holding any trial,'' said Sau Sisovanna, a Cambodian
economics professor and government adviser, who sadly described
Cambodians as ``hostages to fear.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact that 3,500 wiry guerrilla fighters finally abandoned
their Khmer Rouge jungle camps this month, switching allegiance and
uniforms to the Cambodian army, provided little relief from that
fear.
</P>
<P>
   These were believed to comprise the last sizable groups of
hard-line rebels holding out in jungle military bases. Cambodian
defense officials hailed their ``integration'' into the regular
army as the final dissolution of Khmer Rouge power.
</P>
<P>
   Yet photos of a ceremony in Anlong Veng, a rebel center in north
Cambodia, showed some fighters putting on their new army uniforms
over their old guerrilla fatigues.
</P>
<P>
   The Cambodia Daily quoted one ex-guerrilla as pronouncing in one
breath, ``The Khmer Rouge is dead,'' but in the next adding that he
would keep his old uniform ``just in case.''
</P>
<P>
   Some rebel commanders among the defecting troops were not
convinced they would remain government adherents, admitting they
would be tempted to go back to the bush if their old Khmer Rouge
leaders called on them for support.
</P>
<P>
   The key leaders now are living openly in Pailin, a town on the
Thai border the government virtually ceded them as an enclave when
they began agreeing to lay down their weapons in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   These are the men most likely to face any international
judgment, and some have made it clear they will not do so quietly.
</P>
<P>
   Senior leader Leng Sary, once the number three Khmer Rouge
commander, warned that any trial could have disturbing
consequences. His new political union in Pailin issued a statement
that ``in order to make our nation live in peace'' the courts
``should not try this or that person.''
</P>
<P>
   Khmer Rouge were ultra-Maoist communists, who emptied the cities
and forced Cambodians into groveling peasant lives. They killed
almost one-sixth of the population through execution and torture,
and left others to die from starvation, exhaustion and disease.
</P>
<P>
   The Khmer Rouge were ousted when Vietnamese troops swooped into
Cambodia in 1979, but thousands who were not killed or captured
continued fighting from jungle hideouts.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Most Cambodians interviewed believed the remaining Khmer Rouge
could not mount a large-scale civil war today, but feared they
could cause plenty of trouble in an unsettled, poverty-stricken
nation that can only pay its teachers the equivalent of (US)$20 a
month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Small troops cannot make war, but small troops with a will to
survive, to save their lives, could be a terrible source of
suffering for the country,'' said Ok Serei Sopheak, coordinator of
the Cambodian Center for Conflict Resolution.
</P>
<P>
   Cambodia's autocratic Prime Minister Hun Sen has tried to break
the back of Khmer Rouge power by luring leaders and fighters to
defect from their fighting units and peacefully rejoin society,
demanding no accounting from them for the bloody tyranny they
imposed.
</P>
<P>
   His policy of appeasing them finally drew protests at home and
abroad last December, when two of the last major Khmer Rouge
leaders left their jungle hideouts. The prime minister treated them
like visiting dignitaries and suggested the past should be
forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   After a public outcry, Hun Sen has vacillated over whether and
how the Khmer Rouge should be tried. Even if there is an
international tribunal, Cambodian government accord will be crucial
to making it work.
</P>
<P>
   Many here believe a trial is essential not only to reconcile the
past, but to assure the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``The culture of violence is in the mentality of our people,''
said Thun Sary, 47, the president of a Cambodian human rights group
called Ad Hoc(CQ). ``Impunity is the precedent.''
</P>
<P>
   He believes a trial of Khmer Rouge principals is necessary if
Cambodia ever hopes to rein in its rogue police and military who
still torture and kill, if it expects to end official corruption
and judicial partiality.
</P>
<P>
   ``People still feel, 'If we have the force, we can do
anything,''' he said. ``We need to do something about this case.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
