<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TET-OFFENSIVE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIETNAM VETERAN HONORED FOR ROLE IN KEY BATTLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SIG CHRISTENSON  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Thirty-one years after the Tet offensive in
Vietnam, Air Force veteran Alonzo J. Coggins still bears burn
scars, graying hair covers a bullet-size crease in his skull and a
slice of metal remains embedded under the skin above his right
knee.
</P>
<P>
   And there's no forgetting the sight and sound of swarms of enemy
soldiers in black uniforms advancing in the dead of night. But it
could have been worse.
</P>
<P>
   Bunker 051 was a front-row seat to the Tet offensive that
Coggins, then an airman 1st class, inexplicably survived, even
after waves of enemy attacks, tank and mortar fire, and deadly
aerial assaults ordered by American commanders desperate to avoid
defeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was the only one who got out alive,'' Coggins, 53, said
Friday. ``God placed angels around me to get out of the hell that I
went through.''
</P>
<P>
   A wily survivor, Coggins was an obscure hero until Lt. Gen.
David W. McIlvoy awarded him the Silver Star and Purple Heart
Friday at Lackland Air Force Base near San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   As a mostly military crowd of 250 cheered and applauded, Coggins
followed his salute of McIlvoy with a wave of a hand, followed by a
thumbs-up and a big smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something I'm going to treasure for the rest of my
life,'' Coggins, a retired railroad machinist from Jamaica, N.Y.,
told the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   He received the medals years ago in the mail, but never received
them in a formal presentation as typically done by the Air Force.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an emotional day,'' said McIlvoy, vice commander of
the Air Education and Training Command at Randolph Air Force Base
near New Braunfels, Texas, and a veteran pilot of B-52 raids over
Hanoi.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just an experience, a saga, that's a part of our
history,'' said Brig. Gen. Richard A. Coleman, the Air Force
Security Forces Center commander and a Vietnam veteran.
</P>
<P>
   ``And today this event recaptures some of the dedication and
sacrifice that some of those guys made, because Mr. Coggins here
was the only guy to come out of that bunker alive,'' Coleman said.
</P>
<P>
   The battle for the Tan Son Nhut Air Base just northwest of
Saigon began around 3:30 a.m. Jan. 31, 1968, as a force of more
than 1,500 North Vietnamese and Viet Cong waded into a smaller
group of Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Troops with the 377th Security Police Squadron had been placed
on red alert only hours earlier after Lt. Col. Billy Jack Carter
and then-Maj. Carl Bender agreed that an attack was imminent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt they were going to sucker us into something,'' Bender
said.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next eight furious hours of battle, Bunker 051 would be
a vortex of violence, with Coggins first fighting, then playing
dead.
</P>
<P>
   The 21-year-old airman was manning the bunker with four others
when the North Vietnamese broke the annual holiday truce by
launching the huge Tet offensive.
</P>
<P>
   Coggins said enemy troops opened the battle with mortar rounds,
blasting a nearby bunker.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could see and hear them as they walked across a rice
paddy,'' he said. ``It was scary, very scary. You were in a fixed
position. What could you do?''
</P>
<P>
   Coggins and his men fought back and radioed information that
helped commanders launch a counterattack. They battled until the
bunker was hit by enemy rocket fire, killing everyone but Coggins.
</P>
<P>
   With enemy troops using captured American weapons and a
storehouse of ammunition in the bunker, Bender made the tough
choice to direct an airstrike on the position.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of the hardest decisions I've ever made in my
life,'' said Bender, a 69-year-old retired lieutenant colonel who
presented Coggins with a U.S. flag during Friday's ceremony. ``I
had to assume they were all dead.''
</P>
<P>
   That was a reasonable assumption for Tan Son Nhut survivors Bob
Ott and Pat Bowden. The Americans were outgunned and outmanned, but
``also fought better,'' said Bowden, a retired Air Force chief
master sergeant living in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe we were luckier, too,'' added Ott, then a 28-year-old
staff sergeant now living in Sacramento, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Scarred by metal fragments that broke through his face for more
than 20 years after that battle, the crafty Coggins played dead and
prayed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a total God's miracle that man is alive today,'' Ott
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
