<SLUG> BC-CHINESE-CALENDAR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YEAR 2000 PROBLEM IS OLD STUFF IN THE YEAR OF THE RABBIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JULIE CHAO  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _20John Kim doesn't like to discuss it, but
there's no getting around it: he was born in the Year of the
Rabbit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a pleasure being a bunny,'' he said. ``At work, you
want to be taken seriously. If I was a dragon, I'd be saying,
`Don't mess with me.' But since I'm a bunny, I can't say
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Rabbits do have their charms _ sentimental, emotional, romantic,
smart and persuasive _ and this is their year. By the Chinese lunar
calendar, Tuesday was the first day of 4697, time to say goodbye to
the tiger and hello to the rabbit.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese zodiac, which is also used by Koreans, Vietnamese
and Tibetans, has 12 animals which rotate through a 12-year cycle.
Famous rabbits include Albert Einstein, Andy Warhol, Fidel Castro,
Marie Curie, Helen Hunt and Brad Pitt.
</P>
<P>
   By the Tibetan lunar calendar, which calculates the months
slightly differently, the new year, or Losar, begins Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   On new year's eve, some families make offerings of fruit and
other food to their ancestors at an altar they have set up in their
homes. Tibetans make ``dresil,'' cooked rice with raisins and
sugar, which they consider very auspicious.
</P>
<P>
   While Kim, 23, a youth development coordinator for the Korean
Community Center of the East Bay, is not thrilled with his
astrological sign, he does cop to a few rabbit traits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to admit it: I do like carrots,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And he can hop, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can jump pretty high, you know, on the basketball court,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kim also thinks of himself as pretty romantic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been told that I'm not, but I think I am,'' said Kim, who
lives in Oakland. ``I think you need money to be romantic, and you
need more time. Those are two things I don't have. (Otherwise) I'd
be swooning the ladies.''
</P>
<P>
   Edgar Sung, a San Francisco astrology and feng shui consultant
who also owns a real estate business, predicted instability and
wars this year, just like in the rabbit year of 1939.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be more problems in the Middle East,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As for rabbit people, they will have to make their own luck.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time it's their own sign, it's either very good or very
bad,'' Sung said.
</P>
<P>
   The Vietnamese zodiac differs from its Chinese counterpart by
just one animal: They consider this the Year of the Cat.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Vietnamese like the cat,'' said astrologer Vuong Van
Truong. ``They say the cat is kind, but when they want to catch and
bite, they're very clever and smart.''
</P>
<P>
   Truong is well-known among the Vietnamese in San Francisco, who
often like to consult astrologers for important events, such as
determining an auspicious date for a wedding.
</P>
<P>
   Around Tet, as the Vietnamese new year is known, he expects a
lot of customers who will want to learn what good news may be
coming up and how they can avoid bad news.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a Vietnamese saying: `Good behavior can win
destiny,''' said Truong, whose father and grandfather were both
astrologers in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   Lan Do, a board member of the Vietnamese Community Center in San
Francisco who also runs her own translation business, said she is
not superstitious but does believe she has many of the cat traits
of her zodiac sign, such as being sentimental and romantic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can cry easily if I watch a soap opera or some movie,
especially a drama,'' said Do, 47. ``Most of the time, my children
bring a box of Kleenex next to me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
