<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHONECOMEDY-MERCER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOOD OL' BOY ROY D. MERCER'S ON A RAMPAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Name the funniest men in America.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Seinfeld? Check.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Foxworthy? Yep.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Rock? Adam Sandler? No question.
</P>
<P>
   But to this august list must be added Roy D. Mercer, a
consistently angry good ol' boy from Tulsa who spends much of his
life calling up people who he thinks have wronged him or owe him
money (usually both) and threatening them, often punctuating his
missives with the question ``How big'a boy are ya?'' This is
Roy-speak for not caring how big you are, he's gonna come right
down and put a pop-knot on your head, just as soon as you give him
directions to where you are.
</P>
<P>
   Roy D. Mercer, however, does not, technically, exist. Rather, he
is the brainchild of two Tulsa DJs, Brent Douglas and Phil Stone,
who hit upon the idea of a perpetually angry Everyman as a
ratings-booster for their station, KMOD-FM, back in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1997, Mercer's calls have been collected on five CDs, the
first four of which have sold more than a million combined copies
and stayed on the Billboard comedy chart for 89 straight weeks.
(The fifth came out Jan. 26). Last week's SoundScan report found
all four among the 10 most popular comedy CDs in the country, right
up there with Sandler and Seinfeld and Bill Engvall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a voyeuristic deal,'' says Douglas, who does
Mercer's voice. ``Everybody's been bent out of shape or gotten a
call from somebody who's bent out of shape. And everybody knows
somebody or is related to somebody like Roy.''
</P>
<P>
   Roy began life as a composite of various uncles and dads and
cousins.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been hearing `How big'a boy are ya?' since I was
knee-high to a grasshopper,'' Stone says. ``I got uncles right now
that can put a good fistfight on you. It's just _ growing up _
people we knew.''
</P>
<P>
   Back in the early days, Stone and Douglas called people they
knew and unleashed Roy on them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did this until we ran out of friends,'' Stone says.
</P>
<P>
   Then they began taking nominations from listeners. The two would
sketch out an idea for what Mercer might say, and Douglas would
pick up the phone.
</P>
<P>
   A typical bit would be Mercer calling the administration office
of a mall and complaining that his wife, Sharon Gene, had slipped
in a puddle of something while the two were at the food court. She
has whiplash, and he has doctor bills that need to be paid _
pronto.
</P>
<P>
   Another one involved a music store where Mercer had purchased a
pair of drumsticks for his son, Raymond. His daughter, Leteesha,
somehow stuck a drumstick up her nose, the nylon tip came off, and
Mercer has doctor bills that need paying _ pronto.
</P>
<P>
   Some people get frustrated; others (invariably men) get angry.
Over the years, Stone and Douglas have learned one lesson: Watch
for people who are trying to be genuinely vengeful.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be careful,'' says Douglas. ``Words like `ex-wife'
or `stepfather,' you can tell if there's a real vendetta going on.
We try to avoid those. You might really be getting in the middle of
something.''
</P>
<P>
   The bits became so popular that they were collected on two CDs
and sold at a local auto-parts store. But there also were bootleg
copies everywhere _ particularly in truck stops. In 1996, Scott
Hendricks, at the time president and CEO of Capitol Nashville,
heard a bootleg record and was impressed enough to call the
station.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really weird,'' says Stone. ``I just got a message from
Scott Hendricks from Capitol Records, and I figured it was just
some guy who wanted us to play a record, so I nearly threw it in
the trash.''
</P>
<P>
   But he called back, and in February 1997 ``How Big'A Boy Are Ya?
Volume One'' and ``How Big'A Boy Are Ya? Volume Two'' came out.
Volume three followed in October 1997 and four in April 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Stone and Douglas are talking about turning the calls into an
animated TV show. Suggests Stone: ``It'd be like `King of the Hill'
with attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
