<SLUG> BC-WINE-TASTINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MIGHTY RED 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DeLoach Vineyards Zinfandel 1997, Russian River Valley, Calif.
About $18.
</P>
<P>
   Deloach zinfandels are the defensive linemen of California wine.
They don't weigh 300 pounds, but the alcoholic content of some of
them, 16 percent and occasionally more, is the vinous equivalent of
football brawn. These are not wines for the faint-hearted, but then
very few zinfandels have ever been.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, we are talking about genuine red zinfandel here, not
the wimpy white stuff that is actually pink. A number of the
DeLoach zinfandels come from separate vineyards on the estate. This
one is a blend of wine from most of those vineyards, from vines
planted from 1895 to 1934.
</P>
<P>
   The wine has about 8 percent petite sirah in it, has spent 10
months in oak barrels and was bottled on the estate in August 1997.
Some 8,000 cases were made, so it should not be too hard to find.
It will go well with most hearty dishes, including game. Zinfandel
does not have a track record for aging like cabernet sauvignon, but
this wine will almost certainly be more elegant two or three years
from now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-99 1545EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990216.0192 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-16 15:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7237 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MASTER-CHEF-NYT &LR;      02-16 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MASTER-CHEF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SALTING COD IN A ROBUST TWIST ON POT-AU-FEU 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 This is the third of eight columns by Rick Moonen, the executive
chef and an owner of Oceana in Manhattan. His collaborator on these
columns is Dorie Greenspan.  
 By RICK MOONEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   This dish is my fish version of the classic meat stews known as
pot-au-feu in France, bollito misto in Italy or New England boiled
dinner here. In each of these, the broth is savory, the vegetables
generous and the meat big and important. And every version has its
pungent horseradish sauce.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it was the sauce that inspired me to make cod-au-feu.
When I was the saucier at Le Cirque, we made bollito misto weekly,
and I made the horseradish sauce.
</P>
<P>
   You'd think I'd tire of the dish, the sauce or both, but when a
combination is this good, you just want more. To turn this classic
meat dish into a robust fish stew, the sauce would be key. So, I
kept its sharpness but added a handful of parsley to refresh the
palate after the first hit of horseradish and to draw the sauce and
other elements together.
</P>
<P>
   The vegetables are pot-au-feu perennials, sturdy root
vegetables. For the broth, I like to use a good chicken stock, but
this dish will be fine even if you use water. Just don't skip the
bacon. You need its smokiness, fat and fragrance; it provides the
underlying warmth of the dish and ties it to its roots.
</P>
<P>
   But the center of attention is the cod, which is poached atop
the vegetables and served surrounded by them. I'm a fan of cod,
fresh and salted. I love salt cod's texture _ think flaky brandade
_ and wanted to get that into the dish but also keep fresh cod's
clean taste. I got both by salting fresh cod. Thinking about how
meat is dry-aged and how its texture improves with aging, I lightly
salted the cod and refrigerated it overnight.
</P>
<P>
   The salt removes some of the moisture, creates a flakier texture
and concentrates the flavor. These fillets hold their own against
the root vegetables, stand up to the sauce and make the dish every
bit as satisfying as the classic from which it came.
</P>
<P>
   COD-AU-FEU &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 45 minutes, plus 24 hours' refrigeration
</P>
<P>
   Kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   4 skinless cod fillets, each about 6 ounces and cut } inch thick
</P>
<P>
   1 small bunch parsley, stems reserved and leaves finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   20 white peppercorns
</P>
<P>
   4 sprigs thyme
</P>
<P>
   2 garlic cloves, peeled and crushed
</P>
<P>
   1 bay leaf
</P>
<P>
   2 ounces double-smoked slab bacon, cut into 1-by-\-inch strips
</P>
<P>
   { small head green cabbage, cut into quarters, cored and then
cut into 1-by-3-inch strips
</P>
<P>
   3{ cups chicken broth or water
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   16 pearl onions, trimmed and peeled
</P>
<P>
   4 small Yukon gold potatoes, peeled and halved
</P>
<P>
   3 medium leeks, white and light green parts only, trimmed,
washed and cut diagonally into {-inch-thick slices
</P>
<P>
   2 medium white turnips, peeled, halved and cut into {-inch-thick
slices
</P>
<P>
   2 medium carrots, peeled, trimmed and cut diagonally into
\-inch-thick slices
</P>
<P>
   } cup creme fraiche (see note)
</P>
<P>
   \ cup bottled white horseradish, drained, with liquid reserved
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground white pepper.
</P>
<P>
   1. On the day before serving, sprinkle a light dusting of kosher
salt on both sides of each cod fillet. Wrap fillets in plastic
wrap, and refrigerate for 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   2. Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Make a sachet by placing parsley
stems, peppercorns, thyme, garlic and bay leaf in a double
thickness of cheesecloth, folding into a packet and tying with
kitchen string.
</P>
<P>
   3. Place over medium heat a 12-inch saute pan with tight-fitting
lid, or a large flame-proof casserole. Add bacon, and cook until it
starts to render fat but doesn't color, about 1 minute. Place
sachet in center of pan, and spread cabbage evenly over surface of
pan. Add half the broth, and salt to taste. Cover, and bring to
boil. Reduce heat to low; simmer for 5 minutes. Layer onions,
potatoes, leeks, turnips and carrots in the pan, and add rest of
broth. Cover, and bring to boil. Reduce heat to low; simmer for 10
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   4. Place cod fillets on top of the layered vegetables in the
pan; the liquid will not cover the fillets. Cover pan, and place in
oven. Bake until fish is opaque in center and starts to flake, for
6 to 8 minutes. While fish is baking, prepare horseradish cream.
</P>
<P>
   5. To prepare horseradish cream: In medium bowl, whisk creme
fraiche until it holds peaks. Using a rubber spatula, fold in
parsley, horseradish and mustard. Add a little of the reserved
horseradish liquid to thin the sauce and sharpen its flavor; the
sauce should have the consistency of mousse. Season with salt and
pepper to taste.
</P>
<P>
   6. To serve, spoon equal amount of vegetables and bacon into
each of four wide soup plates. Place a fillet in center of each
plate, spoon over some broth, and top each fillet with generous
spoonful of sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   Note: Creme fraiche is sold in specialty food stores. A
substitute can be made by mixing equal parts heavy cream and sour
cream, and setting aside at room temperature for 24 hours. Chill
until needed. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
