<DOCNO> NYT19990216.0193 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-16 15:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7243 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WINE-TALK-ART-NYT &LR;      02-16 0887
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-TALK-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PROFESSOR GIVES 1997 BORDEAUX AN `A' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.J.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By FRANK J. PRIAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   And now for the fabulous 1997 Bordeaux.
</P>
<P>
   Fabulous 1997s? That is not, I hasten to state, my description.
It comes from Orley Ashenfelter, wine iconoclast and bane of the
wine establishment, who is once again making waves with his
contrarian views.
</P>
<P>
   Ashenfelter is an economist _ the Joseph Douglas Green Professor
of Economics at Princeton University _ who judges wines with the
tools of his trade rather than with the traditional taste-and-sniff
techniques of the orthodox experts.
</P>
<P>
   For him, it's all in the numbers. Rather than slog through damp,
chilly cellars, he sits down at his computer, feeds in data about
heat, frost and rainfall in the Bordeaux wine country and comes up
with his predictions about what that year's wine will be like. On
the whole, his prognostications over the past two decade have been
consistently accurate.
</P>
<P>
   He publishes his often controversial findings twice a year in
Liquid Assets, a newsletter geared to serious wine buyers who
follow the prices wines command at auction. In his January issue,
he singled out for high praise the 1997 and 1998 vintages in
Bordeaux.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody in the wine trade wants to admit it,'' he writes, ``but
the 1997 red Bordeaux vintage is the best since the great duo of
1989 and 1990. And now, hot on the heels of the fabulous 1997s,
Mother Nature has produced an excellent 1998 vintage as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics like Robert M. Parker Jr. and Steven Tanzer, and
columnists in the Wine Spectator and Decanter magazines, while not
entirely disagreeing with Ashenfelter about the 1997s, have been
considerably more circumspect. Parker called the wines ``well-made,
soft, user-friendly'' and suggested that buyers would hardly be
``knocked out by their depth or flavor.''
</P>
<P>
   Decanter, a British publication, said ``the overall impression
is of attractive, fruity wines, with charm rather than intensity _
certainly a vintage for drinking ahead of the 1996s and 1995s.''
</P>
<P>
   The general conclusion among these critics is that the 1997s
will be attractive to drink when released but will not age as well
as the more intense, more tannic wines of 1995 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Agreeing that the 1997s are ``very, very ripe,'' Ashenfelter
writes: ``This early drinkability will no doubt lead to many
concerns about the longevity. For the modern wine lover, we think
that these concerns are misplaced.'' Noting that the 1982 and 1983
vintages were also very ripe when released but are now considered
to be among the top vintages of the 80s, he says that ``well-stored
wines from the 1997 vintage will last just as long and they will
deliver even greater pleasure along the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Stripped to its essentials, his hypothesis runs something like
this: hot growing seasons with a minimum of rain at harvest time
produce the best wines. When the rains come just before picking, as
they often do, the grapes absorb the water and lose concentration.
He goes back to the earliest records of Bordeaux weather conditions
to support his claims.
</P>
<P>
   Using the weather as an indicator of what the wines will be
enables Ashenfelter to talk about very young wines, like the 1998s,
which haven't even been blended yet and won't be bottled for
another year. Noting that the hot, dry summer was followed by heavy
September rain, he concludes that '98s, ``although ripe enough to
make excellent wines, will not hit the heights achieved in 1989,
1990 or 1997.'' He compares them to the '95s, ``ripe wines with
good but not outstanding concentration of fruit extracts.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1998s, he predicts, will not measure up to the '97s but will
be ``forward wines that can be drunk with pleasure early on.''
</P>
<P>
   Comparing 1997 with 1990 and 1995, both outstanding vintages,
will irk some more orthodox enophiles. Indeed, Ashenfelter asserts
that the 1997s will be better than the 1996s, '95s and '94s.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are better than all the vintages of the decade of the
1980s with the possible exception of 1989,'' he writes.
</P>
<P>
   Better than 1982 and 1983? Better than 1988? Well, time _ along
with the Ashenfelter charts _ will tell.
</P>
<P>
   As for price, Ashenfelter believes the 1997s could command
prices comparable to what the 1989s are getting at auctions. He
thinks the two are similar in quality and that 1989 was the last
Bordeaux vintage that still represents a good buy.
</P>
<P>
   He could be right. The 1989s from top chateaus like Chateaux
Latour, Mouton-Rothschild and Margaux are selling for $125 a bottle
or more at the auctions, and prices on future contracts being
quoted for the 1997s by some merchants are not too far from that.
</P>
<P>
   Sherry-Lehmann in New York, for example, is asking $150 a bottle
for the 1997 Lafite-Rothschild, for Mouton-Rothschild and for
Latour, and $153 for Margaux.
</P>
<P>
   Buyers of wine futures contracts look forward to seeing their
wines appreciate in value over a long period. If the 1997s are
early maturing wines, it's unlikely that they will appeal to too
many of those buyers. Unless, of course, they are dedicated
followers of Orley Ashenfelter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
