<HEADLINE>
A MALLET WITH MANY FACES 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By AMANDA HESSER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Supermarket meat aisles, with their neat plastic packages and
uniform, heavily trimmed meats, have made meat buying fairly
boring. Buying meat this way, rather than through a butcher, makes
you think that all the work has been done for you and that all you
need to do is to take it home and cook it.
</P>
<P>
   But certain cuts can still use some improvement. Thinly sliced
veal scallops, for instance, can be pounded out so that they are
much thinner and much more tender once they're cooked.
</P>
<P>
   The best way to pound out veal, turkey or beef is with a meat
mallet, with a blunt, preferably heavy plain end for flattening the
meat. You just place the meat between layers of wax paper or
plastic wrap and pound until it is as thin as you like.
</P>
<P>
   Many meat mallets are made of wood, with one flat side and one
toothed side. Most are light and flimsy, however, and after several
uses, their toothed side dulls. Leifheit has come up with a
beautiful alternative: a sleek, chrome version shaped like an ax.
</P>
<P>
   It is solid and heavy: one side is flat, one has regular teeth,
and another has narrower teeth for breaking down tough, sinewy
meat. It is a mallet with muscle and durability.
</P>
<P>
   And for cooks with ambitions of serious home butchering, there
is the added feature of a curved cleaver blade. With the ample
weight of the mallet behind it, it is useful for breaking through
joints and chopping up bones for the stockpot.
</P>
<P>
   The mallet can also be used on tuna, which can be transformed
into carpaccio. When pounded paper thin, it melts like butter on
the tongue.
</P>
<P>
   The mallet is $15.98 at Zabar's, 2245 Broadway (80th Street);
(212) 787-2000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
