   ``Falwell has moved on. See the latest thing? Now, Jerry Falwell
says that Snow White is a prostitute, because when the seven dwarfs
greet her they go, `Hi Ho!'''
</P>
<P>
   ``According to a new survey, they say laid-back coworkers get
more promotions at work than aggressive go-getters. Especially the
ones that lay all the way back.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been found some women are now using marijuana to ease
symptoms of PMS. Boy, there's a drug deal you don't want to go
bad.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The hot book on the market is `Everything Men Need to Know
about Sex.' I guess there's some problems with it already, `cause
women read it page-by-page, whereas guys just rush through, trying
to get to the end.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Looks like the Senate will vote to acquit Bill Clinton on
Friday. Which is also Abraham Lincoln's birthday. Which is kind of
ironic, isn't it? Clinton dodging the bullet on Lincoln's
birthday?''
</P>
<P>
   ``New York Knicks fans are very upset over the new dancers. The
Knicks hired six new dancers to perform for the team: all male.
Boy, the Knicks'll do anything to try and get Dennis Rodman to come
to New York.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Your buddy Mike Tyson back in prison there, Kev. Know what
he's making in prison? Five-and-a-half cents an hour. Actually, it
would've been 11 cents, but Don King gets his cut.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; QUOTABLES FROM NBC'S `LATE NIGHT WITH CONAN O'BRIEN' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Oprah Winfrey did an interview and she said that if other talk
shows don't stop the sleaze, she's going to quit. After hearing
this, Jerry Springer immediately booked a show called, `My
Grandma's Sexing up a Goat.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``After 28 years of covering football for ABC Sports, Frank
Gifford announced he's retiring. When asked why, Gifford says he
wants to focus full-time on being yelled at by his wife.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Johnny Depp reportedly spent $27,000 on dinner at a London
restaurant. Afterwards Depp said, `This kind of thing never
happened when I was dating Kate Moss.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``In her newest videotaped testimony, Monica Lewinsky said that
she views herself as a pessimist. Monica explained, `I always see
the penis as half empty.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerry Falwell has written an article warning parents that the
Teletubby Tinky Winky may be gay because he's purple and carries a
purse. A spokesperson for the Teletubby says that Tinky Winky is
not gay, he's just emulating Dennis Rodman.''
</P>
<P>
   ``According to a new study, people with strong grips and firm
handshakes tend to be healthier. Which means George Michael should
live to 100.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Dan Quayle said that when he and Al Gore debate in the 2000
election, Gore will be asked to explain why President Clinton
ruined the White House. Meanwhile, Quayle will be asked to explain
why Jack and Jill went up the hill.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sources in the Senate say they're pretty sure that by noon
tomorrow, a final vote will be held at the impeachment trial. It
also means by 1 p.m. tomorrow, President Clinton will be reclaiming
his old table at Hooters.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was reported today that after losing the '92 election, Dan
Quayle called Richard Nixon for career advice. Reportedly, Nixon
told him, `You're calling me? Wow, you are dumb.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike Tyson was sentenced to prison today for beating up two
people after being rear-ended in a car accident last summer. Now
that he's in jail, there's an even greater chance he'll be
rear-ended.''
</P>
<P>
   ``President Clinton was acquitted of both charges today and the
impeachment trail is finally over. There is bad news: Ken Starr is
now accusing the President of having an affair with the purple
Teletubby.''
</P>
<P>
   ``According to a new poll, 75 percent of Americans say President
Clinton's faults are no worse than most other presidents. After
hearing this, President Bush said, `Hey, if that's the case
somebody owes me an intern.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``In a statement to the press this afternoon, President Clinton
said, `I believe that anyone who asks for forgiveness should be
prepared to give it.' The President went on to say, `I feel the
same way about oral sex.'''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CITY STREETS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   While shopping recently on Lexington Avenue, I spotted a
paperback restaurant guide that I thought could be of use to my son
and daughter-in-law. Several times a month they take their two
small children out to eat and ``Kids Eat New York'' promised more
than 150 restaurants where ``kids have fun and grown-ups enjoy the
food.''
</P>
<P>
   The back-cover promotional copy said something like ``Give me
your tired, your bored, your cranky children whining for their
food.''
</P>
<P>
   As I was paying for my purchase, a gray-haired man behind me
said, ``I'll take one of those too.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So you have grandchildren?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' he replied. ``But I figure that book will tell me the
restaurants where I don't want to eat.''
</P>
<P>
   _ LAWRENCE HUGHES
</P>
<P>
   The young man, probably in his late teens, wore baggy jeans and
a baseball cap. He scowled at the woman standing next to him, an
elegantly dressed matron sporting a large imitation leopard hat,
and finally gave vent to his anger.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, lady, someone killed an animal for your dopey hat,'' he
called out.
</P>
<P>
   The woman turned toward him and in a modulated tone replied:
``Young man, your ignorance is showing. If you cannot tell the
difference between a faux and a real leopard skin, you are a danger
to all animals. I suggest you close your mouth and open your
mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Evelyn Dayage stood by in admiration as the woman then sailed
serenely across the avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Lenore Nemeth and a young lawyer were sharing a cab when the
lawyer began coughing to such a degree that she was gasping for
breath. She flung $5 at the driver and asked him to pull over as
she had to get out to get some water.
</P>
<P>
   The cab stopped, and as the lawyer was gathering her briefcase,
the driver jumped out, clutching the money, and ran into a corner
delicatessen. In a minute he returned with a bottle of spring
water, a package of cough drops and the change. The drops and the
water, coupled with a good dollop of amazement, worked wonders.
Passengers and driver sped happily to their destination.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Singer overheard this exchange between two sanitation
workers on Fifth Avenue and 12th Street.
</P>
<P>
   Worker No. 1: ``So what's the truth?''
</P>
<P>
   Worker No. 2: ``The truth? There are three truths, her truth, my
truth and the real truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Raleigh Mayer was in the East 60s when she noticed a casually
dressed father and his pre-teen-age daughter window shopping their
way down the block.
</P>
<P>
   Pointing to something in a store display, the man addressed a
woman ahead of them, presumably his wife, ``Ah, Maman,'' he began.
Ms. Mayer pegged them as tourists until they passed her and she
heard the girl's plaintive plea: ``Dad, would you please stop
pretending we're French?''
</P>
<P>
   The cute little boy sat in the hospital waiting room and
fidgeted, not so patiently, as his mother had X-rays taken.
Finally, he went to the receptionist and demanded to know when his
mother would return.
</P>
<P>
   The busy clerk sighed and said, ``Oh, about the time you can
count from 1 to 10 in German.''
</P>
<P>
   As he began pacing the floor, my memory began returning. When I
was a child, my father had me recite the German alphabet and
numbers every night. It was all I ever learned of his family's
homeland.
</P>
<P>
   I whispered to the boy, ``Would you like to learn to count from
1 to 10 in German?''
</P>
<P>
   His eyes lighted up as though he had seen the tooth fairy, and
he turned out to be a quick study _ he had it down pat in about
five minutes. He proudly marched to the receptionist and rendered a
flawless performance. She had obviously forgotten her remark _ or
had no idea of what he had just said _ because she gave him a
puzzled stare.
</P>
<P>
   Miraculously, Mommy appeared at that moment. He tugged at her
sleeve, shouting German numbers. As they left, she looked back at
the waiting room, undoubtedly wondering what had gone on in her
absence.
</P>
<P>
   _ KAROLYN K. WRIGHTSON
</P>
<P>
   Allan and Stephanie Geliebter and three friends were presented
with a bill for $180 after dining at an Upper West Side restaurant.
Two credit cards were presented and the giggly waitress was told to
divide the bill 60-40. They waited for an unusually long time
before the waitress returned and said in a puzzled tone, ``One of
you is paying $60 and the other is paying $40 _ so who's paying the
other $80?''
</P>
<P>
   Theater review: After a performance of ``Electra'' at the
Barrymore Theater, Loretta and Ernest Zahner overheard this
exchange between two women who were discussing the roles of Zoe
Wanamaker and Claire Bloom.
</P>
<P>
   Woman No. 1: ``Claire Bloom didn't have too many lines.''
</P>
<P>
   Woman No. 2: ``True, but at least she got to wear better
clothes.''
</P>
<P>
   Minnie Langer's example of Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's
quality-of-life program reaching some unlikely places: a
handwritten sign on the back of the driver's seat on the 57th
Street bus. It read, ``If you feel the urge to drop your trash on
the floor, take it home and see how it looks on your floor.''
</P>
<P>
   The very small poodle being walked by a matron on Park Avenue
was approached by a very large Rottweiler. The poodle went into an
attack mode, barking furiously and making aggressive moves. The
matron looked down and addressed her poodle. ``Do you have a death
wish?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BILL'S WORLD &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By BILL TAMMEUS &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Most of us wanted love for Valentine's Day, but the truth is we
were, like the president, happy to settle just for acquittal.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Tripp says she's thinking of writing a book. We don't mean
to
</P>
<P>
   influence her, but we're thinking of not reading it.,
</P>
<P>
   Overheard on our bus: Maybe I'm not patriotic enough, but so far
I
</P>
<P>
   don't miss the impeachment trial even a little.'',
</P>
<P>
   Is the presidency weaker because of the Lewinsky scandal?
Probably, but
</P>
<P>
   at least the Marine Band hasn't taken to playing Hail to the
Impeached
</P>
<P>
   Chief.'',
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Clinton says he'd like to continue to be useful in public
affairs''
</P>
<P>
   when he leaves office. Hasn't he had enough trouble with affairs
like that?,
</P>
<P>
   This is a time for reconciliation and renewal,'' says Mr.
Clinton. It's
</P>
<P>
   the sort of thing you often hear from people who've spent a lot
of time
</P>
<P>
   apologizing.,
</P>
<P>
   The president says his wife would be terrific in the Senate.''
Wonder
</P>
<P>
   how she'd have voted in the recent impeachment trial.,
</P>
<P>
   The American people recognize we must reduce our demand for
drugs,''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Clinton says. Would it help if fewer people inhaled?,
</P>
<P>
   John Kasich, also running for president, says we need to begin
to run
</P>
<P>
   America from the bottom up.'' Wouldn't it be more fun to have
the
</P>
<P>
   convertible model _ top down?,
</P>
<P>
   Rust Belt cities are making a comeback, the Census Bureau
reports. You've
</P>
<P>
   got to love a country where even Detroit and Peoria have
futures.,
</P>
<P>
   New national figures show more people are wearing auto seat
belts. Maybe
</P>
<P>
   more of them have sobered up enough to recognize the dangers out
there.,
</P>
