<HEADLINE>
WILL A GOVERNMENT PLAN GIVE STONEHENGE A LIFT? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Feb. 21)  
 (bl)  
 By SARAH LYALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Stonehenge, that stunning collection of artfully placed
rocks on Salisbury Plain, has always been one of Britain's
most-visited, and worst-managed, monuments. For years, officials
from the government departments responsible for culture, roads and
the environment; archaeologists; heritage groups; and surrounding
communities have been squabbling over how to balance a clutch of
competing interests, each with its own stake in Stonehenge's
future.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, the British government presented a plan that it hopes
will be acceptable to everyone. It would involve major alterations
to the roads around the monument, open up the monument to visitors
and establish a new visitors' center and parking lot farther away
from the site, which is about 85 miles from London. The plan is
designed to preserve Stonehenge and alleviate traffic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting everyone to agree to this scheme has been in itself a
huge achievement,'' said a spokeswoman for English Heritage, one of
the agencies responsible for the site. Almost all of the opposition
seems to be satisfied with the current plans, with the exception of
some neighbors worried about an increase in visitor traffic.
</P>
<P>
   But the $200 million proposal is far from being approved, and
still needs to wend its way through a long, arduous process that
will include a public hearing, environmental impact statements and
archaeological surveys, among other things. And even if approved at
every stage, work is unlikely to begin until well into the next
decade. ``We are aiming for the start of works within the next
seven years,'' British Roads Minister Larry Whitty said last fall.
</P>
<P>
   The first part of the proposal, the road improvements, would
involve diverting the A344 _ one of two narrow roads closest to
Stonehenge; the section closest to the monument would be closed
altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the A303, the principal road used by visitors, would
be widened in some sections to two lanes in each direction, from
its current one lane. In addition, a 1.2-mile portion closest to
Stonehenge would be sunken into a tunnel, so that the road will
disappear from view for people walking around the monument. The
visitors' center _ an unsightly structure that consists mainly of a
small underground passage _ would be replaced, the government said.
It is seeking a private-sector partner to help with the financing,
and hasn't decided on a plan for the new structure.
</P>
<P>
   To restore Stonehenge and its surroundings to a more pristine
state, the plan calls for moving the visitors' center and parking
lot, currently next to the monument, to a new site some distance
away. Visitors would take a bus to the monument itself.
</P>
<P>
   The circle of stones that everyone comes to see is in a vast
area that contains some 450 considerably smaller points of
archaeological interest like burial mounds and longbarrows, which
were associated with burial rites and look like long ridges in the
ground. The site covers about 5,000 acres and is classified as a
World Heritage site, meaning that it receives special protection
and is subject to specific planning restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows who built Stonehenge or why, but the first parts of
it were constructed in about 3050 B.C., and it's pretty certain
that it was used for rituals or ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   A reconfiguration of the roads according to the plan is likely
to bring new birds, butterflies and plants to the area, the
government says, and a proposed new network of footpaths would
encourage visitors to wander around the whole area, which is known
as a chalk downland because of its chalky soil and preponderance of
little hillocks, or downs.
</P>
<P>
   And, for the first time in years, visitors would be able to walk
right up to the stone circle itself, rather than staying behind a
fence that keeps them some distance back.
</P>
<P>
   Originally, the actual stones were closed to visitors because of
fears that the monument was being damaged by erosion. But by
ushering people through the whole site, and not just Stonehenge
itself, officials think that they can protect the monument.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think we can encourage visitor access in a way that
protects the monument, partly by distributing people more widely in
the surrounding landscape,'' the English Heritage spokeswoman said.
``We're confident that we can manage it and at the same time enable
people to visit it properly again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
