<HEADLINE>
GETTING TO YOUR DESTINATION WITHOUT DROWNING IN DATA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Feb. 21)  
 (bl)  
 By L.R. SHANNON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are many ways to smooth surfing on the Web for travel
information, or any other kind. One of the simplest is to take full
advantage of whichever browser is your vehicle. Internet Explorer
has ``favorites,'' Netscape Navigator has ``bookmarks.'' Their
exact capabilities vary from version to version, but at a minimum
each allows you to store the full addresses of sites you are likely
to return to so you don't have to type them in again. (It is also
vital to edit the list occasionally so it isn't stuffed with
addresses you don't return to.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No search engine is perfect, and the same terms typed into the
travel subsections of two or more search engines will give you
different results. If Altavista, say, is your usual stop, try
Yahoo, too, or Excite, or Hotbot, or Lycos, or Infoseek, or all of
them. At best, the biggest search engines index about a third of
all the sites on the World Wide Web, and not necessarily the same
third. Also, don't ignore smaller sites. The Mining Company has
been a longtime favorite of mine, and lately I've discovered
Dogpile, which has nothing to do with dogs, but allows you to go to
many other search engines from one home port. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When you don't know the address of a site, often an educated
guess will work. Try ``www.nameofcompany.com,'' which works for all
the sites mentioned here, and you will probably land at the right
hotel, airline or cruise line. Don't forget that not everything is
a ``com.'' Educational organizations are ``edu''; government sites
are ``gov''; organizations, mostly nonprofit, are ``org,'' and
``net'' may stand for ``network'' or, then again, it may substitute
for ``com.'' Sites outside the United States end with a two-letter
country abbreviation, sometimes obvious, like ``ca'' for Canada,
and sometimes not, like ``mo'' for Macau. A complete list of
country codes may be found at
www.ics.uci.edu/pub/websoft/wwwstat/country-codes.txt.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   All addresses on the Web begin with ``http://'' _ something more
recent versions of the browsers allow you to skip. Sometimes you
can also skip the ``www''and the ``com'' or ``gov'' or whatever.
But don't count on that. Search engines let you limit your request
by using what is formally known as Boolean logic, that is, with
``and,'' ``or'' or ``not.'' An ``and'' is easiest. In one search
engine, ``vienna'' yielded 136 sites, ``vienna and travel'' got 46
and ``vienna and travel and hotel'' brought out 13.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of overseas sites, try the foreign name of the city or
country if it differs from the English one. In a Vienna search,
searching for ``wien'' in the travel subsection of my search engine
brought eight matches, including ``Wienerschnitzel'' and
``Wienerbrod'' dough; searching for wien out of the travel
subsection found 149 sites, many of them in German, while ``wien
and travel'' in the travel subsection found one lean and useful
site in English.
</P>
<P>
   In whichever search engine you use, there will be an icon
labeled ``ad-vanced searches,'' or something similar, or a ``help''
icon, to show the syntax required for more complex searches. (The
syntax may differ from one to another.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you cannot connect with one of those footlong addresses
favored by governments and educational institutions, shorten it to
the part before the first slash; 
``www.nameofuniversity.edu/nameofcollege.nameofbuilding/nameoflibrar
y.html'' becomes ``www.nameofuniversity.edu.'' That often gets you
to the top level of the site, and you can dig deeper from there. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Finally, remember the following advice, from the second edition
of Alfred and Emily Glossbrenner's excellent ``Search Engines for
the World Wide Web'' (Peachpit Press; $17.99), a book for would-be
power surfers: ``Don't assume that the Internet contains the sum
total of human knowledge. Part of being a good online searcher is
knowing when to stop. The information you want may or may not be
available on line. And if it is on line, it may be buried so deep
that it's not worth the time and trouble to locate it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
