<HEADLINE>
BAKING WEB SITES; CHINESE NEW YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By S.A. BELZER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mouse in the Kitchen: Baking Tips on the Internet &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When the winds shake the windows, what could be more comforting
than a warm oven and the smell of baking bread? Though a computer
is not essential to produce the effect, the Internet is ready to
help the baker, and for those who want the goods without the
baking, it also offers places to buy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Welcome to a baker's Camelot'' is the greeting at
www.kingarthurflour.com. The site, run by a company going back to
1790 and boasting that it has never added chemicals to its flours,
offers tips, recipes and even well-illustrated baking ``classes.''
</P>
<P>
   The tips are built into the recipes. For instance, an
introductory note for a recipe for the ``very lightest'' ciabatta,
an airy, slipper-shaped loaf for a sandwich or dipping in soup,
advises that more water will be needed this time of year than in,
say, August, when the flour has been in a humid kitchen all summer.
</P>
<P>
   The people at King Arthur describe themselves on the Web site as
avid bakers. It shows. A recipe for ``crusty Old World sesame
braid'' is in two parts _ for a starter, and then the dough _ and
both parts call for cool water, the temperature favored by
professional bakers to slow the action of yeast.
</P>
<P>
   The online classes are given by Barbara Lauterbach, who owns and
operates the Watch Hill Bed and Breakfast in Center Harbor, N.H., a
distant neighbor of King Arthur, in Norwich, Vt.
</P>
<P>
   In a series of photographs, she takes her charges through maple
walnut scones, whole-wheat granola bread and three other recipes.
</P>
<P>
   The King Arthur catalog, a mail-order storeful of bakers'
supplies and equipment, is pictured on the site, with a number to
call for a copy: (800) 777-4434. Unfortunately, none of that
baker's bounty can be bought on line.
</P>
<P>
   Another good flour company site is www.whitelily.com, based in
Knoxville, Tenn. Like King Arthur, White Lily says that its flour
is higher in protein than all-purpose flour because of a high
percentage of hard wheat. The site describes the company as ``a
Southern tradition since 1883,'' and biscuits are its specialty.
</P>
<P>
   There's a page with four steps and four pictures for light
biscuits. One of the tips is to place the unbaked biscuits on a
sheet an inch apart for crusty sides or almost touching for soft
sides.
</P>
<P>
   Other recipes include apricot orange bread and cranberry nut
bread, and some that change daily or weekly, like a cranberry
danish breakfast round and Italian turnovers with tomato sauce.
</P>
<P>
   The flour can be bought on line, along with White Lily baking
mixes. There are also premiums, including T-shirts and posters.
</P>
<P>
   A surprisingly useful site is the Free Internet Bread Recipe
Archive (http://idt.net/wordup/bread.html). Surprising because the
laissez-faire principle of Rick van Valkenburg, who runs the site,
is ``send your favorite bread recipe.''
</P>
<P>
   He posts or links to what comes in, with the idea of making this
a worldwide recipe exchange. To judge by recipes from South Africa
and Norway, with ingredients in metric units (equivalents sometimes
given), he seems to have succeeded.
</P>
<P>
   Two perfectly bakable recipes from the archive's more than 100
traditional and bread-machine recipes are for Irish brown bread
(using American whole-wheat flour) and ``Duncan's rustic grain
bread,'' which Gerry Duncan, its creator, says is low in fat and
high in protein, freezes well and when toasted goes with chevre.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   For answers to baking questions, a good place for prompt,
knowledgeable responses is Baker Boulanger (www.betterbaking.com),
the site of Marcy Goldman, a food writer in Montreal. Besides
answering questions, she has 400 bread and cake recipes on her
site. This month, she offers Mardi Gras pancake recipes, which can
be enjoyed even after Shrove Tuesday (aka Fat Tuesday or Mardi
Gras, which was Tuesday), and features like ``Ciao Chicago,'' which
tells how to make Chicago deep-dish stuffed pizza.
</P>
<P>
   The Baldwin Hill Bakery (www.baldwinhill.com) occupies an old
farm in rural Massachusetts, where a whole-grain sourdough bread
with macrobiotic overtones is baked in the Flemish desem tradition.
The desem is the sourdough starter, a fermented culture of the
stone-ground wheat (grown without synthetic fertilizer, herbicide
or pesticide) and water from a 500-foot-deep well. No yeast is
otherwise added.
</P>
<P>
   The breads also contain sea salt from the coast of Brittany. A
loaf made from spelt, an ancient member of the wheat family,
indicates that perhaps not enough sea salt is used. That bread is
tightly textured with a strong grain flavor. It is not like biting
into an airy brioche, but it makes you feel as if you are doing
something healthy.
</P>
<P>
   Other Baldwin Hill varieties are whole wheat, sesame wheat, rye,
raisin spelt, raisin cinnamon and rice. There are also lighter
breads. The site has a price list, and the breads cost less than in
stores but must be bought in quantity.
</P>
<P>
   Customers may buy a mixed batch of six loaves for $12 to $13.80,
plus shipping and handling charges. One bread baker advises that
loaves can be frozen without risking freezer burn by wrapping them
first in a plastic bag, then aluminum and then in another plastic
bag. The number for orders and information is (978) 249-4691.
</P>
<P>
   For years, the Collin Street Bakery in Corsicana, Texas, has
been known for a rich Christmas cake that is as close to a solid
block of pecan as a cake can be. ``We have our own pecan shelling
facility in Corsicana,'' Bob McNutt, the president of the bakery,
wrote by e-mail. ``It is the largest single shelling plant in the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   The bakery is now on line at www.collinstreetbakery.com and is
selling that cake, from a century-old recipe from Wiesbaden,
Germany, all year round (regular size, almost two pounds, is
$16.15). True to its pecan mission, the bakery is also offering,
among other temptations, apricot pecan cakes, praline pecan
cheesecake, pecan pie, fudge pecan pie and apple pecan crumble.
Orders can be placed at the Web site or at (800) 292-7400. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Celebrating the Rabbit &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the Chinese lunar calendar, New Year's Day 1999 fell Tuesday.
This is the Year of the Rabbit, named for one of the 12 animals in
the Chinese zodiac, and the parades and feasts to celebrate it can
last from a week to a month.
</P>
<P>
   The event is being observed on the Internet at
www.usarice.com/domestic/recipes (click on ``Chinese New Year''),
the site of the trade association of the American rice industry.
</P>
<P>
   It offers a New Year origin legend, descriptions of Chinese
traditions for the season, a list of propitious foods and an essay
on rice in Chinese cooking by Grace Young, the author of ``The
Wisdom of the Chinese Kitchen'' (to be published in May by Simon &AMP;
Schuster).
</P>
<P>
   There are also homey recipes, the sort that may appear on a
Chinese family's table rather than in a restaurant. These include
tender chicken on rice (made with chicken, ham, mushrooms and a
ginger sauce).
</P>
<P>
   Another site for the season is www.vitasoy-usa.com/recipe1.html,
run by Vitasoy, whose holiday recipes include tofu-mango stir-fry
and eight precious noodles with savory broth.
</P>
<P>
   Gung hay fat choy (Happy New Year)! &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
