<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH PRIORITY ON STATE BUSINESS MAKES SENSE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ People don't get elected president of the United
States _ or governor of Texas _ by being too overconfident.
</P>
<P>
   They have to believe in themselves, their abilities and the
future and project that feeling to the voters. But the pitfalls of
the political process, especially the quest for a major office,
force even the most successful politicians to run scared.
</P>
<P>
   Although Gov. George W. Bush wasn't exactly petrified with fear
during his recent laugher of a re-election campaign, he ran as if
there actually was some doubt that he would win a second term.
</P>
<P>
   His aggressiveness was obviously motivated in large part by his
desire to help sweep Republicans into other state offices, which he
did, and to increase his own viability as a presidential contender,
which he also did.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush, who just four years earlier had unseated a popular
Democratic governor, wasn't taking his own future in the Governor's
Mansion for granted either.
</P>
<P>
   Once Bush's re-election was history, though, pressure
immediately started to build for the governor to announce his
intentions for the White House, which many people have long assumed
is his next desired political destination.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has repeatedly refused to publicly say whether he will make
the big race. But he continues to fuel speculation that he is
running for president by entertaining a stream of national and
foreign visitors in Austin and becoming the subject of a
not-entirely-spontaneous draft by a large group of congressional
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   The draft by Bush supporters from several states apparently was
designed to counter the early attention focused on other Republican
would-be presidents, including the recent splash Elizabeth Dole
made when she quit her post at the American Red Cross to test the
political waters.
</P>
<P>
   Dole and other GOP contenders and potential contenders are
touring the country _ including New Hampshire and Iowa, early key
stops in the nominating process _ while Bush remains in Texas and
lets others keep his name before the national media.
</P>
<P>
   Iowa and New Hampshire, whose early caucuses and primary,
respectively, give them much more clout in the presidential
nominating process than their population sizes deserve, take their
overblown roles seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Several Republican state legislators from Iowa even flew to
Austin last week to urge Bush to run. They bore letters from about
60 of their colleagues, some of whom hadn't even decided whether to
support a Bush candidacy. But they couldn't bear the thought of the
perceived front-runner for their party's White House nomination
snubbing their state.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, not to be overconfident, assured the Iowans that he will
campaign there if he runs, although if anyone could win a
presidential nomination without having to build momentum _ or
create a winning perception _ in Iowa, it would be someone like
Bush, who has a name that is already nationally known and a large
fund-raising network in place.
</P>
<P>
   Those factors buy him more time than most presidential hopefuls.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has indicated he won't announce a presidential race _ if he
is running _ until at or near the end of the legislative session
late this spring.
</P>
<P>
   He says he needs to tend to the state's business while lawmakers
are in town. He does, mainly because that was what he was
re-elected to do but also because some of his legislative
priorities are important to a White House campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Failure to convince the Legislature to enact his proposed tax
cuts, for example, could hurt him in a national race. And failure
to win legislative approval of a voucher bill for private school
tuition or a bill to allow parents to be informed before their
minor daughters could have abortions _ two other Bush priorities _
could cost him the crucial support of social and religious
conservatives in the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   Most Texas voters certainly weren't turned off by the prospects
of a presidential race when 69 percent of them voted for Bush's
re-election in November. Many, if not most, of the people who voted
to give him a new four-year term in Austin probably assumed he
would run for the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty-four percent of the respondents to the Texas Poll released
just last week said Bush should make the national race.
</P>
<P>
   But the governor may be concerned that some Democratic
legislators will use any overt presidential campaigning to fire
away at him and undermine some of his legislative proposals. They
probably would, but some Democrats will fight some of his
priorities anyway, simply because they oppose them.
</P>
<P>
   With a little luck, Bush probably could successfully juggle the
legislative session and some out-of-state campaigning, and most
Texans wouldn't mind.
</P>
<P>
   But that would be testing the limits of confidence.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
