</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEEP YOUR HEAD IN A MONEY CRISIS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PAMELA YIP 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a world where layoffs have become an everyday occurrence and
so many people are without health insurance, you may well be face
to face with a financial crisis someday.
</P>
<P>
   When faced with more bills than you can possibly pay, it's easy
to panic and grab the first available stash of money you can lay
your hands on.
</P>
<P>
   For many workers, it's their 401(k) retirement savings plan.
</P>
<P>
   Others will be stuck with mounting debts they can't pay and a
powerful urge just to ignore the trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, resist the urge.
</P>
<P>
   You give away your future when you tap retirement money early or
don't deal with your debts.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, debt takes on a life of its own if you don't
control it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
RETIREMENT FUNDS ARE A LAST RESORT &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pull money out of your retirement account only if you absolutely
have to.
</P>
<P>
   That means if you literally ``have nothing else,'' said John
Eadie, a partner in the personal financial counseling group at
accounting firm Ernst &AMP; Young in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The tax penalties for withdrawing your retirement money early
are awful, especially if you're younger than 59 1/2.
</P>
<P>
   If you must withdraw retirement money, take out the smallest
amount you can, so you don't take out more than you need.
</P>
<P>
   Eadie said the ideal order in which you should withdraw
emergency money is:
</P>
<P>
   1. Take out money from bank accounts first. There are no tax
consequences for doing that.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a tax perspective, that makes the most sense,'' Eadie
said.
</P>
<P>
   2. If you need more money or don't have a savings account, sell
your investments in non-retirement accounts. If you've held those
investments for longer than a year and profit from their sale, you
will pay a long-term capital gains tax of up to 20 percent. That's
better than paying ordinary income tax rates of as high as 39.6
percent on money withdrawn from your retirement account.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tax consequences of using those other funds would be more
beneficial than the tax consequences of dipping into (your
retirement account),'' Eadie said.
</P>
<P>
   Not only would you be jeopardizing your future retirement if you
pull money out of your retirement funds, you would also have to pay
income tax on the funds, and, if you're younger than 59 1/2, pay an
additional 10 percent penalty for early withdrawal of retirement
funds.
</P>
<P>
   An alternative to withdrawal of your 401(k) money is to borrow
from the account.
</P>
<P>
   I don't advocate this method either because, like total
withdrawal, the money you take out isn't able to compound and grow
for you.
</P>
<P>
   If you must take out a loan, you must repay it or there are
severe consequences.
</P>
<P>
   If you decide to leave your job and you have a 401(k) loan
outstanding, most companies will want you to pay off the entire
amount.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't do that, the loan amount is considered a withdrawal
and you're taxed on it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
IGNORING DEBTS WON'T WORK &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Debts have a powerful effect on people. When you can't afford to
pay your bills, you may be tempted to ignore them and hope they
will somehow pay themselves.
</P>
<P>
   They won't.
</P>
<P>
   Treat your lenders with respect _ you'll need all the goodwill
you can get. If you've reached the point where you just can't make
all the payments _ even after you have cut your spending _ start
setting priorities so you can limit the damage somewhat.
</P>
<P>
   Divide your loan payments between secured credit, such as a
mortgage or car loan, from unsecured credit, such as on credit
cards.
</P>
<P>
   Pay your secured credit first so you can hold on to your home
and car. You need a roof over your head and you need your car for
basic transportation.
</P>
<P>
   Call your unsecured creditors immediately and tell them that
you're experiencing financial problems.
</P>
<P>
   Don't wait until you're late on payments and they start dunning
you. They'll be much less sympathetic to your plight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let them know your intentions are right and that you intend to
pay them,'' said Sharon McLean, executive director of Consumer
Credit Counseling Service of the Gulf Coast Area in Houston, which
helps consumers with credit problems.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of raiding your precious retirement assets, consider
borrowing money from your life insurance policy.
</P>
<P>
   You don't have to repay the loan and you don't pay tax on the
borrowed amount, but I urge you to repay the loan.
</P>
<P>
   The loan amount reduces the cash value on your policy, which
means that your beneficiaries will get less when you die or get
nothing if your policy lapses.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Pamela Yip can receive electronic mail via the Internet. Address
your comments and questions to pamela.yip(at)chron.com, or call
(713) 220-2000 and enter access code 1003. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
