<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-16 16:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7343 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOLS-LOWELL-HNS &LR;      02-16 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOLS-LOWELL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOP SCHOOL AT GROUND ZERO OF QUOTA CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JULIAN GUTHRIE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ At the votex of the highest-stakes lawsuit in
the history of San Francisco's public schools is Lowell High
School, a fiercely competitive campus that is being shaped by race.
</P>
<P>
   It is Lowell that required Chinese-American students to score
higher than children of other races. It is Lowell that uses a
system of racial percentages in an attempt to bring diversity into
its hallowed halls.
</P>
<P>
   And more than any other school, it is Lowell that sparked the
1994 lawsuit that now threatens to topple the 15-year-old federal
desegregation plan in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Many fates hinge on the federal trial to determine the fate of
racial quotas in San Francisco schools: Some $37 million a year in
state desegregation funds could be lost if the plan is ruled
unconstitutional. The trial began Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The district, now wedded to diversity, would face enormous
challenges if its practice of limiting any race to no more than 45
percent of students at a given school is struck down. Thousands of
children could be reassigned to different schools.
</P>
<P>
   But no other school would be altered as much as Lowell, the
city's oldest academic high school that traditionally admits
students based on their grades alone, not the neighborhood in which
they live.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless you make real efforts, you won't find many
African-Americans and Latinos at Lowell,'' said Frank Wu, a Howard
University law professor who has written extensively on affirmative
action. ``At Lowell, a strictly by-the-numbers approach reportedly
results in an almost entirely Asian-American student body. That's
lamentable and should be unacceptable to everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   The best and the brightest students of all races in San
Francisco attend Lowell, and the high standards usually pay off.
Lowell sends a higher proportion of graduates to the University of
California than any other public school in California. It is the
alma mater of several Nobel laureates, the late Gov. Edmund Brown
and Supreme Court Justice Stephen Breyer.
</P>
<P>
   But because blacks and Hispanics overall have lower test scores
than whites or ethnic Asians, they're significantly
underrepresented at Lowell.
</P>
<P>
   And without the rule limiting any one race _ in Lowell's case
Chinese-Americans _ to 45 percent of the student body, the numbers
of blacks and Hispanics could shrink dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, blacks make up 17 percent of all San Francisco
public school students, but 4 percent of Lowell's 2,515 students.
Hispanics comprise 21 percent of the district's students, but 11
percent of Lowell's students. Chinese-Americans comprise 28 percent
of the district's population, but 43 percent of Lowell's students.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, between 70 and 80 percent of students are admitted
solely by their test scores and grades. The remaining 20 to 30
percent have slightly lower grades, but earn compensating
``value-added diversity points'' if their families are poor, if
they live in public housing, if their parents were not able to
attend college.
</P>
<P>
   Statistics show that without those value-added points, very few
black or Hispanic students would get into Lowell.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the diversity-points system note that all students
admitted to Lowell are outstanding. And students from disadvantaged
backgrounds may face greater obstacles in their efforts to study,
or even get to school.
</P>
<P>
   Marsha Cohen, who heads Lowell's admissions committee, said that
if grades alone determine who gets into Lowell, the city's most
prestigious public school could become exclusively white and ethnic
Asian.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the desegregation plan under fire began in 1983 to
settle a lawsuit filed against the school district and the state by
the NAACP, which argued successfully that San Francisco schools
discriminated against blacks.
</P>
<P>
   But a decade later, it was three frustrated Chinese-American
families who filed the current lawsuit, angry that their children
were turned away from schools only because those schools had hit
their limit of Chinese-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chinese-American parents and students have suffered under a
quota system in San Francisco. It's risen its ugly head most
noticeably, but not exclusively, at Lowell,'' said Amy Chang, an
attorney who is on the board of directors with the Asian-American
Legal Foundation, a nonprofit bipartisan group formed in 1994 to
support the Chinese-Americans' cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``We heard from parents whose children were saying, `I wish I
wasn't Chinese ... I don't know why I should do my homework when
ultimately I'm judged by my race,''' Chang said. ``We feel strongly
that all children should be treated equally.''
</P>
</TEXT>
