<HEADER>
A7350 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACHMENT-`OSCARS'-     02-16 1213
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACHMENT-`OSCARS'-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEST IMPEACHMENT TRIAL PERFORMANCES?: AND THE WINNERS ARE...  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This droll 950-word ``separate buy'' article is from The
Independent newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 1-800-444-0267, or fax us at
1-816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By MARY DEJEVSKY  
 c.1999 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Now that the U.S. Senate has wrapped up the
impeachment trial of Bill Clinton, and with it almost six months of
Congressional drama, it is surely time to recognize some of those
whose performances delighted and embarrassed us by turns for so
long.
</P>
<P>
   For services to politics, to America, to entertainment, and _ of
course _ to themselves, they have no peers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We return you,'' said CNN after a spell from the Senate, ``to
our regular program, `Showbiz Today.''' Oh no you don't, we viewers
barracked quietly, we have been there all along.
</P>
<P>
   So, without further ado, we congratulate:
</P>
<P>
   BEST FEMALE LEAD: Who else but Monica Lewinsky, the 25-year-old
Valley Girl turned Presidential Consort, the only Monica in America
who no longer needs a surname?
</P>
<P>
   Her celluloid presence in the Senate convinced even the most
hardened Republican of Bill Clinton's unerring eye for the fair
sex.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bright,'' ``impressive,'' ``poised,'' ``intelligent'' _ who
could not agree with these reviews? (What they meant, of course,
was ``sexy.'') She knew instinctively when to charm, when to act
the air-head, and when to deploy the formidable techniques of legal
hairsplitting she has recently mastered.
</P>
<P>
   She is the unchallenged mistress of the big occasion, if no
longer of the president. But maybe she could have another think
about the hairdo.
</P>
<P>
   BEST MALE LEAD: Dale Bumpers, 73, just-retired senator from the
president's home state of Arkansas, and pleasantly greying, who
drew on all his rhetorical and dramatic skills to plead for his
ally's acquittal.
</P>
<P>
   So at ease was he in the august Senate chamber that he seemed
almost to dance around his microphone.
</P>
<P>
   He struck just the right senatorial register, between his
down-home recollections of Bill, his deep respect for his former
colleagues, the anguish he felt for Bill's wife and family, and his
intimate lawyer's love of the Constitution of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   It was the performance of his life, that enhanced his own
reputation and that of the Senate. Too bad, it was his farewell.
</P>
<P>
   BEST LAWYER IN A SUPPORTING ROLE: Cheryl Mills, 33, a deputy
White House counsel, who was totally unfazed by being the only
black woman in the Senate chamber (and the presence of her parents
in the gallery).
</P>
<P>
   She was half the age of almost everyone except Monica, but rose
to her role with the smooth passion of a seasoned pro. ``A star is
born,'' the reviewers said next day, and they were right.
</P>
<P>
   Mills might have been on some shaky factual ground at times, but
she never, ever showed it. Her ringing refrain, ``It's those facts,
those stubborn facts again,'' delivered in her soft Southern drawl
with half the consonants missing, will long be remembered by her
adoring audience.
</P>
<P>
   BEST PERFORMANCE BY AN UNKNOWN (MALE): No contest here. Lindsey
Graham, 43, Republican representative for South Carolina, wins
outright. Graham's silk-smooth performances in the House judiciary
committee and the House impeachment debate marked him out as a new
force.
</P>
<P>
   A small-town lawyer in his pre-Congressional life, (and a
bachelor, girls!), Graham was that rare Republican prosecutor who
understood that bombast could be self-defeating.
</P>
<P>
   The nearest the Republicans can get to a folksy communicator in
the Clinton mold, Graham also had some of the best lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where I come from,'' he told the Senate of the president's
nocturnal phone calls to Monica, ``a person who calls someone up at
2:30 in the morning is up to no good.''
</P>
<P>
   BEST PERFORMANCE BY AN UNKNOWN (FEMALE): Susan Collins, 46,
Republican senator from Maine, in a close contest with her fellow
Mainiac, Olympia Snowe, and Texan, Kay Bailey Hutchison. But
Collins wins because of the depth of the obscurity from which she
emerged.
</P>
<P>
   Smart, and above all sensible, oh so sensible, Collins dreamed
up an idea that put her, and her distant state, on the impeachment
map.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to square the Constitutional circle of convicting the
president without removing him, she devised the ingenious
``findings of fact'' that would allow senators to put Clinton's
offenses on record, then vote for his acquittal.
</P>
<P>
   After flourishing briefly, the idea was quashed, by the
one-dimensional male majority _ but she presented it well, for all
that.
</P>
<P>
   BEST PLAYER IN MORE THAN ONE ROLE: A tie between the Republican
chairman of the House judiciary committee, Henry Hyde, 74,
representative from Illinois, and the Democratic doyen of the
Senate, Robert Byrd, 81, of West Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde, whose name was never mentioned without the qualification
``respected'' was exposed on the eve of his committee's hearings as
a clandestine adulterer and family-breaker, but went on to spirited
performances, wrapping together Biblical texts, the Gettysburg
Address, ``A Man for All Seasons,'' and a letter from a penitent
schoolboy.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd successfully carried off the epic feat of sponsoring a
motion to dismiss the charges against Clinton as unsubstantiated,
and a week later stating with equal assurance that he was convinced
of his guilt. Well done, Robert.
</P>
<P>
   BEST PERFORMANCE IN A CAMEO ROLE: Chief Justice of the United
States, William Rehnquist, 74.
</P>
<P>
   With a proper sense of occasion, Rehnquist had copied the gold
stripes on his black gown from a performance of ``Iolanthe,'' but
remained himself throughout, attracting criticism for wearing his
gown too informally, by leaving it open.
</P>
<P>
   He kept the faith with his legendary taciturnity, compensating
with a mean performance on the gavel. More moderator than judge, as
the impeachment trial required, Rehnquist nonetheless handed down
two landmark decisions.
</P>
<P>
   He enhanced the atmosphere of his court by allowing the senators
to call themselves ``senators'' rather than ``jurors,'' and he
memorably ruled against the Majority leader's call for a coffee
break. &QL; 
