<SLUG> BC-MOISEYEV-DANCE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOLK TROUPE IS FOUNDER'S LIFE _ EVEN AT 93
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WAYNE LEE GAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If there's proof that art endures while all else changes, it's
in the career of Igor Moiseyev, 93, who founded the Moiseyev Dance
Company in Moscow in 1936.
</P>
<P>
   One invasion, several regimes and a complete counterrevolution
later, Moiseyev, who started the company under Stalin (for whom the
company danced on several occasions), is still going strong.
</P>
<P>
   Though no longer state-supported as it was under the Soviet
government, the Moiseyev Dance Company is currently touring the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Catching Moiseyev by telephone in Jacksonville Beach, Fla.,
recently, we asked him the secret of his longevity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The answer is work,'' he replied, speaking through interpreter
Tanya Sheppard.
</P>
<P>
   Moiseyev, who began his career as a dancer in the Bolshoi
Ballet, quit dancing when he founded the new company, in order to
devote himself to choreography and to training the dancers.
Although the company's idioms are inspired by folk dance, Moiseyev
insists that it is not a folk dance company. Typically, the dancers
are trained in the company's attached school, in the classical
ballet style, starting at age 12 or 13, and join the main company
at about 16.
</P>
<P>
   The classical training ``makes them more fluid,'' says Moiseyev,
who not only tours with the company but also does its choreography
and drops in on class daily. ``I insist on that.''
</P>
<P>
   But the folk influence, drawing on the dozens of ethnic groups
within the old Soviet Union, is what makes the company unique and
what made it a cohesive influence under the Soviet regime. Moiseyev
traveled around the Soviet Union observing folk dance, and then
incorporated it into his ballets for the company.
</P>
<P>
   Starting with 30 dancers, Moiseyev eventually built the company
to more than 200, with a resident accompanying instrumental
ensemble. They traveled around the Soviet Union for decades, and
made their first tour appearances outside the Soviet Union in 1955.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, like most formerly state-supported ensembles in
Russia, the Moiseyev Company tours as a way of earning hard
currency from abroad. The current touring company includes almost
80 dancers and appears with taped accompaniment when traveling.
Both on tour and in residence in Moscow, the company performs with
minimal props and scenery, colorful costumes _ and great
theatricality in the dances.
</P>
<P>
   But the demands of travel and the fall of the communist regime
have had a positive influence. Though he no longer scours the
Soviet countryside for folk dances as he once did, Moiseyev now
looks beyond the former Soviet borders for inspiration: The current
repertory includes an Italian-inspired ``Tarantella'' and an
``Egyptian Dance.'' And this may be the key to the company's
continued existence as an ambassador of dance in a world of
constantly shifting politics.
</P>
<P>
   (Wayne Lee Gay is classical music critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7756, or e-mail:
wlgay(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
