<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FALL-FASHION-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FALL FASHION IS MOLDED, BONDED, STIFF AND LEATHERY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SUSAN PHINNEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Clothes with attitude and bold silhouettes are
marching up and down runways here as fashion designers preview
their fall '99 collections to retailers and the media this week.
</P>
<P>
   Cookie-cutter shapes, stiff fabrics, herds of leather, even a
couple of hoop skirts have been shown. Soft and cuddly these
clothes are not.
</P>
<P>
   It appears designers are rediscovering construction. Bodices are
boned. Leather suits are often sleek and shiny. Skirts have
everything from bustle-like back flaps to seams that curve around
the body. Sometimes these seams are topstitched, as if the designer
is eager to flaunt them.
</P>
<P>
   Take the collection Donna Karan created for her DKNY label. She
refers to her pant shapes as ``molded.'' That means they're
straight, tight and stiff-looking. Bonded fabrics are used for
skirts and for jackets with dolman sleeves. Even the padded
versions appear stiff. The result is jackets that look as if they
could stand without a hanger or body inside, and A-line skirts
resembling little triangles.
</P>
<P>
   According to the program, Karan's message was ``an urban study
of tech and nature.'' To the observer, however, it appeared to be a
group of costumes for laboratory workers in an old sci-fi film.
Maybe that's because she used so many white fabrics. White,
apparently, is now a fall color.
</P>
<P>
   Yeohlee is another designer who's fond of straightforward,
geometric shapes, but they're more supple. Her straight little
shifts, zip-front jackets and comfortable-looking coats come off as
chic and simple _ a combination that's not accidental. It takes a
great pattern, subtle tailoring, superb craftsmanship and quality
fabric to pull off such wearable shapes.
</P>
<P>
   For this designer, that meant wool gaberdine, wool jersey and a
wool that had been given a puckered texture.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the sleekest, most sophisticated clothes shown this week
come from a British designer showing here for the first time.
Tomasz Starzewski's collection of leather suits, lavish fur trims
and bejeweled cashmere T-shirts had a kind of old-fashioned
Hollywood glamour. Models wore leather gloves, leather hats and
very, very high heels.
</P>
<P>
   Starzewski is a favorite of Sophie Rhys-Jones, the fiancee of
Britain's Prince Edward. She was wearing one of the designer's
suits when the engagement was announced.
</P>
<P>
   Will he design her wedding gown? That's what some are wondering.
And Starzewski did happen to close his show with not one, but three
bridal gowns: all ivory, and all feathered.
</P>
<P>
   Lavish fur trims were also featured in the Carolina Herrera
show. The fur collars were so big they looked like an entire stole
had been slung around a neckline. They were held in place by silk
cords tied neatly in the back.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the starchiness in fall shapes comes from the fabric.
Leather, double-faced satin, felt (used by designer Marc Jacobs for
coats) and some high-tech synthetics aren't known for their draping
qualities. Put luggage-caliber nylon in a coat and it's going to
stand up to the world.
</P>
<P>
   If it seems a bit early to be previewing fall fashions, it is.
This is the first time American designers have shown before
collections in Milan, Paris and London. Several months ago the
Council of Fashion Designers of America decided to go first,
claiming the traditional previews set in early April didn't allow
them time to deliver goods as early as stores demanded.
</P>
<P>
   In reality it's more likely American designers were tired of
being last _ and sometimes accused of copying their European
counterparts.
</P>
</TEXT>
