<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RADIO-AUSTIN-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARRESTING RADIO HOAX COLLARS LISTENERS, TOO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN AUSTIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Police in the studio. Dead air. DJs on the way to jail in cuffs.
More dead air. On paper, it sounds like the recipe for broadcast
disaster.
</P>
<P>
   But listeners who tuned in to Metroplex radio station KEGL FM
around 10 p.m. one recent Friday heard an entertaining little hoax
when DJs Kramer and Twitch were seemingly collared on the job.
</P>
<P>
   The overgrown delinquents were not only arrested, but filmed by
a ``TV news crew,'' then dragged out in cuffs. Then, the only other
guy left at the station had to call the program director to explain
it all _ on the air.
</P>
<P>
   The bust was ostensibly the result of some outrageous, perhaps
illegal, prank call Kramer and Twitch had made earlier in the
evening. Of course, it was an act, but who knew for sure?
</P>
<P>
   For listeners who don't mind a little nonsense, the hoax _
engineered by morning KEGL jock Russ Martin as a payback for an
attempted car-towing prank by Kramer and Twitch _ was a nice
example of how a silly radio shtick can still create the old
``theater of the mind.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Granted, it wasn't Orson Welles-level stuff. But love 'em or
not, the hijinks helped Kramer and Twitch practically double their
market share in their first full ratings book.
</P>
<P>
   The pair, who did a stint on sister station KDMX FM before
management moved them to the Eagle, are No. 3 among all Fort
Worth-Dalles listeners age 12 and up, according to the fall
quarterly rating book.
</P>
<P>
   ``They get pretty crazy sometimes,'' program director Greg
Stevens said. ``But there's a little bit of junior-high boy in lots
of men 25 to 54.''
</P>
<P>
   The station's been in need of some good news. These guys dumped
Howard Stern in 1997, a decision that cost the rock station in the
ratings.
</P>
<P>
   And although the Eagle has landed on some decent ratings,
Stevens isn't through tinkering. He's not promising to reconnect
listeners to Stern, but called the Stern firing a ``debacle.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That was before I got here, so I'm allowed to say that,'' he
said, roundly dissing the now-gone owners. ``I told my wife, as
radio owners go, they make a great insurance company.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of morning radio, there's a new wheel on KRNB/105.7
FM's drive time. And in addition to Chicago native Joe Soto,
listeners should also hear some musical differences. And coming
soon: a taller tower, which will allow them to hit target
demographics in places such as south Oak Cliff.
</P>
<P>
   The classic R&AMP;B will continue at night but, for the most part,
program director Al Payne will leave the oldies to the likes of
KTXQ/102.1 FM. That's what the focus groups want, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're telling us they appreciate their oldies,'' he said of
his focus group listeners, ``but they don't want to `feel' old.''
</P>
<P>
   Good point. Fortunately, guys like Kramer and Twitch seem to
know that although we all age, it's never too late to get on the
radio and act immature for your age.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
