<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-HUSKIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUSKIES IN A RAREFIED STATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Phase One is over. The University of Connecticut made its run,
holding the No. 1 spot in the national men's basketball rankings
for 10 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   A loss to Syracuse Feb. 1 knocked the Huskies to No. 2, though
they have run off three straight wins since then.
</P>
<P>
   It is unlikely the Huskies will climb back to No. 1 soon, and in
fact, it is still difficult for many longtime observers of the
program to fathom how they attained such a lofty status in the
first place.
</P>
<P>
   You may question _ as many have _ whether the Huskies were a
legitimate No. 1 team. But no one can question their place among
the elite of college basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Jim Calhoun's team has been too consistent over the past
two seasons _ winning 54 of 60 games _ to be considered unworthy.
</P>
<P>
   Skepticism goes deeper than that, tracing back to when the
school was known as Connecticut Agriculture College and basketball
was something to do between football and baseball seasons; it was a
time when a big achievement for the Huskies was beating the
University of Rhode Island or Holy Cross or Providence, and it was
an honor to be regarded as the best team in New England.
</P>
<P>
   For longtime Husky watchers who remember those days, it
stretches the imagination to ponder how far the program has come.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the 20 years the Big East has been in existence, we've had
a lot of Cinderella stories,'' said conference commissioner Mike
Tranghese, who can talk about the success of Georgetown and St.
John's in the early 1980s, Villanova's national championship run in
1985 (when the Big East sent three teams to the Final Four), Seton
Hall's magic run to the title game in 1989, and Syracuse and
Providence getting to the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the emergence of UConn is the most amazing feat of all.
They are truly a national program now. And not just in men's
basketball. You look across the board at women's basketball and
everything they do. It's been phenomenal.''
</P>
<P>
   The link between UConn's emergence to national contender and the
growth of the Big East is undeniable. It's also remarkable,
considering that former commissioner Dave Gavitt had to politick
hard to get the Huskies in as a charter member in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought there was potential for growth there,'' said Gavitt.
``But some of the schools had to be convinced.''
</P>
<P>
   Convinced. Coerced. Whatever.
</P>
<P>
   Gavitt, like most people, thought the upside would be a nice
solid program that would represent the league well. Like most
people, he didn't foresee the quantum leap to a perennial Top 10
program that UConn has made under Calhoun. He recently became the
winningest coach in school history, surpassing Hugh Greer, who
compiled a 286-112 (.719) record from 1946-63 during what was then
regarded as the golden age of Huskies basketball, when they
competed evenly with every team in New England and occasionally
rose to national prominence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never in my wildest dreams did I foresee what Jimmy has done
in making the program so successful on a national level,'' said
Gavitt. ``We're talking about Storrs, Conn., not Carolina, Duke,
Kentucky, or UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the program was destitute when Calhoun took over from
Dom Perno in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The evolution of UConn basketball had been steady, dating back
to the turn of the century, when CAC was literally a cow college,
stuck in the hills of the northwestern part of the state. The
nearest train station was 3 miles away in Eagleville, and once
winter enveloped the area, there was precious little to do. Some
students paid their tuition by bringing eggs from their chicken
farms to school and selling them.
</P>
<P>
   The administration thought the new sport of basketball was an
``interesting game to watch'' and would provide a diversion between
fall and spring.
</P>
<P>
   Slowly, the Huskies, as they were soon called, developed a
reputation as a nice little New England team, though no threat to
regional powers such as Rhode Island, Holy Cross (stlll the only
New England school to win a national championship), and Providence.
</P>
<P>
   That started to change after World War II when Greer returned to
his alma mater. In 17 seasons, his teams won 12 Yankee Conference
championships and received seven NCAA tournament bids.
</P>
<P>
   The interest level was intense, as it is now. Husky basketball
was the main game in the state, and sellout crowds at the old
Hawley Armory and The Hangar, the Field House, and now Gampel
Pavilion, were common.
</P>
<P>
   The highlights were confined to the region, though, such as
February 1954, when the Huskies came to the Worcester Auditorium
and ended Holy Cross's 47-game home winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   While the success was appreciated, it had a price tag. In 1961,
the program took a major hit when Jack Rose, a three-year
letterman, was indicted in a point-shaving scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Greer's reign ended tragically on Jan. 14, 1963, when he died of
a massive heart attack after a game of handball with assistant
coach George Wighton.
</P>
<P>
   But the Husky beat continued, still on a regional basis. The
hiring of Dee Rowe in March 1969 signified a new direction. Rowe
recruited black players from Connecticut's major cities, keeping
the best players in state, a major goal for any state school.
</P>
<P>
   Rowe, who stepped aside for health reasons in 1979, credits
Calhoun with the Huskies' current elevation in status.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``What Jim has done is take them to the promised land,'' said
Rowe, who remains at the university as a special adviser on
athletics. ``He has put them in rarefied air. When I was there, we
were working like crazy to get into the Final Four in New England.
Now the goal is to get into the Final Four in the country _ not
only that, but to win it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were strictly regional. We had no goals of winning the
national championship. We were strictly a bus league, going to
places like Orono, Burlington, Providence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The change came when we entered the Big East and built Gampel
Pavilion. The commitment was there from the administration and from
Jim. What he has done _ to see us something like seventh in the
country in total wins for the past 10 years _ is mind-boggling.
It's beyond comprehension.''
</P>
<P>
   The transformation came slowly, guided by Calhoun's persistence
and willingness to go anywhere in the world in search of players.
He has gone to Israel and plucked such stars as Nadav Henefeld and
Doron Sheffer. He has gone to Senegal to recruit 6-foot-11-inch
junior forward Souleymane Wane. He has gone to Katy, Texas, to get
6-11 center Jake Voskuhl.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was almost like it had been dormant waiting for a guy like
Jim Calhoun to come here and get a total commitment from the
university,'' said Rowe.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's interesting to see how the change in perception took
place,'' said Boston University coach Dennis Wolff, who played two
seasons for Rowe and Perno. ``We were competitive in New England,
but Providence and Holy Cross were thought to be a cut above
everybody else. Now it's UConn and UMass and more recently UConn by
itself. Not only in the region, but as a national power.''
</P>
<P>
   The defining moments include winning the National Invitation
Tournament in 1988 by beating Ohio State.
</P>
<P>
   ``The table-setter,'' Calhoun called it. ``That gave us
legitimacy. All of a sudden, we were making a little national
noise.''
</P>
<P>
   It became a lot of noise in 1990. The Huskies won the Big East
for the first time. Then came the first Miracle in the Meadowlands
_ a 71-70 win over Clemson in the NCAA East Regional semifinals,
highlighted by Tate George's last-second shot.
</P>
<P>
   With UConn trailing by a point and less than two seconds left,
Calhoun's will and George's skill prevailed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jim Calhoun got us in the huddle and told us we were going to
win the game,'' said George.
</P>
<P>
   Two days later, the miracle went the other way when Duke's
Christian Laettner made a last-second shot to beat the Huskies,
79-78, depriving them of a trip to the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   The loss stung until thousands of UConn fans greeted the team on
its arrival in Storrs that night.
</P>
<P>
   ``You mended those broken hearts,'' said Calhoun, fighting back
tears himself.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, with the exception of 1992-93 and 1996-97, UConn has
been a player in the national picture at the end of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basketball is big at Connecticut,'' said Richard Hamilton,
last season's Big East Player of the Year. ``That's all people
think about. I like the style of play. Storrs is a college town.''
</P>
<P>
   It's more than that. It's become like Chapel Hill and Durham,
N.C., and Lexington, Ky.: a mecca for basketball talent. It's the
lure of the Big East, the lure of a shot at the national
championship, the lure of playing for Calhoun, the former
Northeastern coach who has proven he can win at any level and get
his players to the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``We look at basketball as the front porch of the university,''
said athletic director Lew Perkins.
</P>
<P>
   The odds are still against UConn winning a national
championship, perhaps even of making the Final Four. But that does
not diminish what the Huskies and Calhoun have accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have,'' said Gavitt, with as much admiration as
amazement, ``carried the Big East in the 1990s.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
