<HEADLINE>
OOPS, I'VE GOT ANOTHER KARMA THING COMING  
 (EMBARGOED FOR THURSDAY, FEB. 18) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LAURI NOTARO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - A couple of months ago, I wrote a nasty letter to
``This Old House'' because I didn't like how a Victorian mansion
was being restored. After I mailed it, I realized that, because I
was being so petty, karma _ which returns to you ten-fold _ was
going to be brutal. I now believe that the following letters are a
portion of my penance.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Laurie: You recently printed a letter (Dec. 31) in which a
reader (Unsigned, Scottsdale) corrected you on your use of the
phrase ``you have another think coming.'' I have to say that by
publicly insisting you were right, and Unsigned was wrong, you
really ``stepped in it.''
</P>
<P>
   And if you still don't believe this, I challenge you to come up
with a sentence in which you can correctly utilize the phrase ``you
have another thing coming.'' After considerable thought, the only
one I can think of is, ``You ordered two things in the mail, and we
only sent you one, so you have another thing coming.'' Hardly a
common phrase in the English language. I think you owe Unsigned a
public apology. ``Thing again.'' - David Heward, Mesa, Ariz &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dear Dave: Oh boy, here we go AGAIN, and this time, you want to
CHALLENGE me. Dear God. This is more torture than having to change
out for PE in seventh grade! Dave, in 1982, Judas Priest released
``Screaming With a Vengeance,'' and there was a song on that album,
``You've Got Another Thing Coming,'' that became a pretty big hit
that everyone knew the words to. Turn your radio to KZZP and I bet
you'll hear it within an hour. Doesn't mean that Judas Priest wrote
``The Elements of Style,'' but it is common usage, and folks,
generally speaking, have no problem understanding it.
</P>
<P>
   At the Web site for Roget's Thesaurus of English Words and
Phrases (if you still don't believe me, it's www.thesaurus.com/), I
did a search on both phrases. ``Another think coming'' produced
``WORDS RELATING TO THE VOLUNTARY POWERS; INDIVIDUAL VOLITION'' and
``another thing coming'' produced ``WORDS RELATING TO THE
INTELLECTUAL FACULTIES; FORMATION OF IDEAS.'' So see? We're all
right, we're all wrong, and we're all bored to death of this
subject. In fact, I'm naming this entire chapter of my life ``The
Stupidest Fight I Ever Had With People I Don't Know,'' and am
officially closing the book.
</P>
<P>
   And sure, Dave, I will absolutely apologize: Norm, Steve and
``This Old House,'' I'm very, very sorry, and I SWEAR I'll never,
EVER do it again.
</P>
<P>
   Letter to the Rep editors: We have a problem with Written Off by
Laurie Notaro. She shouldn't put down people who are trying to quit
smoking and make themselves healthy. We're in the '90s and it's
really a shame that people are still addicted to tobacco. The
statistics have shown that it does cause lung cancer and a few of
my friends have died from lung cancer, and it's not too funny. And
about making fun of little old ladies _ she's going to be a little
old lady herself someday, and I'm sure people are going to be
making fun of her. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Susie, Phoenix
</P>
<P>
   Dear Susie: When I was in college, sometimes I drank too much. I
usually ended up hurting myself by falling down on train tracks and
busting my head open, falling down the stairs or falling out of a
car and hitting my head on a big rock.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the hooch, my brain signals were getting all mixed up
and crazy, but eventually I figured out that if I covered one eye,
I understood my environment better _ mainly because there was now
only one of them _ and my injuries decreased dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   Susie, I think you should start reading these columns _ in fact,
start reading everything _ with one eye. You can use your hand to
do this, or create an attractive and vibrantly colored eye patch.
Be creative. You can add lace and decorate it with splashes of
metallic puff paint or shiny sprinkles. While I'm not suggesting
you were drunk when you read the column or wrote the letter, to be
on the safe side, I'd steer clear of any train tracks, stairs or
big rocks.
</P>
<P>
   In the column you wrote your letter about, (begin ital) I (end
ital)am the person who is trying to quit smoking; therefore, (begin
ital) I (end ital) am making fun of (begin ital) myself, (end ital)
and that's (begin ital) OK. (end ital) I'm allowed to do that. I
know lung cancer isn't funny, and that's why I'm (begin ital)
quitting. (end ital) And I don't have to wait until I'm old for
people to make fun of me, because that already happens (begin ital)
now. (end ital)
</P>
<P>
   Just to make sure we understand each other, let's take a simple
yet enjoyable quiz about what we've learned today:
</P>
<P>
   1) The person trying to quit smoking is: a) Laurie Notaro; b)
Susie; c) Norm.
</P>
<P>
   2) Laurie is quitting because: a) it's unhealthy; b) she has
only one eye; c) trains and large rocks frighten her.
</P>
<P>
   3) Laurie thinks cancer is: a) not funny; b) the Spanish word
for ``meat store''; c) a very big crab up in the sky.
</P>
<P>
   4) From now on, if I, Susie, read Written Off, I will do so: a)
with one eye; b) drunk; c) with two eyes, misunderstand the content
and write a mean letter about Laurie Notaro to her boss.
</P>
<P>
   Good luck, Susie. I hope the world becomes a new and less
confusing place for you.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Laurie: The reason for this letter is your article on
smoking really interested me. I began smoking at the age of 26
after I had all of my four children. I was married to a controlling
husband and did it out of spite. Little did I know how hard it was
going to be to quit. I finally did it eight years ago, but 10
months ago I had the craving again, so I went out and bought
Nicorette. That was the biggest mistake I ever did. I am hooked on
it, have tried everything to get off it, but nothing seems to work.
I'd give anything to get rid of this bad gum. It's rotted out my
teeth and now I have to have them out.
</P>
<P>
   It makes my stomach hurt and all kinds of bad things happen to
you. If you know of any way at all how to get off this stuff, I
would be very grateful to you. I even wrote to the company and have
not gotten a reply as of yet. I am going on 60 years old and I know
I still have a good many years left in me. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Roslyn, Yuma, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Roslyn: One time a tooth came out of my own head as I was
eating a Gummy Bear on my 30th birthday, so I know how it feels.
It's icky and sad. But look on the bright side of things: You won't
have to floss anymore, and you won't have to worry that there might
be a piece of spinach on your front tooth when you're talking to
someone cute.
</P>
<P>
   But I do want you to get yourself clean. Honestly, I'd talk to a
doctor or quit cold turkey. If you've given birth four times,
sister, you already know you can do anything. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Laurie Notaro is a freelance writer. Send comments about her column
to the Rep, P.O. Box 2245 NF-19, Phoenix, AZ 85002 or by e-mail at
laurienotaro(at)usa.net. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
