<HEADLINE>
REGGIE WHITE'S DEFENDERS TURN PLOWSHARES INTO SWORDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GWEN KNAPP  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The advertisement ran in USA Today: ``In tribute
to Reggie White,'' it said, with a picture of the recently retired
Green Bay Packer below, smiling under the words: ``A man of God
needs but one defense.''
</P>
<P>
   A short letter followed, signed by more than 100 NFL players,
including Player of the Year Randall Cunningham, Atlanta safety
Eugene Robinson, Carolina linebacker Kevin Greene and San
Francisco's Merton Hanks.
</P>
<P>
   The letter started by lauding White's football success. Off the
field, it said, ``the world has often tested the strength of his
character and his commitment to Godly principles of behavior.'' The
conclusion was bold-faced: ``So get ready, America, because we're
standing with Reggie to defend the Gospel.''
</P>
<P>
   The point, however carefully veiled, seemed clear. White has
been criticized for his brand of Christianity only once. He took up
the anti-gay cause last spring, using religion as a cover for
bigotry.
</P>
<P>
   Now a bunch of football players are supporting him. It's not all
that surprising, really, given how many NFL players praise Jesus
after a touchdown, or gather at midfield to pray after a game. In
the last 10 years, religion has become as much a part of football
culture as the end-zone dance.
</P>
<P>
   But the tone of this ad last week evoked another tradition of
the game, the need to dominate, to be forever at war. In place of
God's humble servants, we have schoolyard bullies.
</P>
<P>
   On the field, they use their bodies as weapons. Off the field,
they use their fame. Religion is their steroid, used for
unprescribed means, creating bogus muscle.
</P>
<P>
   This is not meant to discount the spirituality of athletes
grateful for their health, for their superior physical gifts, and
for the joy that sports offers. For the most part, Reggie White
seemed to fit that mold _ charitable, decent, a moral beacon to his
teammates.
</P>
<P>
   But he also had an alarming tendency to make football success
sound like validation of Christian grace. Green Bay's Super Bowl
victory was God's will. White's back healed because God wanted him
to play another year.
</P>
<P>
   But if God spoke through Reggie White's football career, what
did it mean last month, when he finished in defeat in the gay
capital of America?
</P>
<P>
   Don't expect his supporters to answer that one. Their religion
is one of convenience, of self-justification. If it doesn't make
them winners, they take their toys and go home.
</P>
<P>
   At least, that's how Bill Horn portrays them. He lives in Iowa
and helps arrange public-speaking appearances for White. They
connected last year, after White kicked off his anti-gay campaign.
</P>
<P>
   It was Horn who put together the ad in USA Today. He said that
athletes around the league had started calling him last spring,
after White's holy war began. He cited Kyle Brady of the Jets as
one of the leaders. Horn found an ad agency to write the text,
persuaded three religious organizations to underwrite the cost and
then sent copies of the ad to team chaplains around the league to
recruit signatures.
</P>
<P>
   Horn was asked whether the players planned to defend
Christianity by asking the NFL to stop playing on Sundays. He
seemed to consider the question impertinent.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people work on Sundays,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But what about keeping holy the Sabbath?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, that depends on the Sabbath as defined by the
Christianity that you espouse,'' Horn said. He was referring to
Seventh-day Adventists, and sounding very Clinton-esque for a man
who has no love of Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Defending the gospel, in other words, isn't a priority if it
means offending the NFL and risking the huge paychecks it doles
out.
</P>
<P>
   There are some voices of reason in the NFL. One of them belongs
to Leigh Steinberg, the most powerful agent in the game. He insists
that his clients perform public service, and he tries to position
them all as role models.
</P>
<P>
   ``They trigger imitative behavior,'' he said. ``They have an
especially profound effect on young, adolescent males, and this is
a group that is in the middle of forming attitudes and behavior.
And while I think it's laudable to model Christianity and spiritual
values to that group, this is exactly the danger group in terms of
intolerance. You know, teen-age boys have been a major source of
anti-gay violence. So I think that athletes have to be particularly
careful that comments they make not be deemed toleration for
anti-gay violence.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently Horn is willing to allow certain sins to slide.
</P>
<P>
   Take Eugene Robinson's alleged pre-Super Bowl dalliance with an
undercover vice cop. After the incident, Horn said, he never
considered removing Robinson's name from the list of signatures.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all not perfect. We all make mistakes,'' Horn said.
</P>
<P>
   Nor did Kevin Greene's sideline attack on an assistant coach
disqualify him from enlisting in the holy war. Now, if he'd kissed
the man instead ...
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Gwen Knapp is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
