<HEADER>
A7386 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      02-16 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TAX CUT FOLLIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ By launching a national crusade for a 10 percent
across-the-board tax cut this week, Senate Majority Leader Trent
Lott is getting too far out in front of his Republican troops.
</P>
<P>
   The odds are that when he looks around, he will find few
soldiers standing behind him. Republicans traditionally love tax
cuts, but this time not necessarily this one.
</P>
<P>
   It is odd that Lott, normally a cautious fellow, is sticking his
neck out on an issue that divides rather than unifies his party.
</P>
<P>
   He is eager to change the political subject from the impeachment
charade that consumed Washington and hurt the Republicans in the
polls. But the overarching need of the GOP congressional majority
is to demonstrate that it can govern without becoming sidetracked
by an intraparty ruckus.
</P>
<P>
   In January, the Senate Republican caucus voted to give broad tax
cuts a high priority. House Budget Committee Chairman John Kasich
quickly introduced a similar plan. But the idea had already lost
steam by the time Lott began a series of town meetings Monday to
promote it as the centerpiece of a new GOP agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the projected federal budget surplus, there are plenty
of warning signals that a substantial across-the-board tax cut has
no wings.
</P>
<P>
   One important sign came recently from Senate Appropriations
Committee Chairman Ted Stevens, R-Alaska, who announced flatly that
he prefers targeted tax reductions that would help families with
specific needs, such as education expenses. ``I don't really favor
the across-the-board (approach),'' he said in a CNN interview.
</P>
<P>
   The charm of targeted tax cuts is that they might actually pass
Congress and be signed by President Clinton, giving both Democrats
and Republicans an achievement on which to run in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, most Democrats and moderates are not fans of
across-the-board cuts. And without their support, GOP conservatives
cannot carry the day. They must move to the center, and that means
compromising.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has been clever at stealing traditional GOP themes by
repackaging them with middle-class ribbons. In spite of his
impeachment troubles, he seems to have done it again.
</P>
<P>
   The president included specific tax cuts in his State of the
Union address, from breaks for child care to help for long-term
care for the elderly and disabled. Many Democrats and GOP moderates
endorse those proposals, in addition to some others such as wiping
out estate taxes and the marriage tax penalty.
</P>
<P>
   The president has been persuasive in labeling across-the-board
cuts as a sop to the wealthy, who would benefit proportionately
more than lower and middle-income families. He has transformed the
issue into a test between saving money for Social Security or
giving it away to the rich.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats have also countered GOP complaints that Americans
are overtaxed by noting that while overall tax revenues have gone
up in the booming economy, the rate has actually gone down for
ordinary folks.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, voters are not clamoring for broad tax cuts. They tell
the pollsters that other goals are more important, such as spending
on education and Social Security or reducing the national debt.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional Republicans made it a point of honor to ignore the
polls that indicated a majority of voters did not approve of their
drive to remove Clinton from office. Even their own party
consultants now agree that such indifference to the public will was
stupid politics. The GOP would be foolish to let their image as
runaway legislators harden by ignoring the voters again so soon.
</P>
<P>
   According to the New York Times, Lott's initial appearance
before about 500 people in Warren, Mich., on President's Day fell
somewhat short of a rousing rally for an across-the-board tax cut.
When asked who would like to pay less in taxes, dozens of those in
the audience failed to reflexively raise their hands. In interviews
afterward, many expressed more concern about reducing the national
debt than reducing taxes.
</P>
<P>
   This begins to look like another Republican miscalculation,
beating a political drum to a rhythm nobody hears. Lott may in fact
be having second thoughts. He said after his speech that maybe
Congress could pass both the broad tax cuts and the targeted ones.
And then what revenues would be left to pay for Social Security?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
