<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-16 17:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7396 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LAYOFFS-STEPS-HNS &LR;      02-16 1572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAYOFFS-STEPS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAID OFF: WHAT TO DO BEFORE AND IF IT HAPPENS TO YOU  

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   By PAMELA YIP 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The sight of energy companies announcing enormous
layoffs can send chills down the spines of even the best of
workers.
</P>
<P>
   Even if you've been doing a great job, you are likely to fear
that the ax will fall, throwing your financial life into disarray.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than just stew about the possible loss of your job, take
some positive steps now to gain control of your life in case the
worst happens.
</P>
<P>
   Even if you're spared from a layoff, you will be better off
having gone through these financial exercises.
</P>
<P>
   ``Take action. The more control you take over the situation in
the beginning, the less stress you will have when the actual event
takes place,'' said Stephanie Cummings, a financial adviser at
Morgan Stanley Dean Witter in Houston, which has conducted seminars
for workers at the United Paperworkers International Union in
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The goal here isn't complicated. You want to see now if you
could pay the bills if your income took a hit.
</P>
<P>
   The key steps include:
</P>
<P>
   _ Consider your living expenses. Could you cut your spending if
you needed to in order to live on a smaller income?
</P>
<P>
   _ Anticipate any big financial hits in the near future, such as
a bill for insurance or income taxes.
</P>
<P>
   _ Determine if you have any spare cash to make up for a possible
decline in income.
</P>
<P>
   Even if you escape this round of layoffs, you'll have a better
idea of where your money is going, which is the first and often the
hardest step in building for the future.
</P>
<P>
   _ Start with a financial checkup. Consider how much a layoff
will hurt your total income. Factor in your severance package,
which could include the company paying for your health insurance.
If you're married, factor in your spouse's income.
</P>
<P>
   Include how much you will be receiving in unemployment benefits,
but don't count on them solely to get you through this.
</P>
<P>
   Jobless benefits are taxable and they're short-term.
</P>
<P>
   After considering how much money you've got coming in, calculate
how much money you'll need in your checking account to pay the
bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need to have an understanding of what type of pressure do
I need to put on myself to find a new job?'' said John Eadie, a
partner in the personal financial counseling group at accounting
firm Ernst &AMP; Young in Houston, which is providing financial
counseling to employees who lost their jobs in the BP Amoco
layoffs. ``You need to understand how much in terms of savings I
have accumulated to convert that into a number of months before I
need to find a job.''
</P>
<P>
   Make a financial worksheet and put down what you spend each
month on such things as food, car needs, utilities, laundry and
cleaning, mortgage and other expenses.
</P>
<P>
   This will give you an idea of how much money you've spent.
</P>
<P>
   Put down what your bills are, how much you owe on them, the due
dates and establish a budget.
</P>
<P>
   If your income comes up short, know where you can find sources
of immediate cash, such as from savings and investments.
</P>
<P>
   ``What does it take to live on the lifestyle that you would like
to have, to continue it?'' Eadie said.
</P>
<P>
   Find part-time work you can get should the ax fall. Tap your
network of friends and business associates for job leads.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't have much cash on hand, cut your spending as much
as possible now and put the money you save in a savings account.
</P>
<P>
   ``If your company is anticipating an acquisition, a merger or
downsizing, start preparing and having at least six months of your
monthly expenditures in a savings account,'' said Sharon McLean,
executive director of Consumer Credit Counseling Service of the
Gulf Coast Area in Houston, which helps consumers with credit
problems. ``It might take you that long to find a job.''
</P>
<P>
   If your company just announced a layoff, chances are you don't
have enough time to do that.
</P>
<P>
   You may have to sell some investments and stash the money away
in a money market mutual fund, where you can get to it easily,
Eadie said.
</P>
<P>
   With stocks selling at such inflated prices now, it may be the
best time to take your profits before prices start tanking.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need to really take a look at, `Do I need to reposition
some of my investments?''' Eadie said. ``Because you need to be a
little bit more conservative because that's the money you need for
very short-term goals. If I invested that money in stocks, I would
move into cash or no more riskier (investments) than bonds until I
got back on my feet.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Tighten your belt.
</P>
<P>
   A layoff will completely throw your lifestyle for a loop, so you
need to look ahead of time for ways to cut back on spending on the
little extras.
</P>
<P>
   Stick to your budget and spend only on the essentials, such as
food, shelter, utilities and transportation. This isn't the time to
splurge on a meal at a fancy restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Involve the whole family in making sacrifices during this time
of need by doing such things as borrowing books from the library
instead of buying them and renting movies instead of going to the
theater. Remember that when you get laid off, your family also is
laid off.
</P>
<P>
   Avoid using credit cards, but if you must do so for emergencies,
use the card with the lowest interest rate. If you overdo it, you
will find yourself in a tough situation even after you've found a
job.
</P>
<P>
   _ Live off your severance pay first.
</P>
<P>
   If you have severance pay, use that as your first source of
cash.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get a severance package, it must be included in
taxable income,'' Eadie said. ``It's after-tax money, whereas if
you pulled money out of an investment account and earned capital
gains, that's money you have a choice of whether you pay taxes on
or not because you have a choice of whether to sell or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoard your severance money if possible. This pay is meant to
cover your living expenses between the time you lose your job and
when you find a new one.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have a $10,000 severance check, you want to be vigilant
that you don't take that money and buy a new car with that,'' Eadie
said. ``You need to use that just as if it was your salary.''
</P>
<P>
   Slice off a portion of that money that's equal to your monthly
salary and deposit it in your checking account to pay the bills.
Stash the rest away in a savings account or money market fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of those psychological things that, `Oh, that's my
savings account,''' Eadie said. ``It tends to make people think
about it more than if it were sitting in your checking account.''
</P>
<P>
   In handling your severance payment, be sure to calculate how
much tax you will have to pay on it and set aside enough money to
pay that tax.
</P>
<P>
   Companies typically withhold 28 percent of the severance amount
for income tax, but they're also required to withhold 1.45 percent
for Medicare tax and 6.2 percent for Social Security, Eadie said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You still may owe more if you're in a higher tax bracket, and
you need to be concerned about whether you need to make estimated
tax payments, or will you owe the difference when you file your tax
return?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't drop insurance.
</P>
<P>
   As you do your budget you will be tempted to cut your spending
by avoiding some costly premiums. It's crucial that you keep paying
for your health benefits and other necessary insurance during this
crisis period. Scrimping on health insurance premiums to save money
would be pound-foolish because one serious illness or accident will
land you in worse financial condition than before your layoff.
</P>
<P>
   If you're married, the lowest-cost option may well be to have
your spouse add you to his or her health plan at work.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, consider Cobra. That is the acronym for the law that
requires companies to tell you that you're entitled to continue
your health care coverage. The acronym stands for the Consolidated
Omnibus Budget Reconciliation Act.
</P>
<P>
   The law requires that the continuation of health coverage last
for generally 18 months, during which you, the employee, pay the
full health insurance premium, plus a 2 percent administrative fee.
</P>
<P>
   Group insurance rates are far lower than what you can find for
individual coverage, but they're still expensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to make the decision right up front without
looking at both of your options,'' said Michelle Miears, a
principal at Buck Consultants in Houston, an employee benefits
consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   Some plans may not allow you to get on your spouse's health plan
until your Cobra coverage has expired, she said.
</P>
<P>
   If you're a member of a labor union, contact the union because
it may have negotiated arrangements on continuation of health
insurance with your employer, Miears said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes (benefits) end immediately on your last day of work
or they may go for the rest of the month,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't try to go it alone.
</P>
<P>
   Take advantage of outplacement assistance and job retraining
programs your employer, union and community organizations offer.
</P>
<P>
   This may also be the perfect time to go into an entirely
different career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you can find a better time to change your
career, to start your own business,'' said Greg Nakanishi, who was
laid off from Tenneco in 1990. He started his own business, GN
Resources in Houston, a human resources consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
