<HEADER>
A7402 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HAWAII-COOKING-ART-63     02-16 1357
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAWAII-COOKING-ART-635&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM QUAIL EGG TO FRIED EGG: HAWAII HIGH AND LOW 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By MARIAN BURROS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONOLULU _ Loco moco is the original fusion food. Created in the
1940s in the kitchens of Hawaii as a lunchtime alternative to
American sandwiches and more time-consuming Asian entrees, it's a
homey combination of two scoops of rice topped with both a seasoned
hamburger patty and a fried egg, all generously covered with thick
brown gravy. Thighs, watch out!
</P>
<P>
   Traditional loco moco turns up in cafes and lunch wagons all
through the islands, but in recent years, it has also morphed into
something more sophisticated, as Hawaiian chefs have converted the
old ``local food'' into Pacific Rim cuisine. Alan Wong's has its
own elegant take on loco moco, with fried rice bound with nori, the
Japanese seaweed, and crowned with a tiny shrimp-and-pork-hash
patty and a quail egg. This handsome little mouthful _ labeled mini
loco moco _ sits on a bed of reduced chicken and veal jus, giving
no clue to its lowly origins.
</P>
<P>
   At Sam Choy's, the loco moco is a crab cake on sauteed Maui
onions on top of fried rice with a shiitake butter-cream sauce. And
a chicken is responsible for the egg.
</P>
<P>
   Loco moco, like plate lunch, crack seed, manapua, Spam and poke,
is a food that bonds the islands' population of Asians, Caucasians
and Polynesians. Visitors to Hawaii may catch sight of a sign
advertising manapua or plate lunch as they are driven to an
obligatory luau, but only persistence will get them to a lunch
wagon serving loco moco.
</P>
<P>
   Natives are certain that mainlanders will make fun of ``local
food.'' With good reason. This Hawaiian version of soul food puts
McDonald's to shame: The fat-laden portions are huge, with nary a
green thing in sight. But the locals can't live without it. ``It's
comfort food,'' said Joan Clarke, food editor of The Honolulu
Advertiser. ``And we all know that fat tastes good.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, these are the same dishes that chefs like Alan Wong,
Russell Siu and Sam Choy are using as inspiration for aspects of
their very ambitious menus. ``This came about naturally,'' Wong
said. ``I should be cooking what I grew up with.''
</P>
<P>
   Hawaii's is a polyglot history: migrating Pacific islanders,
European explorers, New Englanders and Chinese, Japanese,
Portuguese, Korean, Philippine and Southeast Asian immigrants, who
came to work on the sugar and pineapple plantations. Local food
began to appear in the 1920s and '30s, when housewives, lunch-wagon
cooks and mom-and-pop shop owners made the best of what was
available and when schoolchildren, as well as plantation workers,
began trading the lunches they brought from home.
</P>
<P>
   The centerpiece of local food is plate lunch, cheerfully
described by Hawaiians as ``a heart attack on a plate'': two huge
scoops of rice (the Asian influence), a heaping portion of meat or
fish, a scoop of macaroni or potato salad with mayonnaise, and a
nice thick coating of gravy, all ``haole,'' or white American,
elements. It is to be seasoned with soy, teriyaki or hot sauce and
eaten with chopsticks or a knife and fork.
</P>
<P>
   The myriad variations reflect the national origins of the cook.
A Korean plate lunch will have Korean grilled beef and meat
dumplings; a Caucasian version will have spaghetti and meat sauce
mixed up with hot dogs and Spam. (Spam has more fans in Hawaii than
in any other state.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Hawaii is probably the only place in the world where you can
get spaghetti and meat sauce, garlic bread, two scoops of rice and
a macaroni salad all on one plate,'' Wong said.
</P>
<P>
   Choy often sticks closer to the original than chefs like Wong
do. ``I took everyday local food that everyone was ashamed of and
blew it right out of there,'' Choy said as he sat in Sam Choy's
Diamond Head, one of his eight restaurants. ``When people come to
Hawaii, you want them to have a taste of Hawaii, not froufrou
stuff.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   So his favorite plate lunch has the traditional shoyu chicken,
but it is made with five-spice powder and cilantro. The gravy is
from the pan, not the can.
</P>
<P>
   Poke (it rhymes with OK and means bite size) has also become
popular in the last 20 years. Eaten after work with a beer, it is
the casual Hawaiian version of Japanese sashimi. Morsels of raw
fish are cut into bite-size pieces and traditionally seasoned with
Hawaiian salt, chopped seaweed and ground candlenuts, called kukui.
Today, there are at least two dozens kinds of poke, ranging from
ahi tuna to octopus, with almost as many kinds of seasoning.
They're all good with beer, but Wong has taken them into another
dimension by creating a dish called Poki Pines, ahi-poke balls
encased in strips of wonton wrappers, deep-fried and served on
avocado with wasabi sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Hawaiian chefs have also taken inspiration from the luau,
particularly from kalua pig, the pit-roasted centerpiece of the
feast, usually served with poi, the bland paste made from taro
root, which is beloved only by those who have eaten it since
infancy.
</P>
<P>
   At the restaurant 3660 on the Rise, the owner, Siu, fills spring
rolls with sauteed kalua pig, made with onions and Chinese cabbage,
and serves them with a poi vinaigrette and lomi tomatoes. The
tomatoes are taken from a dish called lomilomi salmon (raw salted
salmon mixed with tomatoes and onions), another staple of the luau.
Lomilomi means to rub between the fingers.
</P>
<P>
   Manapua, the Hawaiian street-food version of Chinese steamed
pork buns filled with barbecued pork, or char siu bao, is barely
recognizable in Wong's revision. The char sui is in a tortilla, not
a bun, along with mozzarella. The whole quesadilla is grilled and
served with a tomato relish and chili oil with lemongrass and
cilantro.
</P>
<P>
   Even crack seed _ fruits dried and seasoned with sugar, salt and
star anise _has found its way to Wong's menu. Li hing mui is an
extremely sour and salty version of crack seed. Every Hawaiian
child snacks on it after school. ``You got used to the intensity,''
Wong said. ``The sides of my jaw start to hurt when I think of it.
But to us, it's like the potato chip is to you.''
</P>
<P>
   He uses the flavor in a chutney that alternates with vanilla ice
cream with Jack Daniel's on it, between layers of macadamia nut
puff pastry. The name alone is a mouthful: li hing moi
mille-feuille.
</P>
<P>
   All these innovations are the essence of the new and old Hawaii,
but don't look for them in New York, though the Honolulu chef Roy
Yamaguchi has just opened a restaurant in lower Manhattan. There is
no loco moco or manapua in any form and certainly no Spam on the
menu at Roy's New York, said Troy Guard, the executive chef.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really don't want people to think we're doing Hawaiian
food,'' he said. ``It's Euro-Asian cuisine.''
</P>
<P>
   But then again, it always was.
</P>
<P>
   SHOYU CHICKEN WITH TERI GLAZE
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``The Choy of Cooking'' by Sam Choy (Mutual
Publishing, 1996)
</P>
<P>
   Time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1 cup soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   Juice from 1 medium orange
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup mirin (Japanese rice wine)
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   3/4 teaspoon minced ginger
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon minced cilantro
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon Chinese five-spice powder
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds boneless chicken thighs
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon cornstarch
</P>
<P>
   Green onions and bean sprouts for garnish (optional).
</P>
<P>
   1. Combine soy sauce, orange juice, mirin, brown sugar, garlic,
ginger and 1/2 cup water in large skillet. Blend well. Add cilantro
and five-spice powder. Bring to a boil, add chicken, partly cover
skillet, and simmer 20 minutes or until tender. Remove chicken from
sauce. Set aside, and keep warm.
</P>
<P>
   2. Make the teri glaze, by blending the cornstarch with 2
tablespoons water into a smooth paste. Bring 1 cup of the sauce to
a boil, and stir in paste to thicken into a glaze.
</P>
<P>
   3. Brush the chicken with the glaze. Garnish with green onions
and bean sprouts.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-99 1716EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
