<DOCNO> NYT19990216.0228 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-16 17:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7407 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PIZZA-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT     02-16 0670
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PIZZA-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PIZZA ANY WAY YOU SLICE IT!': PIZZA WORTH AN EXCLAMATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By AMANDA HESSER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When it comes to pizza, it is difficult to get people to jump
out of their seats over new recipes. Perhaps that is why in ``Pizza
Any Way You Slice It!'' (Broadway Books, $20), Charles and Michele
Scicolone do nothing more emphatic than put an exclamation point in
the title.
</P>
<P>
   The book has a few enticing pictures _ bubbling fresh mozzarella
dripping down the side of a puffy pizza crust, and focaccia
sprinkled with rosemary and brushed with golden olive oil _ and a
list of classics we've all heard of.
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing really to get excited about, until you try the
recipes. If you use good-quality ingredients and follow the
instructions carefully, you find that they are not just familiar;
they are superb.
</P>
<P>
   The Scicolones have tried to make the recipes as easy as
possible without destroying their authenticity. And they have
managed to strike a good balance.
</P>
<P>
   The wine focaccia, for example, is made in the food processor,
but the dough is made with a yeasty, frothy starter and is soft and
supple. Once baked, the foccacia is crisp, fragrant and just a
little bit sour, sprinkled with the perfect amount of coarse salt
crystals.
</P>
<P>
   The pizza margherita is fresh tasting and creamy, with a pool of
fresh mozzarella and a thin slick of olive oil. Rather than asking
the reader to hunt down tomatoes in the winter, the authors offer a
tomato sauce made with canned, peeled tomatoes, good olive oil and
a little salt. It is a brave stand, and the results are
surprisingly good.
</P>
<P>
   Piadina, a flat disk of dough that is browned in a skillet and
folded around fillings _ for example, sliced prosciutto and salami,
or arugula and soft goat cheese, or sauteed greens _ is lovely and
a cinch to throw together for a weeknight dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Though it seems slightly off the point, there is also a chapter
on antipasti. In it is a recipe for olive and fennel salad _
nothing groundbreaking. The olives and fennel make a pleasant
contrast of sweetness and acidity, and a pinch of red pepper flakes
gives the salad just enough kick. But just as with the other dishes
in the book, after you try it, you want seconds. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PIADINA &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``Pizza Any Way You Slice It!'' by Charles and
Michele Scicolone
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1 hour 10 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   3{ cups unbleached all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1 cup warm water (105 to 115 degrees)
</P>
<P>
   \ cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 cup soft fresh goat cheese
</P>
<P>
   8 handfuls arugula. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. In a food processor or heavy-duty mixer, combine the flour,
salt and baking powder. Add the water and oil. Process or mix until
the dough is smooth and elastic, about 1 minute. Remove from the
machine, and knead briefly by hand on a lightly floured surface.
Shape the dough into a ball. Cover with a bowl, and let rest 20
minutes to 1 hour.
</P>
<P>
   2. Cut the dough into 8 pieces. Cover all but 1 piece with a
bowl. On a lightly floured surface, shape the piece into a ball.
With a rolling pin, roll out the dough to an 8-inch circle. Place a
piece of wax paper on a large dinner plate, and put the circle of
dough on it. Roll out the remaining dough, stacking the circles on
the plate with wax paper in between.
</P>
<P>
   3. Preheat the oven to 175 degrees. Heat a nonstick skillet over
medium-high heat. Test the temperature by flicking some droplets of
water onto the surface; if the water sizzles and evaporates
quickly, the griddle is ready. Place a circle of dough in the
skillet. Cook 30 seconds, or until the dough begins to stiffen and
turns golden brown. Flip the piadina, and brown the other side.
Place the piadina on a piece of foil in the oven, and keep warm
until serving.
</P>
<P>
   4. To serve, on each piadina, spread about 2 tablespoons of
cheese over half the circle. Place a handful of arugula on top, and
then fold the piadina in half and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 8 appetizers or 4 main courses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-99 1718EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990216.0229 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-16 17:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7408 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHEEHY-CLINTONS-AZR &LR;      02-16 1399
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHEEHY-CLINTONS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECRETS AND LIVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA YOST  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Hillary Rodham Clinton, it seems, is standing by her
man after all.
</P>
<P>
   Tammy Wynette redux. Cookie-baking optional.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the sex scandal that crippled the presidency and
devastated the Clinton marriage, Hillary appears to remain a loyal
_ if icy _ spouse. Bet that farm in Arkansas that when Bill Clinton
leaves the White House at the end of his term in 2000, he'll be
leaving with his wife.
</P>
<P>
   What happens after that is not such a sure thing, says
journalist Gail Sheehy, who has been following the Clinton union
since the campaign of 1992. Could Hillary split once they leave the
White House?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know, and I don't think she knows,'' Sheehy said.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary has not accepted the scandal docilely. She has flicked
her anger at her wayward husband. Buddy is not the only resident of
the presidential dog house.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's putting him through the wringer, and every woman
applauds that,'' Sheehy said by phone from her office in Berkeley,
Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Sheehy is one of the nation's foremost magazine writers and
author of such seminal books as ``Passages'' (1976) and ``The
Silent Passage: Menopause'' (1992).
</P>
<P>
   Sheehy wrote a comprehensive deconstruction of the Clinton
marriage, ``Hillary's Choice,'' in the January issue of ``Vanity
Fair.'' Over a five-month period of exhaustive interviews, she
gleaned the details of the rocky union from Clinton friends and
colleagues bold enough to share their insights.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary herself declined to be interviewed, Sheehy said,
although White House advisers tried to persuade her to open up.
</P>
<P>
   Scandal has taken its toll on the first lady, Sheehy said,
leaving her in no mood to bare her soul to a reporter. The
spontaneity is gone. Her smile is fixed and enigmatic. Prying eyes
are kept at bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's always been a woman with a secret,'' Sheehy said.
</P>
<P>
   With the Monica Lewinsky affair, the secret of her husband's
infamous dalliances was blown wide open.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's very deeply painful for her,'' Sheehy adds.
</P>
<P>
   As a longtime journalist and bestselling author, Sheehy knows
well of the intrusions into a celebrity's life.
</P>
<P>
   She was born Gail Henion in 1937 in Mamaroneck, N.Y. Her father
was an advertising executive, her mother a beauty
consultant-turned-homemaker.
</P>
<P>
   After marrying Albert F. Sheehy in 1960, two years after
graduating from the University of Vermont, she parlayed a stint as
a fashion consultant into a job as fashion writer for the
``Democrat and Chronicle'' in Rochester, N.Y. She came to
prominence as a tough-minded reporter while working at the ``New
York Herald Tribune'' and then as a contributing editor of ``New
York'' magazine in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   Clay Felker, ``New York'' editor and founder, became her mentor.
</P>
<P>
   In 1971, she published a series of explosive articles in ``New
York'' on prostitution. In one, she created a composite of a
prostitute when the woman she wanted to interview refused to talk.
Without Sheehy's knowledge, Felker deleted Sheehy's explanation
that this was a composite, believing it intruded on the article's
literary style.
</P>
<P>
   She must have forgiven him. In 1985, divorced from Albert
Sheehy, she married Felker and now divides her time between New
York and Berkeley, where Felker teaches in a magazine journalism
program at the University of California.
</P>
<P>
   Baby boomers and book lovers know Sheehy best for ``Passages,''
her chronicle of midlife that warned adults what lies ahead as time
marches on. Decade by decade, she spelled out the inevitable
decline when adulthood gains a foothold.
</P>
<P>
   She wrote, ``As such thoughts gather thunder, the continuity of
the life cycle is interrupted. They usher in a decade that can be
called, in the deepest sense, the Deadline Decade. Somewhere
between 35 and 45 if we let ourselves, most of us will have a
full-out authenticity crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   Years later, Sheehy would pen two books addressing the topic of
second adulthood, approaching maturity with optimism and assurances
that life can begin at any age.
</P>
<P>
   Sheehy is also known for her in-depth profiles of such global
personalities as Saddam Hussein, Margaret Thatcher, George Bush and
Mikhail Gorbachev.
</P>
<P>
   Along with her jam-packed schedule of speaking engagements, a
book about Hillary Clinton is in the works, even as other
journalists, including former ``Washington Post'' reporter Carl
Bernstein, begin penning their own Clintonographies.
</P>
<P>
   Sheehy could have the inside track with an insider's knowledge.
Since meeting Hillary six years ago, Sheehy has tended the
relationship, meeting her at least once a year at the annual New
Year's Renaissance Weekend, a gathering of political intelligentsia
on Hilton Head Island, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel I know her,'' Sheehy said.
</P>
<P>
   And to know her is to admire her: ``I think Hillary is the most
intriguing political figure on the national stage today.''
</P>
<P>
   However, 1992 was one of the last times Hillary Rodham Clinton
permitted herself to be shadowed, Sheehy said. The beleaguered
first lady has since drawn curtains around herself and her family,
finding no personal advantage in exposing them to dissection.
</P>
<P>
   Both Clintons recently expressed outrage when ``People''
magazine published an in-depth article on the relationship between
Hillary and daughter, Chelsea. Although nothing negative was
revealed in the text, Hillary felt the piece was an intrusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her instinct is always to be mum,'' Sheehy said. ``She has
always had no tolerance for people knowing about her what she
doesn't want them to know.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a strategy that fails to recognize the prominence of her
position, Sheehy said. A private life under public scrutiny is an
oxymoron that won't serve her well if, as rumored, she runs for
office once the Clintons have left the White House.
</P>
<P>
   However, although she has been touted as an attractive candidate
to run for the U.S. Senate from New York, Sheehy doubts Hillary
would tolerate the inevitable revisitation of past scandals that
would come with a campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Her post-Washington role is more likely non-political, perhaps
as head of a foundation, Sheehy said, where she could enjoy power
without fear of the smears politics can engender.
</P>
<P>
   In her ``Vanity Fair'' article, Sheehy quotes Clinton friend
Betsey Wright as saying, ``That man would lie down and kill himself
before he would let her leave him. There have been other tempt
ations, but Hillary is the love of his life.''
</P>
<P>
   While avoiding psychobabble and the temptation to analyze the
Clinton marriage from a Freudian or Oedipal perspective, Sheehy
does hint of a relationship forged between a needy man and a take-
charge woman.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is this damaged child who has never been healed,'' she
says. ``He is this id walking around.''
</P>
<P>
   The damaged child, however, developed superb political skills
the likes of which Sheehy said she has never before seen in her
lifetime _ exceeding even the celebrated charms of Ronald Reagan
and John F. Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   In marrying Hillary, Bill Clinton found his perfect complement.
She brought discipline to his emotional political style and a
toughness drawn from her own childhood, when she learned to punch
the noses of children who ill-treated her.
</P>
<P>
   Sheehy's article sums up that relationship in one pithy phrase:
``It took a Hillary to raise a president.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the Clintons are the most scrutinized couple in the
country, Americans know little about the people behind the
headlines and the sound bites.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have become stick figures,'' Sheehy said. ``I wanted to
flesh them out, to fill in some of the blanks.''
</P>
<P>
   She determined that Hillary may be a woman wronged, whose
identity has been sorely shaken, but she is no victim and no
martyr.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, Sheehy said, ``It is Hillary who is holding our
country together. It is Hillary who is holding our values together
even as her own house is being shattered by their political
enemies.''
</P>
<P>
   On New Year's Eve, Sheehy gave Hillary an advance copy of the
``Vanity Fair'' article. The magazine had gone to bed, but out of
courtesy she gave the subject of the piece a preview.
</P>
<P>
   Feedback from the White House was succinct: Hillary ``had no
reaction.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheehy was relieved.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's good news for the writer,'' she said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
