<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT NEWS ITEMS ON FOOD AND DINING 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By FLORENCE FABRICANT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ajvar, Anyone? (Now, That's Balkan)
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A food shop named Ljuljhami sounds as if it should be
selling Finnish specialties, or maybe Hawaiian. But the stock in
trade at Ljuljhami (pronounced lool-AH-mee), a tiny, white-tile
market at 4408 30th Avenue, Astoria, N.Y., is Balkan food,
especially items from the Yugoslav republic of Montenegro. It is
owned by Dino Redzic, the maitre d'hotel at the James Beard
Foundation, and his brothers, Hajaro and Ago, and sister, Emira.
</P>
<P>
   ``The name of the shop is the combination of the names of my
father and grandfather, who had a butcher shop in Plav, in
Montenegro,'' Dino Redzic said. ``We're using family recipes for
some of the things we sell.''
</P>
<P>
   Among them are several kinds of excellent, lightly smoked
salami-style beef sausages, sweet and hot, and sausages made with a
combination of beef and lamb. There is also smoked, air-dried beef,
called pastrma, which is similar to pastrami. All are $7 a pound.
</P>
<P>
   Seasoned fresh beef patties and the same meat in a sausage
shape, delicious hot off the grill, are $5 a pound. Since the shop
is only a few blocks from Grand Central Parkway, weekenders could
stop to buy these.
</P>
<P>
   Ljuljhami also sells a condiment called ajvar (pronounced
EYE-var), made from sweet red peppers and garlic, $2.49 for a
10-ounce jar. The delicious hot version goes with the meats but
could double as rouille in a bouillabaisse. Emira Redzic also makes
homemade pickled vegetables, $4 a quart, and the shop sells sour
cherry syrup, $3.99 a liter. It also caters. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Shad Season Is Here &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In this part of the country, the arrival of shad and shad roe in
the market has always been a better sign of the fading winter than
an entire nest of groundhogs. And shad is now here, from Southern
waters.
</P>
<P>
   The fish, which is related to herring and packed with tiny
bones, is rich and succulent and is usually sold filleted. It is
best cooked under a broiler or on a grill. Prices are on the steep
side, many shopkeepers say, because this is the first shad of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   Shad is now at Agata &AMP; Valentina, 1505 First Avenue (79th
Street), $7.95 a pound; Balducci's, 424 Avenue of the Americas
(Ninth Street), $12.99; Citarella, 2135 Broadway (75th Street) and
1313 Third Avenue (75th Street), $7.99; Eli's Manhattan, 1411 Third
Avenue (80th Street), $10.95; the Vinegar Factory, 431 East 91st
Street, $10.95; Fairway, 2127 Broadway (74th Street) and 2328
Twelfth Avenue (132d Street), $8.99; Grace's Marketplace, 1237
Third Avenue (71st Street), $9.99; Leonard's, 1385 Third Avenue
(78th Street), $9.95; Rosedale, 1129 Lexington Avenue (79th
Street), $7.50, and Wild Edibles, 255 Elizabeth Street (Houston
Street), $10.95.
</P>
<P>
   Most of these shops also have shad roe, good to poach and serve
in brown butter.
</P>
<P>
   Shad is also superb with a tart sorrel sauce, a dish that the
French call alose a l'oseille (pronounced ah-LOZE ah loh-ZAY).
Fairway sells delicious fresh sorrel sauce imported from France,
$2.99 for 6 ounces. The sauce is also available in a shelf-stable
package, $2.49 for 7 ounces. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
