<P>
   COXNET WHEELS 0212_ If bigger really is better _ and there's a
segment of the market that agrees with that theory when the goal is
going off-road _ then the '99 Chevrolet Tahoe Z71 is a certified
winner. (DeVault, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: AT A GLANCE _ Facts about the '99 Chevrolet Tahoe
Z71(DeVault, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: SHARP DRIVING _ It wasn't long ago that the automotive
industry was preparing the obituary of the minivan. It seemed
sport-utility vehicles were all the rage and certain to displace
the popular mom-mobile as the vehicle of choice for carrying people
and cargo in the safety of a large vehicle. Well, not so fast.
(Sharp, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   (EDS: This is the CoxNet WHEELS page for the current week. This
layout is now available.)
</P>
<P>
   DELTA-ASA _ Delta on Tuesday said it will buy out commuter
affiliate ASA for $700 million, making it a wholly owned
subsidiary. The deal won't mean much to travelers but gives Delta
greater control of ASA's operations and service. Delta is offering
$34 a share for ASA stock, which trades just under $32. (Thurston,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   w/ASA-HISTORY _ ASA Holdings, Inc. operates Atlantic Southeast
Airlines, Inc., Atlanta's largest regional air carrier with service
to 37 markets, and offers service to 21 airports from its second
hub at Dallas/Fort Worth, Texas. ASA, which was founded in 1979,
has operated as a Delta Connection carrier since 1984. It has a
fleet of 88 aircraft with 2,673 employees based in 40 cities.
(Thurston, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   NAVISTAR-VOLVO _ Navistar and Volvo are talking about a buyout
by Volvo. We update the latest. Also, we follow Navistar on the
market. The stock, after a holiday Monday, is expected to do well
on the heels of the takeover talk and after strong earnings reports
last week. (Springfield News-Sun).
</P>
<P>
   VENTURE _ The South's two hotspots for venture capital - metro
Atlanta and North Carolina's Research Triangle Park -churned out a
record number of deals in 1998, according to new figures from
PricewaterhouseCoopers.With 77 deals valued at $282.8 million, the
Atlanta area topped RTP's 59 deals worth $247.3 million. Both
markets are benefiting from the successful launch of technology
companies in recent years, which is fueling interest among
entrepreneurs and venture capitalists who are funding their
start-ups. (Burritt, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   E&AMP;P-INTERACTIVE _ Editor and Publisher's 10th Annual Interactive
Newspaper conference comes to Atlanta Feb. 17-20 at Hyatt Regency
Atlanta. This is an advance for the conference. (Katz, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   w/WOLFF-INTERNET _ Interview with author Michael Wolff, who
wrote Burn Rate about the birth of the Internet business. He will
speak at E&AMP;P Interactive Newspapers conference on Thursday.
(Clothier, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   INTERACTIVE-MEDIA _ Advance on E&AMP;P Interactive Newspapers and
Association for Interactive Media, which are both meeting in
Atlanta beginning Thursday, Feb. 18. AJC is sponsor of AIM
conference. w/interview of Michael Wolff, author of Burn Rate who
will speak at E&AMP;P (Clothier, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   CNN-WEBMD _ CNN and WebMD announce a content alliance. (Katz,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   NEW-MEDIA _ Who says it takes academe too long to train the
kinds of workers industry needs right now. Several local schools
are training up-to-the minute interactive media mavens right now,
some of whom are already making names for themselves. Everybody
from Clayton State to University of Georgia and Georgia Tech are
doing this. UGA through its journalism school and Tech through its
Literature program. (Holsendolph, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   GEORGIA-Y2K _ The Georgia Y2K citizens' committee is coming out
of incubation. Last Wednesday the Gov. Barnes met with Southern
Company head, A. W. ``Bill'' Dahlberg, the newly-appointed Y2K
czar, about the shape of Dahlberg's new job. (Chambers, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   PBP-SUGAR _ CLEWISTON, Fla. _ The annual three-day sugar junket
for congressional staffers begins today (Wednesday). About 15
staffers will tour U.S. Sugar's new refinery, the port sugar
shipping facility, etc. This is paid for this time each year by the
co-op and the Florida Sugar Cane League, which represents the
Fanjuls and U.S. Sugar. Barring any damaging weather, Florida's raw
sugar crop will reach 2 million tons for the first time ever this
year. And because of rain delays, the harvest season, which usually
ends in March, will stretch into April. (Waresh, Palm Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
   PBP-SITE _ Florida dropped two notches to ninth on `Site
Selection' magazine's annual ranking of the states with the most
new or expanded corporate locations during 1998. The magazine also
reported that number of new or expanded locations _ either plants
or offices _ fell by about 18 percent in Florida from the previous
year. (Sedore, Palm Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
   TESTDRIVE-AUDI _ Review of Audi Avant A6 sport wagon (DeVault,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS. MOVED FRIDAY.
</P>
<P>
   SHARP-DRIVING _ (Sharp, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   THE-MECHANIC _ (Carter, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MONEYTALK _ The personal finance advice column will resume later
this month.
</P>
<P>
   OXBOW _ WEST PALM BEACH, FLA. _ Palm Beach-based Oxbow opens a
$70 million geothermal powerplant in Costa Rica. The company builds
it, operates it, and 15 years from now turns it over to the
government. (Spencer-Wendel, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
