<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-16 17:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7427 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-EXECUTIVE-CHEF-ART     02-16 1080
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-EXECUTIVE-CHEF-ART-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LESPINASSE`S DELOUVRIER FINALLY REACHES THE TOP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., France)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By FLORENCE FABRICANT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ By 8 o'clock one evening last week, a blizzard of
orders were flying into the kitchen at Lespinasse in the St. Regis
and the cooks were ``getting slammed,'' as one of them put it.
Christian Delouvrier, who became the executive chef of the
restaurant last summer, had shed his tall white toque and was in
the thick of it, shoulder to shoulder with the chefs at the fish
station, arranging seared scallops against knots of spinach, then
grabbing an immersion blender to froth a truffle sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Could anyone beyond his staff have picked this compact, slightly
balding cook, who was not saying a word, as the one running the
four-star show? Probably not. Unlike most top chefs these days, his
face is not known to millions from a book jacket, a television show
or a line of products.
</P>
<P>
   He is almost easier to describe by what he is not. He is not, so
far anyway, a globe-trotting businessman like Wolfgang Puck, the
model for so many modern chefs. Nor is he a path-blazing culinary
innovator in the style of Jean-Georges Vongerichten.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, Delouvrier is a cook whose entire culinary life is
testament to tradition. He acquired his restaurant skills
methodically and slowly in France, migrated to the United States
and continually honed his art, modernizing it only after
considerable contemplation. He is a taskmaster on the job, but is
self-effacing, almost shy, in public. About the only way to know
what Delouvrier is about is to eat his food.
</P>
<P>
   He has cooked in Manhattan at the three-star level for nearly 20
years, from 1991 until last year at Les Celebrites in the Essex
House, where he has been replaced by Luc Dimnet, and at Maurice in
the Parker-Meridien before it closed. But he is relatively unknown
to most New Yorkers.
</P>
<P>
   That may not be the case much longer. Since arriving at
Lespinasse late last summer, Delouvrier has been causing a stir
with food that has exceeded expectations, and in December the
restaurant received four stars in a review in The New York Times.
He has managed to dig deep into his experience and creative
reserves to scale new heights. In his first two months at
Lespinasse his cooking changed, and in the process, it soared.
</P>
<P>
   Delouvrier, like a director looking at rushes, examined every
frame of his food to see what he could do to bring the flavors more
into focus. It often meant airbrushing out unnecessary details,
like an extra vegetable garnish, or daring to offer an utterly
simple and rustic chunk of burnished suckling pig on a bed of
tender beans.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I took this job I said to myself, `This kitchen is where
I'll have the exposure and a real chance at four stars,'''
Delouvrier recalled. ``It was something I never thought was
impossible, but this is like a renaissance for me.''
</P>
<P>
   At 52, an age when some chefs have retired at the pinnacles of
their careers and others are considering doing so, Delouvrier has
finally reached the top. He has seen to it that on his watch,
Lespinasse would not lose any of the four stars it received in 1994
with the chef Gray Kunz, who left last summer to pursue other
ventures. Delouvrier said he cares mainly about doing his job, and
plans to keep at it for at least 10 years more.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Cotter, the hotel's general manager, said that in
seeking a replacement for Kunz, ``we looked for somebody with the
potential to be great.'' He said Kunz had recommended hiring
Delouvrier, ``but we did see a little bit of a risk.''
</P>
<P>
   Kunz was known for inspired, often flashy Asian touches and
exotic seasonings. Delouvrier brings to the table the quiet comfort
of a refined French palate and a sure technical hand. He does not
prowl the markets in Chinatown in his free time, as Kunz did. He is
happy to spend his days off at home, in Harrington Park, N.J.,
sitting down to a pot-au-feu or a good roast chicken.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you think about it, Christian's food and his approach to
cooking are more in keeping with the decor, the Beaux-Arts style of
Lespinasse,'' Cotter said.
</P>
<P>
   Delouvrier, a soft-spoken man who whips around the kitchen in a
quick, Chaplinesque gait, spreads the credit around. He says his
accomplishment would not have been possible without the
professionalism of the dining room staff, the depth of the wine
cellar, the support of the hotel management and the high-quality
atmosphere at the St. Regis. Also, being in a restaurant that
serves lunch and dinner (Les Celebrites does not serve lunch) keeps
him closer to the kitchen all day long.
</P>
<P>
   He is even making some changes in Kunz's lavish kitchen, which
the hotel spent more than $1 million renovating. He has added a
rotisserie, and wants to install a Spanish plancha griddle and more
convection ovens to vary the searing and roasting.
</P>
<P>
   Neil Annis, the 32-year-old executive sous-chef, who was also
Delouvrier's second in command at Les Celebrites, recognizes a
change in the chef's cooking. ``It's deeper, slower, more
intense,'' he said. ``It looks simple, but the flavors are rich and
true.''
</P>
<P>
   You know what you are eating with his food. The tastes are
familiar but passionately focused. In a satisfying salad, the
earthy flavor of cepes enriches the warm sweetbreads in natural
juices perfumed with a tantalizing whiff of hazelnut oil. Poached
free-range hen stuffed with foie gras, carrots, leeks and black
truffles is at once succulent and light. The rosy braised veal is
played off against bittersweet caramelized endives. Escoffier-style
dishes _ hare stewed in red wine, for example, or tender shredded
beef cheeks in a lustrous wine sauce capped with mashed potatoes
and black truffle _ are his stock in trade.
</P>
<P>
   You won't find the brilliant dazzle of fish splashed with
kalamansi, an Asian citrus fruit, or stir-fried pea shoots a la
Kunz.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could relate to Gray because of my Asian heritage,'' said
Craig Kokutsu, who has been at Lespinasse for four years and is now
the expediter, barking out the orders as they flood in and adding
finishing touches, like drizzles of sauce from a squeeze bottle or
slices of truffle. ``I haven't done a lot of classical French
cooking, so for me it's now back to basics.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
