<HEADER>
A7430 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-EXECUTIVE-CHEF-ART     02-16 1147
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-EXECUTIVE-CHEF-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: to basics.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Joseph Nase, the sommelier, said that Kunz's spices and
sweet-and-sour flavors made for some tricky wine matches, but
``Christian's food makes me look good.''
</P>
<P>
   And Chris Broberg, the pastry chef, who worked with Kunz for
three years, said that Delouvrier has given him more freedom, and
that the challenge now is to simplify. ``With Gray there was more
layering of flavors,'' he said. ``But I believe desserts should
follow the food.'' Gone are the fruit soups splashed with passion
fruit or scented with lemon grass. Caramel reigns.
</P>
<P>
   Like many accomplished chefs, Delouvrier has vivid memories of
the aromas and flavors of the food of his childhood, especially in
his grandmother's kitchen. He grew up in Boulogne-sur-Gesse, near
Toulouse in Gascony, the region in southwest France that is devoted
to foie gras and duck confit. His father was in the lumber business
but his paternal grandfather had a cafe in Montpellier. By the time
he was 12 he had developed a passion for cooking. Twelve seems to
be the age at which budding chefs in France see the light. He
entered hotel school in Toulouse when he was 14.
</P>
<P>
   His says that his goal, both in school and in the restaurant
kitchens where he began working while still a teen-ager, was ``to
be a good technician, to follow the rules.'' Slowly he rose,
becoming a chef-saucier at the Cafe de la Paix in Paris, later
working at some restaurants in the provinces and eventually moving
to Montreal, to be a chef at Le St.-Amable, a well-known
restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   He came to the United States in 1971, after overhearing that the
Swiss Hutte, an inn in Hillsdale, N.Y., was looking for a chef.
Except for a brief but significant interlude, he has worked here
ever since. It was in Hillsdale that he met and married Mary Dunn,
who now teaches eighth-grade social studies in Tenafly, N.J. They
have two children, Christine, 14, and Marc, 17. Delouvrier said it
takes him 42 minutes to drive home to Harrington Park at about
midnight, when he leaves the restaurant _ ``maybe 44.''
</P>
<P>
   His first job in Manhattan was in 1973 at the Chateau Richelieu
in midtown. He then became the executive sous-chef when Windows on
the World opened in 1976. He was the chef at La Folie, a slightly
bizarre combination of disco and haute cuisine on the Upper East
Side, before returning to France in 1978 for the chance to work
with Alain Senderens at L'Archestrate in Paris. ``Senderens is a
genius and a more spontaneous cook than I could ever be,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When Senderens, whose Paris restaurant, Lucas Carton, holds
three Michelin stars, became the consultant to the new Maurice in
1981, he brought Delouvrier back to New York to be the executive
chef, knowing that he could faithfully execute Senderens recipes
without going off on wild detours. Those were the days of lobster
with vanilla sauce and the thinnest, most gigantic tuiles New York
had ever seen. Delouvrier stayed until 1989, eventually moving on
to Les Celebrites.
</P>
<P>
   ``Les Celebrites was a challenge, and I was motivated to do new
things,'' he said. ``But after a while it started to become
routine. And I began to wonder whether trying to be a superb
technician was a mistake. And then you think of Joel Robuchon. Was
there ever a better technician?''
</P>
<P>
   A trip to France about a year ago revealed food that seemed
younger, lighter and more up to date. ``As a chef, you know what
you do, and sometimes the idea of changing is not in your mind,''
he said. ``But that's unthinkable today.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon thereafter, Delouvrier said, Kunz called him to discuss the
job at Lespinasse. It was all the inspiration he needed.
</P>
<P>
   Or nearly all. One senses a certain tension in Delouvrier. How
far can he _ or should he _ relax his devotion to the classics and
to technical finesse? How much can he experiment, and yet not
compromise his style?
</P>
<P>
   Delouvrier said he relies on Annis to add touches of youthful
modernity to his food, like placing a salad of venison carpaccio
alongside the roasted loin and chops. Annis' touch of cumin in a
lobster salad was welcomed. ``Neil will be one of the great
chefs,'' Delouvrier said.
</P>
<P>
   On that evening last week when the fish orders kept coming,
Annis implored the waiters to try to sell more meat and poultry
dishes. ``The fish station is stressed out,'' he bellowed.
</P>
<P>
   Delouvrier plans to increase the selection of seafood dishes on
the spring menu. ``I'm more comfortable cooking meat, but I have to
do more with fish,'' he said. ``The important thing is that you
never stop learning'' _ even at 52, when you feel the thrill of an
athlete who has finally won.
</P>
<P>
   BUTTERNUT SQUASH SOUP
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Christian Delouvrier
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1 1/2 hours
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons duck fat or butter
</P>
<P>
   2 medium onions, sliced
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   5 ounces smoked bacon, chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 medium butternut squash, peeled, seeded and chopped
</P>
<P>
   6 cloves garlic, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 sprig fresh thyme
</P>
<P>
   4 cups chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   1 small Idaho potato, peeled and chopped
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   8 brussels sprouts, trimmed
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces duck sausage, in 1/2-inch cubes (optional)
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces fresh duck foie gras, in 1/2-inch cubes (optional)
</P>
<P>
   12 chanterelle mushrooms, quartered
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons creme fraiche.
</P>
<P>
   1. Place 1 tablespoon duck fat in a heavy 4-quart saucepan over
medium heat. Add onions, season with salt, cover and cook about 10
minutes, until tender but not brown.
</P>
<P>
   2. Add bacon, squash, garlic and thyme. Cover, and cook 15
minutes. Add chicken broth, and bring to a boil; add potato, and
season with pepper and, if desired, additional salt. Cover, and
cook until vegetables are tender, about 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   3. Meanwhile, bring a small saucepan of water to a boil, add
brussels sprouts and blanch 2 minutes. Refresh under cold water,
drain well and pull off leaves, discarding the cores. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   4. When vegetables are tender, remove sprig of thyme and puree
mixture in a food processor. Return to pot, and bring to a boil.
Remove from heat, and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   5. Heat remaining duck fat in a nonstick skillet. Add sausage
cubes, if using; saute until they start to sear; then add foie
gras, if using, and saute a minute or two, until they are lightly
browned. Drain on paper towel, and cover to keep warm. If you are
not using sausage and foie gras, continue with remaining garnish.
In the same pan saute brussels sprout leaves and chanterelles 5
minutes. Set aside to keep warm.
</P>
<P>
   6. Place soup over medium heat, and bring to a boil. Stir in
creme fraiche, and check seasonings.
</P>
<P>
   7. Place equal portions of sausage, foie gras, brussels sprout
leaves and chanterelles in the center of each of 6 warm soup
plates, and serve them. Ladle hot soup into each plate at the
table.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 servings.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
