</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-EXECUTIVE-CHEF-ART-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: 6 servings. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHEASANT WITH CHARTREUSE OF CABBAGE
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Christian Delouvrier
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1 1/2 hours
</P>
<P>
   1 pheasant, about 2 pounds, preferably female
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   4 quarts well-seasoned chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   4 large leaves savoy cabbage
</P>
<P>
   1 carrot, peeled
</P>
<P>
   1 medium-size white turnip, peeled and quartered
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon fresh thyme leaves, plus 2 sprigs for garnish.
</P>
<P>
   1. Preheat oven to 475 degrees. Season pheasant inside and out
with salt and pepper. Place on a rack in a small roasting pan, and
roast 15 minutes; pheasant will not be fully cooked. Remove from
oven, and set aside. Reserve any fat from pan. Reduce oven setting
to 300 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   2. Bring broth to a simmer, and add cabbage, carrot and turnip.
Remove cabbage leaves after about 3 minutes, and cook carrot and
turnip 10 minutes longer, until al dente. Leave broth on burner
with heat off.
</P>
<P>
   3. Remove end of heavy core from cabbage leaves. Quarter carrot
lengthwise, then slice 1/4 inch thick. Cut turnip into 1/4-inch
dice. Combine carrot and turnip in a bowl.
</P>
<P>
   4. Cut pheasant breasts from the bone, and remove skin. Set
aside. Remove legs and thighs, and set aside. Remove skin from
remainder of carcass. Break carcass in a few pieces, place in broth
over low heat and simmer about 30 minutes, until the meat clinging
to it is fully cooked. Remove carcass from broth. Strain broth
through a very fine strainer lined with cheesecloth or a coffee
filter into a clean saucepan, and season to taste with salt and
pepper.
</P>
<P>
   5. Cut all meat off pheasant carcass, and dice it. Heat reserved
pheasant fat in nonstick skillet; add diced pheasant, carrots and
turnips, and saute briefly. Add thyme, moisten with a few
tablespoons broth and season to taste with salt and pepper. Divide
this mixture between two cabbage leaves, and bring up the sides to
make a bundle. Place each bundle, seam side down, on another
cabbage leaf, and wrap tightly. Place the two bundles, seam side
down, in a small baking dish, and place in oven to keep warm.
</P>
<P>
   6. Reheat skillet, add pheasant legs and sear over high heat
about 5 minutes. Turn them, add breast meat and continue to sear,
turning breast once, until pheasant is browned on the outside but
still very pink and slightly undercooked. Remove from pan, and
season to taste with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   7. Bring broth to a simmer.
</P>
<P>
   8. Place each cabbage bundle in the center of a large, shallow
soup plate. Cut each piece of pheasant breast in half, and separate
legs and thighs. Place 2 breast pieces, a leg and a thigh around
cabbage bundle, and pour hot broth over it; this will finish
cooking the pheasant. Garnish with a sprig of thyme, and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 2 servings.
</P>
<P>
   SAUTEED DUCK FOIE GRAS WITH POTATOES AND ENDIVES
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Christian Delouvrier
</P>
<P>
   Time: 45 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1 large Idaho potato, peeled
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon duck fat
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon butter
</P>
<P>
   1 cup veal stock
</P>
<P>
   Coarse salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 endives, cores removed, halved
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon sherry vinegar
</P>
<P>
   4 slices fresh duck foie gras, 1 1/2 to 2 ounces each.
</P>
<P>
   1. Preheat oven to 200 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   2. Cut a thin slice from each side of potato the long way so it
lies flat. Slice potato lengthwise into four slabs of equal width.
</P>
<P>
   3. Heat duck fat in a heavy saucepan that will hold the potatoes
in a single layer. Place potato slices in pan and cook over medium
heat about a minute on each side. Pour off and reserve excess fat.
Add 1/2 tablespoon butter and 1/4 cup veal stock to saucepan,
season potatoes with salt and pepper, cover pan and braise potatoes
until tender, about 20 minutes. Remove from pan and place on a
baking sheet in oven.
</P>
<P>
   4. Return duck fat to saucepan; add endives cut side down and
cook over moderate heat about a minute. Turn endives, season to
taste with salt and pepper, add remaining butter and saute, turning
once, until they are tender and well caramelized. Remove from pan
and place on baking sheet with potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   5. Add vinegar to saucepan and stir to dissolve caramelized bits
clinging to the bottom. Stir in remaining veal stock and cook over
high heat about 5 minutes, until sauce is syrupy and reduced to
about 1/2 cup. Check seasonings. Remove from heat.
</P>
<P>
   6. Heat a nonstick skillet until very hot. Season foie gras with
salt and pepper on each side; place in pan and sear about a minute
on each side, until browned but rare in the middle. Drain on paper
towels.
</P>
<P>
   7. To serve, place a slice of potato on each of four warm
medium-size plates; top each with an endive half and then with a
slice of foie gras. Briefly reheat sauce and drizzle a little
around the plate and on top of foie gras.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
