<HEADLINE>
TV NOTES: MIKE WALLACE, DRUG-TEST REPORT, `STORM OF THE CENTURY' 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mike Wallace in Double Time
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Walters gets Monica Lewinsky; Diane Sawyer gets Kenneth
Starr; Jamie Gangel on NBC's ``Today'' show gets Linda Tripp.
</P>
<P>
   Who at CBS is still out there getting the big interviews? How
about Mike Wallace, 80 years old and still chasing down stories now
not just for one weekly news magazine program but for two.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace is in London this week, where he interviewed Louise
Woodward, the nanny at the center of one of the most closely
followed murder trials in both the United States and Britain. The
piece will appear on ``60 Minutes'' later this season, he said in a
telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   All he would say about the interview with Ms. Woodward was:
``There is evidence that that which she was convicted of she did
not do. I shouldn't say any more than that right now.''
</P>
<P>
   In October 1997, Ms. Woodward was convicted of manslaughter in
the death of a Massachusetts infant left in her care.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace, the lead correspondent for ``60 Minutes'' since its
inception in 1968, has become almost as ubiquitous a presence on
``60 Minutes II,'' the spinoff introduced by CBS in January. The
program appears for a sixth time Thursday night and Wallace will be
back with his third update of a piece he previously reported for
``60 Minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   This time it is a new look at Bruce Cutler, a former lawyer for
convicted New York mob boss John Gotti. The occasion for the
revisit: Cutler now represents Gotti's son, John A. Gotti, in his
fight to stay out of federal prison.
</P>
<P>
   After Cutler managed to get the elder Gotti acquitted in three
trials, the government separated him from Gotti in its last case
against him. ``He was suspended from practicing in Brooklyn,''
Wallace said. ``He was off in Chicago and Kansas City and other
places. The piece is, in effect, how the mighty have fallen.''
</P>
<P>
   Cutler didn't exactly agree with that premise, Wallace said,
pointing out that Cutler had argued that he had been doing
important things in Detroit. ``I told him that just wasn't the
same. We show a lot of the old stuff with him, declaiming in the
courtroom, quoting Shakespeare. He's such a performer. I must say I
like him.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace also said he now likes the entire concept of ``60
Minutes II,'' which he ardently opposed when it was first
suggested. The turning point, he said, came when the show named
Jeff Fager, once a news executive on the original ``60 Minutes,''
to be the executive producer of ``60 Minutes II.''
</P>
<P>
   That persuaded the entire correspondent staff of ``60 Minutes''
as well as its founding father, Don Hewitt, to sign on to the plan
to update classic reports from the original.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should have been doing it on our own broadcast,'' Wallace
said. ``There are thousands of stories we did where people want to
know what happened to the individuals involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace acknowledged that he has more than enough material of
his own to update. ``I've done 25 stories a year for 30 years.
There's more than enough there to go back and look at again.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By BILL CARTER
</P>
<P>
   Bad Hair Days
</P>
<P>
   A report on ``The CBS Morning News'' this week finds a
disturbing increase in the use of hair tests to screen job
candidates for past drug use _ disturbing because many experts say
the tests are unreliable and possibly racially biased.
</P>
<P>
   The tests can detect drug use over a longer time period than
urine tests (which typically detect back only three days), but they
may also register false positives, even from exposure to drug
particles in the environment. And, as Roberta Baskin shows in the
conclusion to her three-part series Wednesday, different labs came
up with widely different results on samples from identical heads of
hair and with different results on hairs of darker or lighter color
but exposed to the same level of drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's promising technology when used with other kinds of tests,
for forensic purposes,'' she said. ``But used by itself to decide
if someone gets or doesn't get a job, or custody of a child, for
example, it could be very unfair.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Baskin's report might strike many viewers as something they
would be more likely to see on the ``CBS Evening News,'' or a
prime-time news magazine. But Al Berman, the executive producer of
the ``Morning News,'' wants stories like these to distinguish his
show from the other breakfast shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're fortunate to have an investigative team dedicated to
this broadcast,'' Berman said. Ms. Baskin has won many
investigative-reporting awards, including two prestigious Alfred I.
Dupont-Columbia University silver batons, one of them for revealing
serious flaws in the National Football League's drug testing
procedures.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1998 Winter Olympics, Ms. Baskin got into trouble
with Andrew Heyward, president of CBS News, when, in a letter to
him that was leaked to the press, she protested some CBS reporters'
wearing parkas with a Nike logo and she accused the network of
killing a report she had done on Nike.
</P>
<P>
   In unusually angry terms, Heyward denounced Ms. Baskin for her
letter, which she said she had not leaked. Her on-air appearances
dwindled; last July she joined ``The CBS Morning News.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if she had wanted to work there, she said, ``I like to
tell good stories wherever I can tell them,'' and would not comment
on her relationship with Heyward or whether it had influenced her
move.
</P>
<P>
   She did object to the notion that morning programs only do
gentler, consumer-oriented reporting. ``I hate labels,'' she said.
``I'm interested in stories that affect a lot of people, and I like
breaking stories that people haven't heard about yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Berman has offered her series on hair drug-testing to ``CBS
Evening News'' but has not heard yet whether it will run there as
well.
</P>
<P>
   _ By LAWRIE MIFFLIN
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   `Storm' Subsides
</P>
<P>
   It's far from the disappointment of the century, but the latest
ABC Stephen King mini-series certainly qualifies as the
disappointment of the month.
</P>
<P>
   After two parts, King's ``Storm of the Century'' has delivered
ratings that would look good under most circumstances, but not
after a promotional blizzard that had buried the nation since
September.
</P>
<P>
   ABC got winning results both Sunday and Monday night from the
series with the audience of 18-to-49-year-old viewers it covets
most, but the numbers were lower than any previous King novel
translated for television.
</P>
<P>
   And talk about scary endings: Part 3 is scheduled for Thursday
night, up against the episode of NBC's ``ER'' in which George
Clooney says goodbye to the show.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Hyams, ABC's vice president of research, said, ``We expect
there will be high VCR usage Thursday night.''
</P>
<P>
   ABC clearly expected better things from ``Storm of the
Century.'' After weeks of frequent clips from the show, the
network's entire promotion this month was highlighted by the
omnipresent tag line: ``ABC is taking February by storm.''
</P>
<P>
   ABC even caused a flap last week when it ran a crawl (a written
message along the bottom of the screen) during its Wednesday night
comedies that began: ``ABC storm alert.''
</P>
<P>
   The message distressed some stations and emergency services.
More distressed were the producers of ``Dharma and Greg'' and ``The
Drew Carey Show,'' who had not known that their episodes would
include promotional distractions.
</P>
<P>
   For all of that, ABC surely had expected to draw better ratings
than it did two years ago with a remake of King's ``Shining,'' a
version that most critics did not deem successful. In contrast,
most critics praised ``Storm of the Century''
</P>
<P>
   Even NBC was concerned about how well ``Storm'' might do. Lindy
DeKoven, the head of NBC's movie division, said she was gratified
that NBC's mini-series ``The '60s'' was the highest-rated movie of
the season, but added, ``At least until that little storm arrives
on ABC.''
</P>
<P>
   Hyams said, ``We thought the same thing.'' And why did this
``Storm'' pack less punch than expected? ``Who knows?'' Hyams said.
</P>
<P>
   _ By BILL CARTER
</P>
</TEXT>
