<SLUG> BC-ALIENS-TVSPECIAL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIS NAME IS JOHN, BUT CALL HIM MULDER JR.
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
 
By FRED SHUSTER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES _ John Greenewald Jr. can often be found in his
Northridge home tinkering with his Web site that challenges the
U.S. government to tell the truth about aliens.
</P>
<P>
   The feds are crafty, though. They've learned that Greenewald
won't start badgering them until around 3 p.m. each day. That's
when the 17-year-old gets home from Alemany High School in Mission
Hills, where he's a senior.
</P>
<P>
   Greenewald is part of a two-hour special based on Whitley
Strieber's best seller, ``Confirmation: The Hard Evidence of Aliens
Among Us?'' airing at 8 tonight on NBC.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen unusual things in the sky,'' Greenewald
admits. ``I'm driven by curiosity. I have a lot of fun writing
letters to the government. It's fun to think the CIA is working for
me. It's a great hobby, and I love it.''
</P>
<P>
   The TV special, hosted by Robert Davi (FBI Agent Bailey on NBC's
``The Profiler''), examines evidence that the Earth has been
visited by UFOs and alien beings. Included is footage of an alleged
alien implant being removed on camera.
</P>
<P>
   Greenewald began writing the government citing the Freedom of
Information Act in summer 1996 just to see what they would give up
on the issue of aliens.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got the initial document I asked for, which was five pages
long,'' Greenewald explains. ``Then I wondered just how much was
available at other agencies. Those five pages have turned into more
than 7,000 pages. I've discovered there's definitely something the
government is hiding. What it is, you can't be sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the documents I've received are blacked out due to
national security. What's under the black ink, we can't be sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenewald posts his finding on his Web site
(www.blackvault.com), which gets more than 30,000 inquiries per
month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just continue my letters and requests,'' the teen said.
``I'm sure I cause a lot of work for the government.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenewald says his parents think his extracurricular interest
is ``really neat. They're happy I'm focused on something. My sister
doesn't know how to view it. She's a skeptic, and it's always fun
to make her think.''
</P>
<P>
   The local teen, who plans to attend California State University,
Northridge, in the fall, came to the attention of the producers of
TV's ``Confirmation: The Hard Evidence of Aliens Among Us?'' when
an article was published about the boy in a Baltimore newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   ``They e-mailed me asking if I was interested in being
interviewed for the show,'' Greenewald said.
</P>
<P>
   Greenewald says his Web site doesn't detract from his school
work, and his grades have always been good.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the work is done on my free time,'' he said. ``A lot
of the kids at school have no idea what I've done. But those who do
know think it's great.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
