<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Wednesday, Feb. 17, 1999, sent to computer graphics clients of The
New York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(nk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Moderate to heavy rains will develop Wednesday across the
eastern Gulf States as a developing low-pressure system over
Alabama teams with a trailing jet stream disturbance to lift
increasingly humid air from the Gulf of Mexico. Rain will be
accompanied by thunder in some areas, with isolated thunderstorms
approaching severe levels in northwest Florida later Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Rain will spread into the Middle Atlantic States Wednesday night
as the low ripples northeastward along a slow-moving cold front. By
Thursday morning, the heaviest rains will have fallen from Georgia
to eastern Virginia, with rainfalls of one inch or more possible in
some areas. Moderate rains associated with this system will reach
southeast Pennsylvania, New Jersey and southeast New York by
Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Broken areas of generally light snow will develop across upstate
New York and northwest New England associated with a cold front
extending southward from a low-pressure system in Ontario. In the
wake of the low, scattered snow showers and flurries will dust
parts of the Great Lakes region.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, moderate to heavy snows will fall atop the peaks of
the northern and central Rockies as a conveyor of moisture flowing
eastward from the Pacific is forced to rise over the sloping
terrain. Rain and mountain snow will continue to affect parts of
western Washington, western Oregon and northwest California as
moist onshore winds persist. But these winds will gradually weaken,
keeping precipitation generally light to moderate in most places.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Rocking the Boat
</P>
<P>
   A rare February surf rocked boats anchored along south-facing
shores of Hawaii Tuesday. In winter, high surf is usually
restricted to north-facing shores, where large waves generated by
intense storms over the north Pacific Ocean finally break after
dispersing thousands of miles over open seas. About a week ago, an
unusually intense summer storm southeast of New Zealand (in the
southern hemisphere) generated ocean swells that spread north
across the equator and headed toward Hawaii. Waves as high as seven
feet arrived Tuesday on the Waikiki Beach, replacing the typically
tame February surf.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
