<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEW VISIT THE NATION'S GREATEST LOOKOUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TOM STIENSTRA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   YOSEMITE NATIONAL PARK, Calif. _ America's greatest lookout,
normally crowded beyond comprehension, can now be visited with only
a few souls within miles.
</P>
<P>
   It is Glacier Point, where the scope of view is unparalleled,
looking down at Half Dome and silver-tasseled Nevada and Vernal
Falls on one side, and the entire 2,425 feet of Yosemite Falls on
the other and the north rim of Yosemite Valley, with a panorama
beyond of miles of wilderness peaks topped by remote peaks, with
Matterhorn (12,264 feet) and Cathedral (10,940 feet) among the
prominent.
</P>
<P>
   Half Dome looks like a giant iceberg, and the entire landscape
is jeweled in white, with ice crystals sparkling in the sunlight
like tiny diamonds. Out near Washburn Point, scanning up the Merced
Canyon, it is so quiet that it is eerie, where the only sounds are
those of your thoughts, and each breath speaks with a thousand
voices over he awesome magnitude of the moment.
</P>
<P>
   There's a catch, of course: You can't drive here.
</P>
<P>
   But that is what makes it so special for the handful of
explorers willing to go the extra mile to capture this
extraordinary experience.
</P>
<P>
   There are only two ways to get here, cross-country skiing or
snow-shoeing, a 10-mile trip with an overnight snow camp at the new
lodge, complete with indoor plumbing. To facilitate people with the
required zest for this trip, and also to keep it safe, a guided
overnight trip with meals and a bed rack in a small lodge (a store
converted for winter) is available for $110 per person.
</P>
<P>
   The trip starts at the Badger Pass Ski Area and then roughly
follows the snow-covered Glacier Point Road out to Glacier Point.
The route is mostly flat, though there are a few small hills, then
climbs a bit at Seminole Dome, with one switch-backed drop at the
end of the trip down to Glacier Point.
</P>
<P>
   Everything is so pristine and quiet, that it can be difficult to
believe that this is the same place that gets thousands of visitors
each summer day.
</P>
<P>
   For a brochure, phone the Yosemite cross-country ski school at
209-372-8444 and leave your name and address at the tone; for ski
and park information during winter, phone 209-372-1000.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Del Valle Reservoir, and its beautiful park and boating facility
south of Livermore, has become another testimonial to the paradox
of different parts of government spending your tax dollars to work
at cross purposes. On one hand, the California Department of
Boating and Waterways just provided more than $1 million to improve
the boat launching facility at Del Valle Reservoir and the work is
now under way.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the Zone 7 Water Agency is in the planning
stages to sell the water from Del Valle to accommodate growth in
the Livermore-Amador Valley, lowering the lake level by 85 percent
each summer, which would render useless the new boat ramp, picnic
area, swimming area and campground, and turn one of the jewels of
the East Bay Regional Park District into a dust bowl.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
