<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-ALIENS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CONFIRMATION: THE HARD EVIDENCE OF ALIENS AMONG US?':
UNIMPRESSIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.)  
 (bl)  
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   If it were possible to bring unidentified-flying-object
enthusiasts down to earth, Wednesday night's two-hour treatment of
the popular controversy over visitors from out there might do the
job.
</P>
<P>
   ``Confirmation: The Hard Evidence of Aliens Among Us?'' is so
cluttered with hocus-pocus atmospherics _ faked-up images,
far-fetched re-creations, eerie sounds and a heavy-breathing
narrator, Robert Davi, who shows up periodically out of the smoke
of what seems to be a Transylvanian spooker _ that you have to
suspect the producers don't trust their own evidence.
</P>
<P>
   The NBC Entertainment program, based on a best seller by Whitley
Strieber, who claims to have experienced ``a close encounter'' in
1985 that may have left him with an object implanted in his left
ear lobe, brings together most of the by now familiar assertions of
sightings and kidnappings, some apparently owed to
memory-refreshing or fantasy-inducing hypnosis.
</P>
<P>
   There are also charges of official cover-ups, which continue to
occupy conspiratorialists of the Internet. All are countered by
debunkers, leaving viewers to select or reject the strange tales
and shaky photographs as it suits them.
</P>
<P>
   The strangest tale offered Wednesday night comes from one Jesse
Long, who says he was abducted several times over many years; he
reports being subjected to crossbreeding and claims to have wound
up with quite a brood of extraterrestrial descendants. You can
watch Long going through some sort of trauma under hypnosis.
</P>
<P>
   The best-publicized publicists of the paranormal, including Dr.
John Mack of Harvard University and Budd Hopkins, described as ``a
world-renowned abduction expert,'' are heard from, and so are their
critics. Much is also made of an extended dramatized version of
something peculiar that several Ohio police officers say they saw
in the sky in 1993, which an astronomer dismisses as twinkling
stars.
</P>
<P>
   The one sure thing about Wednesday night's offering is that no
responsibility for it is taken by NBC News.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `CONFIRMATION: THE HARD EVIDENCE OF ALIENS AMONG US?'
</P>
<P>
   NBC, Wednesday night at 8 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Channel 4 in New York) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mark Wolper and Whitley Strieber, executive producers; Starling
Price, writer, director and co-executive producer; Tim Rogan,
supervising producer. A production of NBC Studios. Robert Davi,
host.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-99 1757EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990216.0248 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-16 17:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7474 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRISH-CATHOLIC-RIGHTS     02-16 1366
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRISH-CATHOLIC-RIGHTS-250&AMP;ADDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTHERN IRELAND APPROVES POLITICAL REFORMS TO AID CATHOLIC
MINORITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JAMES F. CLARITY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST, Northern Ireland _ The Northern Ireland Assembly on
Tuesday approved sweeping changes in the political structure of
this predominantly Protestant British province. The changes are
designed to give the Roman Catholic minority more power and to end
the sectarian violence that has killed more than 3,200 people in
the last 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   The next step in the process is the creation of an Assembly
executive cabinet to carry out the changes. But the continuing
dispute over disarmament of the Irish Republican Army threatens to
delay formation of the cabinet, which is supposed to be completed
by March 10.
</P>
<P>
   The approval of the changes, after two days of acrimonious
debate in Belfast, was hailed by mainstream Protestant and Catholic
leaders as a historic move toward permanent peace. The vote was
77-29, with all the Catholics and about half the Protestants in
favor of the measure and half the Protestants against.
</P>
<P>
   Seamus Mallon, the mainstream Catholic deputy first minister,
said, ``For the first time since partition, the representatives of
unionism and nationalism have agreed on constitutional issues, on
political issues, on social issues and on economic issues _ for the
first time in 80 years.'' He was referring to the agreement under
which southern Ireland became independent, leaving the North a
British province.
</P>
<P>
   The Catholic nationalists, or republicans, seek closer ties with
the rest of Ireland, while the Protestant unionists seek to
maintain ties with Britain.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The vote was also seen as a victory for First Minister David
Trimble, who held his party, the Ulster Unionists, together in
favor of the changes despite attacks and defections by hard-line
Protestant Assembly members.
</P>
<P>
   The changes would also give the overwhelmingly Catholic Irish
Republic more influence in the North's affairs and pave the way for
the restoration of home rule powers by the British government in
London. Britain has ruled here directly since 1974, with local
councils controlling only burials and garbage removal.
</P>
<P>
   But the final enactment of the changes was still threatened by
the bitter dispute over the disarmament of the IRA, which has
observed a cease-fire for 19 months but refuses to surrender a
single bullet or pound of Semtex explosive from its estimated 100
tons of weapons and explosives.
</P>
<P>
   Protestants contend that Sinn Fein, the IRA political wing, must
not be included in the cabinet until the IRA starts to disarm.
</P>
<P>
   But a kind of IRA disarmament was shown Tuesday night on
television along with the political news. There were pictures of an
arms cache discovered in the Catholic part of West Belfast. Police
said the arms _ an automatic rifle, several pipe bombs, coffee-jar
bombs, fuses and hundreds of bullets _ belonged to the IRA.
</P>
<P>
   Some officials and experts said the timing of the disclosure was
significant, giving the public impression that even though the IRA
is refusing to disarm, some of its weapons are going out of action.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Sinn Fein leader Gerry Adams missed the vote in Belfast to visit
British Prime Minister Tony Blair in London. He said later that
there had been a ``good discussion.''
</P>
<P>
   In the debate Monday, hard-line Protestants hooted when Adams
made his opening remarks in Gaelic, a language few in the Assembly
chamber understand.
</P>
<P>
   Many Protestants considered his choice of Gaelic to be a
taunting reminder that Adams represents Catholics dedicated to
Irish, rather than British, culture. During the voting Tuesday,
Sinn Fein members said ``ta'' and ``nil,'' the Gaelic terms for yes
and no.
</P>
<P>
   Hard-line Protestant unionist Peter Robinson contended in
Monday's debate that Sinn Fein chief negotiator Martin McGuinness
was an active member of the IRA military command. McGuinness, who
has often denied this, then held up what he said was a fragment of
a grenade thrown at Catholics by a Protestant in his home city of
Londonderry.
</P>
<P>
   A former Protestant paramilitary leader, David Ervine, who was
imprisoned in a British jail as a terrorist and is now leader of
the Progressive Unionist Party, objected to the vilification of
Sinn Fein, normally his sworn enemy. He said that many of the
Protestant leaders in the Assembly had met with him frequently, at
his home, during the guerrilla war, when Ervine was a leader of the
Ulster Volunteer Force.
</P>
<P>
   The debate continued Tuesday, with hard-line Protestants
attacking Sinn Fein, contending that it is a front for IRA
terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   Billy Hutchinson, also a Progressive Unionist and a former
Protestant paramilitary who served time for his involvement in a
sectarian killing, chilled many in the Assembly. He said his party
supported the changes, but that ``If Sinn Fein and the IRA start
supporting killing again in Northern Ireland, I know where I'll
be.''
</P>
<P>
   Trimble, the Protestant first minister of the Assembly, supports
the position that until disarmament actually begins, Sinn Fein
should not be allowed to participate in the cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   Without Sinn Fein representing the IRA in the new structures,
their work would be futile, and the situation could lead to a
resumption of paramilitary violence by the IRA and by smaller
Protestant guerrilla groups. Some of the Protestant groups have
threatened attacks in Ireland if the peace effort fails.
</P>
<P>
   Adams notes, accurately, that the peace agreement approved last
year does not require disarmament before May 2000 and contends that
the sustained cease-fire reflects the IRA's support of the peace
effort. Trimble says that this is not enough _ that the Protestant
majority needs assurance in the form of a surrender of arms.
</P>
<P>
   Some mainstream Catholic leaders are straddling the issue. They
affirm the need for disarmament now, but acknowledge that it is not
actually required by the peace agreement approved by leaders last
spring and overwhelmingly confirmed in June in referendums in the
North and the Irish Republic.
</P>
<P>
   Officials say that Trimble and Adams will have to blink soon,
approving a solution to the disarmament dispute that both can
describe as a victory. One possibility, they say, would be a
statement by the chairman of the disarmament commission, John de
Chastelain, a former Canadian general. But no one has proposed
exactly what de Chastelain could say to finesse the problem and end
the growing sense of crisis in the peace effort.
</P>
<P>
   Under the measures approved Tuesday, Northern Ireland is to have
10 government departments to deal with most matters, excluding
security and taxation, and a North-South Ministerial Council of six
units comprising officials from the North and from the Irish
Republic to cooperate in areas that include the economy, tourism
and agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   Protestant hard-liners, like the Rev. Ian Paisley, see this
cooperation as an abominable prologue to a united Ireland, free of
British control, run from Dublin. But the peace agreement
stipulates that there will be no end to British sovereignty in
Northern Ireland without the consent of the majority, which is
likely to remain Protestant well into the new century.
</P>
<P>
   Trimble, as leader of the Ulster Unionist Party, supports the
new structures, but he must deal constantly with attacks by
Paisley, the leader of the Democratic Unionist Party, who accuses
him of consorting with the enemy. The two parties contend for seats
in provincial elections for local councils and in the British and
European Parliaments.
</P>
<P>
   The overall peace agreement was reached after the Irish and
British governments made important concessions to Sinn Fein and the
IRA, including the early release of paramilitary prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   But republican dissidents, castigating the agreement as a
sellout that does not guarantee the withdrawal of British authority
from the island, have continued deadly attacks designed to make the
political process collapse and to plunge the province into renewed
guerrilla warfare.
</P>
</TEXT>
