<SLUG> BC-CALIF-VINEGAR-TASTE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL THAT DRIZZLES ISN'T BALSAMIC 
</HEADLINE>
  (With CALIF-VINEGAR) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By MOLLY O'NEILL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In tasting 24 balsamic vinegars, I discovered you
can't judge a vinegar by its price tag or its label. A number of
vinegars staking a claim to tradizionale status _ or at least
priced as if they were _ were in fact decent vinegars for cooking
but nothing more.
</P>
<P>
   I divided them into three categories: aceto balsamico
tradizionale, for samples that rise to the level of the best
artisanal vinegar; those best for cooking because of their complex
flavors; and salad vinegars, light and thin but often a good
alternative to wine vinegar. Sampled brands are listed in order of
preference.
</P>
<P>
   ACETO BALSAMICO TRADIZIONALE
</P>
<P>
   1. Batteria BM2 (Modena), 3.4 ounces; $135. Sweet, gorgeous
honey flavor, balanced and round with hints of rosemary. Source:
Corti Brothers mail order, (800) 509-3663.
</P>
<P>
   2. Batteria AS19 (Reggio Emilia), 3.4 ounces; $136. Round
flavor, with hints of leather and honey and the rich mellow taste
of currants and pine. Corti Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   3. Batteria AS18 (Reggio Emilia), 3.4 ounces; $94. Medium- to
thick-bodied; mellow and round with a sweet, honey note with hints
of citrus; finishes long and tart. Corti Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   4. Batteria AS15 (Reggio Emilia), 3.4 ounces; $75. Medium body;
piney flavor with hints of honey; bright, lingering finish. Corti
Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   COOKING VINEGARS
</P>
<P>
   1. Affinato (Modena), 3.4 ounces; $94. Medium- to light-bodied;
piney with haunting honey overtones and hints of mint and lemon.
Corti Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   2. Condimento Balsamico San Geminiano, 8.5 ounces; $36. Nicely
balanced sweet and sour flavors, with a hint of cherry and a piney,
spritzy finish. Corti Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   3. Fini Gold Label, 8.5 ounces; $42. Mellow, toasty flavor with
hints of berries and spice. Williams-Sonoma, by mail order, (800)
541-2233.
</P>
<P>
   4. Antico Borgo, 8.5 ounces; $55. Young berry flavor with hints
of caramel, leather and spice; tart finish. Balducci's, by mail
order, (800) 225-3822.
</P>
<P>
   5. Fondo Carrate, 8.5 ounces. Fruity, nicely balanced sweet and
sour components; clean, herbaceous finish. Fairway, 2127 Broadway
(74th Street), New York.
</P>
<P>
   6. Manicardi 21, 8.5 ounces; $36. Highly pronounced cherry taste
with caramel veneer. Dean &AMP; DeLuca, 560 Broadway (Prince Street),
New York.
</P>
<P>
   7. Manicardi 12, 8.5 ounces; $20. Virtually indistinguishable
from Manicardi 21. Dean &AMP; DeLuca.
</P>
<P>
   SALAD VINEGARS
</P>
<P>
   1. San Geminiano, 8.5 ounces; $6.99. Sweet, round caramel tone
on a background of spice; acidic finish. Corti Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   2. Mama Balducci, 8.5 ounces; $12.95. Grapey, lightly spicy
flavor; tart, sprizty finish. Balducci's.
</P>
<P>
   3. Elsa, 8.5 ounces; $9.39. Herbaceous with well-balanced sweet
and sour components; young and grapey, with a hint of leather and
spice. Fairway.
</P>
<P>
   4. Gourmonde 8, 8.5 ounces; $20. Pronounced berry tones; subtle
toastiness with clean finish. Dean &AMP; DeLuca.
</P>
<P>
   5. Compagnia del Montale, 3.4 ounces; $15. Dark, fruity flavor
that only slightly overpowers the acidity. Dean &AMP; DeLuca.
</P>
<P>
   6. Terre Estensi, 8.5 ounces; $10.99. Faintly spicy with a tart
finish and only a hint of sweetness. Fairway.
</P>
<P>
   7. Cavali Balsamic, 17 ounces; $28. Port-sweet, almost cloying
raisin flavor saved by a subtle bite. Dean &AMP; DeLuca.
</P>
<P>
   9. Monari Federzoni, 16.9 ounces; $3.99-$6.99. Pleasantly acidic
with hints of berries. Widely available.
</P>
<P>
   10. Vantia, Vintage XII, 8.5 ounces; $8.99. Bright tasting, with
pronounced raisinlike sweetness and a harsh, woody finish. Fairway.
</P>
<P>
   The following vinegars were barely distinguishable; all were
thin and ranged from light to very dark brown: Regina Balsamic
Vinegar, 12 ounces, $2.99; Condoni, 8.5 ounces, $8.49; Grey Poupon,
17 ounces, $4.69; Progresso, 12 ounces, $1.99 (all from Food
Emporium).
</P>
</TEXT>
