<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-16 18:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7478 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV23-     02-16 0890
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV23-NYTR </SLUG>
  
 (For release Tuesday Feb. 23)  
 By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I wanted to say that Annie Lamott, who has written about being
Christian in ``Traveling Mercies,'' in the same naked, irreverent
way she wrote about becoming a mother in ``Operating Instructions''
and watching a father die in ``Hard Laughter,'' is a role model for
the Religious Left. Her approach to religion is such a refreshing
antidote to the Thought Police of the Religious Right, who say you
can't be a Christian if you don't bash gay people and do as your
husband commands.
</P>
<P>
   To the contrary, Annie defines herself as Christian and liberal
and a feminist. And not just a regular Christian but a ``born
again,'' who blesses her gay friends' wedding and alternately
refers to God as She and He.
</P>
<P>
   Hallelujah.
</P>
<P>
   So, I asked if she were a spokesperson for the Religious Left
and she fittingly protested, ``Oh God, no.''
</P>
<P>
   She is her own believer. As she put it, ``I am one cell of the
great body of believers.'' She paused and added, ``One cell with a
loud mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a brave thing that she has done. It's one thing to be a
former druggie and boozer and have slept with inappropriate men and
confess to sometimes being tough on your kid and not being always
loving to your mother and having unkind thoughts about other
people's children, as she does in her books. It is a huge
confession and a risk to your reputation for being hip and
wonderfully oddball to go on about prayer and Jesus trailing you
around like an insistent kitten until you let him in.
</P>
<P>
   Religion is what we don't talk about at the dinner table.
Religion is what many gave up when they became intellectual and
sophisticated and challenged everything their parents held dear.
</P>
<P>
   Same with Annie. ``It was not what a left wing intellectual
did.'' Being drawn to religion, especially ``the Jesus part,'' she
said was right up there with being a Moonie or a Scientologist.
</P>
<P>
   But I think this loud mouth, with her asides to God as well as
her sweet devotion to all manner of weird human beings, is going to
make an impact with this book. Maybe readers won't be lining up to
be baptized into her Marin County church, St. Andrew Presbyterian,
but she has opened the door to something that has laid dormant and
been uncool for a long time.
</P>
<P>
   She admits that she'd like her book to be ``the great Shalom,
the great welcome to the un-churchable,'' those unwilling or shy
about investigating their own personal faith.
</P>
<P>
   People are shy. Talking about what you believe in is like
walking around town naked. It's showing too much. Someone will
laugh or never think of you the same way again.
</P>
<P>
   It's easier, maybe, if you call it spirituality because that
allows for some movement in belief. It takes it out of a church,
puts it into a redwood grove or around a bonfire at the beach.
Gives you a religion you can dance to.
</P>
<P>
   But it can be an embarrassing subject, even with all the trend
stories lately on how Boomers and others facing mortality are
starting to shop around for a church or temple or looking into
Buddhism. Maybe people find a community in a goddess circle they
don't get in their town.
</P>
<P>
   But Annie's is regular church. It has a gospel choir that rocks
and the congregation is racially diverse and the minister is a
woman. The fact that it's in economically disadvantaged Marin City,
the non-yuppie part of Marin County, makes it anti-chic. But,
beyond that, Annie explains, it's a ``very traditional church,
Bible-based, very Scriptural, very Christian.''
</P>
<P>
   She says in her book that her friends tried to edit her
self-definition of ``born again.'' They would modify it to
``Christian-ish,'' but she sticks with ``born again,'' and writes,
``I could go to a gathering of foot-washing Baptists, and except
for my dreadlocks, fit right in.''
</P>
<P>
   Her hair in dreadlocks, set off by a gardenia at a recent
reading, coil and jump over the gold cross around her neck. Like
her religion, her hair was a surprising fit. She thought she wanted
smooth hair with bangs but she was stuck with frizzy hair which no
amount of moussing could tame.
</P>
<P>
   But a few years ago she found that her hair twists into splendid
dreadlocks and now people come up and ask her who does it, which is
a miracle for anyone who has lived 40 years thinking she wanted
something else.
</P>
<P>
   This devout Christian, who obsesses about hair and cellulite and
says the F word, has faith galore but she doesn't have answers to
why little kids suffer and best friends die. But she has something.
</P>
<P>
   Putting it out there in her neurotic Peter Pan style she's bound
to convert a few. She's aiming for people who rejected the church
of their childhood and people offended by the Christian right.
</P>
<P>
   She thinks there's an ``invisible hunger'' for people to
believe.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's the millennium. Maybe it's simply that we don't want
any group thinking they have exclusive rights to God. Even an
un-churchable type can find herself seeking out a cathedral in a
new city and needing to light a candle. Or sometimes just feeling
compelled to go outside and meet with the stars.
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Swartz is a columnist for The Press Democrat in Santa
Rosa, Calif. Her e-mail address is sfswartz(AT)pressdemo.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
