<DOCNO> NYT19990216.0253 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-16 18:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7490 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-MATISSE-PICASSO     02-16 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-MATISSE-PICASSO-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXHIBITING THE CONTRAST AND RIVALRY BETWEEN MATISSE AND PICASSO 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By SARAH BOXER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ When Picasso saw Matisse's ``Joy of Life''
(1906), he produced ``Les Desmoiselles d'Avignon'' (1907) in
response. When Matisse saw Picasso's portrait of a dreamer, ``Woman
With Yellow Hair'' (1931), he countered four years later with ``The
Dream.'' Matisse and Picasso were goads, rivals and measures for
one another.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one has ever looked at Matisse's painting more carefully
than I,'' Picasso once said, ``and no one has looked at mine more
carefully than he.'' But Picasso never painted a Matisse, and
Matisse never painted a Picasso. As the art historian Leo Steinberg
put it, ``unlike Picasso'' is a mantra for Matisse scholars and
vice versa.
</P>
<P>
   How many ways are there to say that Matisse is not Picasso and
Picasso is not Matisse? At a symposium to kick off the exhibition
``Matisse and Picasso: A Gentle Rivalry'' organized by Yve-Alain
Bois at the Kimbell Art Museum in Fort Worth, there were 49
examples, starting with touch and ending with death.
</P>
<P>
   The first speaker, Steinberg, pondered the way each painter
painted fingers. ``Picasso's touch is too demonstrative to leave
anything out'' (Example No. 1), Steinberg said. Matisse is a master
of fingers with no end (No. 2).
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to making paint or paper scraps ``vicissitate,''
or assume different roles, he said, Picasso rules (3). In one
Cubist collage, ``Siphon, Glass, Newspaper, Violin,'' pieces of
newspaper ``dematerialize into connotations'': one is a siphon, or
is it a wine bottle?; another is a glass and shadow; still another
is scratch paper to draw on. Scraps from the trash become
``dramatis personae,'' players with careers, Steinberg said.
Picasso has ``intrinsic wit'' (4). Matisse can hide figures in a
landscape (5). Picasso can represent multiple views of a figure
(6). Picasso's black eyes are better(7). Matisse makes black a
color (8). ``Matisse feels'' (9). ``Picasso embodies'' (10).
``Matisse resonates'' (11). Picasso begins ``in medias res'' (12).
</P>
<P>
   Steinberg added: ``Matisse can mix drawing and painting, but men
and women? No way'' (13). Picasso is obsessed with mating (14);
even his pigeons do it. In Picasso, there is narrative focus (15).
In Matisse there is no main attraction, not even the face (16).
Why? It would be ``too attractive,'' stealing attention from the
painting itself.
</P>
<P>
   Picasso conducts an ``assault on the center,'' Steinberg said;
he ``closes like a fist'' (17). Matisse is loose and expansive.
``He knows where the center is but his vectors speed past it''
(18).
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at Matisse, and Picasso seems overanxious'' (19),
Steinberg continued. ``Get into Picasso, and Matisse seems
decorative'' (20) and ``shallow'' (21).
</P>
<P>
   That's all well and good. But what happens when they start
trespassing on each other's turf? John Elderfield, the chief
curator at large at the Museum of Modern Art in New York, told a
story about Matisse in Picasso-land. In 1935 Matisse began work on
``The Pink Nude.'' If you look at the photographs of each stage of
the work, Elderfield said, they form ``an archeology of Matisse's
reaction'' to one of Picasso's nudes in an armchair.
</P>
<P>
   For Picasso, paintings that suggest control and submission in
the same moment were second nature. He often painted women gazing
challengingly at the viewer (22) and at the same time seductively
displaying both rear and front (23).
</P>
<P>
   For Matisse such an approach was treacherous (24). He went
through no fewer than 22 tries to get ``The Pink Nude'' right. And
he only found a comfortable solution to it when he took a break.
One afternoon, he drew a satyr spying on a nymph from above. The
next morning he went back to the painting and transformed some
flowers sitting on a chair into a stand-in for the satyr. The
flowers got a view of the model's front; the viewer saw the side.
Unlike Picasso, Matisse didn't distort the figure to get a double
view (25).
</P>
<P>
   That was not the only time one artist chased madly after the
other. In the early 1930s, Albert Skira commissioned Matisse to
illustrate some Mallarme poems and, at the same time, commissioned
Picasso to illustrate a new edition of Ovid's ``Metamorphoses.''
Picasso saw the commissions as a contest, said Lisa Florman, an
assistant professor of art history at Ohio State University. He
rushed to finish first.
</P>
<P>
   In 1933, when both finished, Picasso finally got his digs in. In
one of the prints in the Vollard Suite, Picasso drew an artist
holding up a classic Matissean image, a goldfish in a bowl. Could
it be that Picasso was at last paying homage to Matisse, ``the
master of goldfish'' (26), telling him he admired the way his
figures circulate around the canvas like fish in a bowl (see No.
18)?
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly. Picasso, Ms. Florman argued, was taunting Matisse,
saying his figures were cold (27) and distant (28), too much like
fish behind glass. Matisse, Picasso suggested, had to rely on
sublimation (29), while he himself was driven by desire (30).
</P>
<P>
   Color? Could it be a case of Picasso in Matisse-land? In the
early 1930's Picasso emerged from a painting slump by developing a
pneumatic and parti-colored style, painting the inflated figure of
his new love, Marie-Therese Walter, with migrating body parts,
vacant head and, most notably, yellow hair and violet skin.
</P>
<P>
   Some people see these multicolored confections as the influence
of Walter herself (whose skin Picasso saw as violet). Others think
Picasso is taking a shot at Matissean color. Matisse the Fauve was
famous for arbitrary, unrealistic hues (31).
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But even in his most Matissean moment, Picasso was not Matisse,
argued Rosalind Krauss, an art history professor at Columbia
University. Rather, she said, Picasso was recalling the year 1914,
when he triumphed in his own way over realistic, optical color by
pasting a piece of stippled mauve wallpaper (32) into two Cubist
collages, ``Pipe and Sheet Music'' and ``Bottle of Bass, Ace of
Clubs and Pipe.''
</P>
<P>
   The relationship between Matisse and Picasso was not all
``gentle rivalry.'' Picasso once told Francoise Gilot that
Matisse's ``Still Life With Magnolia'' set ``his teeth on edge.''
Why? There was no cause and effect. It was just one thing after
another: a pot, a magnolia, a shell, a pitcher. Picasso had a point
(34).
</P>
<P>
   Richard Shiff of the University of Texas at Austin observed that
Picasso's paintings always lend themselves to analysis (35). There
is a multiplicity of explanations of each element in his work
because everything is overdetermined (36). ``Words do not fail when
you try to analyze a Picasso,'' Shiff said. The problem, he said,
is ``how to terminate the analysis'' (37).
</P>
<P>
   In this multiply determined world, Picasso is ringmaster, ``the
prime mover,'' Shiff said (38). But with Matisse everything is part
of a harmony (39) that seems to have been achieved unconsciously
(40). Ms. Gilot described Matisse's ``Still Life With Magnolia''as
``full of bliss'' and ``impossible to analyze'' (41).
</P>
<P>
   But what is at the heart of these differences _ Picasso's
narrative intensity and Matisse's harmonious bliss, Picasso's
``assault on the center'' and Matisse's distracted, all-over
structures? Perhaps one can see the core difference in the way they
each confronted death.
</P>
<P>
   Picasso represented ``the desolation of age'' in a series of
skull paintings, said Jack Flam, an art history professor at
Brooklyn College. For Picasso death was an adversary (42). The
battle was to be fought on earth. Old Matisse, though, ``cultivated
an image of youthfulness, a world in which there is no death''
(43). He developed a set of signs _ simplified graphic symbols for
nasturtiums, leeks, leaves (44). These cutout symbols, which Louis
Aragon called a poet's palette of words, look as if they can
transcend the world of things and places as easily as Matisse moved
them from one work to another.
</P>
<P>
   Both artists were obsessed in old age with observing themselves.
When Picasso painted his head, he showed himself becoming an
inanimate object (45). Matisse represented himself looking in the
mirror, his own hand bringing the drawing into being. He was
wondering how he could ``be in and out of himself at the same
time'' (46), Flam said.
</P>
<P>
   Matisse painted goldfish for a reason. Flashing and circulating,
they are nowhere and everywhere at once. Picasso painted heads for
a reason. They are emblems of self on earth. If Picasso raged
against death and the dying of the light (47), Flam concluded,
Matisse was ``preoccupied with life force'' (48). He was sailing to
Byzantium (49).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
