 WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   Israel: Labor Party Picks Candidates
</P>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ In national primaries, the Labor Party has chosen a
list of dovish candidates for the May 17 elections. The top
vote-getter, Shlomo Ben Ami, is a Moroccan-born academic whose high
standing alters the party's image as the representative of the
Ashkenazi elite.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   Britain: A Resignation Call
</P>
<P>
   LONDON _ A tide of public concern about possible health risks
from genetically modified food has led to calls for the resignation
of the trade minister, Lord Sainsbury, the supermarket tycoon, over
reports that he owns the patent to a gene widely used in food
modification.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   India: Party Quits Coalition
</P>
<P>
   NEW DELHI _ Om Prakash Chautala, leader of the Indian National
Lok Dal, a party with four seats in Parliament, said he would
withdraw support from the national coalition government, slicing
its slim majority even thinner. Chautala made his decision after
Prime Minister Atal Behari Vajpayee declined to roll back a rise in
the prices of subsidized food grains and fertilizer.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   Mexico: Police Accused in Massacre
</P>
<P>
   Top police officials in Chiapas helped arm and protect
pro-government gunmen who killed 45 Indians in a 1997 massacre, six
lower-ranking policemen have testified. The officers, who are
serving three-year sentences for supplying weapons to the gunmen,
told prosecutors they were following orders from the Chiapas state
police chief and the highest state official for public security.
</P>
<P>
   Canada: New Territory, New Premier
</P>
<P>
   One of the first duties of the 19 members elected Monday to a
legislative assembly in the Arctic territory of Nunavut will be to
decide which one will become premier when the territory comes into
existence on April 1. A former member of the federal Parliament,
Jack Anawak, is considered the fron-trunner. He has served as
interim commissioner of the largely Inuit area for much of the last
two years.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   Nigeria: 2 Parties Pick Joint Candidate
</P>
<P>
   Two political parties agreed on a single presidential candidate
from the south to challenge the leading party's choice, Gen.
Olusegun Obasanjo, in Feb. 27 elections. The All People's Party,
whose base is in the north, will be represented by Olu Falae, a
former finance minister whom the Alliance for Democracy, a Yoruba
party from the southwest, had already chosen as its flag-bearer.
</P>
</TEXT>
