<HEADER>
A7494 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOLLY-RINGWALD-LADN     02-16 1445
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOLLY-RINGWALD-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN ADULT MOLLY RINGWALD TACKLES SERIOUS MATERIAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
 
  
By REED JOHNSON  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ She probably could pass for 19, or 26, or, if
you're pushing it, maybe even 35.
</P>
<P>
   There's that same razor-straight red hair, only a bit longer and
a shade or two darker than when she made all those John Hughes
movies. Big, meditative brown eyes. A face full of freckles.
</P>
<P>
   She could be your daughter, your kid sister, that ardent high
school sweetheart you never married. When you step into the
interview room she looks at you evenly, swallowing another mouthful
of takeout chili, then quietly asks how you're doing.
</P>
<P>
   Her self-possessed tone suggests there's probably no question
that would rattle Molly Ringwald.
</P>
<P>
   Later, when you ask how she came to be so comfortable with,
well, strange adults, she answers with the verbal equivalent of a
shrug.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's just sort of my makeup,'' the actress replies
thoughtfully. ``I don't think I'm as trusting now as I used to be,
but as a child I was very trusting. Unless I got a weird vibe off
of somebody. I've always been kind of instinctive, too.''
</P>
<P>
   At the end of her third decade (she turns 31 this month), Molly
Ringwald is no longer a kid _ hard to believe if it seems like only
yesterday you watched her in ``Sixteen Candles,'' ``The Breakfast
Club'' or any of the ingenue roles that earned her a Time magazine
cover as the hottest young actress of the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Ringwald has maintained a lower profile, taking a
leave of absence from Hollywood in 1992 and moving to Paris for
four years. She made several foreign films, including ``Seven
Sundays'' with Jean-Luc Godard, before returning to the United
States. She also was seen in the short-lived series ``Townies.''
</P>
<P>
   But the former Brat Packer is still youthful and unjaded enough
to play a teen-ager in ``How I Learned to Drive,'' the Pulitzer
Prize-winning play by Paula Vogel, now in previews at the Mark
Taper Forum in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   In Vogel's unusual coming-of-age story, Ringwald's character,
Lil' Bit, ranges in age from 11 to roughly 35 or 40. When the play
opens, she's looking back at herself as a Maryland teen-ager whose
doting, charismatic Uncle Peck (Brian Kerwin) is teaching her how
to operate a '56 Chevy _ and a whole lot more besides.
</P>
<P>
   Peck, to be blunt, is a pedophile, and his ministrations to his
underage niece are as smoothly and chillingly purposeful as the
expert driving lessons he also imparts during their frequent
outings in the pre-suburbanized Maryland countryside.
</P>
<P>
   But ``How I Learned to Drive'' doesn't depict Peck as a monster
in a freak-of-the-week TV-style melodrama, with Lil' Bit as his
unwitting victim. Without glossing over the dark side of his
character, Vogel shows him to be a complex, sensitive and
profoundly lonely human being who, in some hard-to-define way,
helps Lil' Bit escape from her redneck family and begin the painful
journey toward adulthood and independence.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the only person in her family that sort of understands
who she is,'' Ringwald explains. ``She feels like a freak because
of the thoughts she has; she talks about `the fire in her head.'
And also her body, she's overdeveloped for her age physically and
emotionally. And he's the guy that sort of says, `OK, I see you
someplace else, I know you're going to go someplace else, and you
deserve to be someplace else.' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``How I Learned to Drive'' is Vogel's most successful work since
``The Baltimore Waltz,'' a semi-autobiographical fantasia based on
the life of the author's gay brother, Carl. Like that earlier work,
``How I Learned to Drive'' mixes broad humor and poignant
reflection with a hard-to-classify political viewpoint.
</P>
<P>
   The play earned euphoric reviews when it opened at New York's
Vineyard Theater off-Broadway two winters ago and ended up winning
the Pulitzer Prize. Some 50 productions of the play will have
occurred by the end of this year, across the United States as well
as in Israel, South Africa, France and Japan.
</P>
<P>
   That success probably wouldn't have been possible if Vogel had
written a literal-minded morality tale about child abuse, and
Ringwald for one believes that child abuse isn't the play's main
focus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is a love story,'' she says. ``It's not a love
story that's certainly acceptable in society, and I don't think
Paula set out to write a play that was about these two people who
obviously cannot be together and (imply) that it's OK for them to
be together. What she always says is that she set out to write
something like `Lolita,' but from Lolita's point of view.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Brokaw, who has directed both the New York and the Taper
productions, cite Vogel's remarks that the play is ``about the
gifts we get from the people who hurt us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what the author really wants us to be able to do is
care for both of these people,'' Brokaw says. ``She pulls no
punches in terms of ... what has actually happened. But I think
that by the time we get to the real meat of the matter, we've been
able to be seduced by both of these people and seduced into their
relationship. Not that we will necessarily approve of it, but I
think we will at least understand how and why it happened.''
</P>
<P>
   For Ringwald, playing Lil' Bit means being able to convincingly
portray a girl one-third her own age, an assignment she previously
handled when she took over the role in New York from Mary-Louise
Parker. Ringwald says she generally concentrates on tapping into
Lil' Bit's thoughts and emotions, and the body language tends to
take care of itself.
</P>
<P>
   She and actor Brian Kerwin also worked out their strategy for
dealing with the delicate scene near the end of the play where Peck
and Lil' Bit act out their most intimate physical encounter.
</P>
<P>
   ``You kind of talk about it gently before, and you make certain
ground rules and kind of go from there,'' Ringwald says. ``And
everything's fine. And Brian is a great guy, really easy to work
with.''
</P>
<P>
   Describing herself as ``the baby'' in a Sacramento family of
three children, Ringwald began her acting career before she hit her
fourth birthday. Her first professional stage role was in the
chorus of the musical ``Annie.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good play for a kid because there were a lot of kids
in it,'' she says. ``It wasn't like this dramatic, you know,
`Oedipus' or anything like that.''
</P>
<P>
   If Ringwald, by her own account, was a trusting child, her
parents were always supportive and protective. They were
particularly wary of scripts with any kind of inappropriate sexual
content.
</P>
<P>
   ``(My mom) didn't want me to do anything on film that I hadn't
experienced in my life, so that the overtly sexual scripts were not
even sent to me,'' Ringwald says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Also, I was a California minor, and subject to different laws
than New York, certain nudity laws. It may have changed now in New
York. Which is why Brooke Shields was able to do stuff: She was a
New York minor and I was a California minor. But it was also just
something that my mom didn't want me to go there.''
</P>
<P>
   As a young actress, Ringwald says, she had an additional
mentor-protector in the form of a female studio teacher who served
as her personal tutor. The woman, who passed away a couple years
ago, was something of a Hollywood backstage legend, having also
assisted Jodie Foster and Winona Ryder early in their careers.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was kind of maternal but more like a friend, really,''
Ringwald says.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's kind of what Lil' Bit, I think, finds in Peck. Except
without the other side of it, because obviously this was a
wonderful, healthy relationship in my life. Everything I got from
her was kind of like what Lil' Bit gets. Because she saw something
in me, she always knew that I was kind of destined for other
things, she protected me and taught me things without my knowing
it.''
</P>
<P>
   With several new projects under way, including a role in the
summer thriller ``Killing Mrs. Tingle,'' written and directed by
Kevin Williamson (``Scream'') with teen fave Katie Holmes; and
``Hearts and Bones,'' with Keifer Sutherland and Daryl Hannah,
Ringwald appears destined for more good things. So far, she seems
to be managing the trick, as Casey Stengel put it, of growing up
without growing old.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a very young woman with a very wise soul, the soul of
someone with great experience,'' says director Brokaw. ``And I
think that's what makes her particularly compelling in this part.
Because I think that's true for Lil' Bit also, because even at the
age of 11 (she) has an old soul.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
