<SLUG> BC-BUSH-VISITS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOREIGN DIGNITARIES NOW VISITING BUSH ON REGULAR BASIS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ All governors get occasional visits from foreign
dignitaries, but Gov. George W. Bush's presidential aspirations
have turned the Texas Capitol into a mini-United Nations in recent
weeks, including Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The day's gubernatorial guests included former Canadian Prime
Minister Brian Mulroney and two diplomats from the Persian Gulf
nation of Qatar. Last week, Bush greeted Britain's Tory leader
William Hague.
</P>
<P>
   Mulroney, whose tenure was viewed as a disaster for his
conservative party, left Bush with the impression that ``it's
important for the Republican Party to unify as opposed to splinter.
I think he's worried that the party would tend to shatter on some
issues,'' Bush said after their brief private meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Mulroney didn't meet with the press, but took a bow from the
gallery of the Texas House at Bush's request. Bush described
Mulroney as ``a friend of my dad's ... a friend of America, a great
world leader when he was in power.'' He was prime minister from
1984 until his resignation in 1993, coinciding with George Bush's
terms as vice president and president.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's meeting with the dignitaries from Qatar also was private.
Sheik Hamad bin Jassim bin Jabr Al Thani, Qatar's minister of
foreign affairs, was accompanied by Ambassador Saad M. Al-Kobaisi,
a gubernatorial spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just going to listen,'' Bush said. ``He's just coming by
to make a courtesy call,'' Bush said of the sheik. ``I don't have
an agenda,'' the governor added.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get ambassadors that come all the time. This (presidential)
speculation has seemed to have caused more governments to send
their ambassadors my way, so I look forward to listening,'' Bush
said.
</P>
<P>
   The visitors claim to be doing some listening as well.
</P>
<P>
   According to the British Broadcasting Corp., Hague returned to
England saying he had gathered information about successful GOP
strategies, including Bush's ``compassionate conservatism.'' The
British network described Bush as ``one of the foremost exponents
of the new `caring conservatism.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hague will tell his party it must be seen as `open, inclusive
and compassionate,' as opposed to its past `elitist' image,'' the
BBC reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
