<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-16 18:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7498 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MANDELA-HOMETOWN-ART-     02-16 1098
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MANDELA-HOMETOWN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANDELA'S CHILDHOOD AS NASCENT TOURIST ATTRACTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (South Africa Journal) 
(ART ADV: Graphic map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By SUZANNE DALEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   QUNU, South Africa _ If you don't concentrate you can drive
through this tiny rural village without even noticing it. Of
course, the yellow brick house with the guard tower might catch
your eye. It looks more or less like what it is _ an imitation of a
South African jailer's cottage.
</P>
<P>
   It is President Nelson Mandela's vacation house. He had it built
that way after having spent his last years in prison in a similar
bungalow. He said he wanted the familiar floor plan so that he
could find the kitchen without banging his shins in the middle of
the night.
</P>
<P>
   The house is just a few yards from the main road. On the other
side is the rest of Qunu, mostly a collection of round huts and a
fair number of Mandela cousins who are tending sheep and cattle and
pigs. That is where Mandela did most of his growing up, and he has
said he will retire there.
</P>
<P>
   But that is seeming more and more unlikely, especially now that
he has married Graca Machel, the widow of the former president of
Mozambique. ``What would Graca do there?'' some on the president's
staff have been heard to mutter.
</P>
<P>
   No matter. Mandela has already spent enough time here to put
Qunu on the map. Hundreds of tourists travel out here every year,
though the village is nowhere near any of South Africa's top
tourist destinations. It is a winding potholed three-hour drive
north of the nearest big city, East London, on the southeastern
coast.
</P>
<P>
   But Qunu residents have not let the tourists make much of an
impression on them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, they come,'' said Kutala Tetani, 18, who was chasing
down an errant donkey recently across the road from Mandela's
house. ``They do not bother us.''
</P>
<P>
   No one has thought to put up a sign or open a souvenir stand,
though a visitor can buy a cold drink or a large sack of ground
corn at the tiny store next to the mailboxes.
</P>
<P>
   But much has changed for Qunu since Mandela left prison in 1990.
He came here almost right away, hungry to see the open spaces of
his homeland, where the rolling hills are velvety green in the
summer and there are hardly any trees. Because Mandela is now 80,
not too many people remembered him, but everyone knew who he was.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time he came,'' said Leonard Mandela, 67, a relative
of the president who has lived here all his life, ``he would have a
walk and all the way the people just followed him.''
</P>
<P>
   But in his memoirs, Mandela said he was bothered by what he saw
when he returned. ``What had endured was the warmth and the
simplicity of the community, which took me back to my days as a
boy,'' he wrote. ``But what disturbed me was that the villagers
seemed as poor if not poorer than they had ever been then. Most
people still lived in simple huts with dirt floors, with no
electricity and no running water.''
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays the village has electricity, new water taps, new school
buildings and, right now, a tunnel that is being built so that the
children can safely cross the road to visit Mandela.
</P>
<P>
   Some of this is just a result of new anti-poverty programs. But
some is Mandela's famous corporate arm-twisting at work. The
residents of Qunu can point to villages across the valley that do
not have such amenities. They concede that there is some jealousy.
</P>
<P>
   ``All these other villages, they are complaining,'' Leonard
Mandela said with a shake of his head and a shrug that suggested
that this was too bad, but certainly not something to spend too
much time over.
</P>
<P>
   Down the road at the freshly painted new high school with the
luxury of a book-filled library and a science laboratory, the
principal, Zoneka Jafta, and the deputy principal, Mncedis
Mabuntane, said there was a fair degree of animosity toward them in
neighboring communities.
</P>
<P>
   But Mrs. Jafta, who has been the high school principal since
1984, does not tolerate such complaints. ``They are saying, `Why
does Mandela always do for his own place?' '' she said. ``He is
going to do more everywhere. But he is starting here. I don't see
anything wrong with that.''
</P>
<P>
   When Mandela was released from jail after 27 years, the Qunu
school was a couple of falling-down huts, Mrs. Jafta said, with
floors of hard cow dung. The 10th grade was taught under a tree.
The principal's office was a shack. And in 1989, the outhouse
collapsed, dropping half a dozen students into the pit.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had to be pulled from that,'' Mrs. Jafta said. ``Their
shoes were left behind. And then they had to walk 5 kilometers to
the water to wash. It was very traumatic.''
</P>
<P>
   When Mandela first visited the school, he heard about all the
problems but made no promises, she recounted. Then one day a
helicopter landed. Prodded to do a good deed, executives from
Caltex, the oil company, had arrived. Within the year, Caltex had
built several buildings for the school.
</P>
<P>
   There are still problems. The science lab does not have a single
chair or desk. The children have to take classes standing up and
lean on one another to take notes. There are no refrigerators. Mrs.
Jafta and Mabuntane are assembling a list for Mandela's next visit.
</P>
<P>
   He usually comes by at Christmas time, when he hands out
presents to the children. To hear them tell it, he is rather
single-minded in his conversation.
</P>
<P>
   ``He tells us to stay in school,'' the students say in a chorus.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   One year, Mandela gave the students an American $100 bill. They
eventually voted to use it toward improving the water system.
</P>
<P>
   There are plans afoot to have a museum here. Not that there is
too much left from Mandela's childhood. His mother's hut was taken
down to make room for his brother's house. And the Methodist Church
school that Mandela attended and that gave him the Christian name
Nelson is gone, too.
</P>
<P>
   In his book ``Long Walk to Freedom,'' Mandela tells of his first
day at school, when his father took a pair of his own trousers, put
them on his son, cut them around the ankles to get the length
right, tied them at the waist and sent him off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I must have been a comical sight,'' Mandela wrote. ``But I
have never owned a suit I was prouder to wear than my father's
cut-off trousers.''
</P>
<P>
   In those days, Mandela said, his principal goal in life was to
be the best stick fighter around.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
