</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMAN-SLAVE-PAY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITING `CAMPAIGN' AGAINST GERMANY, CHANCELLOR PLANS FUND FOR
VICTIMS OF NAZIS
</HEADLINE>
  (fe) 
 By ROGER COHEN 
 
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder of Germany announced on
Tuesday that a fund, projected to amount to $1.7 billion, would be
created and financed by 12 German companies to compensate victims
of the Nazis and end what he called ``the campaign being led
against German industry and our country.''
</P>
<P>
   The announcement, in the presence of some of Germany's top
executives, was clearly aimed at stopping a wave of lawsuits in
American courts against German companies that used slave labor and
forced labor during World War II. But Schroeder's choice of words
appeared unlikely to calm the waters.
</P>
<P>
   The chancellor, who took office last October and has been
struggling to stamp his authority on the government, said a main
function of the fund was ``to counter lawsuits, particularly class
action suits, and to remove the basis of the campaign being led
against German industry and our country.''
</P>
<P>
   The chancellor did not say who was behind the ``campaign''
against Germany, but his suggestion appeared comparable to the
response of some Swiss officials who said they saw a darkly
orchestrated anti-Swiss movement in the legal actions by Holocaust
survivors against Swiss banks that ultimately led to a $1.25
billion settlement signed last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an inadequate and embarrassing statement,'' said
Michael Witti, a Munich-based lawyer for tens of thousands of
plaintiffs in the suits already brought. ``It is not a question of
campaigns by anybody. It is a question of Holocaust victims' rights
that have been denied by these corporations for decades.''
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder's statement, in which firmness mingled with remorse,
appeared to catch the ambivalent mood of a Germany anxious to put
the past behind it, irritated over what some intellectuals have
called the ``popularization'' of the Holocaust, yet still conscious
of its inescapable historical responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Since the end of World War II, the German government has paid
out about $80 billion in war reparations and aid, most of it to
Jews who survived concentration camps or fled.
</P>
<P>
   But forced laborers _ people, generally non-Jews, deported to
Germany mainly from Eastern European countries including Poland and
Russia _ have not often been compensated. Nor has a far smaller
category of slave laborers _ some Jewish, some not _ who were put
to work in concentration camps.
</P>
<P>
   The creation of the ``Remembrance, Responsibility and the
Future'' fund is intended to answer the ``moral responsibility of
German firms with regard to such issues as forced laborers,
Aryanization and other injustice during the Nazi regime,'' said
Schroeder, who was speaking in Bonn.
</P>
<P>
   Its aim is thus broad. The term ``Aryanization'' refers to the
takeover, often with derisory payments or none at all, of Jewish
property in Germany. Many Jewish survivors are now seeking
compensation for these acts.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder did not specify the amount of the fund, but officials
here provided the rough estimate of about three billion German
marks, equal to about $1.7 billion. The chancellor said payments
should start ``very quickly, if possible before Sept. 1, 1999'' in
view of the advanced age of many of the people involved.
</P>
<P>
   Witti said the sum of $1.7 billion, if accurate, was substantial
but inadequate. He estimated that there were about 1.6 million
World War survivors who could qualify for compensation under the
fund, each of whom might then receive about $1,000, if payments
were equal.
</P>
<P>
   The Polish government has said there are more than 500,000
surviving forced laborers in Poland alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is clearly right is the idea that payments should be made
against formal abandonment of all class-action suits,'' the lawyer
said. ``German industry must know that when it's over, it's over.''
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder's statement said that ``the governments of the United
States and Israel welcome this initiative as a positive and
courageous answer by German companies to their moral
responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   But American officials said privately that they were surprised
by the timing of the statement. ``We don't really know what to make
of it,'' one said. ``There are some raised eyebrows.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Eugene Dubow, the head of the American Jewish Committee in
Germany, said, ``If Schroeder thinks there is a campaign against
Germany, perhaps he does not totally understand the issue of people
waiting 50 years for justice.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration, aware of the potential impact of the
suits on German-American relations, has followed the issue closely.
The announcement came after protracted negotiations led by Bodo
Hombach, Schroeder's chief of staff, and Stuart Eizenstat, the
State Department under secretary for business and economic affairs.
Eizenstat is expected in Germany next week.
</P>
<P>
   The 12 companies that announced their participation in the fund
on Tuesday are: DaimlerChrysler, Deutsche Bank, Siemens,
Volkswagen, Hoechst, Dresdner Bank, Krupp, Allianz, BASF, Bayer,
BMW and Degussa. The list _ encompassing auto making, banking,
chemical production, insurance and other industrial sectors _
covers many of Germany's top industrial names. They invited other
companies to join them.
</P>
<P>
   At a time that German companies have been on a buying spree
overseas _ last year the auto manufacturer Chrysler and the
publisher Random House were both acquired by German companies _ the
slave-labor question has been particularly sensitive.
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Bank is still trying to complete the purchase of
Bankers Trust, the financial services company. But the acquisition
has met some resistance in the United States, pending clarification
of slave-labor and other issues. The German bank said this month
that it had helped to finance Auschwitz.
</P>
<P>
   Rolf Breuer, the chief executive of Deutsche Bank, was with
Schroeder on Tuesday. He said the fund amounted to a ``large step
in the right direction, but there are still a lot of details to
sort out.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the details is the planned establishment of a German
federal fund alongside the one financed by the companies. It is not
clear how large it might be. Schroeder's statement said, ``A
suitable link with the companies' initiative must now be found.''
</P>
<P>
   The companies said part of the fund would be used to compensate
slave laborers and other victims and part to finance
``forward-looking projects on the basis of understanding of the
Nazi past.''
</P>
<P>
   The quest to find a balance between remembrance and
forward-looking themes has become something of a German obsession
of late, affecting a still unresolved debate over a Holocaust
Memorial in Berlin, the new capital.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the discussions lies an evident German thirst to be
``normal'' and embrace the future in a country where the vast
majority of people alive today played no role in the Holocaust.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
