<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Newspaper industry conference comes to AtlantaBy Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Editor and Publisher, the magazine of the newspaper
industry brings its 10th annual Interactive newspapers conference
to Atlanta Feb 17-20. The four-day event will take place at the
Hyatt Regency Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Keynote speaker Michael Bloomberg, founder and CEO of Bloomberg
News is scheduled to talk about the challenges and strategies
facing journalism in the online world. The president of
Atlanta-based Cox Interactive Media, Peter Winter, will speak
Friday on convergence and managing multiple media streams.
</P>
<P>
   This is the tenth anniversary of the conference first held in
Dallas 10 years ago with 50 attendees and no exhibitors. This year,
according to Marsha Stoltman, Editor and Publisher's vice president
of marketing relations, 1,300-plus attendees are expected along
with 117 exhibitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back in 1990, we were talking about very different products
like videotext, for example,'' Stoltman says, adding that the
conference has become global in scope and issues. ``We have
attendees from 35 different countries. The issues are the same no
matter what part of the world you live in,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   The four day conference addresses all aspects of online
journalism from marketing to editorial and classified advertising.
The classified advertising section features advertisers talking
about how they divide their dollars between online and traditional
media.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll also be focusing on organizational issues, which has
been a really tough issue for many media companies. We'll also talk
about targeting younger consumers, who aren't really reading
newspapers. We'll talk about how they are getting their news and
how the industry is pro-actively working to capture those people.''
</P>
<P>
   Frances Katz writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
