<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEORGIA-Y2K-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Citizens' committee will get first members soon
 &HT;    By Rob Chambers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Georgia Y2K citizens' committee is coming out of
incubation.
</P>
<P>
   Last Wednesday, Georgia's Gov. Roy Barnes met with Southern
Co.'s head, A.W. ``Bill'' Dahlberg, the newly appointed Y2K czar,
about the shape of Dahlberg's new job.
</P>
<P>
   ``The plan now is to have the first 10 members of Dahlberg's Y2K
citizens' committee appointed by Friday. Then we can at least get
the executive order forming that committee signed and done,'' said
the governor's spokesman, Jim Flowers. ``We can add more members
later,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a pretty diverse group,'' Flowers added.
``We're looking at people from the hospital industry,
communications and, of course, the utility industry'' _ this last
reference was to Dahlberg.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've also got a retired banker under consideration,'' Flowers
said. ``We may include a minister.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're aiming for a pretty good cross-section covering the
whole state. For what you can do with 15 to 20 people, it'll be a
fair representation of the state as a whole. We want enough ears
into different areas of the state that we'll hear about everything
one way or another,'' Flowers said.
</P>
<P>
   The citizens' committee will work with the Y2K inter-agency task
force, the latter the product of a Barnes executive order announced
Jan. 29.
</P>
<P>
   The task force will ``coordinate information exchange and
assistance to local governments as they assess and plan for Y2K,''
Barnes said at the time. The information gathered will also be used
by GEMA, the Georgia Emergency Management Agency, ``to coordinate
contingency planning for the state and communities.''
</P>
<P>
   The task force is going to coordinate Y2K surveys ``so we don't
duplicate efforts,'' said Flowers. ``It's also going to coordinate
what other data gatherers have done so we can share best
practices.''
</P>
<P>
   The task force will ``work with communities that have to respond
to surveys, and it will help them respond.'' And it will supply
additional help through volunteers, if necessary, Flowers noted.
</P>
<P>
   ``In other words, if a municipality has embedded processors, and
if it doesn't know what to look for,'' then the task force will
``help them with that,'' Flowers said.
</P>
<P>
   He explained that Dahlberg's citizens' committee will also be in
close contact with all the state agencies.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the citizens' committee will be out in the
communities, Flowers said.
</P>
<P>
   The committee will know ``what's going on, and it can be a
two-way information force, saying, `Here's what's already being
done out there, but here's what needs to be done.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Flowers explained, the citizens' committee will
``make sure that what agencies are doing is both the right thing
and something that's understood by everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   March 5 is the tentative date for the first meeting with the
citizens' committee, Flowers said. ``That's going to be a meeting
where we give a good briefing about the readiness of the state
agencies and also a briefing about GEMA.''
</P>
<P>
   Rob Chambers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
