<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-MEDIA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Institutions respond to call of new media
 &HT;    By Ernest Holsendolph
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Academe has had a reputation for being slow off the
mark when it comes to preparing students for what industry needs
right now. But local colleges, obviously hearing the firebell
ringing, have turned their attention to training people for fields
like Web design and information technology.
</P>
<P>
   And students are eager and ready, too.
</P>
<P>
   Both Georgia Tech and the University of Georgia have designed
programs in new media, emphasizing the science and art of creating
material on the Internet to inform, sell, and connect with a public
anxious to learn and do transactions on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Other schools, like Clayton State, are busy training platoons of
information technologists to massage and manage streams of data for
companies large and small. The school reports nearly 500 students
enrolled since fall, with the demand outrunning the available
teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Williams, president of the Metro Atlanta Chamber of
Commerce, outlined the reason why the pressure is on to accelerate
the production of trained people for the information industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hometown employers are growing so fast we need 19,000 new
trained workers per year to compete with other emerging high-tech
cities,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   That demand is driving starting salaries for some of these
new-minted, new-media mavens to $40,000 and up.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia opened its Dowden Center for New Media Studies in
Athens, Ga. in early 1994, and has now placed about 80 students in
shops and big businesses like CNN, IBM, First Union Bank and iXL.
</P>
<P>
   The Dowden Center, which is a part of the Henry W. Grady College
of Journalism and Communication, has the resources of a nationally
recognized communications industry program, said Scott A. Shamp,
center director.
</P>
<P>
   ``And there is no doubt that new media is a real hot spot in
communications,'' he said. ``In the old days, hard-nosed professors
would say, 'look to the the right, look to the left, only one of
you will make it.' Now these (new media) students are treated like
royalty.''
</P>
<P>
   The Georgia Tech program, which also began in 1994, is lodged in
the School of Literature, Communication and Culture, and draws on
the expertise of the school's computer technology experts.
</P>
<P>
   Although there is a two-year masters program in information
design and technology, Tech also draws hundreds of employed
part-time students for continuing education segments of two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The continuing education program is very much consumer driven,
catering to what students say they need to round out their
understanding, or get them started on a new area of interest,''
said Thomas Winn, director of continuing education.
</P>
<P>
   Even in the more structured full-time programs, schools are
under the gun to be flexible. They are hard-pressed to keep up with
business needs that are growing and shifting fast.
</P>
<P>
   Shamp at Georgia keeps the bridges up, bringing in outside
speakers frequently, including recent graduates of the program _
who can come in and talk about the real, live experiences, convey
the excitement of the new careers, and even scout the best
prospects for their own companies or employers.
</P>
<P>
   Classes are intimate by today's campus standards, with some 16
students per class in Athens, and a limit of 20 annually at Tech.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although we are surrounded by computers, as you see,'' Shamp
told me during one visit, ``the most important item in this room is
that table. That's where our work is done.''
</P>
<P>
   In that seminar-like atmosphere students debate the aesthetics
of existing Web pages they study and think up ways to present
graphics that are fresh and innovative but also clear to people who
view the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   In a more traditional structure, Tech students learn to use the
tools in class dealing with video, digital editing, graphic design
and multimedia. They also study how people learn in courses like
cultural theory and cognitive science.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the feeling that we must do more than train,'' said
Winn. ``We also need to teach history, and also put what we learn
in perspective, the kind of thing that is traditional for
colleges.''
</P>
<P>
   While the universities are dealing with some of the broader
skills in the new media, Clayton is working furiously to train the
technicians to man the computers and get the work done in the
utilities and other major companies which must keep up with the
latest ways to manage data.
</P>
<P>
   The new Information Technology Career Ladder (ITCL) program
started last fall and now has 455 students enrolled. Many of them
are in one-year certificate programs and will be on the job this
summer, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Other students are working toward two-year associate degrees as
well as bachelors degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Chancellor Stephen Portch, talking to the Board of Regents last
week in Atlanta, praised Clayton State for its ``spectacular''
response in gearing up fast.
</P>
<P>
   But economic development policymakers fear that a continued
shortfall in workers could dampen the growth of some technology
industries in metro Atlanta and elsewhere in the state.
</P>
<P>
   For the time being, however, the market is ruled by the freshly
trained grads in new media, the budding royalty.
</P>
<P>
   Ernest Holsendolph writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
