<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Part of Braves team warms up in Florida
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE BUENA VISTA, Fla. _ Like it or not, this spring training
figures to be short on suspense for the 1999 Atlanta Braves. Early
offseason activity by the Braves' front office has left the roster
nearly set, long before pitchers and catchers set foot in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Braves pitchers and catchers are due to report to camp today at
Disney's Wide World of Sports and will begin their workouts on
Thursday. The remaining players are scheduled to report Monday to
begin full-squad workouts on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   With the Braves' offseason acquisitions of outfielders Brian
Jordan and Otis Nixon, second baseman Bret Boone and reliever Mike
Remlinger, there's not much room left for maneuvering when the
Braves break camp and cut the roster to 25 to start the season
April 5.
</P>
<P>
   The only obvious opening is in the bullpen, but only a couple
spots are up for grabs there. With the return of closer Kerry
Lightenberg, setup men John Rocker and Rudy Seanez and the addition
of Remlinger, four spots are all but locked up.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves two to be fought over by Mark Wohlers, who attempts
his comeback after a disastrous 1998; Russ Springer, who is at home
recovering from back surgery and doubtful to be ready by Opening
Day; Odaliz Perez, the 20-year-old left-hander who pitched his way
onto the 1998 postseason roster; and Mike Cather, who reports good
health as he attempts his comeback from rib-extraction surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Barring a disastrous spring from rookie Bruce Chen, the Braves
starting pitching rotation figures to be as tough as ever, with
last season's Cy Young winner Tom Glavine, Greg Maddux as himself,
John Smoltz back with a healthy elbow and Millwood poised for his
second full season in the big leagues.
</P>
<P>
   The only position player who appears to be under the microscope
is Ryan Klesko, but even so, the Braves would like to see what kind
of influence new hitting coach Don Baylor will have on him this
spring before they'd consider letting him go. If that's where the
noise is supposed to come, it might well be a quiet spring.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon and Gerald Williams will give Cox some other worthy
options in the outfield. Even the Braves bench already appears not
only set but solid, with Nixon and Williams, Keith Lockhart's
healthy return from shoulder surgery, Ozzie Guillen, Danny Bautista
and catcher Eddie Perez.
</P>
<P>
   What will be interesting to watch is the new mix of offensive
talent and how manager Bobby Cox plans to work Jordan and Boone
into the batting order.
</P>
<P>
   Heading into spring training Cox said he thought Jordan had the
talent and versatility to bat anywhere from second to fifth. Boone
has batted second but might be useful as low as the eighth hole.
Look for Cox to do a little mixing and matching when the exhibition
season opens on March 4.
</P>
<P>
   But for all intents and purposes, this spring training will be
mostly about tinkering. And for a club that hit a franchise-record
215 home runs and set a modern-day franchise record with 826 runs
in 1998, that's a considerable luxury.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll Rogers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
