<SLUG> BC-FBN-OWNERS17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Houston, L.A. vying for team
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Barring potential snags, NFL owners will choose
between Los Angeles and Houston as their 32nd franchise during the
annual meetings next month in Phoenix. Identifying who will own the
team _ in what probably will be the final expansion franchise
awarded for the next 10-20 years _ figures to take a while longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not clear yet whether we'll choose an owner or simply
select the city and go to a bid process,'' Pittsburgh Steelers
owner Dan Rooney said after a four-hour session of the combined
finance and expansion committees held here.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Houston bid headed by Bob McNair already has
funding in place and is much further along than either of the
proposals from Los Angeles, the conventional wisdom is that NFL
commissioner Paul Tagliabue wants a team in the country's
second-largest market.
</P>
<P>
   Having a team in Los Angeles would give the NFL leverage when it
re-opens its television contracts after five years of the
eight-year deal.
</P>
<P>
   The league does not seem sold yet on either of the men seeking a
team for Los Angeles, former Hollywood agent Michael Ovitz and
developer Ed Roski. The Roski group did gain some clout with the
recent addition of billionaire Eli Broad.
</P>
<P>
   One hurdle confronting the commissioner is that some owners
don't want the league to fund a stadium in the Los Angeles area.
Several league officials concede that they lack the votes for such
a move.
</P>
<P>
   The annual meetings will be held March 14-18.
</P>
<P>
   Len Pasquarelli writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
