<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-16 18:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7518 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICROSOFT17-COX     02-16 0640
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMPAQ OFFICIAL DEFENDS MICROSOFT'S CONDUCT
 &HT;    470&AMP;add. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Despite occasional disputes, Compaq and Microsoft
agree more often than not on what's best for the computer industry,
according to a key Compaq official's written testimony released
Tuesday in the Microsoft antitrust trial.
</P>
<P>
   The testimony is significant because several other executives at
Compaq Computer Corp. have submitted depositions accusing Microsoft
of using its Windows licensing contracts with computer markers to
stifle competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Compaq has not agreed with every position asserted by
Microsoft, nor has Microsoft always agreed with our views,'' John
Rose, senior vice president and group general manager of Compaq's
enterprise computing group, declared in his written testimony as a
Microsoft defense witness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our two companies, however, have generally agreed on solutions
that have benefited customers and accommodated both our interests
and needs, and the computer industry as a whole,'' Rose said.
</P>
<P>
   Due to take the witness stand Wednesday, Rose will be the sole
outside industry executive to testify on behalf of Microsoft Corp.,
the world's largest software firm.
</P>
<P>
   Several Justice Department exhibits released earlier show that
Microsoft threatened to revoke Compaq's right to preload the
industry-standard Windows 95 operating system on its popular
Presario systems after Compaq revealed plans to remove the icon for
Microsoft's Internet Explorer browser from Presario desktops.
</P>
<P>
   But Rose contends in his 17-page brief that Microsoft acted
within its legal rights because Houston-based Compaq, the world's
largest maker of personal computers, breached a verbal deal with
its Redmond, Wash., software partner that had been reached in
August 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I look back on the facts today, I do not believe that
Microsoft had anything to do with whether Compaq in 1996 was also
loading Netscape Navigator or any other non-Microsoft product onto
its Presario computers,'' Rose wrote.
</P>
<P>
   That testimony could weigh heavily in reaching a verdict. The
government holds that Microsoft has illegally used its vast Windows
market power in seeking to dominate Internet commerce, focusing on
Netscape Communications Corp.'s Navigator browser as a prime
target. Earlier, Netscape boss Jim Barksdale had accused Microsoft
in court of harassing Compaq because it wanted to preload Navigator
on some Presario models in place of Internet Explorer.
</P>
<P>
   But Rose explained that Compaq had removed the desktop icon for
Internet Explorer under an accord with America Online Inc.
stipulating that only AOL's Internet icons would be placed in that
prime showcase. That agreement, Rose said, needed to be revised to
quash Microsoft's objections.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   In the courtroom Tuesday, the government played a videotape in a
bid to show that the curbs Microsoft places on AOL make it
difficult for consumers to download Navigator.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's own video, shown to U.S. District Judge Thomas
Penfield Jackson last week, glossed over the full capture process,
which Microsoft's lawyers said took just 10 minutes, ``to save
time.''
</P>
<P>
   But the government tape showed the procedure could take an hour
or longer, depending on the speed of the Internet link. For his
part, Jackson appeared perplexed, confessing to a ``conceptual
problem'' with the multifold downloading routine.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not nearly as easy as their video portrayed it to be,''
David Boies, the government's lead lawyer, said outside court.
``They clearly were trying to shorten the tape.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
