A7520 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AFFIRMATIVE-ACTION-LE     02-16 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFFIRMATIVE-ACTION-LEE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON, HATCH REKINDLE FIGHT OVER HEAD OF CIVIL RIGHTS DIVISION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton and Sen. Orrin Hatch on Tuesday
rekindled an old battle over the acting head of Justice
Department's civil rights division, Bill Lann Lee, whom Republicans
accuse of favoring racial preferences.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch, R-Utah, chairman of the Senate Judiciary Committee, urged
Clinton not to renominate Lee, whose bid for the post of assistant
attorney general for civil rights has been blocked twice but who
nonetheless has been heading the division since December 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``During Lee's tenure, the Justice Department has advocated the
same policies that initially led to his failure to be confirmed as
assistant attorney general,'' Hatch said in a statement. ``The
Senate has already considered the nomination of Bill Lann Lee for
this position.''
</P>
<P>
   However, White House officials immediately confirmed that the
president will nominate him within a month.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president believes that Mr. Lee has done an excellent
job,'' White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said, adding that Lee's
opponents had a ``demonstrable lack of knowledge of his
background.''
</P>
<P>
   When first nominated in 1997, Lee encountered heavy criticism
from conservatives who charged that he was a zealous promoter of
racial preferences in affirmative action cases.
</P>
<P>
   Following an acrimonious debate, Democrats in the Senate
Judiciary Committee blocked a vote, figuring Lee's bid was destined
to fail. Because Lee was not actually voted down by the committee,
the White House retained the option of installing him as acting
director _ and did so on Dec. 15, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton sent Lee's name to the Senate again in January 1998, but
this time the Republican majority refused to schedule a hearing on
his nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch's announcement came on the heels of the release of a
report by former Attorney General Edwin Meese and two conservative
legal watchdog groups accusing Lee of pursuing racial and ethnic
preferences.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Mr. Lee is doing is a flagrant violation of the
Constitution,'' said Meese, who served in the Ronald Reagan
administration, at a news conference here.
</P>
<P>
   Clint Bolick, litigation director for the Institute for Justice,
a conservative legal advocacy group, said Lee's record at the civil
rights division had confirmed ``all of the worst fears raised by
critics of his nomination.''
</P>
<P>
   In a report assessing Lee's first year, Bolick and Roger Clegg,
general counsel for the Center for Equal Opportunity, an
anti-affirmative-action think tank, asserted that Lee has pushed
race-conscious practices in employment, contracts, voting and
education.
</P>
<P>
   One example cited in the report was Lee's support of a 1995
lawsuit filed by the Justice Department against the city of
Torrance, Calif. In that case, the civil rights division argued
that the city's written tests to evaluate applicants for police and
firefighter positions discriminated against minorities.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the lawsuit was rejected by U.S. District Court Judge
Mariana R. Pfaelzer, who called it ``frivolous, unreasonable and
without foundation'' and awarded the city $1.8 million for
attorneys' fees.
</P>
<P>
   The department filed a similar police and firefighter suit in
1997 against Garland, Texas. That case continues to be fought in a
federal district court.
</P>
<P>
   Clegg said that ``the head of the civil rights division should
not be someone who believes that an American's civil rights depends
on his skin color or where his ancestors came from.''
</P>
<P>
   But Christine DiBartolo, spokeswoman for the division, said Lee
has not pushed ``racial quotas'' and has ``always operated within
the law.''
</P>
<P>
   DiBartolo said only about ``1 or 2 percent'' of the division's
resources are devoted to affirmative action cases and that Lee
should be judged as well on his work in other areas such fighting
housing discrimination and upholding the Americans with
Disabilities Act.
</P>
<P>
   ``Senate Republicans should focus on the whole job, not just
affirmative action,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-99 1833EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990216.0275 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-16 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
