<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-16 18:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7525 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNN-WEBMD-COX     02-16 0820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNN-WEBMD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CNN, WebMD form alliance
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Expect to be hearing a lot more from WebMD, the
Atlanta-based health information portal. Tuesday, the company
announced a wide-ranging strategic alliance with CNN News Groups.
</P>
<P>
   While WebMD has devoted much of its time and resources to
developing an online service for physicians, the CNN alliance is a
strategic step in the attempt to drive traffic to its consumer
service. The company also has deals with the online service,
CompuServe, to provide content primarily to professional users.
</P>
<P>
   The terms of the deal call for CNN and WebMD to exchange online
content. WebMD will receive on-air and online promotion across the
CNN News Group, including all CNN cable and radio networks as well
as CNN Interactive.
</P>
<P>
   WebMD has also committed to a three-year multi-million
advertising deal that will make WebMD one of CNN's largest
advertisers. And CNN will also take what it terms ``a modest equity
stake'' in the growing health care portal for consumers and
physicians. The size of that stake was not revealed.
</P>
<P>
   WebMD filed for an initial public offering Jan. 28. It will have
to refile the IPO with the Securities and Exchange Commission
because of CNN's new equity stake. Neither CNN nor WebMD would
discuss details of the deal, citing SEC quiet period regulations.
</P>
<P>
   WebMD (http://www.webmd.com) offers online health information
free to consumers and for a $29.95 charge to practicing physicians.
The company is a ``vertical portal'' _ online lingo that means it
provides specialized health news and information from a variety of
sources. Founder Jeff Arnold said that before deciding to join
forces with CNN, the company did some research of its own showing
that more than half of all physicians say CNN is their No. 1 source
for news.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold wants to attract more doctors to the WebMD site, but he
says the CNN alliance will raise consumer awareness of the company
and its offerings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a vertical medical portal and early on we decided to
build a focused message to physicians that WebMD is an Internet
site that will help them save time and cut costs within their
practice. We've worked hard in the last several months to get that
message out.''
</P>
<P>
   However, he says the company is working equally hard to raise
awareness of WebMD's consumer offerings _ and that's where CNN
comes in. ``To raise consumer awareness, we needed a broadcast
partner,'' he says. ``We are big believers that there will be
convergence of TV and the Internet, eventually in terms of high
speed access but for now in terms of awareness alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a serious topic and it has to be comprehensive and
extremely trusted. When we looked out to see who we should
approach, it was evident very early on that CNN was the perfect
match. It's one of the world's most trusted brands and we think
news and health are very similar topics. We want to be viewed by
consumers and physicians as a company that takes health information
very seriously. That's very important to us and we are always
looking for partners who can validate that,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   He also says the CNN deal is part of the company's first attempt
to build out its consumer strategy. ``WebMD hopes to bring the
entire health care industry online. We think that you have to
target both doctors and consumers to be successful.'' Arnold says
today's announcement is a strong indication the company is
aggressively targeting the consumer market.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold said the multifaceted relationship with CNN is broader
than similar deals in the past. ``We are telling consumers there's
a place (for health information) they can trust. CNN helps us
validate that claim.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In a world of billions of bytes of information, people need
information they can trust,'' said Tom Johnson, president and chief
executive of CNN News Group. ``In the last 18 years, we have become
one of the most trusted brands in news and WebMD is equally
well-respected and will stand for information that can be trusted,
which is a key factor particularly when you are dealing with health
information.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning April 1, CNN viewers will hear of WebMD on all the CNN
cable channels, while visitors to CNN.com will have access to WebMD
content. ``They'll offer the depth we don't have,'' said Rob
Tillison, CNN senior vice president of business development. ``When
we end (an on-air piece), we'll have a tagline send people to our
Web site in association with WebMD.''
</P>
<P>
   ``CNN in any one day will air 32 health-related stories across
their networks,'' Arnold says. ``CNN provides the breaking news and
WebMD is providing the depth and the personalization tools to help
consumers go deeper.''
</P>
<P>
   Frances Katz writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
