<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-16 18:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7538 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MACWORLD-NY-BOS &LR;      02-16 0637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MACWORLD-NY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MACWORLD DECIDES TO STAY IN NEW YORK CITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Organizers of the MacWorld Expo Tuesday say the fabled
computer show will stay in New York City this summer rather than
return to Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Show sponsor IDG Expo Management of Norwood, Mass. has canceled
its August reservations at Boston's World Trade Center, saying the
facility is too small. The company will instead hold MacWorld at
New York City's Jacob Javits Center for the second year, a decision
that could cost Boston $20 million in convention-related revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Until last year, Boston had hosted the summer MacWorld for
years. The event was one of the city's biggest conventions.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Thomas Menino expressed disappointment at Boston's loss of
the show, citing it as further proof that Boston needs the huge new
convention center set to begin construction next year. ``When we
have our convention center on-line, things like that will not
happen in the future,'' Menino said.
</P>
<P>
   Nicole Derany , show director for IDG Expo Management said the
trade center was simply too small, forcing the company to hold many
MacWorld events at other venues, such as the Hynes Convention
Center. ``The Javits Center is better equipped to host the event
for us,'' said Derany. ``It has more space for us and it's all
under one roof.''
</P>
<P>
   IDG expressed doubts about sticking with Boston several weeks
ago, in the aftermath of its successful MacWorld show in San
Francisco last month. Nearly 70,000 people attended the show, up
from 68,000 the previous year, and there was also an increase in
the number of computer companies exhibiting Apple-related products.
</P>
<P>
   The East Coast edition of MacWorld was held at Javits last
summer, but weak attendance numbers led IDG to announce last year
that the show would return to Boston. But since then, Apple has
enjoyed a dramatic renaissance after years of falling sales and
financial losses. The success of Apple's iMac computer has given
the firm new momentum, and IDG expects continued growth in MacWorld
visitors and exhibitors.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of Boston's convention industry worked on alternative
proposals to satisfy the show's needs, only to fall short. One plan
called for the erection of huge computer-shaped tents in the
parking lot of the World Trade Center, to provide additional space.
But IDG wouldn't bite.
</P>
<P>
   World Trade Center president John Drew said that the decision
was mainly based not on a lack of space in Boston, but by Apple's
desire to hold MacWorld in the nation's chief financial center.
``They simply wanted to be in New York,'' said Drew. ``They wanted
to be closer to Wall Street.''
</P>
<P>
   But IDG's Derany said that her firm, not Apple, operates
MacWorld and was entirely responsible for the decision to return to
New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a huge disappointment and it's a huge loss for the
region's visitor economy,'' said Patrick Moscaritolo, president of
the Greater Boston Convention &AMP; Visitors Bureau. ``On the other
hand it also points out the need for the new convention center
that's being built down there in the seaport district.''
</P>
<P>
   The $700 million convention center won't begin construction
until next year and won't be finished until late 2003. Therefore,
said Moscaritolo, it's unlikely that IDG will bring MacWorld back
to Boston before 2004. Derany said that arrangements for next
year's MacWorld have not been completed, but IDG is in discussions
with the Javits Center to arrange a third New York show.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Menino said that the financial loss to Boston is far
outweighed by other major events coming to the area, including
baseball's All-Star Game and the Ryder Cup golf tournament.
``They're more valuable to us than MacWorld,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
