<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARBOON-PICKWICK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BREWER TO REINTRODUCE PICKWICK ALE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Hoping to recapture some of the explosive growth that
microbreweries enjoyed during the early 1990s, the maker of Harpoon
beer will reintroduce Pickwick Ale Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Pickwick was a beer popular in Eastern Massachusetts for much of
the century.
</P>
<P>
   The brand's re-emergence after a roughly 25-year absence is the
result of a licensing agreement between Mass. Bay Brewing Co. of
Boston, which makes and markets Harpoon along the East Coast, and
the Haffenreffer family, which for many years produced Pickwick at
breweries in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The family sold Pickwick in 1964, and it was later marketed
briefly by two other other companies, said Ted Haffenreffer.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a long absence from the local scene, the brand continues
to be admired, and ``Pickwick paraphernalia'' can still be found in
many area tap rooms, said Mass. Bay chief executive Richard Doyle,
who cofounded Mass. Bay in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Though the beer recipe may be modified a bit, Pickwick has ``a
nostalgia-icon quality to it,'' Doyle said.
</P>
<P>
   Most craft-brewers, including Harpoon, could use a boost.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, sales for such brands as Samuel Adams,
Pete's Wicked Ale, and Harpoon surged wildly.
</P>
<P>
   Though tiny, these brands took enough business away from brewing
giants to keep the big companies' beer sales flat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since the early 1980s, beer consumption has been growing at
only about a half a percentage point a year,'' said Benj Steinman,
editor of Beer Marketer's Insights. The $70 billion US beer
business has been ``pretty much a market share game,'' with brewers
trying to take customers away from one another.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for microbrewers, the momentum of the early 1990s
has ``stalled out'' as consumers have lately turned to such
imported beers as Corona and Heineken, Steinman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People want to drink something that's familiar,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Pickwick is certainly somewhat familiar, and it offers another
advantage: In terms of store prices, it could find a niche between
upscale microbrews and mid-priced Budweiser.
</P>
<P>
   With a suggested retail-price range of $4.99 to $5.49, a
six-pack of Pickwick bottles should cost 50 cents less than a
six-pack of Harpoon and 50 cents more than Budweiser, Doyle said.
</P>
<P>
   Privately owned Mass. Bay does not disclose earnings; it
declined to elaborate on details of its Pickwick licensing
agreement. Last year, it produced 55,000 barrels of beer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
