A7543 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WASTE-TRUCKS17-COX     02-16 0463
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WASTE-TRUCKS17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ARMY TRUCKS LATE, OVER BUDGET AND RUSTY
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The U.S. Army purchased thousands of trucks that
were delivered years behind schedule and $100 million over budget,
and whose cabs began rusting even before the vehicles left the
plant, a government report said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The revelations are the latest for one of the biggest and
least-noticed military acquisition programs, the Army's effort to
replace its entire aging fleet of medium-sized trucks at a total
cost of $15.7 billion over 32 years.
</P>
<P>
   The General Accounting Office (GAO), the investigating arm of
Congress, criticized the Defense Department for selecting Stewart &AMP;
Stevenson Services Inc., a Houston-based company, for the work in
1991. The report said the company had little or no experience in
building trucks or combat vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart &AMP; Stevenson's speciality had been gas turbine generators
and aircraft ground support equipment, the report said. The company
enlisted the aid of an Austrian truck maker for the prototype, and
then set up a manufacturing plant in an old oil-drilling equipment
factory.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, production has fallen far behind schedule. The first
Army unit received its new trucks in January 1996, two years later
than planned. Congress and the Defense Department then decided to
extend the $1.2 billion contract with the Houston company by three
years. The GAO said the extension would add $85 million to the
contract and cost the Army $22 million in repairs on old trucks
that had been slated for replacement.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, despite a requirement that the new trucks be designed
to prevent corrosion for at least the first 10 years of service,
the first 4,955 trucks were so rust-prone that many had holes in
the cabs in less than three years. Rather than require the
manufacturer to replace all the cabs at a cost of $31 million, the
Army let it make repairs and offer a warranty worth no more than
$10 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not sure who should get most of the blame, the
contractor, the Pentagon or even Congress,'' said Sen. Tom Harkin,
D-Iowa, who requested the study. ``One thing, however, is for sure
_ the American taxpayers are paying more than they should for this
military truck program.''
</P>
<P>
   Messages left with the Houston headquarters and Washington
office of Stewart &AMP; Stevenson were not returned.
</P>
<P>
   The Defense Department conceded that it had identified ``lessons
learned.'' In its written response to the GAO, the Pentagon said
improvements had been made, and added, ``we are confident that the
fielded vehicles will economically provide the required service
life.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
