<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990216.0289 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-16 18:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7549 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OUTCASTS-960(2Takes)-     02-16 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTCASTS-960(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEPROSY CENTER ABOUT TO BE CLOSED, BUT PATIENTS DON'T WANT TO
LEAVE
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanied by OUTCASTS-HANSENS) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BARRY SHLACHTER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARVILLE, La. _ The gate is open now. Residents come and go as
they please. But there was a time when snatches of freedom _ to
catch a ballgame or make a phone call _ meant slipping through a
hole in the fence and risking 30 days in a lockup. Sixty days for
the second offense.
</P>
<P>
   Within the 330 acres bounded by barbed wire, generations of
residents printed a magazine, earned Boy Scout merit badges,
produced plays, held their own Mardi Gras, authored books, fell in
love and conceived children they were forbidden to raise.
</P>
<P>
   Most are elderly now, the last 73 patients of the only long-term
care center in the continental United States for Hansen's disease,
traditionally known as leprosy. In 1951, its peak year, the
Carville complex housed 480.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government intends to close the Gillis W. Long
Hansen's Disease Center in three years, turning out those who
remain. Last year, 45 residents accepted $33,000 annual
``stipends'' _ double for married couples _ and moved away. The
site will be handed back to Louisiana, whose National Guard will
run a job-training boot camp for at-risk youths.
</P>
<P>
   At Carville, all are cured but many continue to suffer from the
physical damage _ facial deformities, clawed hands and circulation
problems _ incurred before effective treatment was discovered. Then
there are old-age infirmities and a psychological dependency
nurtured by decades of institutionalization.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a world of its own,'' said Texas-born Johnny Harmon,
87, who came to Carville as a young man for two lengthy stays and
finally returned in 1992 with his wife, Anne, whom he had met and
married when both were patients. She arrived at age 10 after
neighbors burned her family's home, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't have come voluntarily, but I lived a fuller life
than if I hadn't,'' said Harmon. Easily Carville's least shy
resident, he tools around in a motorized wheelchair with a large,
hand-lettered sign affixed to the back, advertising his 184-page,
self-published memoir, now in its fourth printing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of lonesome around here now,'' Harmon said of the
departure of more than a third of the residents between August and
late October.
</P>
<P>
   Like others who stayed, he adamantly opposes leaving _ even with
a generous and tax-free living allowance of $33,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like it,'' snapped Harmon, once a draftsman with the
Texas highway department who became a professional photographer at
Carville. ``It's really depressing. They'll have to take me out in
a box.''
</P>
<P>
   For those who don't take the offer, assisted-living quarters are
expected to be found in Baton Rouge, 26 miles to the north, where
the Carville complex will eventually relocate as a scaled-back
clinic, said Julia Elwood, its spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Elwood arrived as a frightened 16-year-old patient from the
small South Texas town of Elsa. After being cured through a series
of sulfone drug injections, graduating college and teaching school,
she returned as a staff member, the first to do so.
</P>
<P>
   None of the residents now carries the leprosy bacteria, whose
mode of transmission still perplexes researchers. It is not a
venereal disease, but specialists believe _ but cannot prove _ it
spreads through skin-to-skin contact, inhalation of
bacteria-containing droplets and, in some Southern states, handling
armadillos.
</P>
<P>
   However transmitted, it's done so with difficulty. Ninety to 95
percent of people are naturally immune. (Only one Carville employee
ever contracted the disease, a power-house worker who did not come
in contact with patients.) The international medical community
recognized in 1956 that there no longer was any need to quarantine
patients.
</P>
<P>
   Today, less than two weeks' outpatient treatment with a cocktail
of antibiotics removes the threat of contagion.
</P>
<P>
   Although leprosy sounds like something out of antiquity _ or a
``Ben Hur'' rerun _ there are 690,000 new cases a year around the
world. It is now called Hansen's disease _ after the Norwegian
scientist who discovered the rod-shaped bacteria _ to differentiate
it from the vague but damning biblical references to leprosy as a
divine curse on the sinful and unclean.
</P>
<P>
   Even after a cure was discovered in the mid-1940s by Carville
researchers, the social stigma endured.
</P>
<P>
   For years, patients were encouraged to take assumed names to
spare their families embarrassment and ostracism back home.
</P>
<P>
   Even after forcible detention ended in 1957, they built their
own society and, at times, an aggressive cohesiveness. They
successfully campaigned to oust one unpopular director and tried to
push out another.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   Today, the Patients Federation opposes stipend-takers returning
to use Carville's subsidized facilities, which include a hair salon
and a canteen that sells tax-free cigarettes, discount beer and
such exotic fare as pickled pig lips. The Federation's leader, a
Colombian-born nun, declined to be interviewed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Residents didn't want those who left to come back and harvest
the pecans,'' said Dr. Bruce Clements, 70, the center's clinical
director. ``I don't think it's very Christian of them. They don't
want them in the cafeteria anymore. I guess it's jealousy.''
</P>
<P>
   Residents fondly recall the U.S. Public Health Service
administrators who lifted penallike restrictions that persisted
years after sulfone drugs proved effective. They closed the jail,
eased the issuance of passes, lifted a ban on social contacts
between patients and staff, and permitted weddings on the grounds.
</P>
<P>
   Today, as far as Washington is concerned, Carville has outlived
its usefulness. There is now no medical need to keep treated
patients apart from society. And the $15.6 million annual budget
has made it a costly white elephant to some.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're victims of our own success,'' said Bunny Harriman, a
Corsicana, Texas, native who is chief social worker at Carville.
``But it's still painful for the very old, staid and entrenched
people. This place is their home, and to have their home threatened
is a sad thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Primarily, relatively younger patients took the stipend offer
last year, Harriman said. ``Now the average age is 70.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   The state of Louisiana purchased the antebellum Indian Camp
Plantation in 1894 after a newspaper series exposed deplorable
conditions endured by leprosy victims in New Orleans. The new
site's conditions were little better until a Catholic order, the
Sisters of Charity, arrived to bolster the sole doctor. Its
smiling, energetic nuns in simple blue habits are still here today
but don't know where they'll go when the center closes.
</P>
<P>
   A one-room museum on the grounds shows how the complex evolved
from one main house and a few huts to more than 100 buildings and a
golf course. On display are crude iron shackles that incoming
patients once were forced to wear and a wicker basket in which
newborn children were carried out, some to an adoption center in
New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   In 1921, the U.S. Public Health Service took over and began
accepting patients from all over the nation and many foreign
countries.
</P>
<P>
   Patients included naval officers, debutantes, homemakers,
cowboys, laborers, musicians, pharmacists, watchmakers, tailors,
lawyers, Protestant ministers, Catholic priests, a rabbi and a
former prizefighter.
</P>
<P>
   Before the mid-1940s, their freedom of movement beyond the fence
was tightly controlled. One man was jailed for sneaking out to
vote, Harmon recalled.
</P>
<P>
   There were suicides and, Harmon said, at least one murder.
</P>
<P>
   A love triangle led to deadly gunplay, he said. ``But after the
trial, the guilty man was sent back to Carville,'' Harmon said.
``They didn't want him in prison.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   At meal time, residents head toward the cafeteria in a fleet of
bicycles, tricycles and powered wheelchairs. An elderly couple,
both blind, led each other on foot, sharing a single cane.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Ruth Lozano Daigle, 81, uses a wheelchair to travel between
buildings but appears far less debilitated than others.
</P>
<P>
   She arrived in 1939 at the age of 22 from San Antonio to
discover that her sister, whom she had been told was attending
college in New Orleans, had preceded her with the same disease.
Sixty years later, she has outlived her sister and the man she met
and married here. Because the diagnosis of her disease came early,
she suffered none of the facial disfigurement or marked
enfeeblement that afflict many here.
</P>
<P>
   Though physically restricting, Carville has provided a full
life, she said. She worked in the infirmary, wrote letters for
patients who could not hold a pencil, and later became editor of
the center's magazine, ``The Star,'' which has fought prejudice
against those who contract the disease.
</P>
<P>
   Explaining why she refuses to leave now, the tiny woman with the
honeysuckle voice turned deadly serious.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government brought me here,'' Daigle said. ``If I didn't
go, they would have put yellow quarantine flags around my family's
house. I became a ward of the government, and I think they should
take care of me till I die. I guess that sounds selfish, but that's
the way I look at it.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
