<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-16 18:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7555 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OUTCASTS-DISEASE-TEX     02-16 0336
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTCASTS-DISEASE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HANSEN'S DISEASE TODAY
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanies OUTCASTS) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today, Hansen's disease is mostly a problem in the Third World,
with India, Indonesia and Myanmar, formerly Burma, accounting for
70 percent of the 1.8 million active cases.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the United States is not free of Hansen's. There are an
estimated 6,500 U.S. cases, 380 of them in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Those are the known ones. There may be more.
</P>
<P>
   Because of unfamiliarity with the disease, ``some people are
misdiagnosed for five or 10 years,'' said Nancy Bernstein, a
Dallas-based public health nurse who supervises care for Hansen's
patients in North Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Early diagnosis and treatment almost always prevent deformities,
Bernstein said. But the afflicted, experiencing numbness in the
feet or hands or finding lesions, spots or nodules, can go from
doctor to doctor being told they might have ringworm or psoriasis,
Bernstein said.
</P>
<P>
   The rarity of the disease also has fostered popular
misconceptions, like the myth that fingers and toes drop off.
</P>
<P>
   Left untreated, Hansen's can cause ``bone absorption,'' which
makes fingers recede into the hand. The bacteria can destroy
cartilage, which leads to a disfigured or flattened nose. Because
of a loss of sensitivity _ the person may feel no pain _ fingers
can be accidentally cut or burnt off.
</P>
<P>
   Funding for research has dried up in recent years, driving
numerous scientists out of the field, even though work on leprosy
could be applicable to tuberculosis and other diseases, said James
L. Krahenbuhl, who supervises leprosy studies at Louisiana State
University in Baton Rouge, where the Gillis W. Long Hansen's
Disease Center in Carville's research branch is now located.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may be dismantling the very research and control measures
needed to truly control Hansen's disease around the globe,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
