<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-16 19:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7559 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-LATAM-0217-CO     02-16 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-LATAM-0217-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON SEEKING $1 BILLION IN EMERGENCY AID FOR CENTRAL AMERICA
 &HT;    EDs: Optional add begins at 450 words.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton asked Congress Tuesday for nearly
$1 billion in emergency recovery aid and debt relief for Central
American countries ravaged last fall by hurricane Mitch.
</P>
<P>
   The largest part of the package -- a requested $613 million for
reconstruction -- would be used to help rebuild homes, farms, roads
and other facilities destroyed by flooding that killed 9,000 people
and left 3 million more homeless in what the administration calls
the worst natural disaster in the history of the Western
Hemisphere.
</P>
<P>
   ''Though the rains have stopped, the hard work of rebuilding and
recovery has just begun,'' said Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright, who, along with First lady Hillary Rodham Clinton and
others, announced the aid request at a White House ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton and the first lady plan to travel next month,
leaving March 8, to Nicaragua, Honduras, El Salvador and Guatemala,
countries hard-hit by Hurricane Mitch.
</P>
<P>
   The storm swept through the region on Oct. 28, ripping across
Honduras with winds up to 120 miles per hour and dumping 25 inches
of rain on the country, causing floods that have set back a
generation's worth of development in thousands of communities
across the region.
</P>
<P>
   ``At just the moment in time when all of these countries were
poised for the future, this devastating natural disaster has seemed
to come out of nowhere and set them back with respect to pursuing
their dreams and their hopes,'' the first lady said. ''We want to
be friends and partners in rebuilding those dreams and hopes.''
</P>
<P>
   The $613 million in reconstruction aid Clinton has requested
would be earmarked for Honduras, Nicaragua, El Salvador and
Guatemala. Some $50 million of that money would also go to Haiti
and the Dominican Republic, which suffered damage from Hurricane
George last fall. Another $10 million of it would go to Colombia,
which was hit with a devastating earthquake earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the reconstruction aid request, Clinton is asking
Congress for:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  $158 million to reimburse the Defense Department and the U.S.
Agency for International Development for emergency assistance it
has already provided due to Hurricane Mitch.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  $80 million to reimburse the U.S. Immigration and
Naturalization Service for the costs of deferring deportations to
hard-hit Central American countries.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  $64 million to help deal with soil erosion, denuding of
woodlands and other environmental ills that contributed to the
flood-related damage.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  $41 million to help ease the burden of foreign debt owed by
Nicaragua and Honduras. Because of the way debt is managed, the
actual relief provided to those countries would be more than double
the amount the program would cost U.S. taxpayers. Nicaragua owes
foreign countries some $6 billion. Honduras owes $3.7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. assistance is part of a broader package of global aid
expected to reach some $4 billion. Aid officials from the United
States, Europe, Japan and other donor countries are scheduled to
meet in Sweden in late May to confer on a long-term recovery plan
for the region.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration is hopeful that Congress will approve
its emergency aid request before that, so the money may be used to
provide urgently needed assistance.
</P>
<P>
   ''We hope Congress will act expeditiously, by the end of
March,'' said Josh Gotbaum, executive associate director of the
White House Office of Management and Budget.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is bipartisan support for action, substantial action,''
Gotbaum told reporters. ''But one should not prejudge the
prerogatives of the Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the aid is being sought under an emergency supplemental
request, it is not subject to budget rules that would require the
White House to demonstrate how to pay for the requests -- through
tax hikes or cuts in other types of spending -- as is required for
normal budget items.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the emergency aid, Clinton plans to ask Congress
soon to enhance the trade terms granted to Caribbean nations under
the Reagan-era Caribbean Basin Initiative, or CBI.
</P>
<P>
   ''CBI is a critical tool for the rebuilding of Central
America,'' said Albright.
</P>
<P>
   Caribbean countries received certain preferential trade
privileges under the terms of the CBI. Those countries have
complained, however, that Mexico got an even better deal under the
provisions of the five-year-old North American Free Trade
Agreement, or NAFTA. The Caribbean countries have been seeking new
terms that would put them on parity with Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials declined to specify on Tuesday whether
Clinton's proposal for enhanced CBI benefits would amount to NAFTA
parity.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
