   TOP
</P>
<P>
   Lead story:
</P>
<P>
   KURD-PROTESTS (Rome) _ Enraged by the capture of the foremost
Kurdish rebel leader, protesters storm diplomatic posts throughout
Europe, taking hostages and setting fires _ and in some cities,
even setting themselves on fire. With what seemed like
extraordinary coordination, Kurds in Paris, Moscow, London,
Frankfurt, Milan, Bern and more than a dozen other cities protest
the arrest of Abdullah Ocalan, leader of the Kurdistan Workers
Party. By Alessandra Stanley. (We plan to move the story by 8 p.m.
ET in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   Story runs with 3-column photo.
</P>
<P>
   With map, sidebars inside.
</P>
<P>
   Off-lead story:
</P>
<P>
   GERMAN-SLAVE-PAY (Berlin) _ Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder
announces the creation of a fund, projected to amount to $1.7
billion, financed by 12 German companies, to compensate victims of
the Nazis and end what he calls ``the campaign being led against
German industry and our country.'' The announcement is clearly
aimed at stopping a wave of lawsuits in U.S. courts against German
companies that used slave labor and forced labor during World War
II. But Schroeder's choice of words appears unlikely to calm the
waters. By Roger Cohen. (The story has moved in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   FOLD
</P>
<P>
   EXCLUSIVE-AGENCY-CORRUPTION (Washington) _ A report to Congress
is disclosing corruption in a federal agency and exploring the
causes and possible remedies. By Neil A. Lewis. (Eds: Story is
competitive. The name of the agency and other details will not be
available until the story moves. We plan to move the story at 9:30
ET in the ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   NY-MRSCLINTON (New York) _ With New York Democrats in an uproar
over the potential Senate candidacy of Hillary Rodham Clinton, the
first lady's friends and advisers are warning her that a race could
be brutal, and that the easy victory predicted by state party
leaders is not at all guaranteed. By Elisabeth Bumiller. (Scheduled
to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BOTTOM
</P>
<P>
   GLOBAL-ECON-III (Undated) _ Part three of the series on the
worldwide economic meltdown: From Asia to Russia to Brazil, markets
intertwined in sometimes dangerous ways. By Nicholas D. Kristoff
and Sheryl WuDunn. (Scheduled to move by 7:30 p.m. ET in ``i'' news
file.)
</P>
<P>
   With photos and graphics; 7,000 words.
</P>
<P>
   TX-DRAGGING-DEATH (Jasper, Texas) _ John William King, his arms
festooned with racist tattoos, had dreamed of forming his own local
chapter of a white supremacist group but felt he needed some
dramatic event to catapult him into the limelight and attract
members. That, prosecutors said for the first time, is their theory
of why King and two other young white men chained a 49-year-old
black man to the back of their pickup truck last June and dragged
him 3 miles down a country road until his flayed and battered body
fell apart. The case against King, 24, the first of the three
suspects to come to trial in the hideous death of James Byrd Jr.,
opens before a locally drawn jury of six men and five women _ all
white but for one black man. By Rick Lyman. (Scheduled to move by
8:30 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE STORIES PROMOTED ON PAGE 1:
</P>
<P>
   IRISH-CATHOLIC-RIGHTS (Belfast, Northern Ireland) _ The Northern
Ireland Assembly approves sweeping changes in the political
structure of this predominantly Protestant British province. The
changes are intended to give the Roman Catholic minority more power
and to end sectarian violence, which has killed more than 3,200
people in the last 30 years. By James F. Clarity. (The story has
moved in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   GORE-POLITICS (Washington) _ Vice President Al Gore has emerged
from the impeachment ordeal in a more commanding position to
capture the Democratic nomination than he would have if the world
had never heard of Monica Lewinsky. Most significantly, Dick
Gephardt has decided not to take on Gore. And among Republicans
there is such a feeling of inevitability to the vice president's
quest to succeed Clinton that former Vice President Dan Quayle, in
announcing his exploratory committee last week, proclaimed: ``I
will win the nomination. And I will beat Al Gore.'' By Richard L.
Berke. (Scheduled to move by 8 p.m. ET in ``w'' news file.) With
photos. 1,600 words.
</P>
<P>
   AIRFARE-DISCOUNTS (Undated) _ With international business travel
weakening because of the economic slowdown overseas and with more
flights scheduled across the North Atlantic, several major airlines
have aggressively cut their fares to Europe, exceeding in many
cases their previous winter sales. By Edwin McDowell. (Scheduled to
move by 9 p.m. ET in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
