A7609 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VENTURE-COX     02-16 0628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENTURE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta, N.C. lure venture capital
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Metro Atlanta and North Carolina's Research Triangle
Park bolstered their reputations as Southern hotbeds for venture
capital by churning out record numbers of deals last year.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta market ranked first in the region with investors
pouring $282.8 million into 77 deals in 1998, according to figures
released Tuesday by accounting firm PricewaterhouseCoopers. The
Research Triangle Park raked in 59 deals worth $247.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Metro Atlanta and the Research Triangle Park _ economic
powerhouses located 400 miles apart on the booming I-40/I-85
corridor _ have emerged as regional models for attracting venture
capital firms.
</P>
<P>
   Venture capitalists typically invest in start-up or fledgling
technology companies that find it difficult to arrange traditional
financing, such as bank loans.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, a growing number of technology success stories
_ such as Atlanta's MindSpring Enterprises, an Internet access
provider _ have fueled interest among entrepreneurs who want to
start companies and venture capitalists who want to invest in them.
</P>
<P>
   ``A little ecosystem is happening here, with more deals and more
companies,'' said J. Michael Cummins, chief executive of the
Georgia Center for Advanced Telecommunications Technology in
Atlanta. ``We are seeing an attitude change.''
</P>
<P>
   To the detriment of technology start-ups across the South,
deep-pocketed investors traditionally have favored putting money
into real estate, textiles, soft drinks ``and other things you can
touch, feel and understand,'' Cummins said.
</P>
<P>
   But the latest figures from PricewaterhouseCoopers' fourth
annual survey show technology investments are rising fast,
particularly in North Carolina and Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Florida reeled in $301.4 million in 49 deals last year, ranking
it first among Southern states, PricewaterhouseCoopers said. But
those deals were spread across Florida, unlike the bunching of
deals in metro Atlanta and the Research Triangle Park.
</P>
<P>
   In the region, North Carolina ranked second, with $300.4 million
in 73 deals. Georgia finished third in investments, with 83 deals
valued at $298.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   In a humbling comparison for the South's venture capital
leaders, California's Silicon Valley hauled in $4.6 billion in 787
deals last year. Nationwide, venture capitalists invested $14.3
billion in 2,856 deals.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in metro Atlanta and the Research Triangle Park, a
6,900-acre technology park between Raleigh, Durham and Chapel Hill,
predicted venture capitalists will invest even greater sums in
coming years as the flurry of activity builds upon itself.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's far-reaching microchip initiative, the Yamacraw
Mission, is seeking $2.5 million from the state Legislature in
technology seed funds in the fiscal year starting July 1, Cummins
said. Private investors would be required to put up $3 for every $1
in state funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Atlanta is starting to bear the fruit of a lot of years of
hard work,'' said Maureen Morrison, a PricewaterhouseCoopers
partner in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, the Research Triangle Park is attracting venture
capitalists from outside the region. A major Atlanta-based firm,
Noro-Moseley Partners, has invested $8 million in four Research
Triangle deals since September 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are starting to get over the hump as far as outside money
is concerned,'' said David Blivin, managing director for
Durham-based Southeast Interactive Technology Funds, the Research
Triangle's largest venture capital firm.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Burritt writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
