<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-16 19:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7615 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WEIGHT-WATCHERS-ART-2     02-16 1066
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEIGHT-WATCHERS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIKE A RESURGENT WAISTLINE, WEIGHT WATCHERS IS BACK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., N.Y., Great Britain)  (Eds: See also WEIGHT-COMPETE) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was lunchtime, but the 30 or so women and one man
crowded into a Manhattan meeting room weren't eating anything.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the focus was on how much weight each had lost, using
the newest Weight Watchers program, which assigns points to foods
based on their fat, fiber and calorie content. In the true spirit
of a support group, they burst into applause when Yvonne, a tall
brunette in a business suit, declared that she had shed 21 pounds,
her goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Weight Watchers gives me a sense of control over my
food and my weight,'' she said before adding: ``Ore-Ida has these
French fries that are 35 for three points. You don't have to
deprive yourselves, guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Yvonne, who would not give her last name, said later that she
was unaware that Ore-Ida and Weight Watchers International were
owned by the same concern: H.J. Heinz Co.
</P>
<P>
   Food and diet have been an odd couple at Heinz for 21 years, and
many analysts, seeing a certain dissonance between the businesses,
have long expected the company to sell Weight Watchers.
</P>
<P>
   But across the country and parts of Europe, Weight Watchers'
offices like the one in Manhattan are drawing a surge of new
customers at a time when Heinz's larger businesses like ketchup are
just treading water. A dud just two years ago, Weight Watchers,
while still a small part of the Pittsburgh-based company, is now
the fastest-growing division in Heinz's empire of Star-Kist canned
tuna, Smart Ones and Budget Gourmet frozen dinners, Nine Lives pet
food, baby food, pickles and ketchup.
</P>
<P>
   The revival of Weight Watchers has come amid a general upturn in
the industry as people flee diet drugs. A simplified nutritional
program and new marketing has also bolstered the chain, creating a
peculiar quandary for Heinz's relatively new chief executive,
William Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first took over this position two years ago, Bill
Johnson said to me, `Kent, we're concerned, and your challenge is
to prove to Pittsburgh that this business is alive and well,'''
said Kent Kreh, the chief executive of Weight Watchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have delivered beyond Pittsburgh's expectations,'' Kreh
said.
</P>
<P>
   The question now is whether Heinz may take advantage of Weight
Watchers' success and sell the chain. Some analysts speculate that
it is time to sell.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to do it at the top of the cycle, instead of at the
bad part of the cycle,'' said John McMillin, a food industry
analyst with Prudential Securities, who noted that a sale would add
needed cash to Heinz's balance sheet. Heinz does not break out
profits for Weight Watchers, but McMillin estimates yearly
worldwide revenue at $500 million for its classroom business and
another $500 million in packaged foods.
</P>
<P>
   Other analysts say Heinz, which has been cutting back and
reorganizing some of its food businesses, may keep Weight Watchers
after all.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Johnson is expected to discuss Weight Watchers as
well as additional cost-cutting and reorganization at a meeting
with Wall Street analysts in Naples, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Heinz have risen sharply in the last week, in apparent
anticipation that further measures will be announced Wednesday,
analysts said. Since reaching a 52-week low of $50.875 on Feb. 8,
the stock has risen more than 9 percent. Still, the stock is down
nearly 10 percent from its 52-week high of $61.75 on Nov. 17.
</P>
<P>
   In a written response to a request for comment on Weight
Watchers' future, Johnson said, ``We are now in the process of
finalizing that review and can't comment further.''
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, Weight Watchers was in deep decline. Attendance,
measured by individual visits, had fallen from a high of 32 million
in 1990 to just 18 million in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   When Heinz's longtime chief executive, Anthony O'Reilly, stepped
down in 1997, speculation grew that Weight Watchers would soon be
sold off. The acquisition had been seen as a personal project of
O'Reilly, who is remembered for taking a pen from his pocket to
structure the terms of the deal with one of the diet center's
co-founders. And late last year, the manufacturing of Weight
Watchers frozen foods was combined with Ore-Ida, leaving the
classroom activities separate from the food business.
</P>
<P>
   But like a waistline that stubbornly reinflates, Weight Watchers
has come back. Enrollment has climbed steadily, and is expected to
hit 30 million by the time Heinz's fiscal year ends in April, Kreh
said. January, February and March are peak enrollment months, he
said, because that is when people resolve to do something about
their eating habits.
</P>
<P>
   Revamping Weight Watchers began by shifting slightly the
philosophy behind its program. While a balanced diet is encouraged,
people are told they can eat whatever they want, as long as their
daily point totals fall within the recommended range for their
height and weight. Someone who weighs between 150 and 174 pounds
could consume between 20 and 27 points, according to the program.
</P>
<P>
   The new points program, 1-2-3 Success, replaced a more
complicated nutritional analysis. The program was introduced in the
United States about 16 months ago after similar success in Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Group leaders also stopped selling the Weight Watchers frozen
foods during the group meetings, though they do beat the drum
constantly on the need to stay enrolled for as long as a year. At
the meetings, customers are weighed and note their weight on file
cards. During the discussions, they exchange information on food
and exercise, and occasionally work on thornier issues, like
whether they have been overeating to compensate for loneliness.
</P>
<P>
   What seems to appeal to people is the program's recent emphasis
on freedom of choice, which permits all kinds of foods but tries to
push people toward healthy eating habits. Vegetables can be
consumed in unlimited quantities. (Ketchup, meanwhile, is worth one
point a quarter-cup.) Words like ``diet'' are discouraged, and
exercise is applauded.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The new program has received a boost from an advertising
campaign that features Sarah Ferguson, the duchess of York, whose
weight had been the subject of much mockery in the British news
media. After losing 11 pounds from her peak of 210 pounds while
attending the British version of the Weight Watchers program, she
signed on as a spokeswoman in early 1997 for a fee estimated to be
between $1 million and $2 million. (A personal trainer and other
methods have helped her lose more weight.) In addition to
television ads, the duchess has lent her name to a Weight Watchers
cookbook and other products.
</P>
<P>
   Weight Watchers, and diet centers like Jenny Craig Inc., have
also benefited as people flee diet drugs, frightened by reports
about two diet pills that were pulled from the market because of
links to heart valve damage. The commercial weight-loss business is
both large and competitive, with Weight Watchers and Jenny Craig,
the two biggest classroom-based methods, up against diets that
offer meal substitutes like milkshakes.
</P>
<P>
   But disillusionment over dieting can also damage diet centers
like Weight Watchers. Complaints that the diet industry was
promising excessive weight loss with little effort or expense led
to an agreement last Wednesday by the Federal Trade Commission and
companies including Weight Watchers. The companies agreed to
publish standard disclosures on the details of their programs, what
consumers can expect, their staff credentials and the cost.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Weight Watchers has a relatively positive image among
nutrition experts. ``Its educational approach is very sound,'' said
Morgan Downey, executive director of the American Obesity
Association, a Washington nonprofit advocacy group. ``It's not
overhyped.''
</P>
<P>
   And the program is clearly very profitable. ``This is a business
that has an incredible operating leverage,'' said Erika Gritman
Long, an analyst with J.P. Morgan. ``If you have 10 people in the
class, and you add two more people, that increment goes straight to
the bottom line.''
</P>
<P>
   Kreh said the break-even point was more like 25 people in a
class.
</P>
<P>
   Each person pays about $30 to enroll, and another fee, which
ranges from $10 to $14, gets tacked on every week for the meetings.
</P>
<P>
   The company has been able to shave costs by not hawking frozen
foods to its classes anymore; many meetings have been moved out of
their old spaces, which were taken up by giant freezers, and into
tinier and cheaper real estate. And along with the rising
enrollment has come another trend: People seem to be staying in the
program longer, eight weeks vs. six or seven in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Weight Watchers has made itself mobile, with At Work programs
set up at offices. And it has tried to be accessible to other
customers, like new mothers, with a Mommy and Me program that has
existed for several years and allows participants to bring small
children to class.
</P>
<P>
   Products for sale in the classrooms include $20 calculators for
adding up food points and copies of ``Dieting with the Duchess,'' a
lifestyle and recipe book published by Simon &AMP; Schuster (listed at
$25) last month, a year after ``Dining with the Duchess.''
</P>
<P>
   Members can also part with $6 apiece for books that list various
foods and their point allocations; the books at least seem
cosmopolitan, demystifying the impact of foods like the Japanese
shabu shabu (8 points), a Starbucks latte (2 points) and, perhaps
in honor of the duchess, Yorkshire pudding (6 points for a
four-inch square).
</P>
<P>
   Kreh says he has his eye on more ways to raise the Weight
Watchers profile and keep the cash rolling in. Last month, the
company signed a licensing agreement with Warnaco for a line of
what Kreh called ``shape wear and active wear,'' mostly women's
undergarments.
</P>
<P>
   The line will be called Weight Watchers In Control, which
perhaps is what is going on at Heinz as well.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
