<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-16 19:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7621 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DELTA-ASA-COX     02-16 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELTA-ASA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Delta announces buyout offer of Atlantic Southeast Airlines
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Delta Air Lines made a $700 million offer Tuesday to
buy commuter affiliate Atlantic Southeast Airlines, saying it plans
to run the smaller carrier as a subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   Delta and ASA, both based in Atlanta, would maintain separate
names, workforces and pay scales.
</P>
<P>
   But Delta, which already owns 28 percent of ASA, would gain
total control of its operations, management and airport facilities,
as well as the deployment of ASA's new regional jets.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say that would enable Delta to use the jets to its best
advantage and fortify its position in the Southeast. Ownership also
protects Delta from losing a key partner to another acquirer.
</P>
<P>
   ASA provides connecting flights at Delta's hubs in Atlanta and
Dallas-Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Delta Chief Operating Officer Maurice Worth said the buyout
poses no labor obstacles _ such as the pilot strife that hobbled
American Airlines _ because workers wouldn't be integrated and
Delta's pilot contract allows such an acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   He also said Delta expects no regulatory opposition, since the
two carriers already are close allies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not competing airlines now, so there's no dimunition of
competition,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Delta is offering $34 a share for stock in ASA Holdings Inc., a
slight premium over Tuesday's opening price of $31.93 3/4. The
price jumped $1.93 3/4, to $33.75, on news of the proposed buyout.
Delta shares slid 6 1/4 cents to $52.50.
</P>
<P>
   The tender offer commences Monday, and Delta said it hopes to
gain the necessary 51 percent shareholder approval and close the
deal by spring.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst James D. Parker of Robinson Humphrey said the price
appears low. He said he was puzzled why ASA, which has long enjoyed
stout revenue and earnings growth, didn't drive a harder bargain.
</P>
<P>
   ASA Chairman George F. Pickett Jr., 57, shed little light on the
reasons for the sale, which he said was approved unanimously by the
board of directors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't a personal decision,'' Pickett said. ``It was an
opportunity that arose, and we accepted it.''
</P>
<P>
   According to a Securities and Exchange Commission filing,
Pickett and his wife, Elizabeth, control 499,937 ASA Holdings
shares worth nearly $17 million under Delta's offer. ASA Holdings
President John Beiser and his wife, Maureen, control 292,147
shares, worth $9.9 million. Other officers and directors hold
smaller amounts
</P>
<P>
   Pickett and Beiser founded ASA in 1979, shortly after airline
deregulation, with a single Twin Otter aircraft flying between
Atlanta and Columbus.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, Delta chose ASA as its commuter partner, and the duo
built ASA into one of the most consistently profitable airlines
anywhere. It now has 88 planes, including 19 jets, and 2,700
workers.
</P>
<P>
   Delta Chief Financial Officer Warren Jenson said ASA posts
higher profit margins that Delta, adding ``we would expect this
deal to be additive to our margins'' in the first year.
</P>
<P>
   Other major airlines, including American, Northwest, Continental
and US Airways, already own commuter subsidiaries.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation about such a move by Delta has arisen periodically,
but the idea moved to the front burner under the management team of
new CEO Leo Mullin, who recently approached Pickett.
</P>
<P>
   If the deal is approved, Delta will install John Selvaggio to
oversee the ASA subsdiary. He was recently hired from US Airways,
where he headed the commuter division. Pickett and Beiser would
give up their titles and become advisors.
</P>
<P>
   Delta said it expects to improve ``fundamental customer service
activities'' at ASA, which has been plagued by spates of canceled
flights, lost bags and staffing shortages while trying to keep up
with the growth of Delta's Atlanta hub.
</P>
<P>
   Worth denied those problems prodded the buyout offer but added,
``It should be a much smoother operation in Atlanta.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, analyst Parker said the deal could tighten
Delta's grip on Hartsfield International Airport, where the carrier
and ASA control 81 percent of the traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Parker noted ASA has 18 gates that Delta could borrow for its
own flights as needed. In such a scenario, ASA might use a remote
gate facility or bus passengers to the terminal, he said.
</P>
<P>
   A Delta spokesman said there are no plans for such a move.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Ray Neidl of ING Barings Furman Selz said Delta's move
reflects ``a basic change of philosophy driven by the impact of
regional jets.'' The planes are being widely adopted by commuter
airlines, which can use them to fly longer routes.
</P>
<P>
   As an independent company, Neidl noted, ASA is obligated to use
its jets as profitably as possible, even if it means competing for
passengers with Delta. A buyout would prevent that potential
conflict, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Worth said the deal won't affect Delta's relationships with
other commuter affiliates. Comair feeds Delta flights in Cincinnati
and Orlando, while SkyWest feeds them in Salt Lake City. Both are
independent and, unlike ASA, also work with other carriers.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of pilot unions at both Delta and ASA withheld
judgment on the deal, although they agreed it is permitted under
their contracts and poses no integration issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the surface I would have to say it's probably very
positive,'' said Frank Ramsey Jr., an Atlanta-based ASA captain and
chairman of its pilot union.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Thurston writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
