<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEIGHT-COMPETE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEIGHT WATCHERS IS NOT ALONE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wis., Calif., Fla.)  (With WEIGHT-WATCHERS) 
(mk) 
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Weight Watchers has plenty of company in the weight-loss
business.
</P>
<P>
   Far older than Weight Watchers, which was founded in 1963, is
TOPS Club Inc., a nonprofit organization whose initials stand for
Take Off Pounds Sensibly. The organization began in 1948, and today
has about 275,000 members in the United States and Canada who pay
$20 a year to join, said a spokeswoman, Susan Trones.
</P>
<P>
   TOPS is based in Milwaukee and maintains a site on the Web
(www.tops.org). Its informal motto, Ms. Trones said, is: ``Your
doctor provides the diet; we provide the `Do it.''' To that end,
the organization does not prescribe particular weight-loss plans
but stresses support at group meetings. ``More and more research is
pointing to the fact that with any kind of lifestyle change _
whether it is losing weight, quitting smoking or getting out of a
bad marriage _group support seems to be the key ingredient,'' Ms.
Trones said.
</P>
<P>
   Another widely known program is the publicly traded Jenny Craig
Inc., which boasts on its Web site (www.jennycraig.com) that it is
the only ``pure play investment opportunity in the field of weight
management.'' Founded in 1983 and based in La Jolla, Calif., the
company's method includes classes for moral support and an emphasis
on healthy eating habits and exercise, and products like gingko
biloba extract.
</P>
<P>
   Slim-Fast Foods Co.'s weight-loss program, which also maintains
a site on the Web (www.slimfast.com), urges people to consume its
milkshakes twice a day, with one regular meal in the evening. The
privately held company, based in West Palm Beach, Fla., calls its
plan ``an easy, delicious way to lose weight,'' though no estimates
are available on the number of people who participate in the
program.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
