<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-16 19:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7648 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBITUARY-KENDALL-BOS &LR;      02-16 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-KENDALL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HENRY KENDALL, 72; NOBEL LAUREATE, MIT PHYSICS PROFESSOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. CHANDLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Henry W. Kendall, professor of physics at the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology, a 1990 Nobel laureate for the discovery of
the building blocks of matter, and cofounder of the Union of
Concerned Scientists, died Monday in Florida during a diving
expedition.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Kendall, 72, was diving with a friend from the National
Geographic Society at Wakulla Springs State Park in Florida. Mr.
Kendall, an experienced diver and underwater photographer, was
taking underwater pictures and was later found in water 6 to 8 feet
deep at the edge of the lake.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Ris, executive director of the Union of Concerned
Scientists in Cambridge, Mass., of which Mr. Kendall had been
chairman for the last 25 years, said Tuesday that Mr. Kendall
``firmly believed that scientists could _ and should _ play an
important role in public policy debates.''
</P>
<P>
   The group strove to carry out that principle, becoming strongly
involved in controversies over nuclear weapons, nuclear power
plants, the Star Wars defense initiative, and global warming.
</P>
<P>
   ``His leadership of UCS was deeply rooted in the belief that,
given accurate and credible information, the public and
policymakers would, ultimately, make the right choices about the
future,'' Ris said.
</P>
<P>
   Fellow Nobel laureate Jerome Friedman of MIT said Tuesday that
Mr. Kendall ``was an outstanding scientist and an outstanding human
being who worked tirelessly for the betterment of society.''
</P>
<P>
   An autopsy Tuesday showed that Mr. Kendall had not drowned,
according to officials at the Wakulla County sheriff's office.
There was no water in his lungs, and there was air in his diving
tank. Police planned further tests on the diving equipment to see
if it malfunctioned, and other tests were being performed to
determine the cause of death. Results are not expected for two to
three weeks, said a spokesman for the sheriff's office.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Kendall won the Nobel prize in physics in 1990, along with
Friedman and Richard Taylor of Stanford, for work done at the
Stanford Linear Accelerator Center in the 1960s that produced the
first direct evidence for the existence of quarks _ tiny particles
that combine in groups of three to form the subatomic particles,
such as protons, from which matter is made.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after learning he had won the prize, Mr. Kendall told
the Globe that he welcomed the honor ``because I think it will help
the UCS and my participation with them.'' He added that ``I have
always considered the things that we do there of very great
importance. . . . I have been astonished at the persistence of high
military budgets and unwise weapons systems, and a frequently
narrow view of what's needed to ensure our national security, and I
would like to see those things change.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, he had concentrated much of his effort with the
UCS on increasing public and political awareness of the issue of
global warming caused by the burning of fossil fuels. He told the
Globe that while this was not in his personal field of expertise,
``the greenhouse mechanism . . . is absolutely genuine, and is not
contested by anybody at all; it's not at all controversial. What is
not established at the present time is whether there is genuinely a
warming trend which you can attribute to greenhouse gases.''
</P>
<P>
   Even nine years ago the evidence was pointing that way, he said.
``What we are pushing for is at least for the country, and
hopefully other nations, to take the steps that don't cost anything
and which are beneficial on their own, independent of the
greenhouse effect,'' he said. ``And what is so striking and
poignant is that our government won't even take steps which are
otherwise beneficial and which would be the first lead-in to
controlling the greenhouse effect.''
</P>
<P>
   Such steps, he said then, included greater investment in known
clean energy sources, such as wind and solar power, to help make
their costs competitive with other sources.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Kendall was part of a panel of scientists who briefed
President Clinton on global warming in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Ris said that recently Mr. Kendall had also been pressing for
the group to get involved in efforts to preserve endangered species
and biodiversity.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Kendall had continued to be active in his own research and
the work of the UCS, Ris said. Unlike many researchers of his
standing, he enjoyed working with beginning students and continued
to teach a freshman physics lab at MIT. ``He was going as strong as
ever,'' he said. ``He was a great man.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Kendall, who earned his doctorate in physics at MIT in 1954,
taught at Stanford University from 1956 to 1961, and had been
teaching at MIT since then. He and his brother were principal
shareholders in the family business, Kendall Co., which made Curad
bandages, Curity diapers, and hospital equipment. They sold the
company in 1972 to Colgate Palmolive Co. for $512 million.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Kendall leaves his brother, John, of Sharon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
