<HEADER>
A7650 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HAPPENINGS-ART-2TAKES     02-16 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAPPENINGS-ART-2TAKES-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MODERN ART'S MISSING LINK: THE JERSEY SCENE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, FEB. 21) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 Edward M. Gomez is the author of the New Design series (Rockport
Publishers), with volumes on Tokyo, Los Angeles, Paris and
London.  
 By EDWARD M. GOMEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Any list of historic centers of modern art must include Paris,
New York, London, Berlin, Moscow and Vienna. And, of course, New
Brunswick, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   But who knew?
</P>
<P>
   Now, with ``Off Limits: Rutgers University and the Avant-Garde,
1957-1963,'' the Newark Museum has organized an illuminating
exhibition about one of modern art's lesser-known but pivotal
creative scenes. It unfolded at a moment when the art world was
transfixed by the apotheosis of Abstract Expressionism, and
still-nascent Pop Art had yet to emerge.
</P>
<P>
   The time was the late 50s and early 60s, when a mutually
influential group of artists, teachers and students came together
at the Rutgers College and Douglass College campuses in New
Brunswick. There, they came up with radical notions and
rule-breaking experiments that helped sow the seeds of performance
art, installation art, conceptual art, Pop Art and the
international current in art known as Fluxus.
</P>
<P>
   ``Off Limits,'' which traces this art-historical path, focuses
on the ideas and early work of Allan Kaprow, Robert Watts, George
Segal, Geoffrey Hendricks, Robert Whitman, Lucas Samaras, George
Brecht and Roy Lichtenstein, examining some of the better known of
these artists' work in unexpected contexts. The show opened
Thursday and will remain on view through May 16.
</P>
<P>
   ``A desire to break down the barrier between art and life
inspired these artists,'' said Joseph Jacobs, the museum's curator
of American art and one of the exhibition's main organizers. ``So
they made art using real objects, real space and time, and live
human beings. They brought the audience into their art.''
</P>
<P>
   Significantly, several members of the Rutgers group attended or
dropped in on John Cage's experimental-composition classes at the
New School for Social Research in Manhattan. Cage taught his
now-legendary courses there from 1956 to 1960.
</P>
<P>
   Students who soaked up the avant-garde master's ideas about a
new, collagelike music made from everyday, ambient sounds included
Kaprow, Brecht, Dick Higgins, Al Hansen, Jackson Mac Low and Toshi
Ichiyanagi. Segal sometimes joined Kaprow; and Watts, Whitman and
Larry Poons also turned up. A devotee of Zen Buddhism, Cage taught
his charges to regard music, like any slice of life, as simply an
endless succession of events transpiring in time and space. (Rare
recordings of some of their experimental soundworks are included in
the exhibition.)
</P>
<P>
   Kaprow, who joined the Rutgers College art faculty in 1953, was
one of the most charismatic figures on the New Brunswick scene.
Like his friend Robert Rauschenberg in the early 1950s, he
developed mixed-media assemblages unlike normal wall-mounted
pieces. With his background in philosophy and art history, he
became a spokesman for this new art form. In a seminal essay, ``The
Legacy of Jackson Pollock,'' he advanced his ideas about it.
</P>
<P>
   Joan Marter, a professor of art history at Rutgers who consulted
on the organization of ``Off Limits'' and edited the accompanying
book, writes in it that Kaprow's Pollock article, which Artnews
magazine published in 1958, ``was the first postmortem of Abstract
Expressionism to articulate a new direction for young artists.''
</P>
<P>
   Kaprow, she notes, ``championed an art that involved a spatial
extension to entangle the participant, breaking with conventional
painting, to an art more actively involved with ritual, magic and
life itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Of Kaprow's process, Jacobs said: ``He made what he called
Environments. Then, from Cage, he added the performer and gave
birth to a new form that was distinctly visual, especially in a
gallery context. Like musical compositions, each of these works had
its own score.''
</P>
<P>
   Reaching beyond the confines even of ``action painting,'' these
works, with their staging and performance instructions, became
known as Happenings. In 1958, Kaprow showed his first Environment
at the Hansa Gallery in New York, filling rooms with mirrors,
dramatic lighting and sheets of cellophane suspended from the
ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   Happenings occurred on the Douglass College campus, but they
were first put in a conventional art context in 1959, when Kaprow
presented ``18 Happenings in 6 Parts'' at the Reuben Gallery in
downtown Manhattan. Moving beyond Cage's teaching and his own
Environments, Kaprow served up a barrage of sensory experiences _
slide projections, painting, a person squeezing oranges _ in a
procession of nonnarrative events.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the more conceptual, interactive Events of Brecht,
a scientist at Johnson &AMP; Johnson who invented the tampon, and the
later Fluxus artists usually required only simple props and brief
instructions. Often these few words were printed on small cards
that conveyed a participatory sense of fun and play.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout ``Off Limits,'' Jacobs and his colleagues have evoked
the humorous, often philosophical, sometimes subversive spirit of
the art on view. Their first wall panel explains a ``score'' in the
context of the period's art-as-life activities and invites viewers
to approach the show's thematic sections as the interactive
Happenings and Events that they describe and emulate.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Thus, in many cases, ``Off Limits'' emphatically proposes:
``Please do touch the art.'' Brecht's signature pointing-finger
symbol, a pick-up from old commercial printing, serves as a
directional marker from one gallery to the next.
</P>
<P>
   Julia Robinson, the museum's coordinator of special projects,
who has worked closely with Jacobs, said, ``A lot of this work is
open-ended and, at the same time, very cerebral, like Kaprow's
`Beauty Parlor III,' an Environment with masks and costumes that
visitors can put on, and photo booths where they can take their
pictures.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Robinson also pointed out works ``that go in another
direction,'' like Brecht's enigmatic ``Repository'' (1961), a wall
cabinet stuffed with found objects, including keys, bottle caps,
rubber balls and a preserved worm. Another is Brecht's ``Exit''
(1963), a metal commercial sign whose message _ part invitation,
part command _ becomes ambiguous in an art context.
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with Kaprow's dictum to make art that did not look
like art, what unifies all of the work on view in Newark is its
conceptual self-awareness. Thus, Lichtenstein's ``Portrait of Allan
Kaprow'' (1961) and ``Portrait of Ivan Karp'' (1961) do not
resemble their named subjects at all. Instead, they are two
identical, generic, clip-art-style images in an irony-laden series
that Lichtenstein could have continued indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Watts' ``Table for a Suicide Event'' (1961), a table
topped with a telephone, a latex glove and other common objects,
refers less to the unsettling act cited in its title than to the
implicit meaning of the steady accumulation, over time, of phone
calls and other everyday actions that inevitably lead to death.
</P>
<P>
   Following the comprehensive Pollock survey at the Museum of
Modern Art, and at a time when popular interest still seems keen
for all things 60s, ``Off Limits'' sheds light on the multilane
bridge that links the output of the Rutgers era to art forms of
later decades. It suggests that the roots of performance art lie
largely in the presentations of Kaprow and his colleagues at venues
like the Reuben Gallery, which existed only from 1959 to 1961.
</P>
<P>
   And Whitman emerges as one of the founding fathers of
installation art. His ``Shower'' (1963), on loan from Rauschenberg,
offered the innovative combination of a functioning showerhead and
a film projection of a woman standing beneath it; again, art made
from and blurring the boundary with real life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Segal, with his plaster figures in `The Dinner Party,' and
Lichtenstein, with `Look Mickey,' were also scavenging from
ordinary life, albeit from radically different sources,'' Jacobs
said. ``And Samaras made a work about danger using real razor
blades.''
</P>
<P>
   Before his death in 1997, Lichtenstein told Jacobs and Ms.
Marter, ``If I had stayed in Oswego, nothing would have happened,'`
referring to the State University of New York campus where he
taught before moving to Rutgers. The artist was still a
conservative Abstract Expressionist painter when he was hired to
teach design at Douglass College in 1960.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like the other Rutgers artists who recalled the period,''
Jacobs said, ``Roy recognized that it was special, liberating. But
it disappeared because it was too complicated and didn't lend
itself to an easy label.'' By 1963, the Reuben Gallery had closed,
Happenings had been publicized in the news media (and sometimes
parodied), artists like Kaprow and Lichtenstein had initiated
promising art-world careers, and members of the Rutgers group and
their activities had been absorbed by Fluxus or other art
movements.
</P>
<P>
   Looking back, Segal has jokingly said that he and Kaprow once
referred to their group's explosion of energy as ``The New
Brunswick School of Painting.'' But the ambitious, inventive, often
ephemeral work it produced, while not completely forgotten, had
never been examined as a whole.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with ``Off Limits,'' the Rutgers era has gained its
thoughtfully documented chapter in the history books _ even if the
rich diversity of its offerings still defies one simple name.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-99 1949EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990216.0330 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-16 19:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7652 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DARTMOUTH-FRATS-ART-9     02-16 1263
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DARTMOUTH-FRATS-ART-990&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALL FOR CHANGE HAS FRAT-DOMINATED DARTMOUTH IN AN UPROAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By CAREY GOLDBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HANOVER, N.H. _ Furious cries of ``Paternalism!'' and protest.
Canceled Winter Carnival parties replaced by rallies and meetings.
Tears and frantic calls home and blizzards of ``Blitzmail,'' the
college e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Here at Dartmouth, an academically distinguished college also
known for a style of fraternity party so wild it inspired the movie
``Animal House,'' the last week has brought a level of turmoil that
old-timers say they have not seen since the place went co-ed 26
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   What has so shaken the campus was an announcement by the Board
of Trustees and Dartmouth's new president, James Wright, that the
school must begin to change its fraternity-dominated social
culture. Among other things, the trustees said the system must be
``substantially co-educational'' and stamp out alcohol abuse.
</P>
<P>
   And although officials are vague about the specifics, many
students read the announcement as presaging the imminent end of
their beloved fraternities and sororities, and responded as if the
college were abolishing their families, stripping them of their
friends and tearing down the venues for the fun that helps them
through scholastic stress and the northern winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``They dropped a massive bomb on the community here,'' said Sean
Maduck, president of the Chi Heorot fraternity, ``and everybody's
up in arms fighting over it.''
</P>
<P>
   Dartmouth is permeated by fraternities and sororities to an
extent far above the national average and unusual in the Ivy
League. Freshmen are not eligible to join, but among upperclassmen,
about half are members of the 28 houses known collectively as the
Greek system. All but three are single-sex, and their basements
often serve as beer fountains and dance halls.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, only about 10 percent of college students are
fraternity or sorority members, said Jonathan Brant, spokesman for
the National Interfraternity Conference. And only a handful of
colleges over the last two or three decades have moved as
dramatically as Dartmouth toward disowning fraternities or
requiring they go co-ed: Williams, Colby, Middlebury, Amherst, and
Bowdoin came to mind, said Brant.
</P>
<P>
   Dartmouth fraternities have certainly calmed down quite a bit
since the Animal House days of the '60s, tethered by alcohol laws
and rules focused somewhat more on social service and speaking
programs. Though houses have occasionally been disciplined in
recent years for backsliding, the misogynistic, vomit-spattered
debauchery several of them were once known for is considered a
thing of the past.
</P>
<P>
   But they continue to dominate the social life at Dartmouth and
that, the trustees decided, in a move that had been discussed for
years, contradicts the college's values.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want a system that, finally, is more inclusive, is fuller,
and is more of a whole experience,'' Wright said in an interview.
``And this crosses lines of race and of background as well as lines
of gender.''
</P>
<P>
   Wright is presenting the new principles as a historic
opportunity to ``re-imagine'' campus life and give students more
``social choice.'' The trustees have laid down the parameters, he
said; now they are taking suggestions from students, beginning a
process that could last a year or so, and will be followed by more
years of change that will include building new gathering spots and
on-campus dormitories to alleviate the bed shortage that forces
hundreds of students off campus.
</P>
<P>
   But students have tended to focus mainly on Wright's firm
statement in the daily Dartmouth newspaper that ``this is not a
referendum'' and a headline trumpeting the end of the fraternity
system ``as we know it.'' Suddenly, this autumn's rush, the
courting ritual between members and prospective members, seemed in
jeopardy. So did many decades of tradition, prompting angry calls
and unconfirmed rumors of withdrawn pledges from among the 50,000
alumni _ though some voices of support as well, Wright said.
</P>
<P>
   Among about a dozen students interviewed on Monday in the Collis
student center, none supported the trustees' decision, though only
about half were members of Greek houses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's absolutely ludicrous to completely wipe out
something so many people are in favor of,'' said Jennifer Coup, a
senior and sorority member. In particular, she said, ``The
single-sex houses foster a lot of really strong bonds of
friendship. It's a very supportive environment for women that I
think, especially in these times of our lives, is very important.''
</P>
<P>
   Kallie Willets, a senior who does not belong to a Greek house
but whose father did, said that when she heard of the trustees'
decision, ``I flipped out and left a message to my Dad: `Dad!
They're trying to kill the fraternity system!'''
</P>
<P>
   He has kept in close contact with his fraternity brothers, she
said, and ``I see the value of the system, that 30 years later
they're still close.''
</P>
<P>
   Fraternity defenders also argue that the Greek houses are not
exclusive in that all women and virtually all men who go through
the rush process are guaranteed an invitation to join from at least
one house. And many parties are open to all as well _ an important
social asset in a small town set in the snowy boondocks and
nicknamed Hangover by some.
</P>
<P>
   But a significant minority of the college's 4,300 undergraduates
dislike the houses as cliques and limiting, students say. And
Dartmouth faculty decided more than a decade ago that Greek houses'
exclusive-by-definition admissions, their behavioral problems and
sometimes downright anti-intellectual attitude outweighed their
pluses, and voted to recommend they be abolished.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were the antithesis of what a liberal arts college should
be,'' said Prof. Hans Penner, a former dean of faculty, recalling
antics like fraternity brothers competing to see how long they
could go without leaving the house, including for classes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time to really try something new,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Some of the intensity of student reaction seemed to stem from
the simple fact that no one _ including the trustees _ knows what
that new thing will be.
</P>
<P>
   At a meeting Monday night with students that was broadcast over
the college's cable system, Wright and two trustees made clear that
though they would not bend on their principles, they wanted to
leave the particulars largely up to students to suggest.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing would happen fast, Wright said, assuring students that
autumn rush would proceed as planned, that the new system would
likely not be put into place while they were students, and that
nothing would be eliminated before a replacement was ready. There
was no set timetable either, they said, nor a formula for what
``substantially co-educational'' meant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would that we had a plan,'' said Kate Stith-Cabranes, a
trustee. ``We don't have any secret plan up our sleeve.''
</P>
<P>
   Among scores of students watching together in the Collis student
center, cries of ``Liar!'' came from the suspicious audience. And
for all the explaining done late into the night by the trustees,
when the meeting ended, students seemed little mollified.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always knew I'd pledge somewhere,'' said Andrew Sonnenborn,
class of '02. ``It irritates me there might be no pledges below
me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
