A7654 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-SHARON-NYT &LR;      02-16 0680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-SHARON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAELI FOREIGN MINISTER INVESTIGATED FOR BRIBING WITNESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Israeli Foreign Minister Ariel Sharon is under
police investigation on suspicion of bribery, his lawyer, Jacob
Weinroth, said Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli police are investigating allegations that Sharon bribed
a former army general, Avigdor Ben Gal, to give false testimony in
a libel trial in 1997. The libel suit was brought by Sharon, who
accused a newspaper of falsehoods regarding his conduct as defense
minister during the 1982 invasion of Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Sharon flew to New York so that his wife, who is ill,
could seek emergency medical care at Sloan-Kettering Hospital.
Police plan to question him when he returns to Israel, Weinroth
said.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday police interrogated Ben Gal, now a businessman and head
of the military aircraft industry, about a trip to Russia with
Sharon shortly before he testified at the libel trial.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon, who was Israel's infrastructure minister at the time of
the trial, had taken Ben Gal along with him to Russia to explore a
deal on importing natural gas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that on the face of it you can see the absurdity,''
Weinroth said. ``It's impossible to even think that a general in
the Israeli military can be bribed by just a ticket to Russia.''
</P>
<P>
   The police investigation grows out of a complaint filed by the
Haaretz newspaper after it won the libel suit _ a victory that
Sharon has appealed to the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon had sued the paper for an article that asserted that
while defense minister he had misled the government of Menachem
Begin about his plans for the invasion of Lebanon in 1982. The
article, an opinion column on the op-ed page, detailed what it
called a pattern of Sharon's ``lies.''
</P>
<P>
   The columnist, Uzi Benziman, described what he characterized as
Sharon's willful deception of Begin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Menachem Begin knows very well that Sharon deceived him,''
Benziman wrote, ``but he doesn't want to hide behind the wide back
of the minister of defense for his responsibility as prime minister
for the war.''
</P>
<P>
   According to some testimony during the trial, Sharon had all
along intended to send Israeli troops deep into Lebanon. However,
the Haaretz article said, Sharon led the government to believe that
he was planning a more limited mission and that he only decided on
the more ambitious advance into Lebanon after the invasion was
already under way based on military realities on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Five years after the invasion, Ben Gal, a commander during the
Lebanon War, gave a lecture at an Israeli university at which he
spoke of a secret invasion plan by the army, about which, he said,
the government was kept in the dark.
</P>
<P>
   During the libel trial, Haaretz called on Ben Gal to testify as
a supporting witness. But once on the stand, he surprised the
newspaper's lawyers by changing his interpretation of the invasion,
saying he had been wrong and apologizing to Sharon.
</P>
<P>
   The day after Ben Gal testified, an Israeli business newspaper
published a report of his trip to Russia with Sharon two weeks
earlier to explore the gas deal.
</P>
<P>
   After Haaretz won the case, the newspaper submitted a complaint
to the police, asking them to investigate whether there was any
connection between Ben Gal's testimony and the Russia trip.
</P>
<P>
   Yossi Sarid, chairman of the leftist Meretz Party, also urged an
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to the government's lawyer, he said: ``It is strange
and odd that Ben Gal hid in his heart the alleged truth for such a
long period of time, without bothering to clean the stain off
Sharon earlier. Only now, after the joint tour of Russia and at a
time when Ben Gal is expecting as a private businessman his own
share in the natural gas deal does he suddenly remember to change
his version from bottom to top.''
</P>
<P>
   Interviewed on Israeli television in 1997, Ben Gal said, ``I did
not discuss with Sharon matters relating to the trial, and this
trial has nothing to do with the trip.''
</P>
</TEXT>
