<DOCNO> NYT19990216.0332 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-16 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7659 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ASH-WEDNESDAY-COX     02-16 1178
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASH-WEDNESDAY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    OUT OF THE ASHES
 &HT;    By Steve Gushee
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ One wag claims that people will flock to
church if you give them something _ even ashes.
</P>
<P>
   And, true to form, many churches will be full for Ash Wednesday
services today on the first of the 40 days of Lent.
</P>
<P>
   The faithful will be marked with ashes on their foreheads as a
sign of death and decay, mortality, penance and other grim
reminders that life is nasty, brutish and short.
</P>
<P>
   And it is one of the most popular days in the church year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't ask me the logic of it,'' said the Rev. Michael
Driscoll, pastor of St. Jude Roman Catholic Church in Boca Raton.
``I'm baffled by it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Driscoll knows that ashes have profound ritual power. They
are often mentioned in the Bible as a sign of humility, penance or
destruction, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Abraham refers to himself as mere dust and ashes. The
long-suffering Job sat in ashes. Jesus mentioned sack cloth and
ashes as tools of repentance.
</P>
<P>
   But, most powerfully, ashes are an unambiguous sign of death.
Many clergy intone, as they impose ashes on the faithful,
``Remember thou art dust and to dust thou shall return.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People like ashes. People flock to ashes, that very rude
reminder of mortality,'' said the Rev. Christopher Kelly, rector of
St. Christopher's Episcopal Church in West Palm Beach. ``Maybe it's
a reminder of a basic fact of life they don't see very often in our
society. We're going to die.''
</P>
<P>
   The popularity of putting ashes on the forehead might be rooted
in ancient religious consciousness. Ashes may touch a chord in the
human spirit that recalls a time when the faithful painted their
bodies or used tattoos as a sign of religious commitment.
</P>
<P>
   And in a strange, ceremonial way, ashes smeared on the forehead
impart a kind of dual identity for the complex season of Lent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ash Wednesday may hark back to rituals where marking the body
was part of your religious commitment,'' said the Rev. Lesley
Northrop, associate professor of religion and culture at Florida
International University in Miami. ``There is something fundamental
or basic about having ashes rubbed on your head as a sign that you
are both sinner and believer.''
</P>
<P>
   Ashes mark the desperate beginning of a grim journey that ends
in glory. They are a sign of the bad news that precedes the good
news of the Christian gospel.
</P>
<P>
   At services today, Christians confess they are sinners, subject
to death and helpless to change their sad lot in life. Ashes
signify that corrupt reality.
</P>
<P>
   But, Christians claim, God can use the ashes of humanity to
create new life through his son, Jesus. That's the Easter miracle
to which Ash Wednesday points. It's the radical claim at the heart
of the Christian message.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not talking Band Aids,'' Kelly said. ``We are not
patching over defects of personality and sin and making a temporary
restitution. We're talking about change in Jesus Christ. The change
is from ashes into living flesh.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly, like most clergy, makes ashes each year by burning palms
saved from the Palm Sunday celebration of the previous year.
</P>
<P>
   Palm Sunday tells the story of Jesus' triumphant entry into
Jerusalem, which led to Easter Day. So, the sign of man's humility
comes from the symbol of God's victory.
</P>
<P>
   And most churches with formal services, including Roman
Catholic, Episcopal and, more recently, many Lutheran, Methodist
and other Protestant traditions, will offer ashes today. Protestant
churches abandoned the practice during the Reformation.
</P>
<P>
   `It's something that's been catching on with increasing
frequency in the last 10 to 15 years,'' said the Rev. Kendall
Taylor, the West Palm Beach district supervisor of the United
Methodist Church.
</P>
<P>
   In the early church, individuals _ ostracized from the Christian
community by serious sins such as adultery or apostasy _ did public
penance until they were reconciled with the church, Driscoll said.
They wore sack cloth covered with ashes and begged from others
prayer and forgiveness.
</P>
<P>
   By the 6th century, the church began to substitute ritual acts
for individual public penance. Soon, ashes were widely used in
those services. And Christians not under church discipline began to
join in the penitential rites.
</P>
<P>
   In 1091, Pope Urban II ordered all churches to use ashes on the
day that was to become known as Ash Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   And ashes still kick off the 40-day season of penance used to
anticipate Holy Week and Easter. Lent involves giving up bad
habits, taking on good ones, paying more attention to your spirit
and less to your body.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, all dairy and meat products _ any foods taken
from animals _ were forbidden in Lent. The abstinence was
rigorously enforced.
</P>
<P>
   Carnivals, such as the New Orleans Mardi Gras, often preceded
Ash Wednesday for a last-gasp celebration before the rigors of Lent
began.
</P>
<P>
   And Lent spawned such things as hot cross buns, pretzels and
alternative rice and lentil dishes that replaced traditional foods.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, they developed so many wonderful foods for Lent that
I think people actually gain weight,'' said the Rev. SimeonCorona,
pastor of St. Mary's Orthodox Church in West Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Orthodox Christians do not observe Ash Wednesday. Orthodox Lent
begins on a Monday, six weeks or 36 Lenten days, before Easter.
That was roughly a tenth, or a tithe, of the year in which to be
penitential.
</P>
<P>
   But Sundays are never part of Lent, so the actual number of days
to Easter is greater. Sunday is always a feast day of Jesus'
Resurrection when the discipline of Lent is relaxed.
</P>
<P>
   Stories abound of faithful penitents waiting breathlessly for
the stroke of midnight on Saturday. Then, they could indulge in the
behavior they ``gave up'' for Lent. Smokers smoked. Others ate
chocolate or had a quick beer before bed.
</P>
<P>
   In the 7th century, the Western church added four days to Lent,
so the season began Wednesday and included 40 days for Lent in a
46-day period.
</P>
<P>
   That made Lent mirror other difficult periods of 40 in the
Bible. Jesus was 40 days in the wilderness, tempted by the devil.
Israel wandered 40 years in the wilderness before reaching the
promised land.
</P>
<P>
   But most scholars suggest that the roots of Lent are found in
nature's annual cycle. The Anglo-Saxon word, Lencten, which is the
root word for Lent, means spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lent has its roots in that period of the darkness of winter,''
Northrop said. ``Then you waited for signs that life would come
back again in spring, at Easter.''
</P>
<P>
   The cycle of life and death is played out in nature and in the
Christian story of the death and resurrection of Jesus. Lent
provides the context.
</P>
<P>
   And, for many, it begins with ashes rubbed on the forehead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a basic gloomy act that is linked to an incredible hope
for change and, somehow, eternal joy,'' Kelly said.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Gushee writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
