<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-16 19:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7663 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOLS-RACE-1STLD-WR     02-16 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOLS-RACE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CASE MAY END SCHOOL DESEGREGATION IN SAN FRANCISCO 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Complete writethru _ adds settlement reached, edits to
conform)  
 (With: SCHOOLS-LOWELL; not optional trim)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JULIAN GUTHRIE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Patrick Wong, Brian Ho and Hilary Chen were
turned away from the San Francisco public schools of their choice
for one undisputed reason: They are Chinese-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Wong, 14 in 1994, was denied a place at top-ranked Lowell High
School because, by policy, Chinese-American children must score
higher on admissions exams than students of other ethnic groups. Ho
and Chen, 5 and 8 at the time, were turned away from their
neighborhood elementary schools because the schools had reached
their quota of Chinese-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you imagine, as a parent, seeing your son's hopes denied
in this way at the age of 14?'' said Patrick Wong's mother,
Charlene Wong Loen.
</P>
<P>
   The families of the students filed a class-action lawsuit
seeking to overturn San Francisco's desegregation plan.
</P>
<P>
   The trial was scheduled to begin Tuesday in federal court here,
but a last-minute settlement was reached in the case. District
Judge William Orrick ordered that the details of the agreement be
kept confidential until a hearing Wednesday on preliminary approval
of the settlement.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome could end the practice of limiting any one race at a
school to 45 percent, and stop the busing set up to achieve that
quota. It could cost the 62,000-student San Francisco school system
$37 million each year in state aid. And, perhaps no less
disruptive, it could shift the boundaries of virtually every
neighborhood school in the city.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition to racial quotas comes not just from
conservatives or from high-achieving Asian-Americans often excluded
by efforts to open doors for blacks and Hispanics. It also comes
from black parents and activists tired of having children bused
across town to meet a diversity formula.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the desegregation plan resulted from a lawsuit filed
against the school district by the NAACP in the 1970s on behalf of
black children.
</P>
<P>
   But the passing years have created an alliance between the NAACP
and the school district. They are now the city's most ardent
defenders of the desegregation system.
</P>
<P>
   Based on written statements by Orrick, who signed the federal
desegregation order in 1983, the school district was headed for
defeat.
</P>
<P>
   Orrick said the district and the NAACP were ``utterly unprepared
to go to trial,'' and their failure to produce evidence in support
of the current system showed they had almost ``no likelihood of
prevailing at trial.''
</P>
<P>
   The case is being closely watched nationwide because it raises
complex legal and social questions, such as whether the
desegregation order is discriminatory.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Girard, the lawyer representing the Chinese-American
families that sued to overturn the quotas, said the use of racial
classification is a violation of the 14th Amendment guarantee of
equal protection.
</P>
<P>
   ``The district and NAACP will tell you the (desegregation)
consent decree has done all of these wonderful things and created
all these great programs,'' Girard said. ``But you can't use an
unconstitutional means to achieve a wonderful end.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the desegregation consent decree, San Francisco's 62,000
students are divided into nine ethnic and racial categories:
American Indian, black, Chinese, Filipino, Japanese, Korean,
Spanish-surnamed, other white and other non-white. No group may
exceed more than 45 percent of any school, and at least four groups
must be represented at every school.
</P>
<P>
   Since that formula was devised in 1983, the state has poured
$300 million into San Francisco schools to achieve desegregation.
The state now spends $37 million per year, roughly 12 percent of
the district's general fund.
</P>
<P>
   School Superintendent Bill Rojas defends the consent decree and
the racial quota system, saying blacks and Hispanics need certain
preferences because they are disproportionately ``denied the means
to achieve.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Harris, an NAACP attorney, said nagging inequities
remain in the school system. Black students are disciplined at
higher rates than students of other races, he said. Schools are
desegregated, but because students are clumped by ability, many
classrooms are still segregated. There also are not enough minority
teachers, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The task was given to the district to make whole these black
kids who had been pushed aside,'' Harris said. ``The district has
shown they're capable, but they must apply this to all black kids,
not just some.''
</P>
</TEXT>
