<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-16 19:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7664 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OCALAN-PROTESTS-BOS &LR;      02-16 0888
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OCALAN-PROTESTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLDWIDE PROTEST ERUPTS OVER REBEL LEADER'S ARREST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLUM LYNCH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Supporters of Kurdish rebel leader Abdullah
Ocalan rioted and stormed Greek and Kenyan embassies across Europe
and in Canada and Australia Tuesday, seizing hostages and setting
themselves ablaze in protest over the roles of those countries in
the capture of their leader.
</P>
<P>
   The arrest marked a major victory for Turkey, which has pursued
Ocalan for leading a 14-year insurgency that has led to the death
of some 30,000 people in Turkey. But it has set off fears in Europe
that the case will spark terrorist attacks and heighten tensions
between Europe's Turkish and Kurdish immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   The reaction, apparently coordinated, underscored the capacity
of Kurdish militants to raise havoc in Europe. And it demonstrates
why European governments have been so reluctant to arrest the
Kurdish leader, who has been turned away by Italy and, in recent
weeks, the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   Within hours of Ocalan's capture in Nairobi, hundreds of Kurdish
protesters had mobilized in more than 20 cities from London to
Vancouver to Sydney. From the Greek embassy in Copenhagen to a
Turkish prison cell, Ocalan supporters set themselves on fire,
leaving at least one dead and several others burned. In London, one
teen-age girl set her sweatshirt on fire, singing her hair and
face, before it was put out by police and fellow demonstrators
protesting near the Greek embassy.
</P>
<P>
   In Vienna, demonstrators gate-crashed a Greek embassy compound,
seizing five hostages, including the ambassador and his wife. In
Frankfurt, protesters overturned cars and clashed with police. And
in Moscow, 50 Kurdish protesters, shouting ``Freedom to Ocalan''
and vowing to die for Ocalan, were detained by police after they
forced their way onto the grounds of the Greek embassy.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Ocalan's Kurdish Workers Party, the PKK, vowed
to continue the fight against Turkey and charged US and Israel
intelligence with helping in the hunt for Ocalan.
</P>
<P>
   Other countries were quick to declare their hands clean. Israel
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu said: ``Israel had absolutely
nothing to do with the Ocalan affair.'' And a White House official
denied that the US played any direct role in the arrest or
extradition of Ocalan, but declined to comment if it assisted the
Turkish government in tracking Ocalan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are obviously very pleased with the apprehension of this
terrorist leader,'' said White House spokesman Joe Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
   But US officials said privately that they have been actively
pressing governments to turn Ocalan over to the Turkish government.
A State Department official said while no Americans had been
targeted by Tuesday's violence, it had issued a warning to American
diplomats and travelers.
</P>
<P>
   European leaders and international human rights activists
appealed to the Turkish government to give Ocalan a fair trial and
resist handing down a death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   In Paris, French Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine urged Turkey to
``respect the rule of law'' in its trial of Ocalan. The Council on
Europe issued a statement calling on Turkey to adhere to
international ``human rights'' standards as it presses ahead with
Ocalan's prosecution. And the UN special rapporteur on torture,
Nigel Rodley, citing concerns that Ocalan may be subjected to
torture, called for establishment of an independent monitor to
ensure his rights are respected.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Ocalan was initially taken to Istanbul before being
transfered to an uknown location outside Izmir, where he is
reportedly being interrogated,'' said Rodley. ``Fears have been
expressed that he may be subjected to torture or other forms of
ill-treatment.''
</P>
<P>
   The US, meanwhile, urged Turkey to use the case as a test to
prove its respect for the rule of law.
</P>
<P>
   ``This represents an opportunity for Turkey to clearly show its
commitment to human rights by ensuring Ocalan is treated humanely
and is given an open and transparent and fair trial in accordance
with international standards of due process,'' said US national
security spokesman P.J. Crowley.
</P>
<P>
   While analysts predicted Ocalan's arrest would deal a deadly
blow to his rebel army, they voiced skepticism over Turkey's
ability to parlay the rebel's capture into an effort to solve the
ongoing conflict between the Kurds and Turkey, which has refused to
grant the Kurds even a small degree of cultural and political
freedom.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a pretty hard blow to the PKK,'' said Neil Hicks, the
Middle East expert for the Lawyers Committee for Human Rights.
``But I'm not confident that the Turkish government is now going to
capitalize on its success.''
</P>
<P>
   US officials and human rights organizations say that Ocalan's
forces are responsible for the deaths of tens of thousands of
people during its war for autonomy in southeast Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since his arrest in December we have been pushing hard to see
him brought to justice,'' said Crowley. ``We have identified him as
a terrorist and we have worked with other governments to see that
there could be a trial.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe staff member David Filipov contributed to this report from
Moscow; and Globe correspondent Peggy Hernandez from London.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
