<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-16 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7666 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HILLARY-CLINTON-HNS &LR;      02-16 1027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HILLARY-CLINTON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HILLARY CLINTON WOULD FACE OBSTACLES IN SENATE BID 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton, who is under
growing pressure to run for the U.S. Senate from New York next
year, would face only minor technical hurdles if she chose to
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   But more subtle obstacles could prove to be a formidable bar to
her candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   First, the minor problems. She's not a New York resident. But
she could rent a place in the state at any time on or before
Election Day 2000 and still qualify to be on the ballot, according
to New York State Board of Elections spokesman Lee Daghlian.
</P>
<P>
   To win a place on the Democratic primary ballot, Clinton would
have to win 25 percent of the delegates at the party's state
convention in May 2000, according to Matthew Hiltzik, spokesman for
the New York Democratic Party. Piece of cake, say her backers.
</P>
<P>
   If for some reason she failed, they add, she would have no
trouble gathering 15,000 signatures on a petition by July 2000 to
force a primary race that September.
</P>
<P>
   But many Democratic experts say it would never come to that.
</P>
<P>
   Any opposition within the party would melt if she decides to
enter the race, they contend. The leading Democratic possibility so
far, Rep. Nita Lowey, D-N.Y., has said that if Clinton runs, she
would forego her own race and enthusiastically support the first
lady.
</P>
<P>
   As New York Democratic politicians sang her praises, Clinton
issued a three-sentence statement Tuesday saying she was giving the
race ``careful thought.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she appreciated ``the large number of people who have
encouraged me to consider running'' for the seat being opened by
the retirement of Democratic Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan.
</P>
<P>
   Alluding to her husband's impeachment ordeal, which ended with
his acquittal by the Senate last Friday, she said she had not been
able to give much thought to a potential candidacy but would do so
now. She said she would make her decision later this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the meantime,'' she said, ``I intend to continue to focus
my attention on the issues central to the president's agenda and on
which we have worked together for so many years.''
</P>
<P>
   As first lady, she has joined the president in cultivating New
York's wealthy elite on the fund-raising circuit, a huge
consideration in the state's ultra-expensive media market.
</P>
<P>
   Political professionals say up to $20 million is needed to win a
Senate seat in New York. That's the same amount of money
presidential candidates need to survive the primary season.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats hope the first lady will decide soon so that if she
refuses to run, Lowey or any other prospective candidate can move
quickly. Michael Tucker, spokesman for the Democratic Senatorial
Campaign Committee, said Democrats expect an announcement ``shortly
... by early March.''
</P>
<P>
   On March 3, Hillary Clinton is scheduled to be the star
attraction at a New York fund-raiser for the Democratic Party's
Women's Leadership Forum, and that could provide her an opportunity
to announce she will run.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton said Monday that ``she'd be great if she did
it'' and that he would enthusiastically support whatever decision
she makes.
</P>
<P>
   If she decides not to run, it might be because of the subtle
obstacles, one being her well-known penchant for privacy,
reinforced by Bill Clinton's affair with Monica Lewinsky and the
just-concluded impeachment debacle.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are some major issues from her past that would surely
come up in any race she entered _ her role as leader of the
administration's ill-fated 1993-1994 attempt to extend health care
to the uninsured and her involvement in the Whitewater real estate
deals in Arkansas in the late 1970s and the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there's the fact that New York is no place for
political wallflowers. Not that she is one, but she may not want
the hassle. If New York City's feisty mayor, Rudolph Giuliani,
chooses to run on the Republican side, she could be in for a
mudbath reminiscent of last year's race between then Rep. Charles
Schumer, D-N.Y., and Republican Senate incumbent Alfonse D'Amato.
</P>
<P>
   Polls so far are sending mixed signals. One taken late last
month by the Marist Institute in Poughkeepsie, N.Y., showed her
beating Giuliani 53 percent to 42 percent. But a Utica, N.Y.-based
Zogby International poll, also last month, showed Giuliani beating
Clinton 47 percent to 39 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Family finances may weigh in against a Senate run. The
Whitewater investigation, the now-settled Paula Jones sexual
harassment lawsuit and the Lewinsky matter have sent the Clintons'
legal bills skyrocketing. The Clinton Legal Expense Trust, set up
to help the couple defray legal costs, officially put the debt at
$4.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   That figure may rise when the trust issues a new accounting
report later this month. Hillary Clinton earned more than $1
million from her best-selling book ``It Takes a Village,'' but the
entire amount went to charity and to pay taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Both Clintons could earn large amounts after President Clinton
leaves office through speaking fees, service on corporate boards
and law practice. A Senate seat pays $136,673, a paltry sum to
those in the upper business and political realms.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans in New York are dismissive what they see as a
Hillary Clinton candidacy bubble. ``At this point, it's a bit of a
longshot that she's going to run,'' said Terry O'Brien, spokesman
for the New York Republican State Committee. ``If she does, she'd
bring in a lot more baggage than the carpetbag she'd bring in from
Arkansas.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Thirty-five years ago, Republican Sen. Kenneth Keating, R-N.Y.,
tried to tag his Democratic opponent, Robert F. Kennedy, with the
label of ``carpetbagger.''
</P>
<P>
   The term originally was used to describe northerners who sought
private gain from Reconstruction governments in the post-Civil-War
South.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy moved to New York in August 1964 in order to run against
Keating. That November he demolished Keating at the polls.
</P>
</TEXT>
