<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The talk suddenly turns to Oscar
 &HT;    By A. Scott Walton
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Fashion Week got a double dose of Oscar hysteria
Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   First, at a breakfast, the upscale retailer Barney's announced a
joint venture with the Christie's of London auction house to raise
money for AIDS charities by selling 50 gowns stars have worn to the
Academy Awards ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   Next, at a pre-lunch show at the Bryant Park Pavilion, Oscar de
la Renta gave matrons with money a reason to salivate.
</P>
<P>
   De la Renta's typical customer (Barbara Walters and Nancy
Kissinger being prime examples) is old enough to remember the Edith
Head-designed gown Janet Leigh wore to present the Oscar for best
original screenplay (for ``Room at the Top'') in 1959.
</P>
<P>
   The woman who wears de la Renta is also wealthy enough to place
a minimum bid of $2,000 for any one of the gowns being auctioned
March 18.
</P>
<P>
   Other Oscar gowns being auctioned include: Kate Winslet's green
silk gown by Givenchy (1997); Sharon Stone's Armani-Valentino-Gap
get-up (1995); and Cher's sheer-beaded gown by Bob Mackie (1983).
</P>
<P>
   As for de la Renta _ whose clientele is so faithful that the
ladies who lunch were lungeing from their limousines to secure
seats for the show _ the nominees for best fall colors are: camel,
ruby red, bright and burnt orange, hot pink and pale blue.
</P>
<P>
   New York's elegant elder statesman favors the A-line silhouette
for fall, with jackets and sweaters that hug the torso and skirts
that flare out to the knee. De la Renta went light on the detail
(sedate embroidery, pin-dot beading, scalloped hems) and heavy on
luxury fabrics such as silk, cashmere and fur.
</P>
<P>
   Naomi Campbell modeled the de la Renta gown with the best chance
of being worn by some leading lady on Oscar night: a red satin
Shakespearean dress with fur trim at the breast, cuff and hem.
</P>
<P>
   A. Scott Walton writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
