<SLUG> BC-FASHION-NOTES17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Johnson lassos stars for thematic downer
 &HT;    By A. Scott Walton
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Credit Betsey Johnson for this: attracting more
celebrities to her fall/winter runway show than any other designer
has so far this Fashion Week. In the crushing crowd Johnson
gathered at a cavernous Mercedes-Benz dealership, the notables
included: Aerosmith front man Steven Tyler, his bride and three of
his daughters; Blondie lead singer Debbie Harry; Jurassic rocker
Lou Reed; comedic actor Damon Wayans; and ``The Practice'' star
Dylan McDermott.
</P>
<P>
   As for Johnson's clothes? Credit denied. If there's a market for
the depressed, disheveled and disturbed looks she sent down the
runway, those shoppers should seek counseling. In her press notes,
Johnson said she designed with a mythical ``Seven Sisters'' in
mind, and she divided her show accordingly. Austerity, morbidity,
infancy, lasciviousness, homelessness, feminism and ego were the
themes. Perhaps reining in the excessive angst of her fall/winter
collection in time for the retail season should be Johnson's
assignment.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Blass out to pasture? Will 2000 be the year that Bill Blass
calls it quits? The designer hinted in the affirmative in a report
Tuesday in the trade publication Women's Wear Daily.
</P>
<P>
   Blass, who suffered a mild stroke in September during a personal
appearance at a Saks Fifth Avenue in Houston, has enjoyed a career
that's lasted more than half a century. At 76, Blass said, ``I'm
not sure I find fashion as stimulating as I once did.''
</P>
<P>
   The sole owner of his company, which caters mainly to rich,
mature women, Blass said he would ``sell it'' if he follows through
with tentative plans to bow out of the business next year.
</P>
<P>
   _ A. Scott Walton writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
