<SLUG> BC-TVSURFER-COLUMN17-COX- </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Agreeing to disagree on TV's great moments
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Love Boat'' over Letterman? ``The Brady Bunch'' ahead of
``Upstairs, Downstairs?'' ``The Dating Game'' but no ``60
Minutes''? Obviously, the editors at Entertainment Weekly have been
watching so much television their brains have turned into TV
dinners.
</P>
<P>
   Those list-o-maniacs are at it again. This time, Entertainment
Weekly has come up with what it modestly calls the 100 Greatest
Moments in Television.
</P>
<P>
   They get a lot right: JFK's assassination and funeral is No. 1,
and Neil Armstrong, ``Roots,'' Johnny Carson, Oprah Winfrey and
Walter Cronkite are all appropriately high up. Most importantly,
the list emphasizes the mix of the serious (Edward R. Murrow,
Watergate hearings) and the silly (Dick Van Dyke's ottoman,
``Saturday Night Live''). That juxtaposition makes TV what it is.
</P>
<P>
   But still, you have to wonder about what was included (``Beverly
Hills, 90210,'' ``The Six Million Dollar Man)'' and what those
shows bumped. So here are 10 genuinely memorable TV ``moments''
(within EW's loose definition) that didn't make the Top 100 but
should be on any list, more or less in order of importance:
</P>
<P>
   1. The debut of CNN. The news network's coverage of the
beginning of the Persian Gulf War made the list at No. 44, but that
was just when everyone started paying attention. The importance of
the global village _ Marshall McLuhan's '60s soundbite, made real
in the '80s and '90s by Ted Turner _ arguably outweighs everything
else on the list.
</P>
<P>
   2. ``60 Minutes'' moves to Sundays. After three years foundering
in the ratings and bouncing around, CBS' newsmag found its home in
1971. It's now the most popular, profitable and influential TV news
program in history.
</P>
<P>
   3. ``The Smothers Brothers Comedy Hour.'' For two brief but
intense years, the brothers brought true subversion into the
mainstream; their anti-Establishment (to use an ancient term)
sensibility was a precursor of much of popular TV today.
</P>
<P>
   4. ``Brian's Song.'' Along with ``Duel'' (which made the list at
No. 59), this 1971 flick launched the made-for-TV movie. And don't
even start on the emotional component.
</P>
<P>
   5. Coverage of the 1968 Chicago Democratic Convention. They said
the whole world was watching, and we were.
</P>
<P>
   6. Clarence Hill vs. Anita Thomas. The greatest he-said-she-said
ever. Real news and real entertainment in one big blur, as
addictive as heroin.
</P>
<P>
   7. ``Jeopardy!'' goes into syndication. The smartest, and
longest-running, game show on TV was on and off from 1964 to 1984,
but it was when Alex Trebek took over and it moved to early
evenings that it became an institution.
</P>
<P>
   8. ``Roseanne.'' She may be nuts, but her sitcom was political,
hilarious and influential.
</P>
<P>
   9. Milton Berle. The first, and in his day the only, television
star.
</P>
<P>
   10. Baby Jessica down the well. Before the white Bronco (No. 30)
and Princess Di's funeral (No. 82), this was the defining media
event that we all cared about even if it had no actual impact on
our lives.
</P>
<P>
   SEEN AND HEARD
</P>
<P>
   ` '70s Show' to carry on
</P>
<P>
   Fox has renewed ``That '70s Show'' for the 1999-2000 TV season,
ordering up 25 episodes. The sitcom will have its season finale on
March 14 and then re-enter the Fox lineup in June as part of the
network's summer strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Fox changing lineup
</P>
<P>
   Fox is about to play the shuffle game.
</P>
<P>
   At 8:30 p.m. March 28, the network will debut Matt Groening's
``Futurama.'' The animated series will then air the following
Sunday at the same time April 4, but then move to 8:30 p.m.
Tuesdays on April 6.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Family Guy'' will then debut in its regular Sunday time
period at 8:30 p.m. April 11.
</P>
<P>
   ``The PJs'' will move to 9 p.m. Tuesdays starting April 6.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, ``Guinness World Records: Primetime'' will be moved
to a new day and time.
</P>
<P>
   Raitt's turning moment
</P>
<P>
   On tonight's ``60 Minutes II'' (9 p.m. on CBS ), singer Bonnie
Raitt says the defining moment for her decision to be clean and
sober happened in Atlanta with the late Stevie Ray Vaughn. ``I saw
him the night he came out of recovery,'' Raitt says. ``He came and
sat in with me in Atlanta, Ga., . . . he was so nervous because he
had never played completely straight, and he burned a hole in the
sun . . . and I said, `There goes my last excuse. I do not have to
kill myself to play this music. And if he can do it, I can do it.'
''
</P>
<P>
   _Contributing: Bob Longino
</P>
<P>
   Phil Kloer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: channelsurfer(at)ajc.com
</P>
