<HEADER>
A7671 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GORE-POLITICS-ART-2TA     02-16 1052
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-POLITICS-ART-2TAKES(1,000)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMPEACHMENT SEEN AS BOOST TO GORE'S CHANCES IN 2000
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Tenn., Ind., Texas, Mo., N.J., Minn., Mass., Wash., Va.,
Iowa, N.H.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After Vice President Al Gore addressed a
closed-door retreat of House Democrats in the Virginia countryside
last weekend, he called on one of his most ardent supporters, Rep.
Norm Dicks of Washington, who posed what had the ring of a staged
question.
</P>
<P>
   ``Isn't it true, Mr. Vice President,'' Dicks asked, ``that if
you wrap this presidential nomination up quickly, you can quickly
turn your attention to raising money for House members?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' Gore deadpanned. The House members erupted in laughter.
</P>
<P>
   Had Dicks dared to try that question a year ago, he might well
have prompted jeers from the assembled Democrats. Many Democratic
lawmakers have never felt close personally to Gore _ and not long
ago were not about to concede, even in jest, that the presidential
nomination would be his in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   But the exchange at the retreat underscored how Gore, 50, has
emerged from the impeachment ordeal in a more commanding position
to capture the Democratic nomination than he would have if the
world had never heard of Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Most significantly, the favorite of many House Democrats,
Minority Leader Dick Gephardt of Missouri, has decided not to take
on Gore. And among Republicans there is such a feeling of
inevitability to the vice president's quest to succeed Clinton that
former Vice President Dan Quayle, in announcing his exploratory
committee last week, proclaimed: ``I will win the nomination. And I
will beat Al Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   That is by no means to say that Gore will win the nomination.
After all, the primary season is a year away, and the field has not
been set. Even his advisers point out that the vice president has
hardly electrified the Democratic electorate _ and might not be a
particularly potent contender in a general election.
</P>
<P>
   Still, through circumstances and by his cautious navigation of
the Lewinsky matter, Gore has strengthened his chances. He has
always had an inside track, if for no other reason than that no
sitting vice president in modern times has been denied the
nomination of his party.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest boost to Gore's candidacy is Gephardt's decision not
to challenge him for the nomination. More than any other rival,
Gephardt had begun to build an infrastructure in the pivotal states
of Iowa and New Hampshire and he had the ability to assemble the
organization and amass the money to become a potent challenger.
</P>
<P>
   But Gephardt's advisers said the central reason he did not move
forward was that the scandal led to the Democrats' unexpectedly
encouraging showing in the election last November _ and convinced
Gephardt that he should seize the opportunity to win the House back
and become speaker.
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt would have been the clear underdog, but would have made
the primary race for more treacherous and divisive for Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Another surprising advantage for Gore has been the Lewinsky
scandal, which essentially froze Gore in place as the Democratic
front-runner. The news media were so preoccupied with impeachment
that other potential candidates were frustrated in their efforts to
draw enough attention _ and traction _ to emerge early as credible
alternatives to Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's only announced opponent is former Sen. Bill Bradley of
New Jersey. Sen. John Kerry of Massachusetts may challenge him as
well Jesse Jackson. But two senators, who at the very least would
have caused headaches for Gore, will not run: Bob Kerrey of
Nebraska and Paul Wellstone of Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the impeachment episode, Clinton was severely
hampered last fall in stumping for candidates around the country;
many did not want to be seen with him. That opened an even greater
opportunity for Gore, who campaigned and raised money aggressively
and cemented contacts with politicians who are in his debt as the
2000 campaign gets underway.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that the president was, in a sense, taken out of the
campaign and Al Gore was the guy everybody was calling on to go to
this state and that,'' Dicks said, ``that gave him a great chance
to solidify himself with a lot of people.''
</P>
<P>
   Polls suggest that while Gore is still not considered as
effective a leader as Clinton, he has endured the White House
scandal with his personal ethics relatively untarnished. Of
Americans surveyed in a recent USA Today/CNN/Gallup Poll about how
Gore's close association with Clinton would affect their voting, 57
percent said they would not be less likely to vote for Gore or that
it would make no difference; 39 percent said they would be less
likely to vote for Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who views Gore's election as affirming his own legacy,
suggested at a Democratic dinner last month that he would reinforce
the notion that the vice president not be tarred by scandal,
saying, ``As you will hear me say increasingly in the months ahead,
any mistakes we made were my fault.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's advisers are so confident that impeachment can be turned
to their advantage that last week they sent a fund-raising
solicitation _ the first of the Gore campaign _ to hundreds of
thousands of past contributions that portrays Republicans as using
the scandal for partisan gain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will our nation succumb to the forces of divisiveness,
extremism and personal destruction that threaten to engulf
Washington as I write this?'' Gore asked. Saying that people are
``tired of the politics of personal attack,'' Gore added: ``We must
not only move politics forward, but also upward, to a higher place.
And to do so, you and I must win a resounding victory in 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   Impeachment has had the unexpected effect of unifying the
Democratic Party, a turn that can only benefit Gore. Driven by
their anger at Republicans for pursuing impeachment _ not out of
devotion to Gore or his policies _ many party figures in Congress
and around the country have coalesced around three goals: defending
Clinton, winning back Congress, and electing Gore as president.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
