<HEADER>
A7672 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-DEATH-PENALTY-BOS &LR;      02-16 0971
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-DEATH-PENALTY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MASSACHUSETTS GOVERNOR REOPENS DEATH PENALTY QUEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK PHILLIPS AND SCOT LEHIGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Surrounded by uniformed police as well as parents whose
children were brutally murdered, Governor Paul Cellucci set the
stage Tuesday for another tumultuous showdown on Beacon Hill by
challenging the Legislature to enact a broad new death-penalty
bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am more determined than ever to wage this fight for
justice,'' Cellucci said, as he announced at a union hall that he
is filing an expanded capital-punishment bill.
</P>
<P>
   Describing murderers as ``monsters who do not deserve hope,''
Cellucci proposed a law that would provide a death sentence for 16
categories of murder, ranging from the killing of police officers
to murders involving torture, rape, kidnapping, robbery or other
serious crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Although he was unsuccessful last year in his battle to restore
capital punishment, Cellucci added three new categories to his
original legislation. They include the murder of a child under 14;
murder involving domestic violence; and murder committed in front
of any member of the victim's family.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't think of a more cowardly act than to kill a child,''
Cellucci said in explaining that addition. Adding drama to the
event were heartfelt appeals for action from two mothers who
daughters were murdered and the father of a state police officer
killed in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci and Lieutenant Governor Jane Swift, both former
death-penalty opponents, also insisted their bill had safeguards to
prevent the execution of an innocent person. Those include a
separate jury required by majority vote to impose the death
penalty; competent counsel to be provided for an accused murderer;
and a final review by the Supreme Judicial Court.
</P>
<P>
   ``We built in all these protections to ensure an innocent life
is not taken,'' Swift said.
</P>
<P>
   But opponents chose to attack those very points. They noted that
in Illinois 10 people who have been sentenced to death over the
past 20 years and sitting on death row were found to be innocent
and released. There have been eight executions in that state during
the same period.
</P>
<P>
   ``The experience in Illinois should be a lesson to us _ there
have been more innocent people released from death row than have
been executed,'' said John Roberts, executive director of the
American Civil Liberties Union of Massachusetts. ``The same
protections against mistakes the governor claims for Massachusetts
exist in Illinois.''
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci would not say that the safeguards can absolutely
prevent the execution of an innocent person. In the past, he has
said it is possible an innocent person could be executed, but that
it was worth the price to use the death penalty to prevent murders
and provide justice for the victim's families.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's press conference sets in motion what will surely
be a re-enactment of the emotional debate in the fall of 1997, when
the House first approved a death-penalty bill by a one-vote margin,
then on reconsideration a week later defeated the measure on a tie
vote when a lawmaker switched his position. The passions over the
issue were inflamed by the abduction and murder of an East
Cambridge child, Jeffrey Curley.
</P>
<P>
   With a strong majority in the Senate backing the bill, the focus
again will be in the House, where few are predicting the outcome.
The 1998 legislative elections appear to have left the same
breakdown over the issue.
</P>
<P>
   But in the last month three House members _ two who voted
against and one who voted for the death penalty _ have resigned.
Elections for their seats will be held in late May. In addition,
two anti-death penalty Democratic House members, Representative
Emanuel Gus Serra of East Boston and Charlotte Golar Richie of
Dorchester, are expected to leave shortly to take government
positions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be right down to the wire,'' said House Majority
Leader William Nagle (D-Northampton), who managed the effort that
killed the bill in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Saying that anti-death penalty House members were out of touch
with public sentiment, Cellucci called on voters to ``turn the heat
up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All we know is that it is close,'' he said. ``That's why it is
very important for the citizens of the state who feel as we do to
let their legislators know.''
</P>
<P>
   But state Representative John Slattery (D-Peabody), whose switch
killed the death penalty last year, accused Cellucci of posturing
on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everyone understands that juries and judges are not
infallible, and when you inform the public that we have a very
tough punishment _ life imprisonment without the possibility of
parole _ people say that is an appropriate and tough punishment for
first-degree murder,'' said Slattery, who won reelection easily,
although Cellucci went there to campaign for his opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci's new bill would reinstate the death penalty for these
categories of murder: The killing of law-enforcement officials; of
a child under 14; of a judge, juror, witness, or prosecuting
attorney; or of multiple victims. Also eligible would be: murder
while in violation of a restraining order; murder where a history
of domestic-violence existed; murder committed in the presence of
the victim's immediate family; murder by someone previously
convicted of first- or second-degree murder; or murder by someone
with two or more prior convictions which would qualify for the
death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Murders committed while trying to avoid arrest; by an inmate; in
the course of illegal drug trafficking; by a bomb or similar
device; by a contract killing; or in conjunction with torture,
rape, kidnapping, robbery, arson, home invasion, stalking, or
assault with intent to rape are also included.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
