<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-16 20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7673 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GORE-POLITICS-ART-2ND     02-16 0619
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-POLITICS-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: as president. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In an example of the newfound unity at the Democratic retreat,
Rep. Charles Rangel of New York, an outspoken Gephardt loyalist,
declared his fealty to Gore. It is a far more kindly dynamic than
the tensions that festered for years between Gore and Gephardt, and
between Gephardt and Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   There are, of course, downsides to the scandal for Gore. Even if
voters do not link the vice president to Clinton's conduct, they
might simply be eager for a change after eight years of a
Clinton-Gore administration.
</P>
<P>
   While Gore may win marks from some voters as a loyal vice
president, his opponents would probably portray him as too close to
the embattled president. They might find it irresistible to remind
voters that on the day Clinton was impeached, the vice president
pronounced him one of the greatest presidents in history. For all
the openings the scandal gave Gore to help Democratic candidates,
it also made it more difficult for him to develop a message
independent of Clinton _ and why he should succeed him.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the partisan tone at the Democratic retreat, the
District of Columbia's representative to Congress, Eleanor Holmes
Norton, was not shy about reminding the vice president of his
weakness as a general election candidate. She questioned Gore about
surveys showing that he would trail in a matchup either with Gov.
George W. Bush of Texas or Elizabeth Hanford Dole, former head of
the American Red Cross.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was surprised by the question from a friendly supporter and
was a little taken aback,'' Ms. Norton recalled. ``It was a
question he should have knocked out of the ball park. He gave the
technical answer that nobody believes in polls at this point _ not
an answer as to why somebody like Bush would be leading.''
</P>
<P>
   And in a sign that the portrait of Democratic unity may be
overstated, Gephardt, in shelving his presidential ambitions, has
not endorsed Gore.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Wellstone and Kerrey said in interviews that while Gore clearly
has the edge, he is still vulnerable in the Democratic primaries.
The lack of other candidates also could strengthen Bradley's
prospects.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Hauser, a spokesman for Bradley, argued that because the
political climate would ``continue to be dramatic and
unpredictable,'' Gore's nomination was not inevitable and that
impeachment has strengthened the resolve of voters interested in a
``fresh start.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if Gore is untouched by the Clinton scandal, Republicans
vow to tar him with his own fund-raising embarrassments, such as
attending a fund-raising event at a Buddhist temple.
</P>
<P>
   ``As Vietnam was to Humphrey, values will be to Al Gore,''
predicted Gov. John Engler of Michigan, a Republican, referring to
former Vice President Hubert H. Humphrey. ``It's a dilemma from
which he cannot extricate himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Gore's image as a straight-arrow, Engler replied
with sarcasm, ``Sure, those weren't really Buddhists who weren't
really writing checks either. There's nobody who's ever run for
office in either party who believed that Al Gore ended up at a
Buddhist temple for a fund-raiser and didn't realize it was a
fund-raiser.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of Gore's advisers said he has survived the scandal in far
better shape than they had expected, and gave part of the credit to
a strategy of stroking his possible rivals and subtly discouraging
them from taking him on. It was no accident, they said, that the
only long national television interview that Gore has agreed to
recently was on the program of a Democrat he does not want to run,
the CNN program, ``Both Sides With Jesse Jackson.''
</P>
</TEXT>
