<HEADLINE>
UAL CHIEF URGES DEFEAT OF PASSENGER RIGHTS MEASURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY ACKERMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Acknowledging that labor problems and weather have
given air travelers recent cause for rage, the top executive at
United Airlines nevertheless called Tuesday for the defeat of
proposals for a national ``passenger bill of rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Greenwald, who is expected to step down as chairman and
CEO at United later this year, said measures proposed in Congress
to penalize airlines for service problems are not justified because
the US Department of Transportation logged a relatively small
number of passenger complaints last year.
</P>
<P>
   Although up 25 percent from 1997, he said in an address to the
Boston College Chief Executives Club, the number of complaints last
year was about 5,000 _ a number that is especially small when
compared with growth in the airline industry since the beginning of
deregulation in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't create competition by limiting it,'' he said. ``You
can't improve service by legislating it. You can't impose easy
answers on a system this complex.''
</P>
<P>
   The pending bills, sponsored by Representative Bud Shuster of
Pennsylvania, Senators John McCain of Arizona and Ron Wyden of
Oregon, and others would compensate passengers for delays.
</P>
<P>
   Shuster, who chairs the House Transportation and Infrastructure
Committee, has urged that passengers left sitting on runways be
paid twice the price of their ticket if they are left stranded on
runways more than two hours _ and three times the price if the
delay lasts three hours _ unless the cause is related to
air-traffic control problems.
</P>
<P>
   Characterizing the mood behind bills as a
``let's-get-the-airlines frenzy,'' Greenwald called on other
airlines, along with their customers and employees, government, and
the public, to join in a ``Declaration of Cooperation'' to ease
pressures that lead to late flights, cancellations, and poor
service.
</P>
<P>
   Greenwald also called for collaborative support for help in
updating an aging air traffic control system and in funding
construction of new runways and gates at airports that cannot
efficiently handle existing traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Greenwald specifically cited the labor standoff that led to
cancellation of more than half of American Airlines flights for
several days last week, and made passing reference to the poor
response to bad weather in Detroit that snarled Northwest Airlines'
coast-to-coast system for nearly a week in January.
</P>
<P>
   Labor relations have ``always been a tough thing in this
business, as American Airlines just experienced, and as did their
stranded passengers,'' he said. ``We have got to find ways to keep
labor-management disagreements from getting in the way of serving
our passengers.''
</P>
<P>
   United, following several years of bitter relations with its
unions, gave labor 55 percent control of its stock and two seats on
its board of directors in 1994 in return for major wage and other
concessions. That agreement expires in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Greenwald, hired in 1994 as a peacemaker, said
in an interview that he plans to step down when his five-year
contract expires this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
