<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MURAKAMI-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SOUTH OF THE BORDER, WEST OF THE SUN': OBSESSION CRIPPLES 2
LIVES 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Publication notes are at end of review.) 
(bl) 
 By RICHARD BERNSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A fragile vessel is the human psyche, or, as Hajime, the
narrator of Haruki Murakami's new novel of quiet psychological
power, puts it, ``A person can, just by living, damage another
human being beyond repair.'' And when that happens, the person who
causes the damage is forever wounded as well. ``Maybe I've lost the
chance to ever be a decent human being,'' Hajime says as he passes
his 20th birthday. ``The mistakes I'd committed _ maybe they were
part of my very makeup, an inescapable part of my being.''
</P>
<P>
   The mistakes that Hajime commits in ``South of the Border, West
of the Sun'' are not more than the usual acts of selfishness that
people are prone to as they pursue experience and gratification.
But in the hands of Murakami, a Japanese writer whose last book,
``The Wind-Up Bird Chronicle,'' considerably enlarged his following
in the United States, these small gestures acquire a savage and
inexplicable force.
</P>
<P>
   ``South of the Border'' is in this sense a curious and absorbing
psychological mystery set in modern Japan, a probing meditation on
human fragility, the grip of obsession and the impenetrable,
erotically charged enigma that is the other.
</P>
<P>
   The central figure is Hajime, born, as he tells us on the first
page, early in the second half of the century, but he is a very
``average'' person from a ``typical'' family. He is, in other
words, an member of the generation that repopulated Japan after
World War II but that never experienced any terrible hardships. If
there is anything unusual about Hajime it is that he is an only
child when the typical Japanese family has several children, and
that bothers him because other people assume that he must therefore
be ``spoiled, weak and self-centered.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But what really depressed and hurt me was something else,''
Hajime continues. ``The fact that everything they thought about me
was true. I really was spoiled, weak and self-centered.''
</P>
<P>
   In his loneliness and sense of isolation, Hajime has but one
true friend, a girl named Shimamoto (this is her last name; Hajime
scarcely uses her first one) who is also an only child and an
afflicted one. Shimamoto had polio as a child, which left her with
a leg that she must drag along when she walks. Hajime and Shimamoto
have a close pubescent friendship, walking home from school
together, listening to records at Shimamoto's house, once and only
once and for ``a fleeting 10 seconds of time'' holding each other's
hand.
</P>
<P>
   When Hajime's family moves away, even though his new town is
only two train stations away from his old, he soon stops seeing
Shimamoto until many years later. But in her unobtrusive way, she
has stolen into his being, such that no other person can ever be
fully meaningful to him. As Hajime grows up and has adult
experiences with women, including a high-school sweetheart named
Izumi whom he betrays, his complaint about them is that ``I
couldn't find within these women something that was waiting just
for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually Hajime marries, with a certain amount of love but
little passion. Helped by a loan from his shady but prosperous
father-in-law, he opens a jazz bar, then another. He has two
children and achieves a degree of prosperity. And then one day
Shimamoto comes back into his life, a quarter-century after they
had parted as 12-year-olds. Shimamoto is much changed. She is a
beauty. She has had an operation to repair her leg. She seems to be
unhappily in the grip of some dark power about which she says
nothing. (It is frustrating that we never find out exactly what
power does control her.) The rest of ``South of the Border, West of
the Sun'' consists of the unfolding of the strangely obsessive
attraction, the ineffable meaning, that each has for the other.
</P>
<P>
   One of Murakami's skills is to create a vague sense of menace as
his characters go about their business. This menace is linked to
the psychological fragility that is the book's leitmotif, the deep
fissures in the carapace that each character lives within, like a
turtle hiding from predators. It is as if our carefully constructed
lives can be fatally punctured with the slightest mistake, and,
given the weakness and self-centeredness that Hajime finds at the
core of his nature, the danger of that puncture always seems near.
</P>
<P>
   An invisible force seems to invest Murakami's pages, a force
that compels his characters to the very acts that will ruin them.
One false move, or one unanticipated circumstance _ the arrival of
an uninvited visitor at just the wrong moment, a snowfall that
causes a flight to be canceled _ and the damage is done.
</P>
<P>
   None of this is ever made explicit in this book, smoothly
translated from the Japanese by Philip Gabriel, but that is because
such things can never be made explicit. Murakami's narrative style
is as spare and unadorned as a traditional Japanese room, so
seemingly empty that it needs to be furnished with the mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something beyond what can be seen or felt,'' Hajime
tells the wife he has almost lost, and whom he may yet lose. This
is not a spiritual or religious statement; it is an analysis of
human hunger, of the void within. Murakami's delicate and affecting
fable explicates that void, and warns of the damage it can do.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `SOUTH OF THE BORDER, WEST OF THE SUN'
</P>
<P>
   By Haruki Murakami
</P>
<P>
   Translated by Philip Gabriel. 213 pages. Alfred A. Knopf. $22.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
