<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ADOPTED-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BESHKEMPIR': GROWING UP IN KYRGYZSTAN, BOYS WILL BE BOYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review.) 
(HLW) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There are no computers, televisions, hi-fi's or fast
cars in the hard-scrabble world of Aktan Abdykalykov's film,
``Beshkempir,'' the first independent movie from the Central Asian
country (and former Soviet republic) of Kyrgyzstan. And on the rare
occasions when the residents of the dusty rural village in which
the film takes place go to the movies, they gape in awe at festive
images of belly dancing and communal celebration that portray a
life far more abundant than any they are ever likely to experience.
</P>
<P>
   The movie, filmed in black and white, with occasional bursts
into color, belongs to a neo-realist tradition pioneered by ``The
Bicycle Thief'' and Satyajit Ray's ``Apu Trilogy'' that
contemplates humanity at the most basic level. Although set in the
present, the society it portrays is pre-industrial. But because it
is centered on childhood, it all feels deeply familiar.
</P>
<P>
   With a soundtrack filled with the sounds of nature, and frequent
images of the wind in the trees, the movie transports you back to
an age when, no matter how sophisticated your environment might
have been, your experience of the natural world was fresh and
filled with a sense of discovery, an age when time seemed to open
up endlessly.
</P>
<P>
   The title character of the movie, which opens on Wednesday at
the Film Forum, is a young boy who is typical of the youths of his
village except for one difference: midway through the movie, during
a squabble with a friend, Beshkempir (Mirlan Abdykalykov) discovers
he is adopted. The information throws him into a tailspin, and for
a while he feels betrayed and rebellious.
</P>
<P>
   The story of Beshkempir's adoption and its personal
reverberations when he is told the truth is only a pretext for
presenting a cinematic portrait of a stable Central Asian culture
viewed through the eyes of a boy approaching puberty.
</P>
<P>
   Beshkempir runs around with a band of youths who amuse
themselves doing the same things boys do everywhere. They have
great fun rolling around in the mud and pulling risky pranks like
stirring up bees' nests and running. One day, they make a sculpture
of a female form in the sand and, giggling, take turns lying on top
of it and simulating sex.
</P>
<P>
   Their mischief-making instincts lead them to steal eggs and to
spy on an obese bare-breasted woman dipping into a bucket and
applying leeches to her flesh. The primary pre-adolescent courtship
ritual is co-ed bike riding and walking. It is competition over a
girl that leads one boy to accuse Beshkempir of being a foundling.
</P>
<P>
   Presiding over Beshkempir's household is a beloved grandmother
who is frail but wise. It is her death that gives Beshkempir his
first awareness of mortality along with a more grown-up sense of
belonging to his family after he is called upon, according to
custom, to officiate at certain posthumous rites.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beshkempir'' doesn't tell us anything about Kyrgyzstan's
politics, economics, religion or social structure. What this
gentle, touching film shows is a group of hard-working human beings
living their lives and experiencing the same family and peer-group
pressures that apply to people everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `BESHKEMPIR'
</P>
<P>
   The Adopted Son
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Aktan Abdykalykov; written (in Kyrgyzstani, with
English subtitles) by Abdykalykov, Avtandil Adikulov and Marat
Sarulu; director of photography, Hassan Kidirialev; edited by Tilck
Mambetova; music by Nurlan Nishanov; produced by Irizai Alibaev,
Cedomir Kolar and Kyrgyzfilm/Noe Productions; released by Fox
Lorber Associates. At the Film Forum, 209 Houston Street. Running
time: 81 minutes. This film is not rated.
</P>
<P>
   With: Mirlan Abdykalykov (Beshkempir) and Albina Imasmeva, Adir
Abilkassimov, Bakit Zilkieciev and Mirlan Cinkozoev (villagers).
</P>
</TEXT>
