<SLUG> BC-NAVISTAR-VOLVO17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Volvo-Navistar: Takeover talk persists
 &HT;    By Don Baker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SPRINGFIELD, Ohio _ News reports continue to fuel speculation
that Volvo AB might buy Navistar in a possible $3 billion deal that
would more than double Volvo's share of the North American truck
market.
</P>
<P>
   The British newspaper Financial Times reported Monday that Volvo
confirmed it has held talks with Navistar on a possible takeover.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper quoted an unnamed source close to the talks as
saying senior executives from Volvo have met with Navistar
officials to discuss a buyout offer.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen from both companies refused to comment, saying they
don't react to rumors.
</P>
<P>
   John R. Horne, Navistar chairman, president and chief executive
officer, is scheduled to appear on the cable business channel CNBC
at 8 a.m. today in a live interview, but Navistar's spokesman said
the appearance was previously scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago-based automotive industry publication Stark's
Component Ledger reported Monday that Volvo also has opened
``exploratory discussions'' on buying Mack Trucks from French car
and truck maker Renault SA. But Renault has consistently said it
will not sell its Mack Trucks division, and Stark's reported that
Volvo is more interested in buying Navistar.
</P>
<P>
   One possible scenario sketched by Stark's has Volvo buying
Navistar and selling Navistar's diesel engine operations to Ford
Motor Co.
</P>
<P>
   Volvo last month announced the sale of its car division to Ford
for $6.45 billion. Ford has a long-term contract to buy engines
from Navistar.
</P>
<P>
   David Cole, director of the University of Michigan's office for
the study of automotive transportation, said Volvo is financially
prepared to take over an American truck maker because of the
billions of dollars it received in the deal with Ford.
</P>
<P>
   ``They would certainly be in a buying mood, and they want to be
in the heavy trucks in North America,'' Cole said. ``Volvo's really
in a growth mode.''
</P>
<P>
   Other reports said Volvo may buy only Navistar's heavy truck
line, or may negotiate a deal for some kind of alliance with
Navistar.
</P>
<P>
   The auto industry is experiencing the merger mania that the
banking industry went through last year, with Volvo being a big
player.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sort of standard operating procedure to line yourself up
with whoever is best positioned worldwide,'' Cole said. ``Merger
mania is just alive and well in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Navistar's stock climbed $2 a share Friday to $35.25. More than
1.25 million shares traded, nearly three times the daily average
volume of about 420,000 shares. The financial markets in the United
States were closed Monday for the federal holiday.
</P>
<P>
   The stock has seen heavy trading volumes in the past week after
reports of a possible deal between Navistar and Volvo hit Wall
Street Feb. 8, and at least two investment firms have increased
their share of the company _ Fidelity Management and Salomon Smith
Barney.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity reported Friday in Securities and Exchange Commission
filings that it now owns more than 4.6 million shares of Navistar
stock _ close to 7 percent of the company and valued at nearly $164
million.
</P>
<P>
   Salomon also filed a report with the SEC saying it owns more
than 4.1 million shares of Navistar, or 6.3 percent of the company
and valued at nearly $146 million.
</P>
<P>
   Prudential Insurance Company of America previously reported it
owns a 7.2 percent share of Navistar, or 4.77 million shares valued
at more than $168 million.
</P>
<P>
   Navistar employees and local officials were talking about the
rumored deal Monday, expressing concern about the possible effect
on the company's Clark County operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will watch it with anxiety and hope it's for the betterment
of our community,'' said Clark County Commissioner John Detrick.
</P>
<P>
   Cole said a merger or acquisition is studied intensely by both
sides before the deal is signed, but it's hard to determine exactly
what will happen in a takeover.
</P>
<P>
   ``You really don't know what they're going to do until they get
you and then they're going to do what's in their best business
interest,'' Cole said. ``I would be surprised if they closed
facilities, but you never know.''
</P>
<P>
   Don Baker writes for the Springfield News-Sun, Springfield,
Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
