<SLUG> BC-AMR-PILOTS-560&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN AIRLINES BACK TO `VIRTUALLY NORMAL' SCHEDULE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   American Airlines, for the first time since pilots began a
sickout on Feb. 6, reported Tuesday that it was flying a
``virtually normal'' schedule of flights.
</P>
<P>
   The airline and the pilots union continued negotiations over the
issue that began the labor action: how fast nearly 2,000 junior
crew members at American will be promoted as a result of American's
purchase of Reno Air in December, and how soon pay raises at Reno
will take effect.
</P>
<P>
   The union and the company were preparing for a hearing Wednesday
morning before a U.S. District Court judge in Dallas, who will
listen to arguments over how much the airline lost from the roughly
3,600 flights canceled after the judge ordered pilots back to work
on Feb. 10. The union handed over a $10 million check to the court
Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   American, in a statement Tuesday evening, said, ``The airline is
enormously disappointed that no progress is being made in our
negotiations with the Allied Pilots Association, despite the fact
that we have put forth another enhanced proposal.'' Both the
airline and the union said they were not negotiating over the
amount of the fine to be imposed by the judge.
</P>
<P>
   Darryl Jenkins, an aviation consultant and professor at George
Washington University, said the company's revenues per flight
averaged about $14,500, and that fuel costs _ about the only
expense American avoided, since all workers, even the pilots, got
paid anyway _ were about $2,000 a flight.
</P>
<P>
   American said Tuesday that it had canceled 6,656 flights, a few
hundred of them on Monday even though pilots were back at work. The
reason was that planes and crews were out of position. The airline,
a subsidiary of AMR Corp., flies about 2,250 flights on a typical
day.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Murphy, an airline analyst at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter,
estimated total pretax losses at $60 million to $100 million. But,
he said, traffic would return to American, as it did to Northwest
after the strike there last year. ``As long as this doesn't happen
again for a year or two, the public will forget this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The company says integrating the two airlines will take as long
as 22 months. The pilots want the pay changes to take effect
retroactive to last Dec. 23, when American bought Reno.
</P>
<P>
   And it is not just Reno pilots who would receive pay increases.
For American pilots, the purchase creates about 250 new captain
slots. In a game of musical chairs, first officers already flying
for American will get all the new captains' jobs. To fill the jobs
of the newly promoted captains, other American crew members will be
promoted. In all, nearly 2,000 will win promotions _ and pay
increases.
</P>
<P>
   Reno Air's 294 pilots will be added near the bottom of the
seniority list of the 9,300 American pilots. The lucky among Reno's
captains will be bumped down merely to first officers, while the
unlucky will fall to the level of flight engineers, who are the
third-ranking officers on jets that use three in the cockpit.
</P>
<P>
   Despite falling to the bottom of the ladder, the Reno captains
will also benefit, according to the union. ``The senior guy at Reno
makes $72 bucks an hour, with six years seniority,'' said Richard
La Voy, president of the Allied Pilots Association. ``A Super 80
captain at American gets $105 an hour.'' The Super-80 is a
relatively small McDonnell Douglas aircraft flown by American.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The newly demoted captains from the former Reno Air could move
back up to captain if American's expansion continues. A spokesman
for their union, Capt. Robert Collins, said that for some of them,
a more important consideration was whether they could continue to
be based in the West, or would have to uproot their families and
move to Miami to work as reserve flight engineers. ``Even for an
increase in money, it's not worth it,'' he said, pointing out that
seniority also gave first pick of routes and work schedules.
</P>
<P>
   Reno pilots have given up hope that American will retain Reno as
a pilot base, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Integration requires training the crews on the unfamiliar
airplanes, and the airline is planning to train a few dozen a
month, and make the pay changes as the crew members change jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The union says a clause that has been in its contract for two
decades requires that all big jets operated by American be flown by
its members, including the 25 owned by Reno. So even if the job
changes cannot happen instantly, they say, the payroll changes
must. The union once accepted a two-tier wage scale but fought hard
to eliminate it in the last two contracts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our principles are that we are not going to operate a
second-tier airline,'' La Voy said in a telephone interview. ``We
understand it takes some transition time, but in the meanwhile we
want to have the equivalent of our green book rates.'' The green
book is the union contract.
</P>
<P>
   At American, Chris Chiames, a spokesman, said the company was
simply following the same approach as when it bought another
airline, Air Cal, in 1988. ``We had a 2-year transition there,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
