<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-16 20:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7687 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HILLARY-SENATE17-COX     02-16 1057
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HILLARY-SENATE17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FIRST LADY CONFIRMS SHE'S WEIGHING SENATE BID
 &HT;    280&AMP;add. Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After weeks of speculation about her plans, first
lady Hillary Rodham Clinton said Tuesday she would give ''careful
thought'' to running for the U.S. Senate next year.
</P>
<P>
   In a brief statement released late in the day, Mrs. Clinton said
''a large number of people'' have urged her to run for the seat
being vacated next year by Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   While Mrs. Clinton has made no decision, President Clinton has
said he would support her ''enthusiastically'' if she chose to run
and that he thinks she ''would be terrific'' in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Mrs. Clinton presided over a White House ceremony to
announce a request for nearly $1 billion in U.S. reconstruction aid
for Central American countries ravaged last fall by Hurricane
Mitch.
</P>
<P>
   ''Mrs. Clinton, everyone wants to know if you're going to run
for the Senate,'' CBS News correspondent Bill Plant shouted as the
event concluded.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton, dressed in a taupe pants suit, just smiled at the
question and waved.
</P>
<P>
   Hours later, though, she gave an answer of sorts.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am deeply gratified by the large number of people who have
encouraged me to consider running for the U.S. Senate seat being
vacated by Senator Daniel Patrick Moynihan,'' Mrs. Clinton said in
a statement released by her office. ''Until now, I have not been
able to do so, but I will give careful thought to a potential
candidacy in order to reach a decision later this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Until then, she said, ''I intend to continue to focus my
attention on the issues central to the president's agenda and on
which we have worked together for many years.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   If Mrs. Clinton did decide to run, a prime Republican opponent
would likely be Mayor Rudy Giuliani of New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's press secretary released a statement Tuesday evening
saying, in part, that ``he would be more encouraged to run''
against the first lady because ``Mrs. Clinton would be the No. 1
unifier of the Republican Party in New York state.''
</P>
<P>
   First ladies are usually active in some sort of social cause
after their husbands leave office.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Bush, for instance, has worked to decrease illiteracy.
Nancy Reagan holds occasional events to spotlight the problem of
drug abuse, And Rosalynn Carter has been active with her husband,
former President Jimmy Carter, on issues ranging from housing for
the poor to the eradication of guinea worm disease.
</P>
<P>
   No first lady, however, has ever run for a major elective
office, said historian Myra Gutin, author of ''The President's
Partner: The First Ladies in the 20th Century.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The only other first lady who held even a quasi-public office
was Eleanor Roosevelt,'' said Gutin.
</P>
<P>
   During World War II, President Franklin D. Roosevelt named his
wife assistant director of civilian defense, a post responsible for
certain types of home-front contingency planning. After several
months, however, she became a lightning rod for criticism of her
husband's prosecution of the war, and she resigned.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton, who often cites Mrs. Roosevelt as a role model,
has suffered similar criticism, specifically for her role in
Clinton's ill-fated first-term effort to remake the country's
health-care system. That effort, a political disaster that many
blame for the Democrats' loss of Congress in 1994, was largely
managed by Mrs. Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Her popularity has soared, however, as she has soldiered on in
the face of the year-long sex and deception scandal that threatened
her husband's presidency and cast her in the very public role of a
woman wronged.
</P>
<P>
   Wildly popular among Democrats, Mrs. Clinton routinely receives
extended standing ovations at public appearances.
</P>
<P>
   A December poll of Americans by the Gallup Organization of
Princeton, N.J., showed her to be the most admired woman in the
world.
</P>
<P>
   Gallup asked 1,055 randomly selected Americans 18 years old or
older to name the woman they most admired and their second choice.
Mrs. Clinton was mentioned by 28 percent of the respondents, far
outpacing television talk show hostess Oprah Winfrey, who was
second with 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In the same poll, 67 percent of Americans said they had a
favorable impression of Mrs. Clinton, with 29 percent saying they
viewed her unfavorably.
</P>
<P>
   Her popularity has become a huge asset to the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   She made repeated visits to New York last fall to raise money
for the successful Senate bid of former Rep. Charles Schumer. Her
support was regarded as vital to Schumer's upset victory over
veteran Republican Sen. Al D'Amato.
</P>
<P>
   When she visited Buffalo, N.Y., with her husband for a speech
last month, it was Mrs. Clinton who stole the show, drawing a
frenzied ovation and evoking cries of support from members of the
audience, many of whom held up homemade signs encouraging her to
run for Moynihan's seat.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Mrs. Clinton's popularity and the endorsement of her
husband, Gutin, a professor of communications at Rider University
in Lawrenceville, N.J., expressed doubt that the first lady would
decide to run for the New York senate seat next year.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton could be effective as an advocate for any of the
issues involving children, women and human rights she has taken on,
Gutin said, without exposing herself to the public scrutiny that
would surely accompany a Senate campaign.
</P>
<P>
   While Mrs. Clinton has been the subject of aggressive press
reports on her role in a host of issues _ from her billings at the
Rose law firm where she worked in Little Rock, Ark., while her
husband was governor, to her role in the firing of the White House
travel office staff shortly after Clinton became president _ she
has never been exposed to the rigors of her own campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ''She has been treated very differently than the president and
certainly than a candidate,'' said Gutin. ''The scrutiny would be
magnified'' were she to run for office, she said. ''And because of
who she is, that scrutiny would go up by at least a factor of
ten.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
