<HEADER>
A7688 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOBACCO-LAWYER-540&AMP;AD     02-16 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-LAWYER-540&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDS INVESTIGATE LAWYER WHO SOUGHT MILLIONS IN TOBACCO AWARD FEES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Fla., Miss.) (nk) 
 By BARRY MEIER and RICHARD A. OPPEL Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Justice Department has begun a preliminary investigation
involving a Texas lawyer who sought hundreds of millions in fees
for his role in the state's lawsuit against cigarette makers, said
people contacted by investigators.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer, Marc D. Murr of Houston, attracted public attention
and complaints last December at a hearing held by an arbitration
panel that was convened to award fees to lawyers hired by Texas,
Florida and Mississippi to sue the tobacco industry. The states
were the first to settle lawsuits against the industry seeking to
recover health care costs spent on smoking-related ills.
</P>
<P>
   At the hearing, Dan Morales, a Democrat who was the Texas
attorney general, argued that Murr, a longtime associate, had
played a critical role in the Texas tobacco case, which was settled
for $17.3 billion. But Morales' contention was disputed by other
lawyers hired by the attorney general to represent Texas and by
tobacco industry lawyers who said they had barely heard of Murr and
had seen little evidence of his participation in talks leading to
the settlement.
</P>
<P>
   While awarding $3.3 billion in fees to a group of Texas law
firms, the arbitration panel held that Murr deserved $1 million. In
earlier arbitration involving only the state and Murr, but not
tobacco industry lawyers, Murr had won a $260 million fee award.
That claim is pending in a federal court in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the current Texas attorney general, John
Cornyn, a Republican who succeeded Morales in January, said that
the FBI had recently contacted his office about Murr. The
spokeswoman, Heather Browne, said that the FBI did not disclose the
nature of its interest in Murr.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he is knowledgeable that they are involved in the
investigation,'' Ms. Browne said.
</P>
<P>
   The precise focus of the federal inquiry involving Murr is
unclear. But several people, who spoke on the condition of
anonymity, said it appeared to be preliminary, adding that FBI
agents had contacted several individuals in the last two months
connected to Texas' case against the tobacco industry and asked
about Murr.
</P>
<P>
   Daryl Fields, a spokesman for the U.S. attorney's office in San
Antonio, said that the Justice Department, as a matter of policy,
does not confirm or deny the existence of an investigation. An FBI
spokesman in San Antonio did not return telephone calls.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to reach Murr were unsuccessful. His lawyer, Roy Q.
Minton of Austin, said that he understood that an FBI agent had
made brief inquiries recently about aspects of the state's tobacco
lawsuit. Minton said that he did not know the nature of the
agency's inquiry but added that he could not conceive of anything
that Murr had done that might arouse the interest of the Justice
Department.
</P>
<P>
   Minton added that the issue of lawyers' fees in the tobacco case
had become a political football in Texas and that people might be
seeking to discredit Murr, who he believed had a made a substantial
contribution to the state's case.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Cornyn announced he had begun an
investigation of Murr over his fee claim. That inquiry is under
way.
</P>
<P>
   Morales, who once worked at the same law firm with Murr, did not
return telephone calls.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In December, Morales, while still attorney general, flew to New
York City to argue on Murr's behalf before a series of arbitration
hearings convened to award fees to lawyers who represented Texas,
Florida and Mississippi. Morales argued that Murr, based on a
contractual arrangement, deserved to be paid up to 3 percent of the
Texas award, a sum that could easily reach in the hundreds of
millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   At that hearing, the positions of Morales and Murr came under
sharp attack by lawyers hired by both the state and cigarette
makers.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen R. Patton, a lawyer for the Brown &AMP; Williamson Tobacco
Corp., stated in an affidavit that Murr was rarely present at or
was excluded from meetings that involved other lawyers hired to
represent Texas. Patton took sharp exception with submissions to
the arbitration panel by Morales and Murr that described Murr as
having a principal role in the state's case.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I asked Mr. Morales what role Mr. Murr had played in
connection with the litigation, he referred vaguely to unspecified
lobbying and public relations efforts,'' Patton stated in
affidavit. ``He did not refer to any `supervisory,' `oversight' or
`co-pilot' role.''
</P>
</TEXT>
