<SLUG> BC-EDUCATION-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDUCATION OFFICIALS CALL FOR PROBE OF HOUSTON-AREA SCHOOLS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: See optional trim, optional ending) 
 
By MELANIE MARKLEY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ State education officials have called for the
investigation of 22 Houston-area schools where excessive erasures
on the Texas Assessment of Academic Skills have prompted concerns
of test tampering.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Education Agency officials say that over a three-year
period, 11 districts statewide _ including Houston, Fort Bend and
North Forest _ had schools where an unusually high number of wrong
answers were erased and changed to correct answers.
</P>
<P>
   The Houston Independent School District had already begun
investigating eight schools on its own last year, but had not yet
reached any conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   Other districts with targeted schools include Clint, Dallas,
Ector County, Laredo, Midland, Pharr-San Juan-Alamo, San Felipe-Del
Rio Consolidated and Wilmer-Hutchins.
</P>
<P>
   Educators who tamper with test results can lose their
accreditation, and schools where cheating is proven could have
their state ratings lowered. The TASS test evaluates students'
abilities in math, reading and writing.
</P>
<P>
   ``As you know,'' state Education Commissioner Mike Moses said in
a letter last month to the districts' superintendents, ``the TAAS
is the cornerstone of the accountability system. As such, it is
imperative that the integrity of the accountability system be kept
intact.''
</P>
<P>
   The districts have been asked to submit the findings of their
internal investigations by April 1.
</P>
<P>
   Several years ago, TEA began asking the testing contractor to
generate a report that analyzes erasures on the TAAS answer
documents. The schools targeted by the state have had classrooms
with excessive erasures each of the past three years.
</P>
<P>
   The state inquiry follows an investigation launched last summer
by HISD that examined excessive erasures in 56 classrooms at eight
schools.
</P>
<P>
   HISD officials, who examined the state erasure reports over five
years, said their probe was started in response to an anonymous tip
and still is ongoing.
</P>
<P>
   ``An investigation like this is very time-consuming because it
involves looking at individual test papers and many interviews,''
said HISD spokesman Terry Abbott.
</P>
<P>
   Abbott said HISD does not want its test achievements compromised
even though the district's overall TAAS scores would decline only
.3 percent if the results at the 15 schools aren't counted.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the public has reason to disbelieve the results of the TAAS
testing, then school districts will lose their credibility, and
that is one major reason why we began aggressively investigating
this last year,'' he said. ``We cannot and will not stand for any
cheating on the TAAS test.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gayle Fallon, president of the Houston Federation of Teachers,
said if wrongdoing is found, however, she fears the district
automatically will blame the teachers without looking at the
administrators at the school.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd like to be real sure that they not only look at whose
classroom it came out of but who really had the opportunity if
there was any erasure leading to changes in the answers,'' Fallon
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fort Bend spokeswoman Martha Morrow and North Forest spokeswoman
Jackie Tolbert said their districts are pursuing the internal
investigations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime we get that kind of letter from TEA, we are going to
be concerned, and we are going to take this very seriously,''
Morrow said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Just last September, TEA officials found that central office
administrators and principals in the Austin school district boosted
ratings at several schools by changing the identification numbers
of some students whose failing test scores they didn't want
counted.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the investigation, three Austin schools had their
ratings lowered, one administrator was suspended and another was
reprimanded.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
