<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CREDIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. TREASURIES RALLY SHARPLY ON POLICY REVERSAL BY JAPAN  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a day of volatile trading, bond prices shot
sharply higher on Tuesday, making up all of Friday's losses and
then some.
</P>
<P>
   The reversal of Friday's selloff had to be painful for many bond
traders and some investors, who had decided the selloff was a
signal that interest rates were moving higher.
</P>
<P>
   The reversal also left some analysts confused about where rates
were going. ``I am still optimistic about interest rates,'' said
Gerald Guild, senior vice president of the taxable fixed-income
department at Advest Inc. ``But I think going through 5.4 percent
was quite significant,'' he added, referring to the top of the
three-month trading range that the yield of the 30-year bond broke
through on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The spark for Tuesday's rally came from the same source as the
impetus for Friday's selling _ Japan, which is infuriating many
investors by making sudden switches in policy.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Japanese officials disappointed investors by saying
that the government did not plan to buy any more Japanese
government bonds. American investors thought this would be a way to
help reverse the rise in Japanese interest rates, which has been
undermining the American bond market by attracting investors away.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Japan partly reversed that decision, announcing that
the government would buy more government bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Another apparent reversal of recent Japanese policy also helped
send the Japanese yen down sharply against the dollar. On Tuesday,
Vice Finance Minister Eisuke Sakakibara said he would accept a
weaker yen, backing away from his support of the current value of
the yen against the dollar. The dollar rally also helped attract
investors back to the American bond market, helping that rally,
analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   In late trading, the price of the 30-year bond rose 1 5/32, to
98 21/32. The yield, which moves in the opposite direction, dropped
to 5.34 percent, from 5.42 percent on Friday. Friday's yield was
the highest since August. In the currency market, the yen dropped
3.9 percent, to 118.65 against the dollar, from 114.05 on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Cloherty, market strategist at Credit Suisse First
Boston, said that while bond investors had to sort out what was
going on in Japan they also had to await next week's testimony by
Alan Greenspan, the chairman of the Federal Reserve. In appearances
before the House and Senate Banking Committees, he will make his
official, semiannual report to Congress on the central bank's
interest rate policy.
</P>
<P>
   Investors will be waiting to see if the Fed thinks that the
current, unexpectedly fast pace of economic growth is worrisome
enough to consider raising interest rates. If that is the signal,
rates should move higher. The fact that strong growth has
foreclosed a chance of another Fed rate cut has already helped send
rates higher the last two months.
</P>
<P>
   But N. Graham Allen, the managing director for global fixed
income at Wells Capital Management in Los Angeles, said that
Greenspan ``is not going to surprise us'' because the Fed is on
hold right now. The central bank, he said, cannot decide to raise
interest rates until they have more information on how much a drag
the recession in Latin American will have on the United States
economy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-99 2033EST &QL; 
