<HEADLINE>
JUDGE IN JONES CASE SAYS SHE MAY STILL HOLD PRESIDENT IN CONTEMPT 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The federal judge who presided over Paula Jones'
lawsuit against President Clinton said on Tuesday that she was
still considering whether to hold Clinton in contempt for giving
misleading answers in a sworn deposition last year in which he
denied a sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Susan Webber Wright of the U.S. District Court in Little
Rock, Ark., said in an order issued there that with the end of the
impeachment trial in the Senate last week, ``I believe that now it
is time for the court to address the contempt issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Wright also disclosed that she had been asked last month to be a
witness in the impeachment trial by one of the House managers, Rep.
Asa Hutchinson, R-Ark., but that she refused. The judge said she
even told Hutchinson that she would file a motion to block any
subpoena for her participation in the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Wright's order on Tuesday was another stark reminder that the
Senate vote last week to acquit Clinton did not end all possible
legal repercussions from the president's relationship with Ms.
Lewinsky and his subsequent actions in the Jones case. Kenneth
Starr, the independent counsel, has left open the issue of whether
he would indict the president on perjury and obstruction of justice
charges, the very same charges of which he was acquitted by the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   If Wright chose to hold Clinton in contempt, she could impose a
fine or try to suspend his ability to practice law. Clinton could
appeal any such finding.
</P>
<P>
   Wright issued her order after a 30-minute conference call on
Tuesday afternoon with lawyers for both Mrs. Jones and Clinton in
which she suggested she was still troubled by the president's
deposition. Wright had traveled from Little Rock to Washington to
preside at the deposition on Jan. 17, 1998, during which Clinton
denied a sexual relationship with Ms. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   But in August, following his grand jury appearance, Clinton
acknowledged an intimate relationship with Ms. Lewinsky and said
his earlier testimony might have been misleading. Clinton argued
that he did not commit perjury during the deposition, however, and
asserted that his answers fell within the definition of sexual
relations that was approved by Wright for the Jones deposition.
</P>
<P>
   But within two weeks, Wright included a surprising footnote in
an opinion on an unrelated matter saying that she might someday
consider whether to hold Clinton in contempt. The opinion was about
whether the press could have access to certain court proceedings,
and her abrupt mention of the possibility of contempt proceedings
stunned the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Her order on Tuesday said that she had put aside the contempt
issue until the completion of the impeachment proceedings. ``The
court did not want in any way to interfere with the impeachment
proceedings then under way which are governed by different
standards and are intended to protect interests other than those
protected by sanctions for contempt,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Wright also said she was free to address the contempt issue now
because the Jones lawsuit itself had been settled last Nov. 13 when
Clinton paid Ms. Jones $850,000 to withdraw her claim that he had
made a crude sexual advance to her in a Little Rock hotel suite in
1991 while he was stilllgovernor of Arkansas. Clinton denied the
allegation even as he settled the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Wright said on Tuesday in the order that she had considered
withdrawing from the case because of the request to be a witness at
the trial but decided, for now, not to do so. Instead, she invited
any of the lawyers to file a motion by noon on Friday asking for
her recusal if they wanted to do so.
</P>
<P>
   The House managers, she said, wanted to ask her about Clinton's
comportment at the Jan. 17, 1998 deposition when his lawyer, Robert
S. Bennett, said that the president did not have sex of any kind
with Ms. Lewinsky. Asked about Bennett's statements later, Clinton
told the grand jury that he was not paying attention. The House
prosecutors argued otherwise and charged that Clinton committed
perjury and obstruction by allowing his lawyer to say things he
knew to be incorrect.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the managers obtained an affidavit from Barry Ward,
Wright's law clerk, who testified about how closely Clinton paid
attention to Bennett during the deposition.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
