<SLUG> BC-HONDURAS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    On a mission of mercy: Custom-made propeller goes to Honduras
 &HT;    By Jim DeBrosse
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ As one of the largest manufacturers of airplane
propellers in the world, McCauley Propeller Systems in Vandalia,
Ohio sends out thousands of its hand-tooled products each year to
every corner of the globe.
</P>
<P>
   But the two-blade propeller shipped out Tuesday to Honduras took
with it something more than the usual care and pride of McCauley's
280 employees. It took a bit of their hearts as well.
</P>
<P>
   Propeller No. 950635 was custom-made and donated to a mission
pilot who has worked closely with the United Christian Center of
Dayton in bringing relief to the Mosquito Coast, a remote region
that was hit hard this fall by Hurricane Mitch.
</P>
<P>
   To reach villages that have no passable roads, Westley Wiles has
been flying his 1966 single-engine Cessna on a wing and a prayer,
often landing on loose gravel runways and in cow pastures full of
ruts. After several mishaps, his Cessna 206, and especially his
McCauley-built propeller, had taken a beating.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Simister, general manager of McCauley, read about the
mission pilot's plight in a Jan. 31 Dayton Daily News story and was
quickly on the phone to his staff. ``We made a decision that day
that, yes, we would support our product,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Simister, 49, is familiar with the logistical problems in Latin
America, having grown up in Peru, Venezuela and Ecuador as the son
of a sales manager for U.S. Royal tires. ``You go to places like
Honduras and the infrastructure is just not there,'' he said. ``We
take for granted, even in a snowstorm, that we can get on a road
and go to'' the grocery store.
</P>
<P>
   Simister said he's also familiar with the generosity of Latin
American people. ``If you need something to eat down there _ even
if they don't have anything themselves _ it's like, `Here, take
it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Doris Swartz, pastor of Dayton's United Christian Center, said
the donation of the $9,000 propeller ``will enable us to continue
to aid the people of Honduras.''
</P>
<P>
   The church's relief efforts in Honduras include the support of a
medical clinic in the village of El Castillo, which treats as many
as 330 patients a week. Recently, the church also distributed more
than 6,000 pounds of relief supplies gathered primarily from the
Dayton area.
</P>
<P>
   Jim DeBrosse writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
