<SLUG> BC-BAYLOR-SETTLEMENT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SETTLEMENT REACHED IN LAWSUIT AGAINST BAYLOR COLLEGE OF MEDICINE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Sacramento Bee) 
 
By RON NISSIMOV 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A $25 million lawsuit filed against the Baylor College
of Medicine by a scientific researcher who was fired in 1995 for
allegedly faking lab results has been settled for $500,000.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, which was in the second week of trial when it was
settled Thursday, had been closely watched by the nation's research
community. The scientist, Kimon Angelides, sued Baylor as well as
his former colleagues who served on a Baylor committee to decide
whether he had faked results.
</P>
<P>
   Although Baylor settled with Angelides, the medical school's
attorney Gerald Pecht said it was a ``total victory for Baylor.''
</P>
<P>
   Angelides, whose brother Phil Angelides was elected California
State Treasurer in November, was fired for allegedly faking
successful results in published papers on the ability of an
antibody to help damaged nerve cells transmit signals. The research
was part of an effort at Baylor to find new ways to treat muscular
dystrophy and multiple sclerosis.
</P>
<P>
   Angelides decided to settle the day after a federal regulatory
body agreed he had committed scientific misconduct and that Baylor
properly investigated the allegations, said Angelides' attorney
James Pianelli. The lawyer said he did not expect the report to be
released during the trial, but said he did not believe it was
intentionally released at this time.
</P>
<P>
   The report, issued by the Departmental Appeals Board, an agency
of the U.S. Department of Health and Human Services that oversees
federal research grants, recommended that Angelides be barred from
receiving federal funding for five years, Pianelli said.
</P>
<P>
   Angelides, who has worked as a researcher in at the University
of Durham in England since he was fired from Baylor, maintains his
innocence but realized the report ``would be detrimental to his
case,'' Pianelli said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have mixed emotions about the settlement,'' Pianelli said.
</P>
<P>
   Pecht said Baylor agreed to the settlement even though it
believes it did nothing wrong because it would have cost the school
millions more to continue fighting. He said a condition of the
settlement was that Angelides not receive any of the money, which
was used to defray some of Pianelli's estimated legal expenses of
$800,000.
</P>
<P>
   Angelides claimed he was fired on trumped-up charges because he
alerted officials about a mistake in a $1 million grant. Because of
the mistake, the grant was withdrawn and Baylor lost about
$400,000, Pianelli told jurors during opening statements.
</P>
<P>
   Pecht said the case was closely watched because federal
regulations implemented in the late 1980s require that research
institutions form their own internal committees to rule on
allegations of scientific misconduct. However, the federal
regulations provide no immunity from lawsuits to scientists who
serve on such committees, and this was the first case to go to
trial in which committee members were sued, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless we find a better way, no one is going to want to serve
on these committees,'' Pecht said. ``There needs to be federal
protection (from lawsuits).''
</P>
<P>
   He said under current rules, any time committee members rule
that a colleague has committed scientific misconduct they can
expect to be sued. He said there are a number of such pending suits
around the country.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the evidence discussed in the trial pointed to a history
of deception by Angelides.
</P>
<P>
   Pecht told jurors that while Angelides was a post-doctoral
fellow at Cornell University in 1979 he applied for a March of
Dimes grant and told the foundation he had a degree from Harvard
and said he published scientific papers, which he hadn't. Angelides
received $80,000 with the help of his false resume, Pecht said.
</P>
<P>
   Angelides' brother Phil went to Harvard, but the scientist did
not.
</P>
<P>
   Also in 1979, Angelides applied for a job at McGill University
in Montreal and once more said he went to Harvard and that he
published papers, which he actually had not published.
</P>
<P>
   He was hired by McGill, but he was told to quit or be fired a
little after one year because his lies had been discovered, Pecht
told jurors.
</P>
<P>
   Angelides resigned and took at job at the University of Florida,
where he was allegedly caught falsifying lab reports and was asked
to resign, Pecht said. He took a job at Baylor in 1986, and the
investigation into his scientific misconduct began in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Angelides' previous problems were reported in Nature
magazine in 1995 after he sued Baylor.
</P>
<P>
   Pianelli said Angelides, who is in his late 40s, will likely
return to the Houston area to reunite with his wife, Dr. Lefki
Karaviti, and try to find a job.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a brilliant scientist, he could work in industry, in a
teaching capacity and reviewing scientific literature,'' Pianelli
said.
</P>
<P>
   Pecht said the jury is still out on whether Angelides is
``brilliant,'' but said ``even if you have a brilliant mind you
have to be honest.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
