<HEADER>
A7708 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LABOR-AGENDA-950&AMP;ADD-     02-16 1129
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LABOR-AGENDA-950&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL LANDSCAPE ALTERED, LABOR SEES GAINS FOR ITS AGENDA
</HEADLINE>
 (nk) 
By STEVEN GREENHOUSE  
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI BEACH, Fla. _ With their supporters among Republican
moderates likely to play a more forceful role in the new Congress,
union leaders who are gathered here for the AFL-CIO's winter
meeting predicted Tuesday that labor would make substantial gains
this year in advancing its legislative wish list.
</P>
<P>
   The labor leaders say the narrowing of the Republican majority
in the House to five votes will give their pet proposals, including
a higher minimum wage and a patients' bill of rights, a better
chance than in the two previous Congresses since the Republicans
took control in the 1994 elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we can get more done this year,'' said Peggy Taylor,
the AFL-CIO's chief lobbyist. ``With the margin so close in the
House and the Democrats feeling so strong and the Republicans so
desperate to get something done in this Congress, I think there's a
lot of opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   The labor leaders, meeting here for four days at the
Fontainebleau Hotel, have put forward a long list of legislative
goals that range from the eminently attainable to the highly
improbable. Among them: an increase in the minimum wage to $6.15 an
hour, from the current $5.15; a requirement that part-time workers
be paid the same hourly rate as full-time employees doing the same
work; the hiring of 100,000 additional teachers to reduce class
size, as proposed by President Clinton, and defeat of the
Republican proposal that would create individual retirement
investment accounts within the Social Security system.
</P>
<P>
   With the Republicans' majority in the House now trimmed, and
with Republican moderates reaching out to labor, union officials
predict that Congress is unlikely to throw them on the defensive as
in the last two years. In the last Congress, Republicans not only
pushed, unsuccessfully, for legislation to limit labor's ability to
use dues for political purposes but also held investigative
hearings on a variety of unions, especially the teamsters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our hope is there'll be less need for defensive work,'' John
J. Sweeney, the labor federation's president, said in an interview
Tuesday. ``Our hope is we'll be able to pursue a pro-active agenda.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Republicans have some sense and want to turn things
around a little bit,'' Sweeney said of the party's political
fortunes, ``they'll be looking for some pieces of legislation. The
question is whether they want to deal with it seriously or just as
face-savers. If they're willing to deal with it seriously, then,
fine, we want to be at the table when it comes to a
working-families agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   Randy Johnson, vice president for labor policy at the U.S.
Chamber of Commerce, said in a telephone interview that unions
still faced tough going in a Republican-led Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``A more realistic estimate of what will happen is gridlock,''
Johnson said, ``although there'll be a few minor victories on their
side, like the minimum wage.''
</P>
<P>
   Labor unions hope to win a minimum-wage increase this year or
next, as they did in 1996, when many congressional Republicans,
feeling vulnerable in an election year, voted for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a very successful economic period,'' Sweeney said, raising
the minimum above the current $5.15 ``is a way of showing that
workers should share in the economic progress.''
</P>
<P>
   Corporate lobbyists maintain that a higher minimum wage will
raise business costs and so cause employers to lay off low-paid
workers, or at least hire fewer of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The AFL-CIO is clearly going to run with it because it's a
terrific political issue,'' Johnson said. ``Unfortunately the vast
majority of economists agree that raising the minimum wage destroys
jobs. But the workers who will lose jobs get lost in the politics
of the issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson conceded that unions would probably also gain some
limited version of a patients' bill of rights. That legislation
would give members of health maintenance organizations greater
rights to use emergency rooms and to appeal HMO decisions, and
would bar ``gag rules'' by which managed care companies limit what
doctors can tell patients about treatment alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   But labor officials say their chief legislative priority is to
strengthen Social Security and to kill the Republican proposal for
privatizing part of it with individual accounts. Tuesday night the
federation sponsored a town meeting in Miami where dozens of
retired union members attacked the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having those accounts is going to end up costing more,''
because of administrative expenses, ``and it ends up taking money
away from benefits,'' said Sandra Feldman, president of the
American Federation of Teachers and chairwoman of the AFL-CIO's
social policy committee. ``And where there are people who are less
sophisticated about making investment decisions, they might lose
their money and be left without a safety net.''
</P>
<P>
   As for other issues, several unions are pushing trade
legislation. The steelworkers, for instance, want tougher
restrictions on unfairly priced imported steel. And labor officials
say Clinton might push again for fast-track trade legislation,
whose renewal was blocked by unions last year on the ground that it
risked a loss of American jobs to countries that did not bear the
costs of the kinds of labor and environmental protections that
prevail in the United States. But Sweeney said he thought Clinton
might submit a reformulated proposal this year to include labor,
human rights and environmental provisions favored by the union
movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the president has gotten the message,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Another issue is part-time workers. Union officials have voiced
frustration in recent years that despite an economic boom, the
percentage of American workers with health insurance and pensions
has dropped, especially among part-timers. Concerned that workers
who do not hold permanent, full-time jobs are getting short shrift,
the labor federation is pushing a bill to require that part-time
workers receive the same hourly pay as full-time employees doing
the same work.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the federation wants a law requiring proportional
benefits for part-time workers _ that is, an employee who works 20
hours a week, say, would be guaranteed half the pension of someone
working 40 hours a week.
</P>
<P>
   In a further protection for ``nontraditional'' workers, labor
leaders want legislation that would extend the Occupational Safety
and Health Act to make employers responsible for the safety of not
only their regular employees but also independent contractors and
temporary workers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
