structure of this predominantly Protestant British province. The
changes are intended to give the Roman Catholic minority more power
and to end sectarian violence, which has killed more than 3,200
people in the last 30 years. By James F. Clarity. (The story has
moved in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   GORE-POLITICS (Washington) _ Vice President Al Gore has emerged
from the impeachment ordeal in a more commanding position to
capture the Democratic nomination than he would have if the world
had never heard of Monica Lewinsky. Most significantly, Dick
Gephardt has decided not to take on Gore. And among Republicans
there is such a feeling of inevitability to the vice president's
quest to succeed Clinton that former Vice President Dan Quayle, in
announcing his exploratory committee last week, proclaimed: ``I
will win the nomination. And I will beat Al Gore.'' By Richard L.
Berke. (The story has moved in ``w'' news file.) With photos. 1,600
words.
</P>
<P>
   AIRFARE-DISCOUNTS (Undated) _ With international business travel
weakening because of the economic slowdown overseas and with more
flights scheduled across the North Atlantic, several major airlines
have aggressively cut their fares to Europe, exceeding in many
cases their previous winter sales. By Edwin McDowell. (Scheduled to
move by 9 p.m. ET in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   STEM-CELL-RESEARCH (Undated) _ In a letter, 70 members of
Congress have asked the secretary of Health and Human Services to
rescind a ruling that federal funds may be used for research on
human embryonic stem cells, the primordial cells from which all the
tissues of the body are developed. By Nicholas Wade. (Scheduled to
move by 9 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
