<SLUG> BC-GROW-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Employee Handbook Is Crucial  &HT;       
 By Peter Sinton  
 c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Question: &LR;  I'm on the board of directors of a small nonprofit. One
of our employees, who is otherwise competent and popular, has twice
committed to large expenditures to help our organization but
without proper authorization. What would a business do in this
situation?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Answer: &LR;  It sounds like you need clearer policies and the
gumption to tell the employee what the rules are after one
violation of the spending limits, much less two.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, you should have an employee handbook that clearly
states policies and procedures, says Baillee Serbin, human
resources senior consultant of the Management Center in San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the employee handbook should state that any
expenditure over $100 (or whatever amount the board of directors
decides should be policy) must be approved by the executive
director and board treasurer (or any board member that makes sense
for your organization).
</P>
<P>
   You should probably establish what maintenance or emergency
expenditures can be undertaken without board permission, like a
broken toilet. If you have no employee handbook, you can call
Serbin at the Management Center, who consults with nonprofits on
their employee handbooks.
</P>
<P>
   You can visit the organization's Web site ( &LR; www.tmcenter.org &LR; )
and search articles in its library. You also can pay $149 to attend
the Management Center's all-day seminar today at San Francisco's
Cathedral Hill Hotel on best practices for managing employees at
nonprofits. One of the speakers is Leyna Bernstein, the author of
``Best Practices: The Model Employee Handbook for California
Nonprofits.''
</P>
<P>
   Online Prospecting
</P>
<P>
   Q: My company has used consultants and rented mailing lists to
target prospective customers. Is there a way to get customer leads
over the Internet?
</P>
<P>
   A: It just so happens that MySoftware Co. of Palo Alto is
announcing agreements today with Netscape, Intuit and Ameritech to
promote its online customer prospecting service. MySoftware's
``e-prospecting'' Web site,  &LR; www.myprospects.com &LR; , allows users to
select a profile of their desired customers and instantly download
highly targeted contact data from more than 13 million business
listings (provided by Experian) and 180 million consumer records
(from the Polk Co.).
</P>
<P>
   MySoftware's new partners are anxious to provide more
information and time-saving tools to their business users,
including helping them find new customers.
</P>
<P>
   It often takes hours or days for a consultant or mailing list
company to prepare a carefully tailored list of prospective
customers. And it usually costs many hundreds or thousands of
dollars. By contrast, MySoftware promises results in about six
minutes and charges from 13 cents to 50 cents per reference, or as
little as $25 for a list of 100 names.
</P>
<P>
   For consumer searches, you can select by geographic location and
26 predefined demographic niches or by specific criteria like
income, age, home ownership, size and value of dwelling, and credit
card usage. For business searches, you can screen by Standard
Industry Classification (SIC) code, location, company size, annual
revenues and other criteria.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of GROW17 (79239 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  MySoftware chief executive Gregory Slayton notes that there are
several CD-ROMs loaded with consumer and business names and
addresses that cost from about $50 to $200. But the stored
information is months old while MySoftware's data is fresh. As a
sign of its bright prospects, the company was the ninth
top-performing stock last year and its shares have zipped from $4
to $20 in the past three months.
</P>
<P>
   How to Host
</P>
<P>
   Q: My business is interested in selling online and establishing
a Web site but we don't know whether to run our own site or hire a
hosting service. Any suggestions?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; A: Deciding whether to build your own site or hire a service
is like choosing the right lease for a physical store, states
Leslie Lundquist, author of ``Selling Online for Dummies'' (IDG
Books, $24.99). She says, ``It can make a big difference in your
customer traffic and in your overhead expenses over the long
term.''
</P>
<P>
   If you are a newcomer to online selling, she suggests hiring a
hosting service. That way, you haven't committed to buying a lot of
expensive computers and software.
</P>
<P>
   You can find Web hosting services in the back of trade
magazines. Many local Internet access providers like Earthlink,
Best communications and Pac Bell offer hosting services. So do
major portal sites like Yahoo, Excite and Lycos.
</P>
<P>
   The YahooStore hosting service charges $100 a month to list 50
items and $300 a month to list 1,000 items.
</P>
<P>
   For a flat monthly fee, hosting services generally provide space
for your site's content files (typically 20 to 25 megabytes),
e-mail accounts and sometimes other services such as domain name
registration, data backup and site statistics.
</P>
<P>
   Before you go with a hosting service, Lundquist, vice president
of research for CommerceNet, a Mountain View nonprofit that
promotes electronic commerce, suggests you ask these questions:
</P>
<P>
   _Exactly what is included in your monthly service fee?
</P>
<P>
   _Are there any restrictions on the service?
</P>
<P>
   _What guarantees do you get about the site's accessibility to
your customers?
</P>
<P>
   _What site statistics do you get?
</P>
<P>
   _What type of security is provided? (Secure credit card
acceptance online often costs an extra $35 to $150 per month.)
</P>
<P>
   If you elect to host your own site, Lundquist notes that you can
find ``a lot of freeware to get you started.'' There also are
inexpensive software programs like Cold Fusion and Microsoft's
FrontPage that help create home pages without having to learn the
HTML programming language.
</P>
<P>
   But unless you have technical expertise and feel comfortable
with Unix operating systems, you probably are better off with a
hosting service.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Send small-business questions to  &LR; entrepreneurs(at &LR; 
 &LR; sign)sfgate.com &LR;  or to Peter Sinton, Grow a Business column, 901
Mission St., San Francisco, Calif., 94103
</P>
</TEXT>
