u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OHIO-GAS-COX     02-16 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OHIO-GAS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ohio enjoys incredibly low oil prices
 &HT;    By Tim Tresslar
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Kelly Black, who commutes in a gas-guzzling 1970
Pontiac with a six-cylinder engine, stops at a Citgo station in the
Warren County, Ohio hamlet of Red Lion a couple of times each week.
</P>
<P>
   When he stopped Tuesday to buy $5 worth gasoline, he found
something local motorists haven't seen since Black's Pontiac was
new gasoline priced at 78 cents a gallon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm driving a long way, so gas means something to me,'' Black
said. ``I'm digging it that it's this low.''
</P>
<P>
   An oversupply of crude oil worldwide has caused gasoline prices
throughout much of the Miami Valley and the nation to plummet. Area
service stations are charging between 80 and 91 cents a gallon for
gas, a level that one oil expert said could hold through the spring
and summer.
</P>
<P>
   In parts of Warren County, street-level competition has is
pushing prices down into the 70-cent range, a price not seen in two
decades. Some Franklin stations on Tuesday sold gas for as low as
75 cents a gallon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost unheard of in these times to have gas that low,''
said Patricia Booker, executive director of the Southwestern Ohio
Garage and Gasoline Dealers Association. ``I don't know how they
can make any money.''
</P>
<P>
   An oversupply of crude oil from oil-producing nations,
struggling foreign economies and warmer weather resulting from El
Nino have pushed down crude oil prices from $23 a barrel in 1997 to
between $10 and $12. As foreign producers try to vanquish oil
reserves, plummeting crude-oil prices have fallen to the lowest
levels ever recorded, when adjusted for inflation. Federal
officials look for gasoline prices to remain low at least into next
year.
</P>
<P>
   For the Citgo in Red Lion, dropping the price to 78 cents per
gallon from 82 cents on Sunday drove up business, said Manager
Maxine Persley. Conversely, she looks for business to cool somewhat
when prices rise, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Definitely we'll see the difference,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In most cases, experts said, low prices strain retailers. Ohio
gas sellers pay 40 cents in state and federal taxes on each gallon
of gas sold. As per-gallon prices drop, so do profits.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not much money to be made,'' Booker said. ``Some of
them are suffering, yes, I would say.''
</P>
<P>
   Depending on overhead costs such as rent, some gas station
owners make only a few cents on the gallon, she said. In some
cases, station owners also must offer auto-repair shops and
convenience stores to bolster earnings, she said.
</P>
<P>
   In Franklin, a price war has erupted on East Second Street as
Dairy Mart and Swifty Service Station charge 75 cents a gallon
while nearby Amoco charges 76 cents. Also in Franklin, the gas
stations at the intersection of Ohio 123 and Interstate 75 are
holding their prices at or below 80 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Billy D. Estes, president of Billy D. Estes &AMP; Sons Oil Co.,
which sells gasoline and diesel fuel to business and industry,
attributes the low Warren County prices to competition and hefty
fuel surpluses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure that's what caused it is a glut of inventory,'' Estes
said. ``If they didn't have the product, they couldn't do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Booker said that while not everyone does it, it's not uncommon
for gas stations to price themselves according to what a neighbor
charges, dropping prices in pennies-per-gallon increments.
</P>
<P>
   In northern Dayton, Nick Allen, manager of a BP station, said
his station's prices have stayed under $1 for more than two months.
The low prices have translated into more sales, he said.
</P>
<P>
   At the BP station in Yellow Springs, the price has topped $1
once during the past three months, said Assistant Manager Craig
McCann. Lower prices prompt people to fill up their tanks and ``get
it while it's cheap,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And in Kettering, the Clark Oil on Saturday dropped its price to
82 cents from 85 cents to remain competitive, said Manager Kim
Pearson. The nearby Speedway charges 82 cents per gallon.
</P>
<P>
   While no one knows how long the low prices will last, most agree
they won't last forever. Mike Kunnen, director of the Cincinnati
Gasoline Dealers Association, said prices probably could remain low
for several more months, which is good for the consumer, but bad
for gas station owners and the United States which will remain
reliant on imported oil.
</P>
<P>
   For her part, Booker hopes prices will stop falling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they can go much lower,'' Booker said.
``Eventually they have to start coming back up again. Might as well
enjoy it while we can.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Tresslar writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
