<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-16 21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7727 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS &LR;      02-16 0659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDWARDS'S KNEE INJURY VIEWED WITH PESSIMISM AFTER SURGERY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Robert Edwards's knee injury looks like a career-ender.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards underwent four hours of surgery Tuesday at Massachusetts
General Hospital, and when it was all over Patriots team physician
Bert Zarins said he was pessimistic about the running back's
chances to ever play football again.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards, the team's top draft choice and leading rusher in 1998,
severely injured his left knee while playing in a flag football
game on the beach in Hawaii two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   The only good news was that, to the surprise of both the
Patriots and the NFL, Edwards has an insurance policy that
apparently would cover what is owed to him on his contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is good news,'' says Patriots vice president Andy
Wasynczuk. ``We didn't know anything about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Zarins, with help from Dr. Jesse Jupiter and Dr. Art Boland,
repaired four ligaments in Edwards's left knee. Unfortunately, they
found that the nerve controlling movement below the knee was
stretched and damaged.
</P>
<P>
   Zarins said the capacity of this nerve to heal and function will
determine whether Edwards will be able to play again. He definitely
will miss the 1999 season.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards began rehabilitation immediately, with continuous
passive motion. That is expected to continue for 4-6 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   It was thought that because Edwards's injury was not sustained
during an NFL game or workout _ but in an event sponsored by NFL
Properties _ that the collective bargaining agreement would
prohibit the Patriots from paying him if he couldn't play.
</P>
<P>
   But it turns out that his contract with New England _ worth
approximately $5.75 million over five years _ has been insured by
his lawyer, Andy Ree of Marietta, Ga., who referred the matter to
Ted Dipple, CEO of American Specialty Underwriters of Woburn, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a policy on Edwards but I can't reveal how much it is
for,'' said Dipple said Tuesday. ``That's all I can say on the
policy, but I will say that the NFL should have insured that game
that Edwards played in and they wouldn't have had to worry about
any of these problems. For not a lot of money, they could have
insured Edwards and all of the other players in that game against
injury.''
</P>
<P>
   Edwards signed a release with NFL Properties that absolved it of
liability in case of injury. The flag football game, featuring top
NFL rookies, has been part of Pro Bowl festivities in Hawaii for
the last three years.
</P>
<P>
   When he signed with New England last spring, Edwards received a
bonus of approximately $2 million, collecting $1 million up front.
Even though they don't have to do so, the Patriots will send him a
check in the near future for another $1 million to complete the
bonus.
</P>
<P>
   The speculation is that Edwards's attorney took out a $2 million
policy against disability in case Edwards was injured away from
football. So even if he cannot play again, it appears that he would
be able to collect, tax free, that amount of money, which is just
about what he would make, after taxes, in the remaining four years
of his Patriots contract.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards's contractual agents, Terris Harris and Allan Wade, did
not return phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   NFL commissioner Paul Tagliabue was upset that Edwards was hurt
in the event and might have blown millions of dollars in the
process.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were unaware that he had some insurance, which is the good
news,'' said an NFL spokesman, ``but we are still very concerned
about Robert Edwards and his future. The matter of these kinds of
games are still under review.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots, who recently lost two key players in free agency _
center Dave Wohlabaugh and punter Tom Tupa _ brought in Green Bay
nose tackle Bob Kuberski and Cincinnati punter Lee Johnson to
Foxborough Tuesday for exploratory talks.
</P>
</TEXT>
