<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MICROSOFT TESTIMONY ATTACKED ON SEVERAL FRONTS
</P>
<P>
   At Microsoft's antitrust trial, a government lawyer attacked the
testimony of Brad Chase, the company's senior marketing executive,
on multiple fronts, and at times the witness's explanations seemed
to cause even the judge to question his credibility. During his two
days on the witness stand, Chase tried to hammer home one central
point: Microsoft's decision to bundle a Web browser with the
Windows operating system was not anticompetitive because
alternative browsers are easily available. The government argued
that the company's browser was gaining market share only because it
was bundled with Windows.
</P>
<P>
   FUND CREATED FOR VICTIMS OF NAZIS
</P>
<P>
   Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder of Germany announced the creation
of a fund, projected to amount to $1.7 billion, financed by 12
German companies to compensate victims of the Nazis. The companies
that announced their participation in the fund were
DaimlerChrysler, Deutsche Bank, Siemens, Volkswagen, Hoechst,
Dresdner Bank, Krupp, Allianz, BASF, Bayer, BMW and Degussa.
</P>
<P>
   HEWLETT POSTS MIXED RESULTS
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard reported mixed financial results, with
first-quarter earnings well above Wall Street estimates, but both
revenues and orders below expectations. For the quarter, which
ended Jan. 31, Hewlett-Packard reported earnings of $960 million,
or 92 cents a share, up 3.3 percent from $929 million, or 86 cents
a share, in the period a year earlier. Revenue rose 1 percent, to
$11.94 billion. Earnings were released after the markets closed.
The company's shares fell $5.9375, to $70.50.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq Computer acquired Zip2, a privately held company that
helps newspapers develop city directory-type Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   DELTA TO BUY REST OF SMALL CARRIER
</P>
<P>
   Delta Air Lines plans to pay $700 million to acquire the part of
Atlantic Southeast Airlines that it does not own in a deal with the
potential for labor problems similar to those that recently
disrupted American Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   WAL-MART EARNINGS RISE 21%
</P>
<P>
   Fourth-quarter earnings at Wal-Mart Stores rose a
better-than-expected 21 percent as the retailer continued to
attract shoppers with its affordable prices and wide selection.
</P>
<P>
   STOCKS MIXED; DOW UP 22 POINTS
</P>
<P>
   Stocks were mixed as Dell Computer fell for a second session,
but a bond rally lifted financial companies. The Dow industrials
rose 22.14 points, or two-tenths of a percent, to 9,297.03. The S&AMP;P
500 rose 11.74 points, or nearly 1 percent, to 1,241.87. Nasdaq
fell 8.02 points, or three-tenths of a percent, to 2,313.87,
erasing a 46-point gain.
</P>
<P>
   In a day of volatile trading, bond prices shot sharply higher,
making up all of Friday's losses and then some.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET INDIFFERENT TO JAPAN MOVE
</P>
<P>
   Japanese bond yields declined slightly while the yen fell
noticeably after Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa announced that
the Government would resume buying a small amount of the bonds it
issues. But the move failed to quell general concerns over the bond
market and rising long-term interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   XL CAPITAL TO BUY NAC RE
</P>
<P>
   XL Capital, one of the leaders in providing insurance against
huge corporate losses, announced that it was buying Nac Re, an
insurer in Greenwich, Conn., greatly expanding its reach into the
U.S. market.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-99 2103EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
