<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990216.0383 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-16 21:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7737 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OHIO-DEATHPENALTY-COX     02-16 0597
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OHIO-DEATHPENALTY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Governor asked to spare life of death row inmate
 &HT;    By Tom Beyerlein
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ If Wilford Berry is put to death Friday, Ohio
will have assisted in a mentally ill person's suicide, according to
an advocacy group which on Tuesday asked Gov. Bob Taft to spare the
life of the condemned killer known as The Volunteer.
</P>
<P>
   As the National Alliance for the Mentally Ill urged Taft not to
become an ``accessory to suicide,'' a bipartisan group of 11
lawmakers, including state Sen. Rhine McLin, D-Dayton, met with the
new governor in a separate bid to convince him to commute Berry's
death sentence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just feel with all the questions about Berry's competency,
his mental illness, there's enough doubt to commute his death
sentence to life in prison without the possibility of parole,''
said Sen. Mark Mallory, D-Cincinnati. ``Whether we convinced (Taft)
remains to be seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Taft spokesman Scott Milburn said the governor is ``watching
this thing unfold in the courts'' as he mulls whether to commute
Berry's sentence. Taft on Tuesday also spoke with the
brother-in-law of Berry's victim, who supports the execution.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Taft) is taking a very thoughtful look at it,'' Milburn
said. ``He's a death penalty supporter, but he takes the
commutation authority very seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Alliance for the Mentally Ill doesn't have a
position on the death penalty, but ``opposes the execution of
someone with a biological brain disorder,'' said Terry Russell, the
group's Ohio executive director.
</P>
<P>
   Berry, 36, of Cleveland, who triedto kill himself at age 9 and
was physically and sexually abused as a child, has been diagnosed
with schizophrenia but has also been found legally competent in the
1989 robbery-murder of his boss, baker Charles Mitroff Jr.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't believe the state of Ohio should be assisting in Mr.
Berry's wish to die, which is a symptom of his disorder,'' Russell
said. ``We're not suggesting in any way he shouldn't be responsible
for his crime. We just believe the state shouldn't be putting a
mentally ill person to death.''
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Taft, national NAMI Executive Director Laurie
Flynn likened Berry to Unabomber Theodore Kaczynski, a mentally ill
killer who escaped the death penalty. ``Mr. Berry may lack a Ph.
D., as well as Mr. Kaczynski's national notoriety, but the
principle is the same. He should not be executed.''
</P>
<P>
   Berry, called The Volunteer because he forfeited his rights to
legal appeals, is to become the first person to be executed in Ohio
in more than 35 years when he receives a lethal injection at 9 p.m.
Friday at the Southern Ohio Correctional Facility at Lucasville. He
says he prefers death to life in prison. His scheduled execution
last March was halted by an 11th-hour stay.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. 6th Circuit Court of Appeals is considering a plea by
public defenders to again stop the execution so Berry can get a new
mental competency hearing on the grounds that he suffered brain
damage in a September 1997 riot on death row at Mansfield
Correctional Institution.
</P>
<P>
   If that effort fails, the public defender plans to file a
last-moment lawsuit in Cuyahoga County Common Pleas Court, where
Berry was convicted. The appeal would cite a 1986 U.S. Supreme
Court ruling that found it unconstitutional to execute a person who
didn't understand why he was being put to death.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Beyerlein writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
