<SLUG> BC-POTATO-CANCER-CURE-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAKED POTATOES WARD OFF CANCER  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This intriguing 250-word ``separate buy'' article is from The
Independent newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 1-800-444-0267, or fax us at
1-816-822-1444.)  
  
 By JEREMY LAURANCE  
 c.1999 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ International medical experts rallied to the cause of
the baked potato as one of the most effective defenses against
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   They were challenging a U.S. study that suggested dietary fiber,
found in abundance in potatoes with skins and in other vegetables,
failed to protect against bowel cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon McVie, director general of the Cancer Research Campaign,
said Tuesday the study of 89,000 nurses in the New England Journal
of Medicine last month was not representative of the general
population.
</P>
<P>
   ``The New England Journal paper does not change the message. A
high-fiber, low-fat diet protects against bowel cancer.''
</P>
<P>
   The study contradicted the accepted wisdom of the benefits of
fiber. The U.S. researchers said cancer was as common in women,
regardless of how much fiber they ate.
</P>
<P>
   But Professor McVie reviewed the research on fiber and cancer,
and said the overwhelming evidence supports the benefits of a
high-fiber diet, which can also reduce the risk of heart disease,
high-blood pressure and non-insulin-dependent diabetes.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 39 studies on fiber and cancer, most showed it had a
protective effect. The latest research, in the European Journal of
Cancer Prevention, was further proof of the benefits of fiber, he
added.
</P>
<P>
   Professor McVie said more research was needed but the
recommended intake of 18 to 20 grams of fiber, or five portions of
fruit and vegetables a day, still stands.
</P>
<P>
   Ten slices of wholemeal bread, 18 bananas, four baked potatoes
or 64 wholemeal crackers contain the suggested daily allowance of
fiber but Professor McVie suggested a variety of fiber-rich foods
to keep cancer at bay. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
