<HEADER>
A7743 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OXYGEN-BAR-HANGOVER-I     02-16 1138
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OXYGEN-BAR-HANGOVER-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRENDY `OXYGEN BARS': FULL OF HOT AIR?  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: California)   (This lively 950-word ``separate buy'' article is from The
Independent newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 1-800-444-0267, or fax us at
1-816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``l'' lifestyle news and ``a'' domestic/general news files.)  
  
 By ANDREW GUMBEL  
 c.1999 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Feeling lacklustre? Prone to allergies or
headaches? Well here, at least according to the latest medical
health-kick fad in America, is the reason: you aren't getting
enough oxygen.
</P>
<P>
   ``In prehistoric times, before we started deforesting the
planet, 30 percent of the air was oxygen. Now the average is around
21 percent and in cities like Los Angeles it is as low as 12 to 14
percent. That leads to disease and fatigue,'' explains John Wood, a
vegan chef who considers himself something of an expert on the
subject.
</P>
<P>
   As indeed he should. Wood is the general manager of a trendy new
``oxygen bar'' on Hollywood's Sunset Strip where, for $13 a pop,
customers are invited to insert a plastic canula tube up their
noses and spend 20 minutes breathing a cocktail of ``oxygen rich''
air, fruit flavorings and aromatherapy oils with names like
Clarity, Passion and Joy.
</P>
<P>
   To judge by the queues snaking around the corner from his
establishment on weekend nights, the concept is catching on.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a company called Rose Creek Health Products recently
took out full-page ads in ``USA Today'' for a product called
Vitamin O. O stands for oxygen, and the product _ a liquid to be
taken in drop form _ claims to add the oxygen to your system that
simple breathing cannot provide.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your bloodstream absorbs the Vitamin O and carries the pure
oxygen straight to your cells and tissues,'' the ad explained.
``There, it maximizes your nutrients, purifies your bloodstream and
eliminates toxins and poisons.''
</P>
<P>
   It sounds so simple it is almost brilliant. ``There's not enough
oxygen in the air in big cities, or in northern latitudes in
wintertime, because there is no grass producing oxygen or leaves on
the trees,'' said Rose Creek's president Don Smith.
</P>
<P>
   His company has been selling 50,000 vials of Vitamin O per
month, and he swears he has received testimonials from grateful
customers, young and old, who have enjoyed relief from conditions
such as wheezing and achiness.
</P>
<P>
   Richard DeAndrea, a Los Angeles doctor and part-owner of the O2
oxygen bar, makes even more grandiose claims: ``Studies have shown
oxygen to be beneficial in fighting cancer, heart disease, chronic
fatigue and migraine headaches. Oxygen may even slow the aging
process.''
</P>
<P>
   So is this the great medical breakthrough we have all been
waiting for, or a load of baloney?
</P>
<P>
   According to Bob Park, a physics professor at the University of
Maryland who specializes in debunking pseudoscience, the makers of
Vitamin O blow their own gaffe when they admit in their adverts
that their product contains ``a liquid solution of sodium chloride
and distilled water.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They tell people exactly what they are buying,'' he says,
``ordinary salt water.''
</P>
<P>
   No wonder the company claims Vitamin O is ``so safe you can drop
it in your eye.'' Whether it is worth $40 for a four-ounce vial,
though, is open to question.
</P>
<P>
   Is it not possible that the water has been oxygen-enhanced? It
is possible, acknowledges Professor Park, but to extract the oxygen
the consumer would need gills. ``You get more oxygen from a single
deep breath than from a daily dose of Vitamin O,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Your correspondent was too tightfisted to try Vitamin O for
himself, but he did venture to the O2 bar on Sunset Strip, where
the oxygen is consumed on a long circular banquette adorned with
brightly colored cushions.
</P>
<P>
   Behind hang an array of metal flexi-tubes which transport the
oxygen down into flavored aromatic water and up into your nose.
</P>
<P>
   The whole thing looks and feels like an opium den, except that
the merest trace of vice has been erased.
</P>
<P>
   O2 _ which curiously is co-owned by Hollywood bad boy Woody
Harrelson _ is so pure it serves no alcohol, and its restaurant
offers only uncooked vegan food.
</P>
<P>
   Oxygen bars did not start in California, but made their way here
via Tokyo and Toronto, where they are also popular.
</P>
<P>
   If there are not more of them in the United States it is partly
because of federal restrictions on natural gases in places of
public entertainment _ hence, despite numerous efforts, no oxygen
bars in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   So who frequents them? According to O2 staff members, the oxygen
treatment is popular not just with health freaks but also with
high-spirited customers from the Red Rock bar next door, who come
in at the end of a boozy night to sober up and hope they can stave
off a hangover.
</P>
<P>
   With the canula inserted up my nose and a steady stream of
Clarity-flavored oxygen whooshing into my system, I asked the
manager, John Wood, whether the gas comes straight from a tank or
is purified in-house.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not oxygen, it's oxygen-rich air,'' he explained, a
little cagily. Street air is passed through a custom-built filter
to make it purer. How much purer? He wouldn't say, for fear that
any claim might be challenged in court by some smartipants
customer.
</P>
<P>
   How did he or Dr. DeAndrea know the oxygen was so beneficial?
Again, he looked sheepish and acknowledged that part of the
phenomenon was a ``placebo effect'' _ people feeling better because
they want to.
</P>
<P>
   Along with my companion, I walked out into the maelstrom of West
Hollywood feeling slightly giddy, not unlike the sensation of
having breathed in exhaust fumes. Within minutes, both of us felt
an oncoming headache.
</P>
<P>
   The bar's slogan is ``Eat _ Drink _ Breathe _ Love!'' Fine
sentiments, but I'm not sure I'll be rushing back for more. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 950-word article, it must be purchased from the
New York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 1-800-444-0267, or fax us at
1-816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
