<HEADER>
A7745 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SINISTER-MUZAK-700&AMP;ad     02-16 1077
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SINISTER-MUZAK-700&AMP;add-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUZAK, AN UNSTOPPABLE FORCE  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Seattle and Boston)   (This entertaining 700-word ``separate buy'' article is from The
Independent newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 1-800-444-0267, or fax us at
1-816-822-1444.)  
  
 (ATTN. EDITORS: For those desiring a shorter version, this article
stands in 700 words; total uncut version is 850 words.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By ANDREW MARSHALL  
 c.1999 The Independent, London  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It came into our building here in Washington a few
months ago, and at first I barely noticed it. But it was always
there, somewhere, floating in the air just out of reach.
</P>
<P>
   It is music. Or rather, it is muzak, for there is a difference.
</P>
<P>
   Muzak should properly be given a capital M. As well as being a
generic term, it is also a large and thriving company based in
Seattle, in the fashionable Pacific Northwest of the U.S., with
revenues of about $100 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
   It pumps out its product via satellite feeds to thousands of
businesses across America every day, broadcasting 60 different
programs, of which only one is now classic ``background music.''
</P>
<P>
   It has its origins way back in the 1920s, when a military
officer was trying his hand at the new science of telephony.
</P>
<P>
   General George Squiers was a formidable character, who
experimented with radio in 1897, only a year after Marconi sent the
first ever wireless message, and was the first-ever passenger in an
aircraft when he flew with the Wright Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   He helped to create two of the most powerful instruments of
American global domination: the United States Air Force, and Muzak.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Squiers formed the name of his company from ``music'' and
the name of his favorite high-technology company, Kodak. It was a
roaring success, and it very quickly became the soundtrack to the
American century.
</P>
<P>
   Whispering strings played cover versions of the Carpenters'
``Afternoon Delight'' or ``A Walk in the Black Forest'' as
Americans went to the supermarket, the garage, motels, restaurants,
fast-food joints or the toilet.
</P>
<P>
   It even accompanied Neil Armstrong to the Moon.
</P>
<P>
   When the Americans left Vietnam in 1975, the helicopters
clattering away through small-arms fire, Muzak played heedlessly on
in the lobby of the American Embassy while puzzled North Vietnamese
soldiers skidded about the marble floor.
</P>
<P>
   Much of it was, by common consent, terrible. It was
unimaginative, dreary, saccharine-sweet rubbish that grated on the
nerves.
</P>
<P>
   If that is your mental image of Muzak, however, it is perhaps
time to think again.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, the company had a small revolution, and it has
put the emphasis back on the main product.
</P>
<P>
   ``This company was built on believing in the power of music,''
says Kenny Kahn, the vice president for marketing, and music is now
what it is about.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the programs offered by Muzak these days are what they
call ``foreground music'' _ original versions of the songs, not
camped-up reproductions. And it is more likely to be Nirvana or
Jimi Hendrix, great products of the city of Seattle, than Puff the
Magic Dragon arranged for strings.
</P>
<P>
   The company itself no longer wishes to think about the bad old
days and has become (slightly self-consciously) hip. ``Our goal is
to say to people, we are not what you think we are,'' says Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   It has a whizzo web site and lots of new concepts to describe
what it does, which sound like the sleeve notes from a techno
album. Its technicians are now described as ``audio architects.''
</P>
<P>
   And it has paid off: last week, the company was bought out for
over $250 million dollars by a Boston-based firm.
</P>
<P>
   It will take a long time before the word loses its associations,
but at least people have heard of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to deal with that,'' says Kahn. ``It's better to be
recognized in some shape or another than not to be recognized,'' he
says, paraphrasing Oscar Wilde.
</P>
<P>
   Basically, Muzak is the world's largest radio station, sending
DJ-free music around the nation by satellite and wire. It is about
to start using the World-Wide Web to sell its wares, taking a
logical step on from its earlier use of technology: after all, Gen.
Squier's company was originally called ``Wired Radio.''
</P>
<P>
   And Muzak is no longer a term of pure invective, as it was a
decade ago. Background music has become deeply fashionable, with
the old 101-Strings sound repackaged as ambient, ``lounge'' or
``cocktail.'' &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
    &UR; (STORY CAN END HERE AT 700. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &LR;  &QC; 
</ANNOTATION>
 &LR;  &QL;
<P>
   Not everybody likes it, of course: indeed some people see it as
the single greatest threat to civilization.
</P>
<P>
   A British organization, based in Wiltshire, called Pipedown
seeks to expunge the menace from England's green and pleasant land.
``The right to public silence is one we must fight to establish,''
it says, claiming success at Gatwick Airport and Sainsburys.
</P>
<P>
   It has not been universally popular in the Independent building
in Washington. The property company which owns the block told us in
their newsletter that everyone loved it, and that feet had been
seen tapping in the corridors.
</P>
<P>
   Some, however, were banging their heads on the wall. There were
dark plots hatched, whisperings about pliers and wiring systems.
Suddenly last week, the seventh floor was silent again.
</P>
<P>
   But by Monday, it was back: Muzak is, it seems, an unstoppable
force. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this lively 700-word article, it must be purchased from
the New York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT
