A7751 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEACHER-LICENSES-280&AMP;     02-16 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEACHER-LICENSES-280&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. EDUCATION CHIEF URGES BETTER TEACHER LICENSING AND
INCENTIVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In his annual speech assessing the state of
American education, Education Secretary Richard Riley on Tuesday
recommended that states adopt more thorough licensing systems to
screen new teachers and reward experienced teachers with special
designations and extra pay.
</P>
<P>
   Riley's remarks, made before an audience of educators at
California State University in Long Beach, underlined the growing
concern nationally about the quality and training of teachers and
represented the secretary's most detailed proposal yet for trying
to improve the situation through a change in the way teachers are
licensed.
</P>
<P>
   States are in no way compelled to follow the model that Riley is
advocating, and many have already raised standards for
certification. Educators said Riley's plea could nudge some states
that have been contemplating changes toward finally committing to
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next few years are, in my opinion, critical for the future
of American education,'' Riley said. ``We can no longer fiddle
around the edges of how we recruit, prepare, retain and reward
America's teachers.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his recommendations about licensing, Riley
announced several efforts by the Education Department intended to
improve teachers' professional lives as well as to spur discussion
about ways to enhance their skills.
</P>
<P>
   He said the Education Department was creating a job bank that
would help connect teachers around the country with available jobs
that matched their skills. In addition, he said, the department
would convene a National Conference on Teacher Quality and
establish a National Commission on Mathematics and Science Teaching
for the 21st Century.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Part of what lay behind Riley's remarks were two statistics. One
is a federal estimate that in the next 10 years, as teachers retire
and student enrollment rises, the country will need 2.2 million new
teachers, and education officials will have to attract and hire
them at a higher rate than they have in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   The other statistic comes from a 1998 survey, released in
January, showing that only one-fifth of more than 4,000 teachers
across the country said they felt well qualified to teach in a
modern classroom.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Levine, president of Teachers College at Columbia
University, said that though educators in many states were trying
to address that problem and to toughen the standards for new
teachers, those efforts were bound to be undermined by the sheer
physical need for men and women in front of the nation's
blackboards.
</P>
<P>
   ``States are actually going to have to lower requirements to get
warm bodies in the classroom,'' Levine said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the problem was being exacerbated by the increasingly
popular pledge by political candidates to reduce classroom size.
</P>
<P>
   Levine nonetheless saluted Riley's expressed vision of teaching
as a selective profession with an arc of advancement and escalating
financial rewards. Other educators were also enthusiastic, saying
that Riley's goals were commendable and that his word did carry
weight with state education officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bully pulpit is very powerful here in calling on states to
do this,'' said Sandra Feldman, president of the American
Federation of Teachers, the nation's second-largest teachers union.
Ms. Feldman said the union basically supported Riley's licensing
ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Essentially, Riley proposed that there be three state licenses
for different stages of a teacher's career. Teachers would
initially be licensed to begin teaching; they would then be
licensed to continue teaching after a few years if they passed,
among other things, a peer review process much broader than the one
most states currently use.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, experienced teachers who pursued further education and
obtained extra skills could receive licenses that would give them a
special designation and a higher salary.
</P>
<P>
   Every state licenses new teachers in some manner, but after that
point, state policies diverge widely. Teachers around the country
can obtain a kind of special certification through the National
Board for Professional Teaching Standards, but a minority of states
reward teachers who go through the intensive, expensive program
with additional compensation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need a sea change in public thinking about the value of
teaching,'' Riley said, adding that ``too many teachers are leaving
the profession because of low pay, poor working conditions and weak
school leadership.''
</P>
</TEXT>
