<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-JETER-660&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THANKS TO ARBITRATION, JETER GETS $5 MILLION DEAL
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ Derek Jeter realized a childhood dream in playing
shortstop for the Yankees and winning two championships in his
first three years. To Jeter, the money that comes with the position
has never seemed quite as important as the job. Even if he had lost
in arbitration Tuesday, he would have been satisfied. ``If I lose,
I'll be making $3 million and I don't think I can sit around and
cry about that,'' Jeter said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   But he won: A three-man arbitration panel on Tuesday awarded
Jeter a $5 million salary, rather than the Yankees' proposal of
$3.2 million. Jeter, paid $750,000 last year, will make the highest
salary in history for any player with between three and four years
of service time.
</P>
<P>
   Jeter's agent, Casey Close, offered to settle the case at $4.1
million just minutes before Monday's hearing, but Yankees General
Manager Brian Cashman rejected that and forged ahead, sure he had a
winning argument. After being informed of the decision _ and
delivering the news to the volatile owner George Steinbrenner _
Cashman said forlornly, ``I think George is happy with Derek, and
disappointed in me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a lot of money,'' Jeter said. ``I'm not going to kid
you.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeter's award matches the second-largest in baseball history;
pitcher Jack McDowell was awarded $5.3 million in 1994 and
outfielder Ruben Sierra won $5 million in 1992. The $1.8 million
disparity between the numbers submitted in the Jeter hearing was
the largest ever. The previous high was $1.5 million, set in 1992
when Rafael Palmeiro won $3.85 million rather than the $2.35
million proposed by the Texas Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Yankees officials, reeling after being informed of the decision
Tuesday, are faced with another case Wednesday, when closer Mariano
Rivera is set for arbitration. Rivera is asking for $4.25 million
and the Yankees are proposing $3 million, but there have been
indications the two sides will look to settle the case before the
hearing.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' payroll will be in the range of $83 million to $84
million, and even with his record salary, Jeter, 24, will be the
seventh-highest-paid Yankee player.
</P>
<P>
   Above and beyond any of his teammates, however, Jeter possesses
star quality _ he's personable, a teen idol, and spectacular in
what he does and how he does it. Jeter is becoming one of
baseball's most recognizable figures, an heir apparent to Cal
Ripken Jr., a status that is reflected in his growing number of
endorsements.
</P>
<P>
   His agent noted Jeter's star qualities in his presentation
Monday to the three arbitrators after reciting his statistics. As
Jeter listened calmly, Close presented exhibits regarding the
player's endorsements and the growing number of Internet inquiries
about Jeter in the players association's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   To the Yankees' officials, this seemed a reach. The cold, hard
numbers, they felt, were clearly in their favor. Juan Gonzalez of
the Texas Rangers previously had the top salary for a position
player between three and four years of service time, $3.4 million
in 1994, and he had led the league with 46 home runs the year
before. Close was proposing that Jeter be paid about 50 percent
more than Gonzalez had been. Last week, Mark Grudzielanek, a
lesser-known shortstop with three solid years in the majors, lost
his case and will be paid $1.9 million _ and Nicholas Zumas, the
arbitrator who made that decision, was sitting on the Jeter panel
Monday, along with Gilbert Vernon and Ira Jaffe.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Casey, who had already won two cases for teams this
spring, presented the Yankees' case, lauding Jeter's performance
but arguing the precedent did not support his bid. The shortstop
spoke only once, saying politely that he had nothing to add to his
agent's arguments. Yankee officials left the room feeling they
would win _ though they were leery about the fact that the teams
had won all five previous arbitration decisions this spring. The
pendulum was bound to swing back, they felt. And it did.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Cashman, who recently received a three-year contract extension,
blamed himself. With Steinbrenner unreachable Monday morning,
Cashman had made the decision to forgo a settlement and push ahead
with the hearing; for this, Cashman may well have been the target
of extreme anger by Steinbrenner in their 20-minute conversation
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made the decision to arbitrate this case,'' said Cashman,
sounding like a post-hurricane weather vane. ``I thought their
figure was extremely out of line, but I was wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I consider Derek part of the family,'' Steinbrenner said.
``Derek did what he had to do. Cash did what he had to do, I have
no bad feeling. I'm just a lot poorer.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeter is tied to the team for at least three more seasons, after
which he would become eligible for free agency. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
