<SLUG> BC-YACHT-RESCUE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A RIVAL PLUCKS AUTISSIER FROM THE SOUTH PACIFIC  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By BARBARA LLOYD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The overnight search for Isabelle Autissier, the French solo
sailor, ended with a successful rescue at sea early on Tuesday in a
remote ocean area 1,900 miles from South America.
</P>
<P>
   Giovanni Soldini, one of the French sailor's rivals in an
around-the-world yacht race called Around Alone, fetched Autissier
from her overturned yacht in the South Pacific. She was apparently
uninjured, and is now safely aboard Soldini's 60-foot sailboat,
Fila.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hello,'' Soldini called to race headquarters by satellite
phone. ``This is Fila. I have Isa inboard with me. Isa and I are
going back to the race. Gio.''
</P>
<P>
   The cryptic message early on Tuesday was music to the ears of
race organizers, who had feared the worst. But with the help of
emergency radio beacons and the high-tech signals of a
satellite-tracking system known as Comstat-C, Soldini found his
proverbial needle in a haystack.
</P>
<P>
   At first the situation looked grim. On arriving at the apparent
search area after a 200-mile diversion from his race route, Soldini
did not see Autissier's 60-foot sailboat in the early-morning
darkness. He wasn't sure if she had capsized, or was in a life
raft.
</P>
<P>
   When he saw nothing but open sea, he changed direction slightly
to the northwest. Two miles into the new course, the 32-year-old
Soldini spotted Autissier's upturned hull bobbing in rough seas.
</P>
<P>
   He made two passes by the boat, yelling her name, but got no
response. On the third pass, Soldini threw a hammer at the
upside-down hull. With that, Autissier appeared, presumably from a
hatch opening in the boat's stern. She told Soldini she had been
sleeping, and had not expected anyone to find her so quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Race organizers learned through Autissier's shore crew on
Tuesday that the capsizing appeared to be the result of a problem
with the boat's self-steering gear. The yacht reared up in 20 knots
of breeze, then laid over on its side.
</P>
<P>
   The full story of her demise is likely to become known as the
two sailors head toward Punta del Este, Uruguay, the next port of
call in the 27,000-mile race that began last Sept. 16 in
Charleston, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``The boat suddenly turned more than 90 degrees, and I could no
longer be in the cockpit,'' Autissier was quoted as saying by The
Associated Press. ``Then it suddenly turned over, and I didn't have
time to shut the door.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Very quickly, the mast snapped into pieces,'' she said. ``When
I saw that, I sent the signal because there was nothing else I
could do. Then I began to get organized, getting security material
together.''
</P>
<P>
   Autissier was first over all at the start of this leg of the
race, which began on Feb. 6 from Auckland, New Zealand. While she
is no longer a competitor, Soldini is still considered an official
race entry. As long as Autissier does not help him sail Fila, he
will keep his place in the race. Soldini will probably receive a
time allotment for changing course.
</P>
<P>
   It was a joyful conclusion to a horrific situation. For the
second time in her solo-racing career, Autissier found herself
stranded on a wrecked 60-foot sailboat in the middle of the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   This time, one individual found her against every odd but
technology. Soldini followed a path of latitude and longitude
reports being emitted from two emergency beacons triggered during
Autissier's capsizing. He also had an unquestioning goal _ to find
a friend and fellow competitor lost at sea.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
