<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-16 21:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7756 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-MRSCLINTON-NYT &LR;      02-16 1088
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MRSCLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HILLARY CLINTON GIVING `CAREFUL THOUGHT' TO SENATE RACE IN NEW
YORK
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As Hillary Rodham Clinton said on Tuesday that she is
giving ``careful thought'' to running for the U.S. Senate from New
York, the first lady's friends and advisers warned her that a race
could be brutal and that the easy victory predicted by state party
leaders is not at all guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady said that she will reach a decision ``later this
year'' and added that she is ``deeply gratified by the large number
of people'' who are encouraging her to seek the seat of Sen. Daniel
Patrick Moynihan, who is retiring in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be a nasty fight,'' said one of Mrs. Clinton's
longtime friends and political advisers, speaking of a potential
opponent, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani of New York City. ``Everything in
Hillary's background will be recycled,'' continued the adviser, who
insisted on anonymity. ``She has to think about whether she is
prepared to go through this battering.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats in New York and elsewhere were taken aback on Tuesday
by Mrs. Clinton's statement that she will delay a decision until
later in the year. If she waits too long, the delay would paralyze
other Democratic candidates who need the time to raise the $10
million to $20 million required for the race.``She needs to think
and think fast,'' said Eleanor Holmes Norton, the District of
Columbia's delegate to Congress. ``That is, unless you want to give
the New York Senate seat to Giuliani.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, Rep. Nita Lowey of Westchester County is the only
Democrat to say she is seriously considering the race. Lowey has
repeatedly said that she will not run if the first lady does.
</P>
<P>
   Major Democratic fundraisers said on Tuesday that Mrs. Clinton
would have no problem raising money, and that she could do it in
two to three months.
</P>
<P>
   As Mrs. Clinton mulls her decision, her advisers are making
calls to New York political leaders and consultants to gauge the
depth of the first lady's support in New York. Polls show her to be
enormously popular statewide, at least for now.
</P>
<P>
   Harold Ickes, a former White House official who discussed the
Senate race with Mrs. Clinton just a few days ago, is to meet on
Wednesday in Miami with Dennis Rivera, one of the most powerful
labor leaders in New York City. ``I'm anxious to talk to him about
it,'' said Rivera, president of Local 1199 of the hospital workers
union. ``We certainly are encouraging her to run.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mrs. Clinton's advisers say the first lady must resolve a
number of concerns before she enters the race.
</P>
<P>
   The most important concern, they say, is that she and President
Clinton are already in serious debt and face what one adviser
estimated to be more than $3 million in legal bills. Senators make
$136,700 a year, and conflict-of-interest rules constrain their
ability to earn outside income.
</P>
<P>
   After the Clintons leave the White House, many Democrats view
Mrs. Clinton as the more marketable of the two through the lecture
circuit and a multimillion-dollar book contract should she write
her memoirs. One longtime friend of Mrs. Clinton said it was
unfair, however, that the first lady, who has been the primary
breadwinner through most of the Clintons' marriage, should be
expected to continue in that role after her husband leaves office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why is it her responsibility to take care of the financial
situation?'' the friend asked.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton's advisers are also telling her that she will face
personal attacks from her opponents on her role in the Whitewater
and Travelgate scandals and her failure on health care reform.
Friends say she has little experience in dealing with the press on
her own, and that her relationship with reporters is often skittish
and tense. Numerous Democrats said on Tuesday that the New York
press corps is particularly combative.
</P>
<P>
   One Clinton adviser called Giuliani a ``formidable candidate''
who would run on a record of lowered crime, reduced welfare rolls
and the overall comeback of New York City in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Giuliani refused to discuss Mrs. Clinton's a
possible candidacy. ``I have no idea what problems there would be
in a hypothetical race that hasn't taken place yet except in your
imaginations,'' Giuliani said at a news conference. ``She hasn't
decided to run. I haven't decided to run. I learned in politics a
long time ago that until there is a race everything is
speculation.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Powers, the former deputy mayor who managed Giuliani's
mayoral campaigns, said Mrs. Clinton is ``untested'' as a candidate
and that ``she'd have to prove why she should be senator over
someone who's turned around a city when everybody said it couldn't
be turned around.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter how popular she is now, Mrs. Clinton's advisers said
that she would be making a mistake if she is tempted to conduct a
Rose Garden strategy and stick close to the White House. New
Yorkers would expect her to spend large amounts of time campaigning
in the state, even without a serious primary opponent. (Under New
York law, a candidate for U.S. Senate does not have to establish
residency in the state until Election Day _ November, 2000 in this
case.)
</P>
<P>
   ``New Yorkers are going to give her a lot of latitude if she
decides to run,'' said one adviser. ``They won't count it against
her if she's an out-of-stater. But she can't run in absentia.''
</P>
<P>
   An additional problem, the adviser said, is that Mrs. Clinton
might take positions that conflict with her husband's. ``Let's say
she disagrees with her husband on trade policy, as a
hypothetical,'' the adviser said. ``It will be trumpeted as a big
deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Other White House advisers say they think a Senate campaign is
more appealing to Mrs. Clinton than actually serving in the Senate,
where she would be a freshman and perhaps not part of the majority
party. The advisers say that Mrs. Clinton is very enticed by the
idea of at last having an independent voice, particularly after her
husband risked his presidency and publicly humiliated her by his
affair with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   One close friend said on Tuesday that the Clinton marriage has
been healing since Mrs. Clinton's birthday in October, and that
Clinton is ``thrilled'' at the prospect of his wife's Senate
candidacy. On Monday, Clinton said that his wife would be a
``great'' senator from New York, but that the idea had not occurred
to her until ``a lot of people started calling.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
