<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-16 21:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7761 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NUHN-COLUMN17-COX     02-16 1340
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NUHN-COLUMN17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    15 years ago and 11 seconds
 &HT;    By Gary Nuhn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ It was 15 years ago; it was 15 minutes ago.
</P>
<P>
   The short version:
</P>
<P>
   Larry Schellenberg grabbed a rebound, dribbled to halfcourt and
passed to Roosevelt Chapman, who sent the ball ahead to Ed Young,
12 feet from the basket smack in the middle of the lane. Young, a
lefty, made a reverse pivot to his right and put up a high, soft
12-foot fallaway jump shot that kissed the glass and whooshed
through the basket. The ball bounced once on the University of
Dayton's then-Tartan floor, the clock ticked to 0:00 and UD had a
72-71 upset of No. 3 DePaul that sent an electric jolt through a
city.
</P>
<P>
   The long version:
</P>
<P>
   It happened 15 years ago Thursday, but the memories are as fresh
as the first loaf out of the oven at Wonder Bread Bakery every
morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm thinking there were 11 seconds,'' Schellenberg said when I
called him a couple of nights ago. ``I remember as I dribbled up
the sideline in front of the DePaul bench (assistant) Joey Meyer
was yelling that I was out of bounds.''
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen years later, it's still burned into his memory like the
Pledge of Allegiance.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got the ball from Schelly, I remember thinking to
myself, `This is my showtime, right now,' '' said Chapman, when I
reached him. ``But for some reason, I saw Ed slice into the middle
and I passed it to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen years later and Chapman remembered verbatim the voice
inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember on the foul before the missed free throw I was over
there hacking at the DePaul guy,'' Young said when I also caught
him without warning. ``Larry was on the other side. I had four
fouls on me, so that would have been my fifth, but they called it
on Larry.''
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen years later, and Young remembered his foul count.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere in UD Land, someone can probably tell you how many
revolutions Young's shot took on its rainbow path.
</P>
<P>
   In their careers at UD, that was one of 365 rebounds
Schellenberg collected, one of 338 assists by Chapman and one of
490 buckets by Young. But put together into one entity, there has
probably not been a more memorable sequence in UD lore. The shot
was voted the ``biggest basket in UD history'' in an unscientific
December poll of UD fans on an Internet e-mail list devoted to UD
basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't even close,'' said UD program editor Brett Hoover,
who conducted the poll.
</P>
<P>
   DePaul was 19-1, ranked No. 3, and its patriarchal coach, Ray
Meyer, had already announced his retirement. As a topper, Meyer
considered this team, led by Tyrone Corbin, his best.
</P>
<P>
   Dayton, meanwhile, began the season 7-7 but had won 7 of 8 when
the Blue Demons walked down the ramp into the Arena.
</P>
<P>
   DePaul owned the first 35 minutes. With just under five minutes
to play, the Blue Demons were up 11 and cruising. Remember, this
was 1984. There was no shot clock, so teams could stall; and there
was no 3-point stripe, so trailing teams came back like snails, two
points at a time.
</P>
<P>
   But then, having shown no signs of life previously, UD started
playing as if possessed. Young, Chapman, Sedric Toney, Dan Christie
and Schellenberg made huge plays. DePaul missed three free throws
and committed two turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly it was 71-68 and Schellenberg did it again, snagging an
offensive rebound and being fouled at 0:13. He made both freebies
to cut it to 71-70. On the in-bounds pass, DePaul's Raymond McCoy,
a .736 free throw shooter inserted specifically for this situation,
was hacked and everyone walked to the other end as 12,723 fans
roared like lions on the Serengeti.
</P>
<P>
   McCoy rimmed the free throw and it came out hot. DePaul's Marty
Embry, in the 2-spot on the lane, reached over Young and tipped the
ball back to himself. Schellenberg, in the 3-spot, leapt over Embry
and pulled it away with one hand.
</P>
<P>
   Then it was like the opening of the Oklahoma territory with
everyone on the court thundering to the other end. Followed by a
shot that kissed the glass like a mother kissing a baby's head . .
. and bedlam. Students rushed the floor as if a professor were out
there handing out As.
</P>
<P>
   Schellenberg is 35 and is no longer the 6-foot-3, 181-pound kid
we remember. Now 240 pounds, he is an imposing presence on the
sidelines in his first year as head coach at his old high school,
Floyds Central, in Floyds Knobs, Ind., in the southwest corner of
the state. Married with three kids, ages 12, 9 and 5, Schellenberg
said he has found his comfort zone and hopes to finish his coaching
career at Floyds Central.
</P>
<P>
   ``The funny thing is, I use that play in my coaching,'' he said.
``I use it to show them how important that 3-spot on the lane is in
rebounding missed free throws. I explain how big that game was, and
I tell them how important the little things are in winning games.''
</P>
<P>
   Chapman is 36 and, like Schellenberg, a teacher-coach back in
his old neighborhood in Brooklyn, where he was a basketball legend
nicknamed Velvet. Chapman is a coordinator/dean at David Ruggles
Junior High and also ``oversees'' the school's basketball program.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids have no idea of who I am,'' said Chapman, who is
close to his playing day numbers of 6-4, 200 pounds. ``They're too
young to remember. But their parents know. Especially the fathers.
They'll say, `You're Mr. Chapman? Is your first name Roosevelt?'
And then it's, `Man, I remember watching you do this or that.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Young is 35 and, like Schellenberg, has added to his once
svelte, 6-7, 196-pound frame. ``I'm 253 and I haven't touched a
basketball in six years,'' he said. ``Right now I'm strong into
golf.'' A salesman for ECG Scanning, a medical supply company,
Young married Channel 2 weekend anchor Kathy Hart last October.
They live in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   ``After I graduated,'' Young said, ``I went to Belgium to play
ball. ``This was four years later, in 1988. One of the first guys I
see over there is Marty Embry. It wasn't just that he lost the
rebound to Schelly. He also had his hand in my face as I took the
shot. The first thing he said was, `Oh, God, not you again.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The mystery remains of why Chapman passed the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went over that situation every day in practice,'' said
then-coach Don Donoher this week. ``The idea was always to get the
ball to Chapman. He was so good at creating a shot. When he got the
ball that day, I thought he'd do some kind of dance, create a shot
and either make it or get fouled.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Once I got Chap the ball, I thought we were in great shape,''
Schellenberg said. ``Then when he gave the ball up, I thought, `I
can't believe it. What's he doin'?' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``We all knew we had to get Chap the ball,'' Young said. ``I was
just running down looking for a rebound, and then all of a sudden I
had the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Back when I lived in Dayton,'' Chapman said, ``people would
always be asking, `Velvet, what possessed you to pass the ball?'
All I can say is that it looked to me like Ed had great post-up
position in the lane, and I knew Ed rarely missed a shot from that
degree.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what?'' Ed Young said. ``I was just lucky.''
</P>
<P>
   There's a lot to be said for lucky.
</P>
<P>
   They are bonded tightly in UD lore, but the three do not keep in
contact.
</P>
<P>
   Schellenberg and Young last saw each other in 1989 at
Schellenberg's basketball camp when Schellenberg was head coach at
Centerville High.
</P>
<P>
   Schellenberg can't remember the last time he saw Chapman.
</P>
<P>
   Young and Chapman saw each other briefly three or four years
ago. ``I was driving past UD and I saw Roosevelt on his bike,''
Young said. ``I pulled over and said, `Whatcha doin'' And he said,
`Nothin', going to play ball at the PAC.' That was it. It was just,
`How you been?' That kind of stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen years ago, 11 seconds tied them together. But even if
they never see each other again, time can never untie them.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Nuhn writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
