<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-16 21:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7762 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NCR-CEO-COX     02-16 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NCR-CEO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CEO of NCR on a winning streak
 &HT;    By Laura A. Bischoff
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Lars Nyberg, chairman and chief executive of
Dayton-based NCR Corp., stands to collect $5.8 million in cash
bonuses this year on top of his usual yearly salary and bonus,
which could easily exceed $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   The windfall will make Nyberg, 47, extraordinarily well paid
when compared with executives in other high-tech businesses. It
also shows just how valued his leadership is by the NCR board.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not all Nyberg stands to gain this year. If he is
still with the company in September, Nyberg will receive 149,533
shares of NCR stock worth $6.6 million at Tuesday's closing price
of $44.62. At the same time, he will be eligible to purchase
another 149,533 shares at $33.44 a share.
</P>
<P>
   The stock option and grant, and $5,875,000 in cash bonuses, are
part of an agreement Nyberg and NCR reached three years ago at a
time when the company's future was tenuous.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement calls for Nyberg to receive $3,875,000 if he is
still with NCR as of June 1 and another $2 million if he agrees to
stay with the company for another two years, according to a
preliminary proxy statement filed with the Securities and Exchange
Commission. Nyberg said last month that he is happy at NCR and
plans to stay with the computer equipment and services company.
</P>
<P>
   Nyberg has led NCR since June 1, 1995. At the time, NCR was a
wholly owned subsidiary of AT&AMP;T Corp. that was losing an estimated
$2 million a day. Nyberg, then an unknown former executive from
Europe, initiated a massive restructuring that led to thousands of
layoffs and widespread changes in company operations.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T divested a healthier NCR in a spinoff in early 1997. NCR
languished that year, but made a dramatic turnaround last year,
boosting earnings 1,642 percent to $122 million, or $1.20 per
share, compared with $7 million, or 7 cents per share, for all of
1997.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts expect NCR to do even better this year, essentially
doubling its earnings to $2 per share or more.
</P>
<P>
   ``One should be compensated for leading that kind of
performance,'' said NCR spokesman Anthony Sprauve. He noted that
NCR's stock options and bonuses are similar to what is offered by
other Fortune 500 companies and Nyberg's bonus was cut due to the
company's poor performance in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Nyberg's base salary last year was $962,000. His 1998
performance bonus and 1999 salary will be determined by the
company's board of directors next month, Sprauve said. The average
salary and bonus last year for 14 chief executives of high-tech
companies reviewed by Executive Compensation Advisory Services was
$1.26 million.
</P>
<P>
   Nyberg shepherded NCR through a turn around by focusing on data
warehousing and professional services, ditching the computer
manufacturing business and dumping its old system of having
independent operating units in 130 countries. It decided to
consolidate operations into five global business units run from the
Dayton headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   The consolidation and other reasons has led to the departure of
eight senior managers since late 1996. The latest is Senior Vice
President Hideh Takahashi, who is scheduled to leave March 31 for
personal reasons, according to the proxy statement.
</P>
<P>
   NCR is also asking the SEC, board members and shareholders to
approve an unusual plan to consolidate the number of stockholders,
according to the proxy statement.
</P>
<P>
   If approved, NCR will ask shareholders at its April 15 annual
meeting to approve a plan to purchase shares from 628,000 people
who own fewer than 10 NCR shares.
</P>
<P>
   The move is expected to save $2.5 million a year in
administrative and mailing costs. NCR will pay the transaction
costs, making it attractive to shareholders who want to avoid
paying broker fees. If these stockholders do not want to be cashed
out, they have to purchase more or consolidate their multiple
accounts so that they hold at least 10 shares.
</P>
<P>
   Sprauve said SEC approval is expected this week. A final proxy
to be mailed in the first week of March will detail the plan to
shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   NCR has about 1.5 million shareholders, mostly because it used
to be part of AT&AMP;T, which is one of the most widely held public
companies. NCR shed 800,000 stockholders through two voluntary
buy-back programs offered to those who owned less than 10 shares.
But the company wants to further consolidate the stockholder base,
Sprauve said.
</P>
<P>
   Laura A. Bischoff writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton,
Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
