<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-16 21:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7770 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DRAGGING-DEATH-TEX     02-16 0898
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRAGGING-DEATH-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RACIAL HATRED DETAILED IN LETTER FROM DRAGGING DEATH DEFENDANT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By BARRY SHLACHTER 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JASPER, Texas _ From prison three years ago, John William
``Bill'' King Jr. wrote that white women who sleep with
African-Americans should be lynched alongside their black lovers.
</P>
<P>
   The correspondence to a 16-year-old girl, half romantic, half
hate-filled, was the first evidence presented on Tuesday in the
capital murder trial of King, 24, who is accused of chaining a
black man behind a pickup and dragging him to his death.
</P>
<P>
   King pleaded ``not guilty, your honor,'' in a hushed, respectful
tone at the start of the prosecution's case yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   District Attorney Guy James Gray told jurors _ 11 whites and one
black _ that King was attempting to form a hate group in Jasper
before his arrest. It was to be called the Texas Rebel Soldiers, a
division of the white supremacist Confederate Knights of America.
</P>
<P>
   ``Evidence will show Bill King needed to do something dramatic
in order to gain in their warped world respect for his newly formed
gang, to attract media attention,'' Gray said.
</P>
<P>
   That, Gray suggested, was the motivation behind the slaying of
James Byrd Jr., 49.
</P>
<P>
   King is accused of masterminding the kidnap-slaying. Two
friends, also ex-convicts, will stand trial later on the same
capital murder charge. King has insisted that one of them, Shawn
Berry, killed Byrd over a drug deal after dropping King and the
other friend at the apartment where all three lived.
</P>
<P>
   But Gray told jurors on Tuesday that all three men would be tied
to the crime through DNA tests on samples taken from their
footwear, cigarette butts and longneck beer bottles. Also found at
the crime scene were a Zippo lighter inscribed with a Ku Klux Klan
symbol and King's prison nickname _ ``Possum'' _ and tools
inscribed with Berry's name.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors displayed a large aerial photograph showing where
Byrd was beaten and chained to the truck, where his body and right
arm were found and, a mile away, the rest of his body. His tattered
clothes, broken dentures, watch, wallet and ball cap, discovered
along the three-mile route where he was dragged, were entered as
evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd's sisters daubed their eyes with tissues and silently wept
as Sheriff Billy Rowles, the first witness, described how the
dismembered body was found.
</P>
<P>
   An 18-year-old Jasper man who knew Byrd, Steven Scott, said he
saw Byrd the early morning hours of June 7 walking along Martin
Luther King Boulevard.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was staggering over the road,'' Scott said, adding it was
obvious Byrd was drunk. When he arrived home a short time later, he
saw Byrd pass by, seated in the back of a gray-primer-colored
pickup. Three white men were in the truck cab, Scott said.
</P>
<P>
   King looked on blankly while 18-year-old Michelle Chapman read
anti-black and anti-semitic portions of letters that she received
from King during his 1995-96 prison stay. She also testified that
King had a tattoo on his arm showing a black man swinging from a
noose. King was serving time on a parole violation, after being
convicted of theft in a video rental shop.
</P>
<P>
   King, who Chapman said she had dated once when she was 15,
affectionately addressed her as his ``Aryan princess.'' The letters
interspersed questions about her school life and expressions of
longing with crude bigotry.
</P>
<P>
   In one, King called Jasper a ``town full of race traitoring''
women blind to the ``pride of their race &AMP; heritage.''
</P>
<P>
   On Feb 26, 1996, he wrote that any white woman ``should be hung
along side'' the African-American with whom she had sex. ``White is
right!!!''
</P>
<P>
   From his cell in the Beto I state prison unit, King told Chapman
he would leave prison with his 65 percent of his body _ including
his genitals _ covered with tattoos to intimidate non-whites.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one is going to ----- with a 209-lb aggrivated (sic)
peckerwood covered in skin art,'' he wrote. ``Till then, take care
and stay white and beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors also introduced into evidence the hand-written
by-laws, constitution, code of ethics, and recruiting materials for
the hate group King was forming. All were signed, ``John W. King,
Captain, Confederate Knights of America, Texas Rebel Soldiers.'' No
gays, bisexuals or anyone ``outside the white Aryan race'' could
join.
</P>
<P>
   King's attorneys, who declined to make an opening statement,
were overruled when they objected to introduction of evidence about
King's tattoos, writings and political affiliations. They contended
the evidence violated his constitutional guarantees of free speech,
and also objected to introduction of autopsy photos, saying they
were so gruesome the jury would be prejudiced against King.
</P>
<P>
   The sheriff said that examination of the crime scene convinced
him that he was dealing with a hate crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a brand new sheriff and I didn't even know the definition
of a hate crime,'' said Rowles, who had been office two years after
serving 27 years as a state trooper. ``But I knew someone was
murdered because he was black.''
</P>
<P>
   That's when he called the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   ``Smartest thing Billy Rowles ever did,'' the sheriff said. ``We
thought we'd looked at everything until the FBI got there.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
