<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-16 21:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7776 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GEN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LA     02-16 0819
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SI NEAR THE EXTREME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's safe to assume very few men received subscriptions to
Sports Illustrated as Valentine's Day gifts from their loved ones.
</P>
<P>
   There are undoubtedly thousands of women with enough
self-confidence to allow their husbands of boyfriends to read
Playboy and Penthouse, or let them linger on the latest mailing
from Victoria's Secret.
</P>
<P>
   But Sports Illustrated's swimsuit issue has become the
equivalent of a nakedly ambitious sneak attack. SI presents foxes
in modest wolves clothing, and its latest edition represents ground
zero in the debate.
</P>
<P>
   The special issue which hit mail boxes and news stands last
week, and which will stay on the shelves for another month, was
SI's most audacious effort yet, pushing the arbitrary extremes of
taste and art to the edge.
</P>
<P>
   Start with the cover. Model Rebecca Romijn-Stamos is wearing a
two-piece swimsuit made of small chains.
</P>
<P>
   Move to the foldout on page 12, where Sarah O'Hare is wearing
sand in the places where a two-piece would usually go.
</P>
<P>
   Page 66 begins an 18-page feature on models wearing nothing but
paint. Joanne Gair, a world-renowned body painter, was hailed to
the Virgin Islands to use the models as her canvas.
</P>
<P>
   Well, that's swell. But the fact Gair did her work based on
actual swimsuits makes one ask why. If a great-looking suit exists,
then having the models painted accordingly looks like an exercise
in prurient shock value.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, you can find models wearing swimsuits made of
netting, swimsuits with see-through bottoms, models wearing
expensive T-shirts that happen to be wet, and a model using a few
well-placed fig leaves to show off a sarong.
</P>
<P>
   That all leads to the ultimate moment later in the magazine,
where cover girl Rebecca is seen looking at a swim suit drying on a
line. It is her swimsuit, and, yes, she is naked.
</P>
<P>
   I'm a healthy male who can appreciate the issue for its base
instincts. And as far as the issue itself, I've always enjoyed a
good debate. It's fun to hear people take sides and get all fussy
on this annual discussion.
</P>
<P>
   To me, the SI swimsuit issue harms no one. These are
professional models whose business is wearing clothing that can fit
in your pocket. It isn't a precursor to anything other than
magazine sales. Some women might find it demeaning, but they're
better off finding more salacious battles to fight than SI's
once-a-year leer.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, two of the stories in the SI swimsuit issue were more
offensive than any pictures. One writer began an article about
model Heidi Klum by describing his butt. Another covered the model
painting with a smirk better suited to junior high school. In a
reference to his professionalism, he says, ``I confess that at
times, such as when Heidi stood topless before me poolside, it was
hard.''
</P>
<P>
   But I do have a line to draw in the sand, right next to Ms.
O'Hare.
</P>
<P>
   The '90s will likely be remembered for the way people and
institutions tried to play both sides of issues. Entertainment
corporations in the business of making money now own teams that are
in the business of winning games. TV networks have news divisions
that cover athletes who snort drugs and slap wives, and sports
divisions with billions tied up in sports right fees.
</P>
<P>
   Newspapers are having a difficult time trying to be all things
to all people thanks to the success of tabloid TV, talk radio and
local TV news, to the degree that they sometimes exchange
objectivity for entertainment and perspective.
</P>
<P>
   SI pretends 51 weeks of the year to be the most serious-minded
and credible sports magazine on the market, to the degree that it
views its chief new rival, ESPN Magazine, as a crayon-armed
teenager with raging hormones and a short attention span.
</P>
<P>
   SI is the magazine which published a cover story saying Pat
Summitt was the new Wizard, the best college basketball coach in
the land. SI put a small black child on the cover as introduction
to a story on athletes who abandon their children and have several
out of wedlock. SI posed the ``whatever happened to the white
athlete?'' question on its cover.
</P>
<P>
   (Having read all three articles, I can confide that SI's
swimsuit issue was much better executed.)
</P>
<P>
   The question is whether an institution can have it both ways.
Can SI do a serious article on Summitt one month and trot out a
naked Klum the next? Can it turn a story on rogue male athletes who
beat their spouses one day and paint swimsuits on women the next?
Can it pontificate one week and pander the next?
</P>
<P>
   It wants to. I'm not sure it can or should. In the era of the
10-second sound bite and the loud screech of talk radio, SI's first
paint-by-numbers swimsuit issue looks like it belongs.
</P>
<P>
   And that's not nearly as becoming as Rebecca, Heidi or Laetitia
Casta.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-99 2142EST &QL; 
