   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 2/16/99. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036
or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) HANOVER, N.H. -- Feb. 16, 1999 -- DARTMOUTH-FRATS-2,
2-16 -- Students at Dartmouth, worried that the college president
and trustees are interfering in their fraternity and sorority
system, attend a rally on Saturday. ``They dropped a massive bomb
on the community here, and everybody's up in arms fighting over
it,'' says Sean Maduck, president of the Chi Heorot fraternity.
(Paul O. Boisvert/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) HANOVER, N.H. -- Feb. 16, 1999 -- DARTMOUTH-FRATS-1,
2-16 -- Students at Dartmouth, worried that the college president
and trustees are interfering in their fraternity and sorority
system, attend a rally on Saturday. Half the students at the
college are members of a Greek house. (Paul O. Boisvert/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) NEW YORK -- Feb. 16, 1999 -- WOMENS-FASHION-2, 2-16 -- A
fisherman's knit pullover and leather skirt by Stephen DiGeronimo;
Mary McFadden's adaptation of a Mongolian wedding coat; Cashmere
sweater and skirt by Hussein Chalayan for Tse New York. (Susan
Farley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) NEW YORK -- Feb. 16, 1999 -- WOMENS-FASHION-1, 2-16 --
Brushed wool jacket, sweater and camel wool pants by Oscar de la
Renta (G. Paul Burnett/New York Times Photo); from Betsey Johnson's
collection, a red corset over printed chiffon; cashmere sweater,
scarf and felt apron skirt by Marc Jacobs. (Susan Farley/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) MOJOKERTO, Indonesia -- Feb. 16, 1999 --
GLOBAL-ECON-III-2, 2-16 -- Global financial problems have reached
into remote corners of Indonesia, severely affecting the life
Sambirah, a peasant matriarch. With her son-in-law Salamet's
rickshaw business under strain, she now pawns her sarongs so the
children can eat. ``I can put up with it if I don't eat,'' she
says. ``But the children aren't used to it. They cry and cry.''
(Nicholas D. Kristof/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) MOSCOW -- Feb. 16, 1999 -- GLOBAL-ECON-III-1, 2-16 --
Since the ruble was devalued last fall and opulent retail outlets
went bankrupt, even fewer Moscow residents have had money to spare
on sales in boutiques, despite offers of 70 percent off. (James
Hill/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) BERKELEY, Calif. -- Feb. 16, 1999 -- BERKELEY-KERR, 2-16
-- At 87, Clark Kerr is perhaps the grand old man of higher
education, the president and chancellor who engineered Berkeley's
pre-eminence and that of the whole California university system.
``Now higher education is the engine pulling society,'' says Kerr,
who is in the process of completing his memoirs. (Dan Krauss/New
York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) WASHINGTON -- Feb. 16, 1999 -- DC-GW-EXHIBIT-FLOATER,
2-16 -- A special exhibition of 25 portraits of George and Martha
Washington opens Friday at the National Portrait Gallery in
Washington and run to Aug. 8. At left, a marble bust by Giuseppe
Ceracchi, on loan from the Metropolitan Museum of Art, casts a
shadowy profile of Washington on the right. (Stephen Crowley/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- Feb. 16, 1999 -- WEIGHT-WATCHERS, 2-16 --
Across the country and parts of Europe, Weight Watchers' offices
like this one in Manhattan are drawing a surge of new customers at
a time when Heinz's larger businesses like ketchup are just
treading water. A dud just two years ago, Weight Watchers is now
the fastest-growing division in Heinz's empire. (James Estrin/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) WASHINGTON -- Feb. 16, 1999 -- GORE-POLITICS, 2-16 --
Vice President Al Gore solidified his Democratic support last year
when he was called to stump for those who feared that the president
might taint them with his troubles. Gore, 50, has emerged from the
impeachment ordeal in a commanding position to capture the
Democratic nomination. (Keith Meyers/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) QUNU, South Africa -- Feb. 16, 1999 -- MANDELA-HOMETOWN,
2-16 -- Virtually treeless hills near Qunu exert a strong pull on
Nelson Mandela. A main road splits the town, and Kate Matembisa is
wary as she crosses. (Lori Waselchuk/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- Feb. 16, 1999 -- BKN-BERKOW-COLUMN, 2-16 --
Charles Oakley is returning to Madison Square Garden on Tuesday
night for the first time since having been traded for Marcus Camby
over the summer. ``I know some people been building this up like a
Tyson-Evander Holyfield rematch, but it's not,'' says the sturdy
power forward. ``I'm not gonna bite anyone's ear off. I don't carry
a grudge.'' (Edward Keating/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) DAYTONA BEACH, fla. -- Feb. 16, 1999 -- CAR-DAYTONA, 2-16
-- Defending Winston Cup champion Jeff Gordon climbs from his
Chevrolet after winning his second Daytona 500 on Sunday in Daytona
Beach. Gordon took home $2,172,246, the largest single-day take in
motorsports history. (Tony Ranze/Lakeland Ledger Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- Feb. 16, 1999 -- NY-EXECUTIVE-CHEF-2, 2-16 --
In Christian Delouvrier's dishes, the flavors are familiar yet
highly focused. A good example is the butternut squash soup he
serves to willing gourmands at Lespinasse. (David Corio/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- Feb. 16, 1999 -- NY-EXECUTIVE-CHEF-1, 2-16 --
Christian Delouvrier of Lespinasse putting the final touches on a
dish in the kitchen. Delouvrier acquired his restaurant skills in
France before he migrated to the United States. He has been the
executive chef at Lespinasse, earning the restaurant a four star
rating, since last summer. (David Corio/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) HONOLULU -- Feb. 16, 1999 -- HAWAII-COOKING-2, 2-16 -- A
plate of loco moco. Created in the 1940s in the kitchens of Hawaii
as a lunchtime alternative to American sandwiches and more
time-consuming Asian entrees, it's a homey combination of two
scoops of rice topped with both a seasoned hamburger patty and a
fried egg, all generously covered with thick brown gravy. Thighs,
watch out! (David Scull/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) HONOLULU -- Feb. 16, 1999 -- HAWAII-COOKING-1, 02-16 --
Chef Alan Wong in his self-named Honolulu restaurant holding a
``mini loco moco'' dish he created. Loco moco orginated in the
1940s in the polyglot kitchens of Hawaii as a lunchtime alternative
to American sandwiches and more time-consuming Asian entrees.
(David Scull/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) PRINCETON, N.J. -- Feb. 16, 1999 -- WINE-TALK, 02-16 --
Orley Ashenfelter with his wine collection at his Princeton home.
Ashenfelter is the Joseph Douglas Green Professor of Economics at
Princeton University. He judges wines with the tools of his trade
rather than with the traditional taste-and-sniff techniques of more
orthodox experts. (Norman Y. Lono for The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) UNDATED -- Feb. 16, 1999 -- CALIF-VINEGAR-TASTE, 02-16 --
In tasting 28 balsamic vinegars, Molly O'Neill discovered you can't
judge a vinegar by its price tag or its label. These are just a few
of the vinegars that she tasted and rated. (Michael Rogol/New York
Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
