<DOCNO> NYT19990216.0411 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-16 21:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7787 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STREET-SFCHRON &LR;      02-16 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STREET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 For a Mere $10,000 Down, You Could Become the Next DeBartolo  &HT;       
 By Mark Veverka  
 c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Calling all couch potatoes and BarcaLounger quarterbacks, it's your
turn to own a piece of a Bay Area professional sports franchise.
</P>
<P>
   What's that you say, you're not the Ohio-bred offspring of an
Italian American shopping center mogul? You mean, you didn't ring
up millions running a publicly held supermarket chain?
</P>
<P>
   Fear not. You still have a shot at becoming a DeBartolo or a
McGowan of your own making. All you need to do is plunk down some
cold cash and purchase a chunk of the San Francisco Bay Seals.
</P>
<P>
   No, not a revival of the beloved minor league baseball team of
yore. The Seals are a scrappy minor league soccer club that calls
Kezar Stadium home. And now the fledgling franchise is seeking
outside investors through a private placement.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to raise money for team development, the San
Francisco Soccer Development Corp. is offering 1 million shares at
a buck a share to qualified investors, says the company's director
of corporate finance, Jan Skwarka.
</P>
<P>
   The offering ``is a great way for soccer to get more exposure on
Wall Street, and soccer needs all of the help it can get,'' says
Skwarka, a Los Angeles native who played professionally in Germany
for two years.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, you may not need to be the second coming of George
Steinbrenner (a shipbuilder, by the way), but you still need a fair
amount of scratch to procure a seat in the owners' box _ even in
minor league soccer. The minimum investment in the Seals is
$10,000, and shareholders must earn at least $200,000 a year
($300,000 for couples) and boast a net worth in excess of $1
million.
</P>
<P>
   Still, before you get out your 49er-inscribed checkbook, it
might behoove any potential investor to study the Seals' business
model. And of course, it's highly advised that they read the
offering prospectus carefully.
</P>
<P>
   First, a little history. The Seals were founded in 1982 as a
youth team by Dr. Tom Simpson, who is still the head coach and
president of the franchise.
</P>
<P>
   It's been a labor of love for Simpson, who has built his
homespun soccer club into a pro squad that competes at the
second-highest level of American professional soccer in the United
Soccer Leagues. The top tier of the USL is Major League Soccer,
which includes teams such as the San Jose Clash (whom the Seals
have beaten) and Los Angeles Galaxy.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of STREET17 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  After first playing at the University of San Francisco, the
professional Seals moved to downsized Kezar last year, where its
largest crowd was 3,000. Capacity is 10,000 and tickets range
between $5 and $10, says company spokesman Burt Glass.
</P>
<P>
   About 40 percent of the team's 1998 revenue of $201,000 came
from gate receipts. And you can forget about salary cap headaches.
The good news for investors is that 1999 player payroll expenses
are projected at about $150,000. Players make about $2,000 a month,
which allowed the mighty Seals to eke out a profit of $2,296 last
year.
</P>
<P>
   OK. So, those aren't exactly Ruthian financials. But at least
the organization is profitable. To be sure, the bet with the Seals
isn't based on earnings but on the potential for the franchise
value to grow _ which is a possibility because the 30-team league
has capped its number of franchises at 32, explains Skwara, an
investment banker and stockbroker by trade.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, franchise values will rise as the next generation of
sports fans, many of whom played soccer growing up, begin taking
their families to watch soccer. In the meantime, it's an investment
in family entertainment not unlike minor league baseball, which has
been financially successful under certain circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   With the hyper-inflation of major league ticket and concession
prices, families are turning to the minors as a more affordable
entertainment option, says professional photographer Michael
Christmas, who owns 22,000 shares in San Diego's USL team, the
Flash.
</P>
<P>
   Christmas was an early investor in the Flash, the first minor
league team to sell stock in a private placement, which plans to go
public later this year. The native Brit watched and played soccer
growing up, but he insists that his stake in the Flash isn't
clouded by sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be truthful, I'm just trying to make money. It's a
business,'' Christmas says.
</P>
<P>
   He's not alone. Stan Berkovitz, a semiretired retail executive
from Boca Raton, Fla., is a major shareholder in the Flash who sees
his investment ``as an opportunity to get in on the ground floor''
of something significant.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of STREET17 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  ``I'm not a soccer fan looking for an investment,'' Berkovitz
explains. ``I'm an investor looking for an opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, like any sports franchise at any level, the financial
success of the Seals will be determined by the organization's
performance _ both on and off the field. And for prospective Seals
stockholders, the value of their shares are likely to ride on the
quality of their product.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Street Smarts runs every Tuesday, Wednesday and Friday. Mark
Veverka can be reached by mail at 901 Mission St., San Francisco,
Calif. 94103, by phone at (415) 777-8444 or by e-mail at
mveverka(AT SIGN)sfgate.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
