u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEAD-DOGS-COX     02-16 0521
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEAD-DOGS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    3 greyhounds died of unidentified illness, tests find
 &HT;    By Peter Donald
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Necropsies performed on three greyhounds
revealed the dogs died of an unidentified viral illness _ not
``kennel cough,'' the epidemic that shut down races at the Palm
Beach Kennel Club for 10 days earlier this year, veterinarians said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   As investigators at the University of Florida veterinary college
tried to identify the virus, the kennel cough epidemic appeared to
have run its course in West Palm Beach, with only two new cases
reported since the suburban West Palm Beach dog track reopened Feb.
5.
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost all the dogs are off the vet's list,'' said track
veterinarian Dr. William Dugger.
</P>
<P>
   He said the kennel cough epidemic was actually a blessing in
disguise because quarantines were in place that probably also
stemmed the spread of the more serious mystery illness.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dogs are looking real good,'' said track publicity
director Theresa Hume. ``The thing that killed our dog was not
kennel cough.''
</P>
<P>
   Hume estimated the club lost nearly $400,000 as a result of the
closures from Jan. 27 to Feb. 5.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 1, Chances Are Free _ a 3-year-old greyhound that raced
at the Palm Beach Kennel Club _ died after suffering a raging fever
and internal bleeding. Because the death occurred in the middle of
the kennel cough epidemic, there was speculation that the dog had
died as a result of complications from the disease, which
veterinarians likened to whooping cough in humans.
</P>
<P>
   Infectious tracheobronchitis, or kennel cough, is a contagious
disease spread through the air within confined kennels. It has been
choking the greyhound racing industry with track closures in
Kansas, Alabama and other states.
</P>
<P>
   But a necropsy performed on Chances Are Free two weeks ago
revealed the dog died of an unrelated and unidentified viral
illness _ not kennel cough.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this time, an unusual form of viral respiratory disease is
suspected, but not proven, as the primary problem,'' said Dr.
William Castleman, a pathobiologist at the veterinary college of
the University of Florida who is investigating greyhound deaths.
</P>
<P>
   Castleman also conducted necropsies on one dog from the St.
Petersburg track and one from the Daytona Beach track, with similar
results. A total of eight greyhounds, including six at St.
Petersburg's Derby Lane, have died in the state.
</P>
<P>
   The dogs were originally believed to have succumbed to
complications from kennel cough, but the results of diagnostic
tests suggested a virus of unknown origins that caused the dogs to
bleed to death as well as other complications stemming from that
virus.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the dogs that died had bacterial pneumonia associated
with E. coli as a complication of the suspected viral disease,''
Castleman concluded. ``The other two dogs have no evidence of
bacterial disease or other common infections of dogs.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Donald writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
