<HEADER>
A7793 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CARLOS-SAURA-FILMS-$A     02-16 1178
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARLOS-SAURA-FILMS-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DEPICTOR OR DANCE REACHES BEYOND IT  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, FEB. 21) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 Will Joyner, a former editor for Arts and Leisure, wrote most
recently for the section about sexuality in European and American
films.  
 By WILL JOYNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   This year's Academy Award nominations offer many reasons for
deep satisfaction, but one such reason hasn't attracted much
attention. Tucked at the end of the list of nominees for best
foreign film, just below Roberto Benigni's ubiquitous ``Life Is
Beautiful,'' is ``Tango,'' an entry from Argentina that is the work
of the hugely gifted, hugely perplexing Spanish director Carlos
Saura.
</P>
<P>
   It would be wonderful in any case for Saura, 67, to be noted
again for Oscar consideration (his ``Carmen'' was nominated in
1983). But it is especially gratifying with ``Tango,'' because
while ``Tango'' is certainly a dance film _ the sort of film that
Saura has come to be associated with in the last 20 years _ it is
not a dance film above all.
</P>
<P>
   Here, the director's distinctive way of depicting dance from the
inside out does not overshadow his more venerable gift for
commenting in a dramatic narrative on subjects like political
repression, personal loss and emotional survival.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, ``Tango,'' the story of an aging film director
intent on using tango to make a politically frank epic in
present-day Buenos Aires, is not an example of a master filmmaker
doing what comes easily, what the public expects of him. Rather, it
is an example of a master filmmaker using a blatant, bravely drawn
alter-ego to look back unblinkingly and try to bring the various
provinces of his own career into closer alignment.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1980s, when he turned to making movies that had the
brashly erotic, rural flourish of flamenco at their heart, Saura
seemed to be performing an about-face esthetically. In the 60s and
70s, he had more quietly illustrated the dark, largely urban
landscape of Franco's Spain in dramas like ``Peppermint Frappe,''
``Cria Cuervos'' and ``Elisa, Vida Mia,'' all of which starred
Geraldine Chaplin, his companion.
</P>
<P>
   With a measured, unobtrusive style that bordered on the surreal
without dwelling on it, he left a memorable impression of a people
whose motives and dreams had been irredeemably marred by politics.
Then, suddenly, he shifted his greatest energies to folklore and
the less ambiguous swirl of stage performance.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of cultural acuity, or even political commitment, there
was actually nothing so inconsistent in this shift. Certainly the
sources adapted in the three flamenco movies that brought Saura
such acclaim in the 80s _ ``Blood Wedding,'' from the play by
Federico Garcia Lorca, ``Carmen'' and ``El Amor Brujo,'' from a
ballet by Manuel de Falla _ were rich in themes that will always
resonate in Spain: love, betrayal, violence, memory, forgiveness.
</P>
<P>
   But Saura brought to these classic vehicles directorial touches
that enhanced their contemporary significance. ``Blood Wedding,''
for example, was presented as a near-documentary of a rehearsal; it
eavesdrops on the musicians and dancers, contrasting their
professional dedication and their backstage preening.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carmen'' included a real love muddle that mirrored the one
under production. At the start of ``El Amor Brujo,'' a camera
panned in from the wings of a darkened but high-tech soundstage to
the rough, highly stylized set, a Gypsy village, giving the
landscape the aura of both past and future.
</P>
<P>
   Still, what dominated in these movies was the flamenco _
especially the brilliant choreography and execution of Saura's
collaborater, Antonio Gades, with the support of scores of other
gifted artists. As Saura's cameras took their place on stage with
the dancers, bringing the audience into the action, the movies
became _ for American viewers, at least _ an education in a dance
and musical form.
</P>
<P>
   Or, more accurately, an education in how flamenco's plaintive
verses and its clapping and stomping added up to something more
sophisticated, more poetic than the sum of the flamboyantly
emotional parts. Watched on video today, as accomplished as they
are, these three films have the feel of artifacts: if you're
naturally mesmerized by the dance, you'll persist, with pleasure;
if not, you'll quickly press stop.
</P>
<P>
   Chances are you won't stop and rewind a movie like ``Cria
Cuervos.'' This is Saura's 1976 film about a 9-year-old girl in an
upper-class Madrid family who refuses to accept the death by cancer
of her supremely gifted and neglected mother or to look away from
the various strategies of deceit surrounding her father, an army
officer who dies in the clutches of his best friend's wife.
</P>
<P>
   The girl, the middle of three sisters, is played by the stunning
child actress Ana Torrent (she's perhaps even better remembered for
Victor Erice's ``Spirit of the Beehive''); the mother, who is
summoned from the dead by the child's imagination, is portrayed in
brief, heartbreaking tableaus by Ms. Chaplin.
</P>
<P>
   Although it takes place in the later days of the Franco era, the
particulars of which are sometimes difficult for non-Spaniards to
decipher, ``Cria'' is an urgent, instantly relevant study in the
arbitrary, often cruel manner in which strong identities are formed
and maintained.
</P>
<P>
   From its first moments _ a sweeping shot of Buenos Aires on a
gray winter day _ ``Tango'' carries this same sense of urgency, on
essentially the same topic. But ``Tango'' was created by an older,
even wiser person than the one who created ``Cria,'' so while its
message is just as chilling, its devices are more straightforward,
more assured, more self-reflective.
</P>
<P>
   By recounting the situation of a venerable, popular filmmaker
who wants to stretch the precise, elegant, urban terms of the
tango, Saura has, of course, devised a context for large ironies
and large judgments at his own expense, and he never shrinks from
the assignment.
</P>
<P>
   The largest and most telling irony in ``Tango'' is that amid
sustained, slyly designed performances by the best tango artists in
the world _ they're led by Juan Carlos Copes, and the Argentine
ballet superstar Julio Bocca even makes an appearance _ the crucial
performance is that of a man hobbled by a car accident.
</P>
<P>
   As Saura's alter-ego, the director Mario Suarez (Miguel Angel
Sola) limps from scene to scene with the kind of dignity and
wide-eyed innocence that belongs only to the brutally honest. As
Mario coordinates his complex production, stands up to his nervous
backers, falls in love with his young star, then admits to her his
doubts about life, the character engages in a blunt, uncontrived
commentary that serves to reconcile the strains of Saura's career.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's the dramatic line that unifies all this?'' Mario asks
at one point. Saura's blunt answer, all the more powerful for being
spoken against a relief of chic, cutting-edge dance, comes a bit
later: ``Imagination is a guardrail that stops you from plunging
into the pit of horror.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-99 2155EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
