<SLUG> BC-PBP-SUGAR-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sugar growers ready to crow over possible record crop
 &HT;    By Julie Waresh
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEWISTON, Fla. _ With the federal government predicting a
record 2 million-ton sugar cane crop for Florida this year, growers
have much to crow about.
</P>
<P>
   They'll get the chance today, as about 15 congressional aides
fly into Palm Beach International Airport for the 15th annual
congressional staff tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we were wine makers, this could be a vintage year,'' said
Dalton Yancey, executive vice president of the Florida Sugar Cane
League, which co-sponsors the junket with the Sugar Cane Growers
Cooperative of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Lots of sunshine and just enough rain this season have produced
what looks like a record crop, Yancey said.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Department of Agriculture predicts Florida's output of
raw sugar will surpass 2 million tons this year for the first time
ever. Last year's harvest produced 1.9 million tons.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the larger yield and several weather delays, the
sugar cane harvest, which typically ends in March, is expected to
stretch into April.
</P>
<P>
   Harvest and loading operations are on the agenda for the tour,
which is paid for by the Belle Glade-based co-op, and the Florida
Sugar Cane League, which lobbies Washington lawmakers on behalf of
this area's two sugar giants: the Fanjul family's Florida Crystals
Corp. and U.S. Sugar Corp. of Clewiston.
</P>
<P>
   This year's attendees include aides to Sen. Bob Graham, D-Fla.,
and aides to congressmen from agricultural states such as Arkansas
and Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   The co-op, made up of 56 smaller sugar farmers, will host
today's activities _ an Everglades tour via airboat and dinner with
growers.
</P>
<P>
   After a night at the Clewiston Inn, attendees will visit U.S.
Sugar's insect lab and its new refinery, as well as Florida
Crystals' Okeelanta mill near South Bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important not only to see the equipment and the process,
but also to see the people,'' Yancey said.
</P>
<P>
   Before flying back to Washington on Friday, attendees will get a
look at the sugar shipping operation at the Port of Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Each year, businesses nationwide try to lure staffers on
educational tours during the President's Day recess.
</P>
<P>
   Sugar growers invited 100 this year, and are expecting just 15.
Yancey said the tour costs growers between $500 and $750 a person,
depending on the cost of air fare.
</P>
<P>
   The junket must adhere to certain rules _ for example,
educational trips can be two nights only _ and must be cleared by
the House and Senate ethics committees.
</P>
<P>
   Julie Waresh writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
