A7797 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PBP-SITE-FLORIDA-COX     02-16 0474
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PBP-SITE-FLORIDA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    List omits Florida's strengths, official says
 &HT;    By David Sedore
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Florida dropped two notches to ninth on
Site Selection magazine's annual ranking of states with the most
new or expanded corporate plants or offices during 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine, which released the rankings Monday, also reported
that the number of new or expanded plants or offices fell by about
18 percent in Florida from the previous year while corporate
movement nationally set a new record. Site Selection credited
Florida with 430 locations in 1998 vs. 526 in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Enterprise Florida Vice President Buzz Canup said his office
reported 567 moves during the year that met the criteria the
magazine uses to calculate its rankings. If the magazine had
counted all those moves, Florida would have ranked seventh once
again.
</P>
<P>
   Site Selection Editor Jack Lyne said moves must meet one of
three criteria to be counted. They must involve a capital
investment of at least $1 million, create at least 50 new jobs or
add at least 20,000 square feet of floor space.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine develops its lists from newspaper clips, news
releases and surveys of economic development agencies such as
Enterprise Florida, Lyne said. It does not count retail and
government projects, schools and hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   The discrepancy between Enterprise Florida's numbers and the
magazine's most likely is because of projects that were the wrong
type or too small, projects about which the magazine had unanswered
questions at deadline or projects that were included in the
previous year's report.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's likely almost all fall into one of the three groups,''
said Managing Editor Tim Venable.
</P>
<P>
   Canup said the magazine's numbers, even accepted at face value,
don't reflect negatively on Florida given their slant toward
manufacturing projects, which isn't one of the state's strengths.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good news is that where Florida is relatively weak, we
actually showed up in the top 10 again,'' Canup said. ``That's a
real kudo for the state.''
</P>
<P>
   Another factor that might mitigate the drop is the dominance of
smaller businesses in the state, many of which would have
expansions too small to be counted by Site Selection.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure a lot are not coming up on the radar screen because
of the criteria,'' said George Haygood, economic development
director for the St. Lucie County Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Florida ranked 11th on the magazine's list of jobs created for
each million in population and 20th in terms of capital investment.
It finished eighth in number of expansions and new facilities for
each 1,000 square miles of area.
</P>
<P>
   David Sedore writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
