A7799 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRETEND-GAY-COX     02-16 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRETEND-GAY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Workshop helps educators feel what it's like to be young, gay
 &HT;    By Mary Ellen Flannery
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Guidance counselors in the Palm Beach
County School District closed their eyes for a minute last week and
pretended to be 13 years old again with a secret so scary that they
couldn't tell a soul.
</P>
<P>
   They pretended to be gay.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of you may have come in here thinking you don't
understand gay and lesbian students, but you know what it's like to
be 13 and feel like you have nobody to turn to,'' Kevin Jennings,
executive director of the Gay, Lesbian and Straight Educators
Network, said during a workshop. ``And you know you have to deal
with these students who feel lost and abandoned, if only because
they don't do well in school.''
</P>
<P>
   The training workshop for guidance counselors, school
psychologists and principals, which cost $2,000, represented the
district's first step toward making school safe for gay students,
Jennings said. Today, the school board will consider the next step:
a new policy that could be approved this spring to prohibit
harassment of and discrimination against gay students.
</P>
<P>
   School district attorneys started work on the policy before the
district earned a failing grade from the gay educators network for
its protection of gay and lesbian students, and its lack of any
gay-oriented curriculum, said Cynthia Prettyman, school board
attorney. The proposed policy is like those in Miami-Dade and
Broward counties that treat anti-gay discrimination the same as
race or age discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something that needed to be done,'' Prettyman said.
</P>
<P>
   Without such a policy, the school district opens itself to
lawsuits like the one filed by Jamie Nabozny, a Wisconsin
seventh-grader whose classmates called him names and kicked and
spit on him, and whose principal said simply, ``Boys will be
boys.'' In 1996, the U.S. Court of Appeals ruled public schools and
their individual officials could be held liable for failing to
address anti-gay abuse, and Nabozny eventually won $900,000.
</P>
<P>
   For Jennings however, these types of policies aren't so much
about protecting districts from lawsuits as they are about
protecting gay students from name-calling, nasty whispers and
vicious pushes into hallway lockers. According to a Massachusetts
Department of Education study, 46 percent of gay and lesbian
students have attempted suicide and 22 percent have skipped school
because they feel unsafe on campus.
</P>
<P>
   At COMPASS, a West Palm Beach agency that serves gays and
lesbians, about 26 percent of the 200 teens who have attended
support sessions have dropped out of school, program director
Sheila Bewsee said. Almost all of them said they didn't feel safe
in their schools.
</P>
<P>
   A study done by Iowa high school students found that the average
high school student hears anti-gay epithets about 25 times a day.
Teachers who hear those words fail to respond 97 percent of the
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know kids get harassed here in Palm Beach County. I know
that for a fact,'' said Sybil Adcock, a music teacher in the
district and co-chair of the local gay educators chapter. ``I know
kids are scared to death to come out. They get pushed in the halls;
they get, `Here comes the faggot.' The emotional scars are
horrendous, but nobody pays attention because it's OK to hate
fags.''
</P>
<P>
   But despite the testimony of gay and lesbian teachers, who say
some 14,000 students in Palm Beach County could be gay, some
parents wonder why sexual orientation has to be added to the
policy. Sexual harassment doesn't have anything to do with gender,
and it most often has to do with heterosexual men and women, wrote
David Walsh, chairman of the Boca Raton High School school advisory
committee, in a memo to board members.
</P>
<P>
   It's a controversial topic, but the policies and workshops don't
endorse homosexuality or tell kids it's OK to be gay, members of
the gay educators network point out. And network members aren't
currently working on bringing any pro-gay curriculum into the
school district, Adcock said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal today is not to get you to like gay people,''
Jennings told the guidance counselors. ``You're entitled to think
I'm a disgusting gay pervert. But you're not entitled to bring that
attitude into the classroom. As teachers, we have an ethical and
professional obligation to support every child, regardless of the
differences among them.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary Ellen Flannery writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
