<SLUG> BC-AGENT-DETAINED-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FBI PROBING POSSIBLE BIAS IN STOPPING OF DEA AGENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHELLEY MURPHY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The FBI is investigating allegations that two police
officers in a town outside Boston violated the civil rights of a
black federal Drug Enforcement Administration agent after a traffic
stop.
</P>
<P>
   DEA Special Agent Paul L.D. Russell Jr. said he was harassed and
detained by two uniformed officers even though he was driving an
unmarked Pontiac Grand Am equipped with blue lights and a radio,
and showed them his badge and his credentials.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no problem with the initial stop, he was just doing his
job,'' Russell said. ``But there was no reason to continue after I
told him I was a federal agent and the car was insured. I was
arrested for an unarrestable offense that was fueled by race _
`He's black in a white town, what's he doing here?' ''
</P>
<P>
   But Reading Police Chief Edward Marchand insists that his men
did nothing wrong, and that the incident was not racial.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point I don't see any crime committed of civil rights
by anybody,'' Marchand said. ``It's just a misunderstanding.''
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Richard J. Sinnott, who represents Russell and lodged
his civil rights complaint with the FBI, said the Reading officers
illegally detained, searched, arrested and assaulted Russell.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they do this to someone who looks like L.D. (Russell) does
and clearly identifies himself as a DEA agent, then I really have
to worry about how they treat the general public,'' Sinnott said.
</P>
<P>
   Russell said the confrontation happened the afternoon of Nov. 3
when Officer Robert Moreschi followed, then pulled over Russell's
Pontiac on High Street, just after the officer stopped to ask
directions at a nearby gas station. Russell said Moreschi told him
the car's registration had expired.
</P>
<P>
   Russell, who was conducting a background check on a DEA
applicant, said he told the officer, ``I'm with DEA. I'm on the
job. I know there are problems with the plate and the DEA is trying
to resolve them. It's a surveillance car.''
</P>
<P>
   Russell said he produced his gold badge, his DEA credentials and
his Massachusetts driver's license. He said Moreschi was
unimpressed, and called for backup.
</P>
<P>
   Russell said he was standing beside the police cruiser when Sgt.
Peter Garchinsky arrived and ordered him to move to a nearby fence
and yelled, ``You! Get over there!''
</P>
<P>
   Garchinsky ``says, `You know there's some holes in your
story,''' said Russell. ``I said, `I'm a federal agent in a federal
vehicle doing my job on federal time.'''
</P>
<P>
   Russell said the sergeant pushed him up against the hood of the
Pontiac and thoroughly frisked him. Moreschi seized Russell's
DEA-issued 9mm Glock, which was strapped to his ankle.
</P>
<P>
   Russell said the officers boxed in the Pontiac with their
cruisers and ordered him to get into his car and follow them back
to the Reading police station.
</P>
<P>
   While enroute, Russell said, he called his DEA supervisor,
Michael Cunniff, on his cellular telephone, and Cunniff advised him
to ``maintain your cool.''
</P>
<P>
   According to a DEA report, Cunniff called the station to
complain, but officers told him that Chief Marchand was on vacation
and Garchinsky was in charge.
</P>
<P>
   Within minutes, Garchinsky called Cunniff, who confirmed that
Russell was a DEA agent. Cunniff also warned Garchinsky there would
be ``serious consequences'' for his conduct _ including the fact
that Russell was forced to the police station for a motor vehicle
infraction that wasn't an arrestable offense, according to the
report.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Marchand said his officers told him that Russell went
to the police station voluntarily.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know Sgt. Garchinsky, he's certainly a good sergeant,''
Marchand said. ``I've never heard him utter anything in regards to
any nationality or race or anything else. If he made a
determination to ask him to come back to the station, I would
certainly think it was a legitimate.''
</P>
<P>
   Marchand said Moreschi has a reputation for being ``very
diligent in his apprehension of motor vehicle violators. He's known
for that.''
</P>
<P>
   When Moreschi questioned Russell and discovered the car was
registered to someone else, he didn't know whether Russell's
identification was valid, the chief said. Typically, DEA
surveillance cars are registered under false names and addresses to
protect the identity of the agents who drive them.
</P>
<P>
   Marchand said there are no blacks on the 41-member force and
just one woman, but estimated that the town's black population is
about 1 or 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Russell, 44, a clean-cut church deacon who has been a federal
agent for 17 years, has worked with state and local police for
years on various task forces. He has worked undercover targeting
inner-city gangs and teaches a course about undercover work at the
State Police Academy.
</P>
<P>
   Russell said he told the officer the problem with the
registration happened when a Boston Police cadet mailed a citation
to the vehicle's registered owner after spotting the car make a
traffic violation. Since then, the DEA had resolved the problem.
</P>
<P>
   After the incident, DEA Special Agent George Festa met with
Chief Marchand while conducting an internal probe. Festa declined
to comment Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   DEA spokesman Pamela Mersky said the agency would only
acknowledge that Russell was in an official government vehicle and
conducting an investigation when the Reading officers stopped him.
</P>
<P>
   ``However, there is an ongoing investigation and possible civil
rights suit and because of this we don't want to comment,'' Mersky
said.
</P>
<P>
   Marchand said he was ``dumbfounded'' when an FBI agent,
investigating Russell's civil rights complaint, contacted him a
couple of weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unfortunate it happened the way it did,'' Marchand said.
``It's too bad it couldn't have been handled right at the scene.''
</P>
<P>
   FBI spokesman Gail Marcinkiewicz said the FBI is the agency
responsible for investigating civil rights violations. Nationwide,
75 percent of the FBI's civil rights investigations involve
federal, state or local officers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
