<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-HUD-REPRIMAND-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSTON HOUSING AGENCY FACES HUD REPRIMAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY RAKOWSKY AND TATSHA ROBERTSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Federal housing authorities are expected to severely
reprimand the Boston Housing Authority Wednesday for failing to
shield eight minority families from racial harassment in the city's
public housing developments.
</P>
<P>
   Three years after the families filed a complaint with the US
Department of Housing and Urban Development, the agency is expected
to finally address the grievances of 34 blacks and Hispanics who
say they suffered relentless vandalism, verbal abuse, and
playground assaults on children while living in South Boston and
Charlestown public housing developments from the late 1980s through
1996.
</P>
<P>
   The form of HUD's sanctions was not clear Tuesday, but could
involve measures ranging from lawsuits to new restrictions on how
to spend federal money, the lifeblood of public housing. The agency
announced a press conference in Washington, listing a fair housing
case in Boston as one of the agenda items.
</P>
<P>
   Ozell Hudson, executive director of the Lawyers' Committee for
Civil Rights, which represents the families, said the evidence
supplied to HUD is overwhelming.
</P>
<P>
   ``HUD would be negligent in its responsibility to enforce fair
housing laws if it did not find that there was a strong basis to
believe BHA systematically discriminated against the tenants of
color in the developments,'' Hudson said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Arguing that the BHA knew that some white residents were upset
about the desegregation of traditionally white developments in
South Boston and Charlestown, the tenants are hoping the federal
government will punish local housing officials for allegedly
failing to stop the harassment, clean up offensive graffitti, or
let them move away from the perpetrators.
</P>
<P>
   The complaints that HUD is expected to uphold include
allegations that a shot was fired into a minority tenant's bedroom
as he slept, rocks were thrown from windows at minority residents,
and doorknobs to minority tenants' apartments were tied by ropes to
prevent exit, according to records and sources.
</P>
<P>
   All the incidents allegedly occurred in the historically white
housing developments in South Boston _ Mary Ellen McCormack, West
Broadway, and Old Colony _ and the Bunker Hill housing development
in Charlestown.
</P>
<P>
   BHA director Sandra Henriquez, who took over the authority after
the complaints were filed, said she has installed policies to
remedy problems like the delays in covering racist graffiti, and
she has made it her mission to evict tenants who break the law or
cause disturbances.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would hope that they look at all the training, all the
programs we've done, the policies we've put in place,'' said
Henriquez.
</P>
<P>
   If HUD decides to file suit, the case likely would proceed on a
separate track from the one already brought in US District Court by
Hudson's clients, according to the department.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Hudson said, his clients' case would be bolstered by
the HUD reprimand.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will strengthen our clients claim to both HUD and federal
court and should expedite settlement discussions,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of its course, any action by HUD is likely to salt
Boston's racial wounds and refresh tensions. Despite periodic
incidents of racial intolerance or even violence, local officials
have declared the desegregation efforts at BHA developments to be
successful, achieved with a minimum of disruption through the
careful efforts of city officials.
</P>
<P>
   The case will undoubtedly dispute that perception, harking back
to the bad old days of the BHA, when it was held in receivership by
HUD for mismanagement, and was subject to a battery of lawsuits
over its failure to integrate developments, particularly those in
South Boston and Charlestown.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the underlying claim of the tenants' lawsuit is that
minorities were harassed in those developments so they would be
pressured into requesting transfers. But, the complaint asserts,
city officials thwarted their emergency bids for transfers because
they were under court orders to integrate the developments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some families paid rent, but lived elsewhere,'' Hudson said.
``Others were so afraid that they wouldn't come home until dark.''
</P>
<P>
   BHA knew about this, he said, and not only failed to address the
problems, ``but failed to protect them from continued acts of
racial violence by not granting them civil rights transfers.''
</P>
<P>
   For her part, Henriquez said, ``I didn't need a lawsuit or a HUD
complaint to actively pursue issues around training and diversity
in this organization.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
