A7810 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATHLETES-LOBBYISTS-CO     02-16 0333
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATHLETES-LOBBYISTS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Athletes team up for autistic kids
 &HT;    (EDS: Moving in (a) General news and (s) Sports categories.)
 &HT;    By Charles Elmore
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ Dolphins' quarterback Dan Marino and
Panthers' right wing Scott Mellanby will play unusual positions
this year _ registered lobbyists in a multimillion-dollar fight
against the insurance industry.
</P>
<P>
   The sports stars will tell lawmakers during the upcoming
legislative session why insurers should be required to pay benefits
for autistic children, said Ron Book, who lobbies for Dolphins' and
Panthers' owner Wayne Huizenga.
</P>
<P>
   Book said he will submit Marino's and Mellanby's names to the
state's lobbyist registry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people know Dan has an autistic child, but not many know
that Scott does as well,'' Book said. ``They've committed to coming
up to help pass the bill.''
</P>
<P>
   There are about 3,700 children in Florida with autism, a
developmental condition that makes it hard for them to communicate
and socialize. They include Marino's son, Michael Joseph, 10, and
Mellanby's son, Carter, who is almost 3.
</P>
<P>
   Marino spoke on behalf of an autism center two years ago but
this is a more sweeping proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Treatment costs as much as $45,000 per year and insurance
companies say this and other proposals to make them pay for
infertility and other treatments could mean some small businesses
couldn't afford to offer insurance to their workers. Insurance
officials acknowledge they dread facing Marino and Mellanby, whose
message is they can afford treatment but many others cannot because
insurers won't pay.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be very tough to oppose,'' said Sam Miller,
vice president of the Florida Insurance Council, because it deals
with autistic children. ``And Dan Marino's on the other team.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Elmore writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
