<HEADER>
A7814 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLA-TYPHOID-FEVER-COX     02-16 0605
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-TYPHOID-FEVER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Unusual cases of typhoid fever stump health officials
 &HT;    By Ron Hayes
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Health officials are investigating Palm
Beach County's first two cases of typhoid fever reported in
residents who haven't visited countries where the disease is
common.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've never seen typhoid fever before in Palm Beach County
with people who haven't traveled outside the country,'' Dr. Jean
Malecki, county health director, said Tuesday. ``This is very
unusual in the United States, and it causes us concern.''
</P>
<P>
   Typhoid fever is transmitted by eating or drinking food or
beverages contaminated with bacteria from an infected person.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is about handwashing, handwashing, handwashing,'' Malecki
emphasized. ``That's the key.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, officials in Miami-Dade County announced an outbreak
of three confirmed and three probable cases of the disease, which
is more typically found in areas such as Latin America and the
Caribbean. The Miami cases are also among people who had not left
the U.S.
</P>
<P>
   The local patients are a 30-year-old man from Hypoluxo, whose
symptoms first appeared on Jan. 24, and a 3-year-old Lake Worth boy
who developed symptoms Feb. 8.
</P>
<P>
   The child was treated with antibiotics at a hospital emergency
room and sent home; he received additional treatment as an
out-patient, Malecki said. The man remains hospitalized, and both
patients are under isolation.
</P>
<P>
   Because the disease is spread when feces from an infected person
contaminates food or drinks, the patients' relatives who work in
food-service jobs are being kept home from work until they can be
tested, Malecki said. There are two such family members but neither
appears sick, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Tests are being done to determine if both patients contracted a
common strain of the bacteria, but results will not be available
until the end of the week, Malecki said. These cases will then be
compared to the Miami cases, but no link is now apparent between
any of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no sign of an outbreak at this time,'' Malecki said.
``These are sporadic cases, but there is something going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials are concerned that the two patients may have
contracted the disease either from a carrier of the bacteria who
isn't sick or from food bought or eaten at the same store or
restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   To track the source, both patients have answered a 12-page
questionnaires about where they have eaten and shopped. Their
answers will then be compared for a common link, Malecki said.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday night, the county health department sent letters to
nearly 2,000 infection control practitioners, emergency room
physicians and doctors with hospital privileges, Malecki said. The
alert notified doctors to watch for typical symptoms of typhoid
fever and to report any suspected cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``These symptoms are very similar to other types of diseases and
I just want to make sure people are looking for it,'' Malecki said.
</P>
<P>
   Typhoid fever is not unheard of in this area. In 1997, two cases
were reported in Palm Beach County, and three last year. But all of
those occurred in people who had recently traveled outside the
U.S., Malecki said.
</P>
<P>
   Florida records from 10 to 20 cases of typhoid fever a year,
according to the state Department of Health, with most of those
occurring in Miami-Dade County because its airport is an
international hub.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Hayes writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach, Fla.
Researcher Barbara Gellis Shapiro contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
