<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-DONATE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTMENT STANDOUT DONATES $10 MILLION-PLUS TO COLLEGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATE ZERNIKE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Boston College received the largest gift in its
136-year history Tuesday, with the donation of more than $10
million to its school of education from investment mogul Peter
Lynch and his wife, Carolyn.
</P>
<P>
   The gift also breaks a record for Lynch, who said it was ``by
far'' the largest gift made by him and his wife, who privately and
through their foundation donated to 265 charities last year.
</P>
<P>
   The Lynches said they were giving to the school, which will be
renamed for them, because of its reputation for a focus on training
teachers, and because of its commitment to improving urban
elementary and secondary schools, an area of particular interest to
the couple.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps predictably, the celebrated stock-picker spoke of his
donation in terms of investing _ this time, in children.
</P>
<P>
   ``People ask why I don't give to the school of management,''
Lynch said in an interview Tuesday. ``We look at this as `Where can
you get a lot for your money?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Mary Brabeck, dean of the BC school of education, called the
gift an ``enormous, enormous'' boost for the often-beleaguered
profession of teaching.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this day, when we've become so cynical about education,
this is an incredible statement, that Peter Lynch thinks education
is worth investing in,'' she said. ``It sends an enormous message
to the community.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lynches asked to keep the specific amount private, except to
say that it surpasses the last-largest gift of $10 million 10 years
ago, and is under $15 million.
</P>
<P>
   It falls far behind the largest gifts to higher education _ the
largest was $295 million in stock donated by three private
foundations to Atlanta's Emory University in Atlanta three years
ago, and several Ivy League schools have received donations of more
than $50 million.
</P>
<P>
   But the gift is a significant milestone for the school of
education and for the college, which has lifted itself up over the
last 25 years from a nearly-bankrupt college for commuter students
to a ``hot'' school with a national and international reputation
and an $814 million endowment. It has vaulted into the top 40 on
the US News &AMP; World Report rankings, and into the top 50 for
schools with the largest endowments.
</P>
<P>
   Lynch, a BC graduate, parent, and trustee, said improving the
college had been like ``pushing a snowball up the hill for a while,
but gravity seems to be working with them.'' Still, he said, ``the
school of education hasn't gotten its proper recognition. It's
dwarfed by arts and sciences, the law school, the management
school.''
</P>
<P>
   The money, which will become part of the BC endowment, is
unrestricted, meaning it can be spent on any aspect of the school
of education.
</P>
<P>
   ``They understand that we want to help strengthen teaching,
particularly in the inner city,'' Lynch said. ``And that's for all
types of students, public and parochial schools.''
</P>
<P>
   Among other ventures, the money will go toward improving the
college's partnerships with public elementary schools the nearby
Allston-Brighton section of Boston, its teacher training programs,
and research, which includes research on testing and the
administration of the widely-regarded Third International Math and
Science Study, or TIMSS, which compares 52 nations on everything
from students' math performance to how much homework they are
assigned, allowing informed comparisons about what works and what
doesn't in teaching math and science.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a wonderful gift for education . . . for our children,
and for Boston College,'' said President William P. Leahy.
</P>
<P>
   Peter and Carolyn Lynch are known for their commitment to
education. Since 1991, the year after Lynch stepped down from the
helm of Fidelity's Magellan Fund at the peak of his career, he has
been the chairman of the Inner City Scholarship fund, which last
year raised $3.3 million to help send needy students to Catholic
schools in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   He has helped set up partnerships between the city's prominent
banking and law firms and the schools of the Archdiocese of Boston,
taking potential donors on an annual bus tour to see the conditions
in the schools firsthand. At BC, he helped set up the Urban
Catholic Teachers Corps, which houses, trains, and pays beginning
teachers to teach in parochial schools for two years.
</P>
<P>
   The Lynches are particularly concerned about high dropout rates
in the nation's cities, in some places, close to 50 percent. And
the age at which students drop out, Lynch noted, is getting lower.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the scholarships and loans in this country are set up to
go to colleges,'' Lynch said. ``I'm not opposed to that, but
there's nothing to keep kids in fourth grade, in seventh grade.
It's hard to get these kids to think so far ahead; if they're 9 or
10, a scholarship to Bates or Bowdoin or Duke seems far off.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're giving kids hope,'' he said. ``They can all make it.
People say these kids are hopeless. It's not true.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lynches's interest in education began with their parents.
</P>
<P>
   Carolyn Lynch's father was a teacher, principal, and
superintendent of schools in Delaware and Pennsylvania. Peter
Lynch's father taught mathematics at Boston College for six years
after receiving his masters from the school. He died when his son
was 11. Lynch went to BC on a $300 caddying scholarship, earning
the other $700 in tuition by caddying at the Braeburn Country Club,
where he happened to caddy for the president of Fidelity. He went
to work at the company in 1968 after a tour in the Army, and by the
time he retired at age 46 had taken the Magellan Fund from $20
million in assets to over $14 billion, for a total gain of 2,700
percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
