<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-16 22:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7817 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CT-POLICE-SHOOTING-1     02-16 1062
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CT-POLICE-SHOOTING-1,030(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MURDER CHARGE AGAINST OFFICER STIRS DEBATE ON RISK 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By MIKE ALLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW MILFORD, Conn. _ In the privacy of his lawyer's office,
Officer Scott B. Smith began to feel sick to his stomach.
</P>
<P>
   Only hours earlier, his future had seemed so promising. He had
been filling in for a detective, showing the brass what he could
do. He had passed the written, oral and agility tests of the
Connecticut State Police, and hoped to become a trooper in training
this summer.
</P>
<P>
   But that late December day in the lawyer's office, it was all
falling apart. The New Milford police officer had shot and killed a
fleeing suspect, and some of the facts did not look good. He had
shot the suspect in the back, while the man was on his knees, and
from such a close range that the muzzle flash had burned the man's
shirt. The suspect, Franklyn D. Reid, had no gun. He was black.
Smith is white.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, 27, contends that if he had not fired that shot, it would
have been his body there on the grassy shoulder of U.S. 202. Reid,
the officer said, had refused to show his hands, and had begun to
reach for his midsection.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors see it differently, and now Smith is facing a murder
charge, the first Connecticut police officer ever to be charged
with murder in the line of duty. Such a charge is so rare
nationally that Smith's lawyer says he has been unable to find a
similar case to help in preparing a defense.
</P>
<P>
   The repercussions of the case have been felt throughout
Connecticut among police and the public alike. Many police officers
say they fear that the case will set a grave precedent that could
make them hesitate a fatal extra second when confronted with a
knife or a gun. The prosecutor, John A. Connelly, contends that the
police just are not used to being held as accountable as other
citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Since Smith was arrested, the public reaction in Litchfield
County, known for the lakefront summer homes of New York's wealthy,
has been loud and angry. But in direct contrast to the recent
demonstrations in New York City after an unarmed street vendor was
killed in a confrontation with four officers, the outcry has been
almost all in favor of the officer.
</P>
<P>
   When a rock radio station in Hartford held a protest rally at
the Capitol, it was to call for Connelly's resignation. The morning
host at WZMX-FM, who goes by the name Sebastian, appeared beneath a
banner that said, ``Sebastian Backs the Blue,'' and drew whistles
and cheers when he referred to the prosecutor as a barnyard animal.
</P>
<P>
   Police departments throughout the state have helped whip up
public support for Smith by selling ``Officer Needs Assistance''
T-shirts, holding dinners to benefit a legal defense fund and
setting up a Web page (members.aol.com/copsupport) that draws 400
to 800 e-mail messages a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it really necessary that the police take the first
bullet?'' the Web page asks.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the officers' anger is focused on Connelly. During a
recent hearing in the case, about 200 officers massed outside the
courthouse to denounce Connelly as ``Judas.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Connelly called a meeting of several police chiefs to
try to defuse the tension. ``Murder is defined as the intentional
killing of an individual,'' he said in an interview. ``There's no
provision saying that if you're a cop, the law doesn't apply to
you.''
</P>
<P>
   Connelly, a former head of the State Police, said that the
evidence _ including the statement of a witness who said Reid had
already been subdued when he was shot _ convinced him that murder
was the only appropriate charge, one that could result in a
sentence of 25 years to life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Four days after Smith was charged on Jan. 19, an East Hartford
officer was shot in the head as he responded to a noise complaint,
leading some fellow officers to wonder whether he hesitated to draw
his gun because of the New Milford case. Three days later, the only
police officer in the Connecticut legislature committed suicide.
The events, although perhaps unrelated, have left police officers
rattled throughout the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of guys are saying it's been tough to even come to
work,'' Officer Peter M. DeLouis, 34, said as he steered his
cruiser along the narrow, winding former cart paths of New Milford.
</P>
<P>
   Besides raising old questions about the proper bounds of deadly
force, the case exposes a predicament for prosecutors in
Connecticut. In this state, prosecutors _ not a grand jury _ are
responsible for deciding whether an officer will face criminal
charges after a shooting. But those same prosecutors also rely on
the testimony of police officers in making cases against everyone
from bad drivers to drug dealers.
</P>
<P>
   New Milford officers who spoke on the condition of anonymity
said that they had already decided against drawing their guns in
situations where their training calls for them to do so, including
answering a report of an armed man in a parking lot, and said they
feared their partners would do the same. One tale, which could not
be verified but has become instant folklore among the state's
police officers, says that some paranoid officers are carrying guns
without bullets.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they're going to tie our hands and arrest us for doing our
jobs,'' said Sgt. Jim Duda, ``then all of us should just hand in
our badges, hand in our guns and get a job that pays just as much
without the risk of having our own life taken.''
</P>
<P>
   All of this is mystifying and even infuriating to Reid's family,
which immigrated from Jamaica in 1986. His mother, Pearlylyn Reid,
acknowledged that her son, who had a long criminal record, had made
mistakes in his life, but added softly, ``The punishment didn't fit
the crime.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Reid's father, Wilbert A. Shaw Jr., 70, considers his
grandson's death to be the culmination of persistent indignities
and outrages that he has faced as a black man in largely white New
Milford. From bar fights to traffic stops to a refusal to consider
his application for a job as a custodian, Shaw said that he had
always felt unwelcome here.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it had been a white boy,'' Shaw said, speaking about his
grandson, ``they wouldn't have been so afraid. They would have
handcuffed him and taken him into custody.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Smith has spent his life striving within the system, while Reid
always fought it. The blond, blue-eyed officer played three sports
at Newtown High School, graduated from Quinnipiac College in 1994
with a degree in social services, and is working on a master's
degree in criminal justice from the University of New Haven. He had
worked as a cardiopulmonary resuscitation instructor for the
American Red Cross, was a volunteer emergency medical technician
for his hometown ambulance corps, and got his first taste of law
enforcement as a security guard at Macy's in the Danbury Fair Mall.
</P>
<P>
   Although he has been suspended with pay, Smith retains unanimous
support in his department. He drops by several times a week in
jeans and a sweater to chat with colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   Reid, on the other hand, was what the police call a ``repeat
customer.'' Reid, who, like Smith, was 27, had served time for
stabbing a relative and for sexual assault. Over the years he had
been charged with child endangerment, drug possession, resisting
arrest and other offenses. When he died, the police were trying to
serve warrants on him for failure to appear in court and
harassment.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1992 case report, an officer who drove Reid to the police
station wrote that the suspect had ``told me to stop my patrol car
so that we could fight it out,'' called him a disparaging term for
a white person and ``threatened to get even with me someday.''
</P>
<P>
   So like other members of the 39-officer force here, Smith knew
all about Franklyn Reid at 11 a.m. on Dec. 29 when a detective told
him that a sergeant was chasing Reid on foot. Smith grabbed the
keys to an unmarked police car, two other detective jumped in, and
they headed south on U.S. 202, where they spotted Reid in the
parking lot of a Sunoco station.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stated, `That's Franklyn Reid' as I rolled down the
window,'' Smith recalled in a six-page affidavit that his lawyer
provided to the Connecticut State Police, which investigated the
shooting. ``When we were within 10 to 15 feet of Mr. Reid I stopped
the car and opened my door and Mr. Reid immediately took off
running. I identified myself as a police officer and ordered him to
stop.''
</P>
<P>
   But Reid did not, and Smith chased him on foot through traffic
to the other side of the two-lane highway. ``I continued to yell at
him, instructing him to show me his hands because I could not see
them,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   He said that he pulled Reid onto the shoulder of the highway.
``As we struggled on the grass near the shoulder of the southbound
lane I continued to hold Reid's clothing with my left hand by his
shoulder area and I forced him to his knees,'' he said. ``Based on
the motions he was making with his arms and shoulders, and based on
the fact that he refused to show me his hands, I believed he was
preparing to use a weapon.
</P>
<P>
   ``While I was yelling at him to show me his hands with my weapon
pointed at him, he made a sudden motion with his body in an
apparent attempt to return to his feet,'' Smith continued. ``At the
same instant I saw both of his arms begin to move quickly away from
his midsection and his body came upwards toward mine. I believed at
that time he was either going to shoot me or stab me. Out of fear
for my life at that instant, I discharged my weapon one time,
striking Mr. Reid.''
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer for the Reid family, Richard A. Bieder, asserted that
the confrontation could have been settled in a much less
catastrophic way. Smith, he pointed out, is 6 feet 2 and weighs 190
pounds, while Reid was much slighter _ 5 feet 4 and 129 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Police officers protest, however, that no one can recreate the
horror of those few seconds. ``The bad guys know where the guns
are, but we don't,'' said Investigator James M. Mullin, 40.
</P>
<P>
   In an unzippered jacket pocket, Reid had a folding pocket knife
with a 2}-inch blade. In part because the jacket was found near his
body, rather than on it, the authorities have declared that he was
unarmed.
</P>
<P>
   The shoulder of U.S. 202 now has a makeshift memorial to Reid _
a dozen bouquets, now dead and muddy, and a cross fashioned from
two chunks of molding and bound together with a red Christmas
garland. Reid's younger brother, Wayne, 21, sports a massive
memorial tattoo on his left bicep showing a cross laced with the
word, ``Brother.''
</P>
<P>
   Connelly, the prosecutor, said that he had no plans to back down
from the murder charge. ``The police are not above the law,'' he
said. ``If they don't have faith in the justice system what does
that tell other people?''
</P>
</TEXT>
