A7819 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAILOR-RESCUE-BOS &LR;      02-16 1049
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAILOR-RESCUE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIVAL BECOMES RESCUER IN WORLD YACHT RACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Through the gale-driven spray, Giovanni Soldini spotted the
capsized hull of the yacht he hoped still contained his friend and
sailing competitor, Isabelle Autissier. Soldini could see the
wrecked rigging and equipment on Autissier's boat, smashed by the
pounding of mountainous seas. He called out. No response.
</P>
<P>
   He circled back and made another pass, yelling her name over the
wind, but again, no response. On the third pass, Soldini got close
enough to throw a hammer at the hull, and after a few more
agonizing moments, Autissier appeared, crawling out of the cabin.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's dramatic rescue came after Soldini, who was closest to
Autissier in a solo around-the-world race, had sailed more than 10
hours through 30-foot waves and high winds to reach a remote spot
in the South Pacific, 1,800 miles from land, halfway between New
Zealand and Cape Horn.
</P>
<P>
   Once she was safely aboard his boat, Autissier explained to
Soldini that she had not expected him to rescue her so soon, and
had fallen asleep after making her mayday calls. She had not heard
him until the sound of the hammer woke her.
</P>
<P>
   Though the weather still roared around them, and with an even
larger gale bearing down, the two sailors took a moment to break
out some wine and cheese, toasting the rescue.
</P>
<P>
   That was the picture related back to race headquarters Tuesday
afternoon after Autissier, 42, the most popular female sports
figure in France, had for the second time in her career escaped
from a disastrous wreck. She was leading 10 other sailors in the
27,000-mile Around Alone sailboat race that started from
Charleston, S.C., Sept. 26.
</P>
<P>
   Autissier's rescuer, Soldini, was sailing a similar 60-foot boat
about 200 miles to the north when an emergency satellite signal
beamed to Race Operations Center in Charleston, signaling
Autissier's predicament.
</P>
<P>
   The beacon, known as a Global Positioning Emergency Radio
Beacon, set in motion a rescue that was equal parts
state-of-the-art navigational electronics and heroic seamanship.
</P>
<P>
   The wind was blowing 40 knots and the waves were up to 40 feet
high, said Autissier, when she first sent her team headquarters a
crackling radio transmission saying she had capsized but providing
no details.
</P>
<P>
   ``The boat suddenly turned more than 90 degrees,'' she told
headquarters, ``and I could no longer be in the cockpit. Then it
suddenly turned over and I didn't have time to shut the door.''
</P>
<P>
   At first report, Autissier was said to have gotten into a
lifeboat, but later reports suggested she stayed aboard the
upturned hull of her sailboat, even though equipment was breaking
up as it pitched and rolled in the stormy seas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very quickly, the mast snapped to pieces,'' she radioed.
``When I saw that, I sent the signal because there was nothing else
I could do. Then, I began getting organized, getting security
material together.''
</P>
<P>
   Because she was so far from commercial shipping areas,
Autissier's only hope was a fellow competitor. Such rescues are
well within the expectations of participant sailors.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1994-95 BOC race, a precursor to this year's Around
Alone, Autissier's boat was dismasted in the Southern Ocean. She
had to jury-rig a sail using a spinnaker pole and other supports,
and sailed more than 1,000 miles until she was rescued by ship and
helicopter after being rolled by a second storm near the coast of
Australia.
</P>
<P>
   But the latest disaster struck too far from land for anyone but
the nearest competitor, Soldini, to help.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anyone had to do this, he was the one,'' said Dan Miller, a
race spokesman in Charleston. ``He's been rescued himself before,
and knew the state of mind someone in that position would be in.
Also, he knew the boat.''
</P>
<P>
   The electronic signal that led to the rescue made a
globe-hopping triangle. When Autissier's boat capsized, it sent out
an emergency beacon to a satellite, which relayed the yacht's exact
position to receivers in Charleston. When it was determined that
Soldini was closest to her, race chairman Mark Schrader directed
him to the rescue. Race headquarters e-mailed, via satellite,
updated information on the position of Autissier's yacht, locating
it within 50 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Sailing through winds upwards of 30 knots, Soldini made his way
south, his average hull speed nearly 20 knots. At about 9 a.m. EST
Tuesday, he radioed to Charleston, ``I am heading for PBR (the name
of Autissier's boat). I'm not letting up until I have found Isa.''
</P>
<P>
   Within a half-hour, with the wind calming to 29-31 knots,
Soldini had made contact, homing in on another electronic signal
from PBR. At 9:37 a.m., the rescue was complete, though Soldini did
not say exactly how he got Autissier from one boat to another in
the heaving seas.
</P>
<P>
   As they resumed sailing toward the northeast Tuesday, another
gale was aproaching from the south, and Soldini told race
headquaters, even as they shared their wine and cheese, ``We're
getting out of here.''
</P>
<P>
   Their destination is Uruguay, the second of three stopovers in
the eight-month world-rounding competition that is scheduled to end
in Charleson in May. The two should reach their destination in
about seven days.
</P>
<P>
   The quadrennial race evolved from the BOC Around Alone race that
started in Newport, R.I., in 1982-83.
</P>
<P>
   Since the rules stipulate single-handed, unaided sailing,
Soldini will be held to the special exception afforded rescues;
Autissier is allowed to sail ``as a passenger'' but forbidden to
aid him with sailing operations.
</P>
<P>
   Although the rescue was successful, Autissier's capsizing is
bound to renew scrutiny and criticism of long-distance sailboat
racing. Her 1995 rescue cost Australia an estimate $6 million in
Naval operations.
</P>
<P>
   Less than two months ago, six sailors died and seven were boats
abandoned when a 650-mile race from Sydney to Tasmania was
devastated by a storm front with 80-knot winds kicking up gigantic
seas.
</P>
<P>
   However, in the four previous sailings of the Around Alone race,
only two of 87 competitors died at sea, according to race spokesman
Dan McConnell, and 56 of that number have finished the races.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-99 2216EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990216.0430 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-16 22:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7820 &Cx1f; taf-z
