<SLUG> BC-CONGRESSMAN-MEETING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: S.C.)  
 AN IMPEACHMENT SEQUEL STARS LINDSEY GRAHAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANDERSON, S.C. _ Didn't Lindsey Graham get the memo?
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, freed at last from the months-long impeachment
ordeal in Washington, are supposed to be following a ``pivot
strategy,'' wherein they shuck the scandal and delve into real
issues that affect real people. But Graham, the folksy Southerner
who soared to national attention on the wings of impeachment and
cable television, is not inclined just yet to move on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is anyone here to talk about Social Security?'' he asked with
a big grin as he walked into a town meeting on Tuesday night in the
chamber of the U.S. District Courthouse, where an overflow audience
cheered and yelled and gave him a standing ovation. ``My God, I
can't believe this!''
</P>
<P>
   Without wasting a minute, the congressman plunged into Topic A:
``Let's talk about what happened and the future of the country,''
he said. For the next 20 minutes he relit the fires that have been
officially declared extinguished, using just a word or two _ ``the
referral,'' ``the dress,'' ``the rule of law'' _ to prompt the
collective memory of his audience, which was with him every step of
the way.
</P>
<P>
   No need to name names. President Clinton became simply ``he,''
as in: ``When he called her at 2:30 in the morning, he was up to no
good,'' eliciting laughter and groans.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Party orthodoxy holds that no good can come of
reliving the impeachment wars. Not so here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to tell them what I did and why,'' Graham said earlier
in Washington as he looked forward to Tuesday night's series of
three town meetings, a kind of victory lap for the hometown boy
even though Republicans lost the case and the Senate acquitted
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a time for the country as a whole to understand what went
on here and where we're going to go,'' Graham said. ``What are the
consequences of this case? What do you do with the next federal
judge who has got wandering hands in the office and someone's got
the courage to say, `No, you shouldn't treat me that way,' and he
starts hiding evidence and getting others to lie for him _ what do
we do with that case?''
</P>
<P>
   Few appeared to ride, if not enjoy, the twists and turns of the
impeachment process more than Graham. The junior U.S. senator in
South Carolina, Ernest Hollings, a 77-year-old Democrat, likened
the ordeal to ``passing a kidney stone.''
</P>
<P>
   But for Graham, 43, one of the 1994 class of Republican
revolutionaries, a chance to demonstrate a down-home folksiness
that stood in sharp contrast to the dour scowls and legal mumbo
jumbo of many of his fellow managers. He became an instant hit on
the all-Monica-all-the-time cable channels.
</P>
<P>
   Was the Lewinsky scandal Watergate or Peyton Place? he mused out
loud. What, after all, is a high crime, he asked. ``How about if an
important person hurts somebody of low means?''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday night, Graham's district, which covers much of the up
country in the northwestern part of South Carolina _ rewarded him
in his first town meeting here since last August. Of the two dozen
questions he was asked, half were about impeachment. Many called
him a hero. One shouted he should run for president and drew more
applause.
</P>
<P>
   Miranda Fowler, 30, a certified public accountant, said after
the meeting that she thought it was entirely appropriate that
Graham devote so much time to impeachment. ``I've been following
this story since it first broke,'' she said, indicating she
approved of Graham's role. ``He didn't go after the president. He
just looked at the facts and put them into everyday language. He's
got a bright future ahead of him.''
</P>
<P>
   The natural assumption is that Graham, the first Republican
elected here since 1877, will use his exposure in the impeachment
case as a springboard to higher office. But some say his current
popularity is fleeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't have the legs to run the distance,'' said Dick
Harpootlian, the state's Democratic Party chairman, who vows to put
up a candidate against him in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because people don't like Bill Clinton doesn't mean they
do like Lindsey Graham,'' Harpootlian said in a telephone interview
from Columbia. ``Once Lindsey Graham's 15 minutes of Jerry Springer
fame fades, people in his district will understand that he's
carrying water for the radical right.''
</P>
<P>
   Even some on his own side think Graham would do well to move on.
``The smart thing for him to do,'' said Whit Ayres, an
Atlanta-based pollster who has worked extensively in South
Carolina, ``is to use the name recognition that he's developed
through this process to build some legislative achievements. This
is the start, rather than the end, of a political career.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
