<HEADER>
A7821 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JASPER-TRIAL-COX     02-16 1007
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JASPER-TRIAL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Racial death aimed to recruit white supremacists, jury told
 &HT;    By Denise Gamino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JASPER, Texas _ James Byrd Jr. lost his life behind a
zig-zagging pickup truck because a neo-Nazi needed to perform a
high-profile feat to earn respect for his new hate group _ the
Texas Rebel Soldiers, a jury was told Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen members of the Byrd family filled the first two rows in
the Jasper County courtroom as a jury of 11 whites and one black
heard the first day of testimony in the trial of John William
``Bill'' King, 24, the alleged ringleader of Byrd's barbaric
dragging death.
</P>
<P>
   At times, Byrd's daughters left the courtroom in tears. His
eldest daughter, Renee Mullins, 28, fled when a prosecutor, wearing
latex gloves, pulled the first item of Byrd's tattered clothing
from a brown paper evidence bag. The white underwear wasshredded
and stained with dirt or dried blood.
</P>
<P>
   King's father had a front-row seat across the aisle from the
Byrd family, but the families did not speak. Ronald King was
accompanied by a local Catholic priest.
</P>
<P>
   King, 24, is one of three white men accused of dragging Byrd, a
disabled black man, nearly three miles on a backwoods road until he
was decapitated last June. The murder shocked the world and brought
unwanted shame to this pine forested town of 8,000 near the
Louisiana state line.
</P>
<P>
   ''Not guilty, your honor,'' was the only thing King said on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But the jury heard much more from King in the form of the
written
</P>
<P>
   word. Prosecutors introduced into evidence dozens of King's
handwritten letters and tracts that he laced with racist threats
and dogma.
</P>
<P>
   ''White is right!!!'' King wrote in a 1996 prison letter to a
white Jasper girl whom he called ''my precious Aryan princess.'' In
a racially incedinary letter, he said that white women are race
traitors for dating black men and should be lynched alongside them.
</P>
<P>
   King wrote a code of ethics, by-laws and recruitment letters as
captain of the Texas Rebel Soldiers, a branch of the Confederate
Knights of America, a white supremacy group.
</P>
<P>
   ''Evidence (will show) that Bill King needed to do something
dramatic that would attract media attention in order to gain, in
their warped world, respect for his newly formed gang,'' Jasper
County District Attorney Guy James Gray told jurors in his
10-minute opening statement.
</P>
<P>
   Gray said King is a neo-Nazi whose body and arms are covered
with white supremacy tattoos _ a Confederate flag, a burning cross,
a lynched black man, an ''Aryan Pride'' symbol, and swastikas.
''He's what they call a full-sleever,'' Gray said.
</P>
<P>
   ''This young man is full of hate,'' Gray said.
</P>
<P>
   The two court-appointed defense attorneys for King did not make
any opening statements to the jury. But they wasted no time in
objecting to much of the evidence offered by the prosecution, which
includes two assistant U.S. attorneys from Beaumont.
</P>
<P>
   Brack Jones Jr. said the government's photographs of Byrd's
battered body were ''inflammatory and and overly gruesome,'' but
State District Judge Joe Bob Golden allowed the jury to see the
photos.
</P>
<P>
   The jury, which includes a black man who went to middle school
with King and now works in a private prison, had been seated for
just over an hour when the 14 photographs of Byrd's dismembered
body were introduced.
</P>
<P>
   Each juror was given a bound copy of a notebook with 8x10 color
glossy photos showing Byrd's body as it was found on the rural road
on June as well as at the autopsy.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're pretty rough to handle, particularly for some of you
ladies,'' Gray said. ''It will be a little rough, but you can do
it.''
</P>
<P>
   One woman wiped her eyes as she viewed the photos, and several
other jurors scowled.
</P>
<P>
   The jury is comprised of five white women, six white men and one
black man. A white man and a white woman serve as alternates.
Prosecutors, who originally summoned 400 Jasper County residents
for jury selection, had hoped to have three blacks on the jury
because of the controversial racial nature of the crime.
</P>
<P>
   The jurors arrived together in a white van from the Jasper
Hillcrest Baptist Church with armed escorts, but they are not being
sequestered during the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors used an overhead projector to show jurors some of
King's prolific writings and close-ups of his tattoos, including a
satanic pentagram-type symbol on the back of his head.
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorneys objected to exhibits about the tattoos because
they said King's skin art was protected by the U.S. Constitution's
protection of free association. The judge overruled the objections.
</P>
<P>
   The first witness in the trial was Jasper County Sheriff Billy
Rowles, who recounted walking several miles over the road where
Byrd died and marking the spots where Byrd's body parts and
belongings were found. He said he feared the worse when a lighter
engraved with a KKK symbol was found nearby.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm a brand new sheriff, and I didn't even know the definition
of a hate crime,'' Rowles said. ''But I knew somebody was murdered
because he was black.''
</P>
<P>
   As Rowles spoke, King's father took the oxygen tube he uses
because of emphasyma and nervously twisted it around his finger.
</P>
<P>
   Across the aisle, some of Byrd's six sisters clutched tissues
and dabbed their eyes. Byrd's one brother kept his arm around one
of his sisters most of the day.
</P>
<P>
   King never glanced at the Byrd family, and he kept his eyes
locked on the table where he sat when one of the dead man's sisters
testified about what clothing her brother wore on the day he was
killed.
</P>
<P>
   The Bryd family prepared for the trial by gathering Monday night
and watching videos of James Byrd Jr., playing the piano and
singing with his parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all crowded together and we encouraged and supported one
another,'' said Clara Taylor, one of Byrd's sisters.
</P>
<P>
   Denise Gamino writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
