<SLUG> BC-HEWLETT-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEWLETT-PACKARD TOPS EARNINGS ESTIMATES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Hewlett-Packard Co. reported mixed financial
results on Tuesday, with first-quarter earnings well above Wall
Street analysts' estimates, but both revenues and orders below
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Hewlett-Packard fell $5.9375, to $70.50, on the New
York Stock Exchange. The earnings were released after the markets
closed.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said Hewlett-Packard's ability to deliver strong
earnings despite slow revenue growth spoke well for the company's
financial management. But they said the company must soon show it
could also increase sales. Hewlett-Packard management had at one
time suggested the company could have double-digit sales growth
this year, a goal they conceded on Tuesday that they were unlikely
to reach.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have clearly developed a low-revenue-growth kind of
model, and it worked very well this quarter,'' said Daniel
Kunstler, an analyst with J.P. Morgan. ``Clearly by moderating PC
growth, they were able to turn up earnings,'' he said, referring to
previous quarters when the company pursued market share in personal
computers at the expense of profitability. ``But I think there are
going to be many questions about the top line,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For the quarter, which ended Jan. 31, Hewlett-Packard reported
earnings of $960 million, or 92 cents a diluted share, up 3.3
percent from $929 million, or 86 cents a share, in the period a
year earlier. Revenues rose 1 percent, to $11.94 billion, from
$11.82 billion in the first quarter of the 1998 fiscal year.
Per-share figures reflect a reduction in the number of shares
outstanding.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts expected Hewlett-Packard to earn 83 cents a share,
according to First Call Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've achieved a good profit outcome despite softness in some
of our businesses and weak revenue growth,'' Lewis Platt,
Hewlett-Packard's chairman, president and chief executive, said in
a statement. ``Even businesses whose revenue was weak or negative
turned in decent profitability,'' he said. ``Still, we're not
meeting our growth objectives. We need to stay sharply focused on
stimulating business while remaining sensitive to the need for
careful expense management.''
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard said total orders were down 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard's weakest business was test and measurement
equipment, which declined 14 percent. Revenue from Unix-based
computer systems also declined compared with a strong quarter a
year earlier, mostly attributed to weak sales in the midrange,
which has changed products. PC revenue growth was mixed, because of
the company's emphasis on profitability, while printer growth was
strong.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly the company has to do something on the product side to
get revenue growth,'' said Steven Milunovich, an analyst with
Merrill Lynch. ``In addition to products they need to articulate an
Internet vision. They've sort of been left out of that,'' he said,
allowing Sun Microsystems and IBM to take the lead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
