<DOCNO> NYT19990216.0435 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-16 22:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7826 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAQFLAK-AZR &LR;      02-16 1549
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQFLAK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARIZONANS FLY INTO AIR DANGER ZONE OVER IRAQ  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DENNIS WAGNER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEAR THE IRAQI BORDER _ An Air Force stratotanker had nearly
finished its three-hour refueling mission along Iraq's northern
border Monday when voices of alarm squealed over the headset:
``Triple-A airburst! Triple-A airburst at Bull 135!''
</P>
<P>
   Capt. Aaron Vangelisti, an Arizona National Guardsman and pilot
of the KC-135, craned his neck looking out the cockpit window.
Iraqi anti-aircraft fire was confirmed by white puffs of smoke
visible above the cloud line to the south.
</P>
<P>
   Other voices began to squawk over the radio in rapid fire
succession.
</P>
<P>
   ``Miller is attacking Target 54 from the west . . . unauthorized
aircraft . . . the SAM missile launch . . . There it is. See the
contrail?''
</P>
<P>
   For crew members aboard Ice One, the Arizona National Guard's
refueling ship, it was a gripping moment in the cat-and-mouse
military game being played by Iraqi President Saddam Hussein and
his troops.
</P>
<P>
   Moments earlier, a pair of F-15s had taken turns hooking up to a
boom that hangs from the tail of this flying gas station. The
fighter jets appeared to be motionless as they sucked up tons of
fuel while traveling at 460 miles per hour, eyeball to eyeball with
the boom operator.
</P>
<P>
   Once sated, they rolled away 26,000 feet over southern Turkey
and headed into the no-fly zone. Six other fighters had done the
same thing during this mission, which crew members said went
smoothly.
</P>
<P>
   But then, as the KC-135 finished its last elliptical pattern
over jagged, snow-capped peaks, at least two surface-to-air
missiles were fired by Iraqi ground forces.
</P>
<P>
   Tech. Sgt. Steve Hanson climbed into the boom pod _ a windowed
cavity in the jet's tail _ and watched the rear through portals. If
a missile was coming, he'd help Vangelisti decide out how to get
out of the way.
</P>
<P>
   The radio traffic grew confusing as two journalists watched and
listened from vantage points aboard the tanker. Air Force officials
said they were the first civilian reporters allowed onto Turkey's
Incirlik air base, or on an Operation Northern Watch mission, in
more than three years. And they'd gotten into the thick of it.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning in late December, Iraqi forces started taking potshots
at U.S., British and Turkish aircraft in the no-fly zones. The
areas of northern and southern Iraq were established as part of the
complex U.S. and U.N. formula to contain and control Saddam Hussein
after the Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   Although coalition fliers and support teams have been acting as
sky cops for more than eight years, public awareness pops up seldom
_ except when there is an exchange of fire. Yet on an almost daily
basis thousands of personnel here and in the United Arab Emirates
have been sending up fighter jets, reconnaissance planes, AWACS
airborne command ships and refueling tankers to patrol the border
airspace.
</P>
<P>
   Operation Northern Watch began three years ago. U.S. authorities
say none of their planes has been hit since then. Pilots and crew
members nervously joke about the feebleness and inaccuracy of Iraqi
firepower. But in dozens of interviews, they also acknowledged a
nagging fear that the Iraqis could score a lucky hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody'd be lying if they told you they weren't scared out
there,'' said Tech. Sgt. Bill Garrett, a boom operator on his way
home to Avondale after three weeks based at Incirlik.
</P>
<P>
   The anxiety level escalated in recent weeks as Iraqi gunners
became emboldened by political instability in Turkey and news
reports suggesting that Saddam would get new weapons from Russia.
On Monday, as Ice One flew within miles of the Iraqi border, Tariq
Aziz, Iraq's deputy prime minister, was in Ankara trying to
persuade Turkish officials to keep the Americans and British out of
Incirlik.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Vangelisti was trying to cope with a missile and
anti-aircraft fire. He said his mind locked on a series of
defensive strategies _ something he and other Guard members have
trained for constantly from their base at Sky Harbor International
Airport. But this time, the hostile fire was real. Vangelisti also
flashed on his wife, Heidi, and their 2-year-old daughter, Bryanna,
back home in Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know where it was,'' Vangelisti said of the flak.
What he did know is that the KC-135 is particularly vulnerable; a
Boeing jetliner that, instead of passengers, carries tons of fuel
in its fuselage and wings.
</P>
<P>
   National Guard units from Arizona and other states fly these
sitting ducks in vulturelike circles just a few miles above Iraq's
northern line. Their job is to fuel the attack aircraft responsible
for enforcing no-fly conditions.
</P>
<P>
   National Guard crews are not active duty Air Force personnel,
but weekend warriors who volunteer once or twice a year to go on
refueling missions. Arizona's wing includes teachers, cops,
accountants and bureaucrats who leave their jobs behind, traveling
7,000 miles around the world on three-week tours.
</P>
<P>
   Vangelisti is a United Airlines pilot. Hanson is a Peoria
firefighter. Maj. Gunnar Buzzard of Scottsdale, another pilot, is
president of a computer company.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona Guard has six KC-135s based at Incirlik. Over a
two-month period, more than 300 members will have left home to
support this refueling mission _ not just pilots and boom
operators, but maintenance crews, intelligence specialists and
ground support.
</P>
<P>
   During Monday's shootout, in fact, the Arizona Guard had three
KC-135s aloft, crewed mostly by Valley residents.
</P>
<P>
   Before Ice One took off at dawn, Lt. Col. Joe Smith, the Guard's
public information officer, warned of potential combat conditions.
If the tanker starts swerving, he said, that means Iraqi aircraft
have penetrated the no-fly zone and we're getting out. Smith added
that the KC-135s are protected by a unified team of aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   If Saddam's fliers breach the border, Smith said, ``They'll be
killed.''
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, Hanson lay on his belly in the boom pod and added
more sober words: ``If we do go down, I want you to do exactly what
I tell you. There's going to be good people looking for you, and
maybe bad people . . . this is not a game.''
</P>
<P>
   Hanson, 44, recited emergency procedures, showing how to open
doors, slide down ropes and run for cover.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't be waiting for anybody,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For three hours the flight was unremarkable except for the raw
beauty of southern Turkey. Rising from the tarmac at Incirlik,
there is a view of fertile croplands and the teeming city of Adana.
That sight yields in moments to the Mediterranean coast, and then
to magnificent peaks ranging east and south from the air base. The
terrain is cold, white and bleak.
</P>
<P>
   As crew members looked down they managed to break tension with
occasional wisecracks. Shortly after takeoff, someone asked, ``We
all right?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Just a little chest pain,'' came the answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Breathe deep.''
</P>
<P>
   Mostly they focused on the job at hand, taking navigational
readings, checking fuel levels, flying toward Iraq. This was their
last mission after a three-week tour and they didn't want anything
to go wrong. Once they reached the appointed refueling pattern,
F-15s and F-16s took turns hooking up to the dangling boom, then
rolling away to patrol duties.
</P>
<P>
   The first hint of trouble came via radio reports of a smoke
plume in Iraq. Fighters with code names like Mad Dog and Reaper
closed in for a look. Moments later, the Triple-A salvos were
hurled skyward, followed by a pair of missiles. It was impossible
to tell who was targeted or how many rounds were fired.
</P>
<P>
   One crew member said there was no doubt who Saddam was aiming at
because the KC-135 is a big, slow, valuable asset.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those missiles were fired at us,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But others indicated that the missiles were launched from 60
miles away and fizzled after traveling about 30 miles north. The
flak also was a long way off. After making some quick mental
calculations, Vangelisti decided there was no need to take evasive
action. At that point, he said, ``We were just in a front-row
seat.''
</P>
<P>
   Dave Hanson of Tempe (no relation to Steve), a backup boom
operator, took it all in stride.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were far enough away and all those (U.S.) fighter pilots
were out there,'' Hanson said after Ice One had landed safely. ``I
mean, it was interesting, but I had paperwork to do up there.''
</P>
<P>
   Only after Guard members, known as Copperheads, returned to
Incirlik did they learn the full story of what went on. U.S.
fighter jets answered the Iraqi volleys by blasting away at Iraq's
anti-aircraft batteries. Saddam responded with threats to attack
not only U.S. aircraft, but Incirlik and other American military
bases _ through the skies or via terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   As Arizona crewmen later boarded a flight from Turkey to Spain
to New Jersey to Phoenix, U.S. officials were taking the threat
seriously. Personnel at Incirlik reportedly were barred from
leaving the base due to concerns about terrorism. That included
about 120 Arizona National Guard members who continue enforcing the
no-fly zone as part of Operation Northern Watch. &QL; 
Dennis Wagner can be reached at 444-8874 or at
dennis.wagner(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
