<SLUG> BC-BKN-BERKOW-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: ENFORCER RETURNS TO GARDEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By IRA BERKOW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Used to be that after having played against the
Knicks, opponents needed respirators and paramedics in order to
leave the arena. And the major cause of such mayhem was Charles
Oakley, all 6 feet 9 inches and 245 foreboding pounds of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time I went to the basket, I knew I was going to be hit
by Charles Oakley,'' Grant Hill recalled Tuesday with a kind of
respect, and maybe some admiration, too. ``So I always made sure I
knew where he was on the court, to be prepared.''
</P>
<P>
   Every player in the league knew that he was going to be hit by
Charles Oakley _ still does. But it is Charles Oakley in a
different uniform, the shocking purple of the Toronto Raptors, and
not the orange, white and blue of the Knicks. And Tuesday night
Oakley returned to Madison Square Garden, the scene of so many of
his greatest collisions, clobbers and clouts, for the first time
since he was traded for Marcus Camby over the summer.
</P>
<P>
   He had expressed unhappiness about being traded from the team he
had been a part of for 10 years _ or at least the manner in which
he was traded _ but then Oakley wears unhappiness as a kind of
badge. (There was a leaked report the night of the trade, and
Knicks general manager Ernie Grunfeld said he tried but couldn't
reach Oakley until later in the night.)
</P>
<P>
   Grumpiness was one of the elements that made Oakley so endearing
to Knick fans. One always got the impression that Charles' shoes,
or shorts, fit too tight. And maybe that was part of the motivation
for his energetic play, which included his diving head first into
the stands for the ball, crashing into and flummoxing fans. It was
never a good idea to sit with a drink or a box of popcorn in your
hands in the first five rows of a Knick game with Oakley in
attendance.
</P>
<P>
   One fan, who has sat courtside for 25 years, wrote of him in The
New York Observer last year: ``Oakley has been a consistently
tremendous ballplayer for the New York Knicks who has contributed
mightily night after night, season after season, and actually gets
better with age. Of course, I'd hate to wake up in the middle of
the night and find him hovering over my bed with that look on his
face, but on the court he's worth every cent they pay him.''
</P>
<P>
   That was Woody Allen's assessment, and most Knick fans would
surely agree with it. But times change, and the Knicks sought a
young, springy Camby _ Oakley is 35, Camby 24.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might work out for them,'' said Hill, whose Piston team
lost to the Knicks Monday afternoon, ``but right now they miss
Oakley.''
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Ewing, the Knicks' often enigmatic center, said that he
missed Oakley, though Oakley wondered about that. ``He never told
me that,'' Oakley said before Tuesday night's game, which the
Knicks won, 95-85. The two never were bosom pals, and sometimes
Oakley, after a good game, shooed reporters from his locker. ``How
come you're comin' over to me now?'' he said more than once. ``Why
don't you go back to Patrick's locker, where y'all usually are?''
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, there was significant interest in Oakley's return to
the Garden, and he received a standing ovation Tuesday night when
introduced before the game. At halftime, the Knicks put on a film
tribute of Oakley's career, which had to include some of his most
arresting fouls. Oakley, who was never a great shooter (though a
competent one when standing in one spot), who often fell when he
tried to dribble, who was a decent passer when he wasn't trying to
be fancy and flinging the ball behind his back and over the
scorer's table, was a good defender, a ferocious rebounder and a
general terror.
</P>
<P>
   He holds a little-known National Basketball Association career
record of having committed 30 flagrant fouls _ that is, contact
deemed excessive, and/or unnecessary _ since that infraction was
instituted nine seasons ago (next in line are those righteous
brothers _ Charles Barkley with 26, and Dennis Rodman, 21).
</P>
<P>
   Oakley has been suspended twice because of the thumping number
of flagrants in a given season, also a record.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know some people been building this up like a Tyson-Evander
Holyfield rematch,'' Oakley said before Tuesday night's game, ``but
it's not. I'm not gonna bite anyone's ear off. I don't carry a
grudge.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he had nothing but good thoughts about New York, which
gave him an opportunity to, he said, ``expand my business
interests.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the game: ``I'm not gonna get caught up in trying to
score 20 points. I'm just gonna try to help my team win.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is what Charles Oakley has always tried to do. Often to
the benefit of the team he was playing for, as well as to the good
fortune of those in the neighborhood selling medical supplies. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
