<SLUG> BC-BRITISH-AMERICAN-ACTORS-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ACTOR WARS: ANOTHER CHAPTER  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, FEB. 21) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By FELICIA R. LEE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The trade agreement governing the number of British and American
actors working on opposite sides of the Atlantic is under attack by
Britain's main international cultural agency, prompting hopes that
the unions involved will reconsider the arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   Under the current rules, a producer who wants to bring a British
actor to New York must seek the approval of Actors Equity, the
American union, just as British Equity's approval is needed to
allow an American actor to go to Britain.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, the two unions try to balance the exchange, and there
are categories for exemptions. For example, actors who are
``stars'' need not be approved. But over the years, some Britons
have charged that provisions for exchange have been unevenly and
unfairly applied.
</P>
<P>
   The sometimes bitter wrangling was reactivated a little more
than two weeks ago with the release of a critical report from the
Arts Council, Britain's principal agency for international cultural
relations.
</P>
<P>
   The report said that American Equity's influence in the actor
exchange ``is unquestionably operating in restraint of free trade
between the countries.'' It added that the American union's
rationale for its approach was based on ``short-term quasi-economic
arguments for which there is little if any justification.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Americans have said that because so much British theater is
government subsidized and because it costs less both to produce
shows in Britain and to use their casts of British actors in New
York, jobs for Americans would be reduced in a more open
marketplace in which Britain would be even more alluring.
</P>
<P>
   It costs roughly $300,000 to mount a straight play in London,
compared with some $1.5 million in New York. Also, American actors
make more money than their British counterparts and must maintain
their American pay standards if they work in London, according to
American Equity their American pay standards if they work in
London, according to American Equity agreements.
</P>
<P>
   The Arts Council report argues that the current policies mean
that audiences in both countries miss seeing a great deal of
theater and that many actors lose opportunities to work.
</P>
<P>
   Jed Bernstein, executive director of the League of American
Theaters and Producers, the trade organization, said recently that
the current system was a failure. But Alan Eisenberg, executive
director of American Equity, said that the trade agreement was
still needed to protect American jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd like to see a subsidy situation in this country,''
Eisenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   The league advocates a joint fund for American actors in England
with the Society of London Theater, the British counterpart to the
league, and the Theatrical Management Association, which represents
regional theaters. Money from the fund would help pay the higher
salaries for American actors that are dictated by American Equity.
</P>
<P>
   The league also favors the creation of a forum in the United
States for British producers to audition American talent, and that
videotapes of Broadway shows housed at the New York Public Library
for the Performing Arts at Lincoln Center be made available to the
London Theater Museum, with an eye toward showing off talent on
both sides of the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   Members of British and American Equities and the two trade
organizations met in London in 1997 but did not reach any
resolution. Next month, British Equity will present the Arts
Council report to its members. All four parties say they are open
to meeting again sometime this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a terribly difficult situation and emotions run high,''
Sally Cowling, head of Drama and Dance for the Arts Council said in
a telephone interview from London. ``It's the only situation of its
kind in the world and terribly close to artists' hearts.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-99 2228EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990216.0438 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-16 22:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7833 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAPAN-BASKETS-ANTIQUE     02-16 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-BASKETS-ANTIQUES-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPANESE RARITIES THAT EVEN THE JAPANESE SELDOM SEE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, FEB. 21) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., N.Y., N.J., N.M.)   (af)  
 By RITA REIF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lloyd E. Cotsen, a mega-collector of ordinary and offbeat
objects that most people ignore, goes to great lengths to share
them with the public. He gave 40,000 children's books to the
Firestone Library at Princeton University, and he sent 2,500 pieces
of folk art and textiles to the Museum of International Folk Art in
Santa Fe, N.M.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Cotsen, who is 69 and lives in Los Angeles, is letting the
public view his most treasured artifacts _ Japanese bamboo baskets.
The 900 baskets in his collection, which is considered the largest
and most distinguished in private hands, are a type of artifact
that is virtually unknown to all but a small group of experts, even
in Japan, where such objects are seldom exhibited.
</P>
<P>
   So Cotsen lent 100 rarities to the Asia Society in Manhattan for
``Bamboo Masterworks: Japanese Baskets from the Lloyd Cotsen
Collection,'' a show on view through May 30.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've collected baskets for 40 years,'' he said. ``I'm always
testing myself to be sure that I choose a basket visually _ first
for its form, then for its texture and finally for its technique.
It goes from my eye to my heart to my head.''
</P>
<P>
   Cotsen mastered his hunting and gathering skills as a boy,
chasing after baseball cards, stamps, marbles, used matchbooks and
the Big Little Books that many of his generation remember from
childhood. As an adult, he amassed huge, scholarly collections,
like the two he gave away.
</P>
<P>
   The folk art was donated with Neutrogena Corp., makers of
moisturizers and health care products, of which he was chairman and
chief executive until 1994 when he sold the company for $924
million to Johnson &AMP; Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   His basket collection is chock full of sculptural prizes. The
most distinctive in the show resemble a Nautilus shell, a cone of
pick up sticks, a wine glass sprouting twigs and the spiraling form
of the Guggenheim Museum in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   He bought his first basket in 1953, when he went to Japan as a
lieutenant in the United States Navy. On a visit to Kyushu, he
picked up a box-like bamboo work fitted with trays like a picnic
basket. Five years later, on a trip to San Francisco, he acquired a
curvy flower basket that was purposely dented in on one side, a
feature that proved irresistible to him. He has been a confirmed
collector ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, even the most imaginative baskets Cotsen acquired
were anonymous works. But in recent years he has bought numerous
signed baskets, assisted by Mary Hunt Kahlenberg, his chief
curator, who helped organize the show at the Asia Society, and
Robert Coffland, her husband. Coffland visited artists in Japan to
find works that he photographed or sent back for Cotsen's
consideration.
</P>
<P>
   The show also includes baskets by Japan's most celebrated
masters of the craft _ the three artists who have been named Living
National Treasures. A tall, angular bowl with deep pockets and a
star-patterned base was created by Shono Shounsai, the first so
honored, in 1967. A satiny black basket of knotted bows is by Izuka
Shokansai (1982), and a basket of thin twigs shaped like
overlapping waves is by Maeda Chikubosai II (1995).
</P>
<P>
   Other artists who were not so recognized fashioned baskets in
equally stunning ways: Izuka Rokansai devised a pocketbook-like
basket from a single sheet of bamboo in the 1930s and Higashi
Takesonosai bent scores of bamboo rods into a glorious rolling wave
in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the spirited shaping of Japanese baskets began a
century ago when artists changed the traditional cylindrical,
rectangular and bowl-like forms long popular in Japan, forms that
had originated in ancient China. By exaggerating the asymmetrical
shapes, the robust proportions and the daring scale, the craftsmen
transformed the conventional baskets into ones that were more
Japanese in character.
</P>
<P>
   In one provocative piece in the show, a tiny basket perches like
a hat on top of a tall, skinny Eiffel Tower-like base. This
triumphant work was signed by Izuka Hosai II, a late-19th-century
artist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Japanese basket producers are masters at making the complex
look simple,'' Cotsen said. ``You look at a basket and don't see
the understructure of knots that hold the weaving in place.''
</P>
<P>
   Cotsen takes pleasure in discovering knots and other secrets
artists have hidden in their baskets. On a vivid orange
window-box-like basket, he was puzzled by the base, which is plain
inside but elaborately patterned outside, until he noticed that it
had a false bottom.
</P>
<P>
   More subtle was the basket that looked as supple as a weaving of
satin ribbons but was in fact woven of 300-year-old sooted bamboo
strips, bands so brittle that they had to be softened into a
silkenlike mesh by a painstaking moisturizing process.
</P>
<P>
   It is a basket that Cotsen loves to touch, but other people dare
not, fearing it might crumble. ``I'm interested in how things
feel,'' he said. ``That's part of what attracts me to these
baskets.''
</P>
<P>
   And since no two baskets ever feel the same, he touches every
one _ often. ``After all,'' he said, ``I've spent my life in the
skin business.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
