</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENQUIRER-BOUGHT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTMENT GROUP BUYS THE NATIONAL ENQUIRER AND STAR MAGAZINE
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A Manhattan investment firm has purchased the company
that owns The National Enquirer and Star magazine and hired the
head of the nation's third-largest magazine publisher to run and
expand it.
</P>
<P>
   The investment group, Evercore Capital Partners LLC, headed by
former Deputy Treasury Secretary Roger C. Altman, announced on
Tuesday that it had acquired the publications for $294 million from
American Media Inc., and that David J. Pecker, the president and
chief executive officer of Hachette Filipacchi Magazines, a unit of
Lagardere Group, would head the company and receive an equity
stake. American Media is a public company whose two biggest
stockholders are the venture capital firm Boston Ventures and
MacFadden Holdings Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Pecker's goal, along with his new partners at Evercore, is to
extend the National Enquirer brand to an array of new ventures that
may include more television programming, new magazines _ such as
Enquirer spinoffs for teen-agers and Hispanic readers _ and online
services. The company owns Country Weekly and The Weekly World
News.
</P>
<P>
   The move comes after years of declining circulation for The
Enquirer as Americans have begun to see reporting that might once
have been considered salacious or sensational appear in mainstream
publications.
</P>
<P>
   The National Enquirer has a circulation of 2,300,000, according
to the Audit Bureau of Circulations, down from its 1977 high of 5
million.
</P>
<P>
   The news weekly regularly runs articles about celebrity diets
and hardly an issue goes by without some sort of swipe at Monica
Lewinsky (``Monica's Gay Secret _ Shocking Report From Inside the
White House''), but in a quest to raise sagging circulation, it has
tried to run more legitimate articles. Steve Coz, the editor of The
Enquirer, said Tuesday that he had tried to make the weekly
newspaper more appealing to readers, most recently asking Roseanne
Barr to guest-edit the newest issue. Ms. Barr once guest-edited an
issue of The New Yorker.
</P>
<P>
   The transaction included the assumption of $473 million in debt.
</P>
<P>
   The venture is not without financial risk. American Media's
total revenue for the nine months ended in December was $222.2
million, of which advertising was $16.9 million, or a relatively
small 7.6 percent. Operating income for those six months was $43.2
million, but the company had $35.6 million in interest expense and
$8.3 million in taxes. The company had net income of $569,000, down
from $6.8 million in the period a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop Cheen, an analyst who follows the company for First Union
Capital Markets, said American Media had failed to move
aggressively in the changed news environment. ``They were going to
buy Canadian tabloids, go down to Mexico,'' he said. ``But they
never did anything with the company. So they shouldered the costs
of newsprints without any economy of scale. And the ad economy has
been great, but they didn't participate because advertising is such
a small part of its revenues.''
</P>
<P>
   Pecker called The Enquirer and Star ``the two most undermarketed
and underpromoted newspapers in this country.''
</P>
<P>
   In his decade as president of Hachette magazines, Pecker earned
something of a reputation as an enfant terrible with an arduous eye
on the bottom line. He cut editorial staffs, slashed budgets and
offered deep discounts to choice advertisers. He posed for
photographs astride motorcycles or with cigars dangling from his
lips. And during his tenure, he built the magazine publisher into a
competitor in the American marketplace, promoting Elle magazine in
such a way that it has leaped over Harper's Bazaar and now trails
only one women's magazine, Vogue, in both circulation and
advertising revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Pecker began several divisions within Hachette, including
Hachette New Media and Hachette Productions, which produces films
like the Isaac Mizrahi documentary ``Unzipped'' and television
programming. And he attracted a burst of publicity by introducing
George, which is edited by John F. Kennedy Jr.
</P>
<P>
   The purchase is Evercore's second as a private equity investor _
its first was a company that sells insulation products _ so it is
clear that it could use Pecker's assets as a magazine publisher.
Altman is one of the firm's three founders and continues to be a
partner. He did not return a phone call to his home. Pecker would
not disclose the percentage of his equity stake.
</P>
<P>
   Pecker will leave Hachette on March 31. Following his departure,
the day-to-day operations of Hachette Filipacchi will be overseen
by Daniel Filipachhi, the chairman of Hachette Filipacchi
Magazines. No successor has been announced.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
