<HEADER>
A7838 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANCIENT-MIAMI-COX     02-16 1157
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANCIENT-MIAMI-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Time running out to save ancient Miami site
 &HT;    By Mike Williams
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ A Buddhist with a shaved head and flowing white robe
skips barefooted down the street with an armful of leaflets, while
an earnest young New Age researcher slaps duct tape to a bed sheet
banner. Nearby, votive candles flicker in the South Florida
twilight while two Native American holy men beat drums and chant
their prayers to the rising stars.
</P>
<P>
   And somewhere in one of the gleaming glass-and-steel high rises
overlooking this neck of Miami's financial district, a developer
with $100 million at stake must be shaking his head and wondering
what laws of karma have their teeth firmly clenched around his back
pocket.
</P>
<P>
   Plans for twin towers filled with luxury shops and apartments on
one of the last open waterfront parcels remaining in Miami's
downtown district have run aground on the discovery of an ancient
Native American ceremonial circle hewn from the limestone rock
underlying the site.
</P>
<P>
   As in the science fiction movie ``Contact,'' in which news of an
intelligent message beamed to Earth from outer space sparks an
outpouring of spiritual froth, the Miami Circle _ as it's come to
be known _ has triggered an international flurry among everyone
from New Age spiritualists
</P>
<P>
   and Internet-browsing shamans
</P>
<P>
   to academics, tourism-minded boosters and fast-talking
politicians.
</P>
<P>
   And for good reason, the experts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've never found anything as profoundly unique as this,''
Miami-Dade County Archaeologist Robert Carr told Miami City
Commissioners at a jam-packed meeting Tuesday. ``This is the only
site known of this type in all of North America.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past few weeks, dozens of protesters have gathered daily
on a draw bridge overlooking the site, which sits by the mouth of
the Miami River. They hold banners pleading with powers political
and otherworldly to ``Save the Circle,'' sometimes chanting,
praying and singing through a bullhorn, as drivers speeding past
honk and wave.
</P>
<P>
   An Internet site, www.MiamiCircle.org, lays out theories on the
site's mysterious makers, while Florida Gov. Jeb Bush has been
swamped with calls and e-mails begging the state to intervene.
</P>
<P>
   ``This didn't happen by coincidence,'' said Christopher Lee, a
Buddhist who has joined the throngs on the bridge. ``Read the
Celestine Prophecy or other New Age books about the Aztecs or the
Mayans or other ancient cultures. The developer may think he owns
this land, but you don't own anything. It's all our planet. We all
own it together, and we need to save this site to learn from the
people who were here first.''
</P>
<P>
   But the ancient circle may not lay undisturbed much longer.
</P>
<P>
   After cooperating with researchers for months, developer Michael
Baumann says he can no longer afford to delay construction. He has
given archaeologists until Feb. 26 to remove the circle or make a
plaster cast of it, saying he'll pay for the work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have cooperated and will continue to cooperate,'' said
Vicky Garcia-Toledo, Baumann's attorney. ``But you have to
understand, the developer is ready to proceed.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, Baumann's ultimatum has rung hollow. A stone mason he
hired who was supposed to begin cutting the circle out of the
ground this week backed out at the last second after speaking with
a Seminole Indian holy man who has set up vigil outside a
chain-link fence surrounding the 2.2-acre plot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just came to the conclusion that this was not something I
could do in good conscience,'' mason Joshua Billig said. ``I didn't
realize how important this is to so many people.''
</P>
<P>
   Miami-Dade County Mayor Alex Penelas wants to save the circle,
and has barraged state and federal officials with calls trying to
come up with money to buy out Baumann. So far, he has no firm money
in hand.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Penelas appealed to the Miami City Commission for a
solid commitment to preserving the circle, which lies within
Miami's city limits.
</P>
<P>
   But Miami's commissioners passed only a lukewarm resolution
urging Baumann to save the site. The city, just emerging from a
long financial nightmare that saw it teetering on the verge of
bankruptcy, has no money to buy the land. Officials also fear
making any statements that might discourage Baumann's financial
backers, which could lead to a lawsuit against the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``The City of Miami is not going to be the fall guy and end up
paying $40 million to $50 million or even $60 million,'' Miami
Mayor Joe Carollo said Tuesday. ``That would mean the end of us as
an entity.''
</P>
<P>
   And so the Feb. 26 deadline looms.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers believe the site may have been used by Native
Americans as long ago as 2,000 years, but date the circle to only
about 800 years ago. They believe it was built by the Tequesta
Indians, who inhabited a village near the river mouth in the 1500s
when Spanish explorer Ponce de Leon explored Florida.
</P>
<P>
   The site was actually covered for the past 50 years by an
apartment building, which was knocked down last summer to make way
for Baumann's development, to be called Brickell Pointe. A surveyor
spotted some relics and called in Carr, who, with Baumann's
permission, took a closer look.
</P>
<P>
   So far he has found some 200 holes that form a perfect circle 38
feet in diameter, perhaps dug to hold up poles on some type of
ceremonial lodge. He also found two stone axes, however, which are
made from rock not native to Florida.
</P>
<P>
   That discovery_plus the fact that another line of holes outside
the circle lines up with seasonal movements of the sun_has prompted
speculation that the site was built by Mayans, the Indian people
who constructed massive, astronomically-aligned temples in Mexico
and Central America.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever its origins, the circle has prompted an outpouring of
interest from around the world. School children have come by the
bus load, along with New Age devotees, amateur historians and
top-ranking archaeologists from around the country.
</P>
<P>
   Some preservationists hope that the discovery of four human
teeth might delay development, since a state law bans building on
burial sites. But state officials say there must be harder proof
than just a few teeth.
</P>
<P>
   Baumann has all the permits he needs to build, and unless the
county quickly raises millions to buy him out or finds some grounds
to ask a court to stop the project, construction may go forward.
</P>
<P>
   That would devastate the rainbow array of activists holding
vigil near the site.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paving covers up so much,'' said Alan Muskat, who lectures on
ancient cultures. ``There's so much disconnection. Now is our
chance to reestablish the connection. If we can preserve this, it
shows there is hope. If we can do it here, we can do it anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Williams writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
