A7841 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-TAXCUT-NYT &LR;      02-16 0643
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-TAXCUT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: DOUBTS ABOUT TAX CUTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, Feb. 17: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One of the hardiest perennials of modern American politics is
back. We speak of the new predictions that Republican moderates
will any moment now seize control of their party. As in the past,
these moderates, mostly from the Northeast and Midwest, complain
that the conservative stranglehold on the party threatens its
chances in the next election. Many urge Republicans to forget about
culture wars and return to the genial tax-cutting conservatism of
Ronald Reagan. The advice is attractive, but its fiscal logic may
be outdated. Grassroots feedback suggests that the GOP needs to
re-examine its worship of sweeping tax cuts like that being
promoted this week by the Senate majority leader, Trent Lott.
</P>
<P>
   In some respects, Republicans are suffering from their own past
success. President Clinton speaks the words of compassion, but his
domestic program is the essence of conservatism. How else to
describe spending three-quarters of the 15-year surplus of $4
trillion to pay down the national debt and  &UR; conserve &LR;  Social
Security and Medicare? Republican theorists and their supporters in
Congress may think they have a better way, perhaps even a more
elegant intellectual way, of restructuring both of these solid old
programs. But the public appears to be in no mood to transform them
radically along the lines suggested by the Cato Institute and the
Heritage Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   At a meeting of Republican moderates last weekend in Miami, two
Northeastern governors had some scathing words for their
colleagues, especially those who made the demonization of Clinton a
centerpiece of the party's message. Christie Whitman of New Jersey
said Americans perceived the party as ``mean-spirited'' and
``vindictive,'' while John Rowland of Connecticut said: ``I will
report to you that the good news is that the rich people and the
business people still like us. But that's about it.'' Yet at a
citizens' meeting in a pro-Reagan suburb of Detroit, Lott once
again pushed for an across-the-board tax cut that would
overwhelmingly benefit the wealthiest 10 percent of taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   Public opinion has moved since President Reagan carried the area
in 1980 and 1984. The polls show that Americans are not clamoring
about high taxes right now, in part because those who are paying
higher taxes are doing so as a result of their income having grown
substantially in the current boom. Perhaps more important,
priorities have shifted, and voters have redefined fiscal prudence.
Even Alan Greenspan has urged Congress to pay down the national
debt rather than pass the money out in tax cuts. Unlike the late
1970s, when Reagan and the congressional Republicans embraced tax
cuts as a cure-all, there is little need to stimulate the economy.
</P>
<P>
   Some moderate Republicans have already rejected the
across-the-board tax cuts advocated by Lott, pushing instead for
targeted tax breaks for married couples and perhaps a cut in the
estate tax. If more join them, there might be a chance of a
bipartisan tax-cut deal with the White House, which wants its own
limited tax breaks for school construction, long-term health care
and care of the disabled.
</P>
<P>
   With the Republican margin so slight in the House, and many
independent-minded Senate Republicans joining in the desire for
paying down debt, the across-the-board tax cut is in deep political
trouble only a few weeks after it was proclaimed as the salvation
in the post-impeachment era. Republicans are also saying they want
to spend more money on defense and education in the next few years.
These trends could mute the tax-cut battle cry in the next year and
give moderates a chance to promote a more nuanced fiscal policy for
the GOP.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
