A7848 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DELTA-ASA-NYT &LR;      02-16 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELTA-ASA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DELTA TO BUY REST OF STAKE IN ATLANTIC
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga., Texas, Southeast)  (nk) 
 By LESLIE WAYNE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Delta Air Lines announced Tuesday that it would pay $700 million
to acquire the part of Atlantic Southeast Airlines that it does not
already own in a deal with the potential for labor problems similar
to those that recently disrupted American Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   Delta, which owns 28 percent of the regional carrier, will pay
$34 each for the rest of the shares of ASA Holdings Inc., the
parent of Atlantic Southeast, and make ASA a wholly owned
subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is intended to protect Delta's grip on Texas and the
Southeast. Analysts, however, say that with contract talks between
Delta and its pilots' union scheduled for this fall, the large gap
in salaries between Delta pilots and those at Atlantic Southeast is
certain to become a contentious bargaining issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as this deal doesn't run into labor headwinds, it
makes sense,'' said James Higgins, an analyst at Donaldson, Lufkin
&AMP; Jenrette. ``But Delta may be underestimating the potential labor
issues here, which are really an extension of the same problems as
at American. You've got to wonder, in light of what's happened in
the industry, whether this issue will come back to bite them.''
</P>
<P>
   The operations of American Airlines, the nation's second-largest
carrier, were severely disrupted for a week in a dispute over
pilots' salaries related to American's acquisition of Reno Air
Inc., a regional carrier in the West where pilots make
significantly less than those at American. American's pilots
returned to work Tuesday in greater numbers under a court order
after staging a sickout.
</P>
<P>
   At Delta, a captain of a Boeing 737, a fleet mainstay with about
110 seats, can be paid up to $135,000 a year. At regional airlines,
which have 50- to 70-seat jets that serve similar distances and
cities as a 737, pilots are paid $70,000 to $75,000 a year. Pilots
in general see the lower salaries of regional jet pilots as a
threat to their wages. And this wage dispute has only grown as big
carriers like Delta, the nation's third largest, and American are
buying regional carriers rather than taking stakes and keeping an
arm's-length arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   ``This deal has very serious labor implications,'' said Julius
Maldutis, an analyst at CIBC Oppenheimer. ``The airline and the
pilots have already started labor discussions, and this will become
a contentious issue in the upcoming negotiations with pilots.''
</P>
<P>
   Both ASA and Delta are based in Atlanta, and the deal is
intended to protect Delta's grip on its main market, the Southeast
and Texas. ASA will bring passengers from smaller cities to Delta's
hubs in Atlanta and Dallas, blocking other carriers from making
inroads into that territory.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is also a departure for Delta, which typically takes
only equity stakes in regional carriers and does not buy them
outright, as do American, Northwest and Continental. Right now,
Delta has stakes in six regional airlines, including Comair
Holdings Inc. in the Midwest and Skywest Airlines Inc. in the West.
</P>
<P>
   ``Delta cannot afford to have other airlines take passengers
around Atlanta,'' said Thomas Longman, an analyst with Arnhold &AMP; S.
Bleichroeder. ``And if Delta controls ASA, it will enable ASA to
get up to a level of jet service that Delta wants much quicker.
This gives Delta much more leverage with its pilots. The pilots may
not like the deal, but it will catch their attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Delta fell 6.25 cents Tuesday, to $52.50, while ASA
rose $1.8125, to $33.75. The tender offer for ASA's shares begins
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Leo F. Mullin, Delta's chief executive, said Delta planned to
expand the number of ASA's jets, which make up 20 percent of its
fleet. ``Plans call for that number to grow substantially in the
coming years,'' Mullin said. ``Regional jets represent a strategic
opportunity for ASA.''
</P>
<P>
   The expansion of regional jet fleets, which are replacing
propeller airplanes, is shaking up the airline industry by
providing customers with option of bypassing many hub cities and
giving hub-based carriers, like Delta, the opportunity to draw
customers from greater distances.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
