<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990216.0451 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-16 23:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7955 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TABLOIDS-SOLD-COX     02-16 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TABLOIDS-SOLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tabloids to be sold
 &HT;    By Marguerite M. Plunkett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LANTANA, Fla. _ Ending a bumpy run as a stockholder-owned
company, the publisher of the National Enquirer and the Star
tabloids said Tuesday it will sell the company for $767 million to
Evercore Capital Partners, a group of New York investors that will
take it private.
</P>
<P>
   Evercore will pay $300 million in cash and assume nearly $470
million in debt in its deal for Lantana-based American Media, the
owner of the weekly supermarket tabloids. Holders of American Media
Class A and C stock will get $7 a share in the deal. The company's
stock closed Tuesday at $6.56, up 38 cents a share77.
</P>
<P>
   The new owner _ an investment firm headed by former U.S. Deputy
Treasury Secretary Roger Altman _ has no plans to move the
Enquirer's and Weekly World News' operation from Lantana _ or the
Star's from Tarrytown, N.Y., Enquirer Editor Steve Coz said.
American Media employs about 200 people in Lantana.
</P>
<P>
   Highly regarded magazine publisher David J. Pecker will become
chairman and chief executive officer of American Media, which will
keep its name, and get an equity stake in the company. To take the
job, Pecker, who has a home in Palm Beach, resigned as chief
executive officer of Hachette Filipacchi Magazines in New York,
whose titles include Elle and John F. Kennedy Jr.'s George .
</P>
<P>
   Pecker doubled Hachette's sales in his seven years there,
according to the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a demonstrated, proven value builder,'' said Austin
Beutner, principal and founder of Evercore.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is expected to close in two to three months.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is fantastic for the Enquirer,'' Coz said. ``These guys
are top-drawer experts of multimedia. They bring to the Enquirer
multimedia vision _ and a boatload of cash to expand and turn it
into a launching pad for ventures for the millennium.''
</P>
<P>
   The Enquirer and Star have evolved over the years into celebrity
and entertainment coverage, leaving behind the aliens and the
supernatural _ or at least leaving them to their wacky sibling, the
Weekly World News.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the editorial shift to the People-like mainstream, the
circulation of the tabloids has been slipping. The Enquirer dropped
to 2.24 million copies at the end of last year from 2.72 million in
June 1997. The Star's circulation fell to 1.82 million from 2.22
million during the same time.
</P>
<P>
   At its peak in 1977, the Enquirer sold 5 million copies a week.
The Star topped out at 3.6 million in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Profit has been heading in the same direction. The company
reported a profit of $569,000 for the first nine months of fiscal
1998, compared to $6.8 million a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The new owner plans a $50 million advertising campaign to
promote the publications, Beutner said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think there's an opportunity to take the brands to another
level, `` said Beutner, suggesting an Enquirer for teens and one in
Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   The company could expand by starting new publications, buying
turnaround candidates and even buying established titles, Beutner
said. The company hopes to lure readers to television and Internet
offerings, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Exiting the limelight of public trading and the demands of
shareholders will eliminate a distraction as the new owners attempt
to build American Media.
</P>
<P>
   The company's stock price (NYSE: ENQ) closed at $6.56 a share
Tuesday. It hit a low of $2.88 in May 1996 after reaching a lofty
$21.38 less than a year after going public in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   A special shareholder dividend of $7 a share _ part of a
settlement with shareholders after the company tried to go private
in 1994 _ has been blamed for some of the stock's problems. The
dividend meant a $292 million payout.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Going private) changes the focus of your management,'' said
Beutner, who has a home on Jupiter Island. ``We're trying to build
value five years from now. We're less concerned with this
quarter.''
</P>
<P>
   This isn't Beutner's first involvement with American Media. A
decade ago, he handled the sale of the company as a partner in the
Blackstone Group after the 1988 death of then-owner Generoso Pope
Jr. of Manalapan. Pecker's actions have attracted the publishing
world's attention over the years. He once killed an article set to
run in Premiere magazine that included information about actor
Sylvester Stallone's business role in the Planet Hollywood
restaurant chain. Premiere co-owner Ron Perelman, a part-time Palm
Beach resident, then was a co-owner of the magazine and reportedly
was planning a deal with Planet Hollywood at the time. The
magazine's top editors resigned after the incident.
</P>
<P>
   American Media Chairman Peter Callahan, who came to the company
with Boston Partners, won't continue with the new company, Coz
said.
</P>
<P>
   Shareholders will receive $7 for each Class A and Class C share
they own, a 26.1 percent premium on the average closing price in
the past 15 trading days, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, subject to shareholder approval, is expected to close
in two or three months. Boston Ventures affiliates and company
executives own 51.1 percent of the total shares outstanding and
control 75.5 percent of the voting rights of American Media.
They've agreed to vote in favor of the deal and have given Evercore
an option to buy their shares.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, American Media, which also publishes Country
Weekly , said it was selling its money-losing Soap Opera News and
Soap Opera Magazine to Primedia of New York, the publisher of
competitor Soap Opera Digest, for $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   Marguerite M. Plunkett writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla. Palm Beach Post wire services and staff researcher
Barbara Gellis Shapiro contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
