<HEADLINE>
NEW-LOOK MAVERICKS SEEM TO BE HEADED IN THE SAME OLD DIRECTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Mavericks' season is seven games old, and they
are already stumbling into a familiar hole.
</P>
<P>
   Some touted this as a playoff team two weeks ago. So far,
though, this year's model looks surprising like the Mavericks who
have been in the NBA draft lottery each of the past eight seasons.
</P>
<P>
   A young Mavericks team with four new players has been hurt by a
lockout-shortened training camp and a schedule that has included
Utah, Houston and Seattle, which were a combined 15-1 heading into
Tuesday's games. The Mavericks are 1-6 and tied with Denver for the
second-worst record in the NBA. And they trailed the Nuggets by 15
points at halftime of their loss in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   Coach/general manager Don Nelson has watched his team basically
play only one half of productive basketball every game, or have a
few players shine while others struggle. The total picture has been
devastating.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't had a game this year where we've hit on all of our
cylinders,'' Nelson said. ``There's always somebody who's not
playing well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't wait until we start playing some games where
everybody's hitting and playing in the 90th percentile of their
game, because I still think we can be pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks have played five of their first seven on the road,
and the two home games were against Utah and Houston. But the
schedule doesn't get any easier with tonight's 9:30 game at the Los
Angeles Lakers and three more games left on a seven-game, 11-day
road trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a horrible schedule for us, and we've somehow got to
figure out how to become better in a really tough situation,''
center Shawn Bradley said. ``The lockout really, really hurt teams
like us that are trying to get better.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley has not been able to unlock his game so far this season.
His scoring is down from 11.4 points per game last season to 5.6
and his rebounds have dropped from 8.1 to 5.9 per game. Starting
guard Michael Finley has also struggled; his scoring has dropped
from 21.5 points per game last season to 17.0 this season and he's
shooting 38.9 percent from the field.
</P>
<P>
   Point guard Steve Nash hasn't found his shooting touch, hitting
33.8 percent of his attempts, though he is averaging 6.3 assists
per game. The up-and-down play of rookie Dirk Nowitzki has led
Nelson to running a revolving door at forward that has included
A.C. Green, Samaki Walker, Gary Trent and John ``Hot Rod'' Williams
playing significant minutes at different times.
</P>
<P>
   As a team, the Mavericks are shooting only 40.8 percent from the
field and are being outscored, 25-21, in the first quarter. The
Mavericks are scoring 90.3 points per game and allowing 97.3. They
also are being outrebounded, 47.7 to 43.3 per game.
</P>
<P>
   Nash said the Mavericks need some practice time to work out
their problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel bad for coach \RNelson\S because he's out there calling
plays and he doesn't have a lot of time to correct the mistakes
that we're making on the practice floor,'' he said. ``He can draw
them on the chalkboard, but we don't get a chance to really run
through them and try to practice on the offense because of the
short season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had two weeks of practice before we saw what was going to
happen in the games, and then it's like wildfire. It's difficult
when you're a young team, because we're still trying to learn,
we're inexperienced and we're new to each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what can be done to overcome the 1-6 start, Finley said:
``Go 6-0. We just have to take it one game at a time, but at the
same time we just have to keep our heads and stay as focused as we
can, despite the 1-6 record.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson said he can't be concerned about the slow start.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to develop a young team here, so whatever happens
in that regard happens,'' he said. ``I don't like losing any more
than anybody else.
</P>
<P>
   ``But one of the things we had talked about was finding
ourselves on this road trip, and some of us are.''
</P>
<P>
   Cedric Ceballos, who averages 12.9 points per game off the
bench, tried to take blame for the Mavericks' malady.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the bench's fault, and I take full blame because I'm
supposed to bring that energy and help us contribute,'' he said.
``I don't know what it is. But we need to find it out so we won't
get too far deep in the hole.'' /
</P>
</TEXT>
