<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-JONES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVEN INJURED, TEXAS TECH'S YOUNG IS A BIG-GAME THREAT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you had your television tuned to any of the sports roundup
shows over the weekend, you saw a clip of Texas Tech guard Rayford
Young.
</P>
<P>
   Young's career-high 41 points in the Red Raiders' upset of
Kansas was highlight news on all the networks. And the clip you saw
was of one of Young's trademark moves from the past. He drives to
the hoop, reverses back outside the 3-point line, turns and jacks
it. Swish.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been one of my favorite moves my whole life,'' the Pampa
junior recalled. ``But with me being as limited as I have been most
of the season, I haven't been able to do it much. In a big game
like that was, though, when the score is close, you've got to go to
your strengths.''
</P>
<P>
   That particular shot against the Jayhawks, incidentally, gave
the Raiders a 70-69 lead with 4:20 to play. They would not trail
again on the way to a 90-84 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Young's injury _ a combination of a bad sprain and bone bruise
above his left ankle suffered in practice Dec. 16 _ continues to
limit the Raiders' explosive point guard despite his sometimes
sensational scoring bursts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always pretty swollen after games,'' Young said. ``But
the intensity is so high during games that I really can't feel
it.''
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't rob him of some of the explosive quickness that
remains one of his best assets.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things that helps make him the player he is are his
wheels,'' Tech coach James Dickey said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to having a hard time with his trademark move, Young
also has lost that quicker-than-you-are first step that allowed him
to frequently blow past a defender on his way into the heart of the
defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been harder to do that because it's so hard to push
off,'' Young said. ``And a lot of the time when I go to the basket,
instead of going off one foot, I have to jump-stop and try to go
off two. And that gives the defensive player that much more time to
catch up to me.''
</P>
<P>
   We discuss Young's problems with the ankle _ which will heal
only with extended rest _ only to elevate Saturday's
accomplishments. Thirty-two points in the final 8:56, including
18-for-18 at the free-throw line.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little painful for me to recall, but Rayford Young was
sensational,'' Kansas coach Roy Williams said. ``As good a
performance for 10 or 12 minutes there as I've ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Dickey likewise could not remember witnessing such an individual
performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best I've ever seen by an individual player in a game of
that magnitude,'' Dickey said. ``He was on fire offensively. He put
us on his shoulders and carried us.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas coach Rick Barnes, whose conference-leading Longhorns
catch Young's act tonight in Austin's Erwin Center, can recall only
one other such performance _ when Eric Murdock scored 45 at Arizona
for his Providence team in December 1990. That still ranks as the
top performance by a collegiate player in the McKale Center.
</P>
<P>
   But after watching Young score 21 against his team last month,
Barnes didn't need to watch tapes of Tech against Kansas to
convince him that Young is a quality player.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went up to Rayford after our game and told him he was one of
the best guards in the Big 12,'' Barnes said. ``I still believe
that today.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though he's only been back in Tech's starting lineup for
eight games after missing five, Young's 16.3-point Big 12-scoring
average among guards trails only that of Oklahoma State's Adrian
Peterson (17.5). Young also averages almost four assists a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to say who is the best player in the league,''
Dickey said. ``But I believe Rayford is as good as any point guard
in the league when he's healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   He's not bad now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
