<HEADER>
A7974 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-DANCE-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      02-16 0634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-DANCE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DANCE IN AMERICA': AILEY THE STYLE, AILEY THE MAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (Editors: production notes at end of review)  
 (bl)  
 By JENNIFER DUNNING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In its long and solid history of creating dance experiences for
television, the ``Great Performances: Dance in America'' series has
achieved a high point with ``A Hymn for Alvin Ailey.'' Filmmaker
Orlando Bagwell uses Judith Jamison's ``Hymn'' as a departure point
for an even larger look at Ailey, his work, his dancers and what
they have meant to audiences around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Jamison's 1993 dance took interviews with Ailey dancers,
sensitively conducted and edited by playwright and performance
artist Anna Deavere Smith, and put them together with a driving
musical score by Robert Ruggieri. Ms. Jamison's choreography is a
fusion of African, jazz and modern-dance styles informed by the
dancers' ballet training.
</P>
<P>
   What emerged from ``Hymn'' was an evocation of Ailey and his
dancers and how they interacted to create classics of American
modern dance like ``Revelations'' and ``Cry.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A Hymn for Alvin Ailey'' also includes scenes of Ailey as a
young dancer and of Ms. Jamison in ``Cry,'' as well as interviews
with Ailey over the years and a glimpse of his being celebrated at
the Kennedy Center Honors performance in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a haunting art-film clip of Ailey in a subway
station along with views of the memorial service held for Ailey,
who died in 1989, at New York's Cathedral of St. John the Divine,
where the program opens.
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell, a producer for the PBS series ``Eyes on the Prize,''
adds material from interviews conducted with longtime Ailey
colleagues, among them a poetic Carmen de Lavallade and a sharply
analytical George Faison. Jack Mitchell recalls photographing Ailey
over the years. Sylvia Waters, the director of the Ailey junior
troupe, talks about Ailey the man with perceptive warmth, and
Masazumi Chaya, the associate artistic director of the senior
company, speaks about the choreographer and his work with poignant,
eloquent simplicity. Ms. Jamison and Ms. Smith are the connecting
threads through the program, as they are in ``Hymn'' itself.
</P>
<P>
   Beautifully photographed and edited, by Michael Chin and Jean
Tsien respectively, ``A Hymn for Alvin Ailey'' offers a record of
powerful dancing. It is very likely to serve as a compelling primer
for people new to Ailey's work as well as material for thought for
those familiar with it.
</P>
<P>
   It is possible to see the Ailey style close up and held nearly
still in time, for example, in the rooted bodies of the opening
moments of ``Hymn.'' And the style is revealed as a complex amalgam
of theatricality and dance forms rather than more easily
dismissable theatricalized jazz dance, for which Ailey was
sometimes criticized.
</P>
<P>
   The tributes paid to Ailey and Ms. Jamison late in the program
occasionally sound a little pat and repetitive. And Ms. Smith's
presence is sometimes jarring and confusing. But ``A Hymn for Alvin
Ailey'' gives words as eloquent as Ailey's best choreography to
what he expressed without words in those dances.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `GREAT PERFORMANCES
</P>
<P>
   DANCE IN AMERICA: A Hymn for Alvin Ailey'
</P>
<P>
   PBS, Wednesday night
</P>
<P>
   (Channel 13, New York, at 10) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Produced and directed by Orlando Bagwell; Rhonda Grauer,
producer. ``Hymn'' choreographed and directed by Judith Jamison;
text conceived, written and performed by Anna Deavere Smith; music,
Robert Ruggieri. For ``Great Performances'': Judy Kinberg, series
producer for dance; Jac Venza, executive producer.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Judith Jamison, Anna Deavere Smith, Masazumi Chaya, George
Faison, Jack Mitchell, Carmen de Lavallade, Sylvia Waters and the
Alvin Ailey American Dance Theater.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
