u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLLEGE-APPLICATIONS-     02-16 1094
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLEGE-APPLICATIONS-ART-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. COLLEGES INUNDATED BY FRESHMAN APPLICANTS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Minn., Va., Ivy League states, Calif., La.)  (ART ADV: Photo and graphic are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By WILLIAM H. HONAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Yale set a record this year, and Harvard nearly did. But the
rising tide of college applications was hardly limited to the Ivy
League.
</P>
<P>
   As the deadline for next fall's freshman class passed at many
campuses on Monday, admissions officers from Yale and Harvard to
St. Olaf College in Northfield, Minn., and Sweet Briar College in
Virginia, all reported big gains.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason is demographic: There are more high school
graduates than ever. But another important factor, some officials
say, is the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Several Web sites now offer users the possibility of sending
electronic applications in bulk. Some colleges encourage the
practice by waiving the fee for an electronic application, saying
it saves them the expense of entering data.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Berman, a spokesman for College Edge, a division of Snap
Technology in San Francisco, said his rapidly growing electronic
application service, which guides students to fill out the
application form and then sends it along to desired colleges, had
processed 500,000 applications this year. The colleges, not the
applicants, pay the costs.
</P>
<P>
   For several years, many colleges have accepted a common
application form that can be copied and submitted to more than one
institution. Now, students with computers can go to a college Web
site or a CD-ROM and fill out an application _ often without ever
touching paper.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no fussing with typewriter margins and all of that
time-consuming stuff,'' said Evan Schnittman, a spokesman for the
Princeton Review. ``It's no wonder there's an explosive use of
these electronic tools.''
</P>
<P>
   Apply!, an application service that was bought by the Princeton
Review last May, distributes a CD-ROM to some 700,000 high schools
around the country. It contains application forms for more than 600
colleges and universities.
</P>
<P>
   The Kaplan Educational Centers, another college preparation
service, distributes a CD-ROM that enables students to connect with
Collegelink and Collegenet _ two electronic application providers.
Students can also link with these services from Kaplan's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   As applications pour in, admissions officers say they have never
worked so hard. ``Our staff is going seven days a week, 10 hours a
day,'' said Richard Shaw, dean of admissions at Yale.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from the extra work, some educators say they fear that
colleges and universities are beginning to lose control of the
application process.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being able to apply to college through the Internet or with a
CD-ROM has made it a kind of game that students play,'' said Joyce
E. Smith, executive director of the National Association for
College Admissions Counseling. ``It has changed the face of how
colleges are chosen, and left counselors confused.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be that high school students would start the
application process by sitting around the kitchen table with their
parents,'' Ms. Smith continued. ``Then they would discuss the
matter with the school's guidance counselor, and bounce it back and
forth before they reached a decision about which three or four
schools might be right. But with online applications that the
student does with his or her own computer, the counselor and even
the parents are left out of the process.''
</P>
<P>
   Virginia A. Carey, dean of admissions at the College of William
and Mary _ one of the few campuses that reported a decline in
applications this year _ said the prevalence of electronic
applications had ``confounded all of the projections that we try to
make.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Once the student has filled out the application, or had one of
the services do it, he or she can apply to additional colleges just
by typing in the school's code,'' Ms. Carey said. ``But how
seriously are we to take those applications? When the fee is waived
for electronic applications, are they really just as serious as a
paper application that enclosed a $40 fee?''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Besides the rise in the numbers of high school graduates and of
electronic applications, admissions officers offer a variety of
explanations for the gain in applications. Ivy League campuses, for
example, have increased financial aid. ``You know that had to
help,'' said William R. Fitzsimmons, dean of admissions at Harvard,
where applications were up 7 percent (to 18,183) this year.
</P>
<P>
   At Fairfield University in Connecticut, where applications rose
11 percent this year, Mary Spiegel, director of admissions, said
the recent success of the university's varsity teams had helped,
and so had a policy of encouraging prospective applicants to make a
campus visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``People come and they like what they see,'' Ms. Spiegel said.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Whiteside, the admissions chief of Tulane University in
New Orleans, said that applications were up 5.5 percent but that he
was even more pleased by a rise in applicants' average SAT score _
to 1,284 from 1,264.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're being seen as a more and more selective institution,''
Whiteside said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that applications were given a lift by the lure of New
Orleans, small class sizes and the performance of Tulane's football
team, which was undefeated last season.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the rise in applications has left many admissions
officers wary. Margaret Williams, admissions director of Sweet
Briar College, said the increase in applicants had greatly
complicated her work.
</P>
<P>
   ``By around May or June,'' Ms. Williams said, ``I want to be
able to go to our president and say it looks as though we're going
to have a freshman class in the fall and this is the size and shape
of it, but now that's a lot more difficult to do. I recently
learned that one of our applicants had applied to 10 schools. It
makes it difficult for us to decide how seriously interested that
student is and whether we should hold a place for her.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Carey, the dean of admissions at William and Mary, said that
last year she started to write a detailed response to a parent who
described her son's academic record and asked if he might qualify
for a merit award.
</P>
<P>
   Then she noticed a line at the top of the query: ``This question
has been sent to at least 100 institutions.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Carey decided not to reply.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
