<HEADLINE>
FINSTERWALD BORN TOO SOON?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE SHELBURNE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The man who was born too soon will be honored as a
past champion this week, when the Nissan Open returns to Riviera
Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   Dow Finsterwald, 69, winner of the 1960 Nissan (then called the
Los Angeles Open) must wonder at times about his timing.
</P>
<P>
   He was one of the finest golfers or his era and finished second
or third in tour earnings for five straight years at the height of
his skills. But Finsterwald's combined winnings during that 1956-60
stretch totaled just $170,225 _ less than a third what the Nissan
winner will earn !ital!this week and at least $7 million shy of
what a similar five-year stretch would earn in this era.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Finsterwald's birth date of September 6, 1929, came just
four days before the birth of another eventual pro golfer of note _
Arnold Palmer.
</P>
<P>
   And when Finsterwald turned 50, in 1970, there was no such thing
as a Senior PGA Tour. But Finsterwald has no thoughts about being
born too soon:
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't feel that,'' he said. ``A dollar probably went
a little further then and it probably went a little easier. . . . I
enjoyed it when I had it and I had it going good, and I hope the
guys that are going good now enjoy it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Besides, there's so many good players now, I don't know if I
could have finished that high. I feel very fortunate to win what I
did.''
</P>
<P>
   His Los Angeles Open victory came at Rancho Park, where he won
by a stroke with a closing 71 after final-round leader Eric Monti
shot 80. Finsterwald remains gracious in victory 39 years after the
fact.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did win the tournament, but it was kind of a back-door
thing,'' he said. ``I was behind by five strokes going into the
last round. . . . Eric Monti, who had been been leading, was a golf
professional next door at Hillcrest. I think he had an awful lot of
members over there pulling for him, but it was just a tough day for
him.''
</P>
<P>
   As for having to go head-to-head throughout his career against
Palmer, the man acknowledged as the finest golfer of his
generation, Finsterwald said he enjoyed the opportunity:
</P>
<P>
   ``Being overshadowed by him, you don't mind. Just to get in his
shadow, you've done a pretty good job.''
</P>
<P>
   Finsterwald finished with 12 tour victories, including a
two-stroke win over Hall of Famer Billy Casper in the 1958 PGA
Championship, the first year that tournament switched from match to
stroke play.
</P>
<P>
   __ Clubs for kids: Anyone donating a new or used golf club to
the Nissan Open's Clubs for Kids program today will be granted free
admission to pro-am play at Riviera Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   Clubs will be accepted at the Longworth Ave. entrance, where
daily shuttle service will bring fans from parking lots at the
Veterans Administration Hospital in Brentwood.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Clubs for Kids program produced 250 donated clubs
in the Nissan Open held at Valencia Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   __ Final qualifiers: Bo Van Pelt of Reston, Wash., and Alan
Bratton of Ft. Worth, Texas, claimed the final two berths in this
week's Nissan Open, topping a 142-player qualifying tournament at
Los Serranos.
</P>
<P>
   Van Pelt shot 7-under-par 65 in the competition held on the
North course. Bratton eliminated 16-year-old James Oh of Lakewood
in a one-hole playoff.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
