<HEADER>
A7980 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BERKELEY-KERR-ART-NYT     02-16 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BERKELEY-KERR-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFLECTIONS OF THE MAN WHO ENGINEERED CALIFORNIA'S STATE UNIVERSITY
SYSTEM
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By KAREN W. ARENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERKELEY, Calif. _ The students milling around the entrance gate
at the University of California here take little notice of Clark
Kerr as he passes by on a mild winter afternoon, a balding emeritus
professor in a wool sports jacket and comfortable-looking black
shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Three decades ago, he would not have escaped their attention. In
the 1960s, Clark Kerr was at the center of the cultural hurricane
that engulfed virtually every American campus, and he paid for it
with his job. Gov. Ronald Reagan and the California Board of
Regents dismissed him as president of the university, saying he had
been too lenient with the protesters in the Free Speech Movement at
Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   It is not how Kerr would like to be remembered, or even,
necessarily, how he should be. At 87, he is perhaps the grand old
man of higher education, the president and chancellor who
engineered Berkeley's pre-eminence and that of the whole California
university system.
</P>
<P>
   Part of Berkeley's campus carries his name. His slender volume,
``The Uses of the University,'' (Harvard University Press, 1964)
was translated into six languages (including Urdu), and is still in
print. Time, Business Week and Psychology Today all featured him in
cover stories.
</P>
<P>
   After his dismissal in 1967, he became chairman and executive
director of the Carnegie Commission on Higher Education. Now he is
completing his memoirs, for publication next year by the University
of California Press, and as he shows a visitor around the campus he
reflects on his experiences.
</P>
<P>
   Although student protests have cooled somewhat, the issues
roiling the University of California _ and other universities _
today are not unlike those faced by Kerr, first as chancellor at
Berkeley and then as president of the university, issues like
diversity, making better use of the campuses and ethics.
</P>
<P>
   He emphatically supports a diverse student body _ to create a
sense of opportunity and because the labor force will increasingly
be made up of minority workers _ but he does not see affirmative
action as the answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The program, I felt, was inherently flawed,'' Kerr said.
</P>
<P>
   He takes the long view, and would like to see a focus on better
preparation of students, beginning in primary school, and on
helping students who are admitted to college to graduate.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he condemns the Regents for prohibiting preferential
admissions, because he fears that will be a signal to minorities
that they are not welcome. And he was dismayed that the Regents
took admissions policy out of the hands of the university Senate,
which he views as an important part of the university's success.
</P>
<P>
   But he does not expect political involvement in higher education
to disappear, because of the growing need for a college diploma and
the central role of universities in scientific research.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't very important before,'' he said. ``We were a
series of institutions on the side of the highway. Now higher
education is the engine pulling society.''
</P>
<P>
   As other states scramble to replicate Berkeley's success, Kerr
said that California's critical decision for higher education was
to have three distinct tiers _ community colleges offering open
enrollment, four-year undergraduate colleges and research
universities _ and to concentrate research support on a limited
number of campuses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may have politicians saying they can't finance it any
more,'' Kerr said, ``but they are not speaking against the master
plan.''
</P>
<P>
   He bemoans the reduced public spending on universities today,
but does not expect a reversal because growth in productivity is
not as strong as it used to be. It is time for higher education
``to start paying attention to being cost effective,'' Kerr said,
sounding more like a corporate trustee than an educator.
</P>
<P>
   He also wants university administrators to pay more attention to
ethics. He says public trust has eroded because of scandals in
athletics and actions like Berkeley's recent agreement to give a
Swiss biotechnology company, Novartis, first rights to
commercializing some research from the university's plant biology
department. Critics complained that Berkeley was auctioning off
research capacity paid for by public support.
</P>
<P>
   And Kerr is critical of the California State University's
decision to remove remedial courses from its curriculum.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want some diversity,'' he said, ``you are going to have
to do some remediation work, considering the state of our high
schools.''
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, Kerr is pleased when he looks back on his
years at the university, but he said that writing his memoirs had
brought back ``nightmares'' about his dismissal.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what troubled him most about the episode, Kerr's gray eyes
look off into the distance and his face clouds momentarily. In his
soft, even voice he talks about how people he had looked upon as
his friends voted against him.
</P>
<P>
   And, he said, he often thinks about what he might have said to
the Regents had they given him a chance to defend himself.
</P>
<P>
   He recalled the response of the labor leader John L. Lewis to
industrialists who accused Lewis during a conference after World
War II of not being a good American. ``Why am I not a good
American?'' Lewis asked. ``Because I improved conditions for my
workers? Because I got pensions for their widows?''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what I might have said,'' Kerr mused. ``But I had the
good sense not to say anything. I accepted what they did and
thanked them for the chance to serve.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
