</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAPTAINS-THEATER-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CAPTAINS COURAGEOUS': SAILORS AT WORK 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By PETER MARKS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ No need to wait for Fleet Week to encounter the
hardest-working crew in or out of New York Harbor. The men are on
the job right now, at the Manhattan Theater Club, lifting anchor,
dropping line, hoisting sails, swabbing decks, climbing masts,
scaling fish and yes, even singing more prettily in multipart
harmony than any a capella group from Princeton or Yale.
</P>
<P>
   They are the lusty, vocally trained sailors of ``Captains
Courageous,'' the new musical based on the Rudyard Kipling novel
about a blueblooded brat who falls off an ocean liner and into the
lives of a Portuguese seaman and his mates on a New England fishing
trawler. The show, which opened Tuesday night, features Treat
Williams as the fearless Portuguese fisherman, Manuel; young
Brandon Espinoza as the rich boy who earns his comeuppance and his
sea legs, and 14 other able-bodied actors in an all-male cast who
do so many ship-related chores they could turn in their Equity
cards and immediately qualify for the seafarers' union.
</P>
<P>
   The director, Lynne Meadow, dreams up an endless checklist of
tasks for her actors, and as ``Captains Courageous'' progresses,
the reason becomes clear. She is desperately trying to create the
illusion of something happening. For all its handsome rigging, for
all the muscular chanteys and wistful sailing songs by the
songwriting team of Frederick Freyer and Patrick Cook, the show
itself is rather static and pale; it lacks the sense of momentum
and profusion of color that should develop naturally in a musical
drama that rides the swells of the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a pleasingly uncomplicated performance by Williams and
the robust if undifferentiated portrayals by much of the rest of
the cast, ``Captains Courageous'' is the equivalent of a torpid
cruise in shallow water. All of the story's tension, it seems,
resides in those ropes the sailors are constantly tugging.
</P>
<P>
   Freyer, who wrote the music, and Cook, responsible for the book
and lyrics, apparently have been grooming their musical for years;
it has been through numerous workshops at the theater club and
elsewhere. The loving care is obvious. Their score is tasteful and
polished and easy on the ears. For example, Harvey Ellesworth
Cheyne, the wealthy boy played by Espinoza, is picked out of the
sea by Manuel in the middle of Williams' gentle entrance number,
``Little Fish.'' The song segues nicely from Manuel's primitive
ruminations on fishing, to the rescue of the boy, establishing both
Manuel's simple nature and the relationship that will frame the
rest of the show.
</P>
<P>
   But as with so much of the score of ``Captains Courageous,''
``Little Fish'' provides little more than unassuming background
music for the mild, incremental advances in the story. The composer
and lyricist favor songs and song fragments that express a general
mood _ the sailors sing on such predictable ideas as adventure and
loneliness _ over those that might reveal character or drive the
plot. Thus the music, while full of verve, never achieves much
individuality. On the rare occasions that it does, as in ``Regular
Fellas,'' an energetic if routine Act II comedy song performed by
Manuel and Harvey, the parched audience responds with something
like deep gratitude.
</P>
<P>
   In its diminished capacity, the score _ with its chiming echoes
of ship's bells and other sounds of the sea in the rich
orchestrations by Jonathan Tunick _ becomes merely atmospheric. It
serves roughly the same function as the backdrop footage of the
turbulent ocean in the 1937 movie version with Spencer Tracy and
Freddie Bartholomew, or the vivid descriptions of ship life in the
1897 novel.
</P>
<P>
   This, obviously, does not set the stage for musical theater of
the most compelling variety, though it's only fair to point out
that with this source material, Freyer, Cook and Ms. Meadow, the
theater club's artistic director, had a major challenge from the
start. The story of ``Captains Courageous,'' a sea voyage during
which Harvey learns from Manuel what it means to be a man, takes
the form of a travelogue and as such is not inherently dramatic.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The solution the musical comes up with is to stretch out
Harvey's transformation from prig to productive crewman _ in the
novel and movie his change in temperament occurs practically
overnight _ to occupy virtually the entire first act. (A supposed
rivalry with the crew of an unseen fishing boat is another
underwhelming effort to beef up the plot.)
</P>
<P>
   In other words, it's a long way to intermission. Espinoza, an
accomplished young actor, is forever curling his lip and stamping
his feet like a pint-size John McEnroe. ``I'm Harvey Ellesworth
Cheyne!'' he sings haughtily again and again, long after it has
grown tiresome. (It's not until much too late in the show, the
closing song of Act I, ``You Never Saw,'' that Harvey has a chance
to explain his behavior.)
</P>
<P>
   All the while, the crewmen are arrayed in choirlike formations
on Derek McLane's revolving platform, which is used to represent
both ship and shore. Rather than being allowed to emerge as
characters, the men, all played by fine Broadway actors, are
defined by their chores: there is the captain (Michael Mulheren),
the captain's son (Jim Stanek), the cook (Norm Lewis). In Jerry
Mitchell's staging of the musical numbers, they are positioned like
furniture, and their songs are theatrical wallpaper. ``Somewhere in
Gloucester/A ship sails today/So farewell, my lady/I'm going
away,'' is a typical verse, delivered in ethereal harmony with
almost a liturgical cast.
</P>
<P>
   The job of bringing this airy musical to earth is borne chiefly
by Williams. And in the tighter second act, more successful because
it narrows the emotional focus and follows through musically with
touching duets like ``I'm Home,'' he and Espinoza almost pull off
the impossible. As Manuel, Williams is always appealing, whether
teaching Harvey the ins and outs of landing cod or making up songs
to the accompaniment of his ``squeeze box,'' the concertina he
inherited from his father. Possessed of a pleasant, delicate
singing voice, and a more plausible Portuguese accent than the
laughable one Tracy employed in his Oscar-winning performance,
Williams proves a warmly embraceable father figure, soft and
masculine, too.
</P>
<P>
   The role is not the most challenging, of course; pure-hearted
Manuel is about as far as an actor could travel from the broodingly
complex police officer Williams portrayed so compellingly in Sidney
Lumet's ``Prince of the City.'' Espinoza, on the other hand, has to
undergo a radical metamorphosis in ``Captains Courageous,'' and he
carries it off expertly. It is not his fault that he's made to seem
so ludicrously shrill in the first act. The closer he gets to
goodness, the better he gets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Captains Courageous,'' unfortunately, never gets particularly
close to musicalizing the story of Manuel and Harvey in a way that
gives their bonding a blood-coursing urgency. Little that happens
onstage seems real: No one, in fact, gets dirty, or even wet. The
show holds out the promise of taking you on a journey to somewhere
new. But like the platform the production is perched on, it only
goes in circles.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   `CAPTAINS COURAGEOUS'
</P>
<P>
   The Musical
</P>
<P>
   Music by Frederick Freyer; book and lyrics by Patrick Cook,
based on ``Captains Courageous,'' courtesy of Turner Entertainment
Co.; directed by Lynne Meadow; musical staging, Jerry Mitchell;
sets by Derek McLane; costumes by Catherine Zuber; lighting by
Brian MacDevitt; sound by Otts Munderloh; orchestrations, Jonathan
Tunick; music direction, Robert Gustafson; music adviser, Paul
Bogaev; music coordinator, Seymour Red Press; dialect coach,
Deborah Hecht; production stage manager, Ed Fitzgerald; production
manager, Michael Moody; director of musical theater program,
Clifford Lee Johnson III; associate artistic director, Michael
Bush; general manager, Victoria Bailey. Presented by Manhattan
Theater Club, Ms. Meadow, artistic director; Barry Grove, executive
producer. At City Center Stage 1, 131 W. 55th St., Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   With: Treat Williams (Manuel), Brandon Espinoza (Harvey Cheyne),
Norm Lewis (Doc), Jim Stanek (Dan) and Michael Mulheren (Captain
Troop).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-16-99 2318EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
