<SLUG> BC-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIREFIGHTERS' DEATHS RECALL PAIN OF PAST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ For 11 years now, this has been the worst
week of the year for Randal Goodwin. Yesterday's screaming
headline, ``Firefighters die,'' guaranteed this year would be no
different.
</P>
<P>
   Goodwin was on the dreaded elliptical cross-trainer at Huguley
Fitness Center when I walked in yesterday morning, sweat soaking
his T-shirt and running down his forehead and into his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   He's there every day, the center's ``welcome wagon'' volunteer,
always smiling, singing along with the music in his headphones,
rolling through another two-hour workout.
</P>
<P>
   He hits the treadmill. He pumps iron. He rotates among the
machines, working the upper body, then the legs. And at every
machine, every weight bench, every Stairmaster, he shares a joke or
a smile. He seems to know everyone and everyone knows Goodwin.
</P>
<P>
   He's the guy with no feet.
</P>
<P>
   Goodwin gets by quite well, thank you, with prostheses made of
plastic and rubber and metal taking the place of both his feet,
which were amputated above the ankles 11 years ago this week.
</P>
<P>
   You can understand the inspiration he brings to the regulars at
Huguley. It's just that yesterday, for the first time in all the
times I've seen him there, his smile was forced, the pain in his
eyes _ and in his heart _ plain for all to see.
</P>
<P>
   Three of his ``brothers'' died Monday in Lake Worth, Texas, just
outside Fort Worth. Goodwin felt that pain all the way down into
the feet he no longer has.
</P>
<P>
   Goodwin, 31, was a firefighter, too, until a fire took away his
feet and his dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel sad today,'' he said after we'd both served our
sentences on the cross-trainer. ``In the business we're in, we're
all basically related. When brothers get hurt or die in the line of
duty, we're all impacted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you can detach yourself. You have to be able to do
that. But when it comes inside, there's no escaping it. In a few
weeks, the world will move on, but for those families and those
friends, what happened yesterday will always be felt and those men
will always be missing.''
</P>
<P>
   By all rights, Goodwin should me missing, too. How he survived
his own ordeal 11 years ago, when he was a 20-year-old volunteer
for the Briar Oaks Fire Department, just south of Burleson in
Johnson County, remains a mystery.
</P>
<P>
   Goodwin's unit had responded to a grass fire. What they didn't
know was that a downed power line had caused the fire and was still
very much alive. The surging electricity arced to the water stream
from the truck. James Salzman, on the hose, slumped over. Mark
Crawford, rushing to Salzman's aid, went down when he stepped off
the truck.
</P>
<P>
   Goodwin immediately began a rescue operation to try to save his
fellow crew members. He was off the truck, running parallel to the
hot wire, when it arced again.
</P>
<P>
   The electrical current, all 69,000 volts, hit Goodwin above the
right eye, surged through him and into the ground, then threw him
40 feet, over the line itself.
</P>
<P>
   His insulated fireman's coat and pants, built to protect him
from outside heat, also kept the heat inside when the clothes he
was wearing underneath burst into flames. The stethoscope that hung
around his neck welded itself to the left side of his chest.
</P>
<P>
   As crew member Jim Flynn worked to save him, Goodwin's heart
arrested twice, then a third time in the Care Flight helicopter,
where they had to shock him back to life.
</P>
<P>
   Amazingly, none of the three firefighters died, though all were
seriously injured.
</P>
<P>
   Goodwin's injuries were so extensive _ he had second- and
third-degree burns over 87 percent of his body _ that doctors saw
no hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``They told my parents that I wasn't going to make it through
the night and they thought transfusions would be a waste of
blood,'' he said. ``The organ-donor people were there to prepare my
organs for harvesting.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodwin fooled them all. He refused to die. Transfusions were
performed, but as fast as the blood went in, it poured back out
again through his ruined feet, which had taken the brunt of the
electrical charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``The doctors decided to start at the bottom and work up,''
Goodwin said of the amputations. ``They said they'd stop when they
found good tissue.''
</P>
<P>
   Four-and-a-half months later, a full year earlier than doctors
had predicted, Goodwin left the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Today, he runs a support unit for Johnson County firefighters
called Emergency Support Service, providing food, fluids and
on-site medical evaluations as firefighters do their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Besides losing his feet, Goodwin is also blind in his right eye
and has limited vision in his left. But he refuses to let his
physical impairment handicap him emotionally.
</P>
<P>
   ``You reach a point in your life where, `Great, I'm alive,' or
`GREAT, I'm alive!' It's where you put the emphasis,'' said
Goodwin, who married his best friend Grace two years after the
incident. ``Obviously, it was a big change in my life. You think
you have everything mapped out, then it's as if God puts out a hand
and says, `Whoa, time to start over.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I just try to live my life to the fullest. I don't let anyone
set my expectations for me. I try to live without limits. I don't
set out every day to inspire anyone else, but if somebody learns
something from what happened to me, that's cool.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost as painful as losing his feet was the loss of his dream
of being a firefighter.
</P>
<P>
   I'm beginning to understand that dream a little better. I have a
son who shares it and has begun his training to be a firefighter,
too.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just gets in your blood,'' Goodwin said. ``I'd do it again
in a heartbeat. If a magic time machine could transport me back to
that day, Feb. 21, 1988, I don't know if I would change a thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Huguley Fitness Center is a haven for firefighters from all
over the area. They came there to stay in shape and to stay sharp,
knowing the day could come when they will need every ounce of
strength, every bit of smarts, to save others and to survive.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, though, was quieter out of respect for their fallen
comrades. You know it's a sad day when even Goodwin struggles to
muster a smile.
\Ntagtop:Jim Reeves, (817) 390-7972
\Ntagbottom:revo\Nstar-telegram.com
</P>
</TEXT>
