<HEADLINE>
SOUTHERN METHODIST CLIMBS UP WAC MOUNTAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With SMU sweeping two Western Athletic Conference home games
last week, the title picture in the Mountain Division emerged with
crystal clarity.
</P>
<P>
   It is now obvious that any of seven teams can win the
championship. Most of them, of course, could also finish seventh.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the Mustangs players have indicated that winning the
championship is their true goal; but at this point, SMU coach Mike
Dement would probably settle for a berth in the WAC tournament in
Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   He figures that will require a minimum of seven conference
victories, which means that the Mustangs (11-12, 5-5) must win at
least two of their remaining four games. Three would be better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, by beating Colorado State and Wyoming \Rboth 5-6\S we
jumped over them in the standings,'' Dement said, ``But they each
have two home games left, and I don't think anyone will beat them
up there. We're certainly not assured of anything at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   Tomorrow night, the Mustangs visit Air Force (8-14, 1-9) with
what would appear to be a great opportunity for a rare WAC road
victory. There's a catch, however.
</P>
<P>
   While the Falcons figure to be out of the running _ the seventh-
and eighth-place teams in each division miss the trip to Las Vegas
_ they might be more unlucky than inept. For starters, they rank
sixth nationally in 3-point shots made per game (8.7).
</P>
<P>
   They have four league losses by a total of eight points _
including a one-point defeat to division leader Nevada-Las Vegas
(8-2) and a 73-71 loss to SMU at Moody Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed a clutch 3-point shot from Stephen Woods to beat
them,'' Dement said. ``And they had the UNLV game won when, for
some reason, they came back onto the floor with six men after a
timeout. UNLV got the ball on the penalty and hit a last-second
shot to win.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Mustangs have pulled out three last-minute victories in
a row.
</P>
<P>
   Jeryl Sasser has averaged 21 points, nine rebounds and 2.3
steals over his past 14 games; Willie Davis is averaging 18.5
points and 10.5 boards over his past four; Woods scored the winning
points to beat Air Force and Wyoming and is shooting 46 percent
from 3-point range over the past six games. In victories over TCU,
CSU and Wyoming, Davis averaged 12.3 rebounds. Against the Cowboys,
SMU also got 11 points and tough play inside from freshman forward
Michael Niemi.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things are looking better, but we still have a lot of work to
do,'' Dement said.
THE BUZZ
</P>
<P>
   UNLV (15-8, 8-2) gained some breathing room, recovering from a
loss Saturday at Rice with a 54-53 victory at Tulsa late Monday _
handing the Golden Hurricane (18-8, 6-5) their first home loss in
their new arena. The victory opened up a 11/2-game lead over the
surprising Owls (16-7, 7-4), but it was also costly. Center Kaspars
Kambala (6-foot-9, 250 pounds) left the game with a sprained knee
and his status was still uncertain last night. The Rebels are host
to SMU on Saturday and TCU on Monday night. ... ESPN's Dick Vitale
picked Utah guard Andre Miller and TCU's Lee Nailon _ both
finalists for the Naismith Award _ for his ``All-Rolls Royce
Team.'' Nailon was the division's player of the week and has taken
over the WAC scoring lead (23.0), ranking eighth nationally. ...
Utah (20-4, 10-0) has won 15 in a row and leads the Pacific
Division by 21/2 games. The Utes are ranked 12th nationally. ...
Led by Becky Hammon's 27 points Sunday in a victory against SMU,
the Colorado State women (26-1, 11-0) moved up to a No. 4 national
ranking.
</P>
</TEXT>
