<SLUG> BC-DALLAS-ARENA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW DALLAS SPORTS ARENA WILL FEATURE UNIQUE ELEMENTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID A. MARKIEWICZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ By any standard, the new Dallas sports arena will be a
superior facility to 19-year-old Reunion Arena.
</P>
<P>
   The building, plans for which are scheduled to be unveiled in
the next month or so, will boast more and better concessions,
extensive premium seating and improved restrooms and parking _ all
marks of modern arenas.
</P>
<P>
   But the next home of the Mavericks and Stars (scheduled to be
open for the 2001-02 seasons) also will feature unique design
elements that will distinguish it from modern buildings elsewhere
in the country, project architects and team executives said, citing
several examples.
</P>
<P>
   The standard racetrack-style concourse at Reunion and other
sports arenas is being junked for a series of high-ceiling great
rooms, rotundas and hallways creating what architects say will be a
far more welcoming public space, where fans will want to linger.
The new arena will take up about twice the area of Reunion, but the
building will retain some intimacy thanks to architects' efforts to
build in what they call nooks and crannies in seating areas and
concourses.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the ``end-zone'' seating areas will be set at a steeper
pitch than in most arenas, putting fans closer to the action, and
the arena's exterior should be distinctive and allow people inside
to look out on downtown.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of our peers around the country are constructing
buildings, and we said right from the beginning that we wanted to
do something unique and different,'' Mavericks president Terdema
Ussery said. ``We wanted better sightlines and more intimacy. We
wanted our basketball fans to have almost a collegiate atmosphere.
Given the size of the building, we think we've done that well.''
</P>
<P>
   Explained arena architect David Schwarz: ``We're trying to make
this a humane building, where being in the building is a great deal
of fun. That's not a new idea. It's just restoring some traditional
architectural values.''
</P>
<P>
   Architects say they can distinguish the $230 million downtown
Dallas arena, in part, by creating soaring public spaces in the
concourses and by allowing for some asymmetrical design elements in
the seating bowl. There will be, for example, three levels of
suites on one end of the court, one level on the opposite end, and
two levels on the sides.
</P>
<P>
   Schwarz suggests that the features which distinguish baseball
stadiums such as The Ballpark in Arlington, which he designed, can
also be built into indoor arenas.
</P>
<P>
   ``People,'' he said, ``have not done arenas as well as stadiums.
Arenas, too, can have nooks and crannies.''
</P>
<P>
   Among Schwarz's ideas is to give fans inside the arena views to
what's outside the building.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have huge quantities of glass in our rooms because we want
you to know where you are when you're on the inside,'' Schwarz
said. ``We don't ever want you to feel lost. In other buildings,
you don't know where you are.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryan Trubey, vice president and director of the sports
facilities group at HKS, the Dallas architectural firm working with
Schwarz, said arena architects ``worked to create more of a
collegiate basketball atmosphere in the \Rseating\S bowl'' by
effectively pulling the end-court areas in tighter to the playing
floor.
</P>
<P>
   Trubey called this task ``difficult to achieve in a pro sports
arena where you have both hockey and basketball'' because permanent
seating has to be designed around the hockey surface, which is
larger than the basketball court. Standard attempts to bring fans
closer to the court using retractable seating have had only
marginal success.
</P>
<P>
   While both the Stars' and Mavericks' needs were satisfied by the
seating design, the two franchises don't share all elements of
their wish lists. Arena Group president Brad Mayne said, for
example, that the Stars wanted a modern press box in the new arena,
and the Mavericks wanted a separate practice court. However, the
Stars had no need for a practice rink, and the Mavericks no need
for a press box. Ultimately, he suggested, the new arena will have
both the practice court and press box because each is necessary in
a modern facility.
</P>
<P>
   Stars president James Lites agreed that project architects were
asked to come up with a building that met many different desires.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted the new arena to be bigger \Rthan Reunion\S, but not
too big. We wanted it to feel grander but not too cold,'' Lites
said. ``We wanted to make the concourses wider but intimate. We
wanted steeper angles \Rin seating areas\S, but we didn't want it
too tight.''
</P>
<P>
   Other building users, including the circus, ice shows and
concerts, have special needs, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``The give-and-take sessions take place weekly,'' Mayne said.
``We're basically building from scratch.''
</P>
</TEXT>
