<SLUG> BC-JASPER-TRIAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROSECUTOR SAYS JASPER SUSPECT WANTED `RESPECT' FOR NEW RACIST
GANG 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PATTY REINERT 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JASPER, Texas _ Dragging a black man to death behind a pickup
was just the bold event a young racist needed to attract recruits
for his new white supremacist group, a prosecutor told jurors
Tuesday, the first day of testimony in John W. ``Bill'' King's
capital murder trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill King had laid out his intention to form a hate group in
Jasper, Texas,'' Guy James Gray said in his 15-minute, low-key
opening statement. ``And he needed to do something dramatic to
attract media attention in order to gain, in their warped world,
respect for this newly formed gang.''
</P>
<P>
   King, 24, is the first of three white men to be tried in the
June 7, 1998, killing of James Byrd Jr., a 49-year-old disabled
man. Byrd, who had accepted a ride from King and two of his
friends, was found dead the next morning, his beaten, dismembered
remains strung over a three-mile trail on a back road east of town.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted, King would face either life in prison or death by
injection.
</P>
<P>
   Gray, the Jasper County district attorney, began the day by
apologetically showing the jury of 11 whites and one
African-American a book of more than a dozen color photographs of
Byrd's mutilated corpse, saying, ``It'll be a little rough on you,
but you can do it.''
</P>
<P>
   He pointed out that Byrd, while he may have been drunk, was
alive and conscious when he was chained to the pickup. As proof, he
offered photos of Byrd's elbows, which were ground down to the bone
when he attempted to keep his head off the pavement as he was being
dragged.
</P>
<P>
   Jurors showed little emotion, but Byrd's 17-year-old daughter,
Jamie, left the courtroom in tears, accompanied by her brother,
Ross.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just walking in here, we realized they wouldn't be able to
stay,'' said Mylinda Washington, James Byrd's sister. ``It's just
too hard. It's rough to hear this.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, as prosecutors showed the jury Byrd's shredded underwear
and other clothing ripped from his body as he was dragged, Byrd's
sister, Clara Taylor, and his daughter, Rene Mullins, left the
courtroom briefly.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Byrd's three children, the first few rows of the
courtroom were filled with other family members, including the
victim's father, seven siblings, his former wife and his 2-year-old
granddaughter.
</P>
<P>
   The family had arrived Monday night in Jasper and watched videos
of James Byrd Jr., whom they called ``Son,'' playing the piano.
</P>
<P>
   King's father, Ronald, sat opposite the Byrd family and was
accompanied briefly, by the defendant's girlfriend, Kylie Greeney,
who had to leave the courtroom as soon as testimony began because
she may be called as a witness in the case.
</P>
<P>
   King, dressed in green slacks and a plaid, long-sleeved shirt
that covered his heavily tattooed arms, sat quietly at the defense
table, speaking only once, to politely answer, ``Not guilty, your
honor,'' when state District Judge Joe Bob Golden requested his
plea.
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorney C. Haden ``Sonny'' Cribbs Jr. declined to give
an opening statement, but reserved the right to do so later.
</P>
<P>
   Gray spent much of the morning taking Jasper County Sheriff
Billy Rowles through methodic testimony of his investigation,
enumerating each piece of evidence found at the crime scene: King's
Zippo cigarette lighter, engraved with the ex-con's prison
nickname, Possum, and a symbol of the Ku Klux Klan, tools of
co-defendant Shawn Allen Berry, Byrd's dentures and his clothing.
</P>
<P>
   The sheriff said that once he realized he was dealing with a
dragging and not a hit-and-run case, he drove to the FBI office in
Beaumont and asked for help.
</P>
<P>
   Once the federal agents arrived in Jasper, he formed a
roundtable discussion, and ``we went through everything, and
everything and everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if that turned out to be a good idea, the sheriff
answered, ``You betcha _ smartest thing Billy Rowles ever did.''
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution also offered evidence found at King's apartment,
including King's hand-written notes, racist drawings and a
membership application, constitution, bylaws and code of ethics for
a hate group King allegedly planned to form July 4, 1998. The
group, which King had named the Texas Rebel Soldiers of the
Confederate Knights of America, was to be formed in Jasper.
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorneys objected to each piece of evidence and each
photo of King's racist, Satanic and anti-Semitic tattoos, saying
they were constitutionally protected as free speech and could
prejudice jurors against their client. Golden overruled all the
objections.
</P>
<P>
   Also testifying Tuesday was 18-year-old Michele Chapman, who
said she had met King at a party when she was 13 and later
corresponded with him while he was serving time in a Tennessee
Colony prison from 1995-97.
</P>
<P>
   Chapman said she received 19 letters from King, many of them
touting his racist beliefs, and turned all of them over to the FBI
following King's arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors read aloud portions of three letters, which
contained descriptions of King's tattoos, as well as racial slurs
and fantasies of erotic interludes.
</P>
<P>
   In a series of letters written in 1996, when Chapman was 15,
King called her his ``Aryan princess'' or ``my beautiful kitten
(Puss In Boots).'' Many of the letters were romantic, but strewn
with racial slurs and vulgarities about Jasper-area ``whores'' who
became traitors to their race by dating blacks. Such women should
hang from the same tree as their black boyfriends, he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   King also groused about not getting parole, but said he had more
to look forward to in prison than at home. ``I have it made in all
actuality, why give it up for a world full of nothing?
</P>
<P>
   ``At least in here, I don't have to worry about much,'' he
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The thing King clearly liked best about prison is the
availability of free ``skin art,'' as he called his tattoos. He
bragged that he had gotten $3,000 worth of free tattoos.
</P>
<P>
   Once he got out of prison, Chapman testified, he visited her at
her home and showed off his tattoos. Describing one tattoo
depicting a black man hanging from a rope, Gray asked her, ``Was he
proud of that one?'' and she responded, ``As anybody would be, I
guess.''
</P>
<P>
   After the testimony, Gray described the day as slow and
``disjointed,'' but promised he would pull everything together for
the jury in the next few days. Planned for today is testimony from
a DNA expert, who will tell the jury that Byrd's blood was found on
the shoes of King and his co-defendants, Berry, 24, and Lawrence
Russell Brewer Jr., 31. Berry and Brewer will be tried later.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities Tuesday braced for the arrival of black militant
groups, who had called to say they would fight Judge Golden's order
keeping demonstrators off the courthouse square. None showed up,
but Houston black activist Quannel X said he and a group of
followers plan to attend the trial Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   He said he spoke to Golden several times, assuring him they
would not be disruptive, but intend to wear their black
military-style uniforms in the courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   He also warned that if authorities attempt to arrest them, armed
members of the group would be prepared to defend them.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
