r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHURCH-FIRE-TEX     02-16 0603
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHURCH-FIRE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE DOG FINDS MORE EVIDENCE OF ACCELERANT IN CHURCH FIRE
</HEADLINE>
 By JACK DOUGLAS Jr. 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE WORTH, Texas _ A specially trained police dog found more
evidence of accelerants Tuesday in the charred ruins of a church
fire that killed three area firefighters.
</P>
<P>
   The dog's discoveries led authorities to believe that it's
possible that an arsonist set a fire Monday inside Precious Faith
Temple in Lake Worth outside Fort Worth, investigators said. But
they said the samples may just as likely have come from common
household goods kept inside the church, such as glue.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the same dog _ a yellow Labrador retriever from
Wichita Falls _ found evidence of accelerants in the rubble of a
storage shed behind the church. That prompted investigators to
describe the fire as ``suspicious.''
</P>
<P>
   No official ruling has been made in the cause of the blaze, but
the U.S. Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms has issued a
$10,000 reward for information leading to the arrest and conviction
of anyone responsible for the tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   The fire, reported shortly before 10:45 a.m., is being
investigated by the multiagency Tarrant County Arson Task Force.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Collins, 35, Phillip Dean, 29, and Garry Sanders, 20, were
killed when the fire spread rapidly and a portion of the roof
collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   Four volunteer firefighters were injured. Joe Hamilton, 24, and
Andrew Ailara, 29, were released yesterday from Parkland Memorial
Hospital in Dallas. Harry Mayes Sr., 55, and Paul Burns, 37, were
treated Monday at area hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Dean and Collins were full-time Fort Worth firefighters who at
the time of their deaths were working as volunteers for the
suburban River Oaks Fire Department. Sanders was a volunteer Sansom
Park firefighter.
</P>
<P>
   The dog, named Buddy, hit on about six locations of soil and
charred debris that may contain a flammable substance, mostly in
the very back interior of what remains of the building, said Lt.
Kent Worley, spokesman for the Fort Worth Fire Department.
</P>
<P>
   Worley said it's possible that the dog caught the scent of an
arsonist who worked from within the church. But he was quick to add
that it is too early to know for sure.
</P>
<P>
   Precious Faith Temple pastor J.C. Terry said Tuesday that paint
to touch up the church had been kept inside. Other than that, he
said, he was unaware of any flammable chemicals in the building.
</P>
<P>
   Samples are being sent to ATF laboratories in San Francisco, and
some test results are expected back Wednesday, Tarrant County Fire
Marshal Randy Renois said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL ADD FOLLOWS) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Initially, investigators were going to obtain a search warrant
before sending the dog into the debris. But they said that would
have been time-consuming, so they opted to have the church's pastor
sign a consent-to-search order.
</P>
<P>
   Terry said he was glad to do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what they're looking for, but they must have some
reason to look, which I don't mind at all,'' he said. ``They can
search all they want.''
</P>
<P>
   Someone charged with setting a fire that results in a
firefighter's death could face murder charges, Assistant District
Attorney David Montague said.
</P>
<P>
   Texas law allows for a capital murder charge when the facts show
that a firefighter is intentionally killed as he carried out his
duties, Montague said. Proving the intent to kill would probably be
difficult in Monday's fire, he said.
</P>
<P>
   (Staff writer Bill Teeter contributed to this report.)
</P>
